<HEADLINE>
RESEARCH CONFIRMS ERROR IN BROKERAGE'S FILING OF DST STOCK
PURCHASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK DAVIS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ It took a week and a lot of checking, but the
folks at Salomon Smith Barney confirmed Wednesday that they never
really owned 16.3 percent of DST Systems Inc., the Kansas
City-based mutual fund services firm.
</P>
<P>
   Chalk it up to a computer-coding error.
</P>
<P>
   On May 10, SSB FvLH &LR; m9agement Inc., part of Citigroup's Salomon
Smith Barney, reported publicly that it owned more than 10 million
shares of DST. The filing with the Securities and Exchange
Commission was the first anyone had heard that Salomon Smith Barney
had put $560 million into DST stock.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Heckmann, an analyst at George K. Baum &AMP; Co. in Kansas
City, immediately became suspicious of the filing, which had come
the day before DST's annual shareholders meeting.
</P>
<P>
   He questioned how Salomon Smith Barney could have accumulated so
many DST shares in such short order. The daily trading volume
wasn't big enough, he said. The buying would have driven the stock
price sky-high.
</P>
<P>
   Heckmann even ruled out the unlikely possibility that Kansas
City Southern Industries Inc., a large DST shareholder, had
arranged a private sale of DST stock to Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Heckmann's doubts grew stronger after word from Ken Hager, DST's
chief financial officer, that Salomon Smith Barney's institutional
buyers hadn't been in touch with the company. Heckmann said he
couldn't believe anyone would take such a big position in a company
without long talks with management.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Connie Kain, a vice president with SSB Citi Asset
Management Group, passed along confirmation from the company that
the filing represented holdings in the Smith Barney Mutual Funds.
She also promised to get a reporter an interview with the analyst
behind the decision to buy 16.3 percent of DST.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Kain's search uncovered the error and she called with
the news Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Someone had created the filing on a computer using a dummy
account, she said. The document was a test of the systems that
create the electronic SEC filings. But someone mistakenly put
genuine coding on the false document and it made its way to the
SEC, Kain said.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the funds own less than 1 percent of DST shares, Kain
said. A corrected filing went to the SEC on Tuesday, and Kain said
a letter of apology was on its way to DST.
</P>
<P>
   DST officials, naturally, were caught unaware by the first
filing. But Hager said Wednesday that the corrected filing had
cleared up the situation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
