<HEADLINE>
TWO SUFFER THROUGH, FOR LOVE OF `STAR WARS' NUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News ServiAU1%ents)  
 By JOE POSNANSKI  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Karyn Walch and I are Star Wars soulmates.
That is, neither of us wanted to see it on opening night. There we
were, though. Karyn stood in line for 10 hours to buy tickets to
``The Phantom Menace,'' the newest (and oldest) Star Wars movie.
She had never seen any of the Star Wars movies. Still, she stood in
line for 10 hours because, well, she loves her husband very, very
much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man,'' a guy in line behind her said as he noticed someone
dressed up like a Star Wars character, ``that's a nice light saber.
I'd sure like one like that.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't know Karyn, a real-estate agent in town, but you may
have seen her husband, Rob. He was the one dressed as Obi-Wan
Kenobi on the front page of The Kansas City Star Wednesday. This
was in the moments before the first showing of ``The Phantom
Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, my wife, Margo, was dressed as some sort of
wide-ranging, ambiguous Star Wars character, with a cape and a hood
and sandals. Between them was a stranger with his face painted to
look either like a professional wrestler or The Phantom Menace
himself.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Around us, people began to have duels with their light sabers in
the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Karyn and I just looked at each other and wondered what strange
roads had brought us here.
</P>
<P>
   There are three kinds of Star Wars people. The first could not
care less. Maybe they've seen one or two of the movies, maybe not,
but it doesn't matter because, to them, it's all some weird cult
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' they will tell you, perhaps with a touch of an English
accent, ``I'm not really a science fiction person.''
</P>
<P>
   The second group likes Star Wars just fine. Cute movies. She has
a crush on Harrison Ford, he has a thing for Princess Leia, the
music's good, the special effects are fun, whatever. It's all fun.
</P>
<P>
   That's my camp.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, I married outside of my Star Wars culture. So did
Karyn. So we stood there, clinging to spouses, standing among 800
people outside the Glenwood Theatre who had eD
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
