<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT INVOKES `DUCK' PRINCIPLE _ AND MICROSOFT COULD FOOT THE
BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) A federal appellate court has waded into ``If it looks
like a duck, if it walks like a duck...'' territory, and the
ripples promise to spread throughout the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether thousands of Microsoft ``permatemps'' _
temporary agency workers who have worked at Microsoft for a long
time _ should be eligible for company stock options available to
Microsoft employees.
</P>
<P>
   A court in California said last week that eligible permatemps
should be able to participate in Microsoft's employee stock
purchase plan, which provides a 15 percent discount on stock
prices.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge panel drew on earlier court decisions that said
temp workers should be considered employees by ``common law.'' That
definition covers temps who have been on the same job for five
months or more and ard0substantially trained, supervised or
recruited by the company where they work, instead of byuwe staffing
service that signs their paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   Except for different-colored name tags, sources say you would
have trouble distinguishing Microsoft employees from Microsoft
temps. They look, walk and act like the same ducks.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, certain to be appealed by Microsoft, could involve
big bucks. Microsoft could take a $20 million hit if forced to
extend employee benefits to up to 10,000 of its permatemps, current
and former.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the permatemps could profit handsomely.
Consider: The chief economist for the state of Washington, home to
Microsoft headquarters, says the average earnings of Microsoft
employees who exercised stock options last year were nearly
$300,000.
</P>
<P>
   Is that ducky, or what?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, different vested interests in the workplace are
lining up for or against the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Temporary and Staffing Services
issued a statement that the decision was unfair because it flew in
the face of the staffing service contracts signed by Microsoft and
its temporary workers.
</P>
<P>
   The National Employment Law Project said the decision was fair
because workers who do the same jobs should be treated the same
way.
</P>
<P>
   When the case finishes percolating through the judicial system,
the outcome will affect Microsoft the most, but all employers who
hire temporary workers should pay attention. That's a lot of people
and places. The temporary-staffing industry places about 3 million
temps in the U.S. workplace every day.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of temp employment stretches beyond high-tech
industries, where temps are a cost-effective and flexible way to
staff up for new projects. Temps are easy to let go when the
project is finished or when sales slide.
</P>
<P>
   While on board, though, temps are not necessarily cheaper than
employees. They often earn more per hour than their employee
counterparts, and the employer pays a premium to the staffing
agency that placed them.
</P>
<P>
   Time will tell whether the decision stands and whether it is
interpreted narrowly or broadly. Meanwhile, it has put, shall we
say, a quack in the wall separating employee and temp workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
