<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASTE-GOVERNMENT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPENDING WATCHDOG COMMENDS ASHCROFT'S PORK-FREE LEGISLATIVE DIET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John Ashcroft of Missouri can claim he's
perfect this morning and get away with it.
</P>
<P>
   A watchdog group in favor of cutting government waste and
keeping taxes low will announce Thursday that Ashcroft is the only
member of the Senate to get a 100 percent rating on various 1998
spending votes. Two senators got 95 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The nonpartisan Citizens Against Government Waste annually
selects as ``Taxpayer Heroes'' members of the Senate and House who
score at least 80 percent in votes it deems to be of particular
taxpayer interest.
</P>
<P>
   The only other ``hero'' besides Ashcroft in the Missouri or
Kansas delegation is fellow Republican Sen. Sam Brownback of
Kansas, who scored 85 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a total surprise to me,'' Ashcroft said. ``I hope people
respect the commitment I've made as governor and as senator to keep
taxes low.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft served two terms as governor and faces a challenge from
the current governor, Mel Carnahan, in his bid for re-election next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan's political adviser, Roy Temple, said he didn't know
much about the ranking, but he noted that the National Journal
magazine reported in January that no one in the Senate had a more
conservative voting record than Ashcroft.
</P>
<P>
   The Citizens Against Government Waste evaluated votes on 20
Senate issues in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sen. Ashcroft has been a leader in stopping pork barrel
politics and in this age of so-called budget surpluses it's very
easy for politicians to spend every penny they can get their hands
on,'' said Aaron Taylor, an organization spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens Against Government Waste was founded in 1984 as a
spinoff of President Reagan's drive to cut wasteful spending, but
it is not a Republican organization, Taylor said. Its president,
Thomas A. Schatz, used to work for the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans had an average rating of 70 percent, compared with
18 percent for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. Kit Bond of Missouri got a 63 percent rating and
Republican Sen. Pat Roberts of Kansas got 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   House members were ranked on 28 votes from 1998. In Missouri,
Rep. Karen McCarthy, a Kansas City Democrat, received an 18 percent
rating. Reps. Richard Gephardt and William Clay, St. Louis area
Democrats, got zero.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy spokesman Phil Scaglia said such ratings are hard to
gauge in that last month McCarthy got a 72 percent rating _ the
best in the Missouri delegation _ from the Concord Coalition, a
bipartisan group that advocates fiscal restraint.
</P>
<P>
   The government waste group gave a rating of 29 percent to Rep.
Ike Skelton of Lexington, Mo., and 50 percent to Rep. Pat Danner of
Kansas City, North. Both are Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Former Rep. Vince Snowbarger of Johnson County, a Republican
defeated for re-election by Democrat Dennis Moore in November, got
a rating of 82 percent, the highest in the four-member Kansas House
delegation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
