<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLD-CURE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TREATMENT CAN STAVE OFF COLD SYMPTOMS, BUT IT'S FAR FROM A
CURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A nasal spray that stops a cold dead in its tracks?
</P>
<P>
   Sounds great, but don't put away your boxes of Kleenex just yet.
</P>
<P>
   A study in Wednesday's Journal of the American Medical
Association found that an experimental drug sniffed as a nasal
spray or powder can reduce cold symptoms by almost half.
</P>
<P>
   But not even the researchers themselves are ready to stir hopes
of a cure just yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not close,'' said Frederick Hayden of the University of
Virginia Health Sciences Center in Charlottesville. ``This is
really just a first step.''
</P>
<P>
   The drug in question, tremacamra, serves as a decoy that keeps
cold viruses from attacking the body. Instead of latching onto
cells and doing damage, the virus binds harmlessly to molecules of
the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Hayden and researchers at the Medical University of South
Carolina in Charleston recruited about 200 healthy men and women
and isolated them in hotel rooms. About half sniffed a tremacamra
nasal spray or powder six times a day for seven days. The rest got
a placebo.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers gave the subjects nosedrops containing a rhinovirus,
the most common type of cold virus, either before taking tremacamra
or shortly after treatment had begun. Most of the subjects got
colds.
</P>
<P>
   But those who received tremacamra rated their symptoms about
half as severe. And their nasal secretions _ weighed by collecting
all their used tissues into plastic bags _ were about half as
heavy.
</P>
<P>
   Hayden said the study shows the drug works, in principle. But
some doctors remain skeptical about its practical application.
</P>
<P>
   ``This therapy is innovative, but the results aren't
breathtakingly dramatic,'' said Michael Luchi, an infectious
disease expert at the University of Kansas Medical Center. ``I
don't consider this a major breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   There are quite a few more steps, Luchi said, between this
experiment and a useful treatment:
</P>
<P>
   - Tremacamra has been tested against one rhinovirus, but there
are about 100 such viruses. Hayden believes the drug should be
effective against most of the rest. But rhinoviruses account for
only 40 percent of colds. Tremacamra promises no protection against
other types of cold viruses.
</P>
<P>
   - Tremacamra was tested on people before they developed cold
symptoms. It's unclear whether it would help someone with a
full-blown cold.
</P>
<P>
   - Taking tremacamra as often as the test subjects did is
impractical. Hayden believes it would have to be taken at least
daily through cold season to be effective.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
