<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DATE-RAPE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SEE MORE REPORTS OF SUSPECTED RAPES AFTER DRUG INGESTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE VENDEL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Kansas City police lately have heard the same
story too often: At a bar, a young woman accepts a drink from a man
she has just met. They dance. Then the woman becomes dizzy and
blacks out. The next day she awakes in a strange place. She
suspects she's been raped. But can't be sure.
</P>
<P>
   Sex crimes detectives think they know what happened: A man
slipped a drug into her drink and raped her.
</P>
<P>
   Similar crimes have garnered national attention in recent years,
but police in Kansas City started noticing reports of drug-rapes
last fall, said Sgt. Jim Keane of the sex crimes unit. Keane said
he had seen two to six reports of the crimes each weekend, mostly
in the Westport, Country Club Plaza and Northland areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stories these women are telling are so similar,'' Keane
said. ``They all received a drink from a man at a bar and then have
a gap of time where they can't remember what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Keane expects to see more cases as the weather warms, college
students return home and patrons crowd local bars.
</P>
<P>
   Police from Overland Park, Kan., and Independence, Mo., have
received similar reports within the past year, but not in the
numbers that Kansas City has recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Overland Park police Sgt. Joe Reed said he saw about five such
reports last year and one this year. Independence counted three
such cases in the past 10 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three years ago, we didn't see any problems like this,''
Independence Sgt. Gregg Wilkinson said. ``But now I can think of
three recent cases. You also have to understand that for every rape
reported, there are about 10 that aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   Victims' advocates said women, who suspect they were drugged and
raped, rarely make a report to police.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen about 10 women in this type of situation over the
last two years,'' said Michelle Paynter of the Metropolitan
Organization to Counter Sexual Assault. ``Most of them did not go
to a hospital or report it to police. They are just so
self-blaming.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when women report the case, proving a crime is difficult.
Some victims wait too long to report a crime, plus their memories
are hazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people can give us almost no leads at all,'' Keane said.
Few, if any, cases ever reach the prosecutor's office, because
there isn't enough evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Police and rape victim advocates are trying to educate women and
hospital workers about preserving evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``To detect these drugs, we need a urine sample,'' said Linda
Netzel, senior criminalist at the Kansas City Crime Lab. ``If
nurses don't know to ask for that and they take blood or no samples
at all, we lose the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Some tests conducted on women who have reported such incidents
have shown evidence of sexual intercourse. None have shown the
presence of the common drugs used to take advantage of women.
</P>
<P>
   With the threat of drug-rapes in Kansas City, police want to
warn women to change their habits at bars, parties and even at
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the victims have said, `But he looked like a nice guy,'
'' Keane said. ``I don't know what they think a rapist looks like.
Just because a man looks nice doesn't mean he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Keane said women should watch their drinks as closely as they do
their purses and should never accept drinks from strangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate women have to act this way, but they aren't
safe out there anymore,'' Keane said. ``Any nice guy you see in a
tavern could be a rapist.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
