<SLUG> BC-NY-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI SNUBS CLINTON'S VISIT FOR RAIL HUB 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ President Clinton flew to New York on Wednesday to
join Republican and Democratic leaders in celebrating a $484
million proposal to transform the General Post Office on Eighth
Avenue into a new Pennsylvania Station. But Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
boycotted the ceremony, disparaging both the cost and the scope of
a project that has gathered wide support among New York political
and civic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton used the visit to announce that he would ask Congress to
provide $60 million for the project, which has been championed by
Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, who attended the ceremony on
Wednesday. The design of the new station, with a soaring glass and
steel roof, is reminiscent of the original Pennsylvania Station,
which was considered a fine example of 20th century neo-classical
design. It was torn down 36 years ago. Officials said that an
additional $60 million is still needed for the project, an amount
Moynihan's aides described as relatively modest.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani, who spent the morning at City Hall, said he was
skeptical about the financing. He added that he had skipped the
event because he was afraid it would confer legitimacy on something
that should still be on the drawing board.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money isn't in place,'' the mayor said. ``And I don't want
to give the false impression that the money is in place, because
then the city will have to pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   When Giuliani first began discussing the station project with
reporters on Wednesday, he praised it as a ``really good project.''
But by the time he had finished, he was warning that it would be
plagued by cost overruns. He also said that the project Clinton was
celebrating was less ambitious than had originally been envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no longer going to have an entrance and exit on Eighth
Avenue _ it's going to be in the middle of the block in an
alleyway,'' Giuliani said. ``So it's a different project. I think
there's value to the project, but I don't want the city to have to
bear the big burden of paying for this.''
</P>
<P>
   As a practical matter, Giuliani's complaints are unlikely to
jeopardize the project, even though they clearly annoyed some
officials involved in planning Wednesday's event. To date, New York
City has contributed just $25 million to the project, and
Moynihan's aides said that they would find the rest of the money
elsewhere if Giuliani declined to contribute more.
</P>
<P>
   As a political matter, several Democrats and Republicans
suggested that Giuliani's decision to skip the event had saved him
from appearing on a stage with public figures whom he might prefer
to avoid, including Gov. George Pataki, with whom he has quarreled
in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's absence was apparent the moment Clinton strolled onto
the stage, which was set up in an old mail-sorting room at the
James A. Farley Post Office, with Moynihan and Pataki behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani was represented by an adviser who sat not with Clinton
on stage but in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Tony Bullock, Moynihan's chief of staff, disputed Mr.
Giuliani's complaints about the financing, as well as his
prediction that it could end up costing as much as $600 million.
Bullock also said that he was not worried about finding the
remaining funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will finish this project,'' Bullock said. ``It is very,
very close now to getting final approval. We're counting on the
mayor's support and additional assistance as necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   The president used much of his speech to pay tribute to
Moynihan, who seemed moved each time the audience rose to applaud
and cheer him. Indeed, Wednesday's event seemed as much to pay
tribute to Moynihan, who announced last year that he would retire
at the end of 2000, as to rally support for the new station.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Moynihan has been called the nation's best thinker
among politicians since Lincoln, and its best politician among
thinkers since Jefferson,'' Clinton said of the senator, with whom
he has frequently disagreed over the last seven years. ``Today we
might say he also may be the best arm-twister since Farley.''
</P>
</TEXT>
