<HEADER>
A4163 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-BIG-THREE-     05-20 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BIG-THREE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
LOS ANGELES _ It's easy to overlook the pitching on a team that
averages almost six runs per game, and that appears to be what's
happening to a trio of Astros starters who quietly have established
themselves among the best in the National League so far in 1999.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But it never fails; any analysis of the Astros includes
questions about their pitching and highlights the fact they don't
have a dominant No. 1 starter. The Astros no doubt will continue to
be lumped in with the contending teams that hope to add a starting
pitcher at the trading deadline, but general manager Gerry
Hunsicker is hardly a man in search of starting pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sick and tired of hearing that,'' Hunsicker said.
``Statistically, we have the best pitching staff in the National
League, and it's an insult to the pitchers we have when people keep
saying that we need an ace. Well, we had one (Randy Johnson) last
year, and we didn't get past the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many No. 1s are out there? Probably four or five. Would I
like to have one of those five? Sure. But I like the guys we have,
too, and I like the challenge of competing without the high-profile
guy that everyone says we are lacking. That makes it extra
satisfying when we quietly keep winning while everyone else is
debating what we need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering Wednesday night's game against the Dodgers, the Astros'
starting pitchers led all NL starters with a 20-10 record and a
3.94 ERA. Shane Reynolds, Mike Hampton and Jose Lima are the three
most responsible for those numbers. They have 18 wins among them
and a cumulative ERA of 3.12. They may not be aces, but each is a
strong card to play every fifth day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't ask for anything more from those guys,'' manager
Larry Dierker said. ``Then again, those guys have been doing it for
a while now, so we can realistically expect them to keep pitching
this way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they really think of themselves as No. 1
starters, and in a way, that's good. I think that creates some
internal competition. But at the same time none of them has to
carry the burden of being the No. 1 guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros catcher Tony Eusebio has seen the best starters in
baseball from the perspective of a hitter, and he doesn't believe
the Astros' Big Three have to take a back seat to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a group, they're right up there with the best in the
league,'' Eusebio said. ``No other club has three pitchers throwing
as well as they are right now. When they pitch, we know we have a
good chance to win the game, and that's all you can ask for.''
</P>
<P>
   If the All-Star team had to be picked today, Padres manager
Bruce Bochy, who will manage the NL stars, would have to give
strong consideration to each of the Astros' aces-in-waiting. Lima
is tied for the NL lead with seven wins, Reynolds was just a
victory off the pace entering Wednesday's start, and Hampton's 2.80
ERA ranks among the NL leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But Hampton isn't quite ready to put the Astros' starters on par
with Atlanta's Greg Maddux, Tom Glavine and John Smoltz, although
the Astros trio has outpitched the Braves' triumvirate of Cy Young
Award winners in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we complement each other very well, but it's so
early,'' Hampton said. ``We all pull for each other, and we all
want to be considered `the man.' If there's a losing streak that
needs to be stopped, each one of us wants to be the guy to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not just me, Shane and Lima; that's Sean Bergman and
Chris Holt, too. Each of us is off to a good start, but that
doesn't mean anything right now. As long as we have the best record
in the NL Central at the end of the year, that's the most important
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   If this is any indication of the type of starting pitching that
can be expected from the Astros for the remainder of the season,
winning the NL Central is a modest goal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
