<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBMD20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WebMD, Healtheon near merger
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ WebMD Inc. and Healtheon Corp. were poised late
Wednesday to finally unveil a high-profile merger that could put
the combined company's market value at $16 billion, its name at the
head of the Net's health care class and its headquarters in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for two companies that have yet to report a dollar in
profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the Internet market,'' said analyst Michele Pelino of
the Yankee Group. ``Almost no one is making money. It's all based
on future expectations and what they will do to the world.''
</P>
<P>
   What these two could do is almost instantly become the
best-known Internet health care company, with the deep pockets
needed to brand its name on the consciousness of consumers and
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they are dominant, but they'll be the key player
until you see some other alliances,'' Pelino said. ``I think this
gives them a jump on the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding muscle is the involvement of Microsoft, which will trade
several hundred million dollars for a stake in the combined
company. The blessing of Microsoft alone can be critical for a new
venture, but the WebMD-Healtheon union will also include strategic
investments with chipmaker Intel and with Excite, an Internet
portal. In April, DuPont agreed to invest $220 million in WebMD
over five years.
</P>
<P>
   The two merging companies mesh. Healtheon concentrates on
transactions, especially among insurers and heath care providers.
WebMD, which focused at first on doctors who pay fees, now
emphasizes its consumer side where advertising must pay the
freight.
</P>
<P>
   But both businesses are immature _ to put it mildly. Healtheon
last year had revenue of $48.8 million and reported a $54 million
loss. WebMD had a $7.8 million loss on revenue that was shy of
$100,000. But hype goes hand-in-hand with hope: Health care
accounts for 14 percent of the nation's $6 trillion economy, and if
the Internet grows, health care could be one of its huge segments.
Meanwhile, the Yankee Group estimates that the number of households
online with computers _ now one in four _ will double in three
years.
</P>
<P>
   So the stock valuation of WebMD and Healtheon as of Wednesday
would be the eighth largest among Georgia companies, greater than
that of Delta Air Lines, which last year had revenues of $14.1
billion and a $1 billion profit.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Healtheon rocketed $24.37 1/2 a share to close at
$80.25. With the pending acquisition of MedeAmerica, announced in
April, Healtheon will have about 100 million shares outstanding.
The companies are planning a merger of equals in which new shares
of the combined company would be issued to complete the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Many other pretenders are anxious to cash in on the presumed
Internet payday. Some have name recognition, like the Web sites of
Dr. C. Everett Koop and the Mayo Clinic. Others like Medscape,
Medirisk, Net.Medic, and Atlanta-based Medcast echo the offerings
of WebMD and Healtheon.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some rivals, WebMD gets most of its content from others,
buying, licensing or linking to it. But WebMD has forged a series
of deals that are putting its name in the places where Net surfers
go, including previous agreements with Lycos and CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based adam.com, another health care site focused on
consumers, believes the merger does not signal the endgame for
competitors, said company CEO Robert Cramer. ``Owning content _
especially proprietary medical and health content _ is a very
strong position to be in and nobody owns content like adam.com.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of adam.com rose 25 percent to close at a 52-week high of
$23.75.
</P>
<P>
   Choice of Atlanta as headquarters seems to follow the decision
to market the combined company as WebMD and make WebMD's founder,
Jeffrey Arnold, chief executive. However, there are no plans to
move Healtheon's more than 600 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has apparently made peace with James Clark, a bitter
rival when he ran Netscape and now Healtheon's chairman. Clark will
remain with the combined company, although probably surrendering
the chairman's post to Michael Long, Healtheon CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Despite speculation that his presence was a sticking point,
WebMD's President and Chief Operating Officer Jay Gilbertson will
probably stay in some operational role.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will make a number of individuals rich _ at least on
paper _ and also swell the coffers of some corporate shareholders.
For example, corporate filings show that Premiere Technologies owns
about 12 percent of WebMD, whose office is in the same building. At
Wednesday's closing price, that share could be worth nearly $1
billion. Premiere's CEO, Boland Jones, sits on the WebMD board and
holds about 13 percent of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold owns about 21.5 percent of WebMD, which would be worth
$1.72 billion by Wednesday's valuation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
