<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PENN-STATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PLANNING FOR GREATNESS TO COME 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, May 20:
</P>
<P>
   There are not enough names for the emotions that great
architecture inspires, and as a result the names of buildings
themselves become shorthand for the complex impressions they leave
behind. Grand Central is one name for many feelings, and so, in a
different key, is the United States Custom House and Rockefeller
Center. These constructions are a homage to reason, to the
constraints of site and the possibilities of engineering. But they
also allude to the human susceptibility to space, to the way
remarkable buildings remodel the emotional interior of the humans
who pass among them.
</P>
<P>
   The new Penn Station in Manhattan may well become such a
building. Its design, by David Childs of Skidmore, Owings &AMP;
Merrill, was unveiled by President Clinton on Wednesday morning in
a ceremony at the James A. Farley postal building on Eighth Avenue.
Since 1963, when Pennsylvania Station was torn down and Madison
Square Garden erected in its place, the Farley building has stood
as the ghostlike twin of an intention the city first fulfilled, in
the original station, and then defiled. Now that intention is
revivified. There is no rebuilding the original McKim, Mead &AMP; White
Penn Station. But it is possible to re-embody something of its
spirit, to make the sacrifice of the original station, which
brought about the birth of the Landmarks Preservation Commission,
almost tolerable.
</P>
<P>
   In his reworking of the Farley Building, part of which was
designed by McKim, Mead &AMP; White, Childs has kept many of the grand
attributes of the old Penn Station _ unbroken vistas, the
interpenetration of light and loftiness on an enormous scale. But
rather than reconstruct the steel and glass roof that rose over the
concourse, and was invisible from the street, Childs has taken a
new departure. He has designed an arching glass and metal roof that
curves upward over the main entrance on 33d Street. It is as though
he had taken the concourse roof from the old station _ an open web
of steel and glass _ smoothed it out, and stood it on its side. It
will suggest to passersby, more than the facade of the original
Penn Station could, something of the grandness that lies within.
</P>
<P>
   A moment will come when the new Penn Station, nearly finished in
2003, will stand opposite Madison Square Garden and the banal
subterranean station that replaced McKim, Mead &AMP; White's building.
It will be one of those moments when two distinct paths through
urban history become visible side by side. One path is essentially
time-serving, a version of modernity in which the individual human
experience of space is considered insignificant, irrelevant to the
perception of the city as a whole. The other path, embodied by many
buildings still standing in New York and by the plans for a new
Penn Station, is one in which a person passing through them, or
within their shadows, finds something unexpected being kindled. It
does not happen to everyone every day. But it happens often to many
people, to tourists and commuters alike, and when it does it makes
a civic difference. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 0023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
