<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CITIZENS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ONE NATION, FOR RICH AND POOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, May 20:
</P>
<P>
   In a closely watched welfare case, the Supreme Court this week
struck down a California law that discriminated against newcomers
by holding them, for one year, to the benefit levels of the states
from which they had moved. Fourteen other states, including New
York, have similar laws that are now in jeopardy. By implication,
the ruling also negated a provision of the 1996 federal welfare
overhaul approved by Congress that specifically authorized states
to offer disparate benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-to-2 decision powerfully reaffirmed the right of equal
citizenship for rich and poor alike. In essence, it extends the
principle of fairness behind the court's decision three decades ago
in Shapiro vs. Thompson. In that case, the court ruled that denying
welfare benefits to newcomers violated the right to travel implicit
in the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, however, the court moved beyond the loosely
defined right-to-travel rationale by breathing new life into the
so-called privileges and immunities clause of the 14th Amendment _
a clause providing that ``No state shall make or enforce any law
which shall abridge the privileges or immunities of citizens of the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Answering the practical arguments raised by California, the
majority opinion cited evidence to show that the state's concern
that its higher benefits would make it a ``welfare magnet'' were
overblown, and that it had other ways to save money on benefits
besides unconstitutional discrimination. ``Citizens of the United
States, whether rich or poor, have the right to choose to be
citizens `of the state wherein they reside,''' wrote Justice John
Paul Stevens for the majority, quoting from the opening sentence of
the 14th Amendment. ``The states, however, do not have any right to
select their citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   This was only the second time in this century that the court has
used the privileges and immunities clause to strike down a state
law. In so doing, the court reinforced the ingenious architecture
of the federal system that binds the 50 states into one nation.
Perhaps, too, the decision signaled a new commitment by this court
to protect individual rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 0046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
