<SLUG> BC-HEART-NEED-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. WOMAN DISCOVERS LONG-LOST NIECE IN DIRE NEED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY STEVE CARNEY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Elated at reaching her sister in Ukraine for the
first time in 25 years, Lioudmila McDonald's joy soon turned to
grief.
</P>
<P>
   A niece she had never met needed open-heart surgery to save her
life, and only surgeons in the United States had the necessary
expertise and facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors agreed to donate their services, but now the
teen-ager needs $8,000 to cover other costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much frustration,'' said McDonald, 45, of suburban
Sun Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's hope _ hope something is going to go through. And
then, nothing. It would be so much easier to step away, or just
disown her, but I can't do it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her niece, Karina Molchasian, already has had two unsuccessful
operations in Ukraine to repair a hole in her heart, a congenital
defect. The condition leaves her constantly tired and breathless.
</P>
<P>
   A Los Angeles doctor volunteered to do the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't fix it, most likely she's going to die from it at
a certain point,'' said Dr. Alfredo Trento, chief of cardiac
surgery for Cedars-Sinai Medical Center. ``At a certain point, it
may be too late.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Trento said a cure for her heart problem would be
routine, not a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   ``A heart operation is always a complex operation,'' he said.
``But if that's what it is, a simple hole in the heart, it can
easily be fixed.''
</P>
<P>
   A Valencia-based charity, Healing the Children, secured Trento's
help and found a way to bring Karina here.
</P>
<P>
   But a forbidding obstacle remains _ the hospital needs $8,000 to
defray its costs for supplies used in the operation. Until that's
collected, Karina won't be going anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald fled the Soviet Union in 1978. Since then she
continually tried to locate her younger sister. When she finally
reached her in September 1997, McDonald began contacting charities
and hospitals seeking help for her niece, and published a plaintive
letter in a Russian-language newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   But apart from neighbors who have chipped in a few hundred
dollars, results have been scant.
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor who is a nurse at Cedars-Sinai put McDonald in touch
with Trento, who in turn put her in touch with Healing the Children
in March.
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit group has 13 chapters nationwide, and started 20
years ago in Spokane, Wash. Since then it has sponsored 65,000
treatments and operations for children overseas and brought 5,000
others to the United States for help, said executive director Cris
Embleton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a big, fancy organization,'' Embleton said. ``This is
moms and dads who want to help other moms and dads.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the group sends volunteer doctors overseas to operate
on needy children, performing procedures common in this country but
unavailable in those areas. And for operations in the United
States, Healing the Children gets airlines to donate travel
expenses, doctors to volunteer their services and hospitals to
offer six-figure treatments for nominal costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's based on people reaching out, and we have been so
rewarded,'' Embleton said. ``It's an opportunity to see miracles.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 0049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
