</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-BOSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX SHUT OUT YANKEES, 6-0 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After witnessing a listless performance by Hideki Irabu
and a lethargic effort by the Yankees against a 23-year-old pitcher
who was recalled from Class AAA on Wednesday, Joe Torre might want
to reconsider his decision to return to manage this sputtering
team. It would have been easier for him to watch this torturous
display on television.
</P>
<P>
   But Torre is back for good two months after undergoing prostate
cancer surgery, and it is his job to inspire and improve the
Yankees, who tumbled to an ugly 6-0 loss to the Red Sox on
Wednesday night at Fenway Park in a game that was delayed by rain
for 73 minutes after the eighth inning before the Yankees bowed out
meekly in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The defending World Series champions have lost seven of their
last eight games and have not played like a club that was deemed
one of the best teams in baseball history last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were spoiled last year,'' Torre said. ``We didn't have any
malfunctions. Someone is going to take a beating soon. Tonight it
was us.''
</P>
<P>
   This was supposed to be a series in which the Yankees proved
something to the Red Sox and even to themselves. The Yankees' grip
on first place in the American League East had loosened, but they
had an opportunity to smack the plucky Red Sox and continue
controlling the division. Instead, they have lost two straight and
are one and one-half games behind the first-place Red Sox, and they
have given Torre plenty to ponder in his first two days back in
uniform.
</P>
<P>
   All Torre has to do is analyze the reams of statistics that are
available to him each day to decipher why the Yankees are hurting.
After Irabu was clipped for five earned runs and nine hits in three
and two-thirds innings, it meant that the Yankees' starters were
5-10 with a 6.15 earned run average in the last 20 games. After the
Yankees went 0 for 4 with runners in scoring position on Wednesday
night against Brian Rose, it meant they were batting .157 (11 for
70) in thaat situation in the last eight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always concerned,'' Torre said. ``Not to the point of
thinking that we can't do something. It's just a matter of winning
to turn it around.''
</P>
<P>
   That did not happen on Wednesday night, and Torre was
disenchanted with Irabu, who could not keep his fastball or his
forkball down and who failed to put hitters away after getting two
strikes. Irabu surrendered three hits and two runs in the fourth
inning, all after he had been ahead 0-2 on the batters, and that
enabled the Red Sox to grab a 5-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew if I got a strikeout on some of those 0-2 counts, it
could have changed the game,'' Irabu said. ``I might have thrown my
forkball too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   It was understandable for the Yankees to lose Tuesday night to
Pedro Martinez, who leads the major leagues with eight victories.
But the proud Yankees would admit that it was unacceptable to fall
tonight to Rose, a pitcher who was an emergency replacement for
Juan Pena (tendinitis in right shoulder) and who entered the
evening with a 1-4 record and a 7.38 era in 10 career games in the
major leagues over three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But Rose mastered the Yankees even more than Martinez did. Using
a fastball and a changeup and taking advantage of the Yankees' lack
of patience, Rose rolled through the lineup with precision. He
breezed through the fourth on five pitches (all three Yankees swung
at the first pitch), and he did not get to a three-ball count until
he walked Paul O'Neill in the sixth. In all, Rose stifled the
Yankees on six hits in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch, who is 3 for his last 42, stranded four runners
in his last two at-bats as the Yankees, who were shut out five
times in 1998, were blanked for the third time in eight days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we get down, we're trying too hard,'' Tino Martinez said.
``We're trying to do it all with one swing. It's frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Irabu had permitted only 3 earned runs in his previous 14
innings and since Torre loves having Ramiro Mendoza in the bullpen,
it seems obvious that Irabu is secure in the rotation. Or is he?
The Red Sox nicked Irabu for two runs in the first, and Jason
Varitek, who had two homers and two singles, crushed a 436-foot
home run to right to nudge the lead to 3-0. All that was before
Irabu fell apart in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   After jumping ahead of Varitek and Darren Lewis 0-2, he gave up
singles to both. Two outs later, Irabu had an 0-2 count on John
Valentin. But Valentin worked the count to 3-2 and lined a
one-bounce double off the center-field fence. That is when Torre
popped out of the dugout to make a change.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees need more changes, too. Soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
