<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAR-ANTI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME FIND FILM EASY TO RESIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A short time ago (Wednesday, actually) in a galaxy
close, close by (OK, it's our very own Milky Way) (italics) some
(end italics) citizens of the Blue Planet took little note of the
opening of the most hyped movie in the history of humanity.
</P>
<P>
   To them, the debut of George Lucas' ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The
Phantom Menace'' was, well, just another movie, albeit one with
lots of bells and whistles, light sabers and the mother of all
flashbacks.
</P>
<P>
   For some, it turned out to be a case of too much information for
too long a time.
</P>
<P>
   Angel Magana, 22, of suburban Granada Hills is already one with
the force. A seaman in the U.S. Navy, Magana will head out for
deployment Friday. He's taking the advice of a notorious
personality when it comes to fitting ``Phantom Menace'' into an
already tight schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Howard Stern says it's not that great so I think I'll go
with Howard. I'll wait until it comes out on video,'' Magana said.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Wodetski and her 7-year-old son, Jordan, had some time to
kill before a visit to the dentist so they could have worked the
movie into their schedule. They chose to shop instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really jazzed about it but we'll probably go see it,''
the Palmdale resident said. ``I've heard about it in the news but
that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, a Luke Skywalker fan, was not begging his mom to take
him to the movie, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only guy I like,'' he said of the original film's
protagonist. ``I used to watch a lot of `Star Wars' movies but I
wasn't in school. But not anymore. I've got to go to school now.''
</P>
<P>
   Granada Hills resident Mike Zabarsky, 27, admits to being a big
fan of Lucas' series. In fact, he's stored a complete collection of
toys from the original ``Star Wars'' to eventually pass on to his
children.
</P>
<P>
   However, the owner of Play It Again Sports in suburban
Northridge didn't give himself the day off to catch the
most-talked-about flick in the world.
</P>
<P>
   No fan of standing in line or being stuck in a parking lot,
he'll wait until the excitement dies down before seeing the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like a book. I already know the ending, so why go
see the beginning right away? But I like the `Star Wars' mythos.
The Greeks had Homer and we've got Lucas. It's a departure from
reality, it's got a clear message and it's attention-grabbing.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the release of this movie, Lucas really grabbed the
attention of the media.
</P>
<P>
   Print and electronic journalists churned out story after story,
day after day in advance of the opening. The only thing absent were
splashy television ads, which the movie didn't need, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been advertising itself for the last year or so,'' said
Rich Ingrassia, an entertainment industry analyst at Paul Kagan &AMP;
Associates in Carmel. ``Why spend money when ``Entertainment
Tonight'' is showing the trailer every day?''
</P>
<P>
   Ingrassia has seen the movie and said it lives up to the hype.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Leyland, editor in chief of PR Week, a trade publication,
said Lucas knew he had a good story and that the media would be all
over it.
</P>
<P>
   So a big advertising budget was not necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Leyland compares the opening of ``Phantom Menace'' to the recent
launch of products like the Volkswagen Beetle and Apple's iMac.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's a good story to tell and the media wants it you don't
need to advertise because the media will lap it up,'' Leyland said.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of reaction turned off Jeff Griffith, 29, of suburban
Woodland Hills, a computer programmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate media hype. I hate anything that's big because it's
big. It works negative for me,'' he said, noting that ``Phantom
Menace'' is not on his ``must see'' list.
</P>
<P>
   Granted it's still early, but ``Menace'' did not seem to be
setting any fashion trends Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bev Segal, manager of the Hair House, a styling salon, said no
one had rushed in requesting a copy of the Queen Amidala coiffeur.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could change. We get a lot of younger people in towards
the weekend,'' she conceded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
