<HEADLINE>
AVALANCHE'S NEWFOUND BALANCE IS NOT JUST A SNOW JOB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Colorado Avalanche team the Stars will face in the
Western Conference finals beginning Saturday is not the same
run-and-gun unit that was upset in the first round of last season's
playoffs by the Edmonton Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche isn't even the same team that struggled in the
first round this year against the San Jose Sharks or the one that
lost the first two games to the Detroit Red Wings in the conference
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche team that comes to Reunion Arena for Game 1 at
6:30 p.m. Saturday is the one that just swept four games from the
defending Stanley Cup champion Red Wings. It's the one that took
three of the needed four wins on the road. It's the one that has
learned to temper its dangerous offensive talent with a trapping
system that balances offense with a newfound respect for team
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those four games against Detroit, they became a different
team,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``They play smart,
conservative hockey. I think they've found a balance. When you know
that you have enough top-end people who can score, you feel that
you don't have to put on a show. Now, they're patient; they just
feel the other team is going to crack, eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Stars winger Mike Keane, a member of the 1996 Stanley Cup
champion Avalanche: ``They're a much different team than when I
played there. They're a much different team than when we played
them earlier in the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said the addition of a defensive system to the
world-class scoring ability of Joe Sakic, Theo Fleury and Peter
Forsberg makes the Avalanche tough to beat. Adding Fleury (five
goals, nine assists) and gritty center Dale Hunter in late-season
trades created depth. Getting solid performances from rookies Milan
Hejduk and Chris Drury added energy. Shuffling Adam Deadmarsh and
Shjon Podein provided calm defensive hands to a high-energy forward
group.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to beat that system, Hitchcock said, is with
patience and teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're overly aggressive, you can get burnt. If you're
careless with the puck, you're going to get burnt,'' Hitchcock
said. ``Your whole group has to stay on the same page. And, really,
that's been the strength of our team all year _ staying on the same
page in a team system.''
</P>
<P>
   Patience combined with intelligence has allowed the Stars to
plow through two early series in which they were pushed hard by the
Edmonton Oilers and St. Louis Blues. And while there were tenuous
moments and five overtime games, the Stars still have posted an 8-2
record in the playoffs, tied with the Buffalo Sabres for tops in
the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are 3-2 in overtime games in the playoffs and 6-2 in
games decided by one goal. And Hitchcock and his players say they
have to be ready to take an attitude of patience to the new-look
Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've done and what we do is win close hockey games.
That's who we are,'' Stars defenseman Craig Ludwig said. ``The past
three years, we've been winning games 2-1 and 1-0 with every game
coming down to the last second. But that's been a good thing for
us. We're used to playing in that kind of high-pressure game every
night.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
