<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLONIAL-HISTORY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT COLONIAL, BIZARRE IS PAR FOR THE COURSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE COCHRAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ What next?
</P>
<P>
   They've bounced shots off the clubhouse, whiffed putts, smashed
clubs and chased balls into the lake. One year, a young Canadian
held the lead for five days. And lost.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Trevino trudged off the course one hot, windy day and said
he felt as though he'd just escaped from the Twilight Zone.
</P>
<P>
   Cary Middlecoff, a former dentist, won the 1951 Colonial
championship with a closing round of 3-over-par 73 and confessed
that he was pondering a return to dentistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to play this course every day for a living,'' he
sighed, ``I'd go back to pulling teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   Strange things do, in fact, occur at Colonial Country Club. .
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a real strong run,'' tournament chairman Phil Thomas
said recently as he and committee members plopped down in the
Terrace Room and reminisced about Colonial's half-century on the
PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be hard to beat what we've done. We've got a lot of
champions that any tournament would love to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, from Ben Hogan in '46 to Tom Watson in '98, the names on
Colonial's Wall of Champions are magic. They include Heafner,
Snead, Bolt, Boros, Sanders and Arnold Palmer in the first 15
years.
</P>
<P>
   Then Casper, Crampton, Stockton, Devlin, Dickinson, Blancas,
Littler, Weiskopf, Geiberger, Trevino, Crenshaw and, by 1980,
Lietzke.
</P>
<P>
   Since then: Zoeller, Nicklaus, Jacobsen, Pavin, Wadkins,
Baker-Finch, Price, Lehman, Frost and last year's unlikely but
incredibly popular champion, Tom Watson.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, much has changed since Bantam Ben fired a 5-under-par
65 in the closing round of the first Colonial to nip Dallas rival
Harry Todd and escape with $3,000 in prize money.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest change is the prize money: $504,000 to the 1999
champion.
</P>
<P>
   To put that in perspective, this year's winner will earn
$484,000 more than the $20,000 total Hogan got for five Colonial
victories, the last 40 years ago this week.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds strange. Is strange. But strange things happen on the
professional golf circuit, particularly the one known as ``Hogan's
Alley.''
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Bolt, nicknamed ``Thunder,'' once took a 9 on the par-4
ninth, and a scribe foolishly asked him how. ``I sunk a 14-foot
putt,' he snarled.
</P>
<P>
   Thunder won the Colonial in 1958, the year heavy rains nearly
rendered the course unplayable. Conditions were so awful that Byron
Nelson failed to find words to describe them.
</P>
<P>
   But he tried.
</P>
<P>
   ``The course is too wet to be muddy,'' he said, ``and somehow,
it's the driest wet I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Bolt, Watson once made a 9 at nine, and then wound up
trailing the eventual 1977 Colonial champ, Ben Crenshaw, by two
strokes. In a typical touch of Colonial irony, Watson hit the
pivotal shot of the 1998 Colonial from an awkward lie in a bunker
at that same No. 9.
</P>
<P>
   The ball sailed the pond and stopped 10 feet from the pin. The
momentum carried him that Sunday to a two-shot victory over Jim
Furyk.
</P>
<P>
   In 1950, Sam Snead celebrated his 38th birthday at Colonial. On
Saturday, with Snead ahead by five shots, Jimmy Demaret led the
crowd around the 18th green in singing ``Happy Birthday''.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Demaret, aglow with Colonial cheer, serenaded the
newly c-;ned champion again, this time with ``Some Enchanted
Evening''.
</P>
<P>
   In 1954, Johnny Palmer won with a 72-hole total of 280, even
par. Ten years later, he set a scoring record unmatched even today.
His 87-81-82-79_331 was 51 over par.
</P>
<P>
   With Hogan unable to play in the 1949 Colonial because of his
near-fatal car-bus collision, God intervened. So sayeth golf
historian Dennis Roberson and tournament MB;Br.
</P>
<P>
   ``God washed out the tournament with a flood,'' Roberson said.
</P>
