<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-VOTE-FOLO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS RE PEAT DESIRE TO REMAIN IN VALLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 and LES POLK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Gallardo Bros. movers showed up at the Cardinals'
Tempe training facility early Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't there to move the team out of town. They were there
to return election paraphernalia from Tuesday night's Rio Salado
Crossing project party.
</P>
<P>
   There was no panic from the Cardinals a day after a lopsided
loss in their bid for a new stadium. Owner Bill Bidwill reaffirmed
his desire to get a new facility in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the Valley was where he wanted to be, Bidwill
said, ``It always has been.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bidwill, team vice president who spearheaded the stadium
drive, didn't spend Wednesday calling on cities that might be
interested in courting the Cardinals. He joked that he was trying
to get tickets for the new ``Star'' ``Wars'' movie.
</P>
<P>
   A Houston businessman immediately expressed interested in having
the Cardinals relocate there, but team officials dismissed the idea
just as quickly. Businessman Bob McNair told a Houston TV station
that he would like to talk with the Bidwills but added that he
wanted to have ownership in the team.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bidwill said again Wednesday that he has no plans to sell
the team, which has been in his family since 1932.
</P>
<P>
   An NFL spokesman told ``The Arizona Republic'' that ``no one in
the league is talking about moving the Cardinals, starting with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bidwill said the Cardinals ``are all ears'' to stadium
possibilities in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals also might get assistance from a change in NFL
policy (Resolution G-3) that could allow the league to contribute
as much as 50 percent of the private money for new stadium
projects. The league's contribution would be a loan to be repaid
from visiting teams' shares of club seat premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts officials are using that to build a $225 million
stadium for the New England Patriots in Foxboro.
</P>
<P>
   Tempe Mayor Neil Giuliano already has suggested finding a way to
renovate Sun Devil Stadium, where the Cardinals have played since
moving to the Valley in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   But the team doesn't seem interested in remaining the only pro
team playing in a college stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cardinals still need a facility that is comfortable for
the fans and that allows us the ability to remain competitive,''
Michael Bidwill said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, John F. Long, the West Valley developer who donated
the land for the Maryvale baseball complex used as a spring
training home for the Milwaukee Brewers, said he again would
entertain the prospect of offering the Cardinals free land for a
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, he offered the team a parcel just north of
Interstate 10 between 79th and 77th avenues, near Blockbuster
Desert Sky Pavilion. But the deal went nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really haven't thought much about it, but I guess we would
be willing to listen if they had something,'' Long said. ``We're
always interested in any and everything that helps the west side.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Valley leaders have said they won't give up.
</P>
<P>
   After Tuesday's results, House Speaker Jeff Groscost, R-Mesa,
pledged to work on a revised Rio Salado Crossing plan.
</P>
<P>
   And Kerry Dunne, executive director of the East Valley
Partnership, said he would be willing to go through the wars again
if a project to benefit the East Valley could be resurrected.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, the Cardinals spoke to members of three
Indian communities _ the Gila River, Salt River-Pima Maricopa and
Fort McDowell _ about building a stadium on reservation land.
</P>
<P>
   Several league owners said at the time that they had a problem
with placing a stadium on a site that allows casino gambling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a couple of initial conversations,'' Michael Bidwill
said. ``We never got to the point where we had the interest of the
East Valley Partnership, and those conversations are all dormant
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the Cardinals don't appear to be going anywhere soon, it's
time for a cooling-off period, a key Valley sports official says.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Sculley, executive director of the Maricopa County Sports
Commission, hopes to bring all the parties together after a few
months to come up with a viable plan for a stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to let cooler heads prevail,'' Sculley said. ``After
a while, we will make an attempt to get all the parties together.''
</P>
<P>
   The parties include the Cardinals, Arizona State University, the
Fiesta Bowl and a potential Major League Soccer franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Sculley says if the parties could find consensus on a new
approach toward solving the Valley's stadium problem, something
good would happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not out of the realm of possibility that we could come up
with a plan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sculley said any plan would need unified support from the state,
county and Valley cities, and that it would not be successful if it
involved a sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   He advocates a simpler stadium plan than the massive, $1.8
billion Rio Salado Crossing stadium and convention center proposal
that went down to defeat Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan was just overwhelming to the general public,'' he
said. ``We need something that is not so grandiose.''
</P>
<P>
   Sculley hopes to put the issue on all key parties' radar screens
by the time football season rolls around and the bitter taste of
election defeat goes away.
</P>
<P>
   There's just too much at stake, he said, citing NFL football,
the Super Bowl, the Fiesta Bowl and a better facility for Sun
Devils football.
</P>
<P>
   With Tuesday's loss of the Rio Salado Crossing project by a 3-2
margin, the NFL won't be following through on its pledge to bring a
Super Bowl in 2004, 2005 or 2006 to the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was contingent on a new stadium,'' NFL spokesman Greg
Aiello said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the city of Phoenix, home to Bank One Ballpark and
America West Arena, hasn't thought about getting into the stadium
game again. At least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not even on the radar screen,'' Councilman Sal DiCiccio
said.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, McNair has the rights to an exclusive deal with the
Harris County (Texas) Sports Authority to build a $310 million,
retractable-roof stadium adjacent to the Astrodome. His exclusivity
runs until Jan. 31, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Chip Namias, a spokesman for McNair, said McNair sympathizes
with the Cardinals because ``they worked so hard and it was very
important to them.''
</P>
<P>
   But McNair told Houston station KRIV-TV that he wanted to reopen
talks with the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a way we could participate with them, either buying
it or being partners with them and moving to Houston, yes, we would
have a definite interest in that,'' McNair said. ``But it's
important to us that we have Houstonians owning the Houston team.''
</P>
<P>
   Namias said that even if McNair were a minority owner of the
team, he would want control of the club.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio has sought an NFL team for the Alamodome. But an NFL
observer close to the San Antonio situation said Red McCombs, the
San Antonio native who owns the Minnesota Vikings, wants to protect
the San Antonio market as leverage in case he doesn't get a new
stadium in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Two other cities that have been mentioned for possible NFL teams
are Hartford, Conn., and Toronto. But league owners likely wouldn't
vote to move teams there because of Hartford being in the Patriots
market area and Toronto's proximity to Buffalo. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
