</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO IS THAT RIDING TO RESCUE? IT'S TEMPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - This was not the end. This was an overweight trial
balloon exploding on takeoff. A hopeless referendum bellying up.
</P>
<P>
   Proposing a tax to the voters of Mesa is like bringing the hen
house to a fox. Like trying to sell air conditioners in Alaska. And
if this was the Cardinals' best shot, well, they're dumber than
advertised.
</P>
<P>
   No, this was not the end. Only the prelude to an end.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday morning, Tempe Mayor Neil Giuliano re-emerged as a
popular man. A man whose city once again holds a big hand in the
Cardinals' future. And the first offer is what you might expect, an
invitation to participate in a vague project, the sketchy $200
million renovation of Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're filling the lake on June 2,'' Giuliano said. ``The best
location is Sun Devil Stadium. If the Cardinals want to come in and
explore what renovations would be necessary to accommodate their
needs, I'm sure the university would be open to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely, the Cardinals have other plans. And while a move to
Houston is certainly a clear and present danger, Giuliano's offer
is just another trial balloon, the start of what could be the final
drama.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliano is desperately trying to save the Fiesta Bowl. The
Bidwill family would very much like to settle down and retire the
vagabond image. These are the bookends of compromise, and with the
Super Bowl and the Bowl Championship Series and the lure of the
Final Four, there is too much at stake for everything to die in
Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   There are too many heavyweights with too much to lose, and too
much money left on the table for someone else to seize.
</P>
<P>
   No, this is not the end.
</P>
<P>
   If Tuesday's referendum really had been the last stand, you
would have witnessed an all-out barrage. NFL Commissioner Paul
Tagliabue would have been front and center, exerting a league
provision to float huge loans in the name of private capital. Bill
Bidwill Jr. wouldn't have infuriated his family by refusing to show
up at election headquarters on Tuesday. The old man would have left
his fishing jacket in the closet and dressed for the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue knows all about the stubborn mule that is the Arizona
voter, but for the past few weeks, he has been conspicuously
silent. And in his concession speech, Bill Bidwill looked very
content, describing the process as a ``tremendous experience.''
</P>
<P>
   They must be saving their bullets for another battle.
</P>
<P>
   Like the one that's just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 60-40 loss in Mesa tells me you don't go back to Mesa, no
matter what,'' Giuliano said. ``A 60-40 loss is not something you
can attribute to strategic error.''
</P>
<P>
   When Tempe bailed on the Rio Salado Crossing, there were
questions about Cardinals greed. Why would they reap master
development rights on property surrounding the stadium? Why would
they receive non-game day parking revenue? And why the mad rush for
a spot on the November ballot?
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, when Tempe bailed, it was over. And now it's
coming full circle, to where the answer must rest.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is the lingering notion of a peace-pipe
conclusion. The Cardinals simply turn in the rain check, grab the
free land and build a stadium on an Indian reservation. The NFL
wears a public frown when it comes to casino gambling, but the
league is careful not to look like complete hypocrites. After all,
football is gambling, a fact the NFL will neither confirm nor deny.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, it could happen. And if done tastefully, it could be
a shrine to the American Indian, a romantic stadium true to its
historic roots.
</P>
<P>
   But that would kill the dream of a Final Four and do nothing to
solve the growing dilemma over the Fiesta Bowl. So the Cardinals
and the city of Tempe once again cross paths, and surely, there is
a plan. A way to scale down Rio and make it work. For everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their stadium district dissolves after 30 days, and then, it's
a clean slate,'' Giuliano said. ``There are a lot of different
scenarios floating around. And we're willing to talk to them about
it.'' &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at (602) 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
