<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-GIANTS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZALEZ HITS WALL 
 GOES 0-4, SEES STRING END AT 30 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Pride, a return to first place and even a bit of
revenge.
</P>
<P>
   That's what San Francisco Giants left-hander Alan Embree was
pitching for when he faced Diamondbacks left fielder Luis Gonzalez
on Wednesday at 3Com Park with what appeared to be one last chance
to extend his hitting streak to 31 games.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs in the top of the eighth inning, Embree fed the
left-handed-hitting Gonzalez a steady diet of off-speed pitches,
getting him to swing at a slider down and away in the dirt, and it
was over.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, was the Diamondbacks' one-day stay by themselves atop
the National League West, as the Giants used home runs by Jeff Kent
and Rich Aurilia and 10 walks to record an 8-3 victory and pull
even with Arizona at 23-18.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had pitched him (Gonzalez) well all day, and I didn't want
to be the one to give it up,'' said Embree, who was followed to the
mound by ace closer Robb Nen in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't want to give it up, especially when it was one of his
former teams. Embree was acquired by the Giants Nov. 10 in a trade
that sent outfielder Dante Powell to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's satisfying to do it against the team that traded
you,'' Embree said. ``We needed a shot in the arm, to get back into
first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Embree had faced Gonzalez before in 1997 when Embree was with
the Atlanta Braves and Gonzalez with the Houston Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew a little bit about him, and it was my goal to try to
get him to chase something,'' Embree said. ``Yeah, I knew what was
going on. I knew he had an 0-for and knew he was coming up when the
crowd got louder.''
</P>
<P>
   For all their bluster normally directed at opponents, the 3Com
fans gave Gonzalez a nice, loud ovation when he returned to left
field in the bottom of the eighth. He tugged on the bill of his cap
in response.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not disappointed at all,'' Gonzalez said of the streak's
demise. ``I got a lot of support from my teammates and fans in
Phoenix and around the country. I got to 30 games, and that is
quite an accomplishment, being with an elite group of
ballplayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter: ``The most rewarding
thing about the streak was how it was directly connected to us
playing good baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   In the city where legend Joe DiMaggio was born, Gonzalez found
it difficult to believe that the 56-game hitting streak that came
in 1941 will be broken.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many different pitchers and match-ups, it will be
tough to do,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   The ending of the streak will not be the beginning of a
tailspin, predicted Diamondbacks hitting coach Jim Presley.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got too good of a flat swing, right through the (strike)
zone to let that happen,'' Presley said. ``He knows what he's
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The most amazing thing about it was how hard he hit the ball,
night after night. You never know how long these things are going
to last, so we were pretty quiet even into the 20s. But once it got
to 25, 26, we all got louder, had more fun with it. It was a great
run and it couldn't happen to a better guy. I know he doesn't
really like the limelight all that much. He'll just go out (today)
and try to get it going again.''
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks right-hander Andy Benes couldn't get it going and
fell to 2-5, giving up five runs (three earned), while walking six
and striking out four in six innings. Right-hander Amaury Telemaco
didn't fare better in his wake, giving up three runs (all earned)
and three hits while walking four in 1 innings
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like we were wild, but we missed, and you can't
afford to give up 10 walks in any game, period. You won't win very
often that way,'' Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   It is expected to be as tough during a four-game series against
the Colorado Rockies at Coors Field that begins tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The only Diamondback to get anything going with the bat was
catcher Damian Miller, who hit a two-run homer off left-hander Kirk
Rueter that gave Arizona the lead in the second and an RBI double
off Rueter in the seventh. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
