<HEADLINE>
STREAK OVER BUT THRILL WILL LINGER FOR A WHILE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO - After he swung and missed for strike one, he
backed out of the batter's box.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't feel comfortable at the plate and hadn't all day.
</P>
<P>
   Now something told him this could be it. He sensed the end was
near.
</P>
<P>
   He gathered himself. Looked around. Reflected. ``You never know
if you'll ever get here again,'' he said. ``I kinda took in the
moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Luis Gonzalez knew his streak would end, probably sooner than
later. After hitting safely in his 28th consecutive game, he
thought of Joe DiMaggio and the record, the noblest record in
baseball. Gonzo was impressed not by how far he had come but by how
far he had to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got halfway,'' Gonzalez said, a grin lighting his long
narrow face, ``I thought 'There's no way in ``hell'' I'll get
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez stepped back in. He pawed at the dirt. Tapped the
inside edge of the plate once with his bat as he does before each
pitch. Feet spread wide, back straight, he watched a fastball.
Strike two. I ; Is anything in baseball more exciting than a player
who starts hitting and keeps on hitting game after game after game?
We are fascinated with those who beat the odds and tempt fate.
Following Gonzalez as he climbed up the hit chart was like watching
a high roller at Las Vegas riding a hot streak.
</P>
<P>
   The gamble excites us. The longer he rolls the dice, the higher
the stakes, the bigger the thrill. The crowd around the table
grows.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio's 56-game streak is to baseball what ``Rock of Ages''
is to the Baptist Hymnal. En
</P>
</TEXT>
