<HEADLINE>
FIESTA BOWL STANDS BEHIND ITS SUPPORT OF PROJECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - On the morning after, with defeat pounding in his
head, Fiesta Bowl Executive Director John Junker said he had no
regrets about the bowl's endorsement of the failed Rio Salado
Crossing project.
</P>
<P>
   But the project's demise Tuesday does place the bowl in an
uncomfortable situation.
</P>
<P>
   The bowl now has no alternative to playing in Sun Devil Stadium,
which bowl officials think could be inadequate in a few years. And
in endorsing the Cardinals' plan for a new stadium, they irritated
Tempe Mayor Neil Giuliano and didn't deepen any friendships at
Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   But at least, Junker said, Valley residents now know the bowl
will struggle to remain among the nation's elite if it stays in an
unrenovated Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``To take the other position _ `gee, you should have been quiet
and not said anything' _ I think creates a big credibility
problem,'' Junker said.
</P>
<P>
   Junker and other bowl officials spent part of last weekend
campaigning for the Rio Salado Crossing project. They believed in
the project, Junker said, because it offered a concrete solution to
the bowl's facility problems, while the Sun Devil Stadium
reno6Be% &QC; 9 is
just a proposal, without a firm financing plan.
</P>
<P>
   Bowl officials think the Fiesta's long-term future could be
threatened if competing bowls have better stadium situations.
</P>
<P>
   The Fiesta is one of four bowls in the Bowl Championship Series,
which is designed to match the nation's two top teams at the end of
the season. The bowls rotate hosting the game.
</P>
<P>
   Three years remain in the basic BCS agreement, but officials are
expected to begin discussing a new contract within the next two
years. By then, the Fiesta Bowl could be facing competition from
bowls that play in newer stadiums, Junker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will begin to play an increasing, concerning role,'' Junker
said. ``We thought it was important to let the public know what
we're going to face.''
</P>
<P>
   Stadium revenue and the quality of a facility are important to
the bowl's success, Junker said, and the bowl likely will be a
player in future stadium developments.
</P>
<P>
   ASU is discussing spending as much $200 million to renovate Sun
Devil StadiuK
</P>
</TEXT>
