<SLUG> BC-LA-REFUGEES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVAR REFUGEES EN ROUTE TO HAVENS IN L.A. AREA HOMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: Today in story refers to Thursday.) 
BY MICHAEL COIT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The first ethnic Albanian Muslims from war-torn
Kosovo to seek refuge in Los Angeles are expected today and will
begin settling in host homes across the west San Fernando Valley
and the Conejo Valley, resettlement officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Hajrush and Renee Vlashi of suburban West Hills have been
scrambling with help from the Jewish Federation/Valley Alliance to
find the six families who agreed to house his 32 relatives for
their first weeks in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   They are due today at Los Angeles International Airport, joining
the recent wave of refugees from Macedonia. An additional 29 are
expected to soon join two other ethnic Albanian families, in
suburban Sherman Oaks and Altadena, north of L.A., officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see my family for eight years and finally, through
the Jewish Federation, they're all going to be here,'' said Hajrush
Vlashi, waiter in suburban Studio City. ``I'm overwhelmed with how
people have helped and cared. In such a short time, it's
unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Renee Vlashi, a professional puppeteer who is Jewish, turned to
the federation in West Hills after the Clinton administration
announced April 21 that it will bring 20,000 ethnic Albanian
Muslims to the United States to live with relatives and volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   The federation, through its Jewish Family Services agency, is
one of the main refugee resettlement groups in Los Angeles. The
ethnic Albanian Muslims follow the Vietnamese, Iranian and Russian
Jews the group has helped settle in the region since the early
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no idea what we're in for. As a matter of fact, we
didn't expect this,'' said Miriam Prum Hess, who oversees the
federation's resettlement program.
</P>
<P>
   Julie and Michael Edelstein don't know what to expect as hosts,
so they are preparing their home in Westlake Village northwest of
downtown as much as possible for one family of Vlashi's relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what they have, but I wanted to have something to
make them feel welcome. We have a wonderful home and are happy to
share it,'' said Julie Edelstein, taking a break Wednesday from
preparing three bedrooms and packing groceries.
</P>
<P>
   Edelstein has spent time on the Internet learning Albanian
phrases, such as ``how are you'' and ``this is my dog,'' and
learning a little about their culture, including foods, and their
history.
</P>
<P>
   She also is preparing toilet kits and a few personal touches.
There are the L.A.-theme T-shirts and a computer-generated
``welcome'' sign in the Albanian language.
</P>
<P>
   Despite having little time to prepare, only learning of the need
for host families during a meeting Tuesday at the Jewish
Federation, the couple didn't hesitate. They were moved by the
``ethnic cleansing'' campaign of Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have everything. I have my health, I have my home, I have my
family and I just can't imagine walking away and leaving that all
behind,'' Julie Edelstein said.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees will welcome their freedom in the United States
from the suffering they have experienced in their homeland, said
Hajrush Vlashi. They have been living with relatives and friends in
Macedonia since fleeing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe the country I served (in the army) and grew
up in could do this to its own people,'' he said. ``I grew up with
Serbs, they were my neighbors. My generation never dreamed this
could happen to us or to anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs, mostly Orthodox Christians, maintain that Kosovo is
the birthplace of their religious and national identity.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts by the Serbian army to forcibly remove ethnic Albanian
Muslims from Kosovo reminds many Jews of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there's a crisis, the Jewish community has always been
there. The whole situation in Kosovo is very close to home,'' said
Barbara Creme, the federation's Jewish community relations
director.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little crazy, but it's very exciting and it's wonderful
to see such a positive response,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The federation provides signed assurances to the federal
government that the agency will resettle the families, who are
recognized as refugees by the U.S. Department of State.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees receive one month of cash assistance, which
averages about $300 a person, and three months of services.
</P>
<P>
   The federation provides a caseworker to work with host families.
They learn how to recognize post-traumatic stress, for instance,
given the ravages of war the refugees likely faced, and what is
expected in terms of housing and transportation.
</P>
<P>
   A second caseworker helps the families settle. There are Social
Security cards to obtain, health screenings provided by Los Angeles
County, English-language classes, children to enroll in school, and
job assistance programs.
</P>
<P>
   While the NATO goal is to return the refugees to their Kosovo
homes under the protection of an international security force, they
are eligible to remain here as refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The hosts have been asked to house families for as long as two
weeks. In the meantime, the federation will seek rental housing and
provide limited financial assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of Jewish temples in the area also are seeking financial
help, transportation and other forms of assistance from their
congregations.
</P>
</TEXT>
