<HEADLINE>
EL PASO INFIELDER BECOMES BIG HIT  
 DURAZO MAKES GAINS AT PLATE, WITH HIS GLOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Erubiel Durazo has had to adjust most of his life, moving from
Mexico to Tucson, learning English, fitting in, finding acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   It's always been easier on the baseball field, where he's made a
smooth transition from the Mexican League to the Texas League,
showing the Diamondbacks there is another young, left-handed first
baseman with potential.
</P>
<P>
   What he's done so far in Double-A El Paso has been an eye
opener.
</P>
<P>
   Durazo, who graduated from Tucson Amphitheater High in '93,
entered Wednesday running away with the league batting title with a
.431 average (53 for 123). The next-closest player is 50 points
behind. Durazo had a 14-game hitting streak, during which he hit
.537 with seven homers and 21 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew he could hit, but I think he's played beyond our
expectations at this point,'' said  &UR; Tommy Jones, Arizona director
of minor leagues. ``He's hitting the ball to all fields. He's
played a solid first. He's showing a lot of ability.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  &LR; $U4a DZX[K,S,-
</P>
