<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOTTLEMYRE TO MISS AT LEAST 1 START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Although a magnetic resonance imaging test on
his right shoulder proved inconclusive Wednesday, Diamondbacks
pitcher
 &UR; Todd Stottlemyre will miss his next scheduled start Saturday
against the Colorado Rockies at Denver's Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre, who left Monday night's game against the San
Francisco Giants after having pain and stiffness while warming up
for the fifth inning, was scheduled to have a second, more detailed
MRI later Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   He also was examined by  &UR; David Zeman, the team's orthopedic
surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   Even if no damage is found, Stottlemyre will miss at least this
start because of the dye that is injected into the system as part
of the MRI procedure.
</P>
<P>
   The rotation will be altered as a result. Left-hander  &UR; Omar Daal
will have his next start pushed back from Friday night into
Stottlemyre's spot Saturday. Taking the mound Friday night will be
left-hander  &UR; Brian Anderson, who will be recalled from Triple-A
Tucson earlier that day.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who started 32 games for Arizona in 1998 and finished
12-13, was 0-1 with a 9.58 ERA and one save in eight relief
appearances for the Diamondbacks this season before being optioned.
He started two games for Tucson in an attempt to get his arm used
to a longer period of work.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Stottlemyre were not injured, Anderson likely would have
been recalled because of the rapid rate at which pitchers
extinguish themselves at hitter-friendly Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   That would give the Diamondbacks 12 pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter said everyone in the
bullpen will be available tonight, although he hopes he won't have
to use anyone with left-hander  &UR; Randy Johnson on the mound. &QL; 
Connor, umpire ailing &QL; 
The Diamondbacks on Wednesday were without the services of pitching
coach  &UR; Mark Connor, who was taken to a Bay area hospital after
experiencing severe pain as the result of what appeared to be
kidney stones.
</P>
<P>
   Connor likely will return to Phoenix for a few days of rest,
General Manager  &UR; Joe Garagiola Jr said. &UR; Connor's role with the big
club will be temporarily taken by  &UR; Gil Patterson, a roving pitching
instructor in the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Also,  &UR; Angel Hernandez, the second base umpire, left the field
because of pain in his lower back early in Wednesday's game, but he
returned. &QL; 
Time change &QL; 
The game next Wednesday between the Diamondbacks and the San Diego
Padres at Bank One Ballpark has been moved from 7:05 p.m. to 7:35
to accommodate a national cable telecast on ESPN. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
