<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-TICKETS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES PRICES STAY SAME  
 SEASON TICKET COSTS FROZEN FOR 3RD STRAIGHT YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. - Seizing an opportunity to further cash in
with their fans a day after voters approved the first step for a
new arena, the Coyotes on Wednesday announced plans to freeze
season ticket prices for next season.
</P>
<P>
   It's the third straight year in which the Coyotes have kept
prices in check.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fans have been incredibly supportive during our first
three seasons and this is our way of showing our appreciation,''
said Brenda Tinnen, Coyotes senior vice president of marketing and
sales.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a modest increase in the price of single-game
tickets for next season, but the continuing price freeze for season
ticket holders is unusual. The Coyotes claim they have lost up to
$15 million since 1996-97, due in part to 4,200 sight-obstructed
seats at America West Arena, which sits 16,210 for hockey.
</P>
<P>
   An official from the ``Team Marketing Report,'' which does
ticket price analysis, recently said teams in the four major sports
usually raise prices by 7 percent annually. And if they skip a
year, they may make a jump of 12 percent to 14 percent, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that's a good business decision by them,'' said Pat
Steinberg of Scottsdale, who said she has been a season-ticket
holder since the Coyotes' first season in the Valley. ``I don't
feel they had any choice, though. They would lose season ticket
holders if they raised ticket prices, in my opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``{I'd go watch them play anywhere, but America West Arena is an
uncomfortable arena. Not only are there a lot of bad seats, but
more and more women are attending hockey game, and the
accommodations for women just aren't good there at all. It takes a
whole period to stand in line just to use the restrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad they froze their prices. They needed to. Once we get
into that new building in Scottsdale, it will be a whole different
story. But as far as I'm concerned, it couldn't be better. We need
a new arena. It's a good thing for the team and the fans, and it's
a good thing for Scottsdale.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Scottsdale voters overwhelmingly approved the
formation of a stadium district to proceed with plans for a
proposed $624 million sports-entertainment complex on the site of
Los Arcos Mall to be anchored by an 18,000-seat hockey arena.
</P>
<P>
   Tinnen said Wednesday's announcement regarding the freeze in
season ticket prices would have been made regardless of Tuesday's
election outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been in the works for a while,'' Tinnen said. ``We've
been analyzing it for the past month. This would have been the
prices, win or lose on Tuesday's vote, win or lose in the playoffs.
We just want to make it as easy as possible to be a season ticket
holder and to grow our fan base.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGinley, a season ticket holder who sits in Section 111,
where many of the fans, including himself, dress up in hockey
helmets and thick, black glasses, applauded the team's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wonderful. I think it's a great move,'' he said. ``It's a
way of showing they care about the fans. They get plenty of my
support anyway, but I'll look at them a lot differently now. It
also may change the way I spend my sports dollar on other teams in
the Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinley also has season tickets for the Cardinals, Arizona
State football and the Diamondbacks, but he said he considered
canceling after the baseball team announced ticket prices increases
during Fan Appreciation Weekend late last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes, who have a season ticket base of about 10,000, also
announced they will continue to offer an automatic monthly payment
plan, which allows season ticket holders to pay for their seats
during the course of the season through automatic withdrawals from
their checking or savings accounts. Other professional teams that
have used the plan include the NHL's Los Angeles Kings and Colorado
Avalanche and the NBA's Minnesota Timberwolves and Denver Nuggets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a unique system that lets you pay over five or six months
without maxing your credit card and having to pay additional
fees,'' Tinnen said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
