<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDD WON'T ATTEND DRAFT LOTTERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Suns have changed their plans for Saturday's NBA draft
lottery, which will be televised by NBC.
</P>
<P>
   The club had planned to have  &UR; Jason Kidd at the lottery to
represent the Suns. But Kidd will be attending the funeral of his
father,  &UR; Steve, in Oakland, as will Coach  &UR; Danny Ainge. General
Manager &UR; Bryan Colangelo will represent the club instead.
</P>
<P>
   The lottery order is determined using 14 pingpong balls,
numbered 1-14. There are 1,000 possible four-number combinations
that can be drawn, and the Suns will be assigned 36 of those
possible combinations.
</P>
<P>
   If any of the 36 Phoenix combinations come up first, second, or
third, the Suns would have the first, second or third pick in the
draft.
</P>
<P>
   Teams that do not land among the top three will be arranged in
inverse order of their record. The bottom line: The Suns cannot
pick lower than 11th. They have a 3.6 percent chance of landing the
top pick, a 4.17 percent chance of getting the No. 2 pick and a
4.93 percent chance of being awarded the third choice.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns are in the lottery because of Dallas' first-round pick,
which the Mavericks traded to Phoenix as part of a deal for  &UR; Steve
 &UR; Nash.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns have not participated in the lottery since 1988, when
the club picked Temple's  &UR; Tim Perry with the seventh choice in the
first round. &QL; 
Kidd's the Man
</P>
<P>
   Kidd is honored in the current issue of`` Basketball News''
magazine as that publication's choice for Player of the Year. Kidd
joins San Antonio's &UR; Tim Duncan, Utah's  &UR; Karl Malone, Miami's &UR; Alonzo
Mourning and Philadelphia's  &UR; Allen Iverson on the magazine's
All-NBA first team.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix forward &UR; Clifford Robinson, who was not included among
the two NBA all-defensive squads picked by coaches this season, is
on ``Basketball New''s' second-team all-defensive unit. &QL; 
Visits begin
</P>
<P>
   The Suns will begin bringing top draft prospects to the Valley
next week for interviews and workouts leading up to the June 30
draft, to be held at the MCI Center in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have some players in next week and the week following
that,'' Colangelo said. ``There are some complications because
number of the players who are underclassmen don't have agents yet.
Several also have decided to await the results of the lottery order
before they commit to visits.''
</P>
</TEXT>
