<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT WITH THE JAZZ, IN WITH THE KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Something must be done about the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   The old school pick 'n' rollers with a penchant for flopping and
arm-grabbing are disrupting the youthful, upstart spirit of these
NBA playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Iverson and Philly. Tim Duncan and the Spurs. Kobe and
Shaq with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   If only the basketball gods could bring back Jason Williams,
please.
</P>
<P>
   And while I never thought I'd say it, bring back Chris Webber
and Vernon Maxwell, too.
</P>
<P>
   Bring back Corliss Williamson and Vlade Divac, because maybe if
the Kings got a third chance to beat the Jazz, they might finally
get it done. We could all use another round of TBS and TNT
announcers gushing and chuckling over the no-look passes and
breakneck crossover dribbles of Pistol Pete Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento was the funnest team in the postseason. They were the
life of the party, the way Williams played with John Stockton's
mind and Webber body-slammed home a few messages.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, all the pressure of knocking off the Jazz is on the
Blazers, another upstart team. Judging from Game 1 of that Western
Conference semifinal, though, Utah seems doggedly inspired to prove
that in playoff crunch time experience and $10,000 high-flying
elbows are nine-tenths of the law.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers did get rattled. As Cheryl Miller pointed out during
her sideline report Tuesday at the Delta Center, if former Running
Rebels Greg Anthony and Stacey Augmon are the two most rational,
level-headed veterans on Portland's bench, you understand why the
Blazers lack the maturity to hang with the steady-as-a-jackhammer
Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is a youth-movement NBA postseason. We're going to
stand by Rasheed Wallace and see if the Blazers can keep their cool
in the end.
</P>
<P>
   Tops on our wish list is to see Paul Allen leading the wave in
the Rose Garden this weekend, though Allen must take care not to
rip the underarms of those expensive suit jackets.
</P>
<P>
   Is it heresy to take up the Blazers' cause, the same way we were
sucked into the spunk and spirit of the Kings?
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, there is a special feeling of kinship with the
dearly departed Kings. After all, the Sonics picked up two-fifths
of the old Sacramento starting lineup in Billy Owens and Olden
Polynice. We all know how far that got us.
</P>
<P>
   But in exchange for adopting the Kings' used parts, Seattle can
take credit for clearing the Kings' roster and opening the curtain
on a new era in NBA basketball. The Sonics' loss was Sacramento's
gain, which delighted hoop fans across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   If the absence of Michael Jordan was assumed to be the death
knell for the league, these Air-less playoffs have opened our eyes
to the entertaining youthful alternatives who, with no Jordan
around to draw impossible comparisons, have demonstrated they
possess the game, star power and competitive will to make May
madness must-see TV.
</P>
<P>
   Bully to you, Mr. Stern. The kids are all right, aren't they?
</P>
<P>
   In fact, with Iverson securing his first NBA scoring title and
leading the Sixers in a decisive run over Penny Hardaway (the
second coming of Jordan once, no?), the NBA has officially unveiled
its new crop of stars.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson's 33-point, 10-steal, 5-assist wizardry in Game 3
against Orlando was a defining moment for the controversial
third-year player. One game after Iverson had been the victim of
Orlando coach Chuck Daly's ``Iverson Rules'' _ when the Magic
rewrote the ``Jordan Rules'' for Iverson and knocked the
waterbug-quick guard on his butt all night long _ Iverson soared.
</P>
<P>
   For Iverson to come back from Game 2's smash-mouth Orlando
defense and take charge of Game 3 and the series proves that,
beyond his penchant for hoisting up shots, there lurks an
unconsciously talented ballplayer on whom NBC can hang its Big Bang
broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, we'll admit it. We want Iverson to take down Indiana, just
as it seems fitting to hope the Blazers dispense with the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Jordan's retirement package should have been that
Stockton, Karl Malone, Bryon Russell and Shandon Anderson could not
assume the first No-Air NBA title was theirs for the taking.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, when Jordan pushed Russell out of the way in Game 6
for that '98 championship-winning jumper in Salt Lake City, it was
a signal:
</P>
<P>
   Jordan took what was rightfully his. With that shove, Jordan hit
his final shot, won the final game and all but declared that since
the Jazz could not beat the Bulls during Jordan's reign, then Utah
should take its cue and understand its place in history.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz's shining moment was to serve as Jordan's final foil.
They were a vaguely sympathetic lot back then.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, it is a new era. It's not that the Jazz deserve
disdain, but if we can't have the perfection of Jordan whipping the
venerable pros of Utah, we are surprisingly eager to root for the
wildness and audacity of youth.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 0132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
