<SLUG> BC-STAR-HOOKY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY FAR, FAR AWAY DRAWS FAITHFUL FROM CAMPUSES, BUSINESSES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JESSE HIESTAND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Star Wars'' fans ditched classes, skipped
college lectures, put meetings on hold and mustered a myriad of
excuses to catch the newest installment on the first day of its
release.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything for `Star Wars,' '' said Barbara Bonds, 30, in line
for the 11 a.m. showing at General Cinema's Sherman Oaks theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told a customer that I had an appointment but didn't quite
tell them I was going to the movies,'' said Bonds, who runs a
concierge service for people who don't have time to run errands.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same across L.A.'s San Fernando Valley and the nation
as millions of people put their daily grind on hold Wednesday to
lose themselves in ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   San Fernando Valley schools didn't notice an abnormally high
absentee rate, but the smattering of young faces in line suggested
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Trent Olsen, 14, and three fellow ninth-graders from Campbell
Hall School in North Hollywood carefully executed a plan to skip
the second half of the school day. They were still in the school
uniform of white polo shirt and tan slacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just finals,'' Trent said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked our butts off all year. We deserve a break,'' added
friend Michael Quiroz, 15, of North Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Script developer Louis Farber and his boss, Peggy Howard Chane,
didn't drop their work completely. They brought along scripts to
read while waiting in line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided why would we want to be in the office while we
could be out watching `Star Wars,' '' said Chane, a director and
producer for CPC Entertainment in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce College student Steve Sommers, 25, of Van Nuys said he
waited several years to see the new movie and was not about to let
English class delay him any longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love `Star Wars.' It's basically the reason I came out to
Los Angeles to get into the film industry,'' said Sommers, who
arrived from Milwaukee three years ago and is now studying film
production. ``This is a special day.''
</P>
<P>
   With her parents' encouragement, 6-year-old Heather Goldfarb
took the day off from Woodland Hills Elementary School. She and her
parents, Dan and Barbara Goldfarb, studied the ``Star Wars'' series
by watching the first three movies in succession.
</P>
<P>
   She found it frightening at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked the whole movie,'' Heather said. ``It was a bit scary
in the first place but then I got used to it and remembered what my
dad and mom talked about _ that the blood was only ketchup, red
paint or dye.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Goldfarb said she had no qualms about keeping her child
out of school for a day to catch the movie: ``It's an occasion
she'll remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Menendez, 29, a Studio City resident who works on the
Spanish-language police show ``Placas,'' said he indulged his inner
teen-ager when he saw the movie for the first time at midnight
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to let the 13-year-old in you come out or else you
might find some parts are a little too geared to kids,'' he said
while lining up to see the movie again, this time to study the
craft and take in more of the details he missed in the first
viewing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
