<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLONIAL-TREE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHOUT PECAN TREE, 18TH HOLE AT COLONIAL WON'T BE SAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The closing stretch of this week's
MasterCard Colonial will be unlike any other in the tournament's
53-year history.
</P>
<P>
   That much became clear in October, when a signature pecan tree
guarding the left-hand side of the 18th fairway toppled after heavy
rains. Since the course's inception, gnarled branches from that
tree had overhung the fairway, stretching toward the ground and
impacting the approach shots of golfers who hooked drives into the
left rough.
</P>
<P>
   The tree's presence, said Harrison Frazar, altered strategy for
many players.
</P>
<P>
   ``With it sitting there, most guys just tried to hit a 3-wood
down the right side and draw it back to the middle,'' said Frazar,
one of 112 competitors scheduled to tee off in today's opening
round at Colonial Country Club. ``Now, you may see more guys hit
driver down the middle and take their chances. That's going to
alter the hole a bunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Frazar and tournament officials envision the possibility of more
birdies this year on Colonial's closing hole. Other competitors
disagree, saying most players hit past the tree on their drives and
that replacement trees planted last fall at No. 18 serve as a
similar, but less daunting, deterrent for the pull-hooked tee shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you never knew it was there, you'd never miss it,'' David
Ogrin said. ``I don't think it will make that much difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The proof will be found in the scoring average, which shows that
No. 18 traditionally ranks ninth among the course's holes in
difficulty. The 427-yard par-4 hole played to a scoring average of
3.902 in last year's tournament, its lowest mark over the past
eight years. In 1994, players needed 4.154 strokes per trip at No.
18.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Russell, the PGA Tour tournament official in charge of
setting up the Colonial layout, sides with the group anticipating a
birdie bonanza. Without the tall tree, players won't be forced to
hit low, punch shots from the left rough. Recoveries from bad
drives will be easier and birdies, in all likelihood, will be more
plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely missed,'' Russell said of the fallen tree.
``You can't replace something like that. It's just a shame. I think
it'll be a big factor in scoring this week. Before, the players
were very concerned about hitting the ball over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Without question, said Davis Love III, there is more room for
error off the 18th tee this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, if you really killed one off the tee and tried to
cut the corner, you'd still get tangled up,'' Love said. ``You
might get away with one now.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hulbert, playing in his 14th Colonial, said: ``There's more
potential to make birdie from the rough now. In the past, you were
scrambling just to make par.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Furyk, runner-up to Watson at last year's Colonial, said he
doesn't anticipate a dramatic change in scoring at No. 18. But he
can envision a situation where ``a few guys slide by \Rafter bad
drives\S that couldn't before.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone hits it down the left side and makes birdie, then
you've got something,'' Furyk said. ``I guess that could happen,
but it's still not likely.''
</P>
<P>
   Justin Leonard and Tom Watson, the defending Colonial champ,
joined Ogrin in predicting a minimal change, at most, in scoring
conditions at No. 18. Ben Crenshaw, the U.S. Ryder Cup captain who
is playing in his 29th consecutive Colonial, said the hole provides
a visual jolt to longtime visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does look different. I remember that tree so well and it
did play havoc with shots,'' Crenshaw said. ``I think everyone
who's played here has been under that tree at some point. It's sad
to see it gone. But you can still find trouble on that hole, the
way they have it set up.''
</P>
<P>
   Just not as much trouble as in years past. That's why Omar
Uresti said he wouldn't be surprised to see the 1999 Colonial
decided by a birdie on the 72nd hole _ a rarity in Colonial annals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as intimidating sitting back there on the tee box as
it used to be,'' Uresti said. ``More guys will be willing to try
and take it down the left side. I'll probably hit driver down the
middle and take my chances. If you hook it, it's not as big a
concern. I think you'll definitely see more birdies and pars down
the stretch.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
