<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-DEVIL-RAYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS APPLY TRUSTY TOURNIQUET IN RELIEVER ZIMMERMAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ One of Jeff Zimmerman's assets, in addition
to a 90-plus mph fastball and a devastating slider, is a large dose
of humility.
</P>
<P>
   Suggest to the rookie right-hander that he is the Rangers most
valuable player for the first seven weeks of the season, and he's
quick to go into denial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all, not with the way Palmeiro's been swinging the
bat,'' Zimmerman said. ``Us guys in the bullpen are kind of the
bottom feeders of the baseball world.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Rafael Palmeiro is not a bad choice. The Rangers'
designated hitter has a .377 average with 11 homers and 36 runs
batted in, and played a big role in the team's 7-6 victory against
the Tampa Bay Devil Rays yesterday at The Ballpark in Arlington
with two home runs.
</P>
<P>
   But without Zimmerman, the Rangers probably don't beat Tampa
Bay, and they're probably not in first place in the American League
West.
</P>
<P>
   The game resembled an episode of ``Home Run Derby,'' with the
two teams combining to smash seven balls out, before Zimmerman
entered and seized control.
</P>
<P>
   The score was tied, 6-6, when he came in with two runners on and
two outs in the sixth inning. He struck out dangerous slugger Jose
Canseco to end the uprising, then pitched two more perfect innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers scored in the eighth, when Tom Goodwin singled home
Roberto Kelly, to give Zimmerman his third victory in as many
decisions. John Wetteland finished for his 12th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to say,'' manager JohDNy &LR; Qes said. ``He's
using the same scouting report as everybody else, believe it or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' starters aren't doing much with those scouting
reports. Mark Clark pitched 5 2/3 ineffective innings, surrendering
six runs (five earned) on nine hits, including a mammoth, 491-foot
shot by Paul Sorrento and two-run shots by Canseco and Fred
McGriff.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's earned-run average rose only slightly, from 7.53 to
7.58, and the starters' ERA as a group hovers just below 7.00.
</P>
<P>
   When the rotation is going that badly, a club needs a strong
bullpen to bail it out.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Zimmerman.
</P>
<P>
   His ERA fell to 0.61, lowest among all big-league relievers. He
has retired 23 consecutive batters, tying the club record for a
reliever set by Gary Mielke in 1990. The Rangers are 13-3 when he
pitches, and he has appeared in eight of their past 10 victories.
</P>
<P>
   Although Palmeiro batted .500 with five homers and 13 RBI on the
seven-game homestand, those pitching stats seem to be team MVP
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ain't supposed to be this easy,'' Oates said. ``It's been a
long time since I've seen someone, every time out, be in command
like he is. His numbers speak for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The game did not look like one that would be decided by pitching
for the first five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay scored its first five runs on Sorrento's monster
homer, which landed at the very top of the grass berm in dead
center and was the longest ever hit at The Ballpark, Canseco's
two-run shot, which was prevented from being a tape-measure shot
only because it hit the left-field foul pole, and McGriff's
409-foot blast, also with a man aboard.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers outslugged the visitors with four homers, all off
former Texas starter Bobby Witt. Palmeiro hit one with Luis Alicea
aboard in the third and, after Rusty Greer doubled, Ivan Rodriguez,
Palmeiro and Todd Zeile went deep on consecutive at-bats in the
fifth for a 6-5 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay tied it in the sixth when Mike Difelice scored on an
infield single by Dave Martinez off Mike Venafro. That's when
Zimmerman did his imitation of a tourniquet, striking out Canseco
and breezing through the next two innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's incredible,'' Palmeiro said. ``He's been our savior all
year. Every game that he has been in has been a crucial situation
and he's come through.''
</P>
<P>
   So, where would the Rangers be without him?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to think about it,'' Oates said. ``Wow.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
