<HEADLINE>
WORLD'S SECOND-RANKED PLAYER BATTLES ACHING BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J. DOUGLAS FOSTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A month away from the PGA Tour wasn't enough
to get Davis Love III's ailing back feeling 100 percent again.
</P>
<P>
   The pain he experiences while playing, however, wasn't enough to
keep him away from the MasterCard Colonial again.
</P>
<P>
   Love, who moved up to No. 2 in the world rankings on Monday,
missed the Colonial last year because of a bad back _ the first
time he failed to play in the event since he first entered it in
1986.
</P>
<P>
   His disc problems began flaring again a month ago, forcing him
to withdraw from the MCI Classic before the final round. He also
backed out on commitments in Japan and New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   But for one of the Tour's biggest students of golf history,
Colonial was a different story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't want to miss Colonial,'' Love said. ``This is
one of my favorite tournaments. I missed it last year for the same
reason. I didn't want to miss it twice.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Colonial officials didn't want Love to be absent from
their event again, either. His presence means Colonial's field not
only has one of the Tour's most popular players, but also includes
two of the top five players in the world rankings (Vijay Singh is
No. 5).
</P>
<P>
   Yet getting here wasn't easy for Love. After missing the final
round of the MCI on April 18, Love put his clubs away until last
Tuesday. He spent his time at home in Georgia, catching up on some
golf-course design, fishing and attending a horse show with
10-year-old daughter Alexia.
</P>
<P>
   He said his back began to feel better _ at least until the past
two days, when he played in the Colonial Shootout, followed by
yesterday's pro-am. That's when the pain returned and Love realized
he'll need a different approach this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely not going to be 100 percent,'' Love said. ``I
would be happy if I was 75 \Rpercent\S or 80 percent. I'm not going
to be bombing it over the corner at 3 and 5. I'll be easing it
around there.''
</P>
<P>
   So Love will take a slightly more conservative approach _
something he said he's going to start doing with his entire career.
His return this week is part of preparation for the U.S. Open,
which is a month away. After the Open, he plans to give his back
more rest than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look back at all the stuff I've done leading up to
having a bad back _ playing five events in a row, 26 or 27 events a
year _ that contributes to getting worn down early,'' Love said.
``You don't want to slow down, but I have to learn to pace myself
and realize it's better not to play five in a row.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
