<HEADLINE>
SPURS NO LONGER PLAYOFF SOFTIES
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanks to sacrificial bangers Will Perdue and Malik Rose and the
commitment by Tim Duncan and David Robinson to shed their ``soft''
image, the San Antonio Spurs are no longer the NBA's phantom
menace.
</P>
<P>
   Their physical defense is suddenly real and real hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're coming at me pretty tough, and not within the rules,''
said Lakers center Shaquille O'Neal. ``But nobody's going to break
me.''
</P>
<P>
   In Game 1 of the second round of the Western Conference playoffs
Monday, the Spurs took turns hammering O'Neal in the paint. While
some teams concede O'Neal his 28 points per game, San Antonio
remarkably held him without a single dunk and sent him to the
free-throw line 14 times.
</P>
<P>
   For an interior long considered finesse and at the beginning of
the season even criticized by teammate Mario Elie, the Spurs'
frontcourt is taking a major step in the macho direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just can't let guys go the basket unobstructed,'' Robinson
said. ``This is playoff basketball and we've got to protect our
basket.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark it down: If the Spurs keep hacking Shaq, there will be a
brawl. More importantly, San Antonio will also win the series.
PACERS VS. SIXERS As good as Allen Iverson is, point guard Eric
Snow is as bad. Reluctant to shoot and inconsistent when he does,
the Sixers can't beat the Pacers with Snow running the show. ...
Entering last night's Game 2, Indiana's Travis Best had nine points
and 19 fouls in the playoffs. HAWKS VS. KNICKS The most ridiculous
coach in the playoffs is the Knicks' Jeff Van `Grumpy.' After his
team got a lucky bounce to upset the Heat and likely save his job
in Game 5, he left the court hurling expletives at referee Hue
Hollins because Terry Porter's final shot would have counted. ...
As predicted, Allan Houston and Latrell Sprewell of the Knicks are
too athletic for Atlanta's grind-it-out defense. The Hawks will get
swept if forwards Grant Long and Tyrone Corbin don't do better than
their two points on 1-of-12 shooting Tuesday in the opener of their
second-round Eastern Conference playoff series. JAZZ VS. BLAZERS
Temperament beat talent again Tuesday in Game 1 of their
second-round series, triggered by Rasheed Wallace's violent foul
and silly reaction early in the fourth quarter. The Blazers led by
four when Wallace slung Bryon Russell to the court and picked up a
technical for objecting to the obvious call, but were outscored
15-5 the rest of the quarter. NUMBERS GAME 1: Member of the Bulls'
dynasty still alive in the playoffs, another example that Jordan
was pretty good. Spurs backup guard Steve Kerr went 0-of-7 in the
first round and didn't play in Game 1 against the Lakers, but he's
faring far better than former Chicago teammates like Detroit's Jud
Buechler (3-of-15 vs. Hawks), Phoenix's Joe Kleine (only five
minutes vs. Blazers) and Luc Longley (2-of-12), Houston's Scottie
Pippen (32 percent shooting vs. Lakers) or nobody's Dennis Rodman.
Said Kerr, ``At least I know how to pick my bandwagons.'' CRYSTAL
ROUNDBALL The Grizzlies have the best shot at landing the No. 1
pick in Saturday's lottery, which won't include the Mavericks,
thanks to their trade for Steve Nash.
</P>
<P>
   The draft's likely top 10 picks: Rhode Island forward Lamar
Odom, Maryland guard Steve Francis, Duke center Elton Brand,
Connecticut guard/forward Richard Hamilton, UCLA guard Baron Davis,
Duke forward Corey Maggette, Miami-Ohio forward Wally Szczerbiak,
Georgia forward Jumaine Jones, Utah guard Andre Miller and Arizona
guard Jason Terry. 24 SECONDS Maybe Kings rookie Jason Williams was
the last to know that Utah's John Stockton always shoots the jumper
off the pick-and-roll in crunch time. Remember his Game 6 winner
against the Rockets in '97? His Game-6 miss against the Bulls in
'98? And now _ because Williams went under the screen and allowed
Stockton a clean look that saved the Jazz _ remember his 23-foot
buzzer-beater in Game 4 against the Kings? ... The winner of Game 1
in the second round has won the series 85 percent of the time this
decade. ... Most irritating ritual: teammates slapping hands with a
free-throw shooter after a miss. ... Where are they now? Must-have
free agents last February, Pippen, Ike Austin, Tom Gugliotta and
Antonio McDyess are now innocent bystanders. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
