<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RYAN STILL NOT RETURNING, SO RANGERS KEEP LOOKING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ It's a daily pursuit. Doug Melvin works the
phones frequently. Urgency prevails.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching help is needed now.
</P>
<P>
   What Melvin received Wednesday, however, was a message from a
pitcher offering lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan Ryan said he would be buying. Actually, it was the
highlight of Melvin's day, week, month and season. Maybe you
noticed _ major-league baseball has a drastic shortage of competent
pitchers. The Front Row Sports Grill never has a shortage of
cheeseburgers.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, who was in town for several days, mentioned nothing to
Melvin about making a comeback. Lunch was his best offer. Paul
Sorrento can relate.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, Rangers right-hander Mark Clark also served a
fat cheeseburger to Tampa Bay's Mr. Sorrento, a noted
Ranger-killer. Clark ``missed'' on a 2-1 count to Sorrento. History
was made at The Ballpark in Arlington. Sorrento took an
all-you-can-eat swing and his blast measured 491 feet to dead
center field, the longest home run ever in this yard.
</P>
<P>
   An inning later, Jose Canseco might have had more footage than
Sorrento, except this missile rattled the top of the left-field
foul pole. Two innings later, Fred McGriff drilled a 400-foot plus
homer.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, John Burkett didn't seem so bad after all.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers came roaring back with their own long-ball arsenal
off old friend Bobby Witt. Rafael Palmeiro, who has gone nuts, hit
two more homers. Witt gave up four in less than five innings,
including three straight (Pudge Rodriguez, Rafael, and Todd Zeile)
in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Mark Clark was outscored by his own team. Rangers
win, 7-6, surviving a John Wetteland scare in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   But pitching-wise, it has been the longest first seven weeks in
Rangers history. In late April, there was a prominent theory that
the starting rotation could not be as bad as it had performed.
Wrong. It's even worse.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, another homestand ended in a another disaster
Wednesday. The Rangers won only four of seven from the Orioles and
Devil Rays, while the rotation reached new depths. There have been
three homestands, and the overall record is a game under .500.
</P>
<P>
   No explanation is needed for this failure at home cooking. The
pitching staff's earned-run average in Arlington is a massive 6.70,
nearly two runs a game more than the road ERA.
</P>
<P>
   (OK, Juan. Both of us were apparently wrong in suggesting the
ballpark left-field fence should be moved closer.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Melvin keeps looking for arms, but expects to find
nothing. ``Not now anyway,'' he said. ``What I'm basically doing is
contacting clubs who at some point might want to trade pitching.
There are none at the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Waiting for help is as aggravating as watching the current
rotation. Clark has been a total failure as a free-agent signee
from last winter. Aaron Sele is doing everything to prove his 19
wins last season were a fluke. Mike Morgan, at age 39, at least has
a clue, while Rick Helling shows signs of coming around. Burkett
was yanked out of the rotation this week, replaced by rookie Ryan
Glynn, just in from Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that we have a lot of options, but bringing in our own
people \Rminor-leaguers\S has been a high point thus far,'' said
Melvin, meaning the work of Jeff Zimmerman and Mike Venafro in the
bullpen. Zimmerman has actually been too good, causing a concern
that Johnny Oates is overworking him.
</P>
<P>
   The promotion of Glynn last weekend also broke policy, at least
where Melvin's adamant stand against promoting center fielder Ruben
Mateo is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn, like Mateo, is in his first Triple-A season. Glynn, like
Mateo, was also showing great promise. But Glynn was rushed to the
majors while Melvin hopes Mateo will have a full season of Triple-A
exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is the immediate need for pitching help,'' said
Melvin, and Clark's bombing would add an exclamation point to his
answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If an injury put us in a position to bring up Ruben, he would
be here,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   With baseball in a heavy seller's market for pitching, any trade
for the Rangers will come at a steep price. And Melvin concedes an
eventual trade might prove impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you can't do, however, is say pitching is bad all over,
and then fall into a trap of thinking nothing can be done,'' he
added. ``You keep working at it, and hope something turns up, or
hope our rotation turns around.''
</P>
<P>
   And if all else fails, keep hitting home runs while Nolan Ryan
buys lunch. / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
