<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRINCIPAL-INDICT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRINCIPAL ACCUSED OF FAILING TO ACT ON MOLEST REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM HERMANN  
 CHRISTINA LEONARD AND BETTY REID  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ A Phoenix elementary school principal has been
indicted for failing to heed repeated warnings about a counselor
who is charged with molesting nine boys.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the indictment Wednesday against Joanne Talazus,
50, Maricopa County Attorney Richard Romley called her reputed
inaction ``outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It boggles the mind why she wouldn't take reasonable steps''
to protect the chidren from Ronald Maldonado Ruelas, Romley said.
</P>
<P>
   Ruelas, a Longview Elementary School counselor, was indicted in
February on 23 counts involving nine victims, including a relative.
Charges included child molestation, indecent exposure and sexual
abuse, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Ruelas, 31, was accused of fondling boys on the playground,
furnishing them with pornographic materials and exposing himself to
them. All but two of the boys were under 15 years old, the
indictment said. He groomed one boy for three years before sexually
molesting him, according to the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's grand jury indictment says Talazus was repeatedly
apprised of the abuse over a four-year period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time after time after time'' Talazus heard allegations against
Ruelas' misconduct, Romley said.
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``Arizona law is clear,'' about the obligation of
school teachers and administrators to report child abuse to
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Individuals in positions of responsibility for the care of
children should be held accountable when they shirk that
responsibility,'' Romley said. ``This is a very serious matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Talazus will be arraigned June 1 in a Maricopa County Superior
Court. She did not respond to repeated attempts to contact her
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Romley said Talazus will go through a booking process, but will
not be jailed. He said she is not considered a flight risk.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Haws, an attorney for the Osborn School District said, ``We
are taking the allegations very seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's premature to say what will happen other then we are
reviewing the information that we got today. We hope it is clear
that Ms. Talazus is not accused of abusing children herself.''
</P>
<P>
   School district board members voted unanimously to terminate
Ruelas, who now is being held at Madison Street Jail in lieu of
$500,000 bail. His trial is set for Oct. 20.
</P>
<P>
   The parents of seven reputed molestation victims on April 12
took the first step in filing a $65 million lawsuit against Osborn
School District officials by claiming the district knew of prior
complaints against Ruelas but took no action to stop him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools are supposed to be sanctuary for protecting kids, not
a playgound for perverts, and this administration did nothing to
prevent that,'' said Michael Vaughn, who is representing the
children.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the claim alleges, one teacher was fired after she came
forward with accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the families say that Talazus and Osborn
Superintendent Wilma Basnett knew about the allegations as far back
as 1994 from complaints made by students, parents and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Romley, however, said that evidence he has seen did not give
cause to investigate Basnett.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was not part of this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury indictment says that beginning in January 1994,
Talazus was informed of the reputed molestation of Longview
students. The reports allegedly continued to the end of December
1998.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment says Talazus ``failed to immediately report or
cause reports to be made of such information to a municipal or
county peace officer or to the protective services of the state
department of economic security, in violation of (Arizona law).''
</P>
<P>
   The indictment also says Talazus ``knowingly caused or permitted
(a child's) health to be injured or to be placed in a situation
where his health was endangered, in violation of (Arizona law).''
</P>
<P>
   Parents who complained about what they believed Ruelas was doing
received short shrift, according to a notice of claims filed
against the district last month by Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joanne Talazus made it clear that not only would any
complaints against Ron Ruelas be dismissed as false, but those
making such complaints would suffer the consequence,'' the claims
said. ``When a member of her faculty, Maxine Hotchkiss, complained
in writing about Ron Ruelas, she was fired.''
</P>
<P>
   Hotchkiss said in an April interview that the teachers at
Longview were terrified of Talazus, and she protected Ruelas
because he acted as her ``snitch'' against other teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I do think she was trying to cover up for Ron,''
Hotchkiss said.
</P>
<P>
   The claim asserts that Talazus gave an alleged ``child molester
free rein of her campus and created an atmosphere where even
dedicated teachers were afraid to complain about Ruelas.''
</P>
<P>
   The notice of claims demand was a precursor to filing a
class-action lawsuit. Because the school is a government entity,
the plaintiffs must first file an administrative demand in which
the defendants have 90 days to respond, Vaughn said.
</P>
<P>
   The district now must decide whether to pay the demand, deny the
claim or do nothing until the 90 days expire. After that, Vaughn
said, the families can file a lawsuit. As of Wednesday, the
district has not responded to the claim, he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the claims, Ruelas worked closely with students,
involving himself in both their school and home lives, helping with
homework, running after-school programs, and playing after-school
sports.
</P>
<P>
   However, Ruelas reportedly focused his attention primarily on
boys: ``As early as 1994, Longview Elementary staff observed that
`if it was a girl, forget it, that child would never get
counseled,' '' the claim stated.
</P>
<P>
   One student who alleges Ruelas molested him in 1994 told his
mother about his relationship with the counselor. His mother
immediately contacted the school.
</P>
<P>
   When Ruelas and Talazus confronted the student during a meeting,
the claim says, ``(the victim) was confronted with the allegations
and dismissed as someone who exaggerates things.''
</P>
<P>
   When the student approached teacher's aide Hotchkiss, she wrote
a two-page letter of complaint against Ruelas, which also was
ignored, Vaughn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Talazus) chose to ignore that warning and chose not to report
this complaint to (Child Protective Services) as required by law,''
Vaughn said. ``By doing that, it's our contention that she allowed
this guy to run rampant _ and now we have eight or nine victims.''
</P>
<P>
   In a police interview, Talazus admitted she was aware of a prior
allegations against Ruelas by two students, but that the situations
were resolved with the boys' parents.
</P>
<P>
   Romley said he knew of no other situation where a school
official has been prosecuted for failing to take action when he or
she has knowledge of abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we have an outrageous situation, we are going to pursue
it in court,'' Romley said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
