<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GUATEMALA-DEATH-SQUADS _ Officials are scheduled to make public
documentation on Thursday that they say supports accusations that a
secret Guatemalen military unit that kidnapped, tortured and
executed people during the early 1980s as part of a campaign
against leftists suspected of subversion.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ASSESS (Brussels) _ A news analysis on why the alliance
is fraying and whether the lack of a strong U.S. position on how to
conduct the war in Kosovo is a factor. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-BONES (Cambridge, Mass.) _ In what experts believe is the
largest single return of Indian remains, the bones of nearly 2,000
Pueblo Indians left the Peabody Museum here early Wednesday for the
ancient Pecos Valley site in New Mexico whence they came.
Simultaneously, the descendants of the Pecos skeletons set out on a
three-day trek on foot to receive the remains for a private mass
re-burial in New Mexico that tribal leaders say will cap a process
both solemn and full of joy. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   BUTTERFLY-DANGER (Undated) _ All around the country, farmers are
about to finish sowing millions of acres of a genetically altered
form of corn that protects itself from pests by producing a toxin
in its tissues. But researchers reported Wednesday that this
increasingly popular transgenic plant, thought to be harmless to
nonpest insects, produces a wind-borne pollen that can kill monarch
butterflies _ a species that claims the corn belt as the heart of
its breeding range. By Carol Kaesuk Yoon.
</P>
<P>
   FIJI-DIET (Undated) _ Just a few years after the introduction of
television to a province of Fiji's main island, Viti Levu, eating
disorders _ once virtually unheard of there _ are on the rise among
girls, according to a study presented Wednesday at the American
Psychiatric Association meetings in Washington. By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BARBOUR-LOBBY _ As Republican national chairman, Haley Barbour
was a central strategist in his party's campaign to cut the growth
of Medicare. Now he has taken on a new assignment. As a lobbyist
for nursing homes, he pleads with Congress to undo some of the
damage done them by the law he helped write. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-TRADING-WORKPLACE (Undated) _ The flick-of-the-finger
ease with which office workers and others can research, monitor and
trade stocks _ often able to return instantly to their assigned
tasks _ is of rising concern to employers. The stock market ``is
becoming a huge distraction,'' said Victor Woodward, a vice
president at Content Technologies, which develops programs to help
companies create and enforce policies for Internet usage. By Robert
D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   PRICE-FIXING (undated) _ Federal officials are on the verge of a
settlement with drug and chemical companies over accusations that
they fixed prices on vitamin products for people and livestock. By
David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   PSION-CELL-PHONES (Milton, England) _ By harnessing its Epoc
operating system, the basic software of its palm-top organizers, to
the next generation of wireless telephones, Psion PLC and the
world's biggest mobile phone producers are taking aim at no less a
target than Microsoft Corp. The stakes are huge because the winner
of this race will control the technology that cell phones and other
high-speed wireless devices use to connect people to their e-mail,
online stock brokers and myriad kinds of data on the Internet. By
Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   BROKERS-FRAUD-TRIAL (New York) _ The federal government's
high-profile case against a group of stockbrokers charged with
illegal trading on the floor of the New York Stock Exchange has run
into a significant snag. Prosecutors said Wednesday that they
cannot prove how much the defendants profited from the alleged
scheme, an admission that appears to substantially undermine a case
brought with great fanfare last year by Mary Jo White, the U.S.
attorney for Manhattan. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   MUTUALFUNDS-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The Securities Industry
Association, Wall Street's lobbying arm in Washington, is
encountering stiff opposition to a recent proposal that would make
it easier for brokerage firms to do business with their own mutual
funds. By Diana B. Henriques.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINES-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The Justice Department's
antitrust suit against American Airlines accusing it of predatory
behavior is easy to mock. Yet it would be premature to dismiss the
potential importance of the government suit. By Michael M.
Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   LANDS'END-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Lands' End's entire ad budget
through November, estimated at $15 million, seeks to sell the
apparel company's Web site, www.landsend.com, in a TV, print and
Internet advertising campaign. By Patricia Winters Lauro.
