<P>
   &UR; HOME (Moved in ``l'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   QUICK-REFUERBISH (New York) _ Carey Maloney and Hermes Mallea,
the designers of M (Group), were reeling their rolodexes and
flexing their shopping-arm muscles on behalf of Barry Gesser, a
single, 35-year-old hedge-fund manager who had purchased a house in
Bedford, N.Y., and on Memorial Day asked the designers to ``pull
his place together'' by the Fourth of July. He wanted it done _ and
spare no expense: Ten bedrooms, a pool house, stables, tennis
courts and two three-car garages _ overhauled, outfitted and
furnished (down to a selection of clothes hangars) in six weeks. By
Julie Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   HISS-APARTMENT (New York) _ In the center of the mantel, there's
an eight-inch wood plaque bought in the gift shop at the Federal
penitentiary in Lewisburg, Pa. The painted plaque shows the prison
as it looks now, and as it looked when Tony Hiss's father, Alger
Hiss, occupied a cell there, convicted of perjury back in the 1950s
for saying he didn't pass secrets to Whittaker Chambers, an
admitted Communist spy. The plaque is the newest memento in the
Hiss apartment, the same two-bedroom flat on East Eighth Street
that Alger and Prossy Hiss rented in 1947, when they moved up from
Washington; the apartment where Tony Hiss grew up; the apartment
that Hiss, now 57, shares with his own son, Jacob, 7, and his wife,
Lois Metzger, who writes sophisticated novels for teen-agers. By
Tracie Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   POP-RESTAURANT (New York) _ Pop, which opened in April, is much
more than just a deafeningly hot eatery with no sign in front. Read
the menu. Not the entrees or appetizers: a page at the back, titled
``About Pop.'' It's a mouthful: ``Pop is based on the post-war
social idealism and trust in technological innovation, mass
production and pre-fabrication. While it resonates with this
mid-century American dream, Pop has been realized with
end-of-the-century means....'' The author is Ali Tayar, the
architect who conceived this 2,500-square-foot temple of
retro-contempo chic. By Rick Marin.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-DESIGN (Nutley, N.J.) _ On said Richard Hartlage, a
garden designer and horticulturist from Seattle, who is now working
on his first two private gardens in the New York area. By Mac
Griswold.
</P>
<P>
   HORSE-CHESTNUT (New York) _ I was in one of those
down-at-the-mouth moods one morning last week as my cab tore down
Fifth Avenue, when a horse-chestnut tree hailed me from Central
Park. Its pyramidal white blooms _ like giant vanilla cones _ rose
high above the other trees, and I could swear some kind of cosmic
wink passed between us. If you have ever seen a horse chestnut in
bloom you know how impossible it is to ignore. It stands on the
greensward like some king in full regalia: velvet, satin, jewels,
scepter, the tall, magnificent bearing. By Ann Raver.
</P>
