<HEADER>
A4246 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZEDILLO-VISIT-LADN     05-20 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZEDILLO-VISIT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZEDILLO HAILS NEW ERA IN L.A. VISIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Mexico's President Ernest Zedillo, in a
historic-three day visit to California, has offered praise for the
new relationship between his country and the state and a pledge to
work with Gov. Gray Davis to create ``a North American dream.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have far to go,'' Zedillo said in a speech Wednesday to
Town Hall of Los Angeles. ``We now have a great friend here in
California (in Davis) who has made human relations a priority and
has declared Mexico the most important country for California.
</P>
<P>
   ``And California is important to Mexico. What happens in
California affects Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo and Gov. Gray Davis came from Sacramento to Los Angeles
by train and were greeted at Union Station by Mayor Richard Riordan
and other dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan offered praise for both Davis and Zedillo in seeking a
harmonious relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Zedillo) recognizes, as we do, that we cannot prosper as
independent communities if we do not prosper in partnership,''
Riordan said. ``As we celebrate our history, we also embrace the
dawn of a new century and the hope for a new generation where our
people can share in the bounty of opportunity, prosperity and
partnership,'' Riordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Davis and Riordan attempted frequent words and phrases in
Spanish, with the governor often referring to ``mi amigo.'' Riordan
said to Zedillo at one point, ``Nuestra casa es su casa.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who visited Zedillo on an official trip one month after
taking office, said his vision is to see California and Mexico
re-create the American dream as the North American dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``People came to America for liberty, opportunity, prosperity,''
Davis said. ``We want to see equal access to education, health care
and justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo credited Davis for the change in attitudes between the
two countries since his election and the retirement of Republican
Gov. Pete Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   It was Proposition 187 banning many benefits to illegal
immigrants and Wilson's support for it that led to a chill in
relations.
</P>
<P>
   The voter-approved ballot measure has been blocked by the courts
from taking effect and Davis is seeking mediation on the matter,
which has angered many Latino officials. Zedillo, however, backed
the governor and said relations between California and Mexico have
never been better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico is now your No.1 trading partner,'' Zedillo said.
``Just think how much better it could be.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Davis and Zedillo agreed to create a computer hookup
between universities in California and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, they announced California would create 15 trade
centers to work with companies to increase trade with Mexico. They
also announced plans by Mexico's Federal Electricity Commission and
America's Sempra Energy International to construct a 23-mile gas
pipeline, from the border to Rosarito to provide energy. Davis said
the project will include 500 jobs in California.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the U.S. Department of Transportation has approved a
$160,000 grant to study infrastructure needs along the border.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo also called for California authorities to work to
protect the human rights of all people, saying there had been some
problems with the treatment of immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the day was spent in saluting one another.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo took note of the number of Mexican descendants living in
Los Angeles _ more than anywhere else in the world outside of
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``They work hard and proud as (U.S.) citizens, but they do not
forget their heritage,'' Zedillo said.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo also talked of political reform that he is pushing on
his country, where his party will allow open primaries for the
first time in its 70-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``No longer will an official be elected only because he is from
one party,'' Zedillo said. ``We are moving toward more democracy.
We find that nearly all the time, the people are right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
