<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4256 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-20 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN ANTONIO _ They're just kids. NBA infants, really.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant and Tim Duncan have it all in front of them, all
right.
</P>
<P>
   But after a heart-stopping 79-76 San Antonio Spurs win that shed
so much light on the future _ and the present _ of these two
remarkable players, clearly Bryant has further to go.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan already has arrived. If he wasn't the heart and future of
the Spurs before, he certainly got there Wednesday night in a
dramatic, enlightening way.
</P>
<P>
   He did Most Valuable Player-type things, like he did all season.
He did what neither David Robinson nor anyone else in this
franchise's frustrating playoff history did much of before.
</P>
<P>
   With his father in town and watching from the Alamodome
grandstand, Duncan grabbed the ball on the low post, faked one way,
spun around poor Lakers defender J.R. Reid and softly and
confidently lofted the biggest hook shot of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most awesome feeling in the world,'' Duncan said.
``To have my dad here and hit that shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan couldn't say much more. But he didn't have to. He showed
why he is the soul of a Spurs playoff drive that looks legitimately
threatening.
</P>
<P>
   In the time it took Duncan to lift the Spurs upon his shoulders
and carry them to a 2-0 Western Conference semifinal playoff series
edge over the Los Angeles Lakers, he showed 33,293 fans and anyone
else who watched this thriller that he's not just ready to step up.
He already has.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim was huge,'' Spurs coach Gregg Popovich said. ``Like
always. Tim likes to take shots. We just looked at the matchup and
decided what fit this situation. He's not the kind of guy to get
flustered.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bryant tripped and fell face-first in this memorable
game, just when it seemed he was going to do Jordanesque things.
Just when Shaquille O'Neal was becoming the second option and
Bryant was spinning and elevating practically to the Alamodome
rafters, he flopped and then kicked the ground in frustration. Just
like a kid would do.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant scored 28 points, grabbed eight rebounds, passed the ball
like a whiz and confounded the Spurs on virtually every possession.
He was spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   While O'Neal yet again fought off wave after wave of big men
hacking at him inside, finishing with 16 points and eight rebounds,
Bryant flew everywhere. While O'Neal never was the first option in
the final critical seconds, Bryant stepped behind the 3-point line
and nailed a fadeaway go-ahead 3-pointer with less than a minute
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Bryant crashed back down to earth. He showed that he
remains a work in progress. He showed that he's just a kid who can
make you laugh and make the Lakers cry.
</P>
<P>
   In the time it took Bryant to clang a pair of potential
game-clinching free throws with 18 seconds remaining, that much
became so clear.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant stepped up to the line and talked a little garbage to the
Spurs' Mario Elie as the crowd begged for a miss. With the Lakers
up by one point and the Spurs looking for an answer offensively,
Bryant tossed the first free throw up, and when it bounced off, he
merely shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   He raised his eyebrows as if to say, ``Oh, well.'' But the next
one wasn't even close _ bouncing long and hard off the rim as if it
were O'Neal who shot it. Duncan grabbed the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on the other end, there was Duncan again, showing all the
poise of a young player who might be 23 years old to Bryant's 20
but throughout the first two games of this tough, bitter series has
been decades more mature.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan's eight-foot half-hook hit nothing but net. He pointed to
the crowd and showed some emotion. The only problem was DulCB9
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
