<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 02:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4279 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-HNS &LR;      05-20 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Wow.
</P>
<P>
   That's how the Spurs' Avery Johnson summed up San Antonio's
79-76 victory over the Los Angeles Lakers in Game 2 of the Western
Conference semifinals Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Wow, for Tim Duncan's game-winning shot with 8.4 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Wow, for the Lakers' horrid execution down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   And wow, for the Spurs' finally being able to win a big game in
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs made all the big plays down the stretch before 33,293
at the Alamodome to take a 2-0 lead in the best-of-seven series,
which resumes Saturday afternoon in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a heck of a game,'' said San Antonio coach Gregg
Popovich. ``It was a great game for the fans, competitive from
beginning to end. We got after each other, and we were fortunate
enough to hit a shot down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   That shot came courtesy of Duncan, who dropped in a jumper over
the Lakers' J.R. Reid, giving the Spurs a one-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan had the added inspiration of having his father, William,
in from the Virgin Islands to see his son hit the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's awesome, just awesome, to have him here all the way
from St. Croix,'' Duncan said. ``To come in today and watch such a
great game, and to have an outcome like this, it's just really
exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Which pretty much summed up the game _ exciting.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers were so overheated from the excitement that they
forgot they had a foul to give when Duncan was lining up his
game-winner. Instead of hacking away and making the Spurs take the
ball out of bounds, the Lakers stood by and watched the ball leave
Duncan's hands and settle into the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they were going to blade him (Duncan),'' said
Johnson, referring to a hard foul. ``I don't know what happened. I
thought they were going to foul Mario (Elie, as he maneuvered the
ball upcourt), and I thought, `Wow.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Then Tim got the ball and they didn't foul, so I was like,
`Wow! Wow!' I was glad they didn't foul because that would have
disrupted our whole offense.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no wows associated with either the Lakers' ``Man of
Steel,'' Shaquille O'Neal, or their ``Boy Wonder,'' 20-year-old
Kobe Bryant, neither of whom could deliver the win for the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   It was more like bow-wow.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say that the hype over Bryant being the next
Michael Jordan is starting to cool off, kind of like Bryant down
the stretch Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant had cranked up the hype machine when he drilled a
fadeaway 3-pointer with 36.8 seconds left that gave the Lakers a
brief one-point lead, but he did nothing but trip, stumble and fall
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   First, he missed two free throws with 18.1 seconds to play that
would have given the Lakers a three-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised,'' said Bryant, who finished with a game-high
28 points. ``Some strange stuff happens sometimes. I missed them
because my release was horrible. It was odd.''
</P>
<P>
   Kind of like the rest of the fourth quarter. Bryant then turned
the ball over on the inbounds play with 6.8 seconds left, ignoring
a wide-open Rick Fox and trying to zing the ball to Derek Fisher
instead.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Elliott finally capped a 19-point night by draining two
free throws that put the Spurs up 79-76 with just 5.3 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant then misfired on a potential game-tying 3-point attempt
as time expired, closing out a thoroughly frustrating final period.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly Jordanesque by any stretch of the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   And O'Neal, who vowed revenge after a less-than-stellar effort
in Game 1 of the series, suffered through a foul-plagued 16-point
night, making just two of his 10 free throws and turning the ball
over four times.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more amazing than the finish was how different this game
turned out than expected.
</P>
<P>
   The way everyone was talking, this was supposed to be a slugfest
of epic proportions. It was supposed to be so gory that TV
executives were salivating at the chance to turn it into one of
those real-life, caught-on-camera shows, something like World's
Scariest Basketball Videos.
</P>
<P>
   It was supposed to be the revenge of O'Neal, who had been
manhandled by the Spurs and ignored by the referees in Game 1, then
fined by the NBA when he complained about it.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was rough, as the combined total of 51 personal fouls
indicates.
</P>
<P>
   But it was hardly the melee most everyone anticipated after the
physical first game of the series. What it turned out to be was a
hard-fought, grind-it-out victory for the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   A victory with an exciting finish, courtesy of Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim Duncan likes to take that shot,'' said Popovich of the
game-winner. ``David Robinson likes to take that shot, but we
looked at the matchups out there and figured that in this
particular situation, Tim was the guy to go to. It worked out for
us. He's not going to be flustered by what happens in a game, good
or bad. He just competes, and he goes home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
