<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 02:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4280 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-DODGERS-HN     05-20 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-DODGERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
LOS ANGELES _ The Astros have been like a gang of Supermen with
bats, doing more damage than a team of locomotives and leaping all
over some unsuspecting pitcher on a nightly basis.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the mere sight of Kevin Brown standing on a pitcher's mound
has the effect of kryptonite on the National League's most potent
offense. As he has done so many times before, Brown on Wednesday
night zapped the life out of the Astros with a dominant pitching
performance that doomed them long before the outcome was decided.
</P>
<P>
   Brown held the Astros to four hits in eight innings to key the
Los Angeles Dodgers' 5-2 victory, which snapped the Astros'
three-game road winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Been there, done that,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said in
reference to being on the wrong side of Brown's mastery. ``Same
stuff, different venue. Brown was dominant as normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Shane Reynolds pitched effectively for seven innings, but it
would have taken a near-perfect effort to beat Brown, whose only
mistake turned into a solo homer for Jeff Bagwell.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers closer Jeff Shaw replaced Brown (5-2) in the ninth, and
Bagwell belted his first pitch into the left-center-field pavilion
for the 16th multiple-homer game of his career. But any hopes of an
Astros comeback quickly faded as Shaw retired the next three
batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the offense we have, we normally have about a 50-50
chance to get back into almost any game,'' Dierker said. ``But when
you're going against the cream of the crop, it's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Bagwell's homer, Brown allowed singles to
Reynolds, Tim Bogar and Craig Biggio, and that was the extent of
the Astros' offense against their longtime nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros matched their lowest hit total (five) of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin Brown is the toughest pitcher to hit in the National
League,'' said Bagwell, who has 13 homers this season. ``It's
always a battle against him. He's tough. Against him, you have to
capitalize when you have opportunities, and we haven't had very
many opportunities against him. Some of the stuff he was throwing
was just filthy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' offense was red-hot before Wednesday, but no one
cools them off like Brown, who lowered his career ERA against
Houston to 1.60. The Astros have scored only eight runs in six
career games against the Dodgers' $105 million man.
</P>
<P>
   Before Wednesday, the Astros had outscored their opponents 63-27
in their last seven games _ a stretch during which they hit .340
and won six times. Only four of their 23 wins have come when they
scored four or fewer runs, and they have yet to win a game with a
run total lower than three.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Wednesday's game) didn't surprise me,'' said Astros center
fielder Carl Everett, who was 0-for-4 and one of Brown's eight
strikeout victims. ``He left pitches over the dish. Everyone had
pitches to hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking for pitches that he doesn't even throw.
Everyone was talking about sliders and cutters; he threw an
occasional splitter, but it was basically his fastball, and we're a
good fastball-hitting team.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers second baseman Eric Young missed Tuesday's game because
of leg soreness, but his wheels were turning just fine on his
leadoff double in the first inning. He moved to third on a wild
pitch and scored on Gary Sheffield's sacrifice fly to right field.
The Dodgers pushed their lead to 2-0 in the second when Mark
Grudzielanek's two-out single chased home Eric Karros.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't pitch a very smart game,'' Reynolds said. ``The pitch
to Karros, I hung it. Brown always keeps his team in the game, and
those runs I gave up early cost us the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Astros were being pistol-whipped by Brown, who
retired nine of the first 10 batters he faced and didn't allow a
run until Bagwell's opposite-field solo home run in the fourth.
Bagwell joined Jack Howell and Bill Spiers as the only players on
the Astros' roster to have homered against Brown in their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Karros' two-run homer off Reynolds (6-3) gave the Dodgers a
three-run lead in the bottom of the fourth. It was the fourth homer
Reynolds has allowed this season. But Reynolds, who is 1-2 with a
7.88 ERA in his last three starts, settled down and retired seven
of the 10 batters he faced after Karros' home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just haven't been hitting my spots or making pitches in my
last few starts,'' Reynolds said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers added an insurance run in the eighth on Todd
Hundley's RBI single off Jay Powell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
