<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 02:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4284 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-ASTROS-RE     05-20 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-ASTROS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN IS JUST WHAT DODGERS ORDERED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Dodgers needed innings. Kevin
Brown provided them. They needed a stabilizing force. Brown, for a
night, provided that.
</P>
<P>
   And, most importantly, the Dodgers needed a win to avoid their
longest losing streak of the season. Brown delivered that, too.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Kevin Brown demonstrated why he is Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed four hits and struck out eight in eight innings as
the Dodgers beat the Houston Astros 5-2 Wednesday at Dodger Stadium
to end a three-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   It was Brown's third straight win. Since getting battered for
five runs on opening day, Brown (5-2) has allowed 13 earned runs in
his past 58 innings, a 2.02 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best pitcher in the game,'' Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley said.
``Every time out he comes up with something new. It killed me in
the first inning with (Craig) Biggio. We go slider and he goes hard
cutter. You have to be on your toes with him because he'll make up
arm angles every night.''
</P>
<P>
   While Hundley tries to block balls zipping from every angle
around the plate, batters try to solve Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Since yielding those five runs to Arizona to begin the season,
opponents haven't had much success. Brown has allowed two earned
runs in his last 32 innings at Dodger Stadium. The Dodgers (21-18)
are 6-3 in games Brown starts, and Brown is 3-0 following a Dodgers
loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm starting to get comfortable,'' Brown said. ``There's
always room for improvement. I'll take eight innings with one run
any time as far as the results go.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown admitted the job is easier with an early lead. Gary
Sheffield's first-inning sacrifice fly and Mark Grudzielanek's
run-scoring single in the second gave the Dodgers a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Eric Karros ended a four-week home run drought
with a two-run shot in the fourth to give the Dodgers a 4-1 lead.
It was Karros' first homer in 77 at-bats dating back to April 24
against St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess this will allow us to be considered a decent team for
another day,'' said Karros, who was 3 for 4. ``You don't have to
tell me how long it's been since the last (homer). It's no secret I
haven't been swinging the bat well, but it's not going to last all
year.''
</P>
<P>
   The only run Brown allowed to the Astros came via the long ball.
Houston's Jeff Bagwell hit a solo homer to right field with one out
in the fourth. After giving up eight homers last season with San
Diego, Brown's allowed seven this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the overall play of the Dodgers is more pressing to Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get consistent and start playing solid ball,''
Brown said. ``I don't think we played up to our potential to this
point. Hopefully, we'll get our stride here and start rolling some
off.''
</P>
<P>
   With the way the Dodgers' starters not named Brown have
struggled to provide innings, Brown's outing was not only welcomed,
but anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   While the rest of the Dodgers battled to pitch into the seventh
inning, Brown's completed at least seven innings in his past three
starts. He's allowed one run in each of those outings.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' next hope is that it rubs off on the rest of the
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was mostly hard, right at guys,'' Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson said. ``Chan Ho (Park) and (Ismael) Valdes, they're capable
of doing it, (but) maybe not as consistently as Brown''
</P>
<P>
   Brown didn't allow a hit and struck out five through three
innings. His only mistake came on his first pitch to Bagwell with
one out in the fourth but that was all Houston would get as Brown
improved to 2-2 with a 1.60 ERA in six career starters against the
Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Brown) doesn't get himself into trouble,'' Karros said.
``It's why it wasn't a struggle to get five innings from him.
That's why he's here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
