<HEADER>
A4296 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     05-20 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE THIS JOB AND SHOVE IT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Easiest job in the city?
</P>
<P>
   No, not mine. I mean easiest official city job.
</P>
<P>
   It's got to be Cable-Car Push Guy.
</P>
<P>
   Because the three cable car turntables are creaky and balky
(which, coincidentally, is the name of MUNI's law firm), many
gripmen and conductors have suffered injuries pushing the cars
around on the tables, leading to missed days and many lawsuits. As
a stop-gap, MUNI hired  &LR; il,6l,6p6  &LR; five young men to help push.
</P>
<P>
   These ``Public Service Aides'' ($8.65 per hour) give a car a
nudge on the table every 15 minutes or so, then go rest.
</P>
<P>
   The gripman/conductor teams tell me they appreciate the
third-man assist, except that too few of those shifts get filled.
Implementation of the third-man plan, one grip tells me, ``is up to
MUNI standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the funky-clunky tables are costing the city millions
in lost worker time and lawsuits and now extra salaries (and maybe
injuries to come) for the pushers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started (on the cable cars) in '67,'' conductor Gary Ryan
tells me at the Powell-Market turnaround, ``and back then, you
could load the car on the table and turn it like this.''
</P>
<P>
   He pantomimes a soft push with his foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Try it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   There's no car on the table, but I lean against the push-rail.
Nothing. I lean harder. The table creaks slowly and lurches slowly
around. And I'm one powerful mutha.
</P>
<P>
   It's like pushing a stalled car out of an intersection.
</P>
<P>
   MUNI plans a two-phase fix. First a tune-up, jack up the tables
and see what they can straighten and tweak without much trouble.
Then a major overhaul of all three turntables, which could take at
least 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, I'm suing MUNI for a blown-out back.
</P>
<P>
   OY DANNY BOY: Dan Quayle's speech Wednesday at the Commonwealth
Club was billed, even by Dan, as a punchy sequel to his famous '92
``Murphy Brown'' family-values speech, same club, same town.
</P>
<P>
   Did Son of Murphy surpass the original? The artistic equivalent
would be George Lucas' next ``Star Wars'' movie featuring the
special effects of ``Sesame Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Dull? Dan is the Muzak Man.
</P>
<P>
   Honest, I attended the speech hoping to find a reason to praise
Quayle. He thought enough of our city to deliver a key speech here.
Besides, the old Quayle spelling jokes are getting stale. A new
millennium is coming _ let's give him a new chance.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for me to swim against the Quayle-bashing tide: A
brand new Chronicle TV commercial. The premise: Columnist's career
revitalized by Quayle's entry into presidential race, guaranteeing
ample cheap-shot-joke fodder. Footnote: Columnist happens to be me.
</P>
<P>
   Cute ad, but why not fool 'em in real life by praising Danny?
Maybe next time.
</P>
<P>
   CHEAP PUBLICITY STUNT? That's what it looked like when ``Rent''
hit town in February and staged an all-comers cast tryout.
</P>
<P>
   Cute gimmick: Play about starving artists lures hundreds of the
real thing to a mass audition, thus hyping the product. Like they
were really going to pluck a kid off our streets and make him or
her a star.
</P>
<P>
   Well, they did pluck one lucky pluckee.
</P>
<P>
   Jake Manabat, graduate of Lowell High and Cal-Berkeley, was
working the phones for an S.F. mortgage house _ and doing some
moonlight local amateur theater work _ when the ``Rent'' auditions
were announced.
</P>
<P>
   He sang ``Runaround Sue,'' knocked out the producers, and now
he's rehearsing for the role of Steve in one of the two ``Rent''
road companies.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Jake quit his day job.
</P>
<P>
   SLAM THIS: It was impressive when 16-year-old Biko Eisen-Martin,
a junior at Branson School, won a national poetry slam last month.
But Tuesday night Biko moved up a level, competing against 11 local
adult poets.
</P>
<P>
   A slam, by the way, isn't a roses-are-red recital. It's part
poetry, part rap, part power-performance. Biko's poem is about the
New York incident where several cops gunned down an unarmed
immigrant. Biko's slam blew away the judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Step up here and accept your first prize, Biko,'' said the
emcee. ``Biko? Anyone seen Biko?''
</P>
<P>
   From the back of the room, Biko's pal: ``He left. He had to go
do his homework.''
</P>
<P>
   IT TAKES A VILLAGE: Car parked on Mason near the cable car barn
Wednesday, parking patrol officer notices car has unauthorized
resident sticker. Tow time.
</P>
<P>
   But the car is wedged into a tight space, so it takes one hour,
seven parking patrol officers and three cops to do the deed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, three local banks were robbed. Just kidding!
</P>
<P>
   YO DANNY BOY: It's not hopeless. All you need is a little
charisma and fire to balance the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Julia Child. In a recent Biography magazine profile, notes
Alvin Guthertz, Child says for ``comfort food,'' she prefers raw
meat and gin.
</P>
<P>
   Or for a family-values veep, someone who has played a strong
role in a solid nuclear family, the antithesis of Murphy Brown _
how about Bart Simpson?  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
