</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZEDILLO-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ZEDILLO'S PLEA TO CALIFORNIA'S MEXICANS  &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ President Ernesto Zedillo of Mexico came to the
heart of Mexican America Wednesday to tell his former countrymen he
is doing all he can to end the ``severe poverty and injustice''
that forced them to leave.
</P>
<P>
   During a busy day of speeches, Zedillo tailored his message to
Los Angeles' more than 3 million residents of Mexican descent in
what seemed like a plea for reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   A town hall meeting, hosted by Spanish-language KMEX-TV,
presented Zedillo with a challenging format _ a series of
hard-hitting pre-filmed vignettes about the Mexican population
around the state.
</P>
<P>
   In one, a Mexican migrant worker froze to death crossing the
desert border near the Imperial Valley. In another, a Central
Valley farmworker said he could not return to his home in Mexico
because there is no work there.
</P>
<P>
   When Zedillo was asked by the show's moderator what he was doing
to prevent these tragedies, the president squirmed in his seat, but
answered gamely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are fighting the severe poverty and sometimes dramatic
inequality that still exist in Mexico,'' he said. ``These problems
are not going to be resolved quickly, and they will require many
years of hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo faced a tough sell. His audience seemed to appreciate
his coming to California and speaking about his country's problems.
But many did not accept his message. Traditionally, many Mexican
immigrants have opposed Zedillo's PRI party, which has held power
for seven decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's working to make things better, but I don't see it
having much results,'' said audience member Sergio Rubalcava, an
office worker with the city's Metropolitan Transit Authority.
</P>
<P>
   His fiancee, Isabel Martinez del Campo, a school teacher, seemed
to lump all politicians together, blaming all sides for the demise
of bilingual education, a result of Proposition 227 in the November
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything starts with the children, and many times I get
children who can't understand English, but I can't help them,'' she
said. ``What is going to change? I don't see anything here.''
</P>
<P>
   Approved by voters last June, Proposition 227 called for
dismantling the state's bilingual education program in favor of a
one-year immersion course in English.
</P>
<P>
   The TV session was broadcast live on KMEX and other affiliates
of the Univision network, across California and Mexico, to an
audience of tens of millions.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo said he has increased social spending from 5.5 percent
of gross domestic product to 9 percent in five years.
</P>
<P>
   But another audience member, Noel Garcia, who is teaching in Los
Angeles on a government teacher exchange program with Mexico and
who was profiled in one of the show's vignettes, said Zedillo was
full of bunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says he's working to fight poverty, but his economic
programs are worsening it,'' Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo made a broad appeal to his Los Angeles audience, a huge
group that calls both countries home. ``Work hard to be good
citizens of this country, winning respect by working hard to
fulfill your objectives,'' he told his listeners.
</P>
<P>
   ``But don't forget your roots or that you are the descendants of
a reality, a culture that began 30 centuries ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles has the second-largest Mexican population of any
city, trailing only Mexico City. In addition to the giant audience
of KMEX, the largest television station in Los Angeles, the city's
top two radio stations are Spanish-language.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo's visit is having a big effect on the Mexican American
population throughout California, said Marcela Medina, vice
president and general manager of Univision affiliate KDTV, Channel
14 in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo ``is raising awareness about what's happening in
Mexico,'' she said. ``People are watching very closely. I'm amazed
at how aware people are about political issues in Mexico, even
though they work here and live here.''
</P>
<P>
   The president began the second day of his three-day trip in San
Francisco, where he met with business leaders and reporters.
</P>
<P>
   While Gov. Gray Davis and California politicians view the visit
as a way to bolster their image among the state's Hispanic voters,
Zedillo has other agenda items, including promoting foreign
investment in his nation.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has already become a major trading partner despite a
political chill since 1994, when voters passed Proposition 187, the
anti-illegal immigrant measure championed by former Governor Pete
Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Largely as a result of this chill, Texas exported nearly twice
the value of goods to Mexico in 1998 as California did.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the context of a more propitious political environment,
growth in investment and trade might have been more dynamic,''
Zedillo said Wednesday of the recent past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential is enormous. We can do better,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo's aides put it more bluntly. Trade expansion during the
Wilson years was only the ``natural growth related to NAFTA,'' the
North American Free Trade Agreement, his spokesman, David Najera,
said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``California was clearly looking to Asia,'' he said. ``The
political ambience in Sacramento didn't help.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Zedillo ends his stay in Los Angeles by joining Davis
in reading to pupils at Breed Elementary School, which has a
largely Latino student body. He will then travel to San Diego.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
