r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUAYLE- &LR;      05-20 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAYLE- </SLUG>
  
 IN LATEST S.F. SPEECH, QUAYLE BLAMES THE LAWYERS  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Attempting to reclaim the family values issue
that made him the focus of a national debate seven years ago, GOP
presidential hopeful Dan Quayle lambasted America's ``legal
aristocracy'' Wednesday for weakening parental control and
launching ``a crusade against basic moral principles in the
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle spoke before an audience of 200 at the Commonwealth Club
of California in San Francisco in what his campaign touted as a
major address to mark the anniversary of his now-famous 1992
``Murphy Brown'' speech lamenting the decline in American family
values.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the former vice president warned that America cannot
expect a ``quick fix'' to the problems that led to the massacre in
Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's be honest,'' he said. ``It is not just gun control, it's
self-control.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle then accused lawsuit-happy attorneys and children's
rights advocates of turning schools into a ``value-free zone'' that
undermines culture, religious values and parental rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have allowed our legal system to distort and deny the role
of faith in American life,'' said Quayle. ``This puts our children
in charge, when the parents should be in charge.''
</P>
<P>
   But his ``Values Matter Most'' address appeared to lack the fire
of the now-famous speech that blasted Murphy Brown, the popular TV
single mom, for ``mocking the importance of fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   He also made no reference to any of today's popular TV and film
characters. Indeed, in an interview with The Chronicle later,
Quayle appeared entirely unconcerned with two of the nation's
current cultural obsessions.
</P>
<P>
   On TV's ``Ally McBeal,'' the randy single attorney who has
lusted after her married colleague, Quayle said only, ``I'm vaguely
familiar with that'' and admitted he's never seen the show.
</P>
<P>
   And asked for comment on the national mania surrounding the
opening of the new ``Star Wars'' episode, Quayle said, ``I guess
it's starting today in San Francisco?''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle had few words about the movie's emphasis on a supreme
``force'' watching over all or the intergallactic battles it
highlights. ``The violence in this movie is a force of good over
evil. ... It's not the kind of violence people are criticizing,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Quayle took the podium, one of his GOP rivals
accused him of recycling an old theme.
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential candidate Gary Bauer, in an interview
with The Chronicle, argued that Quayle was echoing Bauer's
long-running calls to stop the ``judicial elites'' who would remove
education and religious values from daily life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imitation is the sincerest form of flattery. I welcome him
aboard,'' said Bauer. The Christian commentator charged that Quayle
may even share blame for the appointment of judges who have
weakened parents' rights and religious values because ``many of
them (were) appointed by the Bush administration,'' in which Quayle
was the No. 2 man. But Quayle Wednesday laid the blame for the
nation's ``cultural decline'' on the legal system _ specifically,
the ``aristocracy'' of lawyers and judges.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of QUAYLE20 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  And the ``legal aristocracy has not worked alone,'' he said.
``It's been aided by a compliant news media and an entertainment
community that transmits counterculture values.''
</P>
<P>
   This ``self-appointed, powerful group (lives) in gated
communities and sends their children to expensive private schools.
This is their world. But, folks, it is not the real world,'' Quayle
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't help when O.J. Simpson can get away with double
murder, and a president like Bill Clinton gets away with perjury
and obstruction of justice,'' Quayle said.
</P>
<P>
   There were mixed reactions in the San Francisco audience, which
applauded politely but was hardly fired up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be interesting to hear what he has to
say,'' said Democratic San Francisco Supervisor Michael Yaki, a
Commonwealth Club member. ``It's the curiosity of watching the
captain of the Titanic playing himself out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in him,'' said Carmen Donlon, of San Francisco. ``I
really pray he'll have an opportunity to be president.''
</P>
<P>
   But Quayle's biggest responses came not during his speech but
when he had a chance to take audience questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's true I did not invent the Internet,'' said Quayle,
in a dig at Vice President Al Gore, who recently made the claim
after he was asked about technology. ``But I did invent
spellcheck.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he felt about Texas Governor George W. Bush _ the son
of his former boss _ running for president, Quayle said Bush should
be asked, ``How does it feel to be running against your father's
handpicked vice president?''
</P>
<P>
   After Quayle suggested that the Ten Commandments be posted on
classroom walls, he was asked about citizens with other than
Judeo-Christian origins. There is no harm in allowing them to post
a statement of ``their moral values,'' he replied, if ``we
essentially agree with what is right and what is wrong. So be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if his message would turn off moderates, Quayle launched
into a defense of conservative values, saying Middle America would
understand his calls for reform _ and stand with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we're not leading the GOP over the cliff; we're going to
lead the GOP on to victory,'' he said. ``A party that does not have
the courage of its convictions is a party that will fail.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle added that the GOP ``failed in these last two elections
because we did not have a bold, forthright agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   But left unsaid was the reminder that the 1992 GOP presidential
ticket, one of those to which he referred, consisted of President
George Bush _ and Vice President Dan Quayle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
