<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 10:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4432 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTING20-COX     05-20 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTING20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Six injured in school shooting
 &HT;    By Mike Morris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONYERS, Ga. _ Six students at a suburban Atlanta high school
were injured today in a shooting and authorities had a suspect in
custody, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   None of the injuries was believed to be life-threatening, said
Bonnie Knight, a spokeswoman for Rockdale County schools.
</P>
<P>
   Heritage High School officials said the person who fired the
shots was arrested shortly after the shooting, which occurred about
8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting came exactly a month after the April 20 slaughter
at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., where two students
killed 13 people before taking their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   Today's shooting occurred on the final day of classes for
Heritage seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Rockdale Hospital was preparing its emergency room to treat the
victims, but none had arrived by 8:45 a.m., said spokeswoman Susan
Esslinger. Later, Rockdale sheriff's officials said five people
were sent to that hospital and a sixth to another unidentified
hospital. School and sheriff's officials held a news conference at
9:45 a.m. on the school grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Parents rushed to the school after radio and television reports
of the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody at work heard it on the radio,'' said Darlene Gomez,
29, who was rushing up Ga. Highway 138 past a long line of school
buses that were sent to the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to call the school,'' Gomez said. ``I tried to page my
daughter. I'm a nervous wreck. I've got three kids up there.''
Students at the school were milling about the school's athletic
fields an hour after the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Student Brittany Bennett, speaking from her home to WAGA-TV,
said concerned parents were arriving at the school before emergency
workers did.
</P>
<P>
   Other students were being bused home shortly after 9 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   One victim had what appeared to be a serious foot injury,
Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   Another student, Chris Heck, said the suspect is a 15-year-old
sophomore at the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this person. I've had classes with him and all that,''
Heck told WAGA. ``He wasn't like anybody who would do something
like that,'' Heck said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know him on a first-name basis,'' said another student
interviewed by WAGA. ``I guess he just broke down.''
</P>
<P>
   According to witnesses, the shots were fired at approximately
8:03 a.m. By 8:07, officers from the Rockdale County Sheriff's and
Conyers Police departments arrived and the suspect was arrested at
8:12.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting took place at a common area of the school, near the
cafeteria, where many students gather for breakfast and to
socialize before the 8:15 a.m. opening bell.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bennett, after the gunfire ended the suspect ran
back down the hallway. She said several teachers and school
administrators immediately ran after him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was just screaming and crying,'' Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Whiting, a junior at Heritage, said she arrived just after
the shots were fired. As she drove up, other students warned her
away, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me, ``Leave, get out, somebody has a gun and they're
shooting.'''
</P>
<P>
   Heritage High School has more than 1,300 students, with 88
teachers, and is 25 miles east of downtown Atlanta. Its students
have traditionally done well _ last year, its students earned an
American College Testing program composite score of 22.7 out of a
possible 36 points. That is 0.7 above the county average, and 1.7
above the national average.
</P>
<P>
   The school's average Scholastic Assessment Test score for 1998
was 1014 _ 509 verbal, 505 math _ with 74 percent of students
taking the exam. That score was 46 points above the state average.
</P>
<P>
   Last month assistant principal Greg Fowler said school
administrators had been contacted by the CBS broadcast news
magazine ``48 Hours'' about doing a potential segment on successful
traditional education, showing that what worked 20 years ago still
works today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still think that you can do it the traditional way, and do
it well,'' Fowler said.
</P>
<P>
   Heritage Principal Lowell Biddy said that, while the school
adheres to tradition, it does keep up with the times and is open to
reassessing how well teachers are teaching students. It is
interested in encouraging students who will not go on to college as
well as those who will, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, Fowler said, the school planned to resurrect a
horticulture program, which has been absent for four years because
the school could not find a teacher, Fowler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to attract students to different things,'' Fowler
said last month. ``Not all of them are going to the University of
Georgia. Some of them have different ideas about their futures.''
</P>
<P>
   6 wounded in shooting
</P>
<P>
   at Rockdale high school
</P>
<P>
   Officials say injuries not life-threatening; suspect in custody
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
