<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4445 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV23-C     05-20 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: THE KOSOVO DISCONNECT
 &HT;    For release Sunday, May 23.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an earlier era, pundit Walter Lippmann wrote
that modern wars have become ``hyperbolic.'' Democratic peoples
will ultimately demand total victory as the price for spilling
blood and treasure, Lippmann argued. And such demands, in time, sow
the seeds of the next conflict.
</P>
<P>
   But Kosovo seemingly belies Lippmann's analysis. Nowadays, when
viewers watch television news, they're likely to learn more about
the new ``Star Wars'' movie than the war starring NATO air forces
over Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The scenes of displaced Kosovars, having lost their power to
shock, have been mulched into stock network file footage. Declining
public concern suits President Clinton, whose Balkan policy is
buried under deep layers of ambiguity.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton prefers ``adversary'' to ``enemy'' and just about any
word to ``war.'' Fighting a real war to achieve our objectives
could rile people and spin the situation, as Lippmann once augured,
out of control.
</P>
<P>
   So while Clinton &AMP; Co. find it useful to demonize Slobodan
Milosevic as a Hitlerite, they stop short of equating Serbian
barbarism with the murderous tide of Nazi expansion that befell
Europe in World War II. Their Kosovo War is being distilled, drop
by drop, as if it were being fought in a germ-free lab.
</P>
<P>
   Altruistic moral goals take center stage even as death and
destruction are played down. Clinton and Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright reach back eight decades to evoke the spirit
Woodrow Wilson fostered when he went to Versailles to ``make the
world safe for democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   World War I, the ``war to end all wars,'' began in Serbia. It
cost at least 10 million lives, including 117,000 Americans. It
also convinced Lippmann, who had gone to France as a Wilson
adviser, that weak governments are unable to impose their strategic
goals.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter of a century later, in the words of author David
Kennedy, Americans enshrined another war ``in the mysterious zone
where history mixes with memory to breed national myths.'' Alone
among warring peoples, the nation prospered during World War II,
emerging unscathed on home front even as 406,000 of its fathers and
sons died in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to Wilson's and Franklin Roosevelt's soaring wartime
rhetoric, Clinton's current exhortations come across as mush. His
vision of a Balkan future features ``votes and arguments and
disagreements and demonstrations and religious differences and
ethnic differences, but (recognizes) that is better to work
together for a brighter tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   It's goofy to believe that such lofty if ill-stated goals could
be realized by the narrow military campaign that has been waged by
Clinton and his NATO partners.
</P>
<P>
   They remain unwilling to put combat troops at risk to achieve
their strategic objectives. They lament that Milosevic ``controls
the pictures.'' But they gloss over Belgrade's own limited response
to the air attacks. (Serbia has so far refrained from striking back
beyond its own borders, even keeping open its frontier with
Hungary, an ostensible NATO foe.)
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the ``Today'' show isn't buying. It doesn't take a
pundit of Lippmann's heft to note that wars with fuzzy goals beget
fuzzy results. What's more, they make lousy TV.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
