<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4449 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALING-A-MASTERPIECE     05-20 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALING-A-MASTERPIECE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO HEAL A MASTERPIECE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    FOUR COLOR SLIDES are vailable FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent by mail or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number. Please specify that
you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----- This article is also available in Spanish.-----
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By CURTIS RIST  
 c.1999 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   On a wall in the Brooklyn Museum of Art's conservation
department hangs a remarkable oddity, ``Forest Scene with Brook.''
A century ago, an early American modernist painter named Ralph
Albert Blakelock put his finishing touches on the charming
landscape and set it aside. Curiously, the painting never dried.
``Today the painting has slid off the canvas and onto the frame,''
says conservator Carolyn Tomkiewicz. ``The image is a complete
loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Blakelock's catastrophe, Tomkiewicz and her colleagues believe,
was probably triggered in part by his use of a synthetic pigment
known as Van Dyke brown. The pigment appears to have retarded the
process of drying that has kept other oil paintings clinging to
their canvases for centuries. The demise of ``Forest Scene with
Brook'' illustrates a larger issue: coming up with the materials to
make a painting permanent may be as big a challenge as painting it
in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   To help preserve and authenticate paintings, conservators have
learned to examine them using techniques more common in a forensics
laboratory than in a museum. Poring over flecks of paint narrower
than the width of a human hair, these art doctors have explored the
secrets of some of the world's greatest paintings.
</P>
<P>
   When a vandal slashed Rembrandt's ``The Night Watch,''
conservators at the Rijksmuseum in Amsterdam matched pigments and
painting strokes to stitch the masterpiece together again. In the
Vatican, Michelangelo's Sistine Chapel ceiling murals took on
brilliant new tones once conservators removed centuries of grime by
dabbing them with a watery solution of baking soda and other mild
ingredients. Understanding the basic chemistry of paints and
pigments helps conservators work gently as they preserve original
artwork.
</P>
<P>
   Pigments have a long, rich history. Prehistoric people first
made patterns and images by rubbing chunks of charcoal and iron
oxide onto cave walls. Roman artists created striking translucent
portraits by painstakingly combining pigments with hot wax, then
spreading the mixture onto wooden panels. Medieval scribes frothed
up eggs with water and added colors to produce elaborate
illuminated manuscripts.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a revolution was occurring in northern Europe.
Painters, particularly in the Netherlands, were mixing pigments
with plant oils such as linseed and walnut. These special drying
oils undergo a process known as polymerization. When exposed to
air, the molecules of fat within the oils absorb oxygen and link
together to form insoluble films. Oils allow painters to use
techniques unimaginable with egg tempera.
</P>
<P>
   Working in oils, Renaissance artists could create a vivid
illusion of reality by making individual brush strokes disappear.
Because the paintings also tended to be varnished with shellac, a
purified waxy resin excreted onto twigs by tree-dwelling insects
called lacs, surface imperfections could be smoothed out.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the binding mediums for paints evolved, so did the
pigments. Even a color as fundamental as white has gone through an
elaborate evolution. The Romans developed a pigment called lead
white, which they created by processing lead with vinegar. On their
own, oil and lead white pigment are both transparent, but they
become beautifully opaque when mixed.
</P>
<P>
   A rival to the whiteness of lead appeared after the discovery of
zinc in the eighteenth century. Chemists introduced zinc oxide,
which became popular in the 1830s. The zinc-based paint had a bluer
hue, which some painters preferred
</P>
<P>
   During the Renaissance, the most prized color was ultramarine
blue, which was made from precious crushed lapis lazuli and usually
reserved for the blue in the Virgin Mary's mantel.
</P>
<P>
   Yellows evolved as well. Around 1300, painters began using
lead-tin yellow, a pigment formed by heating lead and tin oxides in
a crucible to tremendously high temperatures. Another shade, called
Indian yellow, was made on the subcontinent by feeding mangoes to
cows and concentrating the urine to retrieve the calcium and
magnesium salts that create the color. (The British government
outlawed the process in 1908 on the grounds of cruelty.)
</P>
<P>
   Chemists can use these distinct chapters in the technological
history of paint to help determine the authenticity of a work of
art. In the 1980s, during an inspection of a painting known as
``Virgin and Child with Saints John the Evangelist and Paul,''
believed to date from the 1400s, a chemical analysis of a tiny chip
of paint found a nasty surprise: zinc. Il Bergognone, the purported
painter, could not possibly have had a zinc-based pigment on his
palette some four centuries before the element's discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Suspicious that the zinc pigment was applied during a modern
restoration, James Martin, a chemist at the Williamstown Art
Conservation Center in Massachusetts, took a closer look at the
painting. Working with a microscope and a computer monitor and a
scanning electron microscope, Martin found lead and tin, an
indication that the pigment was lead-tin yellow _ which dated the
painting to before 1750. The painting was attributed to the school
of Il Bergognone and returned to its wall in the neighboring Clark
Art Institute.
</P>
<P>
   In many old paintings, the original work has been lost beneath
countless layers of touch-ups and revisions by later artists ``Art
Restoration used to be done in secret, so that no one had any idea
what the condition of the original painting was,'' says Martin.
Using a variety of techniques, from X-rays to infrared imaging,
modern conservators can find out.
</P>
<P>
   But deciding what to fix and what to leave alone has become a
touchy issue for modern conservators. Using microscopic analysis to
determine the chemical composition of the original pigments,
conservators now apply paint only to areas where the damage is so
distracting it cannot be left alone. Cotton swabs soaked with
saliva are used to dab paintings clean; the enzymes in saliva
dissolve surface proteins and grime safely, without harming the
picture.
</P>
<P>
   Works of modern art present a whole new set of problems for
conservators. Jackson Pollock, for instance, used drums of World
War 11 surplus paints for his splashiest effects, and he often
added texture by mixing in things such as cigarette butts. These
appear to be stable, so far at least.
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Curtis Rist is a senior writer for This Old House.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
