<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4477 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN21-CO     05-20 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Some thoughts on the eternal sea
and mortal life
 &HT;    (Eds: Joe Murray is on assignment. He left behind this favorite
column from yesteryear.)
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE BEACH _ Each morning, I go out onto the deck overlooking the
beach. I sit and drink a good hot cup of coffee, smoke a big cigar
and watch the sunrise change the colors of the sea and sky.
</P>
<P>
   Each evening, I go out onto the deck overlooking the beach. I
sit and drink a good cold drink, smoke a big cigar and watch the
sunset change the colors of the sea and sky.
</P>
<P>
   In between, I try to relax.
</P>
<P>
   It's lonely work but someone has to do it. Everybody else is too
busy.
</P>
<P>
   If they aren't jogging, they're swimming. If not swimming,
they're playing volleyball. If not playing volleyball, they're
sunbathing. If not sunbathing, they're dancing and drinking beer
and trying to have a good time.
</P>
<P>
   For crying out loud, it's spring break. Take a break.
</P>
<P>
   But what can you expect? Most of these people are too young to
know that there's more to having a good time than dancing, drinking
beer and trying to have a good time.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't jog at the beach. Beaches are too sandy and too uneven
for jogging. You want to jog, better you should spend spring break
at the school track.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't swim at the beach. The water is too cold for swimming
this time of year. You want to swim, better you should spend spring
break at an indoor pool.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't play volleyball at the beach. You fall down and you get
up with a mouth full of sand. You want to play volleyball, better
you should spend spring break at the gym.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't sunbathe at the beach. You go back home looking like
broiled lobster. Ten years from now you look like fried chicken. If
that's what you want, better you should spend spring break in a
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't dance and drink beer, trying to have a good time at the
beach. All that jumping around, you're spilling your beer, you're
falling into the surf, you're getting clothes-lined by the
volleyball net, you're tripping over the sunbathers. You want to
have a good time, better you should sit with me.
</P>
<P>
   Look at that sunset. Somebody's been painting the clouds with
orange finger paint.
</P>
<P>
   Look at those sandpipers at the water's edge, how they scurry
along, as if on fast-forward, as if you could punch reverse on the
remote control and they'd all freeze and then take off backwards.
</P>
<P>
   Look at that ocean, the way the light plays across the waves.
Emerald sparkling with diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   Look down the beach. Diana built an autographed sand castle.
``Diana Was Here,'' says the foot-tall scrawl in the sand.
</P>
<P>
   Take time to take it all in. Take time to see the sunrise and
sip the coffee. Take time to smell the cigar.
</P>
<P>
   Look, the tide is coming in. ``Diana Was Here'' won't be here
for very long.
</P>
<P>
   Nor will we. Sea changes, don't you know?
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.; web page,
http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
