A4480 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARCIA-COLUMN21-COX     05-20 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cornyn-Morales tale needs to be told
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A fellow who knows both John Cornyn and Dan
Morales was perplexed.
</P>
<P>
   He helped to raise money for Cornyn's successful bid for
attorney general. He served on a board with Morales. He knows both
to be solid and trustworthy, so the accusations of civil fraud
hurled at the former attorney general by the current one are
vexing.
</P>
<P>
   It will likely be a long time before Texans are treated to a
battle of the political Boy Scouts that both Morales and Cornyn are
thought to be.
</P>
<P>
   The accusations are serious and the implications are huge. In
effect, Cornyn is accusing Morales of cutting a friend in for a
share of the legal fees in the tobacco case that yielded $17
billion for the state. One byproduct of the settlement was a lot of
yelling and screaming about attorneys' fees.
</P>
<P>
   You'll recall that Morales, who was attorney general when the
case was settled, hired private attorneys who agreed to take 15
percent of whatever they could shake out of the tobacco companies.
When the settlement was a lot bigger than anyone imagined, the
outcry over the huge payday for the lawyers was long and loud.
Incidentally, the attorney's fees were not part of the $17 billion
that the state received, but came out of a separate pile.
</P>
<P>
   Into this walks Marc Murr, a Houston lawyer and friend of
Morales, who at first claimed hundreds of millions of dollars, but
has said lately that he'll settle for $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn, who has a reputation for being extremely careful,
maintains that documents relating to Murr's involvement in the case
were manipulated. Morales has stoutly denied any wrongdoing but
isn't saying much beyond that for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn is a Republican, Morales is a Democrat. Both are thought
to have bright political futures, if they want them. Obviously,
this unfolding saga will alter those prospects for one or perhaps
both of them.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI is said to be investigating, but the G-Men aren't
talking about whether they are or not. If they are not
investigating _ as some suggest _ then it would be prudent to air
the allegations somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations warrant a separate, independent investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But where and by whom?
</P>
<P>
   Republicans don't trust Travis County District Attorney Ronnie
Earle, who is responsible for prosecuting white-collar crime. An
investigation by the Legislature would be vulnerable to charges of
political partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   A court of inquiry may be the answer. State district judges are
empowered to convene them, but rarely do. The logistics could be
tricky because of the politics.
</P>
<P>
   Political implications aside, Texans deserve to know the full
and unvarnished truth about the way the tobacco case was handled.
</P>
<P>
   That old saying about how you don't want to see laws or sausages
made also applies to lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   We're going to have to stand the sight of this one, though.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Garcia is editorial page editor of the Austin
American-Statesman. He can be reached at 445-3667 or at
agarcia(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
