<HEADER>
A4483 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN21-COX     05-20 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Partisan fight over hate-crimes bill uncharacteristic
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Democratic and Republican senators were talking
amicably again this week, but the partisan jousting over the
hate-crimes bill in the Texas Senate exposed some division lines
seldom present on anything short of redistricting.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, after a string of personal-privilege speeches by
Democratic senators forecast a tag-team filibuster unless something
were done, Republican Lt. Gov. Rick Perry had the Senate stand at
ease.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate split into Republican and Democratic caucuses,
meeting in rooms off each end of the Senate chamber. But the
bargaining impasse stretched from before noon well into the
evening, until the Democratic senators acknowledged defeat on the
bill and hurriedly released some other bills from committees.
</P>
<P>
   The situation was unique in recent memory, because few issues
besides redistricting generate such partisan lockstep.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the one-party Democratic days, there were huge battles
between liberals and conservatives. But partisanship as such had
little impact in the Senate until the Republicans accounted for
more than a third of the membership, in 1993. They now number more
than half _ 16 to 15.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock papered over the growing
Republican numbers with his stern grip on legislators of both
parties.
</P>
<P>
   But since Bullock left and Perry took over, party division has
grown. Democrats are trying to differentiate themselves on issues
from the Republicans in a way they thought was not done well in the
1998 elections.
</P>
<P>
   The hate-crimes bill, which had already passed the House, was
one on which all 15 Senate Democrats agreed. The presidential
spotlight on Republican Gov. George W. Bush, and his refusal to
take a position on the proposed bill, served to illuminate it more
brightly.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans insisted their opposition wasn't about gays.
But others acknowledged it was about gays, about concern that
enhancing the punishment of a crime committed because of hate
toward a gay person could be seen as endorsing homosexual behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats saw the Republicans as locked down on the issue,
particularly after compromise language carried back by negotiators
to the Republican Caucus was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans said Bush's run for the White House wasn't a
factor. But many Democrats thought it had a huge impact on
Republican reluctance to vote on the bill _ even as the Democrats
insisted their push for the bill wasn't done to punish Bush, whom
many of them like personally.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Bush's effort to lead the nation wasn't a factor in
criticism of his failure to lead on the hate-crimes bill, it
certainly was an elephant in the room. And the Democrats seemed
determined not to let Bush continue to claim inclusion as a
trademark of his political career without proving he really means
it.
</P>
<P>
   Some thought Bush would have been better off, once the bill got
to the impasse stage, to just come out for it. That dramatic step,
in the name of a black man dragged to death in East Texas, could
have let Bush show he cares more about inclusion than catering to
those Republican primary voters who consider homosexuality itself a
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Not doing so allowed the Texas Democrats to hold onto their
rallying point. Whether that has any lasting impact, and whether
the Senate will be increasingly divided along partisan lines,
remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com or 445-3644.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
