<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ THE BEACH _ Each morning, I go out onto the
deck overlooking the beach. I sit and drink a good hot cup of
coffee, smoke a big cigar and watch the sunrise change the colors
of the sea and sky. Each evening, I go out onto the deck
overlooking the beach. I sit and drink a good cold drink, smoke a
big cigar and watch the sunset change the colors of the sea and
sky. In between, I try to relax. (Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ Here is a list of
allegedly actual excuse notes from parents, including original
spelling, that was e-mailed to me. It makes you wonder if the
parents shouldn't be taking classes. (Ernest Murray is managing
editor of The Lufkin Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ I took three days of
vacation last week to start building a wooden privacy fence in our
backyard. I've never built a fence before, but after pricing what
it would cost to hire someone who actually knows how to build one,
I elected to buy a how-to book and do it myself. I will save about
$1,500 by doing so, though the stress and physical exertion likely
will take at least a month off my life. (Gary Borders is editor and
publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel.) EMBARGOED for Sunday.
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GARCIA-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ A fellow who knows both John
Cornyn and Dan Morales was perplexed. It will likely be a long time
before Texans are treated to a battle of the political Boy Scouts
that both Morales and Cornyn are thought to be. (Garcia, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MCNEELY-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Democratic and Republican
senators were talking amicably again this week, but the partisan
jousting over the hate-crimes bill in the Texas Senate exposed some
division lines seldom present on anything short of redistricting.
(McNeely, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Talk in Waco isn't about Kosovo or
Netanyahu or China spying. It's about where all the money went at
the Emma L. Harrison Charter School. The State of Texas has
committed $750,000 to this endeavor, assuming children would get
taught with innovative methods. At this point, the major innovation
(no doubt Austin is studying closely) appears to be how to get
teachers to teach without pay. (John Young is opinion page editor
of the Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
