<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Friday, May 21,
1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors won't have to look at every day's budget,
Cox's features budgets have daily themes according tothis schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive and personal finance
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Movie reviews, travel, books, fashion, and home &AMP; garden
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion and science &AMP; health
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   SAVE TIME: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available for
purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   GWTW-MUSEUM _ New GWTW museum, in a house that legend holds was
the model for 12 Oaks, opens in Covington, Ga. At least 2 actors
from the movie attend. Ceremony coincides with the 60th anniversary
of the movie's release. (Scott, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: ETA 11 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDS: This is the CoxNet Travel page for the current week. This
layout is now available.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL 0515 -- SOUTH CAROLINA GRAND STRAND -- The rivers
are dark, the marshes mysterious and the gnarled live oaks with
their filigree of silvery moss hold ancient secrets. The upper
coast of South Carolina, with its natural charms, beckons to the
adventure seeker. (Crouch Thrasher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: IF YOU GO -- Info box listing attractions of the upper
coast of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS _ Vermont will mark the 75th anniversary of
its state park system this summer with programs on crafts, wildlife
and history. (Staff, N.Y. Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-NYC _ NEW YORK CITY _ They don't call it the Big Apple
for nothing. It's big, all right _ not to mention noisy, crowded
and frenetic. For a first-time visitor, this vibrant city of 7.3
million can be downright intimidating. No wonder planning a family
escape is such a daunting prospect. There's so much to see and do
in Manhattoan, vacationers find it hard to know where to start
exploring this 12-mile-long, three-mile-wide finger of prime real
estate jutting between the Hudson and East rivers. We help families
plan ahead to make the most of their NYC vacation.(Thrasher,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 23.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-NYCBROADWAY _ A look at what's playing on Broadway that
is suitable for family audiences and a sneak peek at a new book (to
be published in May) called ``Kids Eat Broadway,'' by the mom-son
team of Elizabeth Carpernter and Sam Freund, who wrote ``Kids Eat
New York.''(Thrasher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 23.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-NYCGUIDE _ A compendium of tips, advise and useful
information to help families planning a visit to New York find a
suitable hotel, explore familiar haunts and check out some new
attractions, and venture out for some Broadway shows. Thrills,
deals and splurges.(Thrasher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 23
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-NYCGOING _ A roundup of deals at NYC hotels, plus other
NYC tidbits.(Thrasher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 23.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   STYLE
</P>
<P>
   PEASANT _ Here we are poised on the edge of the new millennium
and designer are promoting a look that was hot in feudal times.
(Walton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   PETITE _ ``The biggest mistake a woman makes is that she tries
to wear the same style that she wore when she felt the thinnest or
youngest,'' says Tori Hartman. ``Often our fashion sense ends in
our late 20s and early 30s.'' Hartman, petite model and author,
shares fashion advice at a series of free petite fashion events.
``The name of the game,'' Hartman says, ``is not to look taller or
thinner, it's about looking terrific no matter what your size.''
(Dayton Daily News) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   HOME AND GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   GARDENING-LIFE _ A gardening column by Lee May. (May, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GRILL-SAFETY _ When it comes to safety, some things are basic.
You're dealing with flammable gases, lighter fuels, hot surfaces
and toxic fumes, and you're handling food outdoors where your
adding potential contaminants you don't have to deal with in your
kitchen. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   PAVERS _ ATLANTA _ How to install the propoer pathway.
(Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   FOX-FALL-LINEUP _ Fox is scheduled to announce its Fall 99 TV
lineup on May 20. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   TV-CLEOPATRA _ Review. Cleopatra on ABC. (Jubera, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   GURVIR _ Waking up with one of Atlanta's popular morning hosts,
Gurvir Dhindsa. (Jubera, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TV-JESSEVENTURA _ Review of The Jesse Ventura Story. (Kloer,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES
</P>
<P>
   STARWARS-BOXOFFICE _ First day box office report for ``Star
Wars.'' Early indications are that it will set a one-day box-office
record of more than $40 million. (Longino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   TREK-DOCUMENTARY _ Can't get in to see ``Star Wars.'' Here's the
documentary ``Trekkies.'' Grade: B. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS _ Mini reviews of all currently playing
movies. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAINMENT PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDS: This is the CoxNet ENTERTAIN page for the current week.
This layout is available today after 2 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAIN 0520_ SUMMER FILM ROUNDUP -- The summer movie
season is around the corner. Here's a look at films you'll be
seeing over the next few months at your neighborhood theater.
(Sims, Palm Beach Daily News.) Art includes four color photos from
films scheduled for summer release and an illustration of a shining
sun. Also, two yellow color bars.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO REVIEWS -- Reviews include ``The Imposters,'' ``The
Cruise,'' ``Very Bad Things'' and ``Bent.'' (Staff, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes 2-column color photo from ``The
Imposters.''
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEWS -- Soundtrack from ``Parade'', Alice Cooper and Jack
Logan, (Staff, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes 1-column
color photo from ``Parade.''
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDS: This is the CoxNet Books page for the current week. This
layout is now available.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS 0518 -- In his new book, Leonard Pitts Jr. recounts
the struggle to cope with his anger toward his father and become a
better parent himself. Interspersed with his memories are stories
of other African-American men facing the same difficulties.
(O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes 3-column
color photo of Pitts and a 1-column color photo of the book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PITTS TIPS -- Advice on how to be a better father.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BOOK NEWS -- It's something of a relief to pick up the
first four volumes in a new series of books, biographies of 150
pages or so, well written by people who know. The series is called
Penguin Lives, and at first glance it might be seen as a kind of
biographical literature for the age of the sound bite. (Bernstein,
N.Y. Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW CRYPTONOMICON -- Neal Stephenson's
``Cryptonomicon'' is filled with technical information about the
minutiae of code-writing and breaking, statistics and probability
theory and encryption within various computer programs. There's a
plot mixed in there, too. (Beach, Austin American-Statesman) Art
includes 1-column B&AMP;W pic of author as a child and a 6-pica color
photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW CLOSE RANGE -- If there is any blood left in our
romance with the West, Annie Proulx wrings it dry in her powerful
new collection, ``Close Range: Wyoming Stories.'' (Lehmann-Haupt,
N.Y. Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   CENTURY-BOOKS _ America finds its voice. the first of an
occasional series on how the arts have refelected and defined our
times. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CENTURY-GOODBOOKS _ A list of the century's most important
American books. (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CYBERAGE-BOOKS _ Are bound works up to the challenges of new
technology. (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-MILNER-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ I have just recently made
a return trip to my old home town, Lubbock, ``The Hub of the Plains
and the Home of Texas,'' and it was indeed a trip. The occasion for
this return to my home town was something called ``Raising a Reader
Book Festival'' put on by the Barnes and Noble Bookstores and the
Lubbock Area Coalition for Literacy. (Milner, Lufkin Daily News)
MOVED WEDNESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   B0OK-NOTES _ Janet Fitch is an unknown author no longer. Not
only was her debut novel picked for Oprah's book club, film rights
have already been sold and the talk show hostess will read the book
for the audio version; Pocket Books plans new teen imprint that
includes an action series and tie-ins with TV shows such as ``Buffy
the Vampire Slayer'' and ``Dawson's Creek''; P.D. James wins Grand
Master award for mystery writing. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-SELFHELP _ Call it ``He Smirked, She Smirked.'' No longer
satisfied just to steal scenes, comedians Ben Stiller (''There's
Something About Mary'') and Janeane Garofolo (''The Larry Sanders
Show'') have taken a swipe at self-help books, relationship guides,
even the ubiquitous ``He Said, She Said'' columns in a new book
entitled ``Feel This Book.'' Taking turns discussing _ and dissing
_ each other and the other sex, the duo cover such essential topics
as compassion (''Is It Overrated?''), money (''How Can I Make it
Off My Spouse?'') and role playing (''I'm Not You and I Never Will
Be _ Thank God!'') We talk to Stiller and Garofolo. (Vejnoska,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
