<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas gave charter just enough money to get into trouble
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The Emma L. Harrison Charter School is $277,000 in
debt, give or take thousands.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Workforce Commission stopped all state funds going its
way because of missed payrolls.
</P>
<P>
   The Teacher Retirement System also put a hold on state payments
alleging the school failed to make payroll deductions required by
law.
</P>
<P>
   A long list of creditors around town told the Waco
Tribune-Herald in March they were waiting for payments on a host of
services ranging from electrical installation to bathroom fixtures
to a 12-foot-long, double-sided, $3,000 custom sign, which was made
but not delivered for lack of payment.
</P>
<P>
   A state-assigned educational master has urged that the school be
closed.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, the Texas Education Agency holds a hearing here on
whether to revoke Harrison's charter. This should be the easiest
call since the official designation of day and night.
</P>
<P>
   Talk in Waco isn't about Kosovo or Netanyahu or China spying.
It's about where all the money went at the Harrison Charter. The
State of Texas has committed $750,000 to this endeavor, assuming
children would get taught with innovative methods. At this point,
the major innovation (no doubt Austin is studying closely) appears
to be how to get teachers to teach without pay.
</P>
<P>
   Within this mighty laboratory for change _ charter schools _ it
appears Texas thinks it has fulfilled its duty by giving the
Harrison entrepreneurs just enough change to get in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Entrepreneurship'' _ that's the language used at the Texas
Education Agency charter division, language that implies taking
risks with capital. Texans appreciate things entrepreneurial, but
they are less appreciative when children's schooling is put at
risk, and when educators are denied paychecks, and when local
businesses are hung out to dry.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works. Charter holders receive a set sum per
student. The money, averaging about $4,000 a year per child
statewide, or $22 a day for 180 school days, is for educating
alone.
</P>
<P>
   What about toilets? What about signs? What about electrical
wiring? What about the van Harrison bought? How to pay for all
that?
</P>
<P>
   As the folks at the education agency explain it, the rest must
come down to belt-tightening and rustling up donations and grants.
</P>
<P>
   ``No start-up or facilities capital'' from this per-student
allotment, is the word from TEA.
</P>
<P>
   What about capital needs? All school districts borrow to pay for
those. That's a good question the state doesn't answer.
</P>
<P>
   One of Harrison's problems is a dilapidated building. The former
R.L. Smith Elementary needs lots of repairs. It has been the East
Waco Community Center for a few years, managed by Harrison CEO Ida
Pinkard. It would appear that the killing of two birds with one
stone _ establishment of a charter school and refurbishment of the
community center _ could have been seen as the opportunity that
came with that $4,000 per student.
</P>
<P>
   Who sees that these dollars are better spent? The state charter
division is a skeleton crew: two people and a receptionist. This
year, leading ``entrepreneurs'' in the Legislature leaned on the
state school board to add 80 charter schools to the current 88.
Gulp.
</P>
<P>
   State charter officials assert that the risk-taking is paying
off at such venues as the Waco Charter School and the newly renamed
Audre and Bernard Rapoport Academy.
</P>
<P>
   Texans still should wonder who is standing in line to play
charter dollars like scratch-off winnings at the gas station.
</P>
<P>
   As for the $3,000 sign that was never delivered to the Harrison
school, and likely never will be, there still can be a use for it.
Texas policy makers should install it on the Capitol grounds to
beam day and night, a reminder of risk-taking with public dollars.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco-Tribune Herald.
His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday. E-mail:
jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
