<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-BISHOP21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Controversial priest pushes new view of Christianity in book
 &HT;    By Kathy Whyde Jesse
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ In his 20-year career as an Episcopal bishop,
John Spong has called for the ordination of gay priests and church
blessings on the commitments gay couples make to each other.
</P>
<P>
   In the 15 books he has authored, he raises such provocative
possibilities as Jesus' illegitimate birth, his marriage to Mary
Magdalene and the homosexuality of St. Paul.
</P>
<P>
   In his newest book, ``Why Christianity Must Change or Die,''
Spong supports the contention that ``any god who can be killed
ought to be killed.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder, then, that ``controversial'' is one of the more
moderate labels he's been stuck with. (Among the more extreme, in a
book review, is ``the right reverend goofball.'')
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in some ways, the mantle of controversy has served him
well. ``It makes it sometimes personally difficult, but certainly
it opens some doorways. I'm not trying to reach traditional
religious people. I'm trying to get to people who have given up on
the church.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows there's an audience out there for this kind of talk. He
has received about 100 letters a week since his latest book came
out a little more than a year ago _ more reader response than from
any book he has ever written. ``The letters are 3-to-1 positive,''
he says. ``They are from people who have dropped out. They talk
about how they've been hurt or violated by church life, how they
have not been allowed to ask any questions.''
</P>
<P>
   In a ``post-Copernican'' world, the Virgin Birth, the
Resurrection, and a three-tiered universe of heaven, earth and hell
simply make no literal sense to people, Spong says. ``And the heart
will never worship what the mind rejects.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a difference between the experience of God and the
explanation of that experience, which is tethered to a particular
time. Although he recites ``The Apostles' Creed'' every Sunday, ``I
don't literalize it. 'He ascended into heaven and is seated at the
right hand of the father' _ what does that really mean? The creed
is symbolic. It describes an experience from antiquity. And I
respect it for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Spong says he is a more deeply committed Christian now
than he has ever been in his life. But he does not see in
Christianity a call to rescue fallen sinners. ``The Jesus story is
a magnificent portrait. It is the impact of the love of God upon
this evolving creature. It is about breaking down barriers between
people: Jew vs. gentile, man vs. woman, rich vs. poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Christian experience is real. We just have to crack it
open and find new ways to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   And it has to happen soon, because Spong believes we are losing
an entire generation of young people ``who have a vacuum in their
hearts where God used to be.'' In the aftermath of the Littleton,
Colo., shootings, people have called for everything from stricter
gun laws to the reinstatement of prayer in schools. Spong doesn't
believe in any cure that simple. ``We can't put back in the God
that used to be. That is a dying God.''
</P>
<P>
   But the changes have to come from within the established church,
he says. Historically, attempts to break out and begin new churches
have failed. ``We need to reform the ongoing tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to know that the Jerry Falwells and the Cardinal
O'Connors are not the only voices for Christianity.''
</P>
<P>
   Church prophets _ and he counts himself among them _ are rarely
taken seriously at first. ``We are the disturbers of the waters.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
