A4492 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BAFFERT-LEWIS21-C     05-20 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BAFFERT-LEWIS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Triple threatens friendship
 &HT;    By John Crittenden
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Owner Bob Lewis and trainer Bob Baffert
bicker about whose horse is better (sort of).
</P>
<P>
   Put your money where your mouth is, Bob Lewis told Bob Baffert
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert has a big mouth. Lewis has a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   The best intentions get caught in the squeeze when top horses
are about to be sent into big races. Friendships last through these
things, but they are tested.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and Baffert are being tested right now.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, 75, courtly and generous, made barrels of money as the
owner of Southern California's two biggest Budweiser
distributorships. Baffert, 43, is brash, boastful and boyish. But
they get along well together. ``Bob is like my son,'' said Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert trained the 1997 Kentucky Derby winner owned by Lewis,
Silver Charm. Baffert still trains 20 horses owned by Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the quality of the horses they are involved with took
Lewis and Baffert in different directions.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis owns Charismatic, first in the Kentucky Derby and
Preakness, trained by Wayne Lukas.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert trains Silverbulletday, undefeated in five races against
fillies this year, owned by Mike Pegram.
</P>
<P>
   If Charismatic wins the Belmont Stakes on June 5, he will be the
first Triple Crown champion since 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert has tried to handle this situation with tenderness. At
the Preakness, he said he found himself pulling for Charismatic
despite his rivalry with Lukas. He wanted Charismatic to win
because of his feeling for Lewis, said Baffert.
</P>
<P>
   Beaten in the Derby and Preakness, Baffert said Sunday, ``This
is not my year for the classics. I'm getting off at this bus
stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four hours later, the trainer realized his name was out
of the publicity shuffle, with no horses in the Belmont. A few
timely pronouncements changed that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have the best 3-year-old (Silverbulletday) in the
land,'' Baffert was quoted. ``If I am going to prove that, I have
to run her in the Belmont,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, if Charismatic wins the Triple Crown, he would win
Horse of the Year and that would knock my horses out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that would involve trying to beat Lewis, one of his
biggest clients, Baffert added, ``That makes it tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert is in Kentucky. Lewis, famous for rarely getting
ruffled, is in California. When the Baffert quotes reached the
owner of Charismatic, Lewis was steamed.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't like Baffert saying that Silverbulletday was best,
after having at least three chances to run against Charismatic
(Santa Anita Derby, Kentucky Derby, Preakness) and taking a pass on
all three races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll make Bob a little challenge,'' Lewis said. ``My $100,000
against his $100,000 as a side bet in the Belmont. Head-to-head,
whoever comes in first gets the money. Winner take all. If your
horse doesn't run, you lose. Then the winner will give the $200,000
to charity.''
</P>
<P>
   Wow, Baffert responded. ``I never said Silverbulletday was the
best horse,'' Baffert declared. ``I said I thought Silverbulletday
was the best 3-year-old filly in the country. I was misquoted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nevertheless, the offer still goes,'' said Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to leave that $100,000 on the table until my horse
gets the respect he deserves,'' said Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob doesn't need to worry about any association that he and I
have. I am looking forward to the Belmont and I would look forward
to a challenge from his filly.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
