<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: 
  
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, May 20, 1999
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Friday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COPS-GUNS (San Francisco) _ The San Francisco Police Department
says it will end a 4-year-old practice of selling obsolete
revolvers and confiscated guns to firearms dealers and instead will
destroy the weapons. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   QUAYLE-VALUES (San Francisco) _ Former vice-president Dan Quayle
is back on the moral values warpath, this time attacking the legal
system for driving religion out of the schools and encouraging kids
to sue their parents. Quayle made his remarks on the seventh
anniversary of his famed ``Murphy Brown speech'' in which he
criticized the fictional TV character for having a child out of
wedlock. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-STAR-WARS (Undated) _ Along comes ``Star Wars:
Episode I The Phantom Menace,'' and wouldn't you know, its dialogue
is flabby and its acting makes like a two-by-four. Big surprise.
But say this for ``Star Wars'' _ it always has been fun
hair-raising, noodle-headed, morally simplistic fun and it always
has been more about innocence and archetypes than irony and art. By
AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RHUBARB (Undated) _ As a vegetable, rhubarb is rather neglected.
Cookbooks, even notable ones, don't include it. Rhubarb deserves
better. This tall, slim vegetable _ yes, it is a vegetable _ is
easy to cook, has a nice tart flavor and can be used many different
ways. By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-LOVER (Undated) _ There's no doubting Amanda Hesser's
devotion to food. Or her ambition or creativity in pursuit of that
devotion. She has volunteered in leading restaurants and bakeries
to learn the craft. And she has written one of the most attractive
and pleasing food books of 1999, ``The Cook and the Gardener: A
Year of Recipes and Writings from the French Countryside'' By DOUG
BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The recycled can colector was
headed toward my recycling bin. Seeing me, he paused again, then
continued. Then his voice _ so sweet and with such melody, I
thought for a moment he was a 6-foot-tall child _ said, ``Thank
you.'' My heart just broke. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
</TEXT>
