<HEADER>
A4570 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IVOR-GEORGE-C-SCOTT-I     05-20 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-GEORGE-C-SCOTT-IN-INHERIT-THE-WIND-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LEGENDARY ACTOR MEETS A LEGENDARY ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of George C. Scott
with Jack Lemmon in ``Inherit the Wind.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It's one of those roles by which actors are measured.
 &HT;    When you think of ``Inherit the Wind,'' the classic Jerome
Lawrence/Robert E. Lee courtroom drama that just barely
fictionalizes the so-called ``Scopes monkey trial,'' great actors
come quickly to mind.
 &HT;    Most notable are the stars of Stanley Kramer's 1960 film
version, which featured Spencer Tracy as defense attorney Henry
Drummond _ closely modeled on the real-life Clarence Darrow _ and
Fredric March as Matthew Harrison Brady, based on William Jennings
Bryan, who prosecuted a Tennessee schoolteacher for instructing his
students on Darwin's theory of evolution.
 &HT;    But when director Daniel Petrie decided to mount a television
version of the play, which will air May 29 on Showtime, he had a
couple of aces up his sleeve: George C. Scott and Jack Lemmon.
 &HT;    Scott had already drawn raves as Drummond, playing opposite
Charles Durning's Brady in a recent Broadway revival. This time,
however, he'd tackle Brady, leaving the heroic Drummond to his
longtime friend, Lemmon.
 &HT;    ``They wanted Jack to play Drummond because of the physical
nature of the two men,'' Scott explains, relaxing between takes on
the set in California's sunny Santa Clarita Valley, where a
1925-vintage courtroom has been meticulously recreated. ``Brady's
bigger, chestier, paunchier _ Jack would not have been physically
suitable for that. So I said, `OK, what the hell, I'll try it.' And
it's been fun.''
 &HT;    A little while later, Lemmon also seems to be having fun, as he
confronts the judge head-on while sweat-soaked spectators fan
themselves vigorously and reporters file their stories from the
courtroom press table.
 &HT;    ``Ignorance and fanaticism is forever busy and it needs
feeding,'' Lemmon booms. ``So, your honor, with banners flying and
drums beating we will be marching backwards to the glorious 16th
century, when bigots condemned Galileo for daring to bring
intelligence and enlightenment to the human mind.''
 &HT;    He would have preferred to play Drummond, Scott admits, but he
didn't mind making the switch. After all, it was Lemmon who was
responsible for getting the play on the screen again. He had so
enjoyed working with Scott in Showtime's remake of ``12 Angry Men''
(1997) _ the first time the two men had acted together, though they
had been friends and Malibu neighbors for years _ that he went
looking for other roles they might play.
 &HT;    ``We used to walk our dogs together and play an occasional golf
game,'' Scott says. ``I don't do that any more.''
 &HT;    Later in the afternoon the two veterans shape one of the play's
signature scenes, where the two old foes sit down together on an
old-fashioned hotel porch and let down their hair a bit.
 &HT;    ``We're not the two men we used to be,'' Brady says. ``We used
to have a mutual understanding and cooperation. Why have you moved
so far away?''
 &HT;    ``It's you who have changed,'' Drummond responds, ``you who are
stealing hope.''
 &HT;    As the ``villain'' of the piece, Scott says, it was a challenge
for him to find something sympathetic in Brady, something to make
him human and not merely a bigot, especially in the final tender
scenes pairing an ailing Brady and his devoted wife Sarah (Piper
Laurie).
 &HT;    Still, the heart of the role lies in the courtroom scenes in
which the fanatical, fundamentalist orator lets loose the full
power of his voice. The 71-year-old Scott, who won a Best Actor
Oscar for the title role in ``Patton'' (1970), has a reverberant
voice which he can turn in a flash into an instrument of
intimidation, completely dominating stage or screen.
 &HT;    That power is still there, although these days the actor is
physically frail, suffering from debilitating arthritis in his
knees.
 &HT;    ``He's being very brave,'' Petrie says, ``It's very, very tough
on him. It's very hard for him to stand up _ he has to grab onto
something to push himself onto his feet. And the walk, which is now
a kind of mincing, almost a shuffle, indicates that. You'd think it
would be impossible for him, but when you look at the performance,
the concentration is there so strongly, you forget about it.''
 &HT;    ``Yes,'' Scott admits, ``my physicality hasn't been so great the
last few years. But I'm hanging in there.''
 &HT;    For Petrie and Scott, the film is a reunion of sorts. They last
worked together more than 35 years ago, on the l963 television
series ``East Side, West Side.''
 &HT;    In those days, Petrie recalls, working with Scott was a trial by
fire for any director.
 &HT;    ``I used to get psychosomatically ill driving to work knowing
I'd have to deal with George,'' he recalls. ``I was scared to death
of him, he was so volatile. If you got in the way of his wrath,
watch out. But he was always respectful and we got along great.
 &HT;    ``Now I find myself speaking his language and he's speaking
mine,'' the director says. ``We've both had a lot of experience,
and a shorthand exists between us _ more even than with Jack, with
whom I have to have more direct communication.''
 &HT;    At 71, Scott continues to give powerful performances in films
and on television. Earlier in May he popped up as Rocky Marciano's
feisty father in Showtime's biography of the former heavyweight
champion.
 &HT;    Next up for him may be a television film with Bill Cosby.
 &HT;    ``It's just the two of us,'' he says, ``and I hope it comes
through _ it's a very sweet piece called `Going Gently.' I'd love
to do it with Cos, because I've known him for years and never
worked with him.
 &HT;    ``Also Marty Sheen, who's another old friend of mine, is going
to do a one-man show on Red Barber, the great sportscaster,'' he
adds. ``He's taking it on tour and he wants me to direct it, and I
very well may do that.''
 &HT;    It sounds like a pretty full dance card for an actor who insists
that he'd love to retire.
 &HT;    Scott smiles.
 &HT;    ``My wife says I'll never quit,'' he says, ``and I just seem to
keep at it.''
 &HT;     c.1999 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Inherit the Wind,'' consult
the Showtime Website at www.SHO.com. And don't forget to visit The
New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
