<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4577 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-STAR-WARS     05-20 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-STAR-WARS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FORCE BEHIND `STAR WARS': FUN AND VISUAL EFFECTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Star Wars'' movies have never been known for razor-sharp
dialogue or Olivier acting skills (Mark Hamill, anyone?). They've
never been subtle, unless you regard Good vs. Evil as a nuanced
tete-a-tete. And they've never been hugely popular with critics,
although a few of them, this one included, might openly confess to
seeing the first three films multiple times.
</P>
<P>
   So along comes ``Star Wars: Episode I The Phantom Menace,'' and
wouldn't you know, its dialogue is flabby and its acting makes like
a two-by-four. Big surprise. But say this for ``Star Wars,'' it
always has been fun hair-raising, noodle-headed, morally simplistic
fun and it always has been more about innocence and archetypes than
irony and art.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who ever expected otherwise should be banished forever to
an endless loop of Andy Warhol movies. And anyone in search of
frothy, uncomplicated entertainment should get a neat kick out of
this much-ballyhooed prequel, which boasts that same goofy mix of
derring-do and Jedi mumbo-jumbo. It also boasts a string of
breathtaking visual effects, including vast armies of android
soldiers and a computer-generated comic sidekick named Jar Jar
Binks.
</P>
<P>
   Lighter than ``The Empire Strikes Back,'' less ruminative than
``The Return of the Jedi,'' ``Phantom'' is most similar to the
original ``Star Wars,'' which set up the plot and characters and
prefigured the struggles that would define the next two films. The
new installment is set a generation or two before the trilogy
(episodes four through six), in an era before the rise of Darth
Vader and the Galactic Empire. It is the first film directed by
Lucas since ``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   As the film opens, the Galactic Republic is in the throes of a
tax struggle with the conniving Trade Federation, led by a
bulb-eyed viceroy with a peculiar French accent. In cahoots with a
nefarious lord and his horned apprentice, Darth Maul, the viceroy's
forces invade the planet Naboo, forcing Naboo's Queen Amidala
(Natalie Portman) to escape with a pair of stout-hearted Jedi
knights: Qui-Gon Jinn (Liam Neeson) and his apprentice, Obi-Wan
Kenobi (Ewan McGregor). Kenobi is, of course, the sagacious geezer
who takes Luke Skywalker under his wing in ``Star Wars'' and dies
in a fight with Vader. Here he's little more than a glowering
Sancho Panza, albeit a Sancho Panza with killer moves; the light
saber duels are spectacular. (He also utters the immortal words:
``I have a bad feeling about this.'')
</P>
<P>
   In search of a safe haven, the Jedis and their companions _ the
queen, our old pal R2-D2 and Jar Jar Binks, a bipedal amphibian in
bell-bottoms _ zoom through the galaxy to the desert planet
Tatooine. Tatooine, you might remember, is Luke Skywalker's home
world.
</P>
<P>
   There Qui-Gon Jinn encounters Anakin Skywalker (Jake Lloyd), the
mystical squirt who later becomes Luke's father and, eventually,
Darth Vader. Qui-Gon senses a swelling of the Force in Anakin and
decides to whisk him away, presenting him before the Jedi Council
(Yoda among them, looking cross-eyed) in the hopes he'll be allowed
to train him as a Knight. ``He is the chosen one,'' Qui-Gon says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Phantom Menace'' drops all sorts of tantalizing hints for
hard-core fans (the origins of the Emperor, for instance), most of
them beyond the comprehension of average moviegoers; a lot of this
is inside baseball. And for all its wild plotting and digital
theatrics, the film lacks three things: a villain as compelling as
Vader (Darth Maul notwithstanding); a scoundrel as wry as Han Solo;
and a hero as burdened by fate as Luke.
</P>
<P>
   Neeson, McGregor and Portman are fine actors (usually), but
their roles aren't fully formed they're embryonic, as though Lucas
left all major character development for the next two films.
</P>
<P>
   Visually, ``The Phantom Menace'' is one show-stopper after
another: an underwater city made of luminous orbs, a congested
urban landscape, a slam-bang riff on the ``Ben-Hur'' chariot race.
The Naboo battle scenes, between Jar Jar's amphibian armies and
long lines of robotic troops, are eye-popping and just about
bloodless; even the film's most delirious action sequences are
breezy and benign, safe territory for young viewers despite the
PG-13 rating.
</P>
<P>
   John Williams' familiar brass motifs open the movie, punctuate
the plot and give way, here and there, to a new score that rides
hard on a booming male chorus. It's evocative and sharp, as well it
should be: This is ``Star Wars'' we're talking about, an alternate
universe as vividly imagined as it is cartoonish.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas may not be the greatest director who ever lived _ he may
not know how to write dialogue, how to direct actors or how to cast
parts _ but he knows how to tap into the deep mythic rumblings at
the heart of every story. And he knows how to have fun.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
