<HEADER>
A4592 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BESIEGED-REVIEW-LADN     05-20 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BESIEGED-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BEAUTIFULLY TOLD LOVE STORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 4 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Spare, beautiful and achingly tender, ``Besieged''
finds filmmaker Bernardo Bertolucci returning to the art of
personal storytelling with a powerful tale of love and
self-sacrifice. This exquisite love story echoes Bertolucci's
``Last Tango in Paris'' in its economy of characters _ there are
only three _ but departs from that film in the way its sensuality
builds slowly instead of immediately erupting. The results,
however, are no less erotic or memorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besieged'' tells the story of two expatriates living in a
crumbling Roman villa near the city's famous Spanish Steps. A young
African woman named Shandurai (Thandie Newton) lives downstairs,
working as a part-time housekeeper for Mr. Kinsky, a reclusive
British pianist. Shandurai fled her country after her husband was
arrested for opposing a military dictatorship. She now studies
medicine, while Kinsky (when not composing at his piano) studies
her.
</P>
<P>
   The two rarely speak but begin to form a connection. Kinsky
spends his days playing the lush music of Chopin, Mozart and Bach;
Shandurai listens to vibrant African pop to dispel her loneliness.
These disparate musical sounds waft through the villa's striking
spiral staircase and eventually start to seep into its occupants'
thoughts and dreams.
</P>
<P>
   The home's living quarters are connected by the central
staircase and a dumbwaiter, which Kinsky uses to send Shandurai
cryptic messages and gifts. There's a composition sheet with a
question mark, a flower and later a piece of antique jewelry. When
Shandurai protests the extravagance of the present, Kinsky blurts
out his deep feelings for her. He is enraptured; she, in turn, is
bewildered by his advances. If he really loves her, she screams,
``Get my husband out of prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Kinsky never again speaks of his passion for her. But he seems
changed by the encounter. His home, before dark and musty, now is
brilliantly lit, its windows open to reveal the splendor of its
surroundings. All this natural light also illuminates a puzzling
mystery. Piece by piece, Shandurai notices, the villa's furnishings
begin to disappear _ tapestries, bookcases, paintings, sculptures.
And Kinsky seems to have traded his aristocratic awkwardness for a
genuine sense of contentment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He who tries to save his life will lose it,'' a priest tells
Kinsky. ``He who gives it away will be saved.'' Kinsky appears to
have taken these words to heart in a way that O. Henry most
certainly would have appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   Befitting such an intimate film, Bertolucci (working from a
screenplay he wrote with his wife Clare Peploe) has discarded the
sweeping canvases of ``The Last Emperor'' and ``Stealing Beauty''
for hand-held cameras and a tighter visual field. The film's
composition is masterful and nothing short of amazing. Almost every
feeling and emotion in ``Besieged'' is communicated visually, and
although Shandurai and Kinsky rarely occupy the same space, we see
that they are always looking for each other.
</P>
<P>
   Newton radiates Shandurai's shining intelligence and aching
loneliness with supreme conviction, and Thewlis fills the
mysterious and mournful Kinsky with all the kinds of English
eccentricities you expect from the Mike Leigh veteran. That said,
he has rarely been this good.
</P>
<P>
   Neither has Bertolucci. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
