<HEADLINE>
MAINE PAPER'S CIVIC DUTY HITS HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It began back in 1997 when reporter Barbara Walsh and her editor
began talking about the perception that ``everything that was bad
in Maine was related to alcohol'' and decided to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the fruits of that labor were rewarded when
the Pew Center for Civic Journalism awarded the Portland Press
Herald a share of the $25,000 prize as co-winner of the Batten
Award for Excellence in Civic Journalism.
</P>
<P>
   In between, ``The Deadliest Drug: Maine's Addiction to Alcohol''
_ the paper's extraordinary 44-page, eight-part series _ did
nothing less than galvanize the public, the social services
community, and the political establishment to openly tackle Maine's
ugly secret, the destructive force of alcohol in the rural state.
</P>
<P>
   Since ``The Deadliest Drug'' kicked off in October 1997, more
than 2,000 Maine residents have gathered at more than 70 locales _
from the Androscoggin County Jail to the Cape Elizabeth Middle
School _ to confront the impact of alcohol in their communities.
Inspired by the series, a newly created Joint Task Force on
Substance Abuse issued a report last November containing 42 public
policy recommendations under the title ``The Largest Hidden Tax:
Substance Abuse in Maine.'' And three pieces of legislation _
dealing with everything from funding the fight against alcohol
abuse to insurance reimbursement for treatment _ are now in the
State House.
</P>
<P>
   In the media world, there are many skeptics about civic
journalism, a controversial practice in which media outlets involve
themselves directly in the search for solutions to local problems.
But in Maine, it's hard to find people who don't think the Press
Herald has done well by doing good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a case in point in which they helped ignite
something,'' says Emanuel Pariser, a cochair of the Joint Task
Force, who is codirector of an alternative high school. ``The brush
was all dry and ready to go and they lit the spark.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What they were able to do was strike a raw nerve,'' adds State
Representative Michael Brennan (D-Portland), ``and give a focus to
an uneasiness people had for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Press Herald staffers stress that ``The Deadliest Drug'' was
conceived not as some do-gooder mission, but as an old-fashioned
reporting project. ``We did this as an investigative story,'' says
editor Jeannine Guttman. In the course of a seven-month
investigation, the Press Herald team of Walsh, Meredith Goad, and
Abby Zimet tracked domestic violence reports, jail records, fatal
fire cases, homicide reports, drunk driving cases, and interviewed
more than 500 sources.
</P>
<P>
   In their opening article, the reporters concluded that ``The
research led to an inescapable conclusion: Alcohol is Maine's
deadliest, costliest, and most formidable adversary.'' Alcohol
abuse costs the state about $1 billion annually; it is involved in
more than half the homicides; one-third of Maine's families are
headed by parents who abuse alcohol; and at least a quarter of
those admitted to Maine's hospitals are there because of
alcohol-related ills. Most notably, 81 percent of Maine residents
who sought help for substance abuse in 1996 had alcohol problems,
compared to only 52 percent nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Deadliest Drug'' humanized alcohol abuse through real
stories _ the middle-aged woman plagued by a 20-year drinking
problem, the 45-year-old man critically injured by a drunk driver,
and the talk-radio host who found her career in shambles after a
drunken driving bust.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am one who still remains skeptical over the place civic
journalism has in newspapering,'' says Michael McGuire, the
executive editor of Courier Publications and a past president of
the Maine Press Association. But ``I actually found this, from the
reader's standpoint, to be very engaging. . . . I really felt that
they managed to keep away from moralizing.''
</P>
<P>
   The series opened the floodgates to an overwhelming public
response. ``We were just amazed,'' says Walsh. ``Hundreds of people
were calling us. . . . You would hear people talking about it in
the gyms and the grocery stores.''
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks, 10,000 reprints of the series had been snatched
up. By November 1997, a coalition of organizations called Maine
Communities Face Alcohol had formed to facilitate statewide
discussions to develop community ``action plans.'' In Farmington,
high school students sat down with college professors. At the
Androscoggin jail, inmates and administrators exchanged ideas. A
new legislative Joint Select Committee on Substance Abuse linked
with the Substance Abuse Services Commission to hold public
hearings and produce ``The Largest Hidden Tax'' report. The three
bills that emerged from this process have been deferred for now.
But $2 million in new funding is currently on the table, and
observers believe more will come later.
</P>
<P>
   No one discounts the still formidable obstacles to a statewide
battle against alcohol abuse. It's difficult to predict how the
State House politics will ultimately play out, a full-scale war on
problem drinking could run counter to the Maine's tourist-friendly
image, and the initial grassroots momentum generated by Maine
Communities Face Alcohol will be hard to maintain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very much an issue that can float back out of
people's consciousness,'' warns Pariser.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Guttman, an innovative editor who has immersed the
paper in civic journalism, is moving on to her next project _
examining the lives and thoughts of Maine teenagers. The idea was
first proposed last fall, says Guttman, and ``in light of
Littleton, I think it's a very prescient process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
