<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYS-MUSCLES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY: MUSCLED ACTION MODELS GIVING THE WRONG MESSAGE TO BOYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN HSU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blame it on Barbie.
</P>
<P>
   For years, researchers have pointed at Barbie for being a bad
role model for the ideal woman: an incredibly busty blonde with a
super-tiny waist.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a Harvard psychiatrist says Star Wars' Luke Skywalker's big
biceps are bad for boys.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison Pope, a researcher at McLean Hospital in Belmont, has
studied how the plastic body shapes of Star Wars and GI Joe toy
figures have bulked up since they were introduced in the 1960s and
70s. He believes the action figures promote an unrealistic body
image for young men, encouraging them to use steroids and work out
with weights compulsively.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, when Luke Skywalker first appeared on toy store
shelves, he had a boyish figure and wore a white robe that covered
his entire chest.
</P>
<P>
   Almost two decades later, when he was re-released for the Star
Wars trilogy series, his partially open robe hung over chiseled
pectoral muscles, large thighs and a smaller waist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite clear that Luke in the 1990s has been spending a
lot of time in the gym,'' Pope said.
</P>
<P>
   Pope and other researchers are worried that the toys _ and other
images bombarding boys _ are promoting a super-muscular, he-man
body, which can't be attained without compulsive body-building and
anabolic steroids.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, researchers measured the circumference of GI Joe's
waist, chest and biceps at different stages in its development over
the years. Such specific comparisons could not be done with the
Star Wars figures because of the clothing they wore.
</P>
<P>
   Then the researchers scaled these measurements to the height of
an actual man.
</P>
<P>
   Pope said the original GI Joe from the 1960s, scaled to human
dimensions, would have a bicep circumference of about 11 1/2
inches, similar to an ordinary man.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, a GI Joe Extreme purchased in 1997 for the study
would have a bicep circumference of 26 inches, larger than any
bodybuilder in history. A dedicated weight-lifter would have about
16-inch biceps, Pope said.
</P>
<P>
   His study of the evolution of action figures is in the current
issue of the International Journal of Eating Disorders. The study's
findings should be cautiously interpreted, Pope said, because he
doesn't know if the bulky toy images are the cause or the result of
boys favoring the bar-bouncer look.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Charness, a spokesman for Hasbro Inc., which makes both GI
Joe and the Star Wars figures, said their sizes have gone up and
down over the years and some of the more buffed-up ones have
actually sold poorly.
</P>
<P>
   Charness said the GI Joe Extreme released in 1995 was ``a
one-year wonder that has come and gone,'' because it didn't sell
well. Back in 1995, Luke Skywalker was also a he-man. ``But kids
didn't like them. And some of the collectors didn't think they were
realistic-looking. And since Star Wars is such a fan-based product
line, we reacted accordingly and changed Luke back to regular
proportions in 1996,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Area gym owners said the trend is actually going away from the
bulky look and more toward the lean, toned look.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are shying away from the competitive body-building look.
Now they want some muscle tone, but not to be huge,'' said Marco
Costentino, co-owner of four Gold's Gyms in the Boston area. ``They
want to be well-manicured.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Barbie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
