<HEADLINE>
BRICKS-MORTAR COMPANIES FIND WAYS TO SURVIVE NET UPSTARTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Internet companies are like Ivory Snow: The purer they are, the
better we seem to like them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pure plays,'' firms that start life as Internet companies, are
awarded huge stock market valuations on the theory that they are
the only ones who have what it takes to make it in the brave new
world. Traditional companies, those with the misfortune to have _
horrors _ bricks and mortar _ are often dismissed as hopelessly
handicapped, road kill on the information highway.
</P>
<P>
   But this week, two bricks-and-mortar firms, CVS and Barnes &AMP;
Noble, struck back, or at least tried to strike back. While it is
too early to tell how successful they will be, their efforts
suggest investors may have decided too soon that the race to the
future is over.
</P>
<P>
   CVS, the nation's second-largest drugstore chain, agreed to buy
Soma.com., an on-line start-up, for $30 million. The move puts
</P>
<P>
   CVS directly into competition with several ``pure'' Internet
players, including Drugstore.com, which is partly owned by
Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   CVS isn't planning to bulldoze its 4,100 stores. Instead, it is
hoping to integrate the Internet operation into its existing
business. In the not-too-distant future, a customer might order a
prescription on-line and come into a store to pick it up. CVS
shopping bags could be used to advertise the on-line service.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes &AMP; Noble Monday said its on-line service would match the
50 percent discount on bestsellers offered by archrival Amazon,
setting off a price war in cyberspace. Barnes &AMP; Noble previously
had announced its intention to spin off its on-line unit as a
separate business.
</P>
<P>
   Up until now, Barnes &AMP; Noble has been the textbook case of the
traditional retailer that doesn't get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company was asleep for three years,'' says Richard Nolan,
a professor at Harvard Business School. During that three years,
Amazon established itself as the name brand in on-line books.
</P>
<P>
   While not excusing Barnes &AMP; Noble's performance, Nolan points
out that meeting the Internet challenge is no easy task for a
bricks-and-mortar outfit. Companies like Barnes &AMP; Noble often have
the wrong people and the wrong skills to do the Internet right,
says Nolan. Their technical people often specialize in back-office
functions, not the customer-connection functions that drive the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the time barrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``In these new companies, guys operate on Internet time,'' says
Nolan. ``It is so fast that it defies understanding in traditional
organizations that work off an annual budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to move to the Internet can also put a traditional
company into conflict with itself. Barnes &AMP; Noble, for instance,
will offer 50 percent discounts on bestsellers on-line, but only 30
percent discounts to those who shop in their stores. What kind of
confusing message does that send to customers?
</P>
<P>
   Compaq Computer ran into a related problem when it tried to
match rival Dell's strategy of selling computers via the Internet.
The move angered the retailers who historically have sold Compaq's
products.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you resolve those conflicts?'' asks Thomas Willmott,
president of the Aberdeen Group, a Boston consulting firm. ``How do
you balance the old with the new?
</P>
<P>
   In the next breath, however, Willmott says such a balancing act,
while difficult, is not impossible. Businesses that are
sufficiently nimble and creative, he says, will find ways of
pulling it off.
</P>
<P>
   In the financial realm, Charles Schwab, which built its business
on the old-fashioned telephone, is the leader in on-line investing,
outpacing start-up rivals like E-Trade. The Gap, whose stores dot
the landscape, has done a good job of integrating the Internet into
its business, according to Kate Delhagen, an electronic commerce
specialist at Forrester Research in Cambridge. One example of that
crossover? Customers who make purchases on-line can return items to
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Delhagen isn't ready to write off Barnes &AMP; Noble, either. She
thinks the upcoming spinoff of the on-line business will help the
company attract the talent it needs to battle Amazon. She also
speculates that as Amazon moves into everything from drugs to pet
food, it may take its eye off books, giving Barnes &AMP; Noble a chance
to come back.
</P>
<P>
   What's the lesson here? It may be that Wall Street has been too
quick to pick winners and losers in the cyber competition. Getting
a head start is important but it is not the only thing. In some
fields the tortoise may catch the hare or the caterpillar may find
a way to turn itself into a butterfly. Pick your image.
</P>
<P>
   If some of today's losers do manage to catch up or even narrow
the gap, stock prices will have to adjust. A lot. The cautious
investor might want to be prepared for that possibility.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
