<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREKKIES-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER `TREK' CREW MEMBER EXPLORES SCI-FI SUBCULTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A little ``Star Trek'' goes a long way. The
problem with ``Trekkies,'' a documentary about fans who build their
lives around Gene Roddenberry's sci-fi TV creation, is that it goes
on too long _ but never far enough.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you think they're charming eccentrics, harmless
idealists or hopeless geeks, Trekkies or Trekkers (the movie never
really decides which name the devoted prefer) are amusing for about
15 minutes, tops. Barring some deep insights into why anyone would
want to build his life around a pop-culture artifact _ even a good
one like ``Star Trek'' _ the cumulative effect is rather numbing.
These folks come off like Elvis impersonators with pointy ears.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's as possible that individual Trekkies lead rich
and fascinating lives as it is likely that somewhere, among the
billions of planets in the universe, there's another one that
supports intelligent life. But we need proof of both theories. And
when all they're talking about is ``Star Trek,'' the fans don't
exactly come off as well-rounded.
</P>
<P>
   The film is the brainchild of Denise Crosby, who played Lt. Yar
on ``The Next Generation'' series for a few seasons. She'd been the
honored guest at some of the many conventions Trekkies stage all
over the place, and found it a ... well, a subculture. She got
director Roger Nygard to follow her around some of these
gatherings, interview most of the stars and creative personnel
associated with the four TV series and nine feature films, and zero
in on a handful of ``Trek'' lifestylers.
</P>
<P>
   We're treated to exhaustive accounts of which action figures are
more collectible, we're informed about how to translate the Bible
into Klingon and other such obsessive ephemera, and we get up close
and personal _ or, rather, we would if she possessed an actual
personality _ with Barbara Adams. She's the Arkansas fanatic who
wore her Starfleet uniform to duty on the Whitewater grand jury, as
well as everywhere else, insisting on being treated like she
actually was an officer in the imaginary organization.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the visit to the rather fun ``Star Trek''
dentist's office. Fun, that is, until the dentist and his perky
wife divulge their rather Romulan bedroom secrets. But hey, they're
nothing compared to the K/S underground, females who publish
fanzines that fulfill their erotic dreams about Capt. Kirk and Mr.
Spock minus the fantasy-busting intrusion of rival women
characters. In other words ... Well, you do the math.
</P>
<P>
   Intriguing as this handful of Freudian hooks may be, the real
psychological issues raised by such obsessive interest are never
explored in ``Trekkies.'' The film's attitude is more one of mild
bemusement _ we're laughing with them, not at them, wink, wink _
and promotional boilerplate about how the Roddenberry ethic of
inclusion, respect and expansive learning isn't the worst thing
people can build their lives around.
</P>
<P>
   True enough, as far as that goes. Too bad ``Trekkies'' gives no
indication that these self-proclaimed individualists are doing much
with that outside of Starfleet's paradoxically restricting
margins. &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
