<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR DUQUETTE, HATE MAIL HAS BECOME LOVE LETTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- I still have several weeks to work on the letter, so
I'm not worried about finishing it. But that's not the point. This
is: I never thought I would have to write it.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you can help me. I am composing an apologetic
letter/telegram/poem/e-mail, addressed to Dan Duquette. It is due
to be delivered the evening of July 13, when baseball's All-Star
Game will be played at Fenway Park. Earlier this spring, I was
convinced that would be the night Roger Clemens and Mo Vaughn would
return to Boston as American League starters. I was also convinced
Duquette's Red Sox would be 15 games out of first place, Jose
Offerman would be in Pawtucket, and certain Sox would begin
marketing ``At Least We're Not The Twins'' muscle shirts.
</P>
<P>
   It is only May 20. There is plenty of time for chaos to bloom. A
nasty losing streak is the only thing keeping today's Sox from
being tomorrow's Orioles. But that won't happen. There will be no
division titles, but there also won't be a 78-84 season. The team
with the squatty ``B'' on its caps will lead the wild-card chase
for most of the season.
</P>
<P>
   How do I know that? Well, we tend to know when we're wrong
faster than we know when we're right. So I've begun preparing for
All-Star night, when Pedro Martinez will start for the AL (All-Star
manager Joe Torre should save some time and leave a lineup card
with Martinez's name on it before the Yankees leave town).
</P>
<P>
   Before I share some of my ``Dear Dan'' rough drafts, my
attorneys have insisted that I include this footnote on all
documents: (itals)Given the choice of a No. 3 hitter, I would like
to make it clear that I'd take Mo Vaughn over Reggie Jefferson. And
given the choice of an additional power source, I would have signed
Vaughn instead of humiliating myself by calling Seattle and asking
about Butch Huskey. If you choose to misrepresent my feelings on
Vaughn, I'll remind everybody that you signed Bob Hamelin. Thank
you.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   With the Sox thumping Torre's Yankees, 6-0, Wedneday to solidify
their hold on first place in the AL East, my Apology Campaign
became even more serious. Do you realize how tough it is to
congratulate someone for not being as terrible as you had
originally thought? That type of compliment is difficult to pass,
no matter what the medium. This is why I need help:
</P>
<P>
   Beginning of letter, first draft:
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dan, I am shocked that the general manager taking the most
heat in the AL is not you. First-year Baltimore GM Frank Wren may
not make it to August. That's a stunner since he was able to lure
Albert Belle and you weren't . . .
</P>
<P>
   Nope. Too harsh.
</P>
<P>
   Second draft:
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dan, I can't believe this letter finds you at Fenway Park.
Two months ago, I would have guessed you'd be home in Dalton, fired
because of your team's awful start and for letting Vaughn walk and
for giving Offerman $6 million a year . . .
</P>
<P>
   Nope. Too negative.
</P>
<P>
   Third draft:
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dan, Success is a choice. Don't listen to the Fellowship of
the Miserable. I've said all along that Tyus Edney is our best
point guard . . .
</P>
<P>
   Oops. Wrong executive; wrong sport.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth draft:
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dan, You need a nickname. It doesn't have to be
complicated. Something like Dan The Man would be fine. You're a
visionary. Silly sportswriters and fans are too emotional to
appreciate your stoic genius. You were right about Clemens. He has
as many wins as Juan Pena. He is ready to come off the disabled
list and had a chance to pitch against the Sox. Guess what? He
backed out and said he would pitch in Chicago. This guy had a
chance to halt a Yankee losing streak against the hated Sox and he
chose to watch here and pitch in Chicago. You tell me. Who the man?
You, baby. Who drafted Nomar Garciaparra? Dan The Man. Who traded
Carl Pavano for Martinez? D-Man, that's who. Who brought in Joe
Kerrigan and suggested that Tom Gordon be a closer? D-Nice. Who let
Mo go for nothing? You _ but you probably had a good reason that we
amateurs can't comprehend.
</P>
<P>
   Look, I know there may have been some favorable things written
about Clemens by me. But that was only because Rog temporarily
forced me to put a ``K'' in front of my name so I could be one of
his K-named boys . . .
</P>
<P>
   Nah. Too rah-rah.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately there are seven weeks remaining before all of
baseball crowds Boston and Fenway. That's enough time to craft the
perfect letter to Duquette. By that time, his team will probably be
in second place because, simply, the New Yorkers are better.
</P>
<P>
   But based on what we've seen in the AL, the Sox should like
their playoff chances. The Indians have virtually won the Central,
the Yankees will emerge in the East, and Texas will probably hold
on in the West. Should anyone worry about the young A's? Should you
be concerned about the Orioles (earned run average of 6.04),
Mariners, or Angels?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Duquette went over the same thoughts last winter, when his
name was a New England obscenity. Now all he should do is sit in
his private box, turn up his beloved Springsteen, and smile.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth draft (rhetorical e-mail):
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dan, What do we know?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
