<HEADLINE>
`AGE-DEFYING' PRODUCTS ARE GETTING OLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the drugstore I saw a sign that asked: ``Do Your Teeth Make
You Look 10 Years Older?'' It was attached to a package of
Rembrandt Age Defying Adult Formula Toothpaste. ``Your mouth will
look and feel years younger!'' a line on the package promised.
</P>
<P>
   There's a whole lot of age defying going on. The battle against
aging has turned positively militant, and promises to escalate into
all-out warfare as the boomer generation succumbs to gravity and
more manufacturers realize that slapping ``age defying'' or similar
words on products boosts profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent story in the Washington Post, a survey of
packaged goods found 69 ``age-defying'' product lines were launched
in 1998, compared with 18 in 1993. They joined hundreds of
age-fighting products already on the shelves, items that promise
not only to defy age, but to defend against it (L'Oreal Wrinkle
Defense), repair it (Estee Lauder Advanced Night Repair
Replenishing Creme), revitalize it (Oil of Olay Revitalizing Eye
Gel), and wrestle it into submission in various other ways.
</P>
<P>
   Now you can defy age not just with skin care products and
makeup, but with hair color, toothpaste, even pantyhose. Where will
it end? Age-defying denture cream? Age-defying bladder control
pads?
</P>
<P>
   I'm weary of the fight. I think I'll leave the age defying to
others and get on with life. It won't be easy, because hardly a day
passes without another catalog arriving in the mail, tempting me
with various creams, nostrums, supplements, devices, and a host of
other stuff designed to stop time in its tracks. Once your name get
on the list of middle-aged marks these catalogs seem to multiply
exponentially.
</P>
<P>
   One recent arrival is Luminescence, a catalog full of
age-fighting weapons, most of them skin-care products featuring
lipids, collagen, fruit acids, emu oil, seaweed extract, various
vitamins. The Alpha Hydroxy Peel of the Rich and Famous will
``reveal youthful skin trapped under dead skin cells.'' The
BioMagnetic Anti-Wrinkle Mask promises ``to restore a youthful
firmness and resiliency with results you can't get from any
moisturizer.'' Including, apparently, any and all of the many
miracle moisturizers advertised elsewhere in the catalog.
</P>
<P>
   On another page, beneath a photograph of a woman wearing a
Hannibal Lecter-style mask, I read, ``Diminish wrinkles at the
deepest layers using the technology NASA astronauts used to absorb
medicine. . .'' Who says the space program is a waste of money? My
favorite item by far is a facial exerciser, the Chin Musle Toner.
It's bright red, ruffled, and wraps around the face like a medieval
chin-and-hair cover, perfect for the woman who wants to look like
the Wife of Bath as she ``tones the muscles of the chin, jaw, and
neck.''
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't expecting anything of an age-defying nature from the
Omega Institute for Holistic Studies in Rhinebeck, N. Y., but the
summer catalog had several such courses listed. The one that caught
my eye was, ``Beauty Without Surgery: Shamanic Shapeshifting and
Modern Medicine.'' The five-day course is taught by Eve Bruce, a
plastic surgeon who has devised a way to ``shapeshift into beauty
without surgery,'' the result of having studied ``the healing
techniques of indigenous shamans in central and South America.''
She was, the catalog notes, ``the first non-Quechua woman to be
inducted into the Circle of Yachaks, birdpeople shamans of the high
Andes.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bruce seems to have put a whole new spin on the ancient,
shamanic concept of shapeshifting. The catalog quotes her: ``As
inner beauty and spirituality blossom , changes in energy and
intent create `miraculous' cellular shapeshifts.''
</P>
<P>
   Why do I doubt that all the wisdom of the Yachaks could succeed
in shifting my shape? I think I'll wait for an anti-gravity pill.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
