<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4613 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS &LR;      05-20 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S A FUNGUS AMONG US! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been a pleasant, if cool, spring with lots of sun and
really not a lot of rain. Just the sort of conditions for us to put
that dreaded plague of mildew out of mind, partly because with such
glorious weather there has not been a lot of it.
</P>
<P>
   But mildew knows no season, and we can expect it sooner or
later, whenever and wherever there are warm, damp surfaces. Mildew
just loves organic things, and will feed on everything but glass,
glazed tile and unpainted metal.
</P>
<P>
   Before we go any further, let it be said that the proper word
for this black plague is mold, but everyone, it seems, calls it
mildew and mildew we will use partly because it sounds more
sinister than plain old mold. It comes in all colors, mostly
black. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Never free &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We will never be free of mildew. The spores of this fungus,
which is related to mushrooms and the mold from which penicillin
was developed, are microscopic. Being very light in weight, the
spores are floating in the air _ indoors and out _ waiting in the
wings, so to speak, to land on any warm, moist surface. Mildew even
grows under water. Check your toilet tank; chances are its sides
and bottom are black with mildew. A little bleach in the tank will
get rid of it.
</P>
<P>
   Because mildew feeds on anything organic, it is not a good idea
to just let it go. The fungus will decay virtually everything it
touches, given enough time. Wood is especially vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Mildew will grow anyplace where there is a lot of moisture:
bathrooms, crawl spaces and basements being probably the biggest
part of the plague, at least indoors. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mildew knows no bounds &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mildew not only has no season but no particular region where it
grows, silent and sinister _ and smelly.
</P>
<P>
   The South is a hotbed of mildew. A writer wrote the handyman
that her two houses in New Orleans were newly painted, and became
black with mildew, on the outside. The fault may have been in the
oil paint, but mildew is just as happy growing on latex paint as
well. The writer also said that in the many previous years she has
lived in the houses, there was no mildew. That is mystifying.
</P>
<P>
   But another writer in Flint, Mich. wrote that his varnished
windows were getting all mildewy and black. That is not mystifying,
simply a matter of too much moisture in the house. Water vapor,
created by breathing, bathing, washing and cooking, builds in the
air until it condenses into water on the cool windows. Result,
mildew on the Flintonian's window frames.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of homeowners are victimized by mildew through no fault of
their own.
</P>
<P>
   But some others have only themselves to blame. For instance, if
a basement or crawl space gets all mildewy, it is because it has
been kept closed tightly, allowing that buildup of water vapor,
condensing, and, ah yes, the mildew.
</P>
<P>
   The same thing happens in a bathroom that is not ventilated or
equippped with an exhaust fan to the outdoors. &QL; 
 &QL; 
What to do? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So, we know why mildew occurs, and where and when. What can we
do about it? Can we get rid of it and keep it away?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, and no.
</P>
<P>
   To get rid of mildew, treat it with a solution of one part
liquid chlorine bleach and three parts water. Paint it on and let
dry. This will kill it in seconds, and it will not hurt wood,
paint, and most stains. It will bleach untreated wood, and there
have been some comments that bleach (sodium hypochlorite) takes
oils out of the wood and causes it to deteriorate prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   If you plan to paint or stain the surface that you just treated
for mildew, be sure to rinse it before painting or staining.
Paints, varnishes, stains and other finishes are not compatible
with bleach.
</P>
<P>
   If deterioration occurs, use a milder bleach/water solution such
as one to five or six. This will still kill the mildew, and you can
experiment to see how weak you can make the solution and still kill
the mildew.
</P>
<P>
   There are substitutes for bleach that can kill or remove mildew,
although they may be less effective. Judson Escalant of Chatham,
Mass. called to say that Era, a Proctor &AMP; Gamble laundry detergent
with enzymes, is designed to remove protein stains (grass, fruit,
blood), but also works well for mildew. Use it straight or diluted
with water, he said. Era is an oxygen-based bleach.
</P>
<P>
   Baking soda in place of bleach also works on mildew. Some
homeowners have had good luck using trosodium phosphate (TSP
cleaner).
</P>
<P>
   Zinsser, a paint company, makes Jomax, a mildewcide concentrate
that is used with bleach and is also effective. This may keep the
mildew off longer than an ordinary bleach/water treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Zinsser also makes a paint for bathrooms, and claims it is
mildew proof. One reader found it to be so, after four years of
mildew-free surface. It is called Perma-White Mildew Proof Bathroom
paint. It has a high gloss and a hard finish, both of which
discourage the growth of mildew. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Keeping it away, indoors &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But no matter what you do, the mildew can come back, given the
proper environment (warm, wet surfaces).
</P>
<P>
   This brings us to the ``no'' part of the question: You cannot
always keep it away, at least outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a way to keep it away indoors, permanently, by
eliminating or reducing moisture. It is simple: Ventilate.
</P>
<P>
   In a crawl space and basement, open windows and vents from April
to October. They can be closed the other months because there is
less moisture in cold air.
</P>
<P>
   If there are no windows or vents, it is best to install some.
And, in a cawl space, cover the earthen floor with polyethylene
plastic, to keep the water vapor from coming up through the earth.
</P>
<P>
   In bathrooms, the best deterrent is an exhaust fan, which must
be vented to the outdoors, not to the attic or anyplace else in the
house. If you ave no exhaust fan and can't put one in, open the
window during showers and leave it open after the shower until the
mirror unfogs. (Hey, so it might be chilly in the dead of winter.
If you want the warmth, then you have to put up with the moisture.)
</P>
<P>
   Attics are another place where moisture builds, and ventilation
is the cure there, too. Put in vents if there are none, and add
more if what you have is inadequate. Unlike vents in basements and
crawl spaces that can be closed in winter, those in attics can be _
should be _ open all year. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Yes, but outdoors? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Outdooors, well, ventilating outdoors is like trying to
ventilate. Heck, the outdoors is already ventilated, so the battle
outdoors involves removal with bleach and water or other means,
which translates to eternal vigilance and maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   And, the use of exterior paints and stains may help, because
virtually all exterior paints and stains contain a mildewcide that
keeps mildew away, but its effect is limited, usually two years,
far short of the standard life of a paint or stain.
</P>
<P>
   Zinsser, the company that makes the Perma-Whtie interior paint,
also makes Perma-White acrylic exterior paint, in a satin finish,
which it claims is mildew proof.
</P>
<P>
   You may be skeptical about that mildew proof claim, but if it
keeps mildew away for several years that's a pretty good start in
the battle against the great mold plague of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Good luck to us all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
