</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHERE TO STAY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Weimar has a few big hotels and many smaller ones; even the
cheapest places are clean and secure.
</P>
<P>
   The Hotel Villa Hentzel, 12 Bauhausstrasse, (49-3643) 86580, fax
(49-3643) 865819, is a comfortable old hotel in downtown that has
been nicely renovated and offers all the basic amenities at a low
price. Its 13 antiques-filled rooms come with cable television,
private baths and floor-to-ceiling windows. Double room with
breakfast, $85 to $107.
</P>
<P>
   Budget: Bargain hunters can find excellent deals at the small
pensions that have been converted from private homes. One of the
more upscale of these is the Pension Savina at 60 Meyerstrasse,
(49-3643)86690, fax (49-3643) 866911. Its 12 rooms have showers,
computer connections, mini-kitchen and cable TV. And there is a
sauna and solarium. Doubles: $78, including breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Luxury: The city's most famous establishment is the 102-room
Hotel Elephant, 19 Markt, (49-3643)8020, fax (49-3643) 802610, now
part of the Kempinski chain. Situated on the central market square,
it was constructed as a government building in 1542 and converted
to a hotel in 1741, with Bauhaus and Art Deco interior. Doubles:
$175 to $220.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHERE TO EAT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Weimar has many small cafes and restaurants, and guides say that
the Residenz Cafe, looking out overthe Ilm at 4 Grunemarkt, is the
oldest cafe in Germany. Today it is a gathering spot with a vaguely
bohemian feel that draws many of the actors and workers from nearby
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   The Scharfe Ecke, 2 Eisfeld, (49-3643) 202430, is one of several
small homey restaurants in the historic section. It serves
Thuringian specialties like the meat-filled dumplings known as
klossen and the spicy Thuringian bratwurst. The walls are decorated
with kitschy German paintings, the ambiance is old-fashioned, the
waiters are friendly to children. Meal for two with wine: $30.
</P>
<P>
   At the Felsenkeller, 37 Humboldstrasse, (49-3643) 850366, the
beer comes from its own microbrewery. It accompanies good
Thuringian cuisine in a wonderful location just a few steps from
the Nietzsche House on a quiet street of meticulously renovated
houses. Picture windows in the back look out onto the woods.
</P>
<P>
   The Felsenkeller offers a range of German meat and fish dishes,
as well as Thuringian specialties such as bierfleisch, pork
marinated in beer and served like goulash. Dinner for two with wine
is about $34.
</P>
<P>
   One of the city's best lunchtime bargains is the ACC Galleria
Cafe next to the Stadtschloss Museum, 1 Burgplatz, (49-3643)
851161. At this little cafe, the chef's daily specials are the best
bet. What the menu lacks in choice it makes up for in creativity
and price. Though the cooking tends toward French, recent specials
included a vegetable paella and an apricot chicken curry. The price
is $6.25 a person, with drinks extra. Open 11 a.m. to 5 p.m. only.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ---- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Edmund L. Andrews is the European economic correspondent for
The Times, based in Frankfurt.)
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Edmund L. Andrews &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
