<HEADER>
A4649 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLOCAUST-STLOUIS-2TA     05-20 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-STLOUIS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ST. LOUIS EPISODE: VOYAGE THROUGH THE TEARS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: Two photos are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (Includes missing passengers list; a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By IRENE SEGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On May 13, 1939, eight months after her father committed suicide
because Jews in Vienna were no longer permitted to work and six
months after Nazi storm troopers ransacked her family's home on the
infamous Kristallnacht, Liane Reif-Lehrer, clutching her mother's
hand, boarded the ocean liner St. Louis in Hamburg. Their
destination was safe haven in America.
</P>
<P>
   Reif-Lehrer was 4 years old, one of more than 900 Jews, mostly
German, who sailed across the Atlantic to Cuba, where they thought
they had the paperwork necessary to await immigration to the United
States. Instead, they were rebuffed by Cuban officials, denied
entry into the United States and eventually forced back to Europe.
More than 220 subsequently died in the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 60 years later, the US Holocaust Memorial Museum in
Washington, D.C., is commemorating the voyage of the St. Louis with
an exhibit that runs until Sept. 6. The former passengers include
two suburban Boston women, 64-year-old Reif-Lehrer of Lexington and
66-year-old Ruth Loeb Forrest of Newton. One of five families
featured in the display includes 84-year-old Sidney Blechner of
Brookline, whose brother Oskar was on the St. Louis and who almost
sailed on the ship himself.
</P>
<P>
   The day Reif-Lehrer, her mother, and her brother boarded the St.
Louis, they headed to the first-class cabins because Chaje Leja
Reif, permitted to take few assets with her, preferred booking
expensive passage to leaving behind money for Nazis to loot. She'd
tossed the gold her husband used in his dental practice into the
Danube River before she departed Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   Forrest's father, Leo Loeb, who'd spent six weeks in Dachau
after Kristallnacht, was already in Havana when the St. Louis
arrived, and he ventured out in a small boat as near as he could to
the ship that carried Forrest, her mother, her brother, and her
paternal grandparents. She could see her father and he could see
them, but the view from their separate craft was as close as they
got before the St. Louis turned around. Her grandparents were
killed in Auschwitz. So was her aunt's father, who was also on the
St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Sidney Blechner was stranded in Poland, released from the camp
to which he'd been deported in 1938 from his hometown of Munich but
unable to secure the documents he needed to make his way to Hamburg
in time to board the St. Louis. So it sailed without him. Blechner
then survived six years in six concentration camps, including
Auschwitz and Bergen-Belsen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The St. Louis affected me,'' says Forrest, a retired nurse and
mother of seven. ``Even in my yearbook I had written that I'm for
the underdog. I feel for the people in Kosovo. It's not just them.
Anytime this happens. Going back to that ship from Haiti when we
wouldn't let them in. That's ingrained in me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I have felt as frightened or angry about any
situation since then as I do now about Yugoslavia,'' says
Reif-Lehrer, a chemist-turned-consultant and mother of two. ``The
concept that in this century _ and especially at the end of this
century _ people are still trying to resolve their differences by
going out and playing `bang bang, let's see who can shoot the most
of the other guy' is so obscene and so outrageously uncivilized. I
don't have words to describe what I feel about this.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis was front-page news in Boston, as elsewhere, in
1939 as it wandered, unwelcome and prohibited from docking, between
Cuba and Florida before turning back, presumably to Germany, on
June 6. Gone was the jovial atmosphere that characterized the
voyage to Cuba. Gone were the sumptuous meals first-class
passengers had enjoyed. The captain feared mass suicide. One man
had tried by cutting his wrists and jumping into the harbor as the
boat left Havana, which earned him a brief respite in Cuba before
he, too, was sent back to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Only on June 13 did Belgium, France, the Netherlands, and
Britain each agree to admit some passengers. On June 17, the St.
Louis docked at Antwerp.
</P>
<P>
   The story has spawned books and films. But it wasn't until
spring 1996, when four St. Louis survivors went to the Holocaust
Museum looking for information, that anyone tried to systematically
learn what happened to the passengers on that ship.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after almost three years of searching written records,
contacting Jewish communities around the world, and, more recently,
publicizing the new exhibit, museum researchers know the fate of
all but 23 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Some 200 were deported to Auschwitz and the killing center of
Sobibor. None survived Sobibor, and five survived Auschwitz.
Another 40 were deported to other camps, where most were killed. An
undetermined number, including the mother of Forrest's aunt, died
in Europe outside the camps. As far as the museum knows, none of
the 287 who went to England, including Blechner's brother Oskar,
died in the Holocaust for the simple reason that Germany never
occupied Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that so many survived in the countries that fell to
Hitler, says museum project coordinator Scott Miller, is because
they were already on waiting lists to enter the United States under
the quota system in place at the time. Their turn to immigrate came
while it was still possible to cross the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Reif-Lehrer and Forrest were young girls on the St. Louis, and
their memories are children's memories boosted by the recollections
of others. Forrest's mother, Bella Loeb, is 95, a resident of the
Hebrew Rehabilitation Center for the Aged in Roslindale, unaware of
either her surroundings or her past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Kristallnacht (Nov. 9, 1938) as though it was last
night. My mother was holding me in her arms and my brother was
hanging onto her skirt,'' says Reif-Lehrer. ``The only thing I
remember from the voyage is we were really seasick almost all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Blechner, whose fateful inability to get to Hamburg in time for
the St. Louis departure led to years of suffering, has only started
talking about the Holocaust in the past few years. For more than a
decade he wore a Band-Aid over the number 69717, tattooed onto his
left forearm at Auschwitz on Oct. 23, 1942.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to start a new life, to cry what is gone is gone,'' says
the retired businessman and father of four. ``If you say something
about the Holocaust you can't work.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reif-Lehrer and her family were among the 224 passengers sent to
France. A fellow passenger, a man bound for England, had been
bothering her mother, so she made sure her family went elsewhere.
``My brother tells me he was absolutely livid that my mother made
that request,'' says Reif-Lehrer. ``It was really stupid to go to
France.''
</P>
<P>
   For nine months the family lived in Loudun, the last two weeks
under Nazi occupation. There she befriended a little boy, Jean-Paul
Berg, who, she believes, did not survive the war. In 1940, under
cloak of night, the Reifs and 14 other Jewish refugees made their
way to Limoges, in unoccupied Vichy France. It was far from their
life of affluence in Vienna, where Reif-Lehrer liked to linger in
the kitchen with the cook and squealed when servants pulled the
runners in the hall to give her rides or bounced her in sheets they
were folding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Food really got to be a problem,'' Reif-Lehrer recalls.
``There were ration coupons. It was one egg per month per person,
but you could never get them. One day my mother and my brother and
I walked for miles and miles and miles and got three eggs, and when
we came back they were rotten. We had to throw them out.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 1338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4650 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLOCAUST-STLOUIS-2ND     05-20 1330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-STLOUIS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 (a and i coding)  
 UNDATED: ... throw them out.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It was very hard to get bread. Because I was little and I was
cute, I got the job of begging for bread. I went in alone to
bakeries and I had to say, `I'm so hungry. I have ration coupons
and I have money and I need bread.' Very often I got bread. That
got shared not just with my family but with other people. A few
years ago I said to my brother, `Did anyone think how demeaning it
made me feel to do that?' My brother looked me straight in the eye
and said, `It wasn't demeaning. It was bread.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in 1941, the Reifs learned of a boat leaving from
Lisbon. They arranged the papers needed to leave France, travel
through Spain, and enter Portugal. On Nov. 10, 1941, four days
before Reif-Lehrer's seventh birthday, the family arrived in New
York. Cousins met them and drove them to the tenements of the Lower
East Side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember in the car, we were sitting in the back seat, and
my mother under her breath said, `Have I suffered all this just to
come to this?' Even though I was only 7, I remember thinking there
was something not right about her saying that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the Reifs were slowly making their way to America via
France, the Loebs were in Brussels. They were from Malsch, in
southern Germany, where Leo Loeb sold cattle. He was president of
the synagogue, which may be the reason he was held at Dachau in
1938 so much longer than his father or brothers.
</P>
<P>
   When the Nazis released him six weeks after Kristallnacht, they
told him to leave the country, so he arranged to go to Cuba to
await entry in the United States. The rest of the family would
follow. Before he left Germany, the family posed for a portrait,
``probably,'' Forrest says, ``just in case we never saw each other
again.'' It is a mournful picture in which Leo Loeb's head is still
nearly bald after being shaved at Dachau.
</P>
<P>
   Every day after he left, Forrest's mother wrote her husband. To
see him across Havana Harbor, unable to reunite, Forrest says,
``must have been horrendous'' for her.
</P>
<P>
   For 10 months after the return of the St. Louis the Loebs lived
in Brussels. When the chance came for some to sail to America on
the Pennland, her grandparents and her aunt's parents said the
young people _ Forrest, her mother, brother, aunt, and cousin _
should go first. The older ones made plans to come a few weeks
later. Their boat never sailed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1940 the Loebs were reunited in Elmira, N.Y., where Leo Loeb
worked first as a chauffeur, then as a clerk in a silk factory.
</P>
<P>
   Before Dachau ``my father played the piano. He had a sense of
humor. He was just a nice guy. After the concentration camp he
became very quiet. My brother and I never asked questions about
what happened. It was almost an unwritten law that we didn't,''
Forrest says. ``The one thing that I didn't have for a long time _
and that I'm trying to acquire _ is a sense of humor. My parents
really, and my mother especially, took everything to heart. It
makes life very sad when you're growing up.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sidney Blechner's brother Oskar, meanwhile, was in England,
waiting out the war, with a job manufacturing belts. Born in Poland
two years before his family moved to Germany, he carried a Polish
passport and avoided the fate of many St. Louis passengers sent to
Britain who were interned as German citizens.
</P>
<P>
   But Sidney Blechner was not so fortunate. After he missed the
St. Louis, he tried desperately, but unsuccessfully, to leave
Germany. He made his way to Switzerland, only to be sent back to
Germany. His father was deported to Buchenwald, where he was
killed, and Blechner managed to flee to Berlin, where in October
1939 he was arrested and sent to his first concentration camp,
Sachenhausen. Initially, at least, he still had contact with the
outside world, and his mother harbored hope she could get him out
of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The family recently discovered the wartime correspondence of
Blechner's mother, and it is filled with frantic efforts to help
her son. Her three other sons were in Switzerland, England, and the
United States. While she was still in the ritual mourning period
following her husband's death, Mina Blechner wrote her son Jakob in
Switzerland, asking him to go to the Chilean Consulate on Sidney's
behalf. ``It is urgent,'' she wrote. ``You should not waste a
minute.'' She signed the letter, ``Your distressed mother.''
Similar efforts to get Sidney Blechner into Portugal, India,
Shanghai, and Bolivia failed. Mina Blechner was deported in 1941 to
Kovno, Lithuania, where she was killed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1942, Sidney Blechner was sent to Auschwitz, and in early
1944, he was among 2,000 internees crowded onto open cattle cars
and transported to Dora-Mittelbau, a concentration camp in Germany.
``It was snowing,'' Blechner recalls. ``And we were all thirsty. We
got nothing to drink so we used the snow and urine.'' Fewer than
200 survived that trip. When he was liberated from Bergen-Belsen,
Blechner weighed 90 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am alive!'' he wrote in a postcard to his brother Jakob on
April 15, 1945. ``It is a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Today Blechner has 14 grandchildren. Forrest has five, with
twins on the way. She asks if a visitor would like to know the
names of her children. Lisa. Susan. Robert. Steven. Richard.
Jonathan. Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how the saga goes on,'' Forrest says. ``We were just
very lucky. People who had to go through the camps and were
liberated _ no matter how hard it might have been for us, it was
nothing compared to what these people went through.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that bothers me the most is inhumanity to man.''
</P>
<P>
   On June 3, Forrest will be in Washington, at the Holocaust
Museum, appearing on a panel with two other former passengers.
``Basically I'm doing it in honor of my grandparents who never got
out of Brussels,'' she says. ``They were on the boat.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
MISSING PASSENGERS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The US Holocaust Memorial Museum is seeking documentation on the
fate of passengers from the 1939 voyage of the SS St. Louis. Anyone
with information about a St. Louis passenger, particularly any of
the unaccounted-for passengers on this list, should contact Scott
Miller, United States Holocaust Memorial Museum, 100 Raoul
Wallenberg Place, SW, Washington, DC 20024 (Telephone:
202-488-0495. Fax: 202-314-7888. E-mail: smiller(at)ushmm.org). &QL;
</P>
