<SLUG> BC-COPS-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO POLICE TO STOP GUNS SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The San Francisco Police Department says it will
end a 4-year-old practice of selling obsolete service revolvers and
confiscated guns to firearms dealers and instead will destroy the
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's time to stop selling them,'' police Chief Fred
Lau said Wednesday. ``There have been concerns from the community.
There is no need to do this any more ... I doubt we'll ever do it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The police are worried that the guns sold by the department
could be re-sold, or stolen from registered owners, and wind up in
the wrong hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It concerns us that we can't control where these guns would
ultimately end up. It could be very embarrassing to have one of
these used in a crime,'' police spokesman Sherman Ackerson said.
``We take every precaution now, but that's always a possibility
down the line.''
</P>
<P>
   The department's decision comes as the city prepares to sue gun
manufacturers over safety issues. Marc Slavin, the spokesman for
City Attorney Louise Renne, praised the police department's change
in policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that if they are taking those guns out of commission,
that is a well-advised policy,'' Slavin said. ``I think that it is
all for the better.''
</P>
<P>
   It is anticipated that Renne will file the lawsuit in June, at
which time San Francisco would join a growing number of cities
taking gun manufacturers to court to recoup police and medical
costs caused by gun violence. Atlanta, Chicago, Cincinnati, Miami
and New Orleans have filed similar lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the Police Department began selling or trading about
1,500 firearms to out-of-state gun dealers and used the proceeds to
upgrade officers' weapons from revolvers to semiautomatic handguns.
The majority of the weapons sold were six-shot, .357-caliber Smith
and Wesson police revolvers.
</P>
<P>
   The department also sold several hundred other weapons,
including a number of ``old shotguns and rifles that are considered
obsolete.'' Among them were World War II-era carbines that were
given to the department in the 1950s by the federal government,
Ackerson said.
</P>
<P>
   Also sold was ``a small fraction'' of the number of confiscated
guns the department had taken in, Ackerson said. He could not give
a specific number.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
