<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-SPRING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS MIND WANDERS, BODY SUFFERS THE HUGE CHORES OF SPRING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE HATCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The work continues. Late spring brings little respite for the
gardener, although the occasional balmy day promises summer's
relaxation.
</P>
<P>
   Mainly the weather bedevils, and we say, ``My, what a wet spring
we're having,'' or we mutter something much worse. Later, we'll
say, ``Gosh, what a dry summer. Will it never rain?'' Of course, we
say these things every year, because those are the weather patterns
of New England _ monsoon to desert to arctic.
</P>
<P>
   A recent trip to England illustrated how different is that
climate, the root cause of frustration for American gardeners
enamored of all those English gardening books. For, while we bend
to Yankee vagaries, they enjoy seemingly everything blooming at
once. Rhododendrons, azaleas, all the bulbs, the earliest of roses,
the host of annuals, and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, they have seasons, but they are blurred, as they should be.
On the other hand, a lot of their favorites are plants from the New
World, things imported by the Tradescants, both father and son, and
those shipped over by John Bartram in the 18th century. We can grow
heat-loving meadow plants, and they must stick to their own. There
are no English prairies.
</P>
<P>
   The gardener's mind wanders in procrastination. I have recovered
from the wounds received in ripping out an incredibly overgrown
Rosa multiflora. It was a good 6 feet tall, with a canopy spread of
5 feet. Its trunk was as thick as my leg, and I had to ease under
it, carefully, to cut it with my pruning saw. Then it leaned onto
the lawn, and its thorns latched onto lawn and edging and low maple
branches (not to mention me), and it refused to budge. I had to cut
it up as it lay, ripping out chunks and carting them off, with
concomitant loss of blood, until it was gone.
</P>
<P>
   With that devil exorcised, I have a lovely bare patch dominated
by a dawn redwood (Metasequoia glyptostroboides). This is a
recuperating plant, which had flagged badly in the center of the
lawn, where it baked too much and its leader (the primary shoot of
a tree) died. I moved it to a low spot on the east side of the
property a few years ago, and now it is shooting up, having
developed a new leader from one of its side branches.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, this deciduous conifer with reddish bark and pyramidal
habit may reach close to 100 feet high (OK, not in my yard it
won't, but it still will be big). It is between a red maple that
lost one of its biggest limbs a few years ago, and about which I
worry, and a crab apple that struggles along and elicits
disparaging comments from my neighbor (``You going to cut that
down?''). The dawn redwood is insurance against the demise of
either adjacent tree.
</P>
<P>
   I am fond of dawn redwoods, and you can see some fine examples
at Boston's Arnold Arboretum. The tree was thought to be extinct
until 1945, and an arboretum expedition fetched seeds from China in
1948, leading to the present collection.
</P>
<P>
   The arboretum is one of six public gardens in the Boston area on
the Garden Conservancy's tour list this year. There are 25 private
gardens as well, and these are worth the cost and procedure
necessary to see them.
</P>
<P>
   The conservancy, dedicated to preserving notable American
gardens, is modeled after its English counterpart. A booklet
describing and giving directions to all the participating gardens
in the nation is sold for $12.95. The visitor then pays $4 at each
garden.
</P>
<P>
   Directories are available at Allandale Farm in Chestnut Hill,
Arnold Arboretum in Jamaica Plain, Garden in the Woods in
Framingham, Mahoney's Garden Center in Cambridge, Russell's Garden
Center in Wayland, Weston Nurseries in Hopkinton, and Winston
Flowers at 160 Southampton St. in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, 10 gardens in Brookline, Chestnut Hill and Weston
will be open. Next Sunday, 15 gardens in Hamilton, Manchester,
Beverly Farms, Marblehead, Salem and Swampscott will be open.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big range in the nature of the gardens, from teeny
little intimate ones to large estates,'' Mary Ann Streeter, the
conservancy's Boston area representative, told me. Being a frugal
swamp Yankee, I'll be seeing as many as I can to get my money's
worth. For this gardener, a brief respite at last.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
