A4653 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHURCH-STAYERS-NYTSF &LR;      05-20 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCH-STAYERS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A CHURCH `STAYER,' THE ROUTINE IS THE ADVENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ``I don't want to go to church today,'' I said, sounding more
like a 9-year-old than an adult.
 &HT;    ``Whatever,'' my husband replied, ``you decide. I'm going.''
 &HT;    Less than an hour later, I went to church -- just as I have been
doing for most of my life. Another standard-issue Sunday. Coffee in
the parish hall.
 &HT;    Liturgy, sermon, Holy Communion. A church brunch thanking choir
members and Sunday school teachers. Another church year -- roughly
the same as a school year -- ends.
 &HT;    For 20 years, my standard Sundays have been in the Episcopal
Church. Before that, several years in no-brand-name evangelical
churches. During childhood, Sundays meant a weekly pilgrimage to
the Methodist church.
 &HT;    I am a churchgoer. Unlike so many of my baby-boomer peers who
only recently have returned to church, I never left. I never
dabbled in Eastern religion, rebelled against my parents, or
doubted the existence of God. Sociologists dubbed my generation
``seekers'' because of our disposition to explore spirituality,
reject institutional religion, and dismiss traditional
denominations.
 &HT;    Eventually, many of these seekers returned to mainline churches
-- thus earning themselves the title ``returnees.'' But I am oddly
out-of-step with this generational ethos. I am a stayer.
 &HT;    For as long as I can remember, the Christian story claimed both
my heart and mind. Growing up, I studied the Bible and theology,
attended prayer meetings and youth rallies, and went on mission
trips. I dreamed of being a preacher or missionary or seminary
professor. On most Sundays during the last 40 years, I have been to
church.
 &HT;    Stayers do not get much attention. Unlike the returnees who tell
tales of experimenting with alternative lifestyles and exotic
religions before coming back, us stayers have no such adventures.
Instead, stayer-spirituality grows in conversation with the Bible
and tradition, with hymnody and theology, with parish life and
church suppers, with fights over church organs and stained glass
windows. On the face of it, it seems a bit dull.
 &HT;    Over the last two decades, I have ``stayed'' within the
Episcopal Church. In those years, I lived in six different states
and been twice married. I changed parishes but never denominations.
Defying the statistic that Americans have no denominational
loyalty, I kept choosing the Episcopal brand.
 &HT;    In the process, I discovered something odd: the Episcopal Church
became my hometown. It grounded me. Within its walls, I found a
common worship experience, similar ways of practicing faith, shared
traditions, and a common language. There were connected
relationships, almost like circles of kin, woven through the
church. Without realizing it, Episcopal people became my people; a
family tied through faith.
 &HT;    I did not choose to be an Episcopalian because of family or
tradition. I choose it because I felt I had come home. For me,
Episcopal worship resonated with something so deep in my soul that
I have never been able to identify it. I only knew I had found what
I was looking for. It was like falling in love.
 &HT;    And thus, I stayed with that which I loved. In time, ardor
dimmed for more mundane concerns -- mostly those of living with
other Episcopalians. Like other towns, this one is full of oddball
and eccentric folk whose tragedies, conflicts, crises, joys and
triumphs give life to the community. These thousands of stories --
diverse as the characters themselves -- come together to share the
communion meal around the altar. Every Sunday. Week after week.
 &HT;    Stayers do the same thing every Sunday, say the same words, see
the same people. But in the places where our stories are known, and
in the place where we know the stories, our lives may be changed in
unexpected ways. The routine is the adventure.
 &HT;    In her small book, ``The Quotidian Mysteries,'' Kathleen Norris
writes, ``Our daily tasks, whether we perceive them as drudgery or
essential, life-supporting work ... have a considerable spiritual
import, and their significance for Christian theology, the way they
come together in the fabric of faith, is not often appreciated. But
it is in daily tasks, daily acts of love and worship that serve to
remind us that religion is not strictly an intellectual pursuit ...
faith is a way of life.''
 &HT;    Stayers often do these daily tasks of faith. Being there.
Chairing committees, changing diapers, cleaning the coffee cups.
 &HT;    ``It is a paradox of human life,'' continues Norris, ``that in
worship as in human love, it is in the routine and the everyday
that we find the possibilities for the greatest transformation.''
 &HT;    Sometimes, after 40 years, I don't want to go to church on
Sunday. It is so routine. But routine is the point. So I go. And I
hope to keep that routine for another 40.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.1999 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass, Ph.D., writes a religion column for the
Santa Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious
studies at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is
``Standing Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th
Century America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
