<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-HUNGARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW NATO NATION WEIGHS ITS DEDICATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAPEST _ It was not the most auspicious timing in history:
Just weeks after Hungary joined NATO, it became a member of an
alliance waging a nasty war, right under Hungary's southern border.
</P>
<P>
   But then again, Hungary has never been known for its well-timed
choices. In World War I, Hungary sided with the Germans, and
forfeited substantial territory when it lost. In World War II,
Hungary sided with the Nazis, and in the postwar negotiations ended
up under the thumb of the Soviet Union for 45 years.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to be on the winning, prosperous side for a change,
Hungary lobbied hard to get into NATO. And now, many Hungarians are
wondering just what they've gotten themselves into _ again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we are again, in the wrong place, at the wrong time.
Throughout history, we have always joined the wrong organization at
the wrong time,'' lamented Agi Veres, 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy Hungary has joined NATO, since it's the first step
to joining Western Europe in general,'' said Veres, a management
consultant. But the timing was off, she said. ``The war is too
close and it could turn into something messy,'' Veres said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's most prominent members are bickering over the extent and
direction of the military campaign against Yugoslavia. The British
are advocating ground troops; the Americans are reluctant to send
them, and both Germany and Italy have made noises about
interrupting the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   As a NATO newcomer, Hungary has officially been extremely
cooperative. The government has agreed to allow the use of
Hungarian air space; it is accepting the arrival of 24 F-18 fighter
jets this weekend; and it is allowing the use of its southern base
in Taszar.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've really stepped up to the plate,'' said a Western
diplomat. ``They've done everything we've asked, and have welcomed
us with open arms.''
</P>
<P>
   But the cracks are starting to show in Hungary's commitment, as
they are in the rest of the military alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Socialist opposition camp, which earlier agreed
to allow the use of Hungarian air space for NATO, have called for a
new vote on the resolution. A recent poll by Teledirect showed that
72 percent of Hungarians opposed air strikes from Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   And while Hungarian voters want to be in NATO, they do not
always want to accept the responsibilities associated with it,
according to surveys by the respected Median polling institute.
</P>
<P>
   Before and after the bombing, a solid 60 percent wanted to be in
NATO, studies from March and April show. But two-thirds say no NATO
troops should be sent from Hungary; just 10 percent think Hungarian
troops should go; and only 26 percent of people think Hungarian
soldiers in general should have to defend other NATO members, which
is a basic element of the NATO mutual-defense charter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We joined NATO for security and peace. Then, right after we
joined, NATO got into a shooting war, and it stunned people. They
are thinking, `Is this what we bargained for?' '' said Laszlo
Kondor, a 58-year-old photographer who fought for the United States
in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's demands ``are a good wakeup call for Hungary,'' Kondor
said. ``People here need to understand there is no free lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Hungary is also feeling an economic pinch. Nearly 8,000
Yugoslavs, both ethnic Albanians and Serbs, have come to Hungary
requesting asylum. Another 35,000-40,000 are staying with friends
and family here, waiting out the war, said Foreign Ministry
spokesman Gabor Horvath.
</P>
<P>
   Hungary's once-blossoming tourist industry is likely to take a
substantial hit, dropping from $1.3 billion in 1998 to an estimated
$1 billion this year because of travelers' worries about touring
just north of the war zone, according to a study released Wednesday
by GKI Economic Research said.
</P>
<P>
   Hungarians are also nervous that they, or the 400,000 ethnic
Hungarians living in nearby Vojvodina, will become targets of
retribution if troops or fighter planes are sent from Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   Vojvodina, a nothern province of Serbia, is best protected by a
speedy NATO victory, British Defense Secretary George Robertson
told reporters after meeting with Hungarian Prime Minister Viktor
Orban Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's scare-mongering to say Vojvodina would be
next in the drive for ethnic purity,'' Robertson said, and Hungary
must do its part in the war effort.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and the European Union are ``attractive to join and bring
benefits,'' he said. ``But they also bring heavy responsibilities,
too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
