A4660 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICS-WELD-BOS &LR;      05-20 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-WELD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WELD'S REAL-LIFE SEQUEL, WASHINGTON IS PART OF THE PLOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH AND FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a novelist, he has sent his fictional alter ego to
Washington. Now Bill Weld admits he still has an interest in making
the journey himself.
</P>
<P>
   Not as a senator or even as a cabinet secretary _ two jobs he
once lusted after but now dismisses with a wave of the hand. Weld
would only shoot for president or vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to come up for air in 2003 and have a look,'' Weld
said while he munched on Chinese food during a lunch interview that
ranged from the future of the GOP to the depredations a red-tailed
hawk has visited upon the Weld family menagerie.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Weld is putting the final touches on his second
novel, which will be published this fall, and mulling the plot for
a third book. He's squeezing in the literary work as he carries out
a white-shoe law practice that is steadily expanding his already
considerable wealth and that promises to give him a hefty personal
bank account to jump-start his political career.
</P>
<P>
   As for his national ambitions, the former Massachusetts governor
would be a long shot, and he knows it. A Republican victory in 2000
would bring the portcullis crashing down on any hopes for 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a Democrat wins next year, the socially liberal Weld
realizes he would have a difficult time overcoming opposition from
hard-core GOP conservatives, the more so since his 1997 showdown
with Jesse Helms, the archconservative North Carolina Republican
and chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee. Weld's
failed bid for for an ambassadorship boosted his national profile
but reinforced his status as anathema to the Republican right wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the most likely result is I'll come up for air, see my
shadow, and plow forward in the business world,'' mused the
governor, in one of a series of mixed and whimsical metaphors.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether another defeat would force the GOP to move
centerward enough to make his politics palatable, Weld sloughed off
the questions. That line of inquiry, he said, puts the focus on a
possible future candidacy and not where it belongs: on his hiatus
from politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm taking a five-year vow of chastity,'' he said. ``And it's
likely the vow will not be only five years. The most likely thing
is that the vow will be sempiternal.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he's obviously thinking change. Weld is backing Texas
Governor George W. Bush for president next year, partly because he
considers Bush's politics a refreshing change from the party's
standard conservative fare.
</P>
<P>
   And in New York, where he spends several nights a week on
business, Weld is a strong supporter of Mayor Rudy Guiliani for US
Senator, even if his foe turns out to be Hillary Rodham Clinton,
Weld's friend since their service together on the House Judiciary
Committee staff during Watergate. He and Guiliani, both former
federal prosecutors, go back nearly two decades. But Weld also
thinks Guiliani's election would help strengthen the GOP's moderate
wing nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my point of view, having Rudy Guiliani and Christy
Whitman to join Olympia Snowe and Susan Collins and Arlen Specter
is helpful from within the Republican Party,'' Weld said.
</P>
<P>
   But when decision time comes, Weld doubts the first lady will
run. ``I am not sure she will see the upside,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Weld says he wouldn't take a cabinet job if the
Republicans win in 2000, he thinks his successor, Paul Cellucci,
stands a good chance of landing a top spot if Bush makes it to the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might not be interested, but I think the Bushes, both
father and son, think highly of him,'' said Weld, who seemed coy
even as he denied having discussed the possibility with his former
Number Two.
</P>
<P>
   Weld may have ruled out ever again seeking a Senate seat, but
Terrence Mullally, the prosecutor-cum-pol he created last year as
the lead character in ``Mackerel by Moonlight,'' his first novel,
commences a career in the Senate in the sequel, ``Big Ugly,'' due
out in October.
</P>
<P>
   There, Weld says, Mullally finds himself over his head, under
fire, and in danger of being revealed as the murderer he became at
the end of the first novel. Last year's title came from an 18th
century insult that John Randolph of Virginia once hurled at a foe:
``Your record, sir, resembles a rotting mackerel by moonlight: it
shines and it stinks.''The sequel is named for a town Weld has
invented in West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   There's never been any doubt that Mullally is Weld in disguise.
And indeed, in speaking about his protagonist, the former governor
sometimes lapses into the first person.
</P>
<P>
   Weld makes no boasts about the book's literary merit. Asked if
his second book is better than his first, which received mixed
reviews, he is forthright: ``No, it's worse.'' But, he says, he's
studied best sellers and hopes that shortening the chapters will
make this a page turner.
</P>
<P>
   Intriguingly, a man who as governor prided himself on never
holding a grudge hints that the book contains a little payback for
Helms, whose opposition blocked his confirmation as ambassador to
Mexico in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you'll find when you read the second book that to the
extent that I had any road rage left over from the fall of 1997, it
was reserved for Big Ugly,'' he concluded.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Frank Phillips and Scot Lehigh are members of the Globe's State
House Bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
