<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING STAINS OFF MARBLE IS A CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Someone left a bucket on my dark-green marble bathroom floor,
leaving a ring on the marble. How can I remove it?
</P>
<P>
   BILL HOYSGAARD, Sherborn, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Marble will stain if you look at it _ it is that absorbent,
and a pain to maintain. Try wetting the spots, applying a little
Soft Scrub, and rubbing a bit. There is enough abrasive in the Soft
Scrub, it is hoped, to abrade the stain without affecting the
marble. If it removes the stain but leaves the spot dull, apply a
little marble polish to that one tile.
</P>
<P>
   An even milder abrasive is rottenstone, sold in hardware stores.
This is how to use it: Apply water to the stain, sprinkle just a
bit of the rottenstone on the wet spot, and rub with your hands.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My prefinished, oak strip flooring was installed last June,
and so far there are no gaps between the strips. Is June a good
time to install strips to prevent development of gaps? Also, I have
another prefinished floor. Can I sand it?
</P>
<P>
   D.P., Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, it's OK to install strip flooring in June but just
barely; definitely not July and August, and maybe September, when
the boards are at their wettest and largest.
</P>
<P>
   The best time to install oak strip flooring (or any other strip
wood) is in winter (October to April and May), when they are at
their driest (the heat is on, helping to dry them out). Then, when
they gain moisture and expand, then contract again, no new gaps
will show.
</P>
<P>
   You can sand and refinish prefinished oak boards, as long as
they are 3/4-inch thick and not laminated.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My Armstrong Never-Wax kitchen floor is 20 years old and
getting dull. How can I refinish it or treat it so it will be a bit
shinier? My daughter has a No-Wax floor. Can the same thing be done
for it?
</P>
<P>
   L.M., Weymouth, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Before doing anything further, call Armstrong to determine
the right treatment. Armstrong and other flooring companies used to
have special treatments for Never-Wax and No-Wax flooring. I would
think they still do.
</P>
<P>
   Short of that, use Future on the floor. It will darken it a bit
but also give it a shine. Repeat in a year. The same treatment can
be used on a No-Wax floor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About those gray marks on nailheads in plasterboard walls that
show up even when covered with joint compound.
</P>
<P>
   The handyman suggested that this was due to water vapor in the
house condensing on the nailheads, which are cooler than the
surrounding plasterboard. The condensing water vapor makes these
spots damp (you might not even see the dampness), and dirt tends to
collect on the damp spots. Those spots also might be mold (mildew).
To clean the dirt, wash with Spic and Span and water, although spot
washing is iffy. If the spots are mold, wash with a solution of
bleach and water.
</P>
<P>
   However, Tom Ruden of Newton Highlands, Mass. has another idea:
that the spots are caused by Earth's magnetic field. Minute
particles of iron (or steel) collect on the slightly magnetized
nailheads (even through the plasterboard), showing up as gray
marks, said Ruden in a recent call.
</P>
<P>
   Good point, Tom. The handyman assumes that these particles can
be brushed off, especially before they show rust (if the spots are
damp).
</P>
<P>
   The solution to the metal particles is to use aluminum, brass,
or other nonmagnetic metal screws or nails to put up the
plasterboard. There is no practical cure for the gray spots if they
are caused by dirt or mold. Simply keep after them by washing
and/or bleaching.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The nailheads on my clapboard siding are beginning to rust.
How can I prevent that rusting? How can I cover the heads?
</P>
<P>
   MARY MURRAY, Sudbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Ah yes, the rusting nailheads on clapboards. It's a perennial
problem on some houses where galvanized nails or bright
(ungalvanized) nails were used. High-quality galvanized nails (hot
zinc dipped, not electroplated) will resist rust for many years,
but eventually will rust.
</P>
<P>
   You probably have galvanized nails that have given up the ghost.
It is not practical to cover them, you cannot countersink them and
fill the holes with putty because the clapboards are too thin, and
painting them with a rust resistant paint is also unsatisfactory _
it won't work for long, and you would have to repaint or restain
the house.
</P>
<P>
   The only real solution is to pull the nails and replace them
with stainless steel ones. To pull the old nails, pry up the
clapboard a bit, then tap back, revealing the head so it can be
pulled. If the head does not reveal, pry up the clapboard again and
hold the shank of the nail with pliers before tapping back.
</P>
<P>
   You can put the stainless steel nails in the same hole, or drive
them an inch or so to one side of the hole. You can fill the holes
with exterior wood filler or leave them alone; left alone, they
will soon virtually disappear when the clapboards gain moisture and
swell up a little.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
