<SLUG> BC-REFUGEES-BREAD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAD IS THE STAFF OF LIFE FOR FAMISHED KOSOVARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ The food chain, spanning continents and
cultures, doesn't quite end with the seven loaves of bread in Adem
Kruiziu's arms.
</P>
<P>
   As he does once a day every day, the construction worker and
Kosovar refugee still has to dole them out to the 15 relatives who
accompanied him to Kukes six weeks ago. It's his job to make sure
that none of the children and adults who make up the displaced
Kruiziu clan go hungry, and it's his job to pick up the loaves from
the back of a relief agency's truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bread is everything,'' said Kruiziu, a 34-year-old father
of five. ``I ate it for breakfast and I will eat it with dinner. We
eat it with beans, with canned meat, with every meal.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Kruiziu, hundreds of thousands of Kosovar refugees now
living in Albania consider bread both sustenance and soccer
equipment. The free loaves, thousands baked locally in Kukes,
thousands more trucked up from the south, are so plentiful that
some youngsters use them to practice kicking goals. Others rot in
piles in a neighborhood park. Pilfered sacks of wheat also
sometimes turn up for sale at local markets.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the fat, golden loaves appear to be used as
intended: as a cheap, easily deliverable staple in a country
overwhelmed overnight by the number of newcomers it must feed. Each
one is expected to sustain two to four people a day, depending on
their other rations, and some refugees joke that they plan to cut
bread from their diet as soon as they return home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is good they give us bread,'' Zade Cholku said through a
translator as she waited in line for the six loaves that her family
of 10 consumes daily. ``They give us a lot of bread. In the two
months we are here, we eat more bread than in all our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The loaves that Choklu and another 30 or so refugees were
waiting to collect outside one of the tractor camps that have
sprung up around Kukes started as surplus US wheat, although Japan,
Turkey and the European Union have donated tons and tons of it,
too. Arriving mostly by ship, the wheat flour's international
flavor expands anew once inside Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Sweden, for instance, has donated a fleet of 20-plus trucks,
drivers and crews to load the flour at the dock in Durres and
unload it at one of the warehouses maintained by the World Food
Programme, the United Nations agency that is overseeing the entire
operation. NATO, the US Army and Albanian truck drivers have also
helped transport enough to provide Kosovar refugees in Kukes alone
with 35,000 loaves of bread a day.
</P>
<P>
   For 20 cents a loaf, paid by the food program with UN funds, the
employees at a half-dozen Kukes bakeries work from before dawn on
to provide their share of the bread. On a recent morning, a human
chain formed outside the bakery where Osman Qoqaj pulls 4,000 black
bread pans a day from six ovens, one batch after another after
another. The men, many of them volunteers, were passing two loaves
at a time from shelf to man to truck in the most efficient way,
perhaps the only way, to move that much bread several times a day.
</P>
<P>
   Himself a Kosovar refugee and third-generation baker Prizren,
Qoqaj said he lines up like everyone else for his own extended
family's share of bread. Thirty-three relatives are currently
sharing a one-room apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a bit sick of bread myself, but I'm glad for the work,''
said Qoqaj, a 29-year-old father of one who landed the job a month
ago, almost as soon as he arrived. ``And it's good to be helping in
the best way I can.''
</P>
<P>
   All told, Kukes bakeries provide 7,000 loaves a day, with
another 25,000 arriving from Albania's largest bakery in Elbasan. A
mobile bakery in Shkodra, as well as four bakeries there, bring
total production to about 50,000 loaves a day _ a number that will
double when a new mobile bakery goes into operation and additional
bakers are hired to provide bread to the new and fast-growing
refugee camps in southern Albania.
</P>
<P>
   From the bakers, non-governmental relief agencies take over
delivery, a system that appears to work better in the camps near
cities than in outlying villages where both Kosovar refugees and
Albanians displaced by Serb shelling along the Yugoslavia-Albania
border are living with host families. Although those refugees do
not yet receive fresh bread, they complain that supplies of wheat
and other basics such as sugar, beans and cooking oil are not
reaching them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no food, no flour, nothing,'' said Hamdi Gajraku, 50,
a construction worker forced to relocate along with 25 relatives
and about 250 other Albanians from their border village to a safer
spot in the hills above Kukes. ``The international community has
done nothing for us.''
</P>
<P>
   As they do in Kukes, Gajraku and about two dozen other
``delegates'' stood waiting for the trucks to arrive. But Reiseal
NiChilleachair, a representative with a distribution agency called
CONCERN, fretted that she could not verify who was a refugee and
who wasn't, and that the food would not reach the right 259 people.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Kukes, attempts are also made to ascertain who is
entitled to the free bread. An employee with Catholic Relief
Charities, which distributes the loaves locally along with the
Adventist Development and Relief Agency, read out names from a list
at each stop. But scores of children had already grabbed as many
loaves as they could carry in their arms and every so often an
impatient adult reached into the pile and popped a half-dozen
loaves into a sack, purse or plastic bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a beneficiaries list, where we've identified group
leaders or the heads of refugee families who can pick up the
bread,'' said Kim Wahlberg, a project coordinator with Catholic
Relief who helps distribute 5,000 loaves a day from the back of the
agency's two white trucks. ``It doesn't always go exactly as
planned, but we know we're getting the bread to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Luke Stephens, a project coordinator wth MedAir, a Swiss
non-profit agency that manages a transit center and has so far
served 70,000 meals of hot soup, ``As far as I can tell, there
aren't any cracks to fall through. You don't see anyone going
hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   Around lunch-time earlier this week, Driton Sahatgiu, a Kosovar
who works one of the Catholic relief trucks for what he described
as decent pay, climbed down, helped spread a cloth on the ground
and began unloading the bread he had loaded only hours ago. On a
typical day, he said, his group makes three bread runs _ morning,
noon and night _ and hands out at least 1,700 loaves at 22 sites
around Kukes.
</P>
<P>
   For Sahatgiu, bread has become both a way to make a living and a
way to keep his mind off his refugee status. Surrounded by the rich
aroma of fresh-baked loaves, a smell that he said reminded him of
home, he bemoaned the dirty, dilapidated hotel where his family now
lives. In Kosovo, they owned two houses, and he stayed behind alone
to protect one until three weeks ago. His wife, mother and other
relatives had been sent ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm doing is good, the money is OK ...,'' Sahatgiu said
in English mid-way through the bread run. ``But someone just told
me that my cousin who is in the (Kosovo Liberation Army) is dead. I
don't want to believe it. I have to find out if he is alive. I'm
going to try to figure out how to do that between deliveries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
