<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4663 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     05-20 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD CHAMPIONS SEEM TO BE WILTING BEFORE OUR EYES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It doesn't get any better than this for beleaguered
Bostonians. Long-suffering legions of Red Sox Nation will tell you
there is nothing sweeter than beating the Yankees; especially a
defending world champion Yankee team; especially with George
Steinbrenner fuming in the expensive seats.
</P>
<P>
   Think these Yankees can win the American League wild-card
playoff spot?
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, no photos of mighty, mighty Boss George snarling from the
lower boxes this morning. Steinbrenner was safely encased behind
the soundproof glass of the 600 Club Wednesday night when his team
fell behind the Red Sox for the second straight evening. George
left early, before a 73-minute rain delay stretched the game toward
the midnight hour.
</P>
<P>
   The final was Boston 6, New York 0, pushing the Sox to a 1
1/2-game lead over the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell, yeah, they're frustrated,'' manager Joe Torre said of
his troops. ``I don't see despair, but they're fighting themselves.
We were a little spoiled last year. We didn't have any
malfunctions. But somebody's gonna take a beating out there one of
these days. Tonight it was us.''
</P>
<P>
   The first ``Yankees Suck'' chants rained down from the Fenway
Park grandstand at precisely 9 p.m. _ an hour before the
ninth-inning rain delay effectively emptied the yard.
</P>
<P>
   In dramatic lore these upstart Red Sox are the gypsies, tramps,
and thieves of the big leagues. Their real names are Varitek,
Offerman, and Rose and Wednesday night they again conquered the
Bronx Bomb Shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Call it ``Duquette's Revenge.'' Call it ``No Fear Strikes Out.''
Maybe the Rocket's red glare somehow brings bad karma to a
successful clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Probably this is only a temporary condition but right now Jason
Varitek is better than Bill Dickey or Thurman Munson, and the
greatest team of the century (one year later) is sagging under the
weight of its own destiny. The Yankees have lost seven of eight,
and eight of 11.
</P>
<P>
   What else is there to say? Bring back Don Zimmer?
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks have the man they love back in the dugout, but not
even the estimable Torre could have expected things to be going
this badly upon his return to the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Hideki Irabu, a.k.a. the ``fat toad'' and ``the fat plum,'' was
the victim of Boston's latest assault. In Georgespeak, Irabu ``spit
the bit,'' surrendering nine hits and five runs in 3 2/3 innings.
In eight innings, Yankee pitchers surrendered 15 hits to the
oft-ridiculed Red Sox. Today's New York starter is Orlando ``El
Duque'' Hernandez, who has a whopping ERA of 6.56. Do they really
expect help from Tony Fossas and Jay Tessmer?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed in myself,'' Irabu said through his Holy
Cross-trained interpreter, George Rose. ``I expect to do well. I
know that's what people expect of me.''
</P>
<P>
   On paper, there is no comparison between the Red Sox and
Yankees. So why have the Sox been able to pummel the pine tar out
of the New Yorkers for two straight days? And why is it that Brian
Rose, he of nine big league appearances and one victory, was able
to shut out the Yankees for seven frustrating innings? In their two
games here this week, the Yankees have scored three runs and left
24 men on base.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly going through a bad stretch,'' admitted center
fielder Bernie Williams. ``We can't get any offense going. It's
very frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   The New Yorkers are reeling. Second baseman Chuck Knoblauch
(he's no Jose Offerman) just snapped out of an 0-for-22 funk, but
continues to struggle at the plate and threw a ball into left field
Tuesday night. Like many of the normally patient Yankee hitters,
Knoblauch has suddenly decided to make things easy on pitchers by
swinging early in the count.
</P>
<P>
   It's pretty much the same up and down the lineup. None of the
Yankee catchers are hitting and that would include Mike Figga, this
year's candidate for the Roger LaFrancois memorial trophy. Figga
has yet to bat this season, though Wednesday night seemed like a
perfect opportunity to give him a shot. Meanwhile, the
ever-combustible Paul O'Neill is in a funk and remains a threat to
destroy all helmets, bat racks, and urinals in his path.
</P>
<P>
   This is all great news for the suddenly surging Red Sox. Boston
fans can only hope the Yankees are still ice cold when the Sons of
Jimy Williams invade the Bronx early next week.
</P>
<P>
   The hallowed halls of Boston's numerous colleges and universites
must be fun this week. Traditionally, Boston-New York athletic
jousts are cause for commotion in the corridors of higher learning
and New Englanders no doubt are having some fun with their New York
classmates during this strange spring of bizarro baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always concerned,'' admitted Torre. ``But not to the
point of thinking you can't do something. It's just a matter of
time when it'll turn around. It's just a matter of keeping your
composure.''
</P>
<P>
   They play one more Thursday night at the Fens. El Duque vs. Mark
Portugal. The Sox are guaranteed to be in first when it's over,
maybe by 2 1/2 games.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
