<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRTH CONTROL INJECTION AWAITS FEDERAL APPROVAL  
 CHINESE HERB MIX SHOWS HOPE ON PROSTATE CANCER  
 SCREENING PROCESS SEEN FOR FORM OF ANAL CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN HSU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 
 Birth control injection awaits federal approval
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For women who have a hard time remembering to take their birth
control pills every day, another choice may be on the way as early
as the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   A once-a-month shot was found 100 percent effective in its first
US clinical trial of almost 800 women. The injectable drug, called
Lunelle, contains estrogen and progestin, the same hormones used in
most birth control pills.
</P>
<P>
   The birth control shot is currently under review by the Food and
Drug Administration. It is developed by Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn, which
also makes Depo-Provera, a quarterly injectable contraceptive.
</P>
<P>
   The study, at 42 sites in the United States for 60 weeks,
compared 782 women ages 18-49 using the monthly shot and 321 women
using Ortho-Novum, a birth control pill. Researchers found that the
most common adverse effects were similar to oral contraceptives,
and women on Lunelle had one less day of regular menstrual bleeding
than those on the pills. After skipping a shot, women returned to
fertility in a month.
</P>
<P>
   One of the study investigators, Dr. Andrew Kaunitz of the
University of Florida in Jacksonville, said the monthly shot is
easily administered in the hip, thigh or shoulder muscles. Kaunitz
said he was not aware of any allergic reactions. During the study,
which will be extended for a year, there were two unplanned
pregnancies in the oral contraceptive group and none in the Lunelle
group. Many of the women who took part in the first phase of the
study plan to continue.
</P>
<P>
   The drug has already gone through extensive testing outside the
United States. About 17,000 women have participated in the World
Health Organization's clinical trials of the product, which has
also been called Cyclo-Provera and Cyclofem.
</P>
<P>
   Depo-Provera, the injectable contraceptive currently on the
market, is administered four times a year. However, women do not
have regular menstrual cycles, experience unpredictable spotting or
absence of bleeding, and do not return to fertility until nine
months after stopping the shots.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn said that the cost of the monthly shot would
be comparable to a monthly supply of pills.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Chinese herb mix shows hope on prostate cancer
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A blend of eight Chinese herbs has shown promise as a treatment
for advanced prostate cancer, even with men who have failed
conventional hormone therapy.
</P>
<P>
   The herbal concoction, called PC-SPES (``PC'' stands for
prostate cancer and ``SPES'' is Latin for hope), is sold in health
food stores as a dietary supplement.
</P>
<P>
   Although researchers at the University of California in San
Francisco are not sure what active ingredients in the mixture are
beneficial, they believe the compound holds estrogenic and active
anti-cancer qualities.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, 61 men received nine capsules of the herbal
mixture daily. Twenty-seven men had not received hormonal therapy,
which is used to reduce a man's supply of testosterone to a
prostate tumor, and 34 were hormone-resistant patients, whose
tumors no longer responded to hormonal therapies.
</P>
<P>
   All the men who never received hormones responded to the herbs
with lower levels of prostate specific antigen (PSA), a blood
marker used to track the cancer.
</P>
<P>
   What surprised USCF associate professor Eric Small was that
almost 60 percent of the hormone-resistant patients also
experienced at least a 50 percent decline in their PSA levels.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the patients have been taking the herbs, which cost
about $450 for a month's supply, for about eight months. To find
out more about the duration of the mixture's effectiveness on
patients, the study will go on for at least another year or two,
Small said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Screening process seen for form of anal cancer
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also at USCF, researchers said a simple, early screening
procedure for anal squamous cell cancer could lead to a drop in
disease and death among gay men similar to what the Pap smear test
has done for cervical cancer in women. Anal sex puts people at risk
for this uncommon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   According to a study in this week's issue of JAMA, 35
HIV-negative gay men per 100,000 develop this form of anal cancer
each year (the rate is even higher among HIV-positive gay men),
which compares to about 40 women per 100,000 who contracted
cervical cancer each year before the Pap smear was widely used.
Now, about eight women per 100,000 get cervical cancer. The
procedure would involve inserting a swab into the anal canal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
