<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4679 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONCOMPUTERS-COLUMN-BO     05-20 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONCOMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERCLOCKING AND LOVING IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a would-be designer of computer games, Boston University
student Tyrell Gales needs the fastest, most powerful computer he
can afford.
</P>
<P>
   His machine is set up to run both Windows 98 and Microsoft's
high-end Windows NT operating systems. It's packed with 128
megabytes of RAM. And where most computers have a single graphics
accelerator to draw 3D images on the screen, Gales has three of
them for razor-sharp image quality.
</P>
<P>
   So you'd expect Gales' machine to have one of Intel's most
powerful chips under the hood. A Pentium II 450 perhaps, or one of
the new Pentium III chips.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he's running an Intel Celeron, a chip developed for use
in those sub-$500 PCs they sell at Best Buy. In fact, Gales uses
the Celeron 300A, a version so obsolete Intel has stopped making
it.
</P>
<P>
   Gales doesn't care; he loves his Celeron. ``They can outperform
the Pentium II 450 on games,'' he says ``There's no question of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute. How can a $100 Celeron chip outperform a $400
Pentium II chip? Well, it can't _ unless you cheat. That's what
Gales and thousands of other hardcore computer buffs do every day.
By using a risky little trick called overclocking, they can turn a
low-end chip into a flamethrower.
</P>
<P>
   The speed rating of the typical chip contains a sizable safety
margin. A Celeron chip rated at 300 megahertz can actually run
faster. You speed up the chip by speeding up the motherboard, and
sometimes by slightly increasing the voltage to the chip. A Celeron
300A was designed to communicate with the motherboard at 66
megahertz. But if you reset the motherboard speed to 100 megahertz,
the Celeron is suddenly running at 450 megahertz.
</P>
<P>
   It gets better. Processor chips use a bit of memory called a
cache to speed up performance. Ironically, the Celeron's cache is
faster than a Pentium II 450's at any speed. So a Celeron running
at 450 is actually a bit faster for some tasks than the Pentium II.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Goodman, who runs PCs for Everyone, the geek headquarters
in Cambridge, told me he can't keep the 300As in stock. College
kids like Gales gobble them up for use as overclocked 450s. The
$300 they save on the processor gets spent on better graphics cards
or larger hard drives.
</P>
<P>
   And cooling fans, of course. Overclocking a chip causes it to
run much hotter than usual. To do it safely, you've got to bolt
extra cooling fans and heat sinks onto the chip. A whole
chip-cooling industry has sprung up to cater to the needs of
overclockers. For instance, a South Carolina firm called KryoTech
Inc. makes a computer case with a small refrigerator built in, just
for cooling the processor. Even the motherboard makers have gotten
into the act, creating special boards tailored for overclockers.
</P>
<P>
   Overclockers are passionate about their art, even compiling
reams of statistics on the performance of their chips. Joe
Citarella, a retired GTE marketing manager, has published their
data at his Web site, overclockers.com.
</P>
<P>
   Like a wine buff who says he can taste a cabernet and tell you
what corner of the vineyard the grapes came from, Citarella says he
can roughly predict the performance of an overclocked chip by
looking at which Intel plant cranked it out. ``The chips that came
out of Costa Rica,'' he says, ``require on average a tenth of a
volt more to run than the chips that come out of Malaysia.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel spokesman Michael Sullivan regards the whole thing with
wary amusement. ``We know that people like to do this and they're
willing to take risks with their property, and that's OK,'' he
says. But Sullivan warns that overclocking will invalidate the
warranty on a computer. Besides, even if it works, overclocking may
shorten the life of the chip. ``Our recommendation is, don't do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fat chance of that. Citarelli's overclockers.com Web site,
founded in November, has drawn nearly a million visitors. Some are
drawn by the technical challenge of overclocking, while others just
like the idea of paying Intel $100 and getting $400 worth of
horsepower. ``I think there's a great American tradition of
sticking it to the big guy,'' says Citarelli. ``I think it's as
simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(You can send electronic mail to Hiawatha Bray at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
