<HEADLINE>
CHEF'S DEVOTION TO FOOD LEADS TO USEFUL COOKBOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's no doubting Amanda Hesser's devotion to food. Or her
ambition or creativity in pursuit of that devotion.
</P>
<P>
   Hesser decided seven years ago when she was at Bentley College
in Waltham, Mass., that she wanted to learn from the very best
everything there is to know about cooking and baking.
</P>
<P>
   She contacted her favorite restaurant, Michela's in nearby
Cambridge and persuaded chef-owner Jody Adams to allow her to come
work weekends _ at no salary _ in the kitchen. She also convinced
her favorite bakery, Panini, to allow her to spend Saturday nights
learning the basics of artisanal bread making. At no salary, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a good view, the real view, of restaurant life and I
learned the basics of bread making. I even drove the delivery truck
around Boston at 6 in the morning, when the sky was just lighting
up,'' Hesser said. ``I guess it shows how nuts I am, because that's
how I spent all my weekends my senior year in college.''
</P>
<P>
   She followed that by spending three months upstate New York at
the highly regarded Wookstock-area bakery Bread Alone, continuing
her education in wood-fired oven baking. Then Hesser took off for
Europe, where she spent the next three years serving
apprenticeships at some of the premier restaurants and bakeries in
France, Germany, Italy and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   She was there to learn, and asked for only room and board in
return. She had prearranged each job while still in the United
States, knowing instinctively that this was a path to a chef's
version of a doctorate degree that didn't require the tuition of a
leading culinary school.
</P>
<P>
   Hesser's experiences in Europe also gave her the opportunity to
write one of the most attractive and pleasing food books of 1999,
``The Cook and the Gardener: A Year of Recipes and Writings from
the French Countryside'' (W.W. Norton, $32.50).
</P>
<P>
   Hesser, 27, a writer for the New York Times' Dining In/Dining
Out section since 1997 (her first full-time job), chronicles a year
she spent as a cook under Anne Willan at the fabled Chateau du Fey
in Burgundy. There, she met the gardener, Monsier Milbert, a
curmudgeonly man mistrustful of the young American chef.
</P>
<P>
   As the seasons change, Hesser slowly gains Milbert's confidence
and their relationship begins to bloom. ``The Cook and the
Gardener'' combines Hesser's descriptions of Milbert and his sage
ways in the garden with more than 200 recipes. Also included is
practical kitchen advice, everything from making spring stock and
strawberry jam to crafting autumn centerpieces.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes are organized, naturally, by season. Most of the
dishes feature just-picked produce, rich with the flavor of the
earth, or, as the French call it, le gout de terroir.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized not long after I arrived that I really didn't
understand the ways of the garden at all,'' she said. ``We're
always striving to cook with the freshest ingredients possible, but
a lot of chefs aren't in tune with the garden. It took me two whole
years to gain a better sense of appreciation for the seasons and
why different things are harvested when they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gardeners are visionaries,'' she added, ``always looking ahead
to the next season, while cooks live for the day.''
</P>
<P>
   From the April chapter, here is Hesser's recipe for crisp
rhubarb preserve. It can be made, she notes, without the berry
leaves.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CRISP RHUBARB PRESERVE
</P>
<P>
   (Serves 4)
</P>
<P>
   1 pound rhubarb stalks, peeled and sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar, or more if needed
</P>
<P>
   4 to 5 boysenberry leaves
</P>
<P>
   4 to 5 strawberry leaves
</P>
<P>
   4 to 5 raspberry leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 bag Ceylon tea
</P>
<P>
   1 pint strawberries, washed, hulled and halved (see note)
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla ice cream, optional
</P>
<P>
   Place the rhubarb in a large heatproof bowl. Bring 1 cup water,
the wine and the sugar to a boil, stirring to dissolve the sugar,
then turn off the heat. Add the berry leaves and tea and let infuse
for 15 minutes. Bring mixture back to a boil and strain over the
rhubarb. Cover the bowl with plastic wrap to contain the heat and
to create a hermetic atmosphere in which the rhubarb can absorb the
flavors of the infusion. Let cool, then refrigerate for at least 8
hours, to crisp the rhubarb and allow it to imbibe the flavors
further.
</P>
<P>
   Before serving, taste the syrup, adding more sugar if desired,
and the strawberries. Ladle into tall parfait glasses or small flat
bowls. If serving ice cream, place 1 scoop in each glass and ladle
the rhubarb over it.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Strawberries may not yet be in season; in this case,
either omit them, of if you have fruit preserved in alcohol (e.g.,
raspberries eau-de-vie) from the previous year, substitute these.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
