<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4683 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RHUBARB-HNS &LR;      05-20 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RHUBARB-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERLOOKED RHUBARB DESERVES MORE RESPECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a vegetable, rhubarb is rather neglected.
</P>
<P>
   Cookbooks, even notable ones such as ``Vegetables,'' by James
Peterson, and ``Uncommon Fruits and Vegetables,'' by Elizabeth
Schneider, don't include it. Even the ``Joy of Cooking'' (1975
version) only gives it a passing mention. Rhubarb deserves better.
</P>
<P>
   This tall, slim vegetable _ yes, it is a vegetable even though
in 1947 the U.S. Customs Court in Buffalo, N.Y., declared it a
fruit _ is easy to cook, has a nice tart flavor and can be used
many different ways.
</P>
<P>
   The Customs Court decided to relegate rhubarb to the fruit
category because that's how it's used most of the time. When it is
used.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a lot of demand for it,'' says Richard Holmes,
owner of Holmquist Farms in Hudson, N.Y., where rhubarb is grown
for sale this time of year. ``I don't think young kids know what
rhubarb is.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether buying rhubarb from a farm stand or at the grocery
store, look for fresh stalks that are firm, not wimpy. Though
rhubarb stalks are both red and green, you'll want to find some
with red in it to give color to your finished dish. As for flavor,
it doesn't matter what color stalks you use, growers say.
</P>
<P>
   You can look for rhubarb with plump, heart-shaped leaves but you
probably won't find any. The leaves, which contain large amounts of
oxalic acid, are poisonous and generally removed before the rhubarb
is sold.
</P>
<P>
   You'll usually need to cook the rhubarb before you use it in
recipes. Elaine Holmquist, Holmes' wife, chops the stalks into
1-inch pieces and places them in a saucepan with a little water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not too much,'' she says, ``only a cup, because the rhubarb is
going to make its own water.''
</P>
<P>
   Boil it down until you have rhubarb puree and add some sugar.
Let cool. At this point, Holmquist says, you can freeze it or use
it in pies, cakes or whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Most people combine rhubarb with strawberries and bake them in a
pie. But there are other uses for rhubarb as well. Anne Gardon
suggests making Mint-Rhubarb Juice in her newly released book,
``Preserving for All Seasons'' (Firefly).
</P>
<P>
   _ Boil 12 cups of rhubarb chunks in 2 cups water until soft.
Drain cooked mixture overnight in a cheesecloth-lined colander (if
you don't have cheesecloth use an old pillowcase). Discard pulp.
Measure juice and add enough water to make 4 cups. Combine juice,
10 springs of mint and 3 cups sugar in a heavy saucepan and bring
slowly to a boil. Cook for 5 minutes. Strain mint, cool and then
freeze in rigid containers. To make a nice springtime ade, plop a
couple scoops of the frozen juice in a blender, add a bit of water
and puree.
</P>
<P>
   Gardon also combines rhubarb with orange in a lively compote.
</P>
<P>
   Simply combine the grated rind and chopped sections of 3
oranges, with 8 cups chopped rhubarb, 4 cups sugar, a pinch of
nutmeg and a pinch of cinnamon in a heavy saucepan. Bring to a
boil, reduce heat to a simmer and cook until thick, 20 to 25
minutes. Ladle into 4 hot 1-cup jars and seal. Keep refrigerated
until ready to use or store in freezer.
</P>
<P>
   Additional tips:
</P>
<P>
   _ In a blender, combine 1 cup rhubarb puree with 2 tablespoons
honey, 1 teaspoon grated gingerroot, 1 pound cleaned strawberries
and 4 cups plain yogurt for smoothies. Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   _ One pound of rhubarb equals 3 cups of raw, sliced rhubarb.
</P>
<P>
   _ Since rhubarb was one of the first crops of spring in colder
climates, it was considered as a tonic, wrote James Beard in
``American Cookery.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Interestingly enough, rhubarb has laxative properties, so it's
best not to have too many helpings of the rhubarb pie.
</P>
<P>
   _ A 1/2 cup serving of diced, sweetened rhubarb has 139
calories, 0.1 gram fat, 2.4 grams fiber, 37 grams carbohydrate and
2 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RHUBARB-STRAWBERRY PIE
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 8 servings)
</P>
<P>
   Refrigerated pie crust for a 9-inch 2-crust pie
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chopped rhubarb
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sliced strawberries
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon grated orange rind, optional
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   Line a 9-inch pie pan with a pie crust. Heat oven to 450
degrees. Combine rhubarb, strawberries, sugar, flour, salt and
orange rind. Turn into pie pan. Dot with butter. Top with other pie
crust and crimp top and bottom edges together. Cut slits in top of
pie. Bake 15 minutes. Reduce heat to 350 degrees and bake 25 to 30
minutes more. Cool on rack. Serve warm or cold.
</P>
<P>
   (Adapted from ``James Beard's American Cookery.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
