<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAYLE-VALUES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAYLE COURTS CONSERVATIVES BY BLASTING LAWYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Former Vice President Dan Quayle is back on the
moral values warpath, this time attacking the legal system for
driving religion out of the schools and encouraging children to sue
their parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have allowed our legal system to distort and deny the role
of faith in American life, and unfortunately it's had a harmful
ripple effect,'' the Republican presidential hopeful said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   He also went after ``children's rights zealots'' for pushing the
idea that children can sue their parents, which he said undermined
parental authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every baby boomer in this room that has teen-agers has heard
the words: `I can sue you,''' he said. ``Where do they get this
idea? From the culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle made his remarks in a much-hyped address at the
Commonwealth Club on the seventh anniversary of his famed ``Murphy
Brown speech,'' in which the then-vice president criticized the
fictional television character for having a child out of wedlock.
</P>
<P>
   In that speech, on May 19, 1992, he said, ``It doesn't help
matters when prime-time TV has Murphy Brown, a character who
supposedly epitomizes today's intelligent, highly paid professional
woman, mocking the importance of fathers by bearing a child alone
and calling it just another lifestyle choice.''
</P>
<P>
   The remark made him the target of ridicule but boosted Quayle's
standing with conservatives in his party. As he tries to break out
of the pack of candidates for the Republican nomination in 2000, he
hopes the family values message will play well with the party's
right flank.
</P>
<P>
   The message may not resonate with enough California voters, said
Allan Hoffenblum, a Los Angeles-based Republican political
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``California is known as a libertarian state,'' he said.
``California voters, the majority of them anyway, get nervous about
candidates who sound more like their preacher than their
lawmaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffenblum said Quayle, knowing the speech would receive
substantial news coverage, was aiming at a larger audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't really the Commonwealth Club he was talking to,''
Hoffenblum said. ``He was talking through the media ... to the
cultural conservative camp'' across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle's new target was an easy mark: lawyers. Quayle, 52, a law
school graduate who began his career in the Indiana attorney
general's office, singled out lawyers for liberal groups, such as
the American Civil Liberties Union, but also criticized judges for
what he described as removing any shred of religion from schools
and other public institutions.
</P>
<P>
   He cited these cases:
</P>
<P>
   _ The ACLU's lawsuit against the Chicago public schools for
sponsoring the Boy Scouts, which declares a belief in God in the
organization's bylaws.
</P>
<P>
   _ A U.S. Court of Appeals ruling that a Colorado schoolteacher
who silently read the Bible during a reading period had violated
the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   _ A decision by the Third Circuit Court of Appeals in
Philadelphia that a student could not read the story of Joshua to
his class because the tale comes from the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legal aristocracy calls it separation of church and state.
But just as the old rule `separate but equal' really meant separate
and unequal, separation of church and state has come to mean all
state and no church,'' said Quayle, saying that any judges he
appointed would have to show a respect for religion.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffenblum said Quayle is trying to find his place among other
socially conservative Republican presidential hopefuls, including
publisher Steve Forbes and commentator Pat Buchanan. Quayle hopes
to find enough support to compete in the primaries against those
seen as the early favorites _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the son of
Quayle's former boss, and former Red Cross President Elizabeth
Dole.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
