<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, May 21:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GEORGIA SCHOOL SHOOTING &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GA-SCHOOL-SHOOTING (Conyers, Ga.) _ A student opened fire at a
suburban Atlanta high school early Thursday, injuring six other
students a month to the day after the Colorado school massacre,
police said. The police said none of the injuries were
life-threatening and the shooter had been taken into custody.
Identified as a sophomore boy at Heritage High School here, the
shooter was taken into custody within 10 minutes, police said.
Witnesses said he carried at least two weapons, a pump-style
shotgun and a revolver. Some reports said he tried to put the
revolver in his mouth before authorities captured him. By Kevin
Sack.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   GA-SCHOOL-SHOOTER (Conyers, Ga.) _ What we know about the
student who fired the shots. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   And these two related stories:
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-CLINTON (Littleton, Colo.) _ President Clinton talks
to families of victims in the Columbine High School shooting. By
Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-PROBE (Littleton) _ An update on the Columbine High
School investigation. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans two pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the continuing crisis over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Viktor Chernomyrdin, the Russian envoy;
Strobe Talbott of the U.S. and President Martii Ahtisaari of
Finland gather outside Moscow for talks following up Chernomyrdin's
talks with Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav president. By Celestine
Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis on all the things
that have gone wrong with the NATO campaign. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ATTACK (Belgrade) _ A scene/news story on the heaviest
NATO attack on Belgrade since the Chinese Embassy was hit. A
hospital was hit with 3 patients reported killed. The residence of
the Swedish ambassador was also hit. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ NATO's account of the Belgrade raid;
The Italian prime minister, Massimo D'Alema, visits and hardens his
position against ground troops, elaborating his bombing pause
proposal. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES-U.S. (Fort Dix, N.J.) _ Kosovar refugees at Fort
Dix are to be resettled in communities across the country as soon
as possible. The first families will go to Boise, Idaho; Sarasota,
Fla.; and Seattle. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SHAS (Jerusalem) _ A feature on Shas, the religious party
that went from 10 seats in the Israeli parliament to 17, the third
biggest bloc after Labor and Likud. A look at their principles and
their appeal. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-POLITICS (New Delhi) _ The Congress Party is expected to
expel three renegade leaders who asked the party leader, Sonia
Gandhi, to bow out of consideration for prime minister is the fall
elections. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   NEPAL-POLITICS (Katmandu) _ Following elections, the Nepalese
premier, who was serving a caretaker role, is to resign. By Barry
Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-GUNS (Washington) _ The Senate expected to pass the
juvenile justice bill, with gun-control measures attached,
including one on gun shows in which the vote was 50-50 with Vice
President Gore casting the tie-breaking vote in favor. The final
vote is expected to be late. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-GUNS-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis on the gun
bill: The Senate has done more in two weeks on gun issues than
anyone ever thought possible, but at the end of the day, it is more
political positioning than real substance. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-MISSILES (Washington) _ Final passage by the for the
missile defense bill. The House version is substantially the same
as the Senate's. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   PENTAGON-SHELTON (Washington) _ Gen. Henry H. Shelton
renominated to remain as chairman of the Joint Chiefs for of Staff
for two more years. By Steven Lee Myers. (a short)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK REGIONAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL (New York) _ Developments at the trial of police
officers accused of brutalizing Abner Louima, a Haitian immigrant
prisoner. By Joseph B. Fried.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-GUNS (Trenton, N.J.) _ Developments in the legislature: votes
on trigger locks, smart guns and parental responsibility. By Ron
Smothers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-COLA (Newark, N.J.) _ Thanks to Coke and Pepsi's desire
to market to children, and the eagerness of schools to participate
because of the money involved, Dan DeRose has been able to position
himself as a financial adviser to schools in exclusive deals that
can involve millions of dollars. But some lawmakers and educators
are moving to prevent the sale or giveaway of soft drinks in
school, citing nutrition concerns. And advocates for education say
schools have no business promoting one product over another. By
Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   PRICE-FIXING (Washington) _ The Justice Department announces the
settlement of price-fixing charges against drug makers Roche and
BASF. A third company, Rhone-Poulenc of France has been cooperating
in the investigation. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-REPORT (Washington) _ The U.S. trade deficit unexpectedly
widened to a third consecutive record in March. Analysts had been
expecting a slower swelling following February's record of $19.4
billion. But the gap rose to $19.7 billion in March, from a revised
$19.1 billion in Feburary.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:50 p.m., stocks were little changed.
The Dow Jones industrial average was up 36 points, the S&AMP;P 500 up 3
points, the Nasdaq composite up 2 points. European markets were
higher, with the FTSE up 1.6 percent and Frankfurst up 1 percent.
Stocks in Japan and Hong Kong were little changed. At midday, the
yield on the 30-year bond was 5.80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHEON-WEBMD (Undated) _ Healtheon and WebMD announce a deal,
with investment from Microsoft. By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-ECON (Washington) _ Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan and
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin testify before the Senate Banking
Committee on international financial issues. By Richard W.
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   FORD-APPOINT (Dearborn, Mich.) _ Ford Motor's chief financial
officer, John Devine, announces he will leave in September to seek
a job with more responsibility. Vice Chairman Wayne Booker will
take on Devine's financial duties, while Vice Chairman Peter
Pestillo gets an expanded portfolio. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   BARCLAYS-CUTBACK (London) _ Barclays, Britain's second-biggest
bank, plans to cut 6,000 jobs, or 10 percent of its British retail
and corporate banking staff, and take a $646 million charge. The
cutbacks are the bank's first strategic move since Michael O'Neill,
its chief executive, quit in April. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   MAZDA-EARNINGS (Tokyo) _ Mazda Motor reports its first yearly
profit in six years, helped by increased exports to the United
States. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   A.M. Rosenthal's ``On My Mind'' and Thomas L. Friedman's
``Foreign Affairs.''
</P>
