<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-SHOOTING _ CONYERS, Ga. _ Six people were shot today at a
high school in Conyers, east of Atlanta, as students were gathering
for the day. None of the injuries were believed to be
life-threatening, said Bonnie Knight, a spokeswoman for Rockdale
County schools. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GOP-NRA _ ATLANTA _ As of Wednesday the NRA's Wayne LaPierre
still planned to speak Saturday at a state GOP convention in
Augusta. Checking back with outgoing state GOP chair Rusty Paul who
invited LaPierre, and also trying to reach NRA board member and
U.S. Rep. Bob Barr, who'll introduce LaPierre on Saturday, to ask
if they still want him to appear in light of Thursday's metro
Atlanta high school shooting. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Other sidebars are developing and will be included on the 6
p.m. EDT budget.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   GUNS _ WASHINGTON _ Propelled by school violence, the Senate
votes for fresh gun restrictions over the strong opposition of most
Republicans. Vice President Al Gore breaks a 50-50 tie in favor of
a proposal to require mandatory background checks for purchases at
gun shows and to put new restrictions on pawnshop sales as well.
(Foskett, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON _ LITTLETON, Colo. _ President Clinton and his wife
console families and survivors a month after the murder-suicide
rampage that left 15 dead. Clinton calls the new shootings in
Georgia ``deeply troubling'' and says Americans must come together
``to protect all of our children from violence.'' Arrival in
Littleton is planned for about 4 p.m. EDT. An address to Columbine
students, rescuers and community leaders is scheduled for 6:15 p.m.
EDT. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH _ WASHINGTON -- Investment guru Peter Lynch addresses
annual meeting of the Investment Company Institute, the mutual fund
trade group. (McNaughton, Cox News Service). 12.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY _ WASHINGTON _ Congress members from both houses
and both parties _ including reform leaders Sens. John Breaux,
D-La., and Bob Kerrey, D-Neb. _ announce their plan for Social
Security on Thursday. (Lipman, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   CUSTOMS _ WASHINGTON _ Rep. John Lewis hears graphic testimony
in hearings on custom service searches at airports and calls for
legislation to end racial profiling in such searches. (Carr, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SETTLERS _ ACHIYA, West Bank _ For Shmuel Kohen, in the
vanguard of right-wing Israel's efforts to control disputed land,
things still look pretty good. Below his hilltop mobile home are
olive orchards and a nearby Arab village. A new paved road snakes
its way up to his remote outpost and, next door, the Israeli
soldiers who protect his and the four other families here are
grilling hot dogs. ``It is important to build Israel,'' says the
affable Kohen, 28. While his daughter toddles around beneath the
posters of famous rabbis, he dismisses the chances of peace with
Arabs. ``They want to kill Jews only because we are Jews.'' But, an
hour's drive in Jerusalem, Kohen's political supply lines have been
damaged. Israel's elections Monday dealt a stunning blow to the
right-wing settler movement. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
