<SLUG> BC-PALM-PILOT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3COM SEEKS TO PUT INTERNET IN YOUR PALM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Internet in the palm of your hand. That's
the hope of the 3Com Corp., which plans to unwrap its new Palm VII
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   This latest version of the popular hand-held organizer kicks the
portable device market to another level. The Palm VII features a
built-in modem that allows users to connect, without wires, to the
Internet, plus send and receive electronic mail.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm VII could be the first successful ultraportable,
easy-to-use Internet-linked computing device. That, so far, has
been an elusive dream of Silicon Valley, which has seen
contraptions such as the Apple Newton hand-held device killed off
by battery-life problems, size restrictions and price.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm VII, which will appear on a limited number of store
shelves later this year, will have a list price of $600 and will
have a ready-made market. Palm hand-helds account for 73 percent of
the palm-sized computer market, according to the market research
firm International Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Palm VII sets the bar of what can be done in the
area of small Internet wireless devices,'' said Jill House, an IDC
analyst. ``It's really a great machine and a great execution of the
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Palm VII resembles the current Palm III models except
that it's a fraction of an inch longer to accommodate the modem and
a rechargeable ni-cad battery. The ni-cad powers the modem and is
charged by the two replaceable AAA batteries.
</P>
<P>
   The modem is actually a small radio data transmitter that beams
information back and forth through the Bell South network. Service
is available in 260 cities, mostly on both coasts.
</P>
<P>
   3Com, based in Santa Clara, says the modem has an 8,000 bps
rate. That's slower than the standard 52K modem, but the connection
is more than adequate, given the Palm VII's connection method to
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm VII automatically links to the Internet when the user
raises a small antenna on the side of the device.
</P>
<P>
   For e-mail, the Palm VII uses installed software called
iMessenger. Here, e-mail is shuttled back and forth through the
Palm.net network. When users sign up for Palm.net service, they are
assigned an e-mail address.
</P>
<P>
   To retrieve e-mail sent to other addresses, it must be forwarded
to the palm.net address. Because of memory limitations, palm.net
service strips away any attachments before sending messages to the
Palm VII.
</P>
<P>
   Standard Palm applications, such as the calendar and contact
information, continue to be featured on the Palm VII.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
