<HEADLINE>
HOPE SPRINGS ETERNAL FROM ISRAELI ELECTION  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Commentary)   (This TIMELY, 475-word ``separate buy'' post-Israeli-election
commentary is from the International Herald Tribune.)  
  
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
  
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable
to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``k'' commentary news and ``a'' domestic/general news files.)  
  
 By GIDEON SAMET  
 c.1999 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV _ The crushing fall of Benjamin Netanyahu tells an
amazing Israeli story of a bright man who changed the rules of the
local political game, and became his own victim.
</P>
<P>
   It was not his policies, though they did set Israel back, that
brought about his resonant, pathetic defeat. It was his character.
</P>
<P>
   A child when Israel was born, I have never witnessed an election
campaign here in which the main issue was the incumbent leader's
personality. And for good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu was, as The Economist once dubbed him, a serial
bungler, an erratic leader for a nation in urgent need for an
orderly agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The popular slogan, referring to his nickname _ ``Just Not
Bibi'' _ ended the three-year dominance of a flawed politician over
the Israeli scene. This abysmal failure to make good on a vaulting
ambition gave his short career almost Shakespearean dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Netanyahu's self-destructive psyche, the election was
about Israel's political culture.
</P>
<P>
   In as much as they are surprisingly conservative, and still
gripped by tribal allegiances, the majority of Israelis felt they
had had enough.
</P>
<P>
   Enough of the cunning play on their angst over Arab threats.
Enough of their leader's unbearable propensity to alienate almost
all his colleagues and most of Israel's friends in the world, while
engaging his opponents with heated hate rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   Opposite Netanyahu, in a meticulous Tony Blair-like campaign,
Ehud Barak smartly grasped the popular urge for reconciliation,
stability and basic common sense.
</P>
<P>
   At times, as his understated tone made some of his TV
appearances seem a disaster, his supporters despaired. But as
Netanyahu was intensifying his populist, distorted attacks on the
``leftist'' elites and on the media, he isolated himself in an
increasingly paranoid campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bibi became a burden. Barak gained momentum. He now enjoys a
rare parliamentary leeway in a political system used to choking
near-ties.
</P>
<P>
   His victory is actually a revival of the late Yitzhak Rabin's
era, which was tragically cut short in the midst of major political
and economic achievements. Barak will now have to renew that
national agenda.
</P>
<P>
   In a vague campaign of soundbites, steered by a host of American
consultants, there was, for example, hardly a mention of the
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations stopped by Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Barak remained opaque on whether his wish for a wide power base
might evolve into an embrace of the religious parties _ and a
cohabitation with the Likud party that poisoned the politics of the
1980s. This will be the stuff of criticism soon awaiting the prime
minister designate.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, hope is rampant. Never have so many enthusiastic
Israelis thronged in the squares to celebrate on election night, as
if it were Independence Day. They also signaled their expectation
of a new leader who would cut a new national deal. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Gideon Samet, a columnist and member of the board
of the Israeli daily Ha'aretz, contributed this commentary to the
International Herald Tribune.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this TIMELY 475-word commentary from the International
Herald Tribune, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
