<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NYC23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New York City family style
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 23.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK CITY _ Parents plotting a family vacation to this
metropolis may feel a bit like those cowpokes in the picante sauce
commercial drawling incredulously ``Noo Yawrk Cee-uh-ty?!''
</P>
<P>
   They don't call it the Big Apple for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   It's big, all right _ not to mention incessantly noisy and
extremely crowded. Everybody, it seems, is in a powerful rush to
get where they're going. Stop to gawk at a skyscraper or consult a
map, and you could find yourself swept down the sidewalk by a tidal
surge of humanity before you know what's happening.
</P>
<P>
   For a first-time visitor, this vibrant city of 7.3 million can
be as intimidating as King Kong on a rampage down Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder orchestrating a family getaway can be a daunting
prospect.
</P>
<P>
   There's so much to see and do in Manhattan, vacationers find it
hard to know where to start. Just deciding how to budget time can
be overwhelming. Is half a day long enough to spend at the American
Museum of Natural History? Can you squeeze the Empire State
Building, the Statue of Liberty and Ellis Island into one day?
Should you buy theater tickets before you leave home or spend an
hour or more standing in line for half-price seats?
</P>
<P>
   With hundreds of hotels in Manhattan (59,000 rooms, if you're
counting), picking the right place to stay can be mind-boggling.
How do you begin to sort the deals from the dumps? Will that
``bargain'' room going for $150 turn out to be a broom closet?
</P>
<P>
   But if you decide to make the trip _ as my family did this
spring _ you'll join the more than 34 million tourists who'll visit
this year. And with savvy planning, you can make the most of your
visit and render the city less forbidding.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, the newly polished Big Apple has never been more
alluring _ or more family-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   Times Square, the famous 30-square-block neighborhood in
Midtown, has been stripped of sleaze and transformed into a
wonderland wrapped in 40 miles of neon and flashing lights with
more than 50 mammoth advertising billboards. A Virgin Megastore and
huge Disney and Warner Bros. stores share the turf with new or
renovated hotels, hundreds of restaurants, Broadway theaters, movie
theaters, those ubiquitous camera and electronics shops, cheesy
souvenir dens and the recently opened Times Square Visitors Center.
Red-uniformed custodians keep the streets and sidewalks swept clean
as a theme park.
</P>
<P>
   Not far away at 42nd Street and Park Avenue is the grandly
refurbished Grand Central Station. The amazing $196 million cleanup
of the once grimy rail station includes rows of chic boutiques and
Michael Jordan's The Steakhouse. Scrubbing of the ceiling, which
was covered in oily gunk, revealed a wondrous celestial scene.
</P>
<P>
   The revitalized city fairly gleams.
</P>
<P>
   Even the criminal element seems to be getting with the program.
The New York Convention and Visitors Bureau boasts that New York's
crime is lowest among cities with populations of 1 million or more.
FBI statistics showed crime down by 11 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, no urban area is ever without danger _ and you'd be
well-advised to hang on tightly to your totes. But don't miss out
on a family vacation to one of the world's most exciting cities
because of safety concerns.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
