<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4729 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUCLEAR-WASTE-BOS &LR;      05-20 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUCLEAR-WASTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IDEA TO SHIP NUCLEAR WASTE OVERSEAS IRKS ACTIVISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frustrated at the glacial pace of federal efforts to open a
nuclear waste disposal site, the owners of three closed New England
nuclear plants quietly discussed shipping their high-level
radioactive waste to Britain, raising alarms among British
anti-nuclear groups when the talks were disclosed this week.
</P>
<P>
   The owners of Yankee Rowe nuclear plant in Massachusetts as well
as two other reactors say the talks last year with British Nuclear
Fuels Ltd. went nowhere. Under the plan, they would have shipped
thousands of lethally hot used fuel rods to Sellafield, England,
for storage or reprocessing into new fuel rather than waiting for a
federal waste site to open in 2010 at the soonest.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have been trying to do is turn over every stone so we
don't miss an opportunity and we can finish the job,'' said Kelley
Smith, spokeswoman for Yankee Rowe and Connecticut Yankee nuclear
plants, neither of which can completely shut down until their used
fuel rods are removed from the sites.
</P>
<P>
   However, disclosure of the waste talks sparked angry accusations
on both sides of the Atlantic over one of the world's true
political hot potatoes. Activists were particularly distressed that
the British firm insisted on secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Secrett, director of Friends of the Earth, which
released documents outlining the talks, said that British Prime
Minister Tony Blair ``must act now to stop British Nuclear Fuels
Ltd. from turning Britain into a nuclear waste dump for other
countries. The BNFL senior management who set up the deal should
resign at once, or be fired.''
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, activist Ray Shadis accused Maine Yankee
nuclear plant officials of withholding information and undermining
efforts to close down the plant safely.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Maine Yankee Atomic Power Company is trying to earn the
public trust, they have a damnably poor way of going about it,''
said Shadis, who had not heard of the talks even though he is a
member of the community advisory panel assisting Maine Yankee in
shutdown procedures.
</P>
<P>
   But officials at the closed nuclear plants said they can't
understand the fuss. After decades of failed federal efforts to
build a waste repository, they say they have considered a wide
array of ideas _ such as shipping the waste to Apache land in New
Mexico _ most of which fizzle out quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't possibly be held to a standard of communicating every
idea,'' said Mary Ann Lynch, vice president for law and government
affairs at Maine Yankee. ``For every 10 ideas that we have on
decommissioning, nine of them end up in the great heap of''
failures.
</P>
<P>
   High-level radioactive waste, which remains dangerous for
millennia, has long been the Achilles' heel of nuclear power. Under
federal law, the US Department of Energy is responsible for finding
a permanent repository, but possible sites _ from the Kansas salt
domes to the wilds of eastern Maine _ have flopped in the face of
intense opposition.
</P>
<P>
   For the past decade, the agency has been trying to develop a
waste site at the Nevada Missile Test Site, but environmental
reviews and political battles have pushed the opening date back to
2010, and many observers say 2015 is more realistic.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the long-simmering issue is coming to a head in New
England, where four of the nine nuclear reactors are closing down.
Officials at Yankee Rowe, which closed in 1991, want to begin
tearing down the buildings, which would put them on a course to
complete decommissioning within a few years _ except for the 533
fuel rods still in the waste pool.
</P>
<P>
   The utilities that own the reactors already have sued the
Department of Energy for the cost of storing the waste, and found a
federal claims court that agrees the department should pay. Maine
Yankee alone wants $130 million, including $60 million to build
concrete and steel casks to hold the waste until the Yucca Mountain
facility opens.
</P>
<P>
   Against that backdrop, Smith said officials from Connecticut
Yankee and Yankee Rowe approached British Nuclear Fuels more than a
year ago about the possibility of shipping their waste to the
Sellafield reprocessing facility. Separately, Maine Yankee
officials made a similar inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said officials at the plants advanced the idea of
exporting the waste to Britain as part of an invitation from the
Department of Energy to offer new ideas for solving the problem.
Ultimately, she said, the federal agency shot down the idea before
formal negotiations could begin.
</P>
<P>
   At Maine Yankee, the British firm went so far as to draft a
paper titled ``Transport of Spent Nuclear Fuel from Maine Yankee
Power Plant: Conceptual Arrangements,'' which laid out a plan for
hauling up to 1,432 used fuel rods from Maine to England, according
to documents from Friends of the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   However, Lynch of Maine Yankee said the plant never received a
formal proposal from British Nuclear Fuels. ``It never got beyond
the most preliminary stages,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Department officials say they were not part of the waste
export talks, but said they warned US utilities that any nuclear
waste exports would have to satisfy federal concerns about nuclear
weapons proliferation. The reprocessing plant at Sellafield
generates plutonium from nuclear waste, a key ingredient in atomic
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But activists say British Nuclear Fuel hoped to get around the
proliferation issue by portraying the deal to the US government as
a storage plan. In Britain, where long-term storage of foreign
nuclear waste is illegal, they would have emphasized the
reprocessing of the waste, activists say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to separate out how much of this is real and how
much of this is the desperate acts of desperate people,'' said
Jonathan Block, attorney for the New England Coalition on Nuclear
Pollution, which is challenging Yankee Rowe's cleanup plans. ``Once
again, we are confronted with what a stupid way nuclear power is to
boil water for your coffee.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
