<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Broadway: Show kids theater at its glitzy best
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May23.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the best things about New York is Broadway theater _ and
a good meal before or after the show. Currently, there are lots of
good musicals that Broadway babies and their families can enjoy
together. Take a look at some options.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE GREAT WHITE WAY:
</P>
<P>
   A KID'S-EYE VIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids Eat Broadway'' (Kids Eat Publishing, $12.95;
212-929-0734) arrives in bookstores just in time to help you plan
your summer vacation in the Big Apple.
</P>
<P>
   Written by 12-year-old Sam Freund and his mother, Elizabeth
Carpenter _ they also wrote ``Kids Eat New York'' _ the book
includes reviews of 25 family shows on Broadway and off-Broadway
plus 50 kid-friendly restaurants. The original ``Annie,'' Andrea
McArdle, who's now appearing in ``Beauty and the Beast,'' wrote the
introduction.
</P>
<P>
   We like ``Kids Eat Broadway's'' comments on each show's
age-appropriateness and appeal for various age groups (infant to 4
years, 4-7 years, 8-12 years and teenagers). For instance, it
recommends the fairy tale ``Peter Pan'' as one of the few shows
suitable for children under 4. ``It is beautiful, filled with song,
and fast-paced,'' the authors write. ``Little children will not
lose interest. However, parents should immediately take their child
out of the theater if they start to cry.''
</P>
<P>
   I was happy to see that Sam and his mom loved ``Annie Get Your
Gun'' and ``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown'' _ both
Tony-nominated revivals _ as much as we did.
</P>
<P>
   Here are excerpts from three of their reviews:
</P>
<P>
   On ``Annie'': ``Everything about `Annie' hits the bullseye. It
is a light-hearted `aw shucks' kinda show, filled with gags,
hillbilly dialogue and terrific, upbeat songs like `Doin' What
Comes Natur'lly' and `Anything You Can Do.' There is nothing
unsuitable for children.''
</P>
<P>
   On ``Charlie Brown'': ``All the scenery and props looked like
they were big comic strip drawings with heavy black outlines filled
in with bright colors. ... Clearly everyone in the cast was having
a good time, and so was the audience. Without resorting to childish
cliches, the actors convincingly deliver the personalities of their
overdrawn characters. The result: A charming show that is the
perfect family entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter Pan'': ``The Neverland of this show is as magical as can
be. The kids in the audience go right along with Peter, Wendy and
the boys on their adventures. ... All the way to the very end, when
Peter makes his dramatic flight out over the audience, this is the
show where there are happy endings, even if the kids do grow up.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  GOOD EATS
</P>
<P>
   Wondering where to chow down in the theater district? Chew on
this baker's dozen recommended byFreund:
</P>
<P>
   1. B. Frites (Belgian-style French fries with sauces), 1657
Broadway, 212-767-0858.
</P>
<P>
   2. Broadway Grill (Italian-American), 1605 Broadway (in lobby of
Crowne Plaza Hotel), 212-315-6161.
</P>
<P>
   3. Cafe Un Deux Trois (French brasserie), 123 W. 44th St.,
212-354-4148.
</P>
<P>
   4. Carmine's (family-style Italian), 200 W. 44th St.,
212-221-3800.
</P>
<P>
   5. Dish of Salt (Cantonese), 133 W. 47th St., 212-921-4242.
</P>
<P>
   6. Ellen's Stardust Diner, 1650 Broadway, 212-956-5151.
</P>
<P>
   7. John's Brick Oven Pizza, 260 W. 44th St., 212-391-7560.
</P>
<P>
   8. Manhattan Chili Co., 1500 Broadway and 1697 Broadway,
212-730-8666.
</P>
<P>
   9. Marlowe (contemporary American), 328 W. 46th St.,
212-765-3815.
</P>
<P>
   10. Stage Deli, 834 7th Ave., 212-245-7850.
</P>
<P>
   11. Tennessee Mountain (barbecue), 121 W. 45th St.,
212-869-4545.
</P>
<P>
   12. West Bank Cafe (American), 407 W. 42nd St., 212-695-6909.
</P>
<P>
   13. Westway Diner, 614 9th Ave., 212-582-7661.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  JUST THE TICKET
</P>
<P>
   These current Broadway shows are particularly well-suited for
children. A good source for information about these shows is the
Family Theater Guide by George A. Wachtel on the Internet at
nyctourist.com/bwaymenu.htm. Wachtel is president of Audience
Research &AMP; Analysis, a market research firm in New York. He has
been taking his 11-year-old daughter, Amanda, to Broadway shows
since she was 2 1/2. The age recommendations in the following list
are by Wachtel.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets are sold through Tele-charge (212-239-6200) or
Ticketmaster (212-307-4100). Most shows have a top price of $75.
</P>
<P>
   ``Annie Get Your Gun,'' Marquis, 1535 Broadway (at 45th Street).
Ticketmaster. 8 and up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beauty and the Beast,'' Palace, 1564 Broadway (at 47th
Street). Ticketmaster. 6 and up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cats,'' Winter Garden, Broadway and 50th Street. Tele-charge.
5 and up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Civil War,'' St. James, 246 W. 44th St. Tele-charge. 12
and up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Footloose,'' Richard Rodgers, 226 W. 46th St. Ticketmaster. 10
and up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fosse,'' Broadhurst, 235 W. 44th St. Tele-charge. 12 and up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jekyll &AMP; Hyde,'' Plymouth, 236 W. 45th St. Tele-charge. 13 and
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Les Miserables,'' Imperial, 249 W. 45th St. Tele-charge. 8 and
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lion King,'' New Amsterdam, 214 W. 42nd St. Ticketmaster.
6 and up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ragtime,'' Ford Center for the Performing Arts, 215 W. 43rd
St. Ticketmaster. 10 and up.
</P>
