<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NYC offers banquet of summertime pleasures
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 23.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York calls itself ``the best restaurant city in the world.''
That may be a matter of opinion, but certainly the numbers are in
its favor: There are 18,000-plus restaurants in the city's five
boroughs, which boast about 144 ethnic communities.
</P>
<P>
   On June 18, 200 restaurants from Manhattan to Queens will take
part in New York Restaurant Day, a whirlwind tasting event.
Participating eateries will sell samples of their signature menu
items (for $3-$5 at lunch) outside their entrances. At least a
dollar from each serving sold goes to hunger-relief organizations
Citymeals-on-Wheels and Share Our Strength.
</P>
<P>
   Then, during Restaurant Week (June 21-25), more than 100 of New
York's finest restaurants will offer a three-course lunch for
$19.99 (exclusive of beverage, tax and gratuity). A list of
participating restaurants will be posted on the Web site www
</P>
<P>
   .restaurantweek.com on Monday; make your reservations anytime
thereafter. Information: 1-800-692-8474.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Alley ``Cats'' (and more): The Broadway theater season ends
with the 13th annual ``Stars in the Alley'' in Shubert Alley (west
of Broadway between 44th and 45th streets). The free event,
produced by the League of American Theatres and Producers, features
music and dance numbers performed by more than 60 cast members from
Broadway's most popular musicals. Showtime is 11:30 a.m.-12:30 p.m.
June 2. It's the highlight of Theatre Week, which culminates June 6
with the 53rd annual Tony Awards. For information on ``Stars'' and
other Broadway events, call the Broadway Line at 1-888-276-2392.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Taking the Fifth: It's one of the world's most famous
thoroughfares _ home to the Empire State Building (34th Street),
Rockefeller Center (47th Street), St. Patrick's Cathedral (50th
Street), the Trump Tower (56th Street) and the Plaza Hotel (59th
Street). An estimated 100,000 people converge on Fifth Avenue each
day.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some quick facts (courtesy of Elizabeth Arden Red Door
Salon and Spa, another Fifth Avenue fixture): It's the site of more
parades than any other avenue in the world. The world's highest
rents are on Fifth Avenue between 50th and 58th streets. More
diamonds are purchased on Diamond Row (Fifth Avenue and 47th
Street) than anywhere else in the world. And it is the inspiration
for a fragrance that's a Top 10 best seller in Tokyo, Paris, London
and Milan _ Elizabeth Arden's 5th Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Supermodel Amber Valletta, the ``face'' of Elizabeth Arden,
offers these Fifth Avenue favorites: the Egyptian Gallery at the
Metropolitan Museum, a walk in Central Park from the museum to the
reservoir (or east to west, from Strawberry Fields to the
boathouse), the view from atop the Empire State Building and
sampling some of the 100 varieties of tea at Takashimya ``Tea
Box.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Garden variety: The New York Botanical Garden's Summer Garden
Getaway brings the world to the Bronx on July 1-Sept. 26. Colorful
model trains take a tour across the country in the
6,000-square-foot outdoor show ``America's Trains and Trees.'' For
a taste of the tropics, head to the Exotic Courtyard Garden at the
pools of the Enid A. Haupt Conservatory. It's a summer of discovery
at the Everett Children's Adventure Garden, where families can see
``Big Bugs'' (dino-sized insects), giant flowers and three mazes
and enjoy lots of hands-on activities. Information: 718-817-8700 or
www.nybg.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Have a ball: The Salisbury Hotel on 57th Street is offering a
``Summer Sports Package for Two.'' For $475 plus tax, you get two
nights' accommodations, continental breakfast for two each day, two
field-level box seats for a New York Mets baseball game at Shea
Stadium and two $25 gift certificates for lunch or dinner at the
Official All Star Cafe in Times Square (along with VIP pass to
bypass the waiting line). The Salisbury has special room rates June
28-Sept. 15: $189 single or double, $209 one-bedroom suites.
Reservations: 1-888-692-5757.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Live it up: Five members of the Leading Hotels of the World in
New York City have joined forces for ``Leading Offers . . . The
Manhattan Summer Sale.'' From June 18 through Sept. 18, travelers
to the Big Apple can enjoy world-class luxury accommodations and
added-value amenities at reduced rates. Participating hotels and
starting nightly rates: the Mark ($299), Hotel Plaza Athenee
($285), the Peninsula New York ($350), the New York Palace ($245)
and the Waldorf Towers ($389). Rates are based on availability and
taxes are not included. Reservations: 1-800-223-6800.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Scents and sensibility: Don't turn up your nose at this
gimmick to rejuvenate jet-lagged and stressed-out travelers. Guests
of the Fitzpatrick Grand Central Hotel, an Irish luxury boutique
hotel in New York, can order the travel-size ``scent-sational''
Aromatherapy Rebalancing Kit for $25 plus tax. Included are Davies
Gate aromatherapy products including Sevilla Body Oil, Sage
Mosturizing Body Mist and a Mixed Herb Bath Salts Sampler.
</P>
<P>
   Reservations and information: 212-351-6800.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
