r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-NYCGUIDE2NTAKE     05-20 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NYCGUIDE2NTAKE23-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   New York City: at most hotels. 1-800-876-9868
</P>
<P>
   MONEY SAVERS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  CityPass: If saving 50 percent off the combined admission
prices at six of Manhattan's top sights is appealing, purchase this
pass. Included are the American Museum of Natural History, Empire
State Building Observatories, Intrepid AirSeaSpace Museum,
Metropolitan Museum of Art, Museum of Modern Art and Top of the
World Trade Center. The pass is good for nine days from the first
use. The cost is $26.75 for adults, $18 for seniors 65 and older,
$21 for ages 13-18.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  MetroCard: NYC Transit offers a one-day card good for
unlimited rides and free transfers on subways and local buses. Buy
one for $4 at subway token booths, newsstands, banks and many other
businesses throughout the city. 212-638-7622.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  TKTS booth: Seems like there's always a line _ actually two
lines _ snaking up the sidewalks between Seventh Avenue and
Broadway at 47th Street. What's everybody waiting for? The chance
to buy discounted day-of-performance tickets for selected Broadway
and off-Broadway productions (available shows are posted each day).
We got great seats for ``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown'' less
than 30 minutes before the 1 p.m. Sunday matinee and we paid $37.50
each for the tickets, half the regular price. We spent a little
more than an hour in line. The booth is open 3-8 p.m.
Mondays-Saturdays, noon-8 p.m. Sundays and 10 a.m.-2 p.m. Saturdays
and Wednesdays. Lines form an hour before opening. There is a
second TKTS booth at the World Trade Center, mezzanine level, 2
World Trade Center, open 11 a.m.-5:30 p.m. weekdays, 11 a.m.-3:30
p.m. Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Freebies: There are lots of things you can do in New York that
don't cost a cent. The Staten Island Ferry used to be a bargain at
50 cents; now it's free. (We were serenaded by a duo that set up a
keyboard and speakers and crooned songs such as ``My Cherie Amour''
to the crowd for tips.) It also costs nothintch the ongoing
diversions at F.A.O. Schwartz on Fifth Avenue _ puppeteers,
storytellers, magicians, etc. _ and play with toys displayed for
hands-on interaction. (But take the kids at your own risk: You'll
be lucky to get out without spending.)
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy the green expanses of Central Park _ which stretches from
59th to 110th streets between Fifth Avenue and Central Park West _
and stop to watch ducks on a pond or lake, roll down grassy slopes,
climb on rock outcroppings, visit the zoo and watch skaters (ice in
winter, roller in summer) at Wollman Rink (if you want to skate, it
costs $7 adults, $3.50 for children under 12 for a whole day).
</P>
<P>
   Check newspapers, magazines and city guides for freebies. For
instance, if you're in New York on June 8, you can join the 21st
annual Museum Mile Festival. From 6 to 9 p.m., there's no charge to
visit nine cultural institutions _ including the Metropolitan
Museum, the Jewish Museum and the Guggenheim Museum _ along Fifth
Avenue from 82nd to 104th street. Look for free concerts in Central
and Battery parks.
</P>
<P>
   MORE THAN A MEAL
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Theme restaurants: At these dining spots, eating is almost
secondary to the atmosphere. Little sluggers will love
baseball-memorabilia-filled Mickey Mantle's at Central Park South.
Sci-fi buffs will be right at home in the alien ambience of MARS
2112 at Broadway and 51st Street. Motorcycle mamas and their
offspring should roar into the Harley-Davidson Cafe at Sixth Avenue
and 56th Street. Scary props are just part of the fun at the
faux-macabre Jekyll &AMP; Hyde on Sixth Avenue between 57th and 58th
streets. Even though Atlanta has all three, kids may want to see
New York's versions of the All-Star Cafe, Hard Rock Cafe and Planet
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   THE REST OF THE STORY
</P>
<P>
   New York may be the city that never sleeps, but you will
definitely want to after a long day of sightseeing. We booked the
425-room Hotel Warwick, just outside the Times Square area at 54th
Street and 6th Avenue, through Hotel Reservations Network
(1-800-964-6835 or www.180096hotel.com). For $225 a night
(discounted from the usual $295-$340 for a double room), we got a
large room with two double beds, roomy marble bathroom and mini-bar
(declared off-limits after my daughter snagged a small bag of
Famous Amos cookies for $4.50).
</P>
<P>
   Another good source for discounted hotel rooms is
www.hotres.com, which features more than 1,000 cut-rate rooms
daily.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Good value: Apple Core Hotels, a group of five recently
renovated turn-of-the-century hotels in Midtown, are
economy-priced. Children under 13 stay free with their parents, and
continental breakfast is included. For example, a room with two
double beds at the Quality Hotel &AMP; Suites Midtown, 59 W. 46th St.,
runs $179-$209; large suites are $239-$269 (1-800-567-7720 or
www.applecorehotels.com).
</P>
<P>
   Others with rates starting below $200: the 131-room Comfort Inn
Manhattan, on 35th Street near the Empire State Building
(1-800-228-5050 or www.choice-hotels.com); the 532-room Holiday Inn
Broadway, Broadway at 32nd St. (1-888-694-6543); the 1,000-room New
Yorker Hotel, 481 Eighth Ave. at 34th Street (1-800-764-4680 or
www.hotelnyr.com); and the 72-room Best Western Seaport, Peck Slip
at South Street Seaport (1-800-528-1234 or www.bestwestern.com).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In the glow of Times Square: If you are drawn to the bright
lights of Broadway, go for 460-room Doubletree Guest Suites, 1568
Broadway (1-800-243-6969); the 1,919-room Marriott Marquis, 1535
Broadway (1-800-483-6275); 770-room Crowne Plaza Manhattan, 1605
Broadway (1-800-243-6969); the 305-room Renaissance, 2 Times Square
at 47th Street (212-765-7676). Expect to pay in the high $200s or
more for a family-size room.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Suite deals: Manhattan East Hotels' ``Suite Family Values''
package, good through July at nine all-suite hotels in East Side
and Midtown neighborhoods, includes a one-bedroom suite,
complimentary Frommer's ``New York City With Kids'' and ``Kids
Cruise Free'' certificate with each paid adult on a Circle Line
Cruise. Rates begin at $220 a night (1-800-637-8483 or
www.mesuite.com). The 450-to-650-square-foot suites include
kitchens with microwaves and refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  We're in the money: The Plaza on Central Park South is where
Macauley Culkin ran up his dad's credit card in ``Home Alone II:
Lost in New York.'' You'll pay $300-plus for the privilege (768 5th
Ave., 1-800-759-3000). But the St. Regis (2 E. 55th St.), Pierre
(2. E. 61st St.), Peninsula (700 5th Ave.) and Four Seasons (57 E.
57th St.) are among the true budget-busters.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Booking a flight:
</P>
<P>
   The lowest fare is $218 round trip for nonstop flights on
AirTran and Delta to LaGuardia or on Continental to Newark, N.J.,
with a 14-day advance purchase.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Recommended reading: ``Frommer's New York City With Kids''
(Macmillan Travel, $15.95) is probably the best all-around
guidebook. ``The Really Cool Parents Guide to All of New York'' by
Alfred Gingold and Helen Rogan (City &AMP; Co., $12.95) takes readers
off the beaten track, beyond the official tourist circuit.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Visitors can call the NYCVB for literature on
events, attractions, accommodations, shopping, theater, dining and
more at 1-800-692-8474. To speak to a counselor, call 212-484-1222
(9 a.m.-5 p.m. Mondays- Fridays). Visit the Web site at
www.nycvisit.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
