<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4738 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-NYCGUIDE1STAKE     05-20 1445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NYCGUIDE1STAKE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pace yourself for big city, bright lights
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 23.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK CITY _ You'll have a much better Big Apple family
vacation if you remember this phrase: You can't do it all.
</P>
<P>
   It would take at least a week to even begin to hit all the high
spots. You certainly can't do more than get a taste in a few days.
</P>
<P>
   Try this: Write down everything you'd like to do while you're in
the city, then cut the list in half. (Then figure out how much you
think you'll spend and double the amount.)
</P>
<P>
   I can't pretend to offer an insider's look; I've visited the
city maybe half a dozen times over the past three decades, counting
a recent visit with my husband and daughter. I planned our trip for
months ahead, working out an ambitious itinerary.
</P>
<P>
   But even the best-laid plans sometimes go awry.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: Having slept in on a Saturday morning after being
out late at the theater and eating pizza at midnight, we were
determined to make up for lost time. So, in one day, we attempted
to tour the Empire State Building (where we also took in a
tummy-churning big-screen virtual-reality attraction called the New
York Skyride), have a quick soup-and-sandwich lunch at Au Bon Pain,
then make it to the ferry to cruise over to the Statue of Liberty
and Ellis Island. Scratch the last part: We arrived in Battery Park
at 3:30 p.m., after a $6 white-knuckle cab ride from Midtown, to
find that they had stopped selling tickets 15 minutes earlier. We
settled on a back-and-forth (but free!) cruise on the Staten Island
Ferry and waved wistfully to Miss Liberty as we passed by.
</P>
<P>
   Still, we managed to cram a lot into four days. And that
includes spending the better part of a day at the fascinating
American Museum of Natural History, where we also saw the IMAX
movie ``Amazon.'' We explored the origins of man, marveled at 90
million-year-old dinosaur eggs from Patagonia, made snarly faces at
a set of T-rex bones, strolled through a rain forest and ogled
gemstones and seashells. (All of which was almost as exciting for
my 11-year-old daughter as spotting spiky-haired MTV personality
Jesse Camp on a Times Square street corner.)
</P>
<P>
   We saw three Broadway musicals _ the now-closed ``Titanic,''
``Annie Get Your Gun'' and ``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown.'' On
Saturday night, we made reservations for dinner at Tavern on the
Green in Central Park, as much theatrical spectacle as dining
experience. One guidebook described it as the place New Yorkers
take their country cousins. Call us Ma and Pa Kettle _ but we were
dazzled by the tiny lights strung in the trees outside, chandeliers
dripping with crystal, over-the-top-ornate decor (mirrors, flowers,
balloons, topiary, statuary) . . . and the food wasn't bad, either.
But it's no bargain. Even the children's menu prices approach those
at a typical suburban eatery. Was it worth $150 for two adults and
a child? Look at it this way: Three theater tickets cost $225 _ and
you still have to eat.
</P>
<P>
   Just being in the Big Apple can be as exhausting as it is
invigorating. By the time we took a limo back to the airport, we
were drained _ yet filled with wonderful, only-in-New-York
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some ideas to help you get started:
</P>
<P>
   THEME OUTINGS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Big Apple A-list: If your family goes nowhere else, these
are a must for first-timers to the city: The Empire State Building,
the Statue of Liberty, American Museum of Natural History and
Central Park. Give your regards to Broadway: Splurge on at least
one show. Buy a hot dog or salty pretzel from a street vendor. Say
hello to Prometheus, that big golden statue, at Rockefeller Plaza.
Take a subway ride (a token is $1.50).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Come visit the world: Find out what's in the city's big
melting pot. Pay a visit to the United Nations (one-hour tours are
offered every 15 minutes), then explore ethnic diversity in
neighborhoods such as Chinatown and Little Italy. Sample the
cuisine of about any country you can think of _ from Chile to
Vietnam, from Hungary to Turkey, Afghanistan to Mexico. Visit Ellis
Island to see where 12 million immigrants who arrived in America
between 1892 and 1954 spent their first hours (or days, in some
cases). The Jewish Museum has a new children's exhibition,
``Pickles and Pomegranates: Jewish Homes Far and Near,'' an
interactive experience that evokes life in two late-19th-century
Jewish households: a Lower East Side tenement in 1897 and a house
of the same period in Persia (now Iran). Take a cab ride _ you
never know what nationality your driver will turn out to be.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The artsy approach: Do a museum marathon, starting with the
Metropolitan Museum of Art, whose major exhibition for the summer
is ``Cezanne to Van Gogh: The Collection of Doctor Gachet.'' Then
do the Guggenheim, the Museum of Modern Art, the Museum of American
Folk Art and/or the American Craft Museum, depending on what most
appeals to you. The current special exhibition at the Children's
Museum of Manhattan is ``Body Odyssey,'' but kids who love the Cat
in the Hat, the Grinch and Sam I Am won't want to miss the
permanent exhibit ``Seuss!''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Two if by sea: Explore New York's maritime past at South
Street Seaport, an 11-square-block historic district just south of
the Brooklyn Bridge on the East River. Take a Circle Line tour
around the island. Visit the Intrepid SeaAirSpace Museum, home of
the 900-foot-long aircraft carrier Intrepid, the guided missile
submarine Growler and the destroyer Edson. The hundreds of
interactive exhibits include dozens of vintage and modern aircraft.
It's at West 46th Street and 12th Avenue on the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  TV or not TV: Hit your kids with this bombshell: There hasn't
always been television. They can learn about the history of the
medium at the Museum of Television and Radio on 52nd Street between
Fifth and Sixth avenues. Selected shows are presented on giant
screens in four theaters, and you can spend up to two hours
watching vintage TV at one of the 96 viewing consoles. New this
spring is the NBC Experience, a high-tech attraction at NBC
headquarters at 30 Rockefeller Plaza, where you can experience what
it's like to do the weather report with Al Roker or settle into Jay
Leno's guest chair. The 20,000-square-foot facility is filled with
interactive stages, a high-definition TV theater, NBC memorabilia
and retail shops with NBC logo merchandise. You could be seen on
national TV if you show up outside the glass studio where the
``Today'' show is taped between 7 and 9 a.m. weekday mornings. NBC
studio tour tickets, which disappear quickly, go on sale at 9 a.m.
in the lobby. Getting tickets for ``The Rosie O'Donnell Show'' is
nearly impossible, but if you call 212-506-3288, you can gauge your
chances.
</P>
<P>
   TIMESAVERS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Insider's Hour tours: This is one way to squeeze in as much as
possible: More than 40 cultural institutions, including South
Street Seaport, Lincoln Center, the Metropolitan Museum of Art and
the Intrepid SeaAirSpace Museum, are offering guided, one-hour
tours highlighting their collections and facilities. For details,
including other participating institutions, visit the New York
Convention and Visitors Bureau Web site at www.nycvisit.com or send
a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: Insider's Hour, NYCVB, 810
Seventh Ave., Third Floor, NY, NY 10019.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Times Square Visitors Center: Talk about one-stop shopping.
Inside the newly renovated Embassy Theater on the east side of
Broadway at 46th Street, you can buy theater tickets, souvenirs,
international newspapers and postcards; book a Gray Line or Circle
Line tour; get cash from an ATM; make a phone call; surf the
Internet; pick up piles of brochures; and, maybe best of all, go to
the restroom. Open 8 a.m.-8 p.m. daily.
</P>
<P>
   Another must stop: the New York Convention and Visitors Bureau's
new state-of-the-art Visitor Information Center at 810 Seventh Ave.
(at 53rd Street).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Double-decker bus tours: The unlimited ``hop-on and hop-off''
privileges make these tours, offered by several lines, a good way
to get to all the major attractions for one price. We like the big
red double-decker buses of New York Apple Tours that take riders
from Harlem to the Statue of Liberty to Brooklyn. With one ticket
($39, $22 children under 12), you can get on and off at 65
attractions over two days and take a night tour. Buy tickets at the
Visitor Information Center at Eighth Avenue and 53rd Street or at
most hotels. 1-800-876-9868.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
