u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENTERTAINMENT-NYT-BUD     05-20 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENTERTAINMENT-NYT-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Weekend Section stories from The New York Times News Service for
Friday, May 21.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH-AMERICA (Undated) _ Much has been made of the fact that
British culture has of late been flooding these shores with almost
colonial aplomb. Just look at Broadway and British film. Paranoia
sets in quickly: everywhere one looks there are Young British
Artists or old British television programs or new British plays.
But despite all the hemming and hawing about the Anglofication of
American life, very few cultural connoisseurs have bothered trying
out all these dandy English imports. I, on the other hand, did. My
mission was simple: to immerse myself during a mere 48 hours in all
things British, from food and drink (with an emphasis,
understandably, on the latter) to sports and sounds to theater and
art. It would take Bondian endurance (as in Bondian, James
Bondian), but I felt up to snuff. By Jesse McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   APPLES-VIRGINIA (Norfolk, Va.) _ Hampton Roads, the natural
harbor where the James River and several lesser streams meet
Chesapeake Bay, has had a balcony seat for history. Hampton Roads _
composed, for our purposes, of the cities of Norfolk, Portsmouth,
Virginia Beach, Hampton and Newport News, plus the towns of
Jamestown, Yorktown and Williamsburg _ has long since overtaken
Richmond as a metropolitan area. Its population now exceeds 1.5
million, roughly a quarter of the state's total, and Virginia
Beach, of all unlikely places, is the Old Dominion's largest city,
with 393,000 people. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
