<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE BIOTECH: SCIENCE, MONEY, RISK
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
special package of stories on the growing biotechnology industry in
Seattle for clients of the NYTimes News Service today for immediate
or for weekend use. All stories will move in the ``a'' category. If
you have any questions, please call Veronica Villarreal at (206)
448-8342.
</P>
<P>
   BIOTECH-EVOLUION (Seatte) _ A child born today stands a good
chance of living into the 22nd century. As futuristic as it sounds,
it's a reality. And it's owed, in part, to a revolution in medical
drug discovery that has taken place over the plast 20 years. That
revolution hasn't happened in big pharmaceutical companies. It has
taken a new type of organization _ one that combines academic
curiosity with entrepreneurial drive, creative thinking and quick
reaction times to make it happen. And it's given rise to a whole
new business sector: The biotechnology industry. MAIN BAR.
</P>
<P>
   By Carol Smith.
</P>
<P>
   BIOTECH-HISTORY (Seattle) - First came two crucial scientific
advances in the 1970s. Then came the 1980s bull market. Those were
the ingredients that fueld the biotech revolution, and the rest is
history. 9 inches.
</P>
<P>
   By Carol Smith.
</P>
<P>
   BIOTECH-SCIENTIST (Seattle) _ Steven Gillis is the man behind
two of the more successful biotech companies in seattle, first
Immunex, one of the first biotech companies, now Corixa. 15 inches.
</P>
<P>
   By Carol Smith.
</P>
<P>
   BIOTECH-PATIENT (Seattle) _ Several biotech companies, including
Immunex Corp. in Seattle, and Cypress Bioscience Inc., have
developed novel new approaches to treat rheumatoid arthritis, which
affects about 2.5 million in the United States and can be a
crippling, even fatal, disease. Their approaches to treat the
disease are based on a new understanding of how the body turns on
its own tissues. For Lisa Caswell, whose rheumatoid arthritis was
particularly aggressive, participating in clinical trials to test
some of these new arthritis therapies has made a huge difference in
her quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   By Carol Smith.
</P>
<P>
   BIOTECH-GLOSSARY (Undated) _ Short glossary of terms used in the
biotech industry.
</P>
<P>
   BIOTECH-BIOINFORMATICS (Seattle) Seattle scientists are aiming
to grab the reins of one of the hottest bandwagons in biotechnology
and medicine _ bioinformatics. Think of a marriage of biology and
computers. That's bioinformatics.
</P>
<P>
   By Tom Paulson.
</P>
<P>
   BIOTECH-GENOME (Seattle) _ Behind the hoopla about genes,
biotechnology and the coming revolution in medicine, is a
labor-intensive, massive and contentious scientific effort that is
building the foundation for all the hopes and promises. It's called
the Human Genome Project. And the goal is to identify the 100,000
or so genes that reside somewhere within the 3 billion ``letters''
of DNA in the human body _ the genome.
</P>
<P>
   Story by Tom Paulson.
</P>
<P>
   BIOTECH-COSTS (Seattle) _ The next 50 years of biomedical
research will bring unprecedented advances in curing diseases as
well as increasing social questions about ethics and costs, a panel
of biotech experts said this at the opening of BIO '99, the annual
meeting of the internation- al Biotechnology Industry Organization.
This year's meeting was held in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   By Carol Smith.
</P>
<P>
   BIOTECH-ACADEMIA (Seattle) _ Biotechnology is fueling
academic-industrial partnerships like never before. The strong need
for cutting-edge basic science in this industry has made for
intimate partnerships with academia. It's a transformation that has
some people worried.
</P>
<P>
   By Tom Paulson.
</P>
</TEXT>
