<HEADER>
A4812 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-SETTLERS-0521-     05-20 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SETTLERS-0521-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SETTLERS SIZE UP ELECTION LOSSES, WHILE LEFT-WINGERS ENVISION
PEACE
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHILO, West Bank _ Shmuel Kohen's life might not be as secure as
it seems.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon, the Israeli settler was in his hilltop
mobile home looking out over olive orchards and a nearby Arab
village. Across the street, Israeli soldiers, who protect the five
families here -- including Kohen's -- were grilling hot dogs.
</P>
<P>
   For a year, Kohen has made his home in this little group of
trailers a short drive from the established settlement of Shilo, in
territory that Israel captured in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   He is claiming biblical land in preparation for the messiah and
acting as a human buffer between Israel, and the Arabs he believes
would destroy it.
</P>
<P>
   But earlier this week, in urban Jerusalem just an hour's drive
away, the political leaders of the settler movement were reeling
from wounds inflicted by the very Jews Kohen claims to protect.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was soundly thrashed in
Monday's election by challenger Ehud Barak. It was Netanyahu who
encouraged people like Kohen to stake claims to new hilltops before
they might be handed over to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am with the right and we failed,'' says the affable,
28-year-old Kohen, relaxed in his yamulka, side curls and T-shirt.
``It was a big failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the ``failure,'' settler power was growing.
</P>
<P>
   Known for their harsh rhetoric and opposition to peace with the
Arabs, the settlers seemed invulnerable to cries from U.S.
officials and left-wing Israelis that their expansions were
destroying Arab trust in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Their population has been growing by several thousand a year.
Now, there are about 150 settlements in Israel's West Bank and Gaza
with more than 171,000 Jewish occupants. They live in gated
communities similar to those in the suburbs of major U.S. cities,
spread among the 2.5 million Palestinians since 1967.
</P>
<P>
   All this week, Netanyahu's loss reverberated among the settlers
and their allies.
</P>
<P>
   Benny Begin, extreme right-wing leader who opposed any land
handovers, resigned from the parliament. He said he felt like a
``public representative without a public.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinhas Wallerstein gave up his job as the settler movement
leader, admitting that the election-night disaster was partly a
result of the settlers' own designs.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, confident they could control the Israeli political
agenda, settler leaders helped topple Netanyahu's government to
punish him for signing the Wye River Memorandum. The Wye accord
continues the Oslo peace process, in which occupied territory in
the West Bank is being handed over to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   However, any hope that Netanyahu would win the election and come
back reborn to his right-wing ways was dashed when he was
humiliated by Barak, a moderate who pledges to restart the peace
process. Instead, Netanyahu's loss and the domino effect among
settler allies has one expert predicting better chances for a final
compromise with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will make it easier, definitely,'' said political scientist
Shmuel Sandler, of Bar-Ilan University. ``Israelis are thinking
about the state, not just some dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak is a former general who pledges to be tough on security.
His stand on the settlements is vague. He has pledged to let most
settlers stay in place and said he shares their religious
commitment to the biblical land.
</P>
<P>
   On his hill in the West Bank, Kohen takes Barak at his word.
But, settler leaders are typically coarse in their warnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have hidden what their actual plans are,'' Yehudit Tayar,
spokeswoman for the settlers association, Yesha, says of Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Even amid the prevailing news images of mass graves in Kosovo,
Tayar defended pre-election accusations that Barak intends to
``ethnically cleanse Jews'' from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Tayar said the settlers will keep expanding with or without his
support.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue is that we're in a struggle for our lives
now,'' she said. ``Anything we can implement now is going to
protect these areas.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Those efforts would continue what Peace Now, Israel's largest
peace advocacy group, and U.S. diplomats see as a dangerous trend.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Wye accord, according to Peace Now, at least 20 new
communities have been started on new hilltops. They usually start
with mobile homes, then get water towers, fences and synagogues.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli papers have reported that even when the Israeli army,
which controls the area, intended to remove such new settlements,
Netanyahu intervened to stop them. Many thought it was his way of
trying to calm the angry settler movement.
</P>
<P>
   The building of the so-called ``pirate settlements'' goes on
despite that, according to Peace Now, more than 3,700 existing
settlement homes are still vacant.
</P>
<P>
   Peace Now's Didi Remez said Barak must at least enforce the law,
allowing the army to remove settlements that are built without
approval. That, he said, is one of the messages of the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The settlements rank very low on the majority of Israelis'
list of priorities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
