<HEADER>
A4815 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CLEOPATRA-TEX     05-20 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CLEOPATRA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CLEOPATRA' FAILS TO CAPTURE THE COMPLEXITIES OF THE QUEEN OF
EGYPT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the more glaring failings of arts criticism is the news
media's follow-the-leader weakness in covering singular
entertainment projects as ``events.'' Take ``Star Wars.'' Its
overblown hype made the actual movie utterly irrelevant, nothing
more than the final hit of a grand marketing sting.
</P>
<P>
   That said, ``Cleopatra,'' the much-hyped, highly bankrolled
miniseries airing Sunday and Monday on ABC, doesn't deserve the
prized space it occupies in this newspaper. But here it is, front
and center, big and bold.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the shame of it. Because in four hours and at a cost
of more than $30 million, ``Cleopatra'' manages to titillate
viewers but hardly illuminate the portrait of the queen of Egypt,
whose life story is complex, fascinating and deserving of a more
definitive, respectful telling.
</P>
<P>
   I've read where director Franc Roddam (''Moby Dick'') has
assured us that this latest version of ``Cleopatra'' does what a
half-dozen others haven't: paint the queen as ``a more fully
realized woman and leader, a person who effectively uses her power
to better the individual and collective health and welfare of her
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that part was cut out of the review tape mailed to this
office.
</P>
<P>
   Newcomer Leonor Varela plays Cleopatra as an irresistibly
gorgeous, power-hungry vixen, as did ABC with those endless
promotional teasers showing a naked Varela sprawled across a bed, a
sheet covering her unmentionables just so.
</P>
<P>
   History buffs know that Cleopatra lacked such drop-dead beauty.
It was Shakespeare's writings that shaped her looks for the better.
Cleopatra was known for her intelligence (she was, after all, an
accomplished mathematician), charm, wit, and certainly ambition.
</P>
<P>
   Hers is an interesting life because she was the last ruler in
the dynasty founded by Ptolemy I in 323 B.C. (Ptolemy was a general
in the army of the Macedonian conqueror Alexander the Great.)
</P>
<P>
   She became queen after the death of her father _ and there's a
question of whether she had him done in. Her 12-year-old brother,
Ptolemy XIII, became her co-ruler and husband, and this is where
``Cleopatra'' jump-starts. Sort of.
</P>
<P>
   We see Rome's Julius Caesar (Timothy Dalton) being seduced by
Cleopatra and later encouraged to bring her back to power, knocking
her brother and sister to the curb. He does, but only after the
couple takes a few dips under the sheets. What Caesar didn't know
is that Cleopatra had hired an Egyptian prostitute to teach her not
only the fine art of lovemaking but also to give her a crash course
on the B.C. version of ``The Rules'' in catching powerful studs
with visions of world domination.
</P>
<P>
   ``To hold (Ra man's) interest,'' Cleopatra is told by the
prostitute, ``you must always make him believe, no matter how much
you've given him, there's still much to conquer.''
</P>
<P>
   With Caesar smitten (he's in bed, sleeping off the night
before), Cleopatra has her jailed sister killed. Her brother is
knocked off, too.
</P>
<P>
   From there, ``Cleopatra'' delivers on its teaser promises:
jealousy, rage, back-stabbing, blood, death, battles, scheming,
sex.
</P>
<P>
   Jeez. It's ``Melrose Place Goes to Rome.''
</P>
<P>
   Roddam directs ``Cleopatra'' from a script by Stephen Harrigan
and Anton Diether, and the vast overhead shots showing the hundreds
of extras _ from horses to Roman warriors _ can be breathless. At
least they pinpoint where the money was spent and establish that
this at least wants to ``look'' like an above-average TV movie.
</P>
<P>
   As for the key performances, Dalton does his usual dance with
the prose, delivering every line as though it's a dying scene.
Varela, who was born in Chile and spent much of her childhood in
Colorado, makes for an exotic Cleopatra. But her performance trails
off when she's asked to do more than purr.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she comes off as more of a spoiled brat than the great
stateswoman depicted in Margaret George's ``The Memoirs of
Cleopatra,'' on which the movie is based. If you get this far,
watch her pout over spending too little time with Caesar, who has
his mind on other things, like conquering every living being.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Zane has the showiest performance as the committed Marc
Antony, who has been maligned in history as a strong ruler who
turned into Cleopatra's helpless puppet.
</P>
<P>
   Several historical truths are skipped for the sake of moving the
story line along. Cleopatra gave birth to twins with Marc Antony.
He left her to marry the sister of his co-ruler, Octavian, for
political reasons. He returned years later and married Cleopatra.
They had another son. In ``Cleopatra,'' Marc Antony and Cleopatra
die as lovers and failed rulers, but nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the killing, there are no emotional beats in
``Cleopatra,'' nothing that stays with you for the long haul. What
producers Robert Halmi Sr. and Robert Halmi Jr. have done is make a
lavish production with no center.
</P>
<P>
   Which isn't surprising. Because of Cleopatra's historical
legacy, no one can get past the more lurid details of her life.
</P>
<P>
   But, boy, does it make for steamy promotions.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
