<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4820 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV2     05-20 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV23-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTIAL ELECTIONS SHOULD FOCUS ON LEADERSHIP, NOT POPULARITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 23)   (For Use By New York Times News Service Clients  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In its early stages the first presidential campaign
of the 21st century resembles the classic Bud Abbott-Lou Costello
``who's on first'' comedy routine that became part of American
folklore.
</P>
<P>
   Like the comedians' hilarious debate over the positioning of
baseball players, discussion of the campaign too often dwells on
how the candidates are faring in the political process rather than
on the qualifications of the two Democrats and 11 Republicans who
aspire to the office.
</P>
<P>
   In our obsession with where the candidates stand in the public
opinion polls we tend to focus on personality and popularity rather
than leadership and character. The problem is especially acute with
commercial television because the nightly news is far more inclined
to spotlight the latest poll results than the substantive comments
of the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Polls undoubtedly are important to candidates and their
supporters, but the individual who is elected in November 2000
faces a far greater task than worrying about polls. He or she must
lead the world's most powerful nation through perilous times.
</P>
<P>
   To the contenders, the battle for the Democratic and Republican
presidential nominations is serious business. Most have proposed
policies on public issues _ Al Gore and Lamar Alexander on
education, John McCain on Kosovo, Elizabeth Dole on gun control,
Bill Bradley on race relations, Malcolm S. ``Steve'' Forbes on tax
reduction and Social Security reform, Patrick Buchanan on a retreat
from globalism and Dan Quayle and most of the other Republicans on
family values, including efforts to ban abortion.
</P>
<P>
   But to many voters and journalists, who read great meaning into
early polling results, the campaign at this early stage is a game
of chance in which there will be winners and losers just as there
are in the Super Bowl and the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The time undoubtedly will come when all of us begin to ponder
the character, courage, talent, steadfastness and credibility of
each of the contenders. We also need to understand that a president
should be flexible enough to abandon bad policies for good.
</P>
<P>
   We still have more than a year to go before the Democrats
convene in Los Angeles and the Republicans in Philadelphia. But if
the pattern of recent years prevails, both parties will have
selected their nominees in primary elections long before convention
time.
</P>
<P>
   So far as we know, none of the contenders has indulged in the
kind of abysmal personal behavior that we associate with Bill
Clinton. Yet in some ways, Clinton has been quite successful.
Working with outgoing Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, Federal
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan and leaders of Congress, he has
presided over a phenomenally successful economy. Using his veto or
threat of veto, he has kept spending in line, while joining the
Republican Congress in approving welfare reform and other issues
popular in middle America.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he has sought protection of Social Security
and Medicare and has moved his party from the left to the center.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing what they do about Clinton's personal life, voters would
probably not reelect him. But that is an option barred by the 22nd
Amendment, which limits a president to two terms.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is possible, after the revelations about Clinton's affair
with Monica Lewinsky and months of impeachment turmoil, that voters
could favor candidates more because of their private behavior than
their public positions.
</P>
<P>
   It is normal for voters to want their president to have led an
impeccably clean life before entering the White House. But that
does not make the individual a good president.
</P>
<P>
   A president wears many hats _ commander-in-chief of the armed
forces, strategist and spokesman for America's position in the
world, leader of a political party, promulgator of domestic policy,
symbol of American democracy and presumably an image for young
people to emulate.
</P>
<P>
   In his memoirs, Harry Truman wrote: ``No one who has not had the
responsibility can really understand what it is like to be
president, not even his closest friends or members of his immediate
family. There is no end to the chain of responsibility that binds
him, and he is never allowed to forget that he is president.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the office has often been filled with men who were not up to
that responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   No one ever would have suggested that Calvin Coolidge was untrue
to his wife or that he was a poor father to his sons. He was a man
who practiced thrift and, so far as is known, led a clean life.
</P>
<P>
   But he was a weak president who spent much of his time napping,
and he refused to recognize dangers on the economic horizon.
</P>
<P>
   During Coolidge's presidency, Herbert Hoover, as commerce
secretary, was the living symbol of the prosperity created by the
free enterprise system in the 1920s and of a decent private life.
Having headed the U.S. effort to feed starving Europeans after
World War I, he was greatly admired.
</P>
<P>
   But shortly after he became president in 1929 the stock market
crashed precipitously and Hoover could not accept the fact that
government intervention was needed to the save the economy. He
served but one term.
</P>
<P>
   Woodrow Wilson offered a bit of wisdom that should be kept in
mind when we choose a new president: ``The president is at liberty,
in both law and conscience, to be as big a man as he can. His
capacity will set the limit.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what the presidency is about. That is what Washington,
Jefferson, Jackson, Lincoln, Wilson, Truman, Reagan and the two
Roosevelts were about.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
