<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREKKIE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAR FROM OTHER GALAZY, FANDOM'S FINAL FRONTIER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., Ark., Calif.)   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Philosophers, physicians, psychologists and poets have struggled
for centuries to fathom obsessive love. So it is probably hopeless
in the presence of ``Trekkies'' to do anything but sit back _
amused, bemused and astonished _ and watch the devotions of fans of
the various incarnations of ``Star Trek.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Trekkies,'' directed and edited by Roger Nygard, is a
disarming documentary that takes a good-natured look at the hold
that the 1966 television series and its sequels and film
incarnations exert over millions of fans. And perhaps only Diogenes
the cynic would care to note that this wide-eyed production arrives
courtesy of Paramount Pictures, home of the lucrative film
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Although historians have observed that the original ``Star
Trek,'' Gene Roddenberry's saga of the adventures of Capt. James T.
Kirk and his crew aboard the starship Enterprise among the Klingons
and Romulans and other alien life in space in the 23d century, was
less than a smashing success on NBC from 1966 to 1969, its reruns
and growing fan base turned it into a phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   And as ``Trekkies'' documents, these fans include grown-ups and
their families and cats and dogs who duly wear their Starfleet
uniforms. An Orlando, Fla., dentist and his staff carry out their
duties in uniform in an office decorated in a ``Star Trek'' theme.
</P>
<P>
   A woman chosen for the Whitewater jury wore her costume to court
in Little Rock, Ark., as she does to work. A bright 14-year-old boy
from Bakersfield, Calif., has attended at least 28 ``Star Trek''
conventions, one of the gatherings said to take place somewhere
every weekend of the year. A Sunday night radio program called
``Talk Trek and Beyond,'' out of Sunland, Calif., lays claim to 2.5
million listeners.
</P>
<P>
   People take Klingon language courses, and Klingon-language
versions of the Bible and ``Hamlet'' are said to be in preparation.
Devotees bid avidly at auctions for Klingon headpieces and other
memorabilia and souvenirs. And fans will debate the difference
between a Trekkie and a Trekker, the former said to be an earlier
designation of a fan, the latter said to connote serious fandom.
</P>
<P>
   With Denise Crosby _ Lt. Tasha Yar of television's ``Star Trek:
The Next Generation'' _ as chief guide to this alien culture,
``Trekkies'' naturally trots out many ``Star Trek'' stars.
</P>
<P>
   These include everybody from William Shatner, Leonard Nimoy,
James Doohan, DeForest Kelley, Walter Koenig, George Takei,
Nichelle Nichols and Grace Lee Whitney of the original crew to
LeVar Burton and Jonathan Frakes of ``Star Trek: The Next
Generation'' and Kate Mulgrew and Ethan Phillips of ``Star Trek:
Voyager.''
</P>
<P>
   Tales are told of depressed and suicidal fans whose lives were
saved by the concern of cast members, and lives of accomplishment
in science inspired by the television series and films, and, of
course, the careers of actors shaped ineradicably by ``Star Trek.''
</P>
<P>
   Love, your magic spell is everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   ``Trekkies'' is rated PG (Parental guidance suggested). It
includes some sexual innuendoes.
</P>
<P>
   TREKKIES
</P>
<P>
   Directed and edited by Roger Nygard; director of photography,
Harris Done; music by Walter Werzowa, Jimmie Wood, J.J. Holiday and
Billy Sullivan; produced by W.K. Border; released by Paramount
Pictures. Running time: 87 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Denise Crosby, Majel Barrett Roddenberry, James Doohan,
Walter Koenig, DeForest Kelley, Nichelle Nichols, Leonard Nimoy,
William Shatner, George Takei, Grace Lee Whitney, LeVar Burton,
Michael Dorn, Jonathan Frakes, Brent Spiner, Buzz Aldrin, Kate
Mulgrew, Ethan Phillips and others.
</P>
</TEXT>
