A4825 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPSHAW-LOVELETTER-TE     05-20 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPSHAW-LOVELETTER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LOVE LETTER' DELIVERS GENTLE ALTERNATIVE FOR MOVIE-GOERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The question is so obvious that you have to ask it, and so
obvious that you don't want to ask it. It's the question for anyone
involved in ``The Love Letter,'' the new romantic comedy opening
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you out of your mind, opening two days after `Star Wars:
Episode I _ The Phantom Menace,' perhaps the most hyped movie in
history?''
</P>
<P>
   So you don't ask. Instead, you ask Kate Capshaw, who stars in
and co-produced ``The Love Letter,'' if she's sick of hearing the
question. And, with mild surprise, you learn that the answer is no.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it was not Capshaw's idea to schedule her $8 million movie
in direct competition with a monolith. The movie studio,
DreamWorks, which was co-founded by Capshaw's husband, Steven
Spielberg, came up with the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they sat down with us to tell us that in fact it was
going to be summertime and that it would be May 21, we all felt
really, really great,'' said Capshaw, a Fort Worth native. ``And
then they said, `It's the same weekend as `Star Wars.' '' And we
all started laughing, because we thought that that was the joke,
that they were going to open this tiny $8 million movie with `Star
Wars.' And they weren't laughing, so we stopped laughing and they
said, `No, we're very serious.' And we all sat down and our hearts
were racing because, of course, this is our baby and we felt like,
`Oh my God, where's the life jacket?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Studio executives gave Capshaw and co-producers Sarah Pillsbury
and Midge Sanford time to sleep on it. ``We all called each other
from our cars,'' Capshaw continues, ``and the next morning we
called each other from breakfast and said, `You know what? What the
heck _ let's get behind this. This is interesting.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It might seem like folly, but a similar strategy worked when
``Phenomenon'' aimed its slingshot at the cinematic Goliath
``Independence Day'' in 1996. The small-scale romantic drama became
a hit even as ``Independence Day'' became a blockbuster, proving
that there was room for both at the multiplex. But, as Capshaw
points out, ``Phenomenon'' had John Travolta. ``The Love Letter''
doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   What ``Letter'' does have is Capshaw as Helen MacFarquhar, a
bookstore owner in a New England town whose life takes a turn when
she discovers an anonymous love note. Believing the letter is for
her, Helen becomes open to a fling with the much younger Johnny
(Tom Everett Scott) _ who thinks that Helen wrote the letter for
him. Helen's co-worker, played by Ellen DeGeneres, also thinks the
letter is for her, and Tom Selleck plays a shyly shambling
firefighter who doesn't know about the letter but is trying to work
up the guts to tell Helen about the torch he's carried for her
since high school.
</P>
<P>
   Capshaw was the driving force behind the movie, which is based
on Cathleen Schine's novel. The actress bought the book after
reading a positive New York Times review and decided before she
finished it that she wanted to make the movie version and be in it.
In the early stages, though, she kept Spielberg out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I moved so quickly and didn't tell my husband because I was
afraid that he would stop me,'' she says. ``You know that thing of,
you know you have to do something, so instead of telling anybody
who might talk you out of it, you just go do it? And that's how I
proceeded.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she teamed with Pillsbury and Sanford, who produced
``How to Make an American Quilt,'' an ensemble piece featuring
Capshaw. Spielberg and DreamWorks came on board late in the game,
when Spielberg became curious about what his wife was working on
and asked that his studio be given a crack at the movie. Although
producing was new to Capshaw, she had absorbed enough from watching
her husband work, and had experienced enough partners, that making
the movie was a pleasurable experience.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a girl from Texas. Or sort of from Texas; she was
born at Carswell Air Force Base but left for St. Louis when she was
5 or 6. If you had asked her father, though, there was no ``sort
of'' about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in the Air Force; he fell in love with Texas,'' says
Capshaw, who was born Kathleen Sue Nail. ``The whole time I was
growing up in Missouri, that's all I heard about, was Texas. And he
would tell me, `You are from Texas. Don't tell anybody you're from
Missouri. You're from Texas.' And he was not from Texas; he was a
farm boy from Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he loved the horses and the cowboys and the ranch
mentality and country-western music. He wore cowboy boots the
entire time I was growing up. Now, in Texas, that is so natural to
see people in cowboy hats and boots that you wouldn't blink an eye.
But in Missouri, in the suburbs of St. Louis, he was the only
father with a cowboy hat on, and cowboy boots on, and the yoked
jacket and the yoked pants. We used to get the country-western
catalogs, and I would hide them. I was so embarrassed that my
father dressed this way.''
</P>
<P>
   Capshaw's father, Edwin Nail, died in December at 65 after
living a quiet existence in Hurst that showed little signs that he
was Capshaw's dad or Spielberg's father-in-law. He had worked 38
years at American Airlines, and Capshaw and Spielberg quietly
attended his funeral in Colleyville.
</P>
<P>
   But then, most of Capshaw's visits were quiet. She visited her
father in Hurst about once a year, until her blended family of
seven children made travel more difficult, and Nail began traveling
to visit her. But work has brought Capshaw to Texas, most recently
with 1997's melodrama ``The Locusts,'' shot in Rosenberg outside
Houston. And although Capshaw left when she was still a child, she
sounds just like a Texan when she talks about the filming:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really hot in Texas in August,'' she says. ``But it's
sooo beautiful. Just beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 1606EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
