<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4836 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-LOVELETTER-TEX     05-20 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-LOVELETTER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LOVE LETTER' SENDS MIXED SIGNALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A movie couldn't be filled with a nicer group of people than the
characters in this film adaptation of Cathleen Schine's novel,
``The Love Letter.'' It follows the waves caused when an anonymous
love letter, filled with ever so slightly lavender prose, makes its
way through a small New England town. (''Do you know how in love
with you am I? Did I trip? Did I stumble? Lose my balance, graze my
knee ... graze my heart?'' the letter begins.) The novel played on
the idea of small-towners who know everything about each other
being rocked by this unsigned note, as well as the ripples of
confusion, delight and despair it sends through the burg's
residents.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a movie about people who are unable to tell others
what they really want until prodded by the letter, which nudges the
plot into motion. Helen (Kate Capshaw) keeps her emotions in a
pincers-like grip. That is, until she discovers the letter, and
slowly the walls of her resolve crumble. Capshaw's willfulness
probably led to the movie getting made, and it shows in her
portrayal of Helen. Her depiction offers a single-mindedness more
heated than the rest of the cast's. Her ambition crashes headlong
into director Peter Ho-Sun Chan's controlled handling, which mixes
the wistful with the humid. ``Love Letter's'' rhythms don't quite
feel like his.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is precise but lacks the knockabout underpinnings of
his Hong Kong work, several of which are romantic comedies that toy
with traditional gender roles (e.g., ``He's a Woman, She's a Man''
and ``Tom, Dick and Hairy''). It's as if the edges have been buffed
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Letter's'' cast includes Tom Everett Scott as Johnny, the
youngster whose blood is riled up by Helen's chin-up independence.
Tom Selleck is George, the decent, divorce-bruised pal who wants to
be more than pals. Ellen DeGeneres brings her worried eyes to the
role of Helen's best friend, who's briefly caught up in the
romantic undertow. Julianne Nicholson is an utter goofy delight as
the intense feminist coed whose ideals are tossed into a blender
when she falls for Johnny. (When she shears her hair after a
romantic stumble, her smooth, round head makes her look like a
naked chick right out of the shell _ and she still seems
shell-shocked.) And Blythe Danner plays Helen's troubled mother _
the kind of low-comedy, highly stylized role that's become her
stock in trade these days _ even though there can't be much more
than a 10-year age difference between her and Capshaw.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its source material, ``Letter'' also seems to take its
lead from the 1985 comedy ``Secret Admirer'' (this device has been
used in other films, too). ``Admirer'' is worth seeking out for the
hilarious performance by Fred Ward as a territorial cop who's eager
to prowl after receiving an anonymous note.
</P>
<P>
   ``Admirer'' has a raucous streak that ``Letter'' could've used.
``The Love Letter'' is so mild and muted that it also could have
used some of the melancholy '60s pop of the ``Rushmore'' soundtrack
instead of the jaunty, jazzy standards we hear played. It has an
autumnal bittersweetness _ right down to the turtlenecks that
Capshaw sports. Problem is, the movie's set in summer and
supposedly floats on the warm winds of summer romance. It just
can't make up its mind.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Love Letter''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Peter Ho-Sun Chan
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Kate Capshaw, Tom Selleck, Ellen DeGeneres
</P>
<P>
   Length: 89 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ adult language and content
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
