<HEADER>
A4837 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FROGS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     05-20 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FROGS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FROGS FOR SNAKES': RECYCLED `PULP' 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(lh) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quentin Tarantino has already blasted himself a niche in cinema
history, but his full impact on the gross national product may not
be measurable until the last of his filmmaking disciples has
exorcised the demon that impels them to imitate ``Pulp Fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest of these bloody black comedies is ``Frogs for
Snakes,'' written and directed by Amos Poe. It tells the story of a
group of lower Manhattan lowlifes circulating in the malign milieu
of a corpulent loan shark who also happens to be a bit of a
theatrical impresario. And all of his associates, lovers,
ex-lovers, children and their friends yearn seriously to act.
</P>
<P>
   So here's the joke that is repeated throughout the film: for all
of these people, killing or maiming is simply business. What really
stirs their blood is the thought that someone else in this circle
might get a part they covet or have the gall to choose a monologue
in an audition or acting class that they regard as theirs. These
are people who would literally kill for a role.
</P>
<P>
   Poe has assembled a fine cast, led by Barbara Hershey as Eva,
and including people like John Leguizamo, Robbie Coltrane, Justin
Theroux, Ron Perlman, Harry Hamlin, Debi Mazar and Lisa Marie. But
in the end, after the oral sex monologue and the bouncing
shotgunned head and the gallons of blood and the diner that have
their ``Pulp Fiction'' counterparts, ``Frogs for Snakes'' remains
derivative.
</P>
<P>
   Although surely not for delicate sensibilities, the film
nonetheless maintains a consistent sense of macabre humor and
delivers vivid performances. Ms. Hershey as the ex-wife of Al
(Coltrane), the mother of their little boy, a sometime hit woman
and occasional waitress, is the best actor of the lot but eager to
escape to a better life. ``I don't kill people,'' she says to one
of her targets. ``I maim them.''
</P>
<P>
   Her determination is intensified after her lover, Zip
(Leguizamo), is gunned down by Al's wheel man, U.B. (David
Deblinger), whose zeal is heightened by his desire for a role in
Al's next production, David Mamet's ``American Buffalo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Frogs for Snakes'' begins intriguingly, but thereafter it is
mostly recycled ``Pulp.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `FROGS FOR SNAKES'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Amos Poe; director of photography,
Enrique Chediak; edited by Jeff Kushner; music by Lazy Boy;
production designer, Michael Shaw; produced by Phyllis Freed
Kaufman; released by The Shooting Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   With: Barbara Hershey (Eva), Robbie Coltrane (Al), Harry Hamlin
(Klench), Ian Hart (Quint), John Leguizamo (Zip), Lisa Marie
(Myrna), Debi Mazar (Simone), Ron Perlman (Gascone), Justin Theroux
(Flav), David Deblinger (U.B.) and Clarence Williams III (Huck).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 92 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frogs for Snakes'' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It contains bloody violence, coarse
language and simulated sex.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
