A4838 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MET-APPOINT-NYT &LR;      05-20 0343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MET-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MET OPERA ASSOCIATION NAMES PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa.)   (af)  
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paul M. Montrone was elected president and chief executive
officer of the Metropolitan Opera Association at its annual meeting
Thursday. The association oversees the company's financial affairs,
and although it has no direct artistic input, it is responsible for
hiring both the general manager and the artistic director. The term
of office is one year, with no term limit.
</P>
<P>
   Montrone, 58, succeeds Bruce Crawford, 70, who was elected
honorary chairman. Crawford was president of the association in
1984 and 1985 and general manager of the Met from 1985 to 1989. He
has been president since he was re-elected to that post in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure the company appointed Joseph Volpe as its
general manager and installed Met Titles, a system that provides
English translations on seat-back screens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real strength of the Met today is a combination of
artistic achievement and financial wherewithal, and today we're
standing strong in both areas,'' Montrone said Thursday. ``My job
will be to maintain that momentum. None of this happens by itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a budget of $170 million, of which we raise about $70
million in contributions, with almost nothing from the government.
So we have a large job to be done each year, and to do it, we have
an active board that is a mosaic of people from various fields.''
</P>
<P>
   Montrone joined the Met's advisory board in 1986 and its
managing board in 1991. He has been a member of the executive
committee since 1992. He is the president and chief executive
officer of Fisher Scientific International Inc., which supplies
products and services to research and clinical laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Scranton, Pa., he graduated from the University of
Scranton in 1962 and later earned a doctorate in economics and
finance from Columbia University. He began his career as a systems
analyst in the office of Robert S. McNamara when he was Defense
secretary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 1615EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4841 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GURVIR1STTAKE23-COX     05-20 1448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GURVIR1STTAKE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Waking up with Gurvir
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 23.
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ She greets me in her bathrobe. Her white bathrobe.
It's early, OK? Really early: 3:25 a.m. The only house lights
glowing on this leafy Decatur (GA.) street this pitch-black morning
are hers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually get up 3:15, 3:30,'' says Gurvir Dhindsa, winning
co-host of WAGA's ``Good Day Atlanta,'' the locally produced
wake-up call (6-9 a.m.) that runs a close ratings race in metro
Atlanta with ABC's ``Good Morning America'' and NBC's ``Today.''
(Third place overall during the last sweeps rating period, ``Good
Day'' tied with ``Today'' for first in the coveted
18-to-49-year-old age group.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I got up a little earlier today because of you,'' she adds,
already showered. ``Want a cup of coffee?''
</P>
<P>
   Dhindsa, 37, is a little thing, with big eyes and a wide smile
framed by short, dark hair. A small-screen, local-news knockoff of
Audrey Hepburn _ if Hepburn had been born in India. Dhindsa says
people often look at her and don't know what to think: Hispanic,
mixed. She left India at age 7 and grew up mostly in Nashville;
she's always ``fixin' '' to do stuff. A news director in
Mississippi once suggested that maybe she should change her name,
to something a little more . . . understandable. Dhindsa (it's
pronounced Gur-veer DIN-za) declined.
</P>
<P>
   Smart move. While Katie Couric on ``Today'' and Diane Sawyer on
``GMA'' wage a high-profile battle for morning network viewers,
Dhindsa plays a version of the same game _ but in the role of clear
local alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good Day'' began as an hourlong alternative in 1992 when WAGA
decided it could do a better job in the morning than CBS, then its
network parent (it's now Fox). The show worked, flourishing with
hosts Amanda Davis and Paul Ossmann. By 1994, ``Good Day'' topped
both ``GMA'' and ``Today'' in local ratings.
</P>
<P>
   But the show lost ground after the 1996 Olympics, and a year
later Davis moved to the evening news. ``Good Day'' floundered
until Dhindsa arrived, in June 1997. Though Ossmann eventually left
for local rival WXIA, the show has regained about 40,000 viewers
since Dhindsa arrived, many attracted to an on-air presence that's
at once uncommon and approachable.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's exotic because she doesn't look like anyone else on
TV,'' says Don Fitzpatrick, a San Francisco-based TV news
consultant. ``She's not a typical white female. And she's not a
black female. And she doesn't have a name that's spelled and sounds
like everyone else's.'' Adds Ossman, now a WXIA weatherman and
``Peachtree Morning'' co-host: ``She's not going to blow you over
with big hair and jewelry.''
</P>
<P>
   It's 3:30 now. Dhindsa, still in her bathrobe, leaves to get
coffee. Two Australian shepherds follow her.
</P>
<P>
   A chance to snoop. Framed pictures are everywhere in a quaint,
crowded living room: lots of relatives; a black-and-white of her
mother and father (wearing a turban), soon after their arranged
marriage; a 6-year-old Gurvir, her dark eyes swallowing even more
of her face than they do now.
</P>
<P>
   Books: Elvis, photojournalism, Robert Kennedy, D-Day, CNN, a
pictoral history of westerns. The fiction tends toward the florid:
``From Here to Eternity,'' ``Gone With the Wind,'' a pile of John
Grishams.
</P>
<P>
   CDs litter the armoire around a blinking TV: Gladys Knight,
Emmylou Harris, Lyle Lovett (``I love Texans,'' she says), Cole
Porter, Willie Nelson (``Heard his new one? Amazing''), Sinatra's
``Best of the Columbia Years.''
</P>
<P>
   Dhindsa arrives with the coffee. Sees me snooping. Couldn't care
less. Grabs a remote. Flips to ``CBS Overnight,'' CNN, back to
``Overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm such a news junkie,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   It's 3:45. She's still in that bathrobe. She hates to get
dressed. She'd wear jeans every day if she could. The bosses keep
steering her toward bright colors. It's a morning show. People like
it bright.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gravitate toward black,'' she says. ``My tendency is to grab
the first black jacket in the closet.''
</P>
<P>
   She heads into her bedroom. Another opportunity to nose around.
An Emily Post wedding book on the coffee table.
</P>
<P>
   Dhindsa is getting married for the first time on Nov. 13, to
George Phillips, former U.S. attorney in Mississippi. Pictures of
him in the living room, her bedroom (snooped there earlier). Twelve
years her senior, he's as much cowboy as counselor: When not
working as legal counsel for U.S. Sen. Thad Cochran, he's all boots
and dogs and pickup trucks. He lives on a farm outside Hattiesburg
with 27 horses, spends time at a mountain cabin in Colorado, where
the two hope one day to settle. They've dated for almost eight
years, having met when Dhindsa covered a big murder trial that
Phillips prosecuted in Biloxi, where she reported and anchored for
nine years.
</P>
<P>
   Dhindsa comes out of her bedroom in a bright blue suit. Pats the
dogs goodbye (``I hate leaving the doggies''), grabs her coffee, a
makeup bag, piles into her car. The station is 10 minutes away. She
turns on news radio, mmm-hmm-ing after each report (President
Clinton held in contempt: ``Mmm-hmm'').
</P>
<P>
   She comes to a red light. Stops. Looks left, looks right. Looks
left again. Steps lightly on the gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't tell anyone I ran a red light, will you?'' she says
as the car glides across an empty North Decatur Road. ``I look both
ways, but at 4 a.m. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   `What you see is what you get'
</P>
<P>
   She is sort of Atlanta's Katie Couric: a smart, likable, morning
picker-upper who, like a hometown version of the ``Today'' co-host,
can bring you the latest school tragedy right along with the latest
spring fashions.
</P>
<P>
   Like Couric, Dhindsa squirms a bit at being called ``perky'';
she also squirms at comparisons to Couric, whom she considers
sometimes ``mean-spirited.'' But, as with Couric, there's an
unmistakable . . . perkiness about Dhindsa that's attractive
exactly because it stops just short of going over the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``Morning TV is very tricky: You can't be too up, so you give
people a headache, and you can't be so laid-back that you don't
wake them up,'' explains John Kukla, WAGA creative services
director. ``It has to be a natural enthusiasm. You have to have the
talent to talk to Bonnie Blair when she brings on her baby, and
then say, `By the way, 15 people were killed at Columbine.' You
have to have news credibility, then turn around and do the Dirty
Bird, and people don't feel like it's fake.''
</P>
<P>
   Dhindsa sums herself up: ``I'm not the best-looking anchor, and
I'm not the best reporter. I think my strength is, what you see is
what you get. Doing a morning show leaves you vulnerable _ you
don't have that anchor desk as a buffer between you and the viewer.
It exposes your strengths and weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   She finishes: ``I am who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a little more complicated than that. While her on-air
personality is only a slightly revved-up version of what she's like
off the air _ Dhindsa is one of those people you meet and you like
_ she's not always what she might seem.
</P>
<P>
   ``People meet her with a certain set of assumptions, then have
to put them aside,'' says Sidmel Estes-Sumpter, ``Good Day
Atlanta's'' executive producer. ``People wouldn't assume that,
being Indian, she really is Southern _ (but) she was raised in the
Deep South, and has lived in a deeper South than most Atlantans.
</P>
<P>
   ``People assume she's a woman of color and expect her to enjoy a
certain kind of music, and to be familiar with issues that affect
women of color,'' Estes-Sumpter adds. ``But she's a country gal who
enjoys living in Colorado.''
</P>
<P>
   Dhindsa isn't so easy to pinpoint on the air, either. Set within
the show's ceaselessly upbeat, welcome-to-our-living-room format,
it's easy to take her lightly. But after chatting up Jane Fonda for
two minutes about teenage pregnancy, Dhindsa turned the
conversation to husband Ted Turner, who had recently angered
Polish-American Catholics with some shoot-from-the-hip comments.
Fonda stewed, saying she should have expected a question like that
from a Fox station. When Evander Holyfield came on to talk about a
children's charity, Dhindsa asked him about his own out-of-wedlock
paternity problems. The boxing champ was not pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``She combines a genuine warmth with an intensity on top of
that,'' says Marc Bailey, Dhindsa's ``Good Day'' co-host. ``That
intensity says, `Don't be mistaken by the fact I'm being warm and
open here _ don't try to snow me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Says Dhindsa: ``I think I'm nice. But I have a real competitive
edge. Don't get in my way.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 1616EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4842 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GURVIR2NDTAKE23-COX     05-20 1350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GURVIR2NDTAKE23-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA: in my way.''
</P>
<P>
   A sheltered childhood
</P>
<P>
   Dhindsa didn't always think she was cut out for television. The
oldest of three daughters born to what she describes as loving but
overprotective immigrant parents, working in TV news seemed a
million miles away. Her father once retrieved her from a movie
theater where she'd gone to see a Saturday matinee with a
minister's son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up very sheltered,'' she says of an upbringing that
began in India, then wound through Oregon and Alabama before
settling in Nashville. ``I grew up with nice people _ my parents
were nice, my parents' friends were nice. People in TV news were
aggressive, cutthroat.''
</P>
<P>
   She describes her first job, behind the scenes at a Nashville TV
station, as ``traumatic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People were cursing, shouting. I thought, `What have I gotten
myself into?'
</P>
<P>
   ``But the news hound in me comes from my father,'' she says of
Harbans Dhindsa, a principal at the Tennessee School for the Blind.
``He watched Walter Cronkite every night. To this day, I won't
watch anything but the `CBS Evening News.' My father encouraged me
to go into journalism. I was scared to death.''
</P>
<P>
   Harbans and Dev Dhindsa were both teachers in India. Harbans'
focus was special education, and he saw greater opportunity in the
United States, where his brother had moved.
</P>
<P>
   Dhindsa recalls her culture shock when she landed in Portland,
Ore., with her mother, who arrived in America with $40.
</P>
<P>
   ``First time I rode in a car,'' she says of the drive with her
uncle from the airport to his house. The first time her father got
a haircut, the whole family trooped with him to the barbershop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat in the car and cried,'' she remembers. ``I thought he
wasn't going to be my father anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The family lived in subsidized housing while Harbans and Dev
alternated going to school for advanced degrees. The Dhindsas then
moved to Talledega, Ala. (``another kind of culture shock,''
Harbans recalls), where the parents worked at the Alabama School
for the Blind and Deaf.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later they moved to Nashville. Gurvir was a go-getter,
into drama, the yearbook, forensics, the school paper (but few
movie dates). She majored in mass communications at Middle
Tennessee State University.
</P>
<P>
   Her first reporting job was at a TV station in Jackson, Miss.
``It was where the world was exposed to me,'' she says of the
local-news universe of crime, tragedy and political corruption. She
loved it. When she next saw her parents, they asked, ``What
happened to your softness?''
</P>
<P>
   She was fired after three years in what she calls a ``classic
personality conflict.'' She was hired a day later by well-regarded
WLOX in Biloxi, quickly becoming evening anchor and the face of the
Mississippi coast's TV news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew she was good, but she turned out to be better than I
thought,'' says WLOX news director Dave Vincent, who hired her.
``You could see it in her eyes. Some people just have an ability to
attract people. When you see it, you know it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite honestly, she seemed better than Biloxi, and it
surprised me she stayed as long as she did,'' Fitzpatrick, the San
Francisco consultant who remembers being impressed with her back
then, says of Dhindsa's nine-year stint in the country's
158th-largest TV market. ``She had major-market qualities. I showed
her tapes to the networks.''
</P>
<P>
   Dhindsa received feelers from major markets: a Boston station, a
fledgling Fox News in New York. But she stayed in Biloxi: She liked
the life there, the station treated her well, she met Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   But even all that eventually wasn't enough. She remembers a
drive back from a vacation in Colorado a few years ago when she
turned to Phillips and said, ``I don't want to wake up years from
now and look at you and resent you (because) I regret what I didn't
do with my career. I need to see what I'm capable of doing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And he said, `Go. Do it. Now's the time.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't do this forever,'' Dhindsa says of her work. ``Look at
the TV _ this business is hard on women and relationships.
Sometimes I wonder if I chose a career over family and
relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Eyeing the future
</P>
<P>
   We're in the bridal salon at Saks Fifth Avenue. The fitting room
is a hall of mirrors _ a mirror positioned to capture a blushing
bride's every blushing angle. Dhindsa has just slipped on her white
Badgley Mischka strapless gown for a final fitting. She turns this
way, that way. She's a stunner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you love it? Really?'' She stares into the mirrors. ``I
feel like a princess. I really feel like a princess in this dress.
Oh, I love it I love it I love it I love it!''
</P>
<P>
   An attendant offers a pair of Vera Wang shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mmm-hmm,'' Dhindsa says. She floats one millimeter back down
to earth. ``As far as shoes, I hate to say this, but is it crazy to
wear . . . slippers?''
</P>
<P>
   Heads tilt. Mouths scrunch up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are my cowboy boots when I need them?'' she sighs,
taking the Vera Wangs and slipping them on.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later she's back home, in jeans and a flannel shirt,
patting and shooing her dogs in the late afternoon light.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could never have kids,'' she says from the couch, where she
greets the same dog she just sent away. ``I have no consistency. As
soon as they suck up, it's all over.''
</P>
<P>
   She's joking, of course. Kids _ and anything else that comes
under the heading of ``future'' _ are very much on her mind these
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been stressing out the last two weeks,'' she says,
``thinking I'm never going to be in the same place (as Phillips)
unless I give up the business. It's difficult being in two
different places, not having a feeling of being settled in any one
place.''
</P>
<P>
   She and Phillips see each other almost every weekend; mostly she
makes the six-hour drive to Hattiesburg. He's eligible for
retirement in less than two years, but there's no chance he'd move
to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want him to move here,'' she says. ``It wouldn't be
who he is.''
</P>
<P>
   But who is she? She loves her job, loves the challenge of
filling three hours of live television every morning, loves the
adrenalin rush when things fall apart behind the scenes while she
coolly ad-libs on the air.
</P>
<P>
   She loves Atlanta: loves being a player in a bigger pond, loves
for the first time, after growing up in suburban Nashville, having
Indian friends and feeling . . . Indian. (Her wedding will have two
parts: the one in the gown from Saks will be preceded by a
traditional Indian Sikh ceremony.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to share a common experience,'' she says. ``As an
Indian friend here said, `We all lived in the same house in
different places.' ''
</P>
<P>
   They love her at WAGA, where management sees limitless
potential. But some there also understand the forces faced by a
37-year-old career woman thinking about children and marrying a man
two states away.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'll be making some very difficult life choices, and those
choices will determine her future,'' says Estes-Sumpter, the
executive producer. ``Things like, `What is the true meaning of my
life, and what do I want my life to be?' (Those questions) are
terrible to face sometimes, and only she can decide her fate.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, her fiance, adds, ``I suspect she'll do just like she
did when she moved (to Atlanta): look at what all her options are,
then pick something that's not only financially beneficial, but
something that keeps that spark in her.''
</P>
<P>
   Have the two discussed family? A pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little,'' he says finally, from a cell phone on his farm,
where the horses he's feeding whinny in the background.
</P>
<P>
   Dhindsa says she'll put off making any decision about her future
for another year, when her three-year contract at WAGA expires.
Until then, she'll keep doing what she likes to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in college, I thought
</P>
<P>
   I wanted Jane Pauley's job,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was the best job in America. You get to do
anything. Funny, now I do have Jane Pauley's job _ on a local
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
