A4843 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAVERS20-COX     05-20 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAVERS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Follow a few simple steps to a quaint stone pathway
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A stone pathway can add a quaint touch to a flower
garden. But if you really want your slice of paradise to offer the
charm of an English cottage garden, fill the gaps between the
stones with creeping plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can really plant anything that's low and crawly and see
what works best,'' said Sylvia Attkisson, an Atlanta garden
designer.
</P>
<P>
   Choose plants based on the pathway's exposure to sun or shade
and ones that prefer well-drained soil.
</P>
<P>
   Herbs such as creeping thyme, Corsican mint and golden oregano,
as well as perennials such as dianthus, make ideal choices. They
may look dainty, but they're tough enough that when walked upon,
they bounce back.
</P>
<P>
   They also are rapid spreaders, quickly filling the gaps,
overlapping the stones and making the pathway appear as if it's
been there for years.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry about choosing appropriate combinations of plants,
Attkisson said. ``Just have fun with it!''
</P>
<P>
   SUPPLIES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Trowel
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nature's Helper soil conditioner
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Plants (suggestions: dianthus `Fire Witch', creeping thyme,
variegated mint, laurentia, Corsican mint, golden oregano, creeping
Jenny, creeping rosemary, mazus, erigernon)
</P>
<P>
   Step 1: Inspect the soil. Herbs don't require rich soil, so the
space between the stones may not need amending. If the pathway is
mortared, you can chisel out a few pockets for planting, but be
aware that the soil may be rich in lime because of the concrete. If
so, amend with a soil conditioner.
</P>
<P>
   Step 2: Using a trowel, landscaper Gregg Catchie digs out the
soil to loosen it. If you plan to amend the soil, remove enough to
allow space for the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Step 3: Plants should be set out so that the tops of their root
balls are level with the stones, Sylvia Attkisson said. If you're
concerned about taller plants, such as creeping rosemary, plant
them along the outer edges of the pathway. Sprinkle soil
conditioner around the plantings once they're in. Pathway plantings
don't require fertilizer because too much growth will cover the
stones.
</P>
<P>
   Finished product: This pathway in Don and Selene Morgan's Ansley
Park garden includes an array of herbs, which when stepped on
release their fragrance. ``The only maintenance is to go out and
pick something for dinner,'' said Attkisson, who designed the
plantings.
</P>
<P>
   The Spring Workshop Series
</P>
<P>
   April 15: Replacing patio screens
</P>
<P>
   April 22: Resealing a backyard deck
</P>
<P>
   April 29: Building a compost bin
</P>
<P>
   May 6: Installing a ceiling fan
</P>
<P>
   May 13: Water gardens
</P>
<P>
   May 20: Plants for stone pathways
</P>
<P>
   The Summer Workshop series begins June 24.
</P>
<P>
   This is the final installment in our Spring Workshop series, a
step-by-step guide to inexpensive weekend projects for the home or
garden. If there's a project you'd like to suggest for our Summer
Workshop or you want more information about this series, call
404-222-8689 or e-mail dflanders
</P>
<P>
   (at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
