<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEASANT23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Peasant perfect for Summer
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday, May 23.
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some women may have a hard time reconciling the way major
designers want them to dress this season _ peasant style _ with the
modern, active lifestyles they lead.
</P>
<P>
   Here we are poised on the edge of a new millennium, and
designers are advocating a look spawned during feudal days. The
``peasant'' look was reborn and renamed ``bohemian'' during the
1950s and '60s. And today's version of the look is being touted as
``hippie chic.''
</P>
<P>
   But these days we live under shrouds of conservatism: Who wants
to look like a hippie? And we live in times of unprecedented
prosperity: What's chic about looking like a milkmaid? And in an
age when women still struggle for equal footing in the workplace,
where's the sense in dressing so flagrantly femininely?
</P>
<P>
   Forget all that.
</P>
<P>
   Now's the right time for peasant dressing because, in the summer
especially, there's never a wrong time for the cool comfort of the
lightweight fabrics that peasant styles come in.
</P>
<P>
   After so many seasons of minimalist clothes in neutral tones,
all the color and embroidery and lace and beading attached to
peasant looks comes as a refreshing change. Besides all that,
what's the use of being a woman if you can't dress like one?
</P>
<P>
   Designers flooded the fashion runways with peasant blouses and
skirts, beaded belts and ethnic espadrilles and embroidered slides
because they offered a romantic escape from the restrictive styles
of seasons past. They presented them as an alternative, something
to dabble in, like the ``utility chic'' and geisha-inspired styles
they also dotted their collections with.
</P>
<P>
   Some women may find the buying and wearing of ``hippie chic''
clothes to be habit-forming, but it's best not to plunge into the
trend too deeply. After all, it's only a matter of time before the
major designers want you to start wearing something else.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
