A4847 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LETTER-FILM-REVIEW-NY     05-20 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LETTER-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE LOVE LETTER': AN UNSIGNED LETTER SENDS THE SPARKS FLYING 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Loblolly by the Sea, the jauntily named New England town that is
the setting for ``The Love Letter,'' is the kind of idyllic seaside
retreat that could exist only in a cheery children's folk song or a
yuppie sitcom. The place radiates an alarming perkiness. And for
its first three-quarters, ``The Love Letter,'' which takes place in
the summer, hurtles toward a seemingly inevitable fairy-tale ending
in which its nice middle-class characters all end up snugly coupled
before the first nip of autumn frost.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about this cute-as-a-button screen adaptation of
Cathleen Schine's whimsical romantic novel is that the story ends
up defying expectations. Once its characters have been magically
awakened to the romantic possibilities of their lives by a stray
document, most of them don't end up sharing Nora Ephron moments.
</P>
<P>
   What's not so wonderful about this wisp of a movie, directed by
Peter Ho-sun Chan from a screenplay by Maria Maggenti, is its bland
dialogue and dull sitcom acting. When the movie's over, you are
hard put to remember a single scrap of dialogue beyond a couple of
sour quips from one character (played by Ellen DeGeneres) who
pretty much disappears halfway into the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Love Letter'' revolves around Helen MacFarquhar (Kate
Capshaw), an attractive divorced woman in her 40s who runs a local
bookstore and spends her spare hours jogging. Helen, who fields
irritated phone calls from an ex-husband who complains about having
to pay for everything, lives a life of contented celibacy. Or so
she imagines, until one day she finds a mysterious love letter,
unsigned and addressed to no one, tucked in her mail.
</P>
<P>
   The letter isn't especially steamy, but it is ardent. And
suddenly Helen's erotic imagination, which has been shut down, goes
into overdrive. In Woody Allen-like fantasy sequences, she imagines
everyone in her orbit secretly drooling over her.
</P>
<P>
   One likely possibility is Johnny (Tom Everett Scott), a
20-year-old college student who has a summer job in the bookstore.
Dropping by Helen's for dinner one night, he accidentally discovers
the love letter on the kitchen counter tucked under a bottle of
wine and assumes she deliberately left it there for him to find. By
the end of the evening, each is secretly convinced the other is the
author, and before long the two embark on a passionate affair.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a more age-appropriate suitor, George (Tom Selleck),
who has been in love with Helen since they were in high school
together and who is in the final throes of a divorce, starts
hanging around and wagging his bushy tail.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden blossoming of romantic possibility among these and
several other characters sets up expectations that ``The Love
Letter'' could evolve into the sort of luxuriant rumination on age,
youth and Eros that Eric Rohmer has turned into a cottage industry
in France. But the deeper literary resonances of Ms. Schine's novel
have been so thoroughly bleached out of the film that Helen and
Johnny's May-September relationship has no depth or poignancy.
Beyond her generic snippiness and his generic ingenuousness, these
two are devoid of personality.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Helen's mother (Blythe Danner) and grandmother
(Gloria Stuart) turn up in Loblolly. The new set of relationships
they introduce arrives in the film so late that they've barely
registered before the final credits are rolling. And not a minute
too soon.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   THE LOVE LETTER
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``The Love Letter'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It has glimpses of nudity
and sexual situations.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Peter Ho-sun Chan; written by Maria Maggenti, based
on the novel by Cathleen Schine; director of photography, Tami
Reiker; edited by Jacqueline Cambas; music by Luis Bacalov;
production designer, Andrew Jackness; produced by Sarah Pillsbury,
Midge Sanford and Kate Capshaw; released by Dreamworks Pictures.
Running time: 88 minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Kate Capshaw (Helen), Blythe Danner (Lillian), Ellen
DeGeneres (Janet), Geraldine McEwan (Miss Scattergoods), Julianne
Nicholson (Jennifer), Tom Everett Scott (Johnny), Tom Selleck
(George), Gloria Stuart (Eleanor) and Bill Buell (Officer Dan).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
