NYT-05-20-99 1618EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4848 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-THREESEASONS-TEX     05-20 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-THREESEASONS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SEASONS' APPEALS TO THE HEART AND THE MIND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a certain type of movie that doesn't want to make you
cry yet is steeped in sadness, that doesn't want to make you guess
but is filled with a sense of mystery. In recent years, ``The Sweet
Hereafter'' and ``Affliction'' have fit that description; they're
movies that sink into your heart and linger long after you've seen
them.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that list ``Three Seasons,'' the beautifully melancholy
new film from 26-year-old Vietnamese-American director Tony Bui.
Like the aforementioned films, ``Season'' is strongly literary but
distinctly cinematic, an astute synching of words, pictures and
sounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seasons,'' the first American film to be shot in Vietnam, is
set in modern-day Saigon. Within the bustling city, which is
dominated by American brand names and symbols (including a cafe
called Apocalypse Now), the movie discovers four interlocking
stories suffused with loss, hope and redemption. A young woman
(Nguyen Ngoc Hiep) picks lotuses for a mysterious master (Tran Manh
Cuong), who finds a bond with her through music. A cyclo, or
bicycle-taxi, driver (Don Duong) falls for a call girl (Zoe Bui). A
street urchin (Nguyen Huu Duoc) searches for his lost case of cheap
merchandise, which he believes has been stolen. And an American war
veteran (Harvey Keitel, who acted as executive producer) sits
quietly in front of his hotel, pensively smoking cigarettes and
becoming engrossed in a search of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Keitel's story, and that of the cyclo driver, are hardly
original, but that makes little difference in this movie's context.
The surprises in these tales, which were written for the screen but
feel as if they were adapted from a short-story anthology, aren't
in the outcomes but in the way Bui lets them envelop you. Although
this is his first feature, he's one of those directors who's
blessed with an instinctive visual sense that can find as much
beauty in a whirring oscillating fan as it can in a rain-drenched
street soccer game or in a shower of rose petals. Cinematographer
Lisa Rinzler (''Menace II Society'') and composer Richard Horowitz
(''The Sheltering Sky'') contribute mightily to the movie's beauty
and mood.
</P>
<P>
   Bui, who was born in Saigon near the end of the Vietnam War and
came to the United States at age 2, tells his stories as
illustrations of the past, of transition, of the present and of the
country's future. But he's not obvious about it, and as a result,
the movie affects you almost subliminally. We are at a time of the
year when most movies want to lead you by the hand, telling you
when to laugh, when to cry or when to duck. And often, we happily
agree to be led. But it's always a welcome sight when you encounter
a movie that trusts you and trusts that you know when to think.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Three Seasons,'' in English and in Vietnamese with
English subtitles
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Tony Bui
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Don Duong, Nguyen Ngoc Hiep, Harvey Keitel
</P>
<P>
   Length: 113 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ brief violence and adult themes
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 1618EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4850 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BESIEGED-FILM-REVIEW-     05-20 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BESIEGED-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BESIEGED': A LOVE THAT SOARS ABOVE WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: production notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an age when televised psychobabble presumes to unlock life's
greatest mysteries, it's easy to forget that love isn't the product
of words and therapeutic negotiation. Civilized relationships are
one thing; the raw force we call love is another.
</P>
<P>
   One reason why ``Besieged,'' Bernardo Bertolucci's new film,
feels so bracingly fresh is that the love that grows between its
two main characters, Jason Kinsky (David Thewlis), a wealthy
expatriate English pianist living in Rome, and his black
housekeeper, Shandurai (Thandie Newton), who has fled an oppressive
African regime, has little to do with words. This is one
contemporary love story in which you won't hear terms like
``boundaries'' and ``narcissistic'' thrown around. You won't even
hear the word ``relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Besieged'' is a purposefully romantic exploration of the
nonverbal connections between people that can blossom into love.
Filled with rich, glinting images of the world imagined as a
confusingly lovely mosaic, the movie has one of the sparsest
screenplays of any film released this year.
</P>
<P>
   For the feelings that this love story examines are built up more
through music than through talking, and through mysterious deeds,
carried out by one character and observed by the other, that don't
seem to add up. Even after the story ends, a lurking sense of
mystery hovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besieged'' opens with a harrowing montage of images from
Shandurai's unidentified African homeland, which is in the throes
of a military coup. As she rides a bicycle toward a one-room
schoolhouse where her husband teaches, posters are slapped upon
buildings of her dilapidated village, and a wizened, gap-toothed
griot hobbles through the rutted streets playing a crude thumb
piano and singing in an anguished wail. Shandurai has nearly
reached the schoolhouse when soldiers barge into her husband's
classroom and drag him away. Subsequent scenes of Shandurai huddled
in bed alone and listening to ominous sounds outside her house
convey a nightmarish terror.
</P>
<P>
   Then suddenly we are in the Roman villa where Jason, an
eccentric musician with a sweetly goofy smile, feverishly plays the
piano day after day, while Shandurai polishes his artworks and mops
his floors. How and when she got there we are never told. We do
learn that she is using her income as a housekeeper to put herself
through medical school, and that she is an A student. Shandurai has
made one close friend, a fellow student, Agostino (Claudio
Santamaria), who says he wants to sleep with her despite the fact
that he's gay.
</P>
<P>
   As Shandurai discharges her housekeeping duties, the tension
between her and Jason builds. Finally, one afternoon he seizes her
in his arms, confesses that he is hopelessly in love with her and
begs her to marry him. He'll do anything to win her love, he
insists.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get my husband out of jail,'' she challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Stunned to realize Shandurai is married, Jason apologizes for
his advances.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the rest of the film the two circle each other
warily in Jason's grand four-story villa, which has a spiral
staircase and dumbwaiter. The camera is continually peering at the
characters from odd angles, including many shots from below the
stairwell.
</P>
<P>
   The film pointedly contrasts the music Jason plays on his grand
piano _ everything from Bach to Scriabin (which Shandurai says she
doesn't understand) _ with the lilting African pop of Salif Keita
and Papa Wemba that she plays on the stereo in her room. But when
Jason begins to compose a piece on the piano, the music he writes,
with its hypnotically repetitive figures, suggests that he has
absorbed some of the incantatory spirit of her favorite music.
</P>
<P>
   Shandurai is overjoyed one day to receive a mysterious letter
informing her that her husband has been transferred from a military
prison to an ordinary jail. She also observes her employer meeting
with a local African clergyman. Meanwhile Jason mysteriously begins
to sell off items from the house. First a lavish tapestry is
removed, and eventually his piano itself is lowered into a truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besieged'' is so determinedly elliptical that its refusal to
be direct seems at times affected and evasive. Its two main
characters, though appealingly played by Thewlis and Ms. Newton
(who gives Shandurai a bursting emotional volatility), never quite
come into focus.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, its anti-psychological perspective is so
refreshing that you applaud its creation of two grown-up people who
don't have to be explained by a list of character traits or fit a
personality profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besieged'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying parent
or adult guardian). It has nudity and sexual situations.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BESIEGED'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Bernardo Bertolucci; written by Bertolucci and Clare
Peploe, based on a story by James Lasdun; director of photography,
Fabio Cianchetti; edited by Jacopo Quadri; music by Alessio Vlad;
production designer, Gianni Silvestri; produced by Massimo Cortesi;
released by Fine Line Features. Running time: 92 minutes. This film
is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   With: Thandie Newton (Shandurai), David Thewlis (Jason Kinsky)
and Claudio Santamaria (Agostino).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 1619EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
