<SLUG> BC-NATO-ADMITS-FAILURE-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOST SERB MILITARY STILL UNDAMAGED, NATO NOW ADMITS  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This timely 425-word ``separate buy'' article is from The
Independent newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By STEPHEN CASTLE  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS _ More than two-thirds of Serbia's tanks and heavy
artillery inside Kosovo are still intact, NATO admitted Wednesday,
raising the prospect of many weeks of further bombardment before
the military capacity of Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic is
rendered ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   Despite greater success in the last two weeks of the air
campaign and reports of discipline beginning to disintegrate, NATO
concedes that the Serbs still have a formidable fighting force left
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   After 57 days of concerted bombing an estimated total of 40,000
troops and paramilitaries remain in the province with 69 percent of
their tanks and heavy equipment intact.
</P>
<P>
   Even these figures are open to doubt because NATO's military
spokesman, General Walter Jertz, said Wednesday that the alliance
had ``struck'' _ rather than destroyed _ 31 percent of Serbia's
heavy forces, a nuance which means there is no evidence of
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics illustrate the distance NATO is from launching a
successful ground invasion of Kosovo, even if it could muster the
political will to assemble one.
</P>
<P>
   NATO would suffer ``enormous'' casualties, one source said _ in
addition to the suffering that would be inflicted on ethnic
Albanians inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   At the current rate of destruction _ 5 percent a week _ the
allies would need to bomb for another month before Serb forces
could be close to breaking point. But there is some doubt as to
whether NATO's existing rate of destruction inside Kosovo can be
kept up .
</P>
<P>
   The alliance said 75 percent of fixed surface-to-air missile
sites and 69 percent of high-performance MiG-29 jets have been
destroyed, along with 11 command posts.
</P>
<P>
   But other statistics were less impressive: only 12 percent of
mobile surface-to-air missile units and 34 percent of remaining
combat aircraft have been destroyed, including 24 percent of
MiG-21s, 46 percent of Galebs and 33 percent of Super Galebs.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance claims to have hit 556 pieces of equipment of which
312 were tanks, artillery or armored personnel carriers. That
compares with the figures given two weeks ago when General Jertz
said that 300 pieces of equipment had been struck, 200 of which
were heavy artillery, roughly 20 percent of the Serbs' total
inventory.
</P>
<P>
   At the time the general cited a figure of 50 percent as the
point at which the Serbs would cease to operate as an effective
force, becoming more concerned with survival.
</P>
<P>
   But the alliance has conceded that President Milosevic might
order his troops to continue with as little as 20 to 30 percent of
its equipment. &QL; 
