<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4883 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOUGH-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     05-20 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUGH-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TOUGH, TOUGH TOYS:' FORKS THROUGH WINDOWS , NEUROSES GALORE   AND
OTHER GROTESQUERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) (DW) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There has never been any question whether the flamboyant British
writer Will Self had talent. The question was whether he would
squander his manic imagination and tactile, hyperventilated prose
on self-consciously nasty exercises in sophomoric humor (``Cock &AMP;
Bull,'' ``Great Apes'') or create fictions commensurate with his
copious gifts (``My Idea of Fun'').
</P>
<P>
   Self's latest book, ``Tough, Tough Toys for Tough, Tough Boys''
represents his most disciplined storytelling yet. The tales in this
collection demonstrate a new control and polish, without
sacrificing anything in terms of inventiveness or plain weirdness.
Like his 1994 novel, ``My Idea of Fun,'' it attests to Self's
ability to render even the most bizarre, ``Twilight Zone''-like
events with convincing verisimilitude while enthralling _ and often
horrifying _ the reader with his scathing, Swiftean humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tough, Tough Toys'' comes with an epigraph from Oscar Wilde _
``Life is a dream that keeps me from sleeping'' _ and most of the
characters in these stories realize that their lives have come to
resemble a nightmare or hallucination. In ``Flytopia,'' a
Hitchcockian thriller that slowly morphs into a William
Burroughsesque fantasy, a mild-mannered clerk enters into a strange
pact with the insects infesting his house. In ``The Rock of Crack
as Big as the Ritz,'' a drug dealer named Danny discovers that
there's a huge vein of crack cocaine running beneath the basement
of his house. In ``A Story for Europe,'' a 2-year-old English child
and a German businessman appear to exchange personalities.
</P>
<P>
   The last of those stories, of course, is meant as a wacky
commentary on the new, unified, economically interdependent Europe,
and its sardonic humor recalls ``My Idea of Fun,'' which satirized
the go-go years of the 1980s by depicting yuppie greed as a
Faustian pact with the Devil. An even more pronounced version of
this sort of social satire can be found in the story ``Caring,
Sharing,'' which depicts a therapy-obssessed America in which
people mate not with lovers but with ``emotos'' _ that is, giant
manifestations of their own inner children. ``The whole messy
business of sexual and emotional entanglement'' has been written
off by these narcissistic Americans; what they want more than
anything is ``the absolute reassurance that an emoto would provide
them with.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the remaining tales in ``Tough, Tough Toys'' are
ostensibly more realistic, their characters fall prey to drug- and
hormone-fueled fantasies that infect their day-to-day lives,
undermining their sense of self and throwing into question their
most basic assumptions about the world. The narrator of ``Dave
Too'' _ arguably, the weakest story in this volume _ sees everyone
around him turning into someone named Dave.
</P>
<P>
   The hero of the title story, a former psychiatrist named Bill,
finds himself forced by a chance encounter with a hitchhiker to
re-evaluate his entire self-indulgent existence. Danny, the
drug-addicted hero of ``The Nonce Prize,'' discovers an unlikely
new vocation as a writer, while serving time in prison for a
horrific rape and murder he didn't commit.
</P>
<P>
   Using his eye for detail to flesh out his oddest imaginings,
Self does a nimble job of evoking the addled states of mind of
these characters. The Dave man looks at his psychiatrist's window
and thinks it looks like an egg: ``If a fork like a prop for a
Magritte painting were to be plunged through the window of Dr.
Klagfarten's office,'' he tells himself, ``a gush of yellow
neurosis would undoubtedly ooze out.''
</P>
<P>
   During long drives, Bill the ex-shrink likes to imagine himself
merging with his car, becoming part of the big machine as he
cruises the long, twisty roads between London and the Orkneys.
While he drives, he allows his mind to wander, musing that the
landscape beyond his windshield is ``a terrain in which a few
triceratops and pterodactyl wouldn't have looked altogether out of
place.'' His favorite fantasy involves a seraglio made up of all
the women he has had sex with: a Felliniesque dream sequence in
which the younger women handle the bulk of the domestic work and
the older ones spend their days in ``idle conversation and
hobby-style activities.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Danny, the former crack addict turned short story writer,
he suffers from visitations of menacing spirits he calls ``the
Fates'' _ ``tall, wispy, indeterminate figures'' who metamorphose,
much like the ghostly special effects in ``Raiders of the Lost
Ark,'' into terrifying djinnlike creatures, ``bearded, turbaned,
wearing long gray-and-black robes, and carrying mutant,
nine-foot-long Kalashnikovs.''
</P>
<P>
   In both this story and ``Tough, Tough Toys,'' Self expertly
orchestrates suspense: in the former by turning a simple drive home
from a country house into a harrowing adventure in which every
attempt to pass another car on the twisting road feels like a life
and death confrontation; in the latter, by conjuring up a
particularly gruesome crime _ the sexual torture and murder of a
6-year-old boy _ and the almost equally terrifying subculture of
sex criminals in a prison.
</P>
<P>
   Although the other stories in this volume may not be as
thrilling as this pair of tales, they, too, attest to Self's ease
and authority as a storyteller. His tendency displayed in previous
books to force his tales into predictable shapes with obvious,
italicized morals, has given way in these pages to masterfully
shaped narratives that are both complex and unexpected, just as his
earlier, adolescent preoccupation with sex has evolved into a more
deeply felt interest in the mysteries of identity and emotional
(dis)connection. Along with ``My Idea of Fun,'' ``Tough, Tough
Toys'' stands as Self's most powerful work yet.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TOUGH, TOUGH TOYS FOR TOUGH, TOUGH BOYS'
</P>
<P>
   By Will Self
</P>
<P>
   244 pages. Grove Press. $23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
