<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4884 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-TREKKIES-TEX     05-20 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TREKKIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEARING THE STARFLEET SEAL OF APPROVAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leave it to Data to sum up the appeal of ``Trekkies,'' Roger
Nygard's bemused and amusing documentary about ``Star Trek'' fans.
Well, not Data, really, but Brent Spiner, who played the
wannabe-human android on ``Star Trek: The Next Generation.'' Spiner
readily acknowledges the peculiarity of the most passionate ``Star
Trek'' aficionados _ but then asks, aren't we all peculiar in some
way?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. Most of us, however, are not so peculiar that we wear
our ``Star Trek'' uniform when called to serve on the Whitewater
jury, as Barbara Adams does in ``Trekkies.'' Or that we would
design our office completely in a Star Trek motif, as Orlando,
Fla., dentist Dr. Denis Bourguignon does (his family and staff also
wear ``Trek'' uniforms). Or muse about getting our ears surgically
sharpened in order to look more Vulcan, as David Greenstein does
(as Greenstein considers this, his wife looks at him as if he's
gone over the edge _ a look that would bear more credibility if she
weren't wearing a ``Trek'' uniform and cradling their uniform-clad
poodle).
</P>
<P>
   Because of people such as these, ``Trekkies'' is often hilarious
without half trying. Its concern isn't with people who've collected
every episode of every ``Star Trek'' series on tape, but with
people who have begun living the phenomenon _ people who make the
``Star Wars'' fans who camped out for ``Phantom Menace'' tickets
look like relaxation therapists. It's hard to tell whether Nygard,
who examined similar fanaticism in the USA Film Festival entry
``Six Days in Roswell,'' is studying his subject with affection or
with condescending irony, but by keeping himself out of the movie
he avoids a ``Daily Show'' sort of nastiness. He makes a smart
movie in using Denise Crosby to ask questions of the Trekkies who
appear on camera. Crosby, a ``Next Generation'' actress who was
merely a blip in the ``Trek'' universe, constantly looks baffled by
their adoration.
</P>
<P>
   What ``Trekkies'' doesn't teach you is why these fans have
reached this point of fanaticism. They frequently complain that
although they're treated like freaks, sports fans who wear the
clothing of their favorite teams are considered normal. Point
taken, and a subject for further research. But Nygard doesn't dig
deeply enough into the ``Trek'' phenomenon to be illuminating about
the culture of fiction-worshiping.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of several ``Trek'' stars buoys the movie, although
William Shatner is only on camera incidentally and succeeding
captains Patrick Stewart and Avery Brooks don't appear at all.
That's indicative of why ``Trekkies'' isn't more satisfying: What
we see is entertaining enough, but it's what we don't see that
makes the movie mildly disappointing. Still, considering the hype
for that ``other'' movie with ``Star'' in the title, this is the
movie that's more likely to come off as a pleasant surprise.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Trekkies''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Roger Nygard
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Denise Crosby and a whole bunch of ``Star Trek'' fans
</P>
<P>
   Length: 87 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG _ mildly adult material
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
