<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4932 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      05-20 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HARD-WORKING QUEEN AND HER MEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's big, it's bad, it's ``Cleopatra!'' What else could anyone
expect? Onscreen, Cleopatra's legend has always been about
spectacle, not character. So ABC's expensive two-night mini-series
includes chariots, warships, battle scenes on horseback, the
Pyramids, the streets of Rome, and countless varieties of Egyptian
headdresses.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a spectacle going nowhere except off the deep end.
Shakespeare may have described Cleopatra's power best when he
praised ``her infinite variety,'' but here her charms are finite.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, this version strains so hard to make her an
overachieving modern woman that she might as well have a to-do list
taped to her throne: 1. Be a sexpot. 2. Be a great mom and queen.
3. Hook up with some Roman guy and try to conquer the world. The
last one, of course, is the killer.
</P>
<P>
   Though Cleopatra should hold this story together, the two halves
of the mini-series have opposite tones, each borrowed from a
different man she seduces. Sunday's installment begins with Roman
legions marching into Alexandria. Julius Caesar arrives, helps
Cleopatra oust her sister and brother to become queen, and falls
for her.
</P>
<P>
   But even when cavorting with Cleopatra, Timothy Dalton's Caesar
is the essence of a buttoned-down Englishman. This episode
resembles one of those clunky Bible movies from the 1950s, full of
clanging armor and stiff declarations of love.
</P>
<P>
   Why does Caesar fall so hard for Cleopatra? Excellent question,
despite the early scene in which she summons a courtesan for a
question-and-answer session. (The ancient advice: leave him wanting
more.)
</P>
<P>
   In the 1963 film, now a legendary bomb, there was logic behind
casting Elizabeth Taylor, then considered the most beautiful woman
in the world. In the public mind, she simply had to show up to
channel Cleopatra. Her off-screen affair with Richard Burton, her
Marc Antony, only enhanced the character.
</P>
<P>
   But this ``Cleopatra'' has poor, unknown Leonor Varela. She
looks exotic enough but you can practically see her straining to
throw smoldering glances at Caesar. The courtesan should have told
her that seduction should never look like that much work.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cleopatra gets her man, and he invites her to Rome, where
she is carried through the streets. The costume department hauls
out many colorful veils to wrap around her sedan chair. Yet the
crowd shouts, ``Caesar's whore!'' She has, after all, brought along
their illegitimate son. (Don't look for historical accuracy here;
the mini-series has written out two children she later had with
Antony.)
</P>
<P>
   And Caesar's troubles are just beginning. When he stands before
the Senate and declares himself dictator for life, the camera
closes in on Brutus, looking plenty mad and stalking out. Could he
be, maybe, plotting something?
</P>
<P>
   The first episode ends with Caesar's assassination by Brutus.
The second begins with Antony avenging his death. At once, Billy
Zane's loony, overheated performance turns ``Cleopatra'' into some
campy late-night cable movie.
</P>
<P>
   Where Caesar was all dignity, Antony is all hands, grabbing
Cleopatra in a drunken passion. The girl can't help it, she's in
love again. Soon she's squeezing pomegranate juice on his back and
licking it off, all the while dreaming of world domination. When
she plans to seduce Antony she says things like: ``Prepare the
royal barge for war. A different kind of war.''
</P>
<P>
   When Antony marries Octavia to form an alliance with Octavian,
her brother and Caesar's successor, Cleopatra is understandably
annoyed. Antony and Cleopatra squabble on the beach, gesticulating
at each other wildly. He says: ``Forget Octavia. I married for
convenience, now I live for love.''
</P>
<P>
   Rupert Graves plays Octavian as if he had been bullied at an
English public school and is now using his power to get even. His
whiny superiority adds an especially icky feel to the scene in
which he and Antony toss around Brutus' severed head.
</P>
<P>
   As the story heads toward the Battle of Actium, and Antony and
Cleopatra's final defeat by Octavian, the Queen picks up a weapon
and proves that, among her many other talents, she's not a bad
little swordswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Franc Roddam (who has directed movies and, for television, the
recent ``Moby Dick'') knows how to maneuver those barges and keep
those sword fights moving. ``Cleopatra'' has the seamless look of a
feature film. But there aren't enough big battle scenes in history
to overcome the laughable dialogue and acting in this tale of her
infinite familiarity.
</P>
<P>
   `The Jesse Ventura Story'
</P>
<P>
   NBC, Sunday night at 9
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 4 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   There's one thing we'd all like to know about Gov. Jesse Ventura
of Minnesota. How in the world did this happen? There are no clues
in this dull, simple-minded, unauthorized movie, which is even
flatter and more whitewashed than the governor's newly published
autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   At least in his book he admits to a wilder streak in his younger
days. Revelations of smoking marijuana and visiting a prostitute
(legally) in Nevada have been good for a few book-promoting
headlines. There isn't even that much candor in this quickie film.
</P>
<P>
   The hero is played by Nils Allen Stewart, a onetime wrestler who
acts with his wardrobe. A uniform tells you when Ventura is a Navy
Seal. During his biker days he wears a fringed jacket. When he
becomes Jesse (the Body) Ventura he parades around the ring in a
fuchsia boa and leopard hat.
</P>
<P>
   All along he is really a good guy, family man and future
governor trapped in a wrestler's body. There are a few wrestling
scenes, but not enough to entice actual fans. There is a political
campaign, but not a fraction of a thought that will aid all those
analysts still fretting over the wrestler-turned-governor
phenomenon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
