</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEATER NOTES: TWO MUSICALS FROM ONE POEM;   CALISTA FLOCKHART
COMES TO BROADWAY;   A NEW PRESS AGENCY OPENS;   AND MORE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Depending on how you look at it, it's either a
testament to the magnetic theatrical appeal of really fine poetry
or it's the paucity of really good stage ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Two top nonprofit theater companies, the Manhattan Theater Club
and the Joseph Papp Public Theater, are in the late stages of
developing musical adaptations of ``The Wild Party,'' based on the
jazz-era poem by Joseph Moncure March. But while the competition
for press attention and audience members would seem to be intense,
both sides are playing nice, at least publicly.
</P>
<P>
   The theater club's version, by Andrew Lippa, had a private
workshop performance Thursday for a select crowd of friends, staff
members and others in the theater. The Public's workshop of a
``Wild Party,'' written by Michael LaChuisa and George C. Wolfe,
was in February and had Mandy Patinkin, Vanessa Williams and Eartha
Kitt in the cast.
</P>
<P>
   This week Wolfe said that the production would probably begin
rehearsals in January for a spring 2000 run and that the theater
was exploring the option of playing in a Broadway house.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a producer, we're looking at various spaces to perform it
in,'' Wolfe said. ``And some of those spaces have been on
Broadway.'' He said part of the reason was that the production's
set may be too large for the Public's theaters.
</P>
<P>
   The Broadway option was hinted at in a brief article in Daily
Variety last week. But Wolfe laughed off the suggestion that the
report had been leaked by Public officials to scare off the theater
club. ``That's just people projecting their own thought processes
on this very pure nonprofit institution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lynne Meadow, the artistic director of the theater club, said
that a production of its ``Wild Party'' was possible but not
definite for next season. Much depends on the reaction to
Thursday's reading.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't describe it as a test,'' she said. ``We just want
to see where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   As for overlap, creative or otherwise, with the Public, Ms.
Meadow said: ``Both pieces are based on the original source
material, but once the material works through the imaginations of
the artists, they could come out looking like two completely
different things. A priori, that would not give us great concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe said his reading settled his insecurities about another
``Wild Party'' stealing the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had asked me this question six months ago, I would have
had more apprehension,'' he said. ``But having done the reading and
found its voice and found its power, I don't get into all that
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Back From `McBeal'
</P>
<P>
   Calista Flockhart, who is ``Ally McBeal'' on television and an
alumna of the New York stage, isn't taking any time off this
summer. Instead, she'll be acting Off Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the skinny: Beginning on June 15 at the Douglas Fairbanks
Theater, Ms. Flockhart will appear in what is tentatively titled
``A Gaggle of Saints,'' three one-act plays by Neil LaBute, film
director of ``In the Company of Men'' and ``Your Friends and
Neighbors.'' Joe Mantello (``Love! Valour! Compassion!'') is likely
to direct.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from Los Angeles, LaBute described his plays as having
``a continuing theme from my work, which is basically beautiful
people doing awful things.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Flockhart, who will appear in two of the three pieces, has
been rumored to be involved in any number of projects over the last
month, from a production of Strindberg's ``Miss Julie'' to a
revival of Marsha Norman's `` 'Night, Mother.'' A promising theater
actress before her break into television, Ms. Flockhart appeared in
``Three Sisters,'' at the Roundabout Theater Company in 1997. She
also played Laura in the Roundabout's 1994 production of ``The
Glass Menagerie.''
</P>
<P>
   Comings and Goings
</P>
<P>
   This week's news that James Morrison, a press agent who
represented many major nonprofit theaters, would close his office
and that another team would open shop shows how part of the
theatrical food chain works.
</P>
<P>
   About the time Morrison announced the closing of his office, two
other rising young press agents, John Barlow and Michael Hartman,
said they were leaving Boneau-Bryan Brown, a powerhouse Broadway
agency, to form their own company. Adrian Bryan Brown and Chris
Boneau, owners of the agency, said the two left ``with our
blessings.''
</P>
<P>
   While the timing may have been coincidental, it is certainly
opportune. Morrison, who represents the Broadway production of ``It
Ain't Nothin' but the Blues,'' has had many mid-size clients,
including Playwrights Horizons and the Classic Stage Company, all
of which will probably need new representation.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison said he would take some time off before deciding what
to do next. He has been making recommendations to his clients about
who might take his place, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Barlow said he and Hartman had not aggressively pursued
clients, he said they felt it was ``the right time'' to set up
shop. They will open as Barlow/Hartman Public Relations on June 28.
</P>
<P>
   Along the Way
</P>
<P>
   ``Contact,'' a dance theater piece by John Weidman and Susan
Stroman, will open at the Mitzi Newhouse Theater at Lincoln Center
on Oct. 7. Boyd Gaines will star.
</P>
<P>
   Dana Ivey, Dylan Baker and Charles Kimbrough will be in the
Public Theater's ``Tartuffe,'' opening in August at the Delacorte
Theater in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   Add Laurence Fishburne, Christian Slater, Christine Baranski and
Chita Rivera to the list of Tony presenters for this year's
broadcast on June 6.
</P>
<P>
   Call it theater or just plain odd, but the latest project of the
producer David Binder (``Rent,'' ``Villa Villa'') is ``Delicious
Vaudeville,'' a melange of twisted circus arts, bizarre monologues
and vaudeville, now playing at the Theatorium in Manhattan.
Information: (212) 420-8877.
</P>
</TEXT>
