<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE-ON-ONE RELATIONSHIP WITH WEB CUSTOMER WAVE OF FUTURE, AUTHOR
SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine a world where companies asked for your ``permission''
before slapping a billboard alongside the highway or piping a
television commercial into your living room.
</P>
<P>
   While such strategies would never fly on Madison Avenue, such an
approach might represent the secret to effective marketing in
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   That's the argument put forward by Web entrepreneur Seth Godin
in a book published this month, ``Permission Marketing: Turning
Strangers Into Friends and Friends Into Customers'' (Simon &AMP;
Schuster, $24, 255 pages).
</P>
<P>
   Godin, who started the Web marketing firm Yoyodyne, which last
year was purchased by Web search engine parent Yahoo!, makes the
case that consumers suffering from media overload have little time
to pay attention to anything and, hence, are increasingly tuning
out many of the mostly irrelevant TV commercials, billboards and
newspaper advertising that bombard them daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's infoglut, people are more selfish than ever,''
Godin writes. ``And they're most selfish about their time and
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   What consumers will pay attention to, Godin says, are
personalized messages from marketers with advertising that touches
issues they are interested in. The consumers most likely to be
receptive to these messages are those who have asked to be placed
on a marketer's electronic mailing list, he writes.
</P>
<P>
   For companies, the idea is to give consumers incentives for
initiating an ongoing dialogue. A marketer, for exmple, may offer a
coupon or gift certificate to a consumer signing up to an
electronic mailing list. The marketer then sends follow-up e-mail
messages to the consumer at regular intervals offering more
coupons, highlighting special deals or simply providing
newsletter-style information to shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must find a reason for the prospect to pay attention,''
Godin writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to offer an explicit reward-information, education,
entertainment or even cold hard cash to get the consumer to opt in
to the message.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a process may sound difficult and expensive. But it may be
more efficient to focus marketing efforts on building a small set
of good customers rather than using the shotgun approach of
mass-market advertising to deliver a message to thousands of people
who couldn't care less about your product or service, Godin writes.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to build lasting relationships with consumers. And
with the cost of sending e-mail small, the expense of sending
frequent messages that can build customer loyalty and future sales
is negligible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Permission marketing cuts through the clutter and allows a
marketer to speak to prospects as friends, not strangers,'' Godin
writes. ``The personalized, anticipated, frequent and relevant
communication has infinitely more impact than a random message
displayed in a random place at a random moment.''
</P>
<P>
   But Godin's book is more than a primer on Web-based direct
marketing. It reminds marketers of some fundamentals that can help
transform a wayward shopper into a customer for life.
</P>
<P>
   The author weaves a variety of examples from outside the realm
of cyberspace to illustrate the power that ``permission marketing''
can wield in the real world.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps one of the best-known permission marketing campaigns of
all time is American Airlines' frequent-flyer rewards program.
Customers hand over key personal information to the airline in
exchange for rewards that ultimately make them more loyal customers
of the airline. American Airlines then takes the information
collected from its reward program to offer users sets of coupons
and services tailored to match their interests.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the one-to-one communication power of the Web,
consumers may expect more companies to begin offering rewards to
shoppers who will spend the time listening to their sales pitches
and share information.
</P>
<P>
   And the companies that are most aggressive in forging these
bonds with consumers will have the inside track on selling to users
_ perhaps for decades to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every industry, just a few companies will end up with the
permission to market to a huge number of qualified customers,''
Godin writes. ``And when that happens, these companies _
gatekeepers _ will start to exert power.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``If You Want to Make God Really Laugh, Show Him Your Business
Plan: The 101 Universal Laws of Business''
</P>
<P>
   By Barry J. Gibbons
</P>
<P>
   Amacom, $22.95
</P>
<P>
   This dense book, written by former Burger King chief executive
Barry Gibbons, is packed with business wisdom from someone who has
spent a lot of time and thought on the front lines. None of his
laws are trivial, and some have such depth that the reader has to
ponder them. Consider Universal Law No. 5: ``Tangible investments
must reap tangible returns. That means you must define the returns
in advance and hold somebody accountable for their delivery.''
Think about it. Then think about buying this book and learning
more.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Managing Multiple Bosses: How to Juggle Priorities,
Personalities and Projects _ and Make It Look Easy''
</P>
<P>
   By Pat Nickerson
</P>
<P>
   Amacom, $15.95
</P>
<P>
   If you need to learn how to communicate under stress, say no to
unrealistic demands or delegate work, this book may have some tips
to help. Written by corporate trainer, speaker and author Pat
Nickerson, this book is full of interesting ideas to manage what
appears to be unmanagable.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Smart Guide to Buying a Home''
</P>
<P>
   By Alfred and Emily Glossbrenner
</P>
<P>
   John Wiley &AMP; sons, $10.95
</P>
<P>
   'Tis the season for home buying, and this guide, written by the
authors of more than 50 books, offers a good overview of this
important purchase. ``The problem with buying a home is that most
people don't do it often enough to get really good at it,'' the
book begins.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
