<HEADER>
A4944 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT &LR;      05-20 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH THE FORCE AS EVER, A GENERATION FAR, FAR AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAR WARS: EPISODE I _ THE PHANTOM MENACE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Liam Neeson, Ewan McGregor, Natalie Portman, Jake Lloyd, Ian
McDiarmid, Ahmed Best, Terence Stamp, Ray Park, Frank Oz &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by George Lucas &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 132 minutes
</P>
<P>
   In a galaxy far, far away, the time is a generation before the
original ``Star Wars'' (1977), and (no huge surprise here) the
powerful are about to dispose of some inconvenient little folk.
</P>
<P>
   For bureaucratic reasons that don't seem to matter much, the
tiny planet of Naboo is singled out for attack by the giant Trade
Federation, which is controlled by an electrostatic see-through
presence named Darth Sidious. Naboo's Queen Amidala (Ms. Portman),
a diminutive teen-ager with a startlingly throaty voice but not
much in the way of a defense force, must succumb and is taken
prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   Amidala, though, has the allegiance of two Jedi knights, the
wise older hand Qui-Gon Jinn (Neeson) and the able but
inexperienced Obi-Wan Kenobi (McGregor). Together the pair
dismantle scores of Federation soldiers (robotic contraptions
called droids) with their light sabers and eventually rescue the
Queen, who determines to mount a resistance.
</P>
<P>
   On the remote planet of Tatooine, the knights encounter Anakin
Skywalker (Jake Lloyd), a tow-headed 9-year-old boy with a gift of
gab and a genius for things mechanical. And Qui-Gon Jinn senses
more: the lad may look like a refugee from ``Leave It to Beaver''
but the Force is clearly with him. Train him right and he could be
a knight among knights.
</P>
<P>
   For now, young Skywalker runs away with the pod race, a wildly
exciting contest between jet-powered chariots that does ``Ben Hur''
proud. Later he hops in a star fighter and, though he can barely
see over the dashboard, plunges into the climactic battle for
Naboo.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE The two knights duel furiously with their light sabers
and there are big battle scenes, with armies laid to waste and
space ships erupting in great orange fireballs. But the violence is
bloodless and often more industrial than fleshly or disturbing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOOTNOTE For all the ``Star Wars'' fanaticism, this is also a
children's film. Convoluted in its details, the story is easy to
follow in broad outline. Creatures tend to be amiable cartoon
critters. Serious matters of villainy are frequently forgotten at
the sight of the next big vista _ an enormous cityscape, a vast
space colony, a stadium for a half-million spectators _ which is
this movie's strong point. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-6 The film may be too much extravaganza for some of the
littlest ones, though not all. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 7-9 They'll love the creatures and the spectacle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 10-13 They'll be hooked, too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 13 AND UP Teen-agers generally will stay on board, but in
some corners of the older reaches of this category there could be a
cry for a little more edge and sophistication.
</P>
<P>
   THE MUMMY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Fraser, Rachel Weisz, John Hannah, Arnold Vosloo &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Stephen Sommers &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 134 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Having misbehaved with the Pharaoh's mistress, a priest named
Imhotep (Vosloo) is whisked off to Hamunaptra, city of the dead,
where he is put to an unimaginably horrible death. Let him lie, the
legend goes, or he will arise and revisit the plagues upon the
earth.
</P>
<P>
   Try to make that stick three millennia later. Pounding up to
Hamunaptra on horse and camel in 1923, scholars and grave robbers
get to the sarcophagus. ``He's still juicy!'' exclaims Evelyn (Ms.
Weisz), a budding Egyptologist.
</P>
<P>
   Once out of the box, Imhotep (who in fully restored form
resembles Kojak) feeds on the innards of stray adventurers, but
what he needs to really get rolling are the contents of several
golden jars.
</P>
<P>
   Charged with defending the interlopers, the dashing Rick
O'Connell ( Fraser), a kind of Harrison Ford knock-off, races all
over the desert blasting away at zombies with a brace of pistols
and rescuing Evelyn and others. ``I'm a librarian,'' she says. Fine
but she has only seconds to decipher an inscription that will save
them all.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE Pitched gun and sword battles produce dozens of dead,
but then many of the victims were dead already. Some situations
promise true horror but shy away at the last second. Flesh-eating
beetles provide the nastiest moments. On balance, there is little
gore and the violence isn't very real. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX It's on the minds of Evelyn and Rick, not to mention poor
Imhotep, who wants to resurrect his ancient beloved, but nothing
transpires. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Some mildly off-color exclamations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-9 This movie rides on its special effects, many of them
in the horror vein. That will frighten many young children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 10-12 Parents should be aware of the violence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 13 AND UP Teen-agers are flocking to the first of the
summer action films.
</P>
<P>
   TEA WITH MUSSOLINI &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cher, Dame Judi Dench, Joan Plowright, Dame Maggie Smith, Lily
Tomlin, Charlie Lucas and Baird Wallace &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Franco Zeffirelli &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG 117 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Florence in 1935 is home to a tight-knit group of Englishwomen
of eccentric demeanor who all but worship at the grave of Elizabeth
Barrett Browning and fondly chide their American friends, Georgie
(Ms. Tomlin) and the big-hearted Elsa (Cher), a former Ziegfeld
girl who collects rich husbands. ``Amazing how they can even
vulgarize ice cream,'' sniffs Lady Hester (Dame Maggie), leader of
the pack.
</P>
<P>
   Then into their midst falls a little boy named Luca (Charlie
Lucas), the illegitimate son of a deceased friend. Taking pity,
Mary (Ms. Plowright) shelters and tutors him until, with the winds
of war building, he is sent to school in Austria.
</P>
<P>
   In Florence, black-shirted gangs of Fascists have begun to make
life difficult for the English. Lady Hester finds that hard to
understand since she has gone to Rome and has had tea with
Mussolini, who gave her his assurances that her little colony will
be allowed to carry on as always.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, however, the women are herded into genteel
confinement. Luca returns a young man and surprisingly un-Nazified.
Together, they resist the German occupation and strike a blow for
art.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE Fascist squads yell and break things, but they are
dissuaded or distracted before physical harm is done. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Elsa is shown in bed with a cad, but the scene is discreet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-9 No. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 10-12 This is an unusual choice for children, but an
evocation of time and place is a nice change of pace. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 13 AND UP Probably not, but certain teen-agers would like
the film if they gave it a chance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
