<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4948 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITISH-AMERICA-ART-3     05-20 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITISH-AMERICA-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BRITISH INVASION? SURRENDER. 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Much has been made of the fact that British culture
has of late been flooding these shores with almost colonial aplomb.
Just look at Broadway, the argument goes: it's British; British;
British; ``Cats''; British, British. (Come to think of it, ``Cats''
is British, too.)
</P>
<P>
   British film, too, seems to be everywhere, from variations on
Shakespeare to ``The Winslow Boy,'' which though directed by David
Mamet, whom nobody would mistake for English, is a movie  &UR; all about
England &LR; . Paranoia sets in quickly: everywhere one looks there are
Young British Artists or old British television programs or new
British plays. Is that a cricket match? Are you in the mood for
steak and kidney pie? What, pray tell, is David Hare writing now?!?
</P>
<P>
   But despite all the hemming and hawing about the Anglofication
of American life, very few cultural connoisseurs have bothered
trying out all these dandy English imports.
</P>
<P>
   I, on the other hand, did.
</P>
<P>
   My mission was simple: to immerse myself during a mere 48 hours
in all things British, from food and drink (with an emphasis,
understandably, on the latter) to sports and sounds to theater and
art. It would take Bondian endurance (as in Bondian, James
Bondian), but I felt up to snuff.
</P>
<P>
   I cheated a bit by boning up on some of the current crop of
British theater and cinema before the weekend, enjoying showings of
``Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels'' and other film imports, as
well as most of the Broadway offerings. And to help in my endeavor,
I picked up a copy of that cheeky London import Time Out New York
hoping the magazine's writers and listings might divulge where
Brits in New York go to find things from home.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I would have to dig a bit, and travel a lot. Despite the
hype, this supposed British invasion is far less overt, and far
more enjoyable, than the accounts might suggest. Indeed, the bits
of Anglia I found in New York were pleasant, polite and reserved,
just like a proper English gentleman.
</P>
<P>
   My weekend began at dusk on a recent Friday in the West West
End, or as New Yorkers still quaintly call it, the theater
district.
</P>
<P>
   Broadway has nine recent productions that arrived after passing
through London's West End: ``Amy's View,'' ``Art,'' ``Cabaret,''
``Closer,'' ``The Iceman Cometh,'' ``The Lonesome West,'' ``Not
About Nightingales'' ``Via Dolorosa'' and ``The Weir.'' Not all are
entirely British; ``The Iceman Cometh,'' by Eugene O'Neill, and
``Not About Nightingales,'' Tennessee Williams' recently discovered
first play, are by American playwrights. But much of the creative
talent that brought these productions to life speaks the Queen's
English.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the imports have drawn strong reviews. Even ones
receiving mixed reviews have a certain sociological value. Those
still laboring under the no-sex-please-we're-British myth might do
well to check out ``Closer,'' by Patrick Marber, which offers more
carnal knowledge than your average Times Square peep booth.
</P>
<P>
   I chose ``Amy's View,'' Hare's loving take on the life of that
stateliest of British creatures, the brilliant if aging actress.
Playing the lead role is Dame Judi Dench, who is typecast, albeit
terrifically. The play, set in a London suburb, passed by quickly
and only whetted my appetite for proper accents and strangely named
products. But one would have to wait until teatime for that.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, after the theater, I sought the British new wave's
latest swell, the electronic dance music known by names like trance
and techno and house, oh my. The British artists who make these
sounds are part of any self-respecting disk jockey's collection,
but some major New York nightclubs have devoted whole nights to the
music. Twilo, the cavernous club on West 27th Street in Chelsea, is
considered a hub for British beats. On my Friday night out, the
club featured a major London drum-'n'-bass act, Planet V.
</P>
<P>
   I also sampled an act that I had seen advertised, something
called Great British House, a weekly DJ party devoted to ``London
underground house'' music. An organizer, Tom Joseph, a Londoner,
described it thus: ``It's more funky and tuneful than just hard. We
try to have a very funky sound. It's more funky-tuneful house
rather than big-room house.''
</P>
<P>
   Aha.
</P>
<P>
   The party is usually held at Vanity on East 23rd Street, a
standard lounge scene with deep red curtains, $7 vodkas and cozy
low-slung couches. The crowd was in its mid-20s and dancing to the
beat in a medium-size back room. There didn't seem anything
particularly British to me, but I did have untrained ears.
Everybody seemed to be grooving in a funky, tuneful, decidedly
un-big room way. After a while, I was knackered and went home.
</P>
<P>
   A Cuppa With Class
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the high point was afternoon tea.
</P>
<P>
   At least a dozen hotels and teahouses in Manhattan offer a
proper British tea. I had never done tea, however, so when I
entered Lady Mendl's Tea Salon, on Irving Place, I'll admit I was a
bit nervous. Was there a protocol to be followed? Were you supposed
to drink as much tea as possible, or nurse a single cup? Would
there be multiple spoons?
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, I had brought a companion with a cool head. A nice
young man in a tie met us at the door and took our names. We waited
for a bit in a parlor, where I noticed I was the only man of about
a dozen nicely dressed women. That ratio would change a bit as tea
approached, but the event was a predominantly ladylike activity.
</P>
<P>
   Lady Mendl's is part of the Inn at Irving Place, an upscale bed
and breakfast with a decidedly English air. Light and airy, the tea
parlor is decorated in a genteel fashion, complete with dried
flowers, deep rugs and lamps with fringed shades. A bushel of
umbrellas sat in a basket by the door. I was only slightly
surprised to find a harpist playing while we took tea.
</P>
<P>
   An afternoon tea usually includes finger sandwiches, scones with
jam and clotted cream in addition to all manner of delicious
amenities, from cookies to cake. Lady Mendl's was no exception.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Cucumber sandwiches?'' quipped my partner. ``That's what we
used to fix when there was nothing else in the fridge.'' (She would
be converted.)
</P>
<P>
   At Lady Mendl's, visitors are first offered a tea menu complete
with exotic blends and more commonplace selections like Earl Grey.
I chose the English breakfast tea, which was served in an antique
silver teapot from 1874.
</P>
<P>
   The first course was a small salad, a concession, I figured, to
the calorie explosion that was about to occur. While I nibbled I
perused ``The East India Company Book of Tea'' by Antony Wild
(HarperCollins, 1994), where I discovered that the world's most
expensive tea was Makaibari Flowery Tippy Golden Flowery Orange
Pekoe, or FTGFOP for short, an exotic blend that fetched $360 a
kilogram in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   After courses of salmon, cucumber and mozzarella sandwiches;
scones, jam and clotted cream, and cookies, I was stuffed. We
passed on the final course, a chocolate mousse cake, determined to
work off the meal in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Our plan? To hit three British art exhibitions, visit a shop run
by and for British expatriates and pop by the British Open, a pub.
I had about three hours.
</P>
<P>
   Completely Different
</P>
<P>
   Two exhibitions were on the same block, West 22nd Street in
Chelsea. The first, at the Brent Sikkema Gallery, showed the work
of Yinka Shonibare, a much-praised English-born, Nigerian-bred
artist. The show is anchored by two large photographs of Shonibare
in Victorian surroundings. The artist's message, critics say, is
partially about skewing perceptions of traditional Britain and its
aristocratic norms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jolly good,'' I thought, and moved on.
</P>
<P>
   Down the street at the Dia Center for the Arts, the Scottish
video artist Douglas Gordon was apparently up to his usual tricks.
Gordon thrives on visual illusions, I discovered from the program.
This exhibition, called ``Left Is Right and Right Is Wrong and Left
Is Wrong and Right Is Right,'' consists of the same 1949 noir film
``Whirlpool'' shown on two side-by-side screens.
</P>
<P>
   The catch is that one version includes only the odd-numbered
frames, the other only the even, leading to a subtle, hypnotic
flicker. Hypnotic flicker. Hypnotic flicker. Hypnotic flicker . . .
.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking away from the movie, we headed south to Soho and the
Lehmann Maupin Gallery to see its show of Tracey Emin's work. Ms.
Emin, 36, is part of the school of artists known as YBA, or Young
British Artists, known for daring esthetic endeavors and a naughty
demeanor. Members of the group include provocateurs like Damien
Hirst, who exhibits dead animals in formaldehyde, and Marc Quinn,
who depicted a dead man's head made of frozen blood. These artists
are very much in vogue after a recent successful showcase at the
Royal Academy of Arts in London. Their exhibition will travel to
the Brooklyn Museum of Art in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Emin's first solo show in New York, ``Every Part of Me's
Bleeding,'' includes an ample supply of biography, including dozens
of crudely drawn self-portraits in various states of undress and
sexual contortion. It also includes an apparently well-used seaside
shanty and a confessional film about Ms. Emin's early sexual
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   After the YBA, I needed something fortifying. I needed to shop.
</P>
<P>
   Next, a Visit to the Dentist
</P>
<P>
   Many British merchants and fashionistas have been laying down
roots in New York, from the wild mod designs of Paul Smith on Fifth
Avenue to Thomas Pink's esteemed Savile Row shirts on Madison
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   For more minor needs, smart shoppers also know that many
Chinatown merchants carry British delicacies like chewy Fruit
Pastilles candies and Marmite spread.
</P>
<P>
   The mother lode of such treats is Myers of Keswick, a spiffy
English grocery on Hudson Street in the Village. Nearby on
Greenwich Avenue, Carry On Tea and Sympathy, in whose sister
restaurant I would later dine, also sells goodies. But Myers has
the range, from homemade Cumberland pork sausages to such fiendish
inventions as mushroom ketchup and Wheetabix. And the shop's
purveyor, Peter Myers, is as friendly as they come.
</P>
<P>
   Warm Beer, Strong Whiskey
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until I encountered the British Open that I began to
feel truly in the British mix.
</P>
<P>
   The pub, on East 59th Street, is a generally friendly
establishment attired with golf clubs, bobbies' hats and a giant
British flag over the bar. Soccer and politics are big topics of
conversation; British tabloids are often laid out on the bar.
</P>
<P>
   Once I had settled in comfortably, I noticed the large, blurry
bloke on me left.
</P>
<P>
   He was chest-to-chest with a glass of whiskey. Our repartee was
short and sweet: He asked if I were British. No, I said, American.
Then he inquired about whether I would like to buy him a drink. I
declined. Finally, he inquired if I had any nude pictures of my
sister. Not today, I said.
</P>
<P>
   He grumbled and stumbled out into the street. I've missed him
ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The bartender, a polite young man in a shirt and tie, apologized
profusely. I didn't have the heart to tell him that I was a bit
flattered. Only 24 hours on the job, I thought to myself, and
already people are mistaking me for British.
</P>
<P>
   Updated Downstairs
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night was spent in front of the telly, tuned to Channel
13, a public television station that true Anglophiles know is a
secret outlet for the best of the BBC.
</P>
<P>
   I sat through the ``Vicar of Dibley,'' a British clergy-comedy,
before finally getting to ``Berkeley Square.'' (Pronounced Barkley
Square, thank you.)
</P>
<P>
   The show, about a group of nannies circa 1902, has a devoted
following in this country for good reason; it is a soap opera par
excellence.
</P>
<P>
   Just listen to the teaser before the program began: ``Hannah
outshines Isabel at a luncheon, Tom snaps under pressure and causes
a shooting accident, and Lydia visits her family and receives an
ultimatum from Hugh.''
</P>
<P>
   Though I hadn't seen it before, midway through I was rapt. (Hugh
is such a cad.) With tired feet and a house full of nannies, I was
in good hands for the evening.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Gooooaaaaal! Beer!  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was all about sport. So at 11:30 in the morning there I
was, shoulder to shoulder in a bar with 200 rabid soccer fans.
</P>
<P>
   The locale was Nevada Smith's, an East Village bar with a
fraternity-friendly reputation. But on most Saturday and some
Sunday mornings, Nevada Smith's is transformed into a perfect place
to watch live soccer games beamed by satellite from Britain and
other points European.
</P>
<P>
   Eight televisions, including a giant screen, circle the bar.
With the windows blacked over (it is very dark) and the speakers
turned up high (it is very loud) the atmosphere is as close to an
actual game as you can get. Raucous cheers and club chants break
out at every goal. Club jerseys are common; conversation is not.
Eyes remained glued to the televisions.
</P>
<P>
   When we arrived on this morning, the mood was tense. Manchester
United, the bar's official team, was losing its final game of the
season, a loss that could cost it the championship. Most people
were rooting for Manchester, though a few detractors were hunched
at the bar.
</P>
<P>
   Though I understood the basics of soccer, I was uncertain about
the particulars: Was the red team winning? The white? Someone?
Anyone?
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, a player in red broke along the pitch's flank and
somehow curled a shot into the corner of the net. A roar of joy
exploded throughout the bar. Men jumped and screamed and hugged and
kissed. I still had no idea what was going on, but I got goose
bumps.
</P>
<P>
   As the game progressed, I became increasingly engrossed, getting
tips from the owner, Paddy McCarthy, and from a helpful English
customer, Garry Jones. Phrases like ``nice touch'' and ``good
ball'' took on new meaning. And when Manchester took the lead, I
cheered, too.
</P>
<P>
   I inched my way out of the bar after our glorious victory with
the sounds of the Manchester fight song ringing in my ears.
Luckily, my next athletic adventure would be significantly more
sedate.
</P>
<P>
   Organized Loafing
</P>
<P>
   Cricket, which is currently holding its world championships, is
exceedingly popular in Britain and in many of its former colonies,
except this one. Still, there are outposts of enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 teams compete regularly in New York and its
suburbs, said Paul DaSilva, president of the Nassau-New York
Cricket Association. They play on pitches, or cricket fields, in
Van Cortland Park in the Bronx, in Marine Park in Brooklyn and on
Randall's Island. The game requires a large circular pitch, which
DaSilva said limits where it can be played. Many local players are
of West Indian, Caribbean or Indian descent.
</P>
<P>
   On DaSilva's recommendation, the match I chose to watch was just
outside the city, in East Rockaway on Long Island. He said the two
best teams in the area would be matched off. I took his word for
it.
</P>
<P>
   DaSilva and a group of other cricket officials patiently
explained the complex rules. What happened was essentially this:
There were two teams in fine, clean uniforms, and a ball, mallets
and collection of sticks known as wickets. Beyond that, I have no
idea.
</P>
<P>
   But what did penetrate my confusion was the grace and peace of
the scene. Players lounged and talked. A breeze blew in off the
Atlantic. Occasionally there would be a flurry of action, and then
peace would return.
</P>
<P>
   I stayed an hour or so; the match would continue another three.
On the drive back to Manhattan, I passed several other matches
under way in Flushing Meadows-Corona Park in Queens. One was
wedged, rather symbolically I thought, between two baseball games.
</P>
<P>
   God Save Bangers and Mash
</P>
<P>
   To end my experiment, I chose the unofficial embassy of all
British expatriates: Tea and Sympathy. This tiny restaurant in the
Village is the city's best-known outpost for complexities of
British cuisine, from bangers and mash (sausage and potatoes) to
shepherd's pie (meat and potatoes).
</P>
<P>
   With only about 10 tables, the restaurant is almost always
packed. But at 6 p.m. I found a spot for myself and two friends,
near a portrait of Queen Elizabeth II.
</P>
<P>
   We started with a delicious Stilton rarebit (melted cheese on
toast). My friends had shandy (ginger ale and beer), while I chose
Ribena (black-currant concentrate and water). Bangers, lamb and
chicken followed, all with a deep mushroom gravy and assisted by
products like Branston Original Pickle and Colman's Classic Mint
Sauce.
</P>
<P>
   As the meal settled, I felt a wash of satisfaction. The weekend
had left me feeling full. I had only sampled the local British
fare, but it was a loverly taste.
</P>
<P>
   And as I pushed away from the table and into the night, I
realized the best part of enjoying England in New York: being able
to walk back home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
