<HEADLINE>
GROWING BIOTECH INDUSTRY IS DRIVEN BY EVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A child born today stands a good chance of living into
the 22nd century.
</P>
<P>
   As futuristic as it sounds, it's a reality. And it's owed, in
part, to a revolution in medical drug discovery that has taken
place over the plast 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   That revolution hasn't happened in big pharmaceutical companies.
It has taken a new type of organization _ one that combines
academic curiosity with entrepreneurial drive, creative thinking
and quick reaction times to make it happen.
</P>
<P>
   And it's given rise to a whole new business sector: The
biotechnology industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biotech companies are the research engines of drug
discovery,'' said Carl Feldbaum, president of the Biotechnology
Industry Organization, a Washington, D.C.-based trade organization
that is bringing 5,000 members of the industry to Seattle this
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not looking for another aspirin, another me-too
drug.,'' Feldbaum said. ``They're seeking cures for diseases where
no therapies exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the life forms that spawned it, the biotechnology industry
in the Seattle area has grown by cell division.
</P>
<P>
   Companies have split apart, budding off new start-ups until
they've colonized a large and complex ecosystem, one that comprises
about 100 companies with more than $200 million in revenues and
more than 7,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   New companies are born at the rate of about six a year, more
than double the rate of a decade ago. About one-third of today's
biotech companies have started up in the past five years, and more
than half of them have either historical or current ties to the
University of Washinwt~9
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
