<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; So, That's Who Kellerman Is! &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to try to get this done 19 years ago, and now I can
hold it in my hand,'' said Herb Gardner. It's been a long wait for
the film with the endless title, but on Tuesday ``Who Is Harry
Kellerman and Why Is He Saying Those Terrible Things About Me?''
will be released by Fox for the first time on tape.
</P>
<P>
   An original and surreal film about the unraveling of the world's
most famous rock composer, portrayed by Dustin Hoffman,
``Kellerman'' is directed by Ulu Grosbard and written by Gardner,
the playwright and director, who adapted it from his short story.
The music is by Shel Silverstein, the writer and cartoonist who
died this month.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971 the film opened to mixed reviews but it drew audiences
substantial enough to lead Gardner to believe that the run might be
extended. ``It belonged to Cinema Center, which was CBS's adventure
in making movies,'' he said. ``We called to find out what their
plans were, and there was no more Cinema Center.'' CBS had suddenly
left the movie business and somehow ``Kellerman,'' physically and
legally, got lost in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner started looking for it in earnest in 1981. ``Nobody knew
who owned it,'' he said. ``It had disappeared.'' He found that odd,
particularly for a film with a major star. Hoffman plays Georgie
Soloway, a man with multiple hit songs, his face on the cover of
Time magazine, all the women he wants (none of whom he can love), a
triplex on top of the General Motors Building and crushing attacks
of loneliness that in his hallucinations have him sailing off his
terrace into the void. ``Send me an overdose of anything,'' he
instructs his pharmacist.
</P>
<P>
   Georgie's imagined plunges land him on the couch of his
psychiatrist (Jack Warden), a man constantly changing identities in
Soloway's fantasies, which include the notion that a man named
Kellerman is spreading vicious untruths about him. ``Picture going
into a studio today and saying we have this part where the analyst
sings like Ray Charles,'' Gardner said.
</P>
<P>
   The movie also stars Barbara Harris, who was nominated for an
Academy Award for her performance as the saddest and most
formidable of Georgie's women. ``For the several scenes she shares
with Hoffman,'' Vincent Canby wrote in The New York Times, ``
`Harry Kellerman' becomes as touching as it is funny. Otherwise
this collapse of identity in a man who apparently has everything
has a flat, tinny sound. But, then, that may be just what the end
of New York will sound like.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually Gardner found the film (CBS had it all along). Last
year ``Kellerman'' played at the Film Forum as part of a double
bill with the acclaimed ``Thousand Clowns,'' adapted by Gardner
from his Broadway play. ``We're always looking for things that
haven't been out there,'' said Bruce Goldstein, the Film Forum's
programming director. ``They don't have to be masterpieces. Just
interesting work.''
</P>
<P>
   And now there is the video. ``We really liked this movie,''
Gardner said. ``We had a good time. We did a number of risky things
and we loved playing with the style and the cutting and the music.
For it to be lost was depressing.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW RELEASES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Saving Private Ryan &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Restoring passion and dignity to the war movie, Steven
Spielberg's film is nominally the story of a detail of soldiers led
by a captain (Tom Hanks, left) on a mission to find a private (Matt
Damon) and return him to a family that has already lost its three
other sons in combat. On a larger level, it salutes the generation
that fought the last great war by telling its story with no
received notions, dramatic or ideological.
</P>
<P>
   At either end are two stupendous battles. In the Normandy surf
and on the beaches, men are blown apart for a totally believable
and intensely uncomfortable half-hour. Between clashes the rhythms
of war and the natures of the men who fight are beautifully caught
by a screenplay that stands aside and lets impressions form
naturally in the hands of an indie-bred cast that includes Edward
Burns, Tom Sizemore, Barry Pepper, Vin Diesel, Jeremy Davies and
Adam Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``As he did in `Schindler's List,''' Janet Maslin wrote in The
New York Times, `` Spielberg uses his preternatural storytelling
gifts to personalize the unimaginable, to create instantly
empathetic characters and to hold an audience spellbound from the
moment the action starts.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -1998. Dreamworks. $107.37. 169 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
Release date: May 25.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Gloria &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Stone brings a honed New Yawk accent to her richly comic
performance as a gutsy ex-con who takes a young boy in tow after
his family is wiped out by mobsters.
</P>
<P>
   The son of an accountant who works for a gangster named Kevin
(Jeremy Northam), young Nicky Nunez (Jean-Luc Figueora) finds his
father dead and himself in the possession of an incriminating
computer disk that Kevin needs back if he is to avoid fatal
retribution at the hands of his own boss, Ruby (George C. Scott).
</P>
<P>
   Together Gloria, a former lover of both Ruby and Kevin and a
long way from her parole officer in Florida, and the boy take
flight in New York City in a ``smoother, funnier, more suspenseful
and more endearing version of the 1980 John Cassavetes film of the
same title'' (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   -1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $105.77. 100 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: May 25.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; In Dreams &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In Neil Jordan's film an artist and mother named Claire Cooper
(Annette Bening) finds herself haunted by the thoughts of a serial
killer of little girls who may be projecting them from the remains
of a town that lies submerged under a reservoir near Claire's
house. At first no one believes her, including her husband (Aidan
Quinn). But then their daughter disappears during a creepy
grade-school staging of ``Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs,''
stirring up ``a nightmare brooding and intuitive enough to recall
the richly textured mysteries of Nicolas Roeg's `Don't Look Now.'''
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   _1999. Dreamworks. $107.37. 99 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time, appeared on television or been on
videocassette in earlier editions.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WINCHELL. Paul Mazursky's film, made for HBO, has plenty of
smoky atmosphere to go with its sharp connections between the
popular-front patriotism of the 30's and 40's and the right-wing
populism of the McCarthy era. As the fast-talking, secret-baring
Hearst columnist, Stanley Tucci nicely captures a sentimental tough
guy who favored his fans against the big shots he raced around
after. ``It's a busy show,'' Walter Goodman wrote in The New York
Times, ``and Tucci carries it along at a vigorous pace.'' 1998.
HBO. $72.12. 108 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   THE SUNSHINE BOYS. Neil Simon mildly updates his play about two
crusty old comedians, with Woody Allen and Peter Falk in the
original Walter Matthau-George Burns roles of Al Lewis and Willie
Clark. This time the pair aren't former vaudevillians but comics
who were in their prime during the ``Ed Sullivan'' years and are
now being asked to appear in a movie. At 60, which he was when this
version was made for television, Allen is a mere stripling in an
uneven production that is, Caryn James wrote in The New York Times,
``a sometimes entertaining curiosity.'' 1997. Hallmark. $19.98. 96
minutes. Release date: May 25.
</P>
<P>
   ROY ORBISON: THE ANTHOLOGY. ``Oh, Pretty Woman,'' ``Only the
Lonely'' and ``Blue Bayou'' are among the songs, and Dwight Yokum,
Bono of U-2 and Robert Plant of Led Zeppelin among the interviewees
in a look back at the country singer and composer. 1998. White
Star. $19.95. 60 minutes. Information: (800) 458-5887. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
