<HEADLINE>
KEY DISCOVERIES IN BIOLOGICAL RESEARCH SPAWNED AN INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The biotech industry evolved out of the primordial
soup of basic biological research in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1970s, biologists made two key discoveries.
Scientists Stanley Cohen of Stanford University and Herbert Boyer
of the University of California-San Francisco, developed a
technique known as recombinant DNA, or gene splicing. For the first
time, researchers could take DNA out of one organism and insert it
into another. For example, they could take the gene for a human
protein, such as insulin, and insert it into the genome of a
bacterium. That new gene would direct the bacteria to produce the
foreign protein, turning the bacteria into tiny drug factories.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, scientist George Kohler developed the
technique for producing monoclonal antibodies _ highly purified
strains of antibodies that acted as molecular probes, letting
scientists fish out selected proteins in the body for study.
</P>
<P>
   Both of these new technologies _ recombinant DNA and monoclonal
antibodies _ were tools in search of applications. Scientists now
had a molecular hammer and saw. Now they had to figure out what to
build and where to build it.
</P>
<P>
   Before 1980, there was no way to capitalize on university
research since most basic scientific research was federally funded
and the government retained title to it. The Bayh-Dole Act of 1980
changed that, giving universities the right to own and profit from
inventions that came out of their research. When the courts upheld
a patent on the Cohen-Boyer recombinant DNA technique _ a key
decision that permitted the patenting of biological molecules and
techniques for the first time _ all the pieces that would give rise
to the biotech industry were in place.
</P>
<P>
   The lightning that sparked these ingredients to life, however,
was the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, a little-known firm called Genentech in South San
Francisco went public.
</P>
<P>
   Its stock went out at $35 a share, shot to $89 a share 20
minutes later, and closed at $70 after ricocheting up and down like
a rock in a tumbler. That first day's trading would come to
symbolize the industry's volatile relationship with the stock
market.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market gave biotech companies a way to get cash for
their discoveries. That gave venture capitalists an incentive to
finance startups, and universities a way to transfer their research
to the real world. The biotech industry was born.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 1703EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
