<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-PATIENT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TREATMENT EASES THE PAIN FOR RHEUMATOID ARTHRITIS SUFFERER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Lisa Caswell was in pain. Excruciating, stabbing pain.
The kind that felt like ``someone taking a hunting knife and
sticking it in your wrist and moving it around.''
</P>
<P>
   Three times she went to the emergency room in the middle of the
night. She was told there was nothing wrong. She was referred to a
psychiatrist. She was taken aside and asked if she was being
beaten.
</P>
<P>
   It took nine months before she learned what was wrong with her.
Caswell, then 33, had rheumatoid arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a shock to me,'' said Caswell, now 41. ``I, like most
other people, didn't realize the mean age of patients is 30 to 50
years old.''
</P>
<P>
   But rheumatoid arthritis, which affects about 2.5 million in the
United States, can be a crippling, even fatal, disease. Traditional
drug therapies have focused on treating symptoms of the disease,
which causes pain, swelling and eventual deterioration of joints
and connective tissue.
</P>
<P>
   As scientists have begun dissecting the underlying disease
process, however, they've discovered new ways to intervene at a
molecular level in the inflammatory process.
</P>
<P>
   Several biotech companies, including Immunex Corp. in Seattle,
and Cypress Bioscience Inc., which has manufacturing facilities in
Redmond, Wash., have developed novel new approaches to treat the
disease based on this new understanding of how the body turns on
its own tissues.
</P>
<P>
   For Caswell, whose disease was particularly aggressive,
participating in clinical trials to test some of these new
arthritis therapies has made a huge difference in her quality of
life.
</P>
<P>
   Before trying experimental treatments, doctors tried every other
drug combination they could think of to help her. At one point, she
was taking high doses of six drugs at the same time, and the side
effects were worsening her physical condition.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile she was losing strength. She couldn't get out of the
bathtub by herself. Her wrists registered ``zero'' in strength
tests. She needed a wheelchair to get around.
</P>
<P>
   That changed after participating in a trial of the Prosorba
column, an innovative blood filtering treatment developed by a
small Redmond, Wash., company and later bought by Cypress
Bioscience. Prosorba was recently approved by the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Mason Research Center in Seattle has been investigating
both how the filtration process appears to interrupt the disease
process, as well as its effects on patients.
</P>
<P>
   The treatment appeared to work for Caswell. After 12 weekly
blood filtration sessions, she felt stronger and was able to pare
back her other medications. Although she still has chronic pain,
she can walk, drive, grocery shop by herself and use a laptop
computer. In July she will defend her doctoral thesis in clinical
psychology with a specialization in helping patients adjust to
traumatic injury or chronic illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life now is a lot closer to normal,'' she said. And she
plans to continue enrolling in research trials as long as she's
able. ``I'll keep doing it,'' she said. ``Until they find a cure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 1703EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4963 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIOTECH-SCIENTIST-SPI     05-20 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-SCIENTIST-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SAVVY SCIENTIST GOT A HIT ON HIS FIRST CAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Steve Gillis has a reason to look satisfied as he
leans back in the boardroom of Corixa Corp., a biotech company he
founded in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen years ago, he worked at a lab bench on the seventh
floor of this same building when it belonged to the Fred Hutchinson
Cancer Research Center.
</P>
<P>
   Today Corixa, which is developing new cancer vaccines and other
therapeutic drugs, takes up four floors in the old Fred Hutchinson
building and last year brought in $18 million in research revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Gillis, 45, made his mark on Seattle's biotech community by
leaving the conventional academic research track to find a new way
to do science. In 1981, he co-founded Immunex Corp., now Seattle's
flagship biotech firm, a move that was considered ``heretical'' at
the time. He left Immunex in 1994 to start Corixa.
</P>
<P>
   And he is still doing things his own way.
</P>
<P>
   Corixa's boardroom, for example, is appointed like a mountain
cabin, complete with fireplace and moose antlers. It's a whimsical
reference to the name of the company, which Gillis, a frustrated
fisherman, named after a fishing fly.
</P>
<P>
   Like fishing, it takes concentration, honed skills and a little
luck to get a yield in the biotech world.
</P>
<P>
   But Gillis waded right in.
</P>
<P>
   Back when Gillis and his colleague, Chris Henney, left Fred
Hutchinson to start Immunex Corp., the biotech industry didn't even
exist.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, industry interest in immunology was running high,
but Fred Hutchinson wasn't used to taking corporate dollars. An
attorney suggested Gillis start his own company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said, `Are you nuts?' '' he said. ``We'd worked so long and
hard to get where we were academically. If we went into industry,
we would be pariahs, second-class (research) citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he thought again. Federal grants were getting harder to
get. A few months later, he and Henney started Immunex with $1
million in seed capital. Immunex is now Seattle's largest biotech
company, with about $243 million in revenue and more than 1,000
employees. It has a variety of drugs in production or under
development for cancer, asthma, rheumatoid arthritis and other
diseases, all bioengineered from molecules in the body's own immune
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started Immunex, we knew several things about science
and zip about business,'' said Gillis. ``We were pretty naive. We
had no idea of what it was like to run a company.''
</P>
<P>
   And if the science guys didn't know much about business, the
business guys they hired knew even less about science.
</P>
<P>
   Immunex's first chief executive officer ``didn't know a T-cell
from a bowling ball,' Gillis said. ``But that was OK back then.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to invent things that had never been invented
before, and we couldn't prove existed,'' he said. ``No one had even
cloned a gene for an immune system hormone yet, but we were going
to use this knowledge to somehow make people better.''
</P>
<P>
   And no one had any idea what it was going to take to bring a
drug from the lab bench to the market.
</P>
<P>
   The early biotech companies wanted to become stand-alone drug
companies that discovered, developed, manufactured and marketed
their own products. That approach, however, required about $1
billion to pull off.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Gillis started Corixa, investors were a lot more
sophisticated _ and realistic _ about the costs of running a
biotech business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It caused us to think about a different way to be a company.
We're going to discover things,'' he said. ``Then we're going to
license away (our technology) to other pharmaceutical companies.
That way we're not going to burn tremendous amounts of cash, so we
don't have to go to the (stock) market and raise $600 million.''
And there are other differences running a second-generation biotech
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's far more competitive today _ far less room to make
mistakes,'' he said. But the goal is the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we tried to do at Immunex and still doing at Corixa is
trying to make products that will help people based on the science
of immunology.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
