<HEADLINE>
A MARRIAGE OF BIOLOGY AND COMPUTERS ON THRESHOLD OF NEW CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Seattle scientists are aiming to grab the reins of one
of the hottest bandwagons in biotechnology and medicine _
bioinformatics.
</P>
<P>
   Think of a marriage of biology and computers. That's
bioinformatics.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates describes the vision this way:
``The two technologies that will dominate the 21st century
scientifically and industrially are biotechnology and information
technologies.''
</P>
<P>
   Its promise is to genetically assess individuals and tailor
drugs or therapy to best fit them. That's not yet possible, but the
history of medicine shows that benefits accrue en route.
</P>
<P>
   One of the leading advocates of bioinformatics is the University
of Washington's Dr. Leroy Hood, recruited to Seattle from the
California Institute of Technology in 1991 after Gates donated $12
million to create a molecular biotechnology department at the UW
School of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Hood, the UW's William Gates III professor of biomedical
sciences, is a pioneer of automated computerized gene sequencing _
a method for identifying genes. He's a grand vision guy with a
tendency to launch biotechnology companies and then move on to the
next interesting conceptual application.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of the speakers at the international Bio '99
conference, talking about the ``Genomic Information Revolution.''
The conference this week was attended by 5,000 scientists and
industry representatives from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Hood's latest endeavor is the UW's new Institute for
Quantitative Systems Biology, a public-private venture intended to
exploit the bioinformatics gold mine produced by increasing amounts
of genetic information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biology today is really all about information,'' Hood said.
There are different kinds of data, he said, beginning with the
linear type represented by the DNA helix _ a long, twisted double
chain of units called nucleotide base pairs that make up the
genetic codes of living creatures.
</P>
<P>
   If computers are a two-unit, or digital, system of information,
DNA is a four-unit information system. All the genetic information
in our body is built from combinations of four units, chemical
bases called guanine, cytosine, thymine and adenine (aka G,C,T and
A).
</P>
<P>
   There are about 3 billion of these G,C,T and A bases in the
human genetic code and the nationwide Human Genome Project is a
massive federal effort aimed at identifying the sequence of all
these bases.
</P>
<P>
   But the linear, sequential way of thinking about genetic
information _ in which a string of thousands of G-C-T-A units make
a gene that then makes a protein which in turn makes something
happen biologically _ is becoming outdated, Hood said.
</P>
<P>
   Bioinformatics, he said, is about thinking in terms of multiple
genes and proteins operating in networks and feedback loops _ with
each gene or protein seen in the context of a web of interaction.
It's about looking at biology in three dimensions, Hood said, or
even as a four-dimensional system that incorporates the element of
time into a new and more complex assessment of the workings of
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a systems approach,'' Hood said.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds great, but how's it done?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an enormous puzzle,'' said Dr. Richard Karp, a UW
professor of computer science and an internationally known expert
in computational biology. Karp acknowledged that the scientific
community is venturing into uncharted waters in bioinformatics. The
exploration is guided by the assumption that powerful computational
tools applied to this massive amount of genetic information will
create an entirely new way of looking at the human body.
</P>
<P>
   But we haven't quite glimpsed the new paradigm, Karp said. ``We
just don't have enough information yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lee Hartwell, president of the Fred Hutchinson Cancer
Research Center in Seattle, also thinks bioinformatics will provide
us a new way to look at the body. Hartwell is an internationally
known geneticist and also a genetic peculiarity.
</P>
<P>
   And so are you, he'd tell you.
</P>
<P>
   Hartwell's particular peculiarity is that he's
sucrose-intolerant. He self-diagnosed this rare intolerance to the
sugar found in beets or sorghum decades ago and now eats
accordingly. More importantly, he points to his peculiarity as
evidence for the need to ``individualize'' medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of activity right now trying to link genes to
disease,'' Hartwell said. ``But even though we all have the same
genes, they can come in different forms.''
</P>
<P>
   Medicine today is based on the clinical trial, he said, which
has been an effective tool used to find the best ``magic bullet''
or drug with the best therapeutic effect for the most people.
</P>
<P>
   The current effort to track down genes that cause disease is
also often a magic bullet approach and has been successful in cases
where disorders appear to be largely the result of one
malfunctioning gene, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But it now appears that most diseases or problems are the result
of many genes and proteins gone awry. Hartwell said medicine needs
to move beyond finding therapies that work for most people most of
the time and toward a a biological model that recognizes our
genetic individuality.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 100,000 genes operating in the human body,
Hartwell said, and each can differ slightly _ a usually benign
variation known as a ``polymorphism.'' If you consider all of the
polymorphic combinations, he said, ``it amounts to more than all
the atoms in the universe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that each of us is absolutely unique,'' Hartwell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stephen Friend is one of those attempting to reap benefits
from bioinformatics. On leave from Fred Hutchinson, Friend is
president and chief scientific officer for Kirkland, Wash.-based
Rosetta Inpharmatics.
</P>
<P>
   The company was created to exploit one offspring of this
marriage between computers and biology _ the biochip. The biochip,
or the ``DNA microarray,'' is literally a silicon wafer with
hundreds or even thousands of DNA pieces embedded in it.
</P>
<P>
   A number of companies, including Rosetta's California-based
partner Affymetrix, have manufactured these biochips, also known as
microarrays, for years. (Some prefer the term DNA microarray to
emphasize that the biochip isn't, like a computer chip, performing
a function. It's more like a chart allowing a simultaneous read on
thousands of genes or pieces of DNA.)
</P>
<P>
   Rosetta, Friend explained, is using the biochip approach to make
drug discovery more efficient. One way to do this, he said, is to
look at how a drug acts within a network of genes and proteins that
mimic the body's biochemistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some drugs work well in some patients and not so well in
others,'' he said. If a biochip can be constructed representing
each patient's complete genetic makeup, he said the drug can be
tested in each one and compared to determine how it affects any of
a hundred gene or protein products.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any single gene that changes may or may not be that
significant,'' Friend said. It's the overall ``pattern of
expression'' of all the genes and proteins that can be used to
better identify drug targets, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Blanchard, formerly part of Hood's department at the UW,
invented the technology that allows Rosetta to look for these gene
or protein patterns.
</P>
<P>
   David Baker, an assistant professor of biochemistry and
bioengineering at the UW, also is digging deeply into
bioinformatics.
</P>
<P>
   Baker and his colleagues are trying to take genetic sequence
information and, with computational help, analyze it to try and
predict the shapes and functions of various proteins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Proteins are basically the body's minimachines in the cell and
their structure is important to what they do,'' he said. It's a
three-dimensional structure, Baker said, where even minor changes _
or errors _ can profoundly affect function.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle is a hotbed for all types of bioinformatics work, he
said. As evidence of this, he noted that the nation's top
post-doctoral fellowship program in computational biology _
sponsored by the U.S. Department of Energy and the Sloan Foundation
_ awarded nine fellowships this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four of them were awarded here in Seattle,'' Baker said.
``This is a new area that's growing extremely fast nationally and
we're on top of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
