<HEADLINE>
THE BIOTECH PROMISE - CURES AND QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The next 50 years of biomedical research will bring
unprecedented advances in curing diseases as well as increasing
social questions about ethics and costs, a panel of biotech experts
said Monday at the opening of BIO '99.
</P>
<P>
   More than 5,000 members of the biotech industry are meeting in
Seattle this week for the annual conference of biotech leaders from
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Progress in biomedical research will happen much more quickly in
the next 50 years because of new tools, especially those merging
computer sciences with genetics, said Lee Hartwell, president and
director of the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center in Seattle.
``We will have drugs for everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The power of computers will give scientists the ability to
predict the three-dimensional structures and functions of proteins
based on their genetic sequences, an ability that will help them
design better medications to intervene in disease processes. It
also will help reduce the dependence on animal testing, scientists
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be enormous advances in public health,'' said
Kathryn Zoon, director of the Center for Biologics Evaluation and
Research at the U.S. Food and Drug Administration. ``How we pay for
it is a major issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Another concern is how to make sure such advances are available
in developing countries, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Chronic diseases, such as cancer, diabetes, heart disease and
others, cost the United States about $600 billion a year, said
George Rathmann, chairman of ICOS Corp. in Bothell and one of the
industry's early pioneers.
</P>
<P>
   New drugs and treatments will cut suffering and eliminate some
costs associated with diseases, but those costs will be replaced by
the cost of the drugs and treatments themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can eliminate suffering, then we ought to be prepared to
pay the price,'' Rathmann said.
</P>
<P>
   Eliminating diseases poses other societal problems as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next 50 years will be mind boggling,'' said Dr. Edwin
Krebs, a University of Washington professor who won the Nobel Prize
for medicine in 1992. ``Life expectancy will greatly increase, and
we may start doing something with life span.''
</P>
<P>
   That poses a new challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is things wear out,'' said Michael Smith,
professor of biotechnology at the University of British Columbia.
``The spare parts issue is going to have to be dealt with. The
question is will it be with our own tissue, or tissue of other
animals?''
</P>
<P>
   Such questions will require public participation and debate, the
scientists said.
</P>
<P>
   And that will require an increasing level of scientific
literacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The awareness of science is quite primitive,'' Rathmann said.
The industry has a ``huge responsibility over the next 50 years to
help get information to the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartwell agreed that education is one of the top challenges for
the industry. To survive, the industry needs both a highly trained
labor force and a scientifically literate public, he said. ``Most
of the public has not even had a high school biology class.''
</P>
<P>
   People need to be able to sort out science fact from science
fiction to be able to make informed decisions about the uses of
technology, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   People can watch ``Star Wars'' and tell where real engineering
stops and fantasy engineering takes off, but they have less ability
to discriminate between reality and fantasy fears in biology, he
said. ``We need a scientifically literate citizenry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 1706EDT &QL; 
