<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRISH STYLE: A `STEPSON' GAINS FAVOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Va., Mich.)   (af)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ireland seems to be entering a golden age. There is the promise
of peace. The country is in the midst of a boom: the so-called
Celtic Tiger's economy is growing at a faster rate than Europe's.
Many computer companies have large operations there, and Dublin has
a new International Financial Services Center, where banks like
Chase are congregating.
</P>
<P>
   The new prosperity is fueling the market for houses, especially
grand old mansions in the countryside, and the Irish art and
antiques to fill them. All of which has been great news for auction
houses and dealers in Irish antiques on both sides of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The property market in Ireland is red hot,'' said Graham
Child, a furniture specialist at Sotheby's, which is holding an
``Irish Sale'' today in London. ``A lot of the old, decaying houses
are being pulled back. The economy has led to the creation of
wealth and a desire to spend the wealth on national things.''
</P>
<P>
   The 405-lot Irish sale has some large 18th- and 19th-century
mahogany dining tables, chairs and sideboards; a rare pair of oval
mirrors with borders decorated with facet-cut studs of blue and
clear glass (expected to sell for $8,000 to $11,200); a circa 1755
architect's table and a graceful mid-18th-century mahogany card
table with a drawer and a typically Irish carved shell on the front
(estimate: $3,200 to $4,000).
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of Irish furniture and pictures are going back to
Ireland,'' said Hugo Swire of Sotheby's London. ``The people who
are restoring the big Irish houses have limitless budgets. The
problem is there's not an enormous amount of supply.''
</P>
<P>
   The golden age of Irish furniture-making began about 1720, when
mahogany from the West Indies and South America reached Ireland,
and ended about 1840. The most popular pieces are 18th-century
Irish Georgian antiques. They can be distinguished by their
weathered patina, dense grain, quirky dimensions and deep carvings
of masks and hairy paw feet.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the furniture was blackened with polish to match the
very dark bog oak, native to Ireland, that was commonly used in
17th-century furniture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Irish furniture is often considered the slightly crazed
stepson of English furniture,'' said Clinton Howell, a Manhattan
dealer. ``I have Irish clients who fly over here every year looking
for Irish antiques. Right now I have only one piece left.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a George II mahogany console table with a breche violette
marble top. The apron has elegant gadroon molding and a carved
acanthus; the cabriole legs have carved knees. Its price tag,
$87,500, is hefty, but only last January Christie's New York sold
an Irish George II mahogany side table, circa 1740, with a large
lion mask for $96,000, against an estimate of $40,000 to $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost all our Irish furniture is gone,'' said John Snead, of
John and Patricia Snead, private dealers in McLean, Va., who
specialize in Irish long-case clocks. ``I recently sold a fine
Dublin clock to an American collector for about $15,000.''
</P>
<P>
   But the surge in demand for Irish antiques is fairly recent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't sell Irish furniture for large sums five years
ago,'' said Desmond Guinness, an Irish author and connoisseur of
houses and antiques. ``Now it's being avidly collected.'' In 1958
Guinness co-founded the Irish Georgian Society with his fellow
Irishman Desmond FitzGerald, the 29th Knight of Glin, to rescue
decaying Irish houses.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday Guinness gave a party for Kindel Furniture of Grand
Rapids, Mich., at Leixlip Castle, his home in County Kildare. A
passionate patron of all things Irish, Guinness agreed to let
Kindel sell its reproductions of 22 fine Irish antiques in his
Gothic gate lodge as a way for his organization to raise money to
restore other Irish houses.
</P>
<P>
   Chantal O'Sullivan, an Irish dealer with galleries in New York,
Dublin and Kenmare, said: ``For a long time no one wanted Irish
antiques, and they were really collectible. When Irish things
became more fashionable, they became harder and harder to find.''
</P>
<P>
   She is partly responsible for that. An American magazine
recently photographed David Mlinaric, a top British decorator, at
her gallery.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish government gives tax breaks to artists of all kinds:
musicians, filmmakers, artists and writers. Ronnie Wood of the
Rolling Stones, members of the band Simple Minds and actors like
Jeremy Irons, Mia Farrow, Anjelica Huston, Daniel Day-Lewis, Liam
Neeson and Miranda Richardson all have houses in Ireland now.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. O'Sullivan, who has dined with President and Mrs. Clinton in
Dublin and Washington, sells mostly through New York designers like
Thierry Despont, Bunny Williams, Thomas Jayne, Mario Buatta, Scott
Salvator, Glenn Gissler and David Anthony Easton.
</P>
<P>
   She currently has for sale an Irish mantelpiece made of Italian
marble ($95,000), a 14-foot-by-5-foot mahogany library table (also
$95,000) and an Irish Georgian mahogany blanket chest with carved
shells and its original brasses, circa 1770 ($22,000).
</P>
<P>
   Several of her tables have carved shells or masks. ``The masks
were carved in the likeness of the absent landlords of the house,''
Ms. O'Sullivan said. ``That's why some have hairy faces. It meant
the owner had thick whiskers. If he were mean, the face would be
ugly, too.''
</P>
<P>
   A prominent Paris dealer, Ariane Dandois, said: ``Everyone is
interested in Irish furniture now. It's English furniture with
fantasy. The shapes are extravagant. It's more macho than English
furniture.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dandois offers a rare set of eight Irish Regency giltwood
armchairs made in Dublin about 1820. The arched crest-rails are
carved with lions drinking from a fountain. The armrests have
eagle-head supports. She has attributed the chairs to a
furniture-maker from Italy, James Del Vecchio Sr., who immigrated
to Dublin in the 1790s.
</P>
<P>
   When Mrs. Dandois, who normally sells 18th-century palace
furniture to the richest clients on earth, starts selling Irish
antiques, it is a clear sign that Irish furniture has joined the
top ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Dillingham in San Francisco and two New York dealers, the Newel
Art Galleries and Philip Colleck, also sell Irish furniture.
</P>
<P>
   There are two unrelated indications of Irish chic. On May 7, the
actress Julia Roberts was one of about 250 people at a book party
at Christie's to celebrate ``West of Ireland Summers: Recipes and
Memories from an Irish Childhood'' (Roberts Rinehart, Boulder,
Colo.), a new book by Tamasin Day-Lewis, sister of the actor.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Roberts had such a good time with the Irish guests that she
was an hour late for dinner with a major fashion magazine editor.
</P>
<P>
   Clue No. 2: The Lower East Side Tenement Museum in Manhattan is
adding an Irish immigrant family apartment to its Jewish and
Italian ones. And this just six months after President Clinton
declared the museum's tenement building a National Historic Site.
Maybe he knew that the White House was designed in 1792 by an Irish
immigrant, James Hoban.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
