<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, May 21, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Scattered heavy thunderstorms will douse parts of the lower Ohio
and middle Mississippi Valleys as a weakening cold front, bolstered
by a trailing jet stream disturbance, lifts humid air from the Gulf
of Mexico. Severe weather is unlikely, but downpours from storms
could result in a quick inch or two of rain in some spots.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, funnel clouds were spotted over the Everglades
National Park in Monroe County in southwest Florida as intense
thunderstorms erupted along a boundary marking the leading edge of
the sea breeze from the Gulf of Mexico. Friday, these sea-breeze
fronts will again become active along the Gulf and Atlantic Coasts
as widely separated thunderstorms produce downpours and frequent
cloud-to-ground lightning strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, thunderstorms will flare over the northern high
plains from western Nebraska and eastern Wyoming to the western
Dakotas and eastern Montana. Here, moist surface winds from the
south-southeast will ascend the westward sloping terrain and then
be further lifted by a compact but potent jet stream disturbance.
</P>
<P>
   Severe weather is possible, with the greatest risk posed in
Montana and North Dakota near the path of the disturbance. Isolated
supercells, which are individual, massive thunderstorms, may spawn
a few tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   Spotty sprinkles or isolated light showers may develop across
parts of southern California as a pool of cold air 18,000 feet
aloft stalls over the region. Meanwhile, sunny, seasonably warm
weather will prevail across much of the Northeast and Middle
Atlantic Seaboards. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Miami Ice
</P>
<P>
   Nickel-sized hailstones pelted parts of Miami on Wednesday as an
intense thunderstorm erupted over south Florida. Hail is rather
rare in Florida, particularly in southern counties. Hailstones
often form in the cold upper reaches of Florida thunderstorms where
they are suspended by strong updrafts of air. However, on descent
toward earth, hailstones typically melt before reaching the ground
as they pass warm tropical air at lower altitudes. On Wednesday,
however, a pocket of dry air aloft encouraged evaporation of
meltwater, allowing hailstones to cool and thereby survive to the
ground.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 1712EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4998 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DRAWING-EXHIBITS-2     05-20 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DRAWING-EXHIBITS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS INTIMATE AS THE TOUCH OF AN ARTIST  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)   By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It may or may not have anything to do with the
arrival of spring, but Manhattan has broken out in some superb
exhibitions of modern drawings _ arguably the most overtly
delectable of all art forms.
</P>
<P>
   What can compare?
</P>
<P>
   Drawings in general are like love letters. Personal in touch and
feeling, physically delicate, they reflect an artist's gifts, goals
and influences in the most intimate terms with a minimum of fuss,
muss and production costs. The irresistibility quotient of drawings
compares favorably with those of puppies, kittens or young
children; the instinct is to pick them up, stare at them intently
and ooh and aah. Which is not to say that well-made drawings can't
be imposing or even intimidating, but rather to suggest that they
encourage a kind of emotional liberty and desire for closeness that
paintings and sculptures may not.
</P>
<P>
   All this can go double for drawings made during the last 100
years or so, when the fall of the academy placed a new premium on
formal invention and personal expression. Drawing became as never
before a direct extension of an artist's signature and very nervous
system, and this freedom widened the perception of the medium
itself to include linear expressions of all kinds. Thus it was that
Indian miniatures, Chinese calligraphy and African textiles began
to exert an influence on modern drawing.
</P>
<P>
   Three large exhibitions of mostly 20th-century works form the
basis of this springtime drawing revel. These shows overlap at
regular intervals, creating an engrossing system of
cross-references, mutual illuminations and, at times, reciprocal
criticism. But even more notable are their differences, which stem
primarily from contrasting forms of ownership, connoisseurship and,
in a way, passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Collecting in Depth: Drawings by Grosz, Schwitters, Ernst and
Klee'' at the Museum of Modern Art comes entirely from the museum's
own collection, formed over the years by successive generations of
drawing curators.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, ``New York Collects: Drawings and Watercolors,
1900-1950,'' at the Pierpont Morgan Library, culls more than 140
drawings from 73 private collections in a city where the building
of such collections can amount to a blood sport. Many of these have
not been exhibited in New York for years, if ever.
</P>
<P>
   But the Drawing Center in SoHo has taken the most unusual tack.
``Drawn From Artists' Collections'' presents 175 drawings and
paintings on paper, some of which date from the 19th century or
earlier or come from non-Western cultures (Tantric paintings and
Chinese calligraphy).
</P>
<P>
   All have been selected from the collections of 18 well-known
contemporary artists, among them Jasper Johns, Julian Schnabel,
Eric Fischl, Sol LeWitt, Terry Winters, Roy Lichtenstein and
Elizabeth Murray. It is possible to imagine a group of artists who
are less homogeneously rich, famous and from New York, but the
resulting show is one of the season's most thought provoking.
Museum of Modern Art
</P>
<P>
   ``Collecting in Depth,'' at the Modern diverges courageously
from the museum's famous preference for French modernism, only to
demonstrate the pervasiveness of its influence. Featuring the
museum's holdings in work by four major German-speaking artists, it
manages to be both exemplary and a little muted and academic in
mood. It's hard to know what would have jazzed it up, perhaps other
works by these artists, or the inclusion of different artists, Max
Beckmann, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Still, basic principles that reverberate through all three shows
are laid out here. First, the modern drawing is established as a
site of endless experimentation and invention that result in its
self-sufficiency as an art form. Equally evident: modernism's
emphasis on form and physical process has provided a foundation
artists of every inclination could build on.
</P>
<P>
   The Modern's show features 14 to 26 works by each artist,
installed in separate galleries, in an order that creates a kind of
sandwich of contrasting sensibilities. First and last are the
drawings of George Grosz and Paul Klee, who explore the expressive
and physical possibilities of line and ground the gridlike
scaffolding of Cubism in realities of their own choosing. For Grosz
this reality was social and political.
</P>
<P>
   His fine insinuating lines repeatedly get at the heart of the
hypocrisy of life in the years following Germany's defeat in World
War I, mercilessly skewering the venality of bureaucrats, generals
and the well-to-do. In ``The End of the Day,'' the weight and
vibration of Grosz's line gives each of four exhausted factory
workers a distinct emotional character and contrasts their
silhouettes with the nearly abstract geometry of the factory
complex behind them.
</P>
<P>
   While remarkably close to Grosz's line in its fineness, Klee's
begins in the interior reality of fantasy and the unconscious,
progresses to some kind of legible sign or hieroglyph and then
lands with dazzling grace on paper to create a visual reality
unlike any other. Klee's arsenal of visual conjurings and physical
effects seems to have been inexhaustible. In ``Errand Boy,'' one of
the less familiar works here, a figure holding a package is
outlined in a heavy austere calligraphy of gray wash that is then
filled with irrepressible effusions of fine pastel stripes and
grids. It's sort of like watching Mozart embellish Beethoven.
</P>
<P>
   In between, Kurt Schwitters and Max Ernst take Cubist collage
and run with it, again in seemingly opposite directions. With
discarded ticket stubs, labels, buttons and other bits of detritus,
Schwitters' Merz collages invented a small-scale formalism that was
resolutely anchored in the real world. By recycling the most minute
ephemera of everyday life, his carefully composed surfaces
commemorate a touching array of human activities, exchanges and
points of contact _ the mail, movies, trains, cafe life.
</P>
<P>
   Ernst's appetite was more for found images than stray bits of
printed matter and colored paper. Pasting cutout parts of half-tone
images onto larger half-tone images, or drawing on
chromolithographs, he cobbled together a universe as fully imagined
as Klee's, and quite a bit scarier. Sometimes he evoked German
militarism with a bitterness only slightly more veiled than
Grosz's, as in the tanklike monument of ``Farewell My Beautiful
Land of Marie Laurencin,'' of 1919. More often, he evoked the
natural world in unnatural disorder, like the strung-together
organs of a small, colorful collage whose extravagant,
exquisite-corpse title reads: ``Stratified Rocks, Nature's Gift of
Gneiss Lava Iceland Moss 2 Kinds of Lungwort 2 Kinds of Ruptures of
the Perineum Growths of the Heart,'' of 1920.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Pierpont Morgan Library
</P>
<P>
   Ravishing is a fitting sound bite for ``New York Collects,''
which was organized by William M. Griswold, head of the Department
of Drawings and Prints at the Morgan, and Carol Selle, a collector
and an independent curator. Sheet for sheet it is the strongest of
the three shows. It includes drawings of near legendary status,
like Dali's disturbing nude-as-furniture, ``City of Drawers'';
Willem de Kooning's ethereal 1940-41 portrait of his wife, Elaine
de Kooning, and Picasso's crystalline ``Man With a Pipe'' of 1912,
a charcoal in which Analytic Cubism readies itself for the collaged
planes of Synthetic Cubism. An example of the latter, Georges
Braque's ``Fruit Dish and Glass,'' also 1912, hangs next to it.
</P>
<P>
   There are also works that are virtually unknown, including a
Cubist gouache by Aleksandr Rodchenko that has been exhibited only
once, in Moscow in 1916, and a haunting self-portrait from 1945 by
Giorgio de Chirico that is making its public debut.
</P>
<P>
   This show skims across the surface of modernism like a train
whizzing past wondrous cities, and yet nearly every drawing can
prompt you to pull the emergency cord and shred your itinerary.
There are shimmering Cezanne watercolors, tour de force selections
of Matisse and Beckmann, a group of three small collages by Juan
Gris. Five magnificent works by Klee top off the Modern's group.
Especially striking is ``Snow Hens,'' whose glowing spots of color
and lines folding to form birds and landscape were last exhibited
in Munich in 1950. Debts are acknowledged: Picasso, Matisse and
Gris, for example all send love letters to Cezanne.
</P>
<P>
   There are isolated wonders: Georges Rouault's ``Old Clown'' of
1904, with its dark, powerful stillness; a mad self-portrait by
Christian Schad and Oskar Kokoschka's circa 1913 '`Encounter,'' in
which the space between nude lovers is charged with dark lashing
strokes that suggest the intensity of their connection but also
recast the scene as an Expulsion from the Garden of Eden.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some Morgan efforts, this exhibition does not peter out
in the back hallway on the way to `` Morgan's Study,'' as the floor
plan calls it. Its head of steam holds up until the end, a 1951
Pollock drawing in black and orange ink on rice paper in which the
marks resemble sputtering embers arranged in a subtle grid.
</P>
<P>
   Back here hang some of the best drawings you may ever see by
Theodore Roszak, Henry Moore, Lucian Freud, Jean Dubuffet and Wols.
Don't miss Roberto Matta's colorful 1937 drawing of Picassoid
figures in a landscape cloaked in a dense net of lines, or Otto
Dix's 1920 ``Skat Players,'' an acrid, velvety ink-and-pencil
drawing of three card-playing war veterans with barely four limbs
among them.
</P>
<P>
   The Morgan has owned 20th-century works for nearly half the
century, but this is its first exhibition of the art of its own
time. To turn to 20th-century art in 1999 is to take a wait-and-see
attitude to the limit. Hopefully the second half of the century
will be tackled sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing Center
</P>
<P>
   ``Artists have more interesting reasons for owning art than rich
people,'' was the way one person, an artist, bluntly characterized
the attractions of ``Drawn From Artists' Collections.'' Artists
acquire art almost as naturally as they make it. The work of other
artists provides them with guidance, sustenance, inspiration,
like-minded company, reflections of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   When they're young and poor, they acquire work by trading with
other young, poor artists or by following their eyes to things that
cost little because no one else is interested in them. (In this
show, only Elizabeth Murray's drawings reflect such a prefame
collecting ritual.) When they can afford to buy what they want (or
trade with interested dealers), all kinds of other forces are set
in motion. Their acquisitions reflect ego, ambition and reverence
as well as tastes so particular that an artist's choosing can
change our understanding of the artist whose work is chosen.
</P>
<P>
   These factors make this show a highly charged, somewhat
voyeuristic affair. The works have been selected by Ann Philbin,
former director of the Drawing Center and director of the Hammer
Museum of Art at the University of California at Los Angeles, and
Jack Shear, an independent curator and artist, undoubtedly with
some input from the artists themselves. The works are grouped
according to owner, which creates the feeling of discrete, somewhat
competitive little exhibitions. One can, for example, move from
group to group, comparing one artist's Matisse or Picasso to
another's.
</P>
<P>
   Some groups are very diverse. Johns' display, the exhibition's
most spectacular, includes astounding drawings by Gauguin, Cezanne,
Redon and Seurat but also a gnarly little self-portrait by Kim
Jones, a performance-sculptor whose alter ego is Mud Man.
</P>
<P>
   The works from Helen Frankenthaler's collection range from a
collage by Robert Motherwell, to whom she was once married, to a
highly finished sketch of horses' rumps by Theodore Gericault to a
relaxed charcoal of a tree by Corot that must be the closest the
French painter ever came to making a Frankenthaler.
</P>
<P>
   In other instances, artists seem to repeatedly home in on
qualities basic to their own work. Thus drawings owned by Alex Katz
share an element of Katzian distillation and include a particularly
minimal landscape by Marsden Hartley. Most of the drawings owned by
Ellsworth Kelly emphasize a cool linearity, including an
uncharacteristic work by Ferdinand Hodler that repeats the form of
an embracing couple with almost line-for-line precision.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, a single focus prevails. From the collection of the
painter Helen Marden come a series of 18th-century Tantric images
notable for their saturated colors and schematized depictions of
sexuality. Georg Baselitz lends 14 drawings by the German artist
Carl Fredrik Hill (1849-1911), whose small awkward landscapes have
a visionary intensity.
</P>
<P>
   This same intensity prevails in the 14 landscape drawings by the
self-taught American artist Joseph E. Yoakum (1886-1972), from the
collection that the Chicago Imagist Roger Brown bequeathed to the
School of the Art Institute of Chicago. One can imagine that Yoakum
and Hill would have found great comfort in each other's work and
maybe even arranged a trade.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
