<HEADER>
A5007 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-POLL-JUVENILE-     05-20 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-POLL-JUVENILE-CRIME-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
 &HT;    
 &HT;      POLL: 61% FAVOR JUVENILE CRIME PREVENTION
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Ron Eckstein  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, May 19 -- Americans overwhelmingly believe the best
way to fight juvenile crime is to put resources into preventive
measures rather than punishment, according to a report done for the
Children's Court Centennial Committee (CCCC).
</P>
<P>
   CCCC is a Chicago-based coalition of juvenile justice
professionals, child welfare advocates and foundations formed to
commemorate the creation of the world's first juvenile court in
Cook County in 1899.
</P>
<P>
   As the U.S. Senate debated juvenile justice legislation which
would increase the penalties for minors who commit violent crimes,
Judge Nancy Sidote Salyers, presiding judge of the Cook County
Juvenile Court's Child Protection Division, was on Capitol Hill to
present CCCC's report to Illinois lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-one percent of adults surveyed said prevention was the
best way to counter juvenile crime, compared to 21 percent who
favored rehabilitation for juvenile offenders and 12 percent who
favored harsher punishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can stop it before it starts, there is no need for
other (measures),'' said one upscale suburban white male who was
surveyed. ``You have to stop them before they hit the criminal
path, and that's when they've got the best chance at making it in
society.''
</P>
<P>
   The research was paid for by the Chicago Community Trust, the
William T. Grant Foundation and the Woods Fund of Chicago on behalf
of CCCC. Peter Hart Research Associates, a Democratic polling firm,
and Public Opinion Strategies, a Republican polling firm, conducted
telephone surveys with 1,059 adults nationwide from December 7-17,
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``People assume the public wants to lock up children in order to
get rid of these problems, but we found that is not the case,''
Salyers explained. ``People want to make sure that when laws are
passed and policies are enacted that they really help children.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey found most adults to believe violent youth offenders
can be rehabilitated. Sixty-three percent agreed that ``all youth
are capable of recovery and redemption, because children are young
and constantly changing, so we should not give up even on those who
have committed violent crimes,'' while 27 percent agreed ``it is
too late to rehabilitate some youth who are more dangerous or
multiple offenders, and the best solution is prison, since
punishment is the only way to send them a message.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one percent of adults said they support the death penalty
for extremely violent juvenile offenders, while 61 percent support
capital punishment for adults.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the survey of adults, 522 Chicago-area high
school students were interviewed in November 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-seven percent of the teens said building more community
centers where kids could play sports and participate in other group
activities would make a really big difference to at-risk kids.
Fifty-seven percent said sending kids convicted of crimes to boot
camp would straighten them out.
</P>
<P>
   More teens found alcohol (55 percent) to be a serious problem
among their peers than drugs (44 percent), exposure to bad
influences (44 percent), being depressed (40 percent), violence in
schools (28 percent) abusive homes (26 percent) dangerous
neighborhoods (22 percent) or involvement with gangs (21 percent).
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
