<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5022 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MENTORS-$ADV23-COX     05-20 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENTORS-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DELAWARE LEADS NATIONAL WAVE OF SWIFT, CHEAP MENTORING
 &HT;    700&AMP;adds. For release Sunday, May 23.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. _ The nationwide growth of mentoring programs
came home to Daryl Burton on a gusty morning this spring when the
sixth-grader convinced his mother he was too sick to go to school.
</P>
<P>
   About two hours later, a state trooper drove a dark silver van
onto Jefferson Street and parked in front of Daryl's home. Gov. Tom
Carper of Delaware hopped out, walked up onto the porch and
knocked.
</P>
<P>
   When Daryl answered the door, Carper looked down and asked,
``What are you doing here? You are supposed to be in school.''
</P>
<P>
   Carper is part of a growing movement by supporters of
traditional mentoring programs to supplement them with new methods
that work more swiftly and cheaply. The movement is being largely
driven by the business community, partly to help assure a steady
future flow of well-educated workers.
</P>
<P>
   On this morning, Daryl's mother let them clear off a corner of
the kitchen table and hold their weekly half-hour mentoring session
there, instead of in Daryl's middle school.
</P>
<P>
   Daryl, 12, who had been a third-grader reading below the
first-grade level when Carper became his mentor three years ago,
put a biography of basketball legend Michael Jordan on the table,
and began to read aloud.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the best he ever read,'' Carper said, as he shared that
moment with thousands of other cheering mentors Wednesday night at
the University of Delaware. Carper said that when Daryl walked him
back to the van, they were both ``walking on air.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Carper, Delaware and its mentors have built a model
program for other states to follow,'' said retired Gen. Colin
Powell, a youth advocate who choppered in to congratulate them on
approaching the governor's goal of creating ``an army of 10,000
volunteer mentors'' in the state by next year.
</P>
<P>
   Under traditional programs run by groups like Big Brothers and
Big Sisters, potential mentors undergo elaborate background checks,
are carefully matched with a particular child, and obtain guidance
throughout their mentorship from case workers and consultants.
Typically, a mentor and child meet for several hours a week for
several years.
</P>
<P>
   In most of today's programs, volunteers make a commitment for a
single school year. They promise to come to a school or a youth
club once a week to coach, tutor, chat with or play with a child
for 30 minutes to an hour. The only background check is to find out
whether they have a criminal record.
</P>
<P>
   Financially, the big advantage is that the $1,000 average cost
of supporting a traditional mentorship drops under the lightweight
programs to somewhere between $350 and $600. On a practical level,
it is easier and quicker for the new programs to recruit
volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   In sheer numbers, the tally is highest in California, with
209,000 mentors _ about one for every 27 public-school students.
</P>
<P>
   But with a ratio of about one mentor for every 11 public-school
students, Delaware now ``leads the nation on a per capita basis,''
Carper said.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts, Ohio, Texas and Connecticut also have
fast-growing programs with strong backing by businesses and civic
organizations, and many states are getting such efforts under way.
</P>
<P>
   Because so many children need one-to-one contact with a caring
adult, even Big Brothers/ Big Sisters of America is encouraging its
affiliates to test the lightweight alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Americans are scaling up all of our mentoring programs,''
Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   In the new approach, the mentors work under the watchful eye of
a coordinator from the school or club, rather than taking the child
somewhere. Training is minimal, sometimes half a day long, but
often little more than a pep talk before they are introduced to a
child selected by teachers or youth counselors. The child, more
often than not, comes from a single-parent home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always kids who need attention so badly that they'll
act out badly in order to get it,'' said Guy Mazza, principal of
Warner Elementary School in Wilmington. ``Want to know what makes
it worth all the administrative burden, and the pull-out times from
class, and the cost? It's that these kids can get attention from
mentors for the opposite _ doing the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional adds follow.)
</P>
<P>
   David Hayden and Ravelle Porter, who work in the audit
department at Hercules Inc., pair up to mentor Artezz(cq) Finney.
Each spends a half hour of company-paid time with the fifth-grader
on a different day of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Both are ``okay,'' said Artezz, who had come running in to greet
Hayden in Warner's mentoring room, where the child-sized tables are
thoughtfully equipped with low chairs wide enough to accommodate a
mentor's bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ravelle and I can fill in for each other when schedules don't
work out,'' Hayden said. ``Our role is to tap into his potential,
showing Artezz how he can accomplish things.''
</P>
<P>
   The positive impact of the traditional weekend-mentoring program
of Big Sisters and Big Brothers was firmly established in a 1995
study frequently cited by supporters of all kinds of mentoring.
Comparing two similar batches of children with and without mentors,
the researchers found that after 18 months, the children with
mentors were far less likely to have started using drugs or
alcohol, hit someone, skipped a class or skipped a day of school
without an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``There haven't been thorough evaluations of the lighter
versions yet,'' said Jean Grossman, vice president for research at
Philadelphia-based Public/Private Ventures, who helped conduct the
1995 study. She said the stripped-down programs might work if the
mentors keep their commitments.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't think that a good-hearted volunteer could hurt
kids,'' she cautioned. ``But mentoring relationships that we
examined that broke up within three months definitely hurt the
kids, because the kids ended up thinking it must be their own
fault. You see self-esteem plummeting, and see the academic
reflection of that.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The loudest applause at Wednesday's rally for mentors came when
Powell ran down a long list of how children can get into trouble,
and concluded, ``We can't just walk away from the problem. They're
all our children _ whether they are in our family or in our
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those applauding was Kenyatta Charles, a third-grader at
MacClary Elementary School in Newark, Del., and her mentor, April
Hubbard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play games, we walk in the woods near school and we play
outside on the swings,'' Kenyatta said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do reading sometimes. But we're really into building
self-esteem,'' Hubbard added. A school mentor once a week, she
recently agreed to a longer-term commitment as Kenyatta's Big
Sister, which will involve three or four hours of contact weekly
all year round.
</P>
<P>
   She said she decided to switch because ``there's also a lot more
support, like having a case worker to consult with'' in moments of
uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
