<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Friday, May 21, 1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-SHOOTING _ CONYERS, Ga. _ A suicidal, disgruntled high
school student, angry over breaking up with his girlfriend, turned
his anger on the world Thursday, shooting six of his classmates and
emotionally scarring countless others on the last day of classes in
this suburban Atlanta high school. J.T. Solomon came to Heritage
High School near Conyers with a broken heart, two guns, and a
terrible agenda. (Schneider, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). ETA: 7
p.m. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GOP-NRA _ ATLANTA _ As of Wednesday the NRA's Wayne LaPierre
still planned to speak Saturday at a state GOP convention in
Augusta. Checking back with outgoing state GOP chair Rusty Paul who
invited LaPierre, and also trying to reach NRA board member and
U.S. Rep. Bob Barr, who'll introduce LaPierre on Saturday, to ask
if they still want him to appear in light of Thursday's metro
Atlanta high school shooting. (Pruitt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTING-OFFICIALREAX _ Official state and national reaction was
swift today to the Conyers shooting. President Clinton called the
incident ``deeply troubling'' in comments moments before leaving
for Littleton, Colo., the site of last month's fatal shooting. New
York Sen. Schummer mentioned today's shooting from the Senate floor
during debate on gun legislation. Also comments from Janet Reno and
Georgia officials. (Cumming-Pruitt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTING-RESIDENTREAX _ CONYERS, Ga. _ People who live in the
middle-class area around Heritage High are not shocked the shooting
happened here, and many believe it signals the time to get God back
in the schools. (Stanford, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTING-SHOOTER _ CONYERS, Ga. _ Trying to piece together what
we can on the 15-year-old gunman in the Heritage High School
shooting. Fellow students said he was a sophomore and a Boy Scout.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTING-LASTER _ CONYERS, Ga. _ The most seriously injured was
15-year-old Stephanie Laster, who was being treated at Grady for a
shot that hit her in the buttocks and passed through to her
intestines. Checking report that her family's house burned about a
year ago. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTING-SECURITY _ CONYERS, Ga. _ Heritage High School is like
a lot of others where shootings have taken place in recent years:
suburban or small-town and with a student body that is middle- or
upper-middle class, mostly white, has high test scores, engages in
very little criminal activity and heads to college after
graduation. Heritage in particular is known for emphasizing a
traditional curriculum, heavy on the 3 Rs. It's the kind of place
where people move to the school district, despite the commute,
because they believe it will provide a safe and sound education for
their kids. Security, compared to some urban schools, is light,
with no metal detectors or cadres of armed guards in the hallways.
(Stafford, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTING-SENIORS _ CONYERS, Ga. _ Thursday was supposed to be a
day for seniors to say goodbye to friends and sign yearbooks,
wishing each other well before next Friday's graduation. Instead,
many kids spent the day watching their school on CNN. ``My last day
at Heritage has been robbed,'' said one senior. (Brett, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTING-FEARYEAR _ CONYERS, Ga. _ Will this school year ever
end? In the waning days of this school year, anxiety seems to be at
an all time high. We talk to parents, students, teachers,
sociologist/psychologists about the fear and tensions this
traumatic year has produced and the sense that we are grappling for
the finish line and possibly the relief of making it to the summer
break. (Emerson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTING-HOWFAR _ DAYTON, Ohio _ How far should school
superintendents and principals go in putting clamps on students in
an effort to control potential problems in schools? Some local
schools have put in measures designed to curb potential problems
(can't wear long coats, can't talk about Columbine, for example)
but that only angers students and the ACLU, which look at such
measures as impinging in personal freedoms. School supers say
they're between a rock and hard place. (Smith, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   GUNS _ WASHINGTON _ Propelled by school violence, the Senate
votes for fresh gun restrictions over the strong opposition of most
Republicans. Vice President Al Gore breaks a 50-50 tie in favor of
a proposal to require mandatory background checks for purchases at
gun shows and to put new restrictions on pawnshop sales as well.
(Foskett, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON _ LITTLETON, Colo. _ President Clinton and his wife
console families and survivors a month after the murder-suicide
rampage that left 15 dead. Clinton calls the new shootings in
Georgia ``deeply troubling'' and says Americans must come together
``to protect all of our children from violence.'' Arrival in
Littleton is planned for about 4 p.m. EDT. An address to Columbine
students, rescuers and community leaders is scheduled for 6:15 p.m.
EDT. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN _ WASHINGTON _ Republican presidential candidate John
McCain, in a National Press Club speech Thursday, launched his
broadest attack yet on President Clinton's foreign and trade
policies. (Lipman, Cox News Service) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   PORTS _ WASHINGTON _ The House Ways and Means Committee passed a
bill that will add 1,700 customs inspectors to increase prevention
of drug smuggling and child pornography. (Schultz, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   GUNVOTES-GA _ Georgia Sen. Max Cleland changes his vote on the
gun bill once again, tipping the balance in favor of background
checks. He says he was influenced by the shootings in Atlanta.
Meanwhile, Sen. Paul Coverdell hangs tough in opposition to gun
control measures. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-SENATE _ WASHINGTON - Is she or isn't she? As Hillary
Rodham Clinton plans for her fourth trip to New York in four weeks
and speculation about an exploratory committee flies, many
political pros are predicting that she'll decide to run for the
U.S. Senate. (Shepard).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving by 6 p.m. ET in (w) Washington and (p) politics
categories.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH _ WASHINGTON -- Investment guru Peter Lynch addresses
annual meeting of the Investment Company Institute, the mutual fund
trade group. (McNaughton, Cox News Service). 12.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY _ WASHINGTON _ Congress members from both houses
and both parties _ including reform leaders Sens. John Breaux,
D-La., and Bob Kerrey, D-Neb. _ announce their plan for Social
Security on Thursday. (Lipman, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   CUSTOMS _ WASHINGTON _ Rep. John Lewis hears graphic testimony
in hearings on custom service searches at airports and calls for
legislation to end racial profiling in such searches. (Carr, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SETTLERS _ ACHIYA, West Bank _ For Shmuel Kohen, in the
vanguard of right-wing Israel's efforts to control disputed land,
things still look pretty good. Below his hilltop mobile home are
olive orchards and a nearby Arab village. A new paved road snakes
its way up to his remote outpost and, next door, the Israeli
soldiers who protect his and the four other families here are
grilling hot dogs. ``It is important to build Israel,'' says the
affable Kohen, 28. While his daughter toddles around beneath the
posters of famous rabbis, he dismisses the chances of peace with
Arabs. ``They want to kill Jews only because we are Jews.'' But, an
hour's drive in Jerusalem, Kohen's political supply lines have been
damaged. Israel's elections Monday dealt a stunning blow to the
right-wing settler movement. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   STATE LEGISLATIVE NEWS
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-TAX _ Proposed state tax breaks for research and
development were expected to get bigger Thursday after a House
committee voted 0on its tax plan. We look at other changes to the
tax cuts, which were approved by the Senate earlier. (Elizondo,
Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
