<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5028 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-EDITORIAL21-     05-20 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-EDITORIAL21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    We must say `no more'
 &HT;    (This is an editorial from Friday's Atlanta Constitution.)
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ To many parents around the country, it had seemed
almost inevitable, like the rumble of far-off thunder signaling a
violent storm headed in their direction.
</P>
<P>
   Springfield, Ore., West Paducah, Ky., Littleton, Colo. ...
</P>
<P>
   And now Conyers, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   The storm has hit home. The shootings at Heritage High School,
25 miles east of Atlanta, refreshed all of those emotions _ fear,
shock, outrage _ that had begun to ease a month after the tragedy
at Columbine High School. And today, or next week, it could happen
again at another school, in another region.
</P>
<P>
   But things are changing.
</P>
<P>
   As shots were being fired at Heritage High, senators in
Washington were preparing to debate whether to require background
checks on gun sales at firearms shows. Sen. Larry Craig, an Idaho
Republican and member of the board of the National Rifle
Association, had bragged just a day earlier that he and his
colleagues would make no more concessions to those advocating
tighter gun-safety laws. They were drawing the line.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate erased Craig's line, voting overwhelmingly for a
Republican measure requiring background checks on all transactions
at gun shows and at pawnshops. Craig was one of 21 senators, all
Republican, who voted against the measure. Sen. Paul Coverdell of
Georgia joined him in that vote.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the Senate approved an even stricter amendment, thanks to
a vote by Vice President Al Gore, who broke a 50-50 tie. Coverdell
voted against that bill as well.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans have long understood the need for sane gun-safety
laws. But in a complex world, gun safety was only one of many
issues that demanded their attention. The numerical advantage of
that majority was more than offset by the intensity of the minority
that saw gun-safety legislation as a conspiracy to take their guns.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, however, the political dynamic is changing. The majority
of Americans is coming to understand that the minority must be
confronted, that its power to squelch sane gun-safety legislation
must be ended. It's tragic that such progress is coming at the
price of children's blood, of parents' anguish, of a deepening
doubt about the fundamental decency of the world in which we are
raising our families. But it's apparently necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect in the Conyers shooting, for example, was a
16-year-old high school sophomore armed with a rifle and a pistol.
For more than five years, state Sen. David Scott, an Atlanta
Democrat, and others in Georgia have tried to pass a law making it
a crime for an adult to allow unsupervised juveniles easy access to
firearms. Every year, their effort has been stymied by NRA
lobbyists, as if the Second Amendment guaranteed the right to leave
loaded handguns on the coffee table in front of children.
</P>
<P>
   That has to change.
</P>
<P>
   Delay is the NRA's best strategy. NRA officials understand that
as Americans, we have an incredibly high tolerance for gun-related
violence. What was once shocking too quickly becomes an accepted
part of the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   The night before the Conyers shooting, an 18-year-old was shot
to death in Gwinnett County. Early Tuesday morning, a motorist on
Interstate 75 was shot dead as he drove down the highway. Tuesday
afternoon, a body was found in DeKalb County with multiple gunshot
wounds. That same day, a young man in Atlanta was shot dead in an
argument over $10. On Sunday night, a wedding guest was shot and
killed in a parking lot in Fairburn.
</P>
<P>
   And the only thing remarkable about those deaths is how truly
unremarkable we find them. Someday, if we don't act responsibly,
the same could become true of schoolyard shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
