<HEADER>
A5029 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASCAR-FRANCE-NYTR &LR;      05-20 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-FRANCE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL FRANCE SOLIDIFIES HIS CONTROL OF STOCK CAR RACING 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Bruton Smith ever had any thoughts about challenging Bill
France for supremacy in stock car racing _ and many believe he did
_ he can forget it.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, France made it virtually impossible for Smith or
anyone else to challenge his authority when International Speedway
Corp., of which France is chairman and chief executive officer,
announced it was buying out Roger Penske's holdings.
</P>
<P>
   That gives France control of 10 major racing facilities, nine of
which currently are sites of one or more Winston Cup events, He
also has controlling interests in new racing venues being built
near Kansas City, Chicago and New York and a proposed site close to
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   With the number of tracks France has up-and-running, under
construction or proposed, he will have enough major facilities to
schedule the entire Winston Cup tour at places he owns within the
next five years.
</P>
<P>
   And, since he also owns and is president of NASCAR, the sport's
governing body, he is in position to do that if he has to.
</P>
<P>
   France's ISC will pay Penske Motorsports Inc. $705 million for
the California Speedway near Los Angeles; the Michigan Speedway
near Detroit; Nazareth Speedway in Nazareth, Pa., and North
Carolina Speedway in Rockingham, N.C.; plus Penske's 45 percent of
the Miami-Dade motorsports complex. France already owns 45 percent
of Miami-Dade.
</P>
<P>
   That list makes France unassailable when you couple it with
Daytona, Fla.; Talladega, Ala.; Darlington, S.C.; Watkins Glen,
N.Y., and Phoenix, Ariz., all operated by ISC, and add
Martinsville, Va., which France is believed to be involved with
although it is not listed as part of his ISC holdings.
</P>
<P>
   France now controls more racing sites than anybody, and even if
Smith, who runs six tracks himself through his Speedway Motorsports
Inc., decides to try to expand, France has shown a willingness to
compete with him.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even more importantly from a revenue standpoint, France
will eventually have tracks near the nation's three major
population centers _ New York, Chicago and Los Angeles _ in
addition to Detroit, the hub of America's motorsports industry.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, through his association with Tony George, he also
has the two most famous American racing venues, Indianapolis and
Daytona,
</P>
<P>
   And he will have sites available for racing in almost every
geographic area of the country, while Smith is confined to the
South and West.
</P>
<P>
   So, if Smith or anyone else has any ideas about stepping out on
their own, they can forget it.
</P>
<P>
   They might be able to take the first step, but they'll never
take the second. France has just seen to that.
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
