<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-PETTY-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETTY TEAM IS RED HOT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a quiet seventh-place finish, but it was significant.
</P>
<P>
   With his run at Richmond, Va., last Saturday, Kyle Petty
recorded his third and Petty Enterprises' sixth top 10 in the last
five races. That span of success began April 11 in Bristol. Tenn.,
when the Winston Cup cars started into the short track portion of
the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with John Andretti's three top 10s, which include a win
April 18 at Martinsville, Va., that gives Petty Enterprises a
record arguably equal to any and better than all but one multi-car
team.
</P>
<P>
   Only Jack Roush's five-car entry with drivers Johnny Benson,
Jeff Burton, Kevin Lepage, Chad Little and Mark Martin has more top
10s over this time _ a total of seven _ but the team has not won a
race.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Childress Racing, featuring drivers Dale Earnhardt and
Mike Skinner, has done as well, also with six top 10s including an
April 25 win by Earnhardt at Talladega, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Yates Racing, with drivers Kenny Irwin and Richmond
winner Dale Jarrett, have five top 10s, all by Jarrett, as does the
powerhouse three-car team of Rick Hendrick, led by Jeff Gordon with
teammates Terry Labonte and Wally Dallenbach.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Gibbs' two drivers, Bobby Labonte and rookie Tony Stewart,
also have five top 10s over the five-race span.
</P>
<P>
   The recent performance of Petty and Andretti seems to indicate
that the merging of their two teams, which took place this season,
is beginning to click.
</P>
<P>
   Petty, for example, has already doubled the number of top 10
finishes he had in '98.
</P>
<P>
   Andretti has returned Petty Enterprises to the winner's circle
after he went winless in 1998, when he came back to drive for
Richard Petty.
</P>
<P>
   Robbie Loomis, general manager of the two-car team and
Andretti's crew chief on race day, said one reason for the improved
performance of both cars is the fresh input provided by the
integration of Kyle Petty's operation with that of Andretti.
</P>
<P>
   That has also been aided by the addition of Doug Hewitt, who
signed on this season as Kyle Petty's crew chief after working with
Derrike Cope.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Kyle and Doug came on board, they looked at our cars and
made some suggestions,'' Loomis said. ``They made us think about
the way we were doing things, and that helped speed up the learning
curve.''
</P>
<P>
   While Kyle Petty struggled virtually all of 1998, Loomis and
Andretti had some success after Andretti left Cale Yarborough to
rejoin Petty Enterprises, where he had worked during part of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were 11th in points, and that wasn't so bad, but I was
pretty disgusted that we didn't win a race,'' Loomis said.
</P>
<P>
   Through the '90s, Loomis has pretty much been the one constant
at Petty Enterprises, serving as Richard Petty's crew chief is his
final seasons and carrying on after the king's retirement in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But he has never been in charge of a two-car team before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to be Rick Hendrick here. We're not trying to
be Jack Roush,'' Loomis said, referring to perhaps the two most
prominent multi-car teams. ``What we're trying to do is get back to
being what Petty Enterprises was, a team that can consistently
compete and win.''
</P>
<P>
   For Loomis, that means learning how to use his time efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to know when to get involved, help out with
something, and you have to know when you need to stand back,''
Loomis said. ``If you don't do that, you can hurt one team more
than you help the other team.''
</P>
<P>
   Another potentially tricky area is keeping Andretti from feeling
he will eventually be squeezed out by the Pettys. With Kyle's son,
18-year-old Adam, showing promise in the Busch ranks, a non-Petty
could become odd man out on a family oriented team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't worry about it,'' Loomis said about Andretti.
``He's gone through a lot of the same thing with his family name.
It doesn't bother his performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently not, judging from the last few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla. is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
