A5035 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALEXANDER-VINEYARD-NY     05-20 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALEXANDER-VINEYARD-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHERRER FAMILY TREE IS A VINEYARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TIM FISH   
 WINETODAY.COM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEBASTOPOL, Calif. _ Fred Scherrer has something he can look at
every day to remember his grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   A vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   Walking through the hunched and bent vines of his family's
Alexander Valley vineyard, Scherrer turns his mind back, to
harvests long ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember not working in the vineyard,'' Scherrer says.
``When I'm working in the old vineyard, I think about my
grandfather. He was a great guy. He planted these vines in his 20s.
I don't think he could have imagined that people would come from
all around to get the wines.''
</P>
<P>
   Word is indeed getting out about Scherrer Winery zinfandels.
</P>
<P>
   After selling the grapes for generations to Gallo, Scherrer
brought some of his grapes to Greenwood Ridge Vineyards, where he
was winemaker, and the winery began bottling a Scherrer Vineyard
zinfandel in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as winemaker at Dehlinger Winery, Scherrer made his own
zinfandel beginning with the 1991 vintage. Today he produces about
2,000 cases, plus a little cabernet sauvignon and chardonnay.
</P>
<P>
   His zins have a cult following in the San Francisco Bay Area and
for good reason. His 1997 Old &AMP; Mature Vines and 1997 Shale Terrace
were rated 4 stars in recent WineToday.com tastings.
</P>
<P>
   The style is classic: ripe, well-structured and powerful in a
way that's never less than elegant. The wines reveal an astute
understanding of the vineyard, of ``place,'' as well as a skilled
but subtle hand in the winery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fred is an original and profound thinker about wine,'' Tom
Dehlinger says. ``He has an extremely personal commitment with his
wines and they're personal creations from the vines to the
bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   Scherrer Vineyard is in the eastern benchland and as you look
west across Alexander Valley, Mount St. Helena is just over your
shoulder. To the south is Silver Oak's famed Alexander Valley
vineyard, and to the north is Sausal Winery.
</P>
<P>
   Scherrer's great-grandfather bought the property in 1899. In
1912, Scherrer's grandfather _ also named Fred Scherrer _ planted
the first zinfandel vines. About 3 1/2 acres of the original vines
remain and they are the base of the Old &AMP; Mature. More zinfandel
was planted in the '70s and early '80s.
</P>
<P>
   There's also cabernet sauvignon and chardonnay but most of it is
still sold to Gallo. Gone are the alicante bouschet and the
Imperial prune trees that Scherrer remembers from his youth. The
family once made its living from the intensively flavorful but
fragile Imperial prunes, but as the market faded, Scherrer's
grandfather slowly replaced the trees with vines.
</P>
<P>
   He has made a study of the vineyard over the years, a skill he
picked up during his decade at Dehlinger Winery, which is
well-known for extensively mapping the soils, grape clones and
microclimates of its Russian River Valley estate vineyards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Understanding what your vineyard wants to be is more than half
the battle,'' Scherrer says. ``You just give it what it needs and
stay out of its way.''
</P>
<P>
   His vineyard, Scherrer learned, is divided between two soil
types _ clay and shale _ each of which bring a different character
to wine. The newer vineyards tend to be planted on shale, which
lets the roots grow more freely and generally produces wines with
softer tannins.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the old vines are in clay soils, which don't allow for
vigorous growth and gives wines a tight structure. Scherrer is
particularly taken by the wines produced from the old vines.
</P>
<P>
   Scherrer Winery is not on a busy wine tourist trail. It's down a
treacherously bumpy dirt road in west Sonoma County, a remote wing
of Wine Country that's still close to its rustic roots. There's no
sign on the road except for the address spray-painted on plywood.
</P>
<P>
   The winery, which isn't open to the public, is in a nondescript
white warehouse that used to be home to a Crema Winery, and
Scherrer shares the space with a medicinal herb company.
</P>
<P>
   Fancy it's not, but then that's not Scherrer's style. His hair
is dark and falls in waves to his shoulders, and like his beard,
it's freckled in gray. Sure, he makes great wine, but he's a farmer
and likes it that way.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Scherrer is just happy to have a winery of his own.
Before February 1998, he made his wines at Dehlinger, but they
outgrew each other.
</P>
<P>
   Scherrer prefers a low-key approach to winemaking, which is a
good thing because he has limited space and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The zinfandels are fermented in open-top tanks and Scherrer
punches down the cap manually to improve color and extraction. Some
of the grapes are typically fermented in whole clusters.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the stems are really ripe, you end up with this beautiful
perfume,'' Scherrer says of the whole-cluster technique. ``If you
do it right, you end up with a silkiness and if you do it wrong,
you end up with a hardness, a greenness or an astringency in the
wine.''
</P>
<P>
   While Scherrer admits his zinfandels have become increasingly
more ripe and higher in alcohol, he believes the change has been
subtle but an improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the reasons I haven't had as much trouble with
alcohol is because I've gotten good about getting rid of raisins,''
Scherrer says.
</P>
<P>
   Zinfandel grapes don't ripen evenly, and a single bunch may
include green grapes, ripe grapes and raisiny grapes. Scherrer
removes as many of the raisins as possible and even had his
destemmer rebuilt to make it easier to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   Once the wine is in the barrel, ``I leave it alone,'' Scherrer
says. ``I used to do things because that's what you were supposed
to do. I rack for a reason instead of because, `That's what you
do.' ''
</P>
<P>
   (Winetoday.com is a daily Internet wine publication published by
the New York Times Co. and The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif.
The Web address is http://www.winetoday.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
