<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5038 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-BEST-BUY-ART-NYT     05-20 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-BEST-BUY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPARING THE AUTO-QUALITY STUDIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ It is a question that anyone who drives cars for a
living is asked over and over: What's the best car, or truck, to
buy? Well, it depends _ on your price range, on your driving style,
on the importance you place on quality, design, performance and
other factors.
</P>
<P>
   Two new quality surveys seem to be saying that, too. The
surveys, from J.D. Power &AMP; Associates and AutoPacific Inc.,
generally agree on the makes and models that fared the worst, but
often disagreed on those at the top. Indeed, the surveys, each of
which are based on interviews with more than 40,000 buyers of 1999
vehicles, differ in what they measure and how they measure it.
</P>
<P>
   The Initial Quality Study by J.D. Power, the big market research
firm in Agoura Hills, Calif., measures product quality in the first
three months of ownership. Vehicles are rated based on problems
reported for each 100 vehicles, covering 135 specific areas across
nine categories including vehicle interiors and exteriors, power
trains, features and controls, as well as ride, handling and
braking. All items _ whether a door won't close properly or an
engine fails completely _ carry the same weight. This survey does
not measure customers' satisfaction with the vehicle and the
dealership, though those factors are rated in other surveys by J.D.
Power.
</P>
<P>
   Also this month, AutoPacific released its 1999 Vehicle
Satisfaction Scores. AutoPacific, of Tustin, Calif., which conducts
studies for automakers, has been doing this survey for its
automotive clients since 1994 but has publicly announced the scores
only once before. AutoPacific measures owners' satisfaction with
vehicle quality, styling, performance and features, as well as
price and dealership experience. The study includes rankings by
manufacturers, brands and individual models.
</P>
<P>
   Respondents rated their 1999 vehicles on 51 attributes, 32 of
them related directly to their vehicles. From these responses,
AutoPacific calculated a Pure Product Satisfaction score. The
remaining 19 questions dealt with financial and dealership matters.
Added together, these make up the Vehicle Satisfaction Scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Products are getting better and better and better,'' said
George Peterson, president of AutoPacific. ``The difference between
the worst car and the best is pretty close. So rather than look at
things gone wrong, we try to bring in the emotional aspect and
importance aspect of 51 vehicle attributes.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki and Kia held the last two places in both the J.D. Power
and AutoPacific surveys; Isuzu, Jeep and Mitsubishi were near the
bottom as well. Toyota and Lexus captured segment leadership in
multiple categories in both studies.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the rankings at the top were all over the map. One
big surprise was J.D. Power's No. 1 ranking of Jaguar _ whose
infamous mechanical maladies had made it a punchline of car jokes
for decades. Not so surprisingly, AutoPacific had Lexus as No. 1;
Jaguar landed in a still-respectable seventh place in AutoPacific's
product quality survey.
</P>
<P>
   The most notable discrepancies between the two product-only
surveys were the positions of Nissan, Mazda and Saab. J.D. Power
put Nissan at No. 11, while AutoPacific's product survey rated it
below average at No. 24. J.D. Power put Mazda just above average at
No. 16, but AutoPacific put it near the bottom, at No. 32.
Similarly, Saab was ranked below average by J.D. Power and in the
top 10 by AutoPacific.
</P>
<P>
   While overall quality has improved sharply since J.D. Power's
first survey in 1987, gaps remain. ``There very definitely are
differences between quality within segments,'' said George Owens,
project director of J.D. Power's Initial Quality Study. ``That's
important information to give to the consumer. Releasing the top
three performers in each segment gives folks a good indication of
quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Although manufacturers buy complete results from J.D. Power, the
company does not publicly disclose its rankings below No. 3, making
it difficult for consumers to use the survey when shopping. (The
New York Times obtained the complete list from a J.D. Power
subscriber.)
</P>
<P>
   What's more, these are by no means the only surveys of new-car
owners. Indeed, J.D. Power conducts several others that often come
up with quite different results. For instance, one study asks
consumers what they like and dislike about their vehicles in
general terms. Quite often, the top-rated brands in that survey do
not match those with the highest quality scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some vehicles have very good quality and very good appeal _
Lexus and BMW vehicles tend to do that,'' said Owens of J.D. Power.
``There are buyers who are looking for quality vehicles that don't
break down. They sometimes don't have much appeal. And there are
buyers who are willing to deal with product problems for an
exciting ride.''
</P>
<P>
   John Paul MacDuffie, an associate management professor at the
Wharton School, said the quality studies served consumers in
another way. ``The surveys have had a tremendous impact on the
industry by prompting quality efforts, particularly with the Big
Three,'' he said. ``The effect on what the companies are doing is
as great as the impact on consumer purchasing decisions. And the
consumer ultimately benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Customer satisfaction with the buying experience is rated in a
separate J.D. Power survey, the Sales Satisfaction Index, which
will be released in July. Saturn, which ranked below average in
J.D. Power's Initial Quality Study, has scored high in the past in
customer satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   AutoPacific considers the sales experience crucial to buyers'
overall satisfaction and includes it in its annual study. ``The
consumer can look at our ratings and see overall how satisfied
their peers are with products they purchased and with the treatment
at the dealership,'' said Peterson of AutoPacific. The surveys show
that Saturn gets a boost from its dealers. ``Our study shows Saturn
is an adequate car sold by great dealers,'' Peterson said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the Porsche 911 and Chevrolet Corvette rank high in
product satisfaction but much lower in sales satisfaction. ``They
are great cars, but the dealers are abusing customers in some way _
maybe financially or in dealership courtesy,'' Peterson said.
``There is something that is not making the 911 and Corvette buyers
happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
