<HEADLINE>
HAMPTON ROADS: A COSMOPOLITAN MAKEOVER FOR A TIDEWATER BACKWATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORFOLK, Va. _ Hampton Roads, the natural harbor where the James
River and several lesser streams meet Chesapeake Bay, has had a
balcony seat for history.
</P>
<P>
   It was into these waters that Captain John Smith and his
companions sailed in 1607 after their first landfall at Cape Henry,
on their way to establish Jamestown. It was near here that the
French admiral Francois de Grasse turned back a British relief
fleet in 1781, sealing the fate of Lord Cornwallis at Yorktown.
</P>
<P>
   Here Commodore Matthew Perry set sail for his voyage to Japan in
1853, here the Monitor fought the Merrimac, heralding the age of
the ironclad that revolutionized naval warfare, here the U.S.
invasion force set out for North Africa during World War II. Here
U.S. warships have been built and the powerful Atlantic Fleet has
long been based.
</P>
<P>
   But until recently, much of Tidewater, as the locals call the
region, was a backwater. The writer William Styron grew up in
Tidewater, and in his early novel ``Lie Down in Darkness'' (1951),
he wrote feelingly of ``the low, sorrowful beauty of tideland
streams winding through marshes full of small, darting, frightened
noises and glistening and dead silent at noon, except for a
whistle, far off, and a distant rumble on the rails.''
</P>
<P>
   You still find such places. One is the little county seat of
Surry, across the river from Jamestown, where a Confederate
memorial bears the bittersweet inscription, ``Our Heroes.'' Life
there is lived legato.
</P>
<P>
   They are no longer typical, though. Hampton Roads _ composed,
for our purposes, of the cities of Norfolk, Portsmouth, Virginia
Beach, Hampton and Newport News, plus the towns of Jamestown,
Yorktown and Williamsburg _ has long since overtaken Richmond as a
metropolitan area. Its population now exceeds 1.5 million, roughly
a quarter of the state's total, and Virginia Beach, of all unlikely
places, is the Old Dominion's largest city, with 393,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   On a long weekend here recently, my wife, Betsey, and I were
flabbergasted by the transformation. As a schoolgirl 40 years ago,
she used to take the train to Buckroe Beach in Hampton on swimming
outings, and as a draftee 40 years ago I was based at sleepy Fort
Monroe, nearby, writing speeches for Gen. Bruce Clarke, one of the
lions of the Battle of the Bulge, and sometimes for Gen. Maxwell
Taylor, a D-Day hero.
</P>
<P>
   What happened? I asked my brother-in-law St. George Pinckney, a
Richmond man through and through. Simple, he said: ``The foreigners
and the come-heres'' did it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last 25 years, Europeans at the NATO headquarters in
Norfolk, people at the military bases, civilians from all over the
country whose companies moved them into the area, all helped break
through the crust of insularity,'' he said. ``In Richmond, that
never happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The benign climate helped. This may not exactly be the Sun Belt,
but snow is about as common in these parts as Russian submarines.
</P>
<P>
   The Fleet's Really In
</P>
<P>
   The military remains the economic prime mover, despite a lot of
recent diversification. People here work in a Ford assembly plant
and a Budweiser brewery, for the mail-order queen Lillian Vernon
and Pat Robertson's Christian Broadcasting Network.
</P>
<P>
   But one in every four workers in Hampton Roads _ like Los
Angeles County, it is politically subdivided but economically
united _ takes home a paycheck from Uncle Sam, and total defense
spending here in 1997 totaled $6.92 billion. In terms of
active-duty personnel, seven of the nation's 60 largest military
installations are located in Hampton Roads.
</P>
<P>
   The Army has Fort Eustis, its transportation center, and Fort
Monroe, the only moated installation still in active use, where
Jefferson Davis was imprisoned after the Civil War. The Air Force
has Langley Air Force Base, the oldest active air base in the
country. Near that is NASA's big Langley Research Center,
established in 1917, where the astronauts learned the Right Stuff
for the pioneering Mercury and Apollo space shots.
</P>
<P>
   Norfolk, of course, is a Navy town par excellence. All along its
western flank rise the fearsome gray superstructures of aircraft
carriers, cruisers and other vessels _ fighting machines catching
their breath between missions. The Norfolk Naval Base is the
largest in the world, home to more than 100 major ships and 27
squadrons of aircraft. More than 75,000 people work there. More
than 25,000 other people work at the Little Creek amphibious base
and the Oceana Naval Air Station, both in Virginia Beach.
</P>
<P>
   But Norfolk is no longer the brawling liberty town of World War
II. It was once as disorderly and disreputable a place as you could
find on the East Coast, and Main Street, a young man we met there
told us, ``used to be nothing but bars, cathouses, tattoo parlors,
and more bars.'' Now it is lined with gleaming modern buildings,
including hotels, a world trade center and bank towers, as well as
Nauticus, a Disneyesque maritime museum.
</P>
<P>
   Norfolk has yet to attract a big-league sports franchise; this
must be one of the largest metropolitan areas in the nation without
one. But the New York Mets' Triple-A farm team, the Norfolk Tides,
play their home games in Harbor Park, a spiffy stadium close to the
waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   Most surprisingly, perhaps, Norfolk's metamorphosis has included
its emergence as a cultural center of note, with the Chrysler
Museum of Art and Virginia Opera in the vanguard. Both rank among
the outstanding institutions of their size in the South and, for
that matter, the nation.
</P>
<P>
   It was Walter P. Chrysler Jr., son of the founder of Chrysler
Corp., who enabled Norfolk to join the late 20th-century revolution
in which museums have helped to power the revival of struggling
cities. Married to a Norfolk native, he lifted a provincial
collection into the top rank in 1971 with the gift of 30,000
objects that ``any museum in the world would kill for,'' as John
Russell wrote on one occasion in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the museum was deftly enlarged, modernized and
reorganized by the Washington architects George Hartman and Warren
Cox.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A series of rooms just to the right of the main entrance
contains two of the museum's treasures. A collection of Art Nouveau
furniture by Majorelle and Colonna, accompanied by Tiffany and
Galle accessories, fills the first.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes a feast of glass, unmatched on this continent except
in the glass-making towns of Toledo, Ohio, and Corning, N.Y.: room
after room of Favrile vases and Tiffany lamps, dozens of major
pieces of Lalique, Steuben and Wiener Werkstette glass, Sandwich
glass, Amberina, Murano glass.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs, in the picture galleries, my eye was caught by a
precise profile portrait of a man in a red turban, attributed to
Domenico Veneziano, Piero della Francesca's teacher, whose
surviving works are exceedingly rare; Georges de la Tour's pensive
St. Philip; a brassy, recumbent blonde, ``Mlle. Monna Lils,'' by
the Dutch modernist Kees van Dongen, and a mural by Thomas Hart
Benton, painted for the original Whitney Museum of American Art in
New York, which vividly embodies the breakneck pace of modern life.
</P>
<P>
   An elaborate parcel-gilt silver cup in the shape of a pineapple,
made in London in 1610, testifies to the civilization the Jamestown
settlers left behind three years earlier for a rude life in the
wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   Until fall, in the largest of the Chrysler's galleries, a giant,
golden Dale Chihuly glass sculpture, ``Laguna Murano Chandelier,''
has joined Venetian masterpieces of another era by Veronese and
Tintoretto. At the far end of the room, Bernini's great, wide-eyed
``Bust of the Savior,'' which the Baroque master originally
intended for Queen Christina of Sweden, ``finally has something to
stare at,'' as a curator irreverently remarked to us.
</P>
<P>
   More Chihulys, some of them so dazzling they made me weak in the
knees, are on show for three months at the Contemporary Art Center
of Virginia in Virginia Beach, magnificently installed and
brilliantly lit.
</P>
<P>
   The Music Man
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia Opera has had but one general director in its
quarter-century existence, a Brooklyn-born violist named Peter
Mark. He has put it on the musical map in not one but three
locations. The company's principal residence is the Harrison
Theater in Norfolk, a smashing post-modern conversion (by the
Boston architect Graham Gund) of a seedy former USO theater and
wrestling arena. Completed in 1993 on a budget of under $10
million, it eschews frou-frou to focus on comfort and capacity
(1,600 seats).
</P>
<P>
   Next season Virginia Opera will stage 46 performances of five
operas, including a Handel rarity, ``Rodelinda,'' here and in
Richmond and northern Virginia. In addition, it will take its shows
on the road, performing in various guises before a quarter-million
Virginia schoolchildren, an unmatched educational touring program.
</P>
<P>
   Mark, who also conducts, has given important early breaks to
singers as important as Renee Fleming. Two dozen of his alumni are
on the current roster at the New York Metropolitan Opera. The
company has done ``Don Pasquale'' as a spaghetti western, no less,
and it has presented acclaimed premieres of several works by Mark's
wife, the Scottish composer Thea Musgrave, most recently her eighth
opera, ``Simon Bolivar,'' in January 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like picking up a live wire,'' Mark said of his arrival
here. ``In New York and L.A., people take things for granted. Here,
people who want something better for their children realize they
have to roll up their sleeves and create it.''
</P>
<P>
   The 75-year-old Virginia Symphony Orchestra, which plays for the
opera's performances, has begun to burnish its reputation under its
young conductor, JoAnn Faletta. This spring, the orchestra was
featured during the wide-ranging third annual Virginia Waterfront
International Arts Festival. The thoroughly professional Virginia
Stage Company plays in the handsome old Wells Theater downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Norfolk is a very old city, of course, and quite a few
handprints of history have survived the free-swinging wrecker's
ball of recent decades.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most notable are three grouped close together
downtown: St. Paul's Episcopal Church (1739), shaded by towering
magnolias, which has a Revolutionary cannonball lodged in its south
wall; the Federal-style Moses Myers House, built in 1793 by the
city's first Jewish family, who brought with them from New York
portraits by Gilbert Stuart and Thomas Sully, which still hang in
the house, and the gray-and-white Old Norfolk Academy (1840),
designed in a rigorous Greek Revival style by Thomas U. Walter, who
added the House and Senate wings and the cast-iron dome to the U.S.
Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   A General's Tomb
</P>
<P>
   Another of Walter's local buildings, the domed Old City Hall,
has been turned into a Napoleonic mausoleum for Gen. Douglas
MacArthur, a tomb almost as grandiose as his ego. No fan of his, I
gave it a pass and instead visited the Scope Arena, a soaring,
saucerlike dome of interlocking concrete triangles, supported only
by a system of massive buttresses outside. The work of the Italian
Pier Luigi Nervi, this is engineering become art.
</P>
<P>
   You have to climb into the car to see the three 17th-century
brick buildings that lie beyond the city's perimeter. So far as I
know, they are the only survivors of their kind in the country: the
simple, story-and-a-half Adam Thoroughgood House in Virginia Beach
(circa 1680), named for a man who came to Virginia as an indentured
servant and made a fortune in tobacco, an early example of American
upward mobility; Bacon's Castle (1665), near Surry, a two-story
Jacobean manor house with a pair of triple chimneys and curvilinear
gables, and the wonderful, cherry-pink St. Luke's Church (1632),
near Smithfield, probably the only truly Gothic (as against Gothic
Revival) structure remaining in America, with the stone buttresses,
pediment, crockets and finials of the old-country models faithfully
copied in brick.
</P>
<P>
   If you come to Hampton Roads in springtime, you will encounter
an intoxicating array of flowering shrubs and trees along most
streets _ Bradford pears, wisteria, camelias, magnolias and
azaleas. The very best show is at the excellent Norfolk Botanical
Gardens, created by the WPA.
</P>
<P>
   A Rolling Excursion
</P>
<P>
   A 10-minute trip across the Hampton Roads Bridge-Tunnel will
take you to Hampton, the oldest continuous English-speaking
community in America.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Monroe, once known as ``the Gibraltar of the Chesapeake,''
stands at its edge. Burned twice, in the War of 1812 and the Civil
War, the old town has little to show for its long history, with the
notable exceptions of Hampton University, founded in 1868 as
Hampton Institute to educate freed slaves, and St. John's Church,
the oldest Anglican parish in the Western Hemisphere, dating from
1610. The present church dates ``only'' from 1728, but its lovely
silver communion plate, made in England in 1618, is still in use
weekly.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Newport News, which lies to the west of Hampton, is more of a
19th-century phenomenon. Railroad baron Collis P. Huntington chose
it as the eastern terminus of his new Chesapeake &AMP; Ohio Railroad,
with which he linked his Western lines to the Atlantic. He also
established the gigantic Newport News Shipbuilding &AMP; Drydock Co.,
still the nation's biggest.
</P>
<P>
   It was Collis' son, Archer, who contributed to the city the
institution you're most likely to visit there, the Mariners'
Museum. It has fabulous collections of ship models, from 6 inches
to 6 feet long; ship's figureheads, including a 3,200-pound eagle
from the USS Lancaster, built in 1881, and artifacts associated
with the ill-fated liner Titanic.
</P>
<P>
   Farther up the Virginia Peninsula, as the tongue of land between
the James and York rivers is known, two towns a few miles apart
witnessed the beginning and the end of Britain's colonial
experience in America.
</P>
<P>
   Yorktown is not nearly as interesting a battlefield as
Gettysburg or Antietam, frankly, and the recreated Jamestown
Settlement, despite impressive museums, has something of the theme
park about it. The site of the original village, administered by
the Colonial National Historical Park, includes the broken tower of
the settlers' fourth church, finished in 1647, which stands amid
lacy dogwoods _ ``God's perfect trees,'' Betsey calls them.
</P>
<P>
   But somehow neither the tower nor the reproduction huts at the
Settlement proved as evocative for us as other features of the
historic park, like the pitch swamp where the settlers struggled to
survive, now inhabited most visibly by herons, or the simple list
of the 104 settlers who stayed in 1607, and the 50 among them who
died within six months.
</P>
<P>
   It was fascinating, too, to put some flesh on the cardboard
figure of John Smith, the colony's gutsy, imperious leader. Long
before he reached the American wilderness, it turns out, he had
fought in Hungary, been taken in captivity to Turkey, been sold
into slavery in Russia, killed his master, escaped and made his way
home to Britain. I guess he must have sailed for Virginia to inject
some excitement into a humdrum life.
</P>
<P>
   The Lure of Williamsburg
</P>
<P>
   I have saved for last the area's premier attraction for
tourists, Colonial Williamsburg, the reconstituted capital of
Patrick Henry and George Washington, willed back into existence by
the millions of the philanthropist John D. Rockefeller Jr.
</P>
<P>
   There is no more need to describe it than to describe the Statue
of Liberty. Suffice it to say that I went there as a kid, visited
it often when I was at Fort Monroe and took my stepchildren there.
I have never tired of it, especially the restored Governor's
Palace, with its formal gardens, and the George Wythe House, which
belonged to Jefferson's law teacher. This time, Betsey and I
especially enjoyed a 10-minute midday prayer service at Bruton
Parish Church, sitting in a box pew that belonged to St. George
Tucker, whose descendant, another St. George Tucker, christened
her. Fond of continuity, these Virginians.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's the ensemble that counts in Williamsburg _ shops
and taverns, houses and gardens _ plus two amazing museums. One
houses Abby Aldrich Rockefeller's pioneering collection of American
folk art; a special show of Edward Hicks landscapes has been
mounted there this year. The other, designed by Kevin Roche and
named for DeWitt Wallace, a co-founder of The Reader's Digest,
houses a world-class decorative arts collection.
</P>
<P>
   And more, always more: just down the road stands Carter's Grove,
the Georgian plantation often described as ``the most beautiful
house in America,'' and all over Williamsburg there are daily
re-enactments of turning points in colonial history, designed to
involve visitors in the past.
</P>
<P>
   These last were part of the recipe for Williamsburg's rebound
after an attendance slump in the late 1980s and early '90s, caused
partly by theme parks and science centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt we had to create a more compelling environment to tell
the story of our country's ideals and values,'' explained Robert C.
Wilburn, Williamsburg's outgoing president. ``We needed more than
antiques and gardens. This is no longer your mother's Colonial
Williamsburg, and we're back to the busiest we've ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Here is information about visiting the Hampton Roads area around
Norfolk, Va.:
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   COLONIAL HOUSES, 302 E. Francis St., Williamsburg, (757)
565-8440. This is Williamsburg's best-kept secret. It's hard to
imagine a more charming place to spend a night or a weekend than
one of the 18th-century houses or taverns in the colonial capital,
with authentically creaking floors, fetchingly time-worn antiques,
working fireplaces and modern plumbing. Ours, once occupied by Cary
Grant, came with a quartet of well-mannered sheep across the
street. Double room: $99 to $200 a night.
</P>
<P>
   MARRIOTT WATERSIDE, 235 E. Main St., Norfolk, (757) 627-4200. An
unusually well-managed chain hotel, Norfolk's best, with
fascinating views over the ship-filled harbor from rooms on the
upper stories. Right in the middle of the downtown area, near
Waterside Marketplace, yet close to freeways. The 405 rooms are
bright and immaculate if not luxurious. The good-humored clerks and
bellmen act as if they enjoy what they do. Double room: $159 to
$179 a night.
</P>
<P>
   PAGE HOUSE INN, 313 Fairfax Ave., Norfolk, (757) 625-5033. Four
rooms, two suites, in a superbly refurbished Georgian Revival brick
mansion, built in 1898, with the leafy streets of the Ghent
district on the doorstep. This urban, urbane bed-and-breakfast is
so close to the Chrysler Museum of Art that you could come back at
midday to rest your feet for an hour or so if need be. Up-to-date
gear, including cable TV, modems and in-room fridges. Double room:
$116 to $185 a night.
</P>
<P>
   WILLIAMSBURG INN, Francis Street, Williamsburg, (757) 229-1000.
The region's premier establishment, owned by Colonial Williamsburg,
is sedate and agreeably old-fashioned. The decor is pure 1930s,
with quilted sateen bedspreads, swag curtains and flowered
wallpaper, but the bathrooms and air-conditioning are 1990's and
the sheets and towels are to die for. The staff is remarkably
friendly and accommodating. Killer breakfasts. Double room: $365 a
night.
</P>
<P>
   What to Eat
</P>
<P>
   FORD'S COLONY, 240 Ford's Colony Drive, Williamsburg, (757)
258-4100. Among his peers, David Everett is considered one of the
South's standout chefs. No wonder. In a formal dining room
overlooking a suburban golf course, he serves delicious,
technically accomplished dishes like a four-story tower of
tomatoes, blackened and spiced crabmeat and chopped cured salmon.
The wines are superb; the service, alas, is a little pompous.
</P>
<P>
   LUCKY STAR, 1608 Pleasure House Road, Virginia Beach, (757)
363-8410. Decorated with 1940s flea-market finds, this congenial
spot is tucked into a strip mall halfway between downtown Norfolk
and the beach. Butch Butt, once a fisherman, knows where to find
the best local, seasonal raw materials, and his partner, Amy
Brandt, cooks them simply and skillfully _ prime soft-shell crabs,
from the Atlantic, not the Bay; wild rockfish, cherrystone clams
from their place of origin, Cherrystone Creek on the Eastern Shore.
</P>
<P>
   PIERCE'S PITT BAR-B-QUE, 137 Rochambeau Drive, Lightfoot, (757)
565-2955. You won't miss it on the highway near Williamsburg, not
with its orange and red Day-Glo paint job. Pierce's is expanding
again. But the pitmaster sticks to tradition: succulent ribs and
pork shoulder, slow-cooked over oak and hickory logs. Pitt? A
sign-painter's mistake that stuck.
</P>
<P>
   SURREY HOUSE, Route 31, Surry, (757) 294-3389. A '50s roadhouse
in a little courthouse town near the James River ferry, serving
authentic, unadorned regional food: peanut soup, proper crab cakes,
dynamite country ham cured by S. Wallace Edwards &AMP; Sons, just down
the road, and lemon chess pie with a featherweight crust. Wanda,
the waitress, has the sweetest smile and softest voice this side of
heaven.
</P>
<P>
   TODD JURICH'S BISTRO, 210 W. York St., Norfolk, (757) 622-3210.
Norfolk's standout, an unpretentious room with paper tablecloths.
Jurich is a wizard with Eastern Shore shellfish; try his
mouthwateringly plump, juicy fried oysters or the irresistible
oyster stew, flavored with slivers of country bacon. Some dishes
have too many ingredients, but the wine list is exemplary and the
prices are minuscule (no starter above $8).
</P>
<P>
   TRELLIS, 403 Duke of Gloucester Street, Williamsburg, (757)
229-8610. Marcel Desaulniers is a noted cookbook author who
specializes in salads (spicy shrimp with shaved parmesan and
celery, marinated tuna with arugula) and satanically rich chocolate
desserts. The main courses taste better than they read, especially
the pan-fried chicken. More than a dozen Virginia wines, plus
plenty of others; the wait staff is overstretched.
</P>
<P>
   Attractions
</P>
<P>
   CHRYSLER MUSEUM OF ART, 245 W. Olney Road, Norfolk, (757)
664-6200. Hours: Tuesdays through Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.;
Sundays, 1 to 5 p.m. Admission: $6; $5, the elderly and students;
12 and under, free.
</P>
<P>
   ST. PAUL'S EPISCOPAL CHURCH, 201 St. Paul's Boulevard, Norfolk,
(757) 627-4353. Mondays through Fridays, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.; services
on Sunday at 8 and 10:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   MOSES MYERS HOUSE, 331 Bank St., Norfolk, (757) 664-6200. Open
Tuesdays through Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Sundays, 1 to 5 p.m.
Admission: $4; children 12 through college, those in active
military duty, teachers and the elderly, $2.50; children under 12
are free.
</P>
<P>
   OLD NORFOLK ACADEMY (HAMPTON ROADS CHAMBER OF COMMERCE), 420
