<HEADLINE>
ENVOYS OF SOUTH ASIAN RIVALS SAY TENSION IS EASING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One-year after tit-for-tat atomic weapons testing
in South Asia, two diplomats from India and Pakistan said Thursday
that tension between the rival countries had diminished along with
the threat of nuclear war.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a joint news conference, Riaz Khokhar, the Pakistani
ambassador to Washington, said ``the tension has certainly gone
down,'' adding, ``there is no reason for us to believe that there
is an imminent threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Naresh Chandra, India's ambassador to the United States, said,
``I don't think that tensions have gone up'' and noted that the two
countries signed an agreement in February to improve cooperation
and relations.
</P>
<P>
   India and Pakistan, which have fought three wars since they
gained independence from Britain in 1947, conducted a series of
nuclear tests last May and only last month test fired ballistic
missiles that can carry nuclear warheads and reach well into the
other's territory. The tests have sparked concerns of a nuclear
arms race on the volatile subcontinent.
</P>
<P>
   Both ambassadors said their countries seek to avoid an arms
race, although it remains uncertain whether either nation will sign
the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, an international agreement that
forbids nuclear weapons tests, by the September deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pakistan does not want a nuclear war. Pakistan is not looking
for an arms race. Pakistan is interested in revolving problems,''
Khokhar said. ``I hope that we ... could find solutions to our
problems so that we could get rid of the scourge of nuclear
weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   India backs nuclear disarmament if simmering issues over
contested territory can be resolved, said Chandra, who added that
his country was ``perfectly willing'' to give up its nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the optimism, the Carnegie Endowment for International
Peace, a nonpartisan think tank here, warned that the ballistic
missile tests and atomic detonations ``raise the specter of a
slowly developing regional arms race.''
</P>
<P>
   China, a traditional ally of Pakistan, might be drawn into a
regional arms race because it might feel threatened by India's
nuclear missiles that can reach Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``China will likely reassess its nuclear force structure and
posture towards India,'' the Carnegie Endowment said.
</P>
<P>
   India, with a population of nearly 1 billion people, and
Pakistan, with 133 million people, have been at odds over
territorial disputes, national boundaries and restive ethnic groups
for decades.
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at the email
address eric(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
