<HEADER>
A5058 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     05-20 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A `LESSON' WE COULD ALL LEARN FROM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A Lesson Before Dying'' begins and ends with murder _ the
murder of a shopkeeper and the murder of the man accused of pumping
bullets into the shopkeeper's chest.
</P>
<P>
   The accused is innocent, but no matter. He's strapped to a
chair, electrical currents ripping through his body until it no
longer moves.
</P>
<P>
   Being there _ in the shop, watching the shopkeeper go down _
cripples his defense. The location of his hands _ inside the cash
register _ seals his fate.
</P>
<P>
   It's 1947, rural Louisiana. The accused man is black, the dead
shopkeeper white. Quick trial. Quick sentence. Quick death.
</P>
<P>
   Wasn't much time to set things in order.
</P>
<P>
   Like dying with dignity.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Lesson Before Dying,'' airing at 9:30 p.m. EDT Saturday on
HBO, is based on Ernest J. Gaines' captivating novel about death
and despair, courage and triumph, dreams and inner
self-preservation.
</P>
<P>
   Neither junky nor clunky, puffed nor gimmicky, ``A Lesson Before
Dying'' arrives at just the right time in this month of bloated
silliness. It's subtle and moving, eloquent and powerful.
</P>
<P>
   You watch it and wonder why the networks, with their legions of
captive viewers, refuse to offer such movies free of sludgy
self-promotion and importance.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they feed us ``Cleopatra'' and ``Noah's Ark.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Lesson Before Dying'' focuses on Grant Wiggins (Don Cheadle,
certainly one of the most skilled actors today) who has returned to
teach in the small town where he was raised. Bitterly resigned to
racial injustice in the South, he is saddled with anger and
ambition, which fuel his dreams of escaping the second-class life
of a black man in a difficult time.
</P>
<P>
   He's realistic in his wants and needs and goals: He's no messiah
in the tiny town that has need of his composure and strength and
hope.
</P>
<P>
   When Jefferson _ his only name _ (Mekhi Phifer) is sentenced to
die, Grant is asked to visit the jail cell, to give him hope.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson was a poor lad with little schooling. He spent most of
his time fishing and trying to stay out of trouble. Trouble came
looking for him in the form of two buddies who gave him a lift to
his favorite watering hole. They stopped off at the shop where
things get out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   When the shopkeeper pulls a gun, the two men pull theirs. All go
down in a flurry of bullets. Jefferson goes for the cash register,
just as a crowd of men bursts in. White men. Case closed.
</P>
<P>
   The game plan for Jefferson's defense: He's a brainless,
subhuman mutant unable to think. He was bred to work in the fields,
nothing more. Killing him would be akin to slaying a hog.
</P>
<P>
   The jury decides to slay the hog.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Lesson Before Dying'' also stars Cicely Tyson, Lisa
Arrindell Anderson and Irma P. Hall, in a dead-on performance as
Jefferson's suffering guardian.
</P>
<P>
   Director Joseph Sargent crafts this film with a sensitive hand.
But what's best about the production is its subtle nudging about
education and life's affirmations and God's place in all this.
Meeting with Jefferson in the tiny jail cell, Grant learns the most
lessons. About race, about friendship, about courage. Scenes are
played out with understated restraint and yet with so much tension.
</P>
<P>
   Gaines' more complex literary themes are woven into the fabric,
illuminating situations that often seem rather simple on the
surface. And ``A Lesson Before Dying'' manages to reflect the
book's issues _ issues that take place within a community of
African-Americans. Issues rarely talked about.
</P>
<P>
   The parallel journeys undertaken by the two key figures make for
a fascinating exploration.
</P>
<P>
   Give it a sample. Then shelve ``A Lesson Before Dying'' _ the
book and the movie _ right up there with ``Sounder'' and other
classics examining the black condition.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
