<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5059 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RADIOACTIVE-WASTE-$AD     05-20 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIOACTIVE-WASTE-$ADV23-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS LAMENT RADIOACTIVE DETOUR THROUGH CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May. 23)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Over the protests of California's two senators,
trucks bearing tons of low-level radioactive waste from around the
country may start rumbling through the Golden State's desert near
Death Valley next month on a circuitous path to a dump site in
Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Under an Energy Department plan, truckers hauling waste
generated in the East and Midwest can select from four routes to a
government repository for spent radioactive material called the
Nevada Test Site, about 65 miles northwest of Las Vegas. Two routes
approach the facility from the east, while the other two detour
through eastern California.
</P>
<P>
   While the government says that thousands of shipments of such
waste using specially lined containers have been transferred from
facility to facility without incident since 1961, environmental
groups are questioning the safety of nuclear waste in transit.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Dianne Feinstein and Barbara Boxer, both California
Democrats, have raised the issue by noting that the detours involve
roads that are not as good as the interstate highways that the
waste trucks usually take.
</P>
<P>
   The waste that could cross into California includes contaminated
debris, soil, sludge, concrete, wood and lab equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the Energy Department asked 15 government
and private plants around the country that generate the waste _
mainly the byproduct of nuclear weapons manufacturing _ to avoid
current truck-shipping routes through Las Vegas and over the Hoover
Dam, where massive road construction is under way and delays are
commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Energy Secretary Bill Richardson on May 12,
Feinstein and Boxer wrote, ``As 90 percent of these shipments are
from defense facilities to the east, we do not understand the
rationale for diverting shipments into California, only then to
reverse direction and proceed east to the Nevada Test Site.''
</P>
<P>
   The two paths through California would put truckers on rural
roadways that are not as well maintained and as safe as the
interstates.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the waste shipments ``have traveled on more direct
routes for many years,'' the senators insisted that ``the current
interstate highway routes are most appropriate'' for them. They
added, ``There is no supportable reason for moving these
transportation routes into California, or for using roads of lesser
quality for these shipments.''
</P>
<P>
   They particularly objected to the proposed use of State Route
127, which they said ``is a primary access route for tourist
traffic to Death Valley National Park.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson hasn't responded to the lawmakers but in a statement
to the Hearst Newspapers said, ``We will continue to work with the
senators, the state of California and the counties of Inyo and San
Bernardino on this issue.'' The counties contain the proposed
alternate routes.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure for a route change to bypass Las Vegas grew after a
1997 incident in which a truck hauling some radioactive waste from
an Ohio nuclear weapons plant leaked some of its liquid cargo in
Kingman, Ariz., 110 miles southeast of Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The liquid itself was not radioactive, but the incident sparked
a safety review and a 16-month moratorium of shipments to Nevada
from the facility, the Fernald Enviornmental Management Project
outside Cincinatti.
</P>
<P>
   Responsibility for shipping waste rests with the 15 individual
weapons plants, four of which are in California, which select
private companies for the task. The routes taken to the Nevada Test
Site are determined by the shipping companies. They take into
consideration the Energy Department's suggested routes but are not
required to travel them.
</P>
<P>
   Darwin Morgan, an Energy Department spokesman in Las Vegas, said
that so far no low-level radioactive waste generated outside
California has crossed the state en route to Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   The department is also considering possible train shipments to
Nevada and is conducting a environmental assessment of the idea,
said Michael Giblin, an Energy Department environmental adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Fernald already has begun rail shipments of radioactive dirt to
a Utah landfill.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Environmental groups are concerned that an accident involving
nuclear waste in transit could have terrible consequences. Large
swaths of land could be contaminated, said Diane D'Arrigo,
radioactive waste project director for the Nuclear Information and
Resource Service.
</P>
<P>
   A rail accident could be even more dangerous, said the Safe
Energy Communication Council in Washington, D.C. ``With
approximately 3.7 accidents per million train miles each year, an
accident involving a train carrying nuclear waste is more than just
a statistical probability,'' the group said.
</P>
<P>
   But Morgan noted the good safety record of transporting such
waste and said the material from the 15 plants has such a low level
of radioactivity that workers aren't required to wear special
clothing when handling it.
</P>
<P>
   Local fire departments and state police already are versed in
how to handle such a clean up, Morgan added. ``In almost all cases,
it's a simple as coming in with shovels and front end loaders and
putting it back in boxes,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the Energy Department's plan for alternative routes around
Las Vegas, trucks zig-zagging over one would travel on 53 miles of
California roads. Vehicles approaching Las Vegas from the south in
Nevada would turn west into California on Interstate 40 for 20
miles then head north on U.S. 95 just past Needles for another 20
miles. They would cross back into Nevada for 20 miles, then turn
west on Route 164 only to return to California and connect to
Interstate 15 heading north for 13 miles and cross back again into
Nevada for another 100 miles to the test site.
</P>
<P>
   In another circuitous path, trucks would travel on the same 53
miles of California roads. But at Interstate 15, near Nipton,
Calif., they would head 40 miles southwest toward the interior of
the state before turning north for 80 miles on Route 127 in a
region known as the Devil's Playground until they reach the Nevada
border. The Nevada Test Site is 35 miles from that point.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 1810EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
