<HEADER>
A5064 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-0521-     05-20 0392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-0521-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BIPARTISAN SOCIAL SECURITY REFORM PLAN UNVEILED
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (a) general news categories
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bipartisan proposal to reform Social Security by
using a portion of payroll taxes to finance individual savings
accounts from birth to retirement was unveiled Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we have moved the debate past the argument of
whether there should be private investment to how private
investment should be done,'' said Sen. John Breaux, D-La. ``There
is a growing consensus that we can strengthen the safety net
provided by Social Security while at the same time providing
Americans with more investment opportunities and retirement
choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaux offered the plan -- which would divert 2 percentage
points of the 12.4 percent payroll tax into individual investment
accounts -- as a ``mainstream'' alternative to ones offered by the
Clinton administration and Republican leaders of the House Ways and
Means Committee, and as one that could ``build support from the
center out.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would use the projected federal surplus to supplement
voluntary contributions workers could make to their retirement
accounts. Workers would receive a $100 supplement from the
government for their first dollar voluntarily contributed and then
a dollar-for-dollar match on contributions up to 1 percent of the
taxable wage base for Social Security -- $726 in 1999. Workers
could contribute up to $2,000 to their individual accounts
annually.
</P>
<P>
   Children born after 1995 (CQ) would receive a Social Security
account worth $1,000 at birth. Another $500 a year would be added
for the next five years, for a total of $3,500.
</P>
<P>
   Like several other plans being offered in Congress, the proposal
by Breaux and Sen. Gregg Judd, R-N.H., would eliminate the
``earnings test'' that reduces Social Security benefits for workers
aged 65-to-69.
</P>
<P>
   It also would accelerate an increase in the eligibility age to
67 for full benefits, from the year 2027 to 2011.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday, after meeting President Clinton, House Ways and
Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer said he would hold hearings
this summer on proposals to strengthen Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
