<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYLITE(SMILE)-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 May 20, 1999  
 (These items may be published)  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; RIVERDANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A southern minister was completing a temperance sermon. With
great expression he said, `If I had all the beer in the world, I'd
take it and pour it into the river.`
</P>
<P>
   With even greater emphasis he said, `And if I had all the wine
in the world, I'd take it and pour it into the river.`
</P>
<P>
   And then finally, he said, `And if I had all the whiskey in the
world, I'd take it and pour it into the river.` Sermon complete, he
then sat down.
</P>
<P>
   The song leader stood very cautiously and announced with a
smile, `For our closing song, let us sing Hymn (NU)365: 'Shall We
Gather at the River'.`
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SECOND TIME AROUND &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A prospective juror in a Dallas District Court was surprised by
the definition of voluntary manslaughter given the panel...`an
intentional killing that occurs while the defendant is under the
immediate influence of sudden passion arising from an adequate
cause, such as when a spouse's mate is found in a 'compromising
position.'`
</P>
<P>
   `See, I have a problem with that passion business,` responded
the jury candidate. `During my first marriage, I came in and found
my husband in bed with my neighbor. All I did was divorce him. I
had no idea that I could have shot him.`
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WINE, WOMEN AND FOOD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A man is walking down the beach and comes across an old bottle.
He picks it up, pulls out the cork and out pops a genie.
</P>
<P>
   The genie says, `Thank you for freeing me from the bottle. In
return I will grant you three wishes.`
</P>
<P>
   The man says `Great! I always dreamed of this and I know exactly
what I want. First, I want one billion dollars in a Swiss bank
account.` Poof! There is a flash of light and a piece of paper with
account numbers appears in his hand. He continues, `Next, I want a
brand new red Ferrari right here.` Poof! There is a flash of light
and a bright red brand-new Ferrari appears right next to him. He
continues, `Finally, I want to be irresistible to women.` Poof!
</P>
<P>
   There is a flash of light and he turns into a box of chocolates.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DEATH AND THE JEWISH MOTHER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Mothers come in all shapes and sizes. For example, an Italian
Mother might chastise her offspring for not eating by saying, `Eat
your dinner, or I'll kill you.`
</P>
<P>
   A Jewish Mother on the other hand would say, `Eat your dinner,
or I'll kill myself.`
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE FROM GEORGE CARLIN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Don't sweat the petty things and don't pet the sweaty things.
</P>
<P>
   One tequila, two tequila, three tequila, floor.
</P>
<P>
   If man evolved from monkeys and apes, why do we still have
monkeys and apes?
</P>
<P>
   The main reason Santa is so jolly is because he knows where all
the bad girls live.
</P>
<P>
   I went to a bookstore and asked the saleswoman, `Where's the
self-help section?` She said if she told me, it would defeat the
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that all those trick-or-treaters wearing sheets
aren't going as ghosts but as mattresses?
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it a bit unnerving that doctors call what they do
`practice?`
</P>
<P>
   Where do forest rangers go to `get away from it all?`
</P>
<P>
   What do you do when you see an endangered animal eating an
endangered plant?
</P>
<P>
   Would a fly without wings be called a walk?
</P>
<P>
   Why do they lock gas station bathrooms? Are they afraid someone
will clean them?
</P>
<P>
   Why don't sheep shrink when it rains?
</P>
<P>
   How do they get the deer to cross at that yellow road sign?
</P>
<P>
   What was the best thing before sliced bread?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Very early one recent morning I left a West Side coffee shop and
was greeted by an attractive woman with an exuberant ``Hi, honey!''
Recovering my composure, I responded that I had always dreamed of
being greeted so warmly by a beautiful woman first thing in the
morning.
</P>
<P>
   It was only then I realized that she had been speaking to her
dog, which she had tethered outside the coffee shop and which, in
the 10 or so seconds in which this had all transpired, had walked
several circles around me, effectively trapping me within its
leash. The woman said with a smile, ``Was being tied up part of
your dream?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' I answered. ``That's probably a West Side thing. I live
in New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   _JOEL RAVEN
</P>
<P>
   Sign of the times: Fred Ehrman was walking along 55th Street
recently when he noticed four burly constuction workers sitting on
the sidewalk, eating their breakfast and deep in conversation. An
attractive woman passed in front of them but none of the men looked
her way. As Mr. Ehrman passed by the men he overheard the following
exchange:
</P>
<P>
   First worker: ``So what happened last week?''
</P>
<P>
   Second worker: ``Telephone and the Internets had big drops but I
made up that decline with my cyclicals and financials.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Ehrman's postscript: ``I found myself ironically nostalgic
for those old leering whistles.''
</P>
<P>
   On the 86th Street crosstown bus recently, a passenger picked up
something from the floor and gave it to the driver. The driver then
announced: ``Someone just found a clip-on earring. Everyone check
to see if it's yours. That goes for both men and women.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the passengers laughed and checked their ears. But the
perfectly groomed woman seated next to me declared in an
exasperated tone, ``Men don't wear clip-ons.'' _ DONALD J.
CHRISTENSEN
</P>
<P>
   Can you lose 20 years in a matter of minutes? Yes!
</P>
<P>
   A grandmother of three boys, I was standing on a bus, crowded
with schoolchildren, going to meet my pregnant daughter. I was
holding a book that I was planning to give her, ``What to Name Your
Baby Girl.'' A boy about 10 years old, who was sitting in front of
me, obviously noticed the title of the book. He looked at me and
asked, ``Would you like to sit down?''
</P>
<P>
   I didn't take him up on his offer because I was getting off
soon, but when I did alight it was with a wide grin on my face and
a more sprightly spring to my grandmotherly step.
</P>
<P>
   _ELAINE ARDEN
</P>
<P>
   Marjorie J. Witherspoon, who recently moved to Manhattan, was
interested to observe the difference between the freedom her
children enjoyed growing up in Vermont and the routine enjoyed, or
at least employed, by some youngsters here. She noticed a boy about
10 or 11 leaving a store on the West Side, walkie-talkie in hand,
reporting, ``I'm the leaving the store now.'' Walking behind him as
they came to the first crossing, she heard him call again, ``I'm at
109th.''
</P>
<P>
   At the next corner, the boy apparently couldn't get a response _
there was an anxious query of ``Dad, Dad.'' An exasperated voice
responded, ``Give it a rest, Greg.'' The youngster ignored the
advice _ at the next block he again reported his location. How long
the two-way communication went on isn't known _ Ms. Witherspoon
veered off.
</P>
<P>
   Elly Elliott wondered whether it was a slip of the tongue or a
sign of the times. She recently heard the announcer on a classical
music program say that the next composition to be played would be
``a work by Smetana _ the overture to `The Battered Bride.'''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Fifty years ago, with my Army discharge and brand new N.Y.U.
degree in finance, I was hired as a trainee at one of the large
prestigious banks on Wall Street. The president, a tall,
distinguished- looking former Ivy League football player,
occasionally descended from his aerie and spoke to the trainees.
His talk went something like this: ``You men are the future of this
bank _ you will be calling on the General Electrics and I.B.M.'s of
the nation. When a man from our bank steps into a meeting, I expect
that his bearing and demeanor will be such that a hush will come
over the room.''
</P>
<P>
   That night, flush with the image of myself as a corporate
leader, I looked in the mirror at the East Side tenement in which I
had grown up. What I saw was a 130-pound, 5 foot 5 inch,
24-year-old with a receding chin who looked closer to 16. I said to
myself, ``That son of agun was not talking about me.'' Right then
I decided to resign. Many years later, I became president of a
much, much smaller bank. And what kind of young men did I hire to
represent it? Yes, football-player types with a firm handshake who
could enter a room and be noticed.
</P>
<P>
   _ GEORGE TREBAT
</P>
<P>
   I was avoiding the abandoned umbrellas and pleas for a quarter
on the Bowery when I looked up to see a rainbow stretching over the
East Village. In front of the Jean Cocteau Theater, I stopped and
stood with half-a-dozen early playgoers, admiring the sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine that, a rainbow in New York,'' an elderly woman
remarked. Further up the block, I exchanged smiles with a man
hurrying along.
</P>
<P>
   By Cooper Union, I looked up and the rainbow had dissipated into
pink, blue and orange blotches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, at least we had it with us for a little while,'' a
stranger who noticed me looking up commented.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks later at an intersection,. a car tried to jump the
light and honked at me. Walking past his fender, I gave him my best
city scowl and looked up to see the sky gray once again.
</P>
<P>
   _G. SOKOLOW
</P>
<P>
   One day, Elayne Rosen's 85-year-old mother had instant recall
about a year-old incident. Later the same day, though, Ms. Rosen
asked about something that had happened a few hours earlier. Her
motherenid doesn't have name. replied, ``I can remember last year
but you'd better call me next year about today's question.''
</P>
<P>
   Very early one recent morning I left a West Side coffee shop and
was greeted by an attractive woman with an exuberant ``Hi, honey!''
Recovering my composure, I responded that I had always dreamed of
being greeted so warmly by a beautiful woman first thing in the
morning.
</P>
<P>
   It was only then I realized that she had been speaking to her
dog, which she had tethered outside the coffee shop and which, in
the 10 or so seconds in which this had all transpired, had walked
several circles around me, effectively trapping me within its
leash. The woman said with a smile, ``Was being tied up part of
your dream?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' I answered. ``That's probably a West Side thing. I live
in New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: THE FOLLOWING NYLITE REMINISCENCE FIRST APPEARED TWO
YEARS AGO. WE REPEAT IT ON REQUEST) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Every year, I get the itch to do it again. &QL; 
It doesn't last long. All I have to go is go down to the field, and
 &QL; 
stick around for one inning. After the first crying tantrum, thrown
helmet, misplaced glove, `Coach, when do I go in,' and `Hey, why
isn't my kid playing,' I get back in the car, drive home, let the
dog out to chase squirrels,  &QL; 
open a beer, turn on the TV and feel sorry for anyone who has to
deal with  &QL; 
10-year-old prima donnas. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Some tips to Little League coaches: &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. Do not draft any kid who has a father, mother, grandparents, or
lives with any adults who might come to watch him play. &QL; 
 &QL; 
2. The neater the kid, the cleaner the shoes, the newer the glove,
the worse the kid plays. There are no exceptions to this rule. Only
dirty kids with torn shoes and old gloves have any talent. &QL; 
 &QL; 
3. Never offer to drive a kid home. The ones who need rides never
live near &QL; 
you and they never know how to get to their house. &QL; 
 &QL; 
4. Tell the fattest kid on the team that he is the catcher. This is
how we keep the stereotype alive. You have an obligation to do so. &QL; 
 &QL; 
5. Ask at the first practice who wants to be catcher. Then,
announce  &QL; 
that the catcher will always get to be first in line for pizza or
ice cream after the game. Then offer ten bucks a game. No one will
have volunteered. &QL; 
Then tell the fat kid he's the one. &QL; 
 &QL; 
6. Basic phrase for keeping fathers away from the fence: ``I can
always tell which father is here for more than just to watch his
own kid. The one who's always going to be there to help when I need
him. The one who has time for all the kids, not just his own.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
7. Kids don't get hurt. They're kids. They only twist their ankle
when they get picked off base. They only hurt their arm after one
of their throws lands in the refreshment stand. They only have
stomach aches when they are in the on-deck circle in the last
inning with the bases loaded. Don't panic. Walk over to the
stricken kid, carrying the water jug subtly under your arm. Tell
him to get up, get on with the game, or you'll pour water on him
and announce that he wet his pants.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
8. Never coach third base. Put someone there you really hate. And
then practice screaming, ``How could you send him in that
situation, you just cost us the game!''and ``Why did you hold him
up, they never could have thrown him out!''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
9. There will be kids you can't stand. Here's how to have fun with
them. Ask them if they are wearing protective cups, like they are
supposed to. These are the kind of kids who never do, but tell you
they are. Pick up a bat and jab them in the crotch. They will
collapse in pain. You'll feel better and they will have learned a
lesson in why to wear a cup and why not to tell a lie. &QL; 
 &QL; 
10. Practice rotating your clipboard 180 degrees with one hand.
This will come in handy when a parent complains about your
coaching. And then, look him  &QL; 
straight in the face, stare into his eyes, flip the clipboard and
say, `Here, you take over, I'm going home.' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; TIPS TO LITTLE LEAGUE COACHES ON HOW TO BEAT THEIR OPPONENT'S
BUTT. &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Forget the 9-man lineups you see on television. You only have
three kids who can really play. Bat them 1-2-3 in the lineup. They
get up more, the team scores more, you win more. You're a genius.
</P>
<P>
   Cleanup? An interesting concept. People with concepts rake the
field after the game.
</P>
<P>
   2. Remember the neighborhood game running bases? Same principle.
The way to beat 10-year-olds is to make them throw the ball and
catch it. Most of them don't do either very well. If a kid gets a
hit, tell him to keep running.
</P>
<P>
   The fielder has to throw the ball to the next base where someone
has to catch it and make the tag while keeping the ball securely in
the glove. Guess the odds of that happening.
</P>
<P>
   Some sourpuss will whine that this strategy is not in the spirit
of the game. Tell him the spirit of the game went out with the
designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   3. Pretend you feel sorry for the opposing pitcher when he walks
six batters in a row. Try not to laugh when you tell him to `relax,
take your time, and just get it over.'
</P>
<P>
   Want to see a kid walk TEN batters in a row? Tell him to relax,
take his time, and just get it over.'
</P>
<P>
   4. Chances are, the umpires will be high-school age kids out to
make a buck. When the other coach yells at him over a call get up
and say `It doesn't matter how young you are, YOU'RE in charge
here!'
</P>
<P>
   When he tells you to shut up later in the game for challenging a
call, walk out on the field and tell him for all to hear, `Don't
you EVER talk to an adult like that!' His spirit is now broken. You
should get every call from that point on.
</P>
<P>
   5. Just like you have only three hitters (if you are lucky), you
only have three kids who can catch the ball _ usually your
shortstop (your kid, since you're the coach,) your pitcher (thereby
costing you a fielder) and your firstbaseman (maybe). Remember who
is in the outfield and why you put them out there in the first
place. In other words, anything your shortstop, pitcher or first
baseman can reach is theirs.
</P>
<P>
   6. If the outfielder MUST try to make a catch, (he won't) send
your shortstop, first baseman and yes, even your pitcher, out to
get the ball as fast as possible. You can try to train your
outfielders to move to the ball quickly by constantly yelling at
them to `GET IT IN,' but the season will be almost over before they
realize you aren't telling them that their fly is open. 7. The
worst brats in the world are little league pitchers. They are prima
donnas who have been told by their fathers and grandmothers that
they are great. They are crybabies who think the umpire is out to
get them and there hasn't ever been a ball hit that a little league
pitcher didn't think someone should have caught.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how to drive him nuts. Runner on third, next batter
walks. There is nothing in the rules that says the batter has to
stop at first. Tell him to keep running. The pitcher, being the
little superstar he is, will try to get the runner at second. The
runner on third will romp home with an easy run. The pitcher will
literally stomp his feet and look around everywhere to find someone
to blame. He will then walk at least six batters in a row,
particularly after you tell him to relax and just get it over.
</P>
<P>
   8. Select a good-looking mother to keep the scorebook during the
long, lonely season. Oh, you would rather share the bench with
someone who has a knowledge of the game. Good concept.
</P>
<P>
   9. Oh, no, the umpire didn't show up!
</P>
<P>
   This is a real gift! Walk over to the other side, put on your
best poker face and ask the other team's parents if someone would
like to call the game. The idiots on your side will go nuts,
thinking you really blew it this time. But you know better. As he
takes the field, tell the volunteer that even though everyone
thinks he is going to cheat, you know better. You will get every
close call all day.
</P>
<P>
   10. After the game, divide the equipment bags by putting one bat
in one bag and the other 50 pounds of bats, balls, helmets, etc.,
in the other. When `dad' approaches to ask why Jason only played
two innings, stop and pretend you really want to discuss it with
him. Ask him to help you carry the gear to the car, giving him the
heavy one. Walk to the car as fast as you can while 'dad' drags the
load, trying to keep up with you. When you get to the car, take off
for home. Don't worry, he'll bring the gear to the next game or
Jason won't play at all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
