u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-LEGISLATURE-HNS &LR;      05-20 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-LEGISLATURE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH VISITS TEXAS SENATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With virtually all of Gov. George W. Bush's
legislative agenda still pending while the clock rapidly winds
down, Bush on Thursday paid his first visit to the Texas Senate in
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a while since I've been in the chamber,'' Bush said.
``The reason I came by today is that we're heading toward the end
of the session and it's a chance to make my presence felt.''
</P>
<P>
   Reminded that critics have said he has spent too little time on
state matters and has been preoccupied with his likely presidential
run, Bush said:
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be people who figure out ways if something
doesn't go their way or something's not perfect, they all blame
presidential politics,'' he said. ``I said at my state-of-the-state
(address), let's not let the speculation get in the way of us
having a successful session, and I believe we're going to have a
successful session.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said it was merely coincidental his visit occurred the same
day Republican members were trying to rally sufficient support to
amend a controversial voucher program to a House bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't aware the voucher bill was coming up until the
lieutenant governor informed me,'' Bush said. ``I'm not here to
lobby for a piece of legislation. I'm here to make my presence
known.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called the lieutenant governor and asked him if it would be
appropriate for me to come and say `hello' to some of the senators
on the floor,'' Bush added. ``We've got less than two weeks to go
to get the session over with, and I think it's good for me to be
saying hello to people. A lot of the senators have been coming to
my office; some of them haven't and I need to visit with them.``
</P>
<P>
   But he also acknowledged that talk of the voucher bill arose as
he greeted senators on the floor and that he encouraged them ``to
vote for my agenda and for Lt. Gov. Perry's agenda.``
</P>
<P>
   And he gave Perry, the first Republican to serve in that post
since Reconstruction, high marks for his first session.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done a very good job,'' Bush said. ``I think any
objective observer will give him good very good marks for running a
good session.''
</P>
<P>
   As for those who accuse Bush of ignoring what's been happening
in the Capitol, the governor said they don't know what they're
talking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those people must not be paying attention to what I'm doing,''
he said. ``I meet with people all the time from both parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the state budget hammered out by a conference
committee has yet to be approved, and the school finance bill _
which contains components for his key property tax cut proposals _
did not make it out of &UR;  &LR; the House Education Committee until
Thursday afternoon. Bush's proposal to end social promotion also is
hung in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the session is going well,'' Bush added. ``I'm pleased
with much of the progress that's being made. ... I think the key is
going to be what happens at the end of the session as to determine
how effective we have all been in doing what's right for Texas.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
