<HEADER>
A5073 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     05-20 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTEWORTHY MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy movies currently playing in theaters. Running
times and ratings of films are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   `AFTER LIFE,' starring Arata, Taketoshi Naito and Erika Oda.
Written, directed and edited by Hirokazu Kore-eda (not rated, 118
minutes). Much of this transcendently compassionate, gently
humorous Japanese film is set in a drab office building where
courteous caseworkers welcome the week's new clients. The place
turns out not to be a social service agency but a metaphysical way
station where the newcomers are people of all ages and types who
have just died and have three days to select one memory to take
with them into eternity. Before they depart, those memories will be
filmed. As they tell their stories and make their choices (those
who can't choose remain at the processing center as caseworkers),
the movie becomes a profound meditation on life's meaning and value
and the relationship of movies, memories and dreams (Stephen
Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `COOKIE'S FORTUNE,' starring Charles Dutton, Glenn Close,
Patricia Neal, Julianne Moore and Liv Tyler. Directed by Robert
Altman (PG-13, 118 minutes). What a treat. The sweet assurance and
guerrilla wit of Altman's vintage ensemble films make a copacetic
return with a Southern small-town black comedy. Seamlessly made and
completely enveloping, it tells of the machinations set off when a
wealthy old woman (Ms. Neal) outrages her diabolically genteel
niece (Ms. Close) by committing suicide. As the old woman's dearest
friend and the niece's unwitting nemesis, Dutton is rock solid and
appealing. The entire cast works on a single wavelength as Altman
makes the most of a well-woven screenplay by Anne Rapp (Janet
Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE DREAMLIFE OF ANGELS,' starring Elodie Bouchez and Natacha
Regnier. Directed by Erick Zonca (R, 113 minutes; in French with
English subtitles). In this very special French film about two
freewheeling young women, their turbulent friendship is frayed by
sexual passion and economic realities. The weaker and more
head-turning of the women (Ms. Regnier) falls for the advances of a
rich nightclub owner, while her fiery friend, played with
unforgettable immediacy by Ms. Bouchez, rages against what she
views as imminent disaster. In the process, Zonca shows astonishing
acuity in observing how the women's diverging values affect every
aspect of their lives. A rare and wrenching drama (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `EDGE OF 17,' starring Chris Stafford and Tina Holmes. Directed
by David Moreton (not rated, 100 minutes). It's 1984 in Sandusky,
Ohio, and Eric (Chris Stafford), a skinny, fresh-faced high school
student who worships the Eurythmics and Culture Club, has his first
homosexual experiences. This is not boy-meets-boy (Romeo meets
Romeo and they fall madly in love) but boy is used and confused and
tries to go straight by sleeping with his former girlfriend. The
teen-age coming-out story is realistic but warmhearted, the best
among the recent gay coming-out films (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `ELECTION,' starring Matthew Broderick and Reese Witherspoon.
Directed by Alexander Payne (R, 105 minutes). From the acerbically
funny director of `Citizen Ruth' comes this caustic satire of the
American electoral process in a high school setting. Its leading
candidate, Tracy Flick, played tartly by Ms. Witherspoon, has a
mother who sought tactical advice for Tracy from Connie Chung and
Elizabeth Dole. Broderick plays the hapless good-guy teacher who
thinks this wicked little front-runner needs to be stopped. And the
hunky newcomer Chris Klein plays Tracy's reluctant opponent in a
style best described as early Keanu. With a lovely ear for
hypocritical conversation, the screenplay specializes in keeping
all the characters a few beats off what they actually mean
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `ENTRAPMENT,' starring Sean Connery and Catherine Zeta-Jones.
Directed by Jon Amiel (PG-13, 105 minutes). This glossy caper
summons the days when being a thief was the profession of choice
among debonair movie heroes. And heroines: As the great-looking
insurance investigator who is supposedly investigating Connery's
glamorous super-burglar, Ms. Zeta-Jones makes a smashing gymnast
and heist expert in her own right. No need to believe the
outlandish details of the story; there's enough verve and charisma
to the stars to make the escapade easy on the eyes. The action
sequence, in which the stars hang off the side of the world's
largest skyscraper, is a vertiginous show stopper. And here's a
nice bonus: Nobody gets killed (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `LEILA,' starring Leila Hatami, Ali Mosaffa and Jamileh Sheikhi.
Directed by Dariush Mehrjui (not rated, 129 minutes). The
devastating drama of a happy marriage destroyed by a monstrous
mother-in-law is the latest cinematic gem from Iran. Think of it as
a contemporary Islamic `Now Voyager' skimmed of suds, in which the
tyrannical matriarch gets her way. On learning that Leila (Ms.
Hatami), the wife of her only son, Reza (Mosaffa), is infertile,
Leila's mother-in-law (Ms. Sheikhi) embarks on a campaign of
intimidation to convince her daughter-in-law to let Reza take a
second wife who might bear him a child. Although Reza claims not to
want a child, the mother-in-law shames Leila into being her
collaborator in the scheme. Minutely observed, beautifully acted,
relentless (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `THE MATRIX,' starring Keanu Reeves, Laurence Fishburne and
Carrie-Anne Moss. Directed by Andy and Larry Wachowski (R, 120
minutes). The time-traveling story steeped in virtual reality will
be all but incomprehensible to anyone but techno freaks. And the
film borrows unapologetically from other sci-fi extravaganzas, with
a big debt to `The X-Files' in the paranoia department. But the
storytelling is intricately bizarre and the special effects are
indeed special, notably when it comes to midair martial arts with a
gravity-defying gusto. And Reeves shows that you can look like a
Prada model while behaving like an action hero. One of the main
stars here is Bill Pope, an inventive cinematographer. He and the
Wachowskis provide a couch-potato epiphany: While the characters
seem to be performing marvelous feats, they're often lying
stock-still in the grip of virtual reality (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `A MIDSUMMER NIGHT'S DREAM,' starring Kevin Kline, Rupert
Everett, Michelle Pfeiffer and Calista Flockhart. Directed by
Michael Hoffman (PG-13, 115 minutes). This is potluck Shakespeare,
with a wildly uneven range of performances and no clear style
holding them together. Rather than wonder why the actors are
wrestling with bicycles in 19th-century Tuscany (a setting used
much less enchantingly than it might have been), it's best to focus
on the most comfortably Shakespearean performances and not wonder
what Ms. Flockhart is doing here. Kline makes a perfect Bottom,
Everett slinks seductively through Oberon's role and Ms. Pfeiffer
makes an appropriately gorgeous fairy queen. The younger cast
members are largely used as window dressing for the Leo-Does-Romeo
set (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
