<HEADER>
A5076 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPOT-BUDGET-BOS &LR;      05-20 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
  
 For Release FRIDAY AMs, May 21, 1999  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONFLICT IN THE BALKANS &LR;   &UR; (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA (New York) _ Faced with increasing calls for a halt
in NATO's bombing campaign, President Clinton appeals to his
European counterparts to remain tough, vowing to carry on the air
war until Belgrade meets all of NATO's demands. By Colum Lynch and
Kevin Cullen. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-BOMBING (Belgrade) _ At least four people die when a
NATO missile that went astray crashes into hospital intensive care
unit. By Kevin Cullen. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   ALBANIA-AID (Tirana, Albania) _ NATO says it will supply
long-term military aid to Albania and Macedonia and draw up plans
to help get the two Balkan countries into the alliance. By Lynda
Gorov. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TIANANMEN (Beijing) _ With two weeks to go before the 10th
anniversary of the massacre of democracy demonstrators around
Tiananmen Square, Chinese authorities detain several key dissidents
and heighten surveillance of many others. By Indira A.R.
Lakshmanan. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-GUNS (Washington) _ Vice President Gore breaks a 50-50
tie in favor of a proposal to require mandatory background checks
for purchases at gun shows and to put new restrictions on pawnshop
sales as well. By Michael Kranish. 1250 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-PRECAUTIONS (Undated) _ Foreboding envelops schools, an
uneasy sense that the angry kid, or the outcast kid, or the kid no
one would ever expect might suddenly erupt in violence. In
response, some schools are taking extraodinary precautionary steps.
By Mitchell Zuckoff. 1300 words.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA-SHOOTING (Washington) _ On the one-month anniversary of
the Columbine massacre, a student opens fire on his classmates. The
suspect, a sophomore, flinches at killing himself. By Anne E.
Kornblut. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   CELLUCCI-GEORGES (Boston) _ Gov. Paul Cellucci cautiously
endorses oil and gas exploration on the Canadian side of the
Georges Bank fishing ground, drawing a wave of international
criticism. By Scott Allen. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NEWENGLAND-ECONOMY (Boston) _ Job growth around New England is
going to slow sharply this year and next, a group of economists say
in their semiannual forecasts for the region. By Kimberly Blanton.
600 words.
</P>
<P>
   GTE-BIDDERS (Undated) _ Most bidders for GTE Corp.'s
defense-electronics units are interested in buying fragments of the
company, rather than the whole division. By Ross Kerber. 500 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKEES-REDSOX (Boston) _ By Gordon Edes.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   BBA-REDSOX-COMMENT (Boston) _ By Larry Whiteside.
</P>
<P>
   w/
