<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5077 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTA     05-20 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: set (Maslin). 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `THE MUMMY,' starring Brendan Fraser Rachel Weisz, Arnold Vosloo
and John Hannah. Directed by Stephen Sommers (PG-13, 134 minutes).
More like a video game than a movie, this incoherent spoof (very
loosely based on the 1932 Boris Karloff horror classic), overloaded
with cheesy special effects, suggests an unwieldy hybrid of
`Raiders of the Lost Ark' and `Abbott and Costello Meet the Mummy'
via `Night of the Living Dead.' The intrepid adventurers who
disturb an ancient Egyptian crypt that carries a fearful curse are
Fraser (playing a swashbuckling American in the Foreign Legion),
Ms. Weisz (as a plucky, wide-eyed English librarian) and John
Hannah (as her twitty older brother). It's all played for laughs.
The only scary moments involve swarming scarabs who burrow under
the skin and do awful `Alien'-like things (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `SHAKESPEARE IN LOVE' (the Oscar winner for best film, best
original screenplay, best art direction, best costumes and best
comedy score). Starring Joseph Fiennes, Gwyneth Paltrow (the
best-actress winner) and Judi Dench (best supporting actress).
Directed by John Madden (R, 113 minutes). A witty, sexy and merrily
literate delight, with an exhilaratingly clever premise that only
gets better as the film unfolds. The screenplay, originating as
Marc Norman's brainstorm and turned by Tom Stoppard into
razor-sharp dialogue reminiscent of his `Rosencrantz and
Guildenstern Are Dead,' dares to imagine whatever it likes about
the link between Shakespeare's artistic passions and his mad
yearning for a certain aristocratic beauty. Meanwhile, this
tirelessly inventive comedy envisions an Elizabethan theater
fraught with the same backbiting and conniving we enjoy today and
has great fun presenting the creation of `Romeo and Juliet,'
glitches and all. Fiennes and Ms. Paltrow make a fine, tempestuous
duo, and she gives the first great, fully realized starring
performance of her career (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `STAR WARS: EPISODE I _ THE PHANTOM MENACE,' starring Liam
Neeson, Ewan McGregor, Natalie Portman and Jake Lloyd. Directed by
George Lucas (PG-13, 132 minutes). Stripped of hype and breathless
expectations, Lucas' first installment offers a happy surprise:
It's up to snuff. It sustains the gee-whiz spirit of the series and
offers a swashbuckling extra-galactic getaway, creating illusions
that are even more plausible than the kitchen-raiding raptors of
`Jurassic Park.' While the human stars here are indeed reduced to
playing action figures, they are upstaged by amazing backdrops and
hordes of crazily lifelike space beings as the Lewis Carroll in
Lucas is given free rein. The `Star Wars' franchise was funnier and
scrappier when it was new. But it simply wasn't capable of this
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `TEA WITH MUSSOLINI,' starring Cher, Judi Dench, Joan Plowright,
Maggie Smith and Lily Tomlin. Directed by Franco Zeffirelli (PG,
117 minutes). The screen divas (especially Maggie Smith) who give
`Tea With Mussolini' a patina of class obviously relish chewing the
scenery in this sudsy historical drama (adapted from a chapter of
Zeffirelli's autobiography) about a circle of English expatriate
women living in Florence on the eve of World War II. Ms. Smith, a
quintessential British snob, is the leader of the pack, nicknamed
the Scorpioni, whose comfortable lives are shattered when the
Fascists rise to power and they find themselves carted off to
another city where they are held under house arrest. Cher is her
usual likable self as a free-spending, free-loving wealthy American
heiress and art collector who befriends the group (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `THIS IS MY FATHER,' starring Aidan Quinn, Moya Farrelly and
James Caan. Directed by Paul Quinn (R, 120 minutes). Made with
obvious sincerity, this story of a glum Chicago schoolteacher (
Caan) in search of his more interesting Irish forebears ( Quinn)
involves a third Quinn brother as well. And Declan Quinn's
cinematography adds warmth to an atmospheric, sentimental tale
featuring stellar Irish actors (Stephen Rea, Brendan Gleeson, Colm
Meaney) in cameo roles. Aidan Quinn's sturdy performance, as a
lonely farmer in love with a fiery young lass from a prosperous
family, does a lot to help the film override its hackneyed elements
and keep it moving (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE WINSLOW BOY,' starring Nigel Hawthorne, Rebecca Pidgeon and
Jeremy Northam. Written and directed by David Mamet (G, 110
minutes). Terence Rattigan's play about the 1910 schoolboy's trial
that created a furor in England has been artfully pared down to its
essentials in this stately and deliberate adaptation. Played with
unusually effective restraint by a fine, meticulous cast, it works
as a precisely calibrated war of nerves in which the family of a
cadet accused of theft is quietly staggered by the consequences of
that accusation. Benoit Delhomme's cinematography is beautifully
lucid and painterly. Ms. Pidgeon's defiantly arch acting style sets
the film's tone and gives her suffragist character a sharp edge
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   Film Series
</P>
<P>
   `ALFRED HITCHCOCK.' Alfred Hitchcock's birthday doesn't arrive
until Aug. 13, but that isn't stopping anyone from celebrating the
centennial of the master of suspense (1899-1980). The tributes are
already in progress. At the Museum of Modern Art, `Alfred
Hitchcock,' with more than 50 features, shorts and documentaries,
as well as an exhibition of posters, photographs and papers, is
trumpeted as the most comprehensive Hitchcock film retrospective
ever mounted in the United States. At 2:30 p.m. Friday and 5:45
p.m. Saturday, the attraction is `Notorious' (1946), with a cast
including Ingrid Bergman, Cary Grant and Claude Rains. Francois
Truffaut said, `In my opinion, `Notorious' is the very quintessence
of Hitchcock.' Continuing through June 15 at the museum, at 11 West
53rd St., Manhattan, the series is free with museum admission:
$9.50 for adults, $6.50 for students and the elderly; free for
those under 16 accompanied by an adult. Pay-what-you-wish on
Fridays from 4:30 to 8:30 p.m. Information: (212) 708-9400
(Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
</TEXT>
