<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5078 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV27-     05-20 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV27-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: PENIS ENVY? NOT IN THIS CROWD. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday, May 27)  
 (bl)  
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Picture this: an auditorium of mostly women, students,
grandmothers, management types, teachers, plus a few men, listening
to six women in black dresses talk about the V-word. Reading about
vaginas from notebooks held in their laps, they are as poised as a
choral group. Elegant women with private smiles on their faces.
</P>
<P>
   For more than an hour, all use the taboo word, the one seldom
spoken aloud in public, more commonly heard in coarse slang terms,
but which in other languages takes poetic names like ``golden
gate,'' ``doorway of life,'' ``lotus.''
</P>
<P>
   What's happening here is a performance of ``The Vagina
Monologues,'' the title of a little red book published a year ago
based on a wildly successful off-Broadway show by author-playwright
Eve Ensler.
</P>
<P>
   The title itself is fun to repeat, just because it's almost
guaranteed to startle. ``The What?''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, there have been readings from the book by the likes
of Susan Sarandon, Winona Ryder and Lily Tomlin. Now it's a road
show, performed by local women in different parts of the country,
to benefit women's organizations, this particular night in Santa
Rosa for Women Against Rape.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure Susan, Lily and Winona would do amazing renditions but
there's greater delight in hearing your neighbors, who in this case
include the administrator of a child care center, an acupuncturist
and a midwife, be so articulate and uninhibited on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Some might react, ``Is nothing sacred?'' for which the answer is
``Haven't you been reading the front page lately?'''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the vagina has always attracted more profane than
sacred attention. As a defining detail of female sexuality, it's
never gotten much respect.
</P>
<P>
   Here we have a lovely antidote to locker room jokes, a salve
against the ongoing brutality and disregard for women's bodies in
our own community and around the world and a reprieve from the
embarrassment, guilt and ambivalence women have over being sexual.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that women haven't been a party to keeping the subject
under wraps. Ensler has a piece on ``down there,'' a common
euphemism used by an earlier generation of women who wanted to get
as much distance from their own vaginas as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in recent years we've become more enlightened about
women's body parts. We boldly speak of PMS, menstruation and
menopause. TV commercials whisper of solutions for certain feminine
problems.
</P>
<P>
   This, however, is not a clinical or hygienic discussion but
sexual politics in the most basic sense. And the mood is more
pajama party than bachelorette night. Do not confuse this laughter
with what accompanies tucking dollar bills into male strippers'
G-strings.
</P>
<P>
   We are laughing out loud about ourselves, about experiences we
all have but seldom voice. We are laughing with relief to finally
be talking about it.
</P>
<P>
   When a friend told me about the book I remember wondering how
much can a person write about a single body part, even one this
versatile.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, there are worlds to say.
</P>
<P>
   Ensler got 200 women to talk about their vaginas, an amazing
reporting feat in itself. They were old and young women, lesbian,
straight, from many cultures, brazen and shy, ones who flaunted
their sexuality and ones still fearful of it.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the stories are tough. You cannot talk about women's
bodies without acknowledging the offenses and crimes committed on
them.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the audience is quiet, barely able to breathe, afraid
of what they know is coming next. Some women have to leave the room
and go sit in the lobby for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   But if they come back inside the mood switches again and they'll
be there to hear the moans. The good moans. Don't miss the part
about the good moans.
</P>
<P>
   This is sex ed for grown-ups, a tender, respectful primer on
women's sexuality. Pass it on.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartz(AT)pressdemo.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
