<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-SENATE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FIRST LADY WILL MAKE SENATE RUN, MANY DEMOCRATS BELIEVE
 &HT;    Eds: This story, originally scheduled for Sunday release, is now
available for immediate use.
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Will she or won't she? Here and in New York, more
and more political pulse-takers are convinced that First Lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton does indeed plan to run for the Senate in
New York next year.
</P>
<P>
   If so, her race is likely to have far-flung consequences,
affecting the 2000 presidential contest and fund-raising by both
parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear to me that she wants to do this,'' said state
Democratic Chairwoman Judith Hope. ``She has been trying it on for
size, and so far it's been a real good fit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's going to run, I really do,'' said state
Comptroller H. Carl McCall, one of the numerous New York Democrats
with whom Mrs. Clinton has consulted about seeking the seat of
retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the signs are she is going to do it,'' said Lee Miringoff,
director of the Marist Institute for Public Opinion in New York.
``She seems to be crossing the line a little bit more,'' he said,
amid acknowledgement by her office that she is weighing the
formation of an exploratory committee that could pay for her travel
to the state.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post, citing unidentified sources, reported
Thursday the first lady would take such a step within weeks of
returning from a Florida vacation later this month with President
Clinton and Chelsea, the couple's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   But the revelation did not startle anyone in New York who has
followed Mrs. Clinton's activities since the trial balloon of a
possible campaign was floated earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   In the past four weeks, Mrs. Clinton has visited New York four
times. And she will visit again Monday, attending an arts event, a
book signing for Matilda Cuomo, wife of former Gov. Mario Cuomo,
and a fund-raiser for the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee,
the group that leads the effort to increase Democrats' numbers in
the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The event will be ``the first Hillary Clinton fund-raiser,''
predicts Sen. Robert Torricelli of New Jersey, chairman of the
DSCC.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady also reportedly plans to visit incoming Prime
Minister Ehud Barak in Israel next month, a trip interpreted as an
attempt to reassure the large and politically active Jewish vote in
New York. Though a strong supporter of Israel, Mrs. Clinton has
made controversial statements supporting an independent Palestinian
state.
</P>
<P>
   Such moves reinforce the widespread belief that ``she wants to
do this in the worst way,'' said Erie County Democratic Chairman
Steve Pigeon.
</P>
<P>
   However, the double-digit lead Mrs. Clinton initially recorded
in hypothetical polling match-ups with Mayor Rudy Giuliani of New
York City has disappeared. The race, if held today, would be a
toss-up, according to Miringoff.
</P>
<P>
   What appears to have hurt Mrs. Clinton most is the
``carpetbagger issue'' _ the fact that she is not from New York.
However, on this issue, she has at least one advantage over the
late Bobby Kennedy, who moved from Virginia to New York to get
elected to the Senate in 1966, according to Miringoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``She isn't from anywhere. She's from TV, so she's not quite as
much a carpetbagger,'' he said. ``She's a celebrity. But the
difficulty will be moving from celebrity to candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one of the reasons to form an exploratory committee is
to avoid legal complications over traveling so frequently to New
York at taxpayer expense. Some watchdog groups have already hinted
at possible lawsuits challenging Mrs. Clinton's travels to New
York, and forming an exploratory committee would allow her to raise
money to help finance the trips.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's candidacy would clearly energize the state
Democratic Party, especially women and minorities, said Celinda
Lake, a noted Democratic pollster. And there would be ``tremendous
synergy'' between the first lady's campaign and the presidential
campaign of Vice President Al Gore, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But it is equally likely to energize the entire Republican
Party, said Jack Pitney, a former Republican National Committee
official who now teaches political science at Claremont McKenna
College in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary is the new Newt Gingrich _ a cash cow for both
parties,'' he said. ``Her side will give because they hate her
opponents, who in turn will step up their donations because they
hate her.''
</P>
<P>
   Running for the Senate will dredge up all the scandals of the
Clinton administration, something Gore wants to avoid, Pitney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every corner of her life and record is potential ammunition
for the Republicans,'' he said. ``But what people forget is that
she is as tough and as nasty as any New York pol, and she will
answer every attack on her with an attack on her enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
