<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO LOVEBIRDS AND A BOOKSHOP  
 TAKING FLIGHT AGAIN 
NICE GUY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Richard Curtis, the British screenwriter for ``Four
Weddings and a Funeral,'' has had a persistent fantasy for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to drive across the bridge to Battersea to have dinner
with my friends and I would always think, `What would happen if I
turned up with the most famous woman in the world _ say Princess Di
or Madonna or someone like that?''' said Curtis , who is 42. ``One
of my friends would have screamed and enjoyed every moment of it;
one would pretend not to be affected, and the third would have no
idea who these women were.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued, ``It was, of course, sort of a fairy tale
scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of this fantasy, Curtis wrote ``Notting Hill,'' a romantic
comedy in which Julia Roberts stars as a movie star (not much of a
stretch) who meets a bookshop owner, played by Hugh Grant, in the
Notting Hill section of London. Despite their differences in style,
money and status, the two have a romance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fame thing isn't real, you know,'' says the Roberts
character, named Anna Scott, in the movie. ``Don't forget, I'm also
just a girl. Standing in front of a boy. Asking him to love her.''
</P>
<P>
   A reverse Cinderella story, the film, directed by Roger Michell
(``Persuasion''), is scheduled to open on May 28.
</P>
<P>
   Although not a sequel to the highly successful ``Four Weddings
and a Funeral,'' the new film has a similar pedigree. It
reassembles a team with Grant, who starred in ``Four Weddings,''
Curtis, and Duncan Kenworthy, who produced the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis said he had been working on the script off and on for
five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a very slow writer,'' he said. ``It was interrupted by,
among other things, the birth of two children as well as this other
job I have working for charity.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis is co-founder and vice chairman of British Comic Relief,
for which he works four months a year. The organization raises
money through comedy performances to help the poor and disabled in
Africa and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis said Grant was the actor everyone wanted for the role of
the charming bookshop owner. ``It was Hugh or someone no one had
ever heard of. We couldn't think of anyone else for the part,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Roberts was also the first choice for her role, but the
producers were not sure she would accept. The actress read the
script and promptly agreed, asking only for a few changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wanted it a bit funnier,'' Curtis said. ``Julia said we
should lighten her character up. She wanted to crack a few jokes
about herself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was dazzling to work with a female movie star of that kind
because her relationship with the camera is simply extraordinary,''
Curtis added.
</P>
<P>
   He chose Notting Hill, in which most of the film takes place,
because he lives there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very eclectic, strange and mischievous area,'' he said.
``There's an extraordinary mix of cultures, rich and poor; it's a
melting pot of Portuguese and Jamaicans and English; there are very
expensive flats with private gardens and quite scuzzy flats, all
within a thousand yards from each other. It seemed like a realistic
place where two people from two worlds could coexist.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides,'' he added, ``I live there so I didn't have to wake
up early every morning when we were making the film.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking Flight Again
</P>
<P>
   After his directing debut in ``Con Air,'' a successful but
critically drubbed action film, Simon West yearned to prove to
Hollywood, and perhaps to himself, that he was not merely a
filmmaker specializing in guns and explosions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read endless scripts,'' West said. ``I wanted something
dramatic and I wanted to find something that was rather more
serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Along came Paramount and Mace Neufeld, a producer of such films
as ``The Hunt for Red October'' and ``Patriot Games.'' They sent
West the screenplay of the Nelson DeMille best seller ``The
General's Daughter,'' and he was immediately interested.
</P>
<P>
   The film tells the story of the murder of a general's daughter,
herself an Army officer, against a backdrop of long-hidden secrets
that a tenacious Army investigator seeks to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read the screenplay and then read the book,'' West said. ``I
knew there was more in the book. I went back and found a lot of
things that should go into the screenplay. The book itself is very
visual and was almost like a screenplay; it had all the elements of
a Hollywood movie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a classic but dark story involving betrayal and honor and
conspiracy,'' he said, adding: ``It has sexual tension. It has a
decidedly Shakespearean feel to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, which is scheduled to open on June 18, stars John
Travolta as the Army investigator, who joins another officer,
played by Madeleine Stowe, to look into the murder. The film's cast
includes Leslie Stefanson, James Cromwell, Timothy Hutton, James
Woods and Clarence Williams 3rd.
</P>
<P>
   As a Briton, West said he knew little about the U.S. military,
but he soon found that he could understand the institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, the Army is a feudal system and, being English, I
could relate to that,'' he said. ``In so many ways the military,
and not just the American military, is similar to the class system.
Everyone knows exactly what position they're in.''
</P>
<P>
   West began his career in 1981 as an apprentice film editor at
the BBC in London and worked on a number of award-winning
documentaries during his four years at the network. By the late
1980s he had emerged as a successful creator of television
commercials, which led, finally, to the job on ``Con Air.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, my directing career took off after that,'' West said.
``There's nothing quite like having a hit. It saved me years of
struggling in this business.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 1848EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
