<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5102 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     05-20 0473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: this business.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nice Guy
</P>
<P>
   Although Harvey Keitel has appeared in more than 50 films since
his 1968 acting debut in Martin Scorsese's ``Who's That Knocking at
My Door?,'' he says that few have stirred him the way Tony Bui's
``Three Seasons'' did.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which has received generally positive reviews in
recent weeks and has played modestly around the nation, is the
first American movie shot in Vietnam since the war. It deals with
the lives of several disparate people in Ho Chi Minh City, the
beautiful old Saigon, now in the grip of change. Keitel plays a
former soldier who returns to Vietnam to the daughter he fathered
and left behind during the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read the script and it took me someplace I had never been
before,'' Keitel said. ``I had a similar reaction when I read
`Reservoir Dogs.'''
</P>
<P>
   He said the script had a personal resonance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about the struggle of a human being seeking self-esteem;
it's about reconciliation between daughters and fathers. I identify
with that,'' he said. Keitel has a 13-year-old daughter with his
former wife, actress Lorraine Bracco.
</P>
<P>
   Keitel, whose credits include ``Mean Streets,'' ``Taxi Driver,''
``Bugsy'' and ``Pulp Fiction,'' has usually played tough guys in
films. He credits Jane Campion, director of ``The Piano,'' for
helping alter his screen persona in that film, in which he played
Holly Hunter's lover.
</P>
<P>
   In Keitel's newest film, ``Holy Smoke,'' also directed by Ms.
Campion, the actor plays a counselor involved in helping people who
want to leave religious cults. He described the film, which opens
later in the year, as a black comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Keitel speaks with a religious ardor about acting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being typecast is a struggle, yes, but the struggle is
welcome,'' he said. ``Actors should welcome the struggle. That's
part of the journey.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a lucky guy and I have no regrets about anything,''
he continued. ``It's all part of the path. It would be dumb of me
to say all the good things were wonderful and the bad things were
just a waste of time. It's not true. Each one informs the other.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Keitel is fortunate because he is a gifted
character actor who never seems to stop working. Although he lives
in New York, he is often abroad. Now he is filming ``U-571,'' a
submarine drama directed by Jonathan Mostow. The film is being made
in Italy and Malta.
</P>
<P>
   He also will be in ``My West,'' in which he plays a retired
gunfighter. The movie, made by Giovanni Veronese, was also shot in
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Keitel, a Brooklyn-born former marine, laughed when asked about
being typecast as a tough guy. No matter how hard he tries, he
said, the tough guy scripts keep coming in.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you say one more word about me being a tough guy,'' he
said, ``I'll beat you up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
