<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5103 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPENDING-0521-COX     05-20 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPENDING-0521-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS PASSES KOSOVO SPENDING BILL
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (a) general news categories
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress completed action Thursday on a nearly $15
billion emergency spending bill that includes money to pay for the
Balkan war, provides relief to last year's hurricane victims and
protects states' tobacco settlement money.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the Senate voted 64-36 in favor of the measure,
President Clinton indicated he would reluctantly sign it. The House
approved the bill Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton chided lawmakers for adding measures that were not
considered emergencies and was sharply critical of the provision
protecting the states' tobacco money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were it not for the pressing needs in Kosovo, Central America,
the Middle East and America's heartland, I would have rejected
several of these measures that reward special interests, weaken
environmental protection, and undermine our campaign to stop teen
smoking,'' Clinton said. ``This is no way to do the people's
business, and I will not tolerate this kind of special-interest
meddling as we complete the annual budget process.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill included roughly $12 billion to pay for the war effort
against Yugoslavia -- including higher pay for the military and
$1.1 billion in humanitarian assistance to the Kosovar refugees --
plus $2.9 billion to assist Central American victims of Hurricanes
Mitch and George and the recent Midwest tornado victims.
</P>
<P>
   The bill cut about $2 billion in already appropriated spending
for food stamps, housing subsidies and community development block
grants.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's passage ends a dispute between the administration and
the states over how tobacco settlement money will be divided. The
administration had indicated the federal government should receive
roughly 55 percent of the $250 billion the states will get from
cigarette manufacturers over the next 25 years. The administration
also sought to place restrictions on how states could spend their
tobacco money.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he was ``extremely disappointed,'' that Congress
prevented the federal government from sharing in the tobacco
settlements and did not ``require states to use even a portion of
those funds to prevent youth smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   But Graham, one of the co-sponsors of the provision, said ``I'm
pleased that we have struck a blow for federalism and the right of
states ... to make decisions for their citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, sponsor of the
provision, said it was crucial to allowing states to ``spend the
money that they so rightly earned from the tobacco companies to
benefit the citizens of their state.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a fight to the finish,'' Hutchison said. ``There were
a lot of people who either wanted to mandate expenditures,'' or
require states to have their spending plans approved by the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. George Voinovich, R-Ohio, said the provision ``recognizes
that this money was not (federal) money. It was state money that
the states aggressively pursued...We're saying (to the states):
'It's your money and you do what you want with it.' ``
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
