</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARCLAYS-CUTBACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARCLAYS PLC TO CUT NEARLY 10 PERCENT OF ITS BRITISH STAFF IN '99 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Struggling against bloated costs and increased
competition, Britain's second-largest bank, Barclays PLC announced
Thursday that it would cut almost 10 percent of its 65,000-member
British work force this year.
</P>
<P>
   The reduction, aimed at saving an annual $320 million, was one
of the biggest reductions of jobs in British banking.
</P>
<P>
   Coming after months of uncertainty and seesawing stock prices,
Thursday's announcement lifted the price of Barclays shares nearly
4 percent, to 18.87 pounds, or $30.33, carrying other banking
stocks with them.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Barclays said it would record an accounting
charge of $646 million this year to reflect the cost of reducing
its staff, mainly in retail financial services, which employ 55,000
people, and in corporate banking, with about 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts, which will be made through attrition, voluntary
retirements and layoffs, follow staff reductions at the bank's
Barclaycard credit card division and at Barclays Capital, the
investment arm that had heavy losses in the Russian debt crisis.
</P>
<P>
   While the job reductions announced Thursday were limited to
Barclays in Britain, executives did not rule out further cuts in
the bank's widespread overseas operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The announcement is very sad, but on a business level this is
absolutely essential,'' said Sir Peter Middleton, the Barclays
chairman and acting chief executive. ``This is to produce a simpler
structure for people to bank with us and reduce costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Middleton has been running the bank since the last full-time
chief executive, Martin Taylor, quit last November in a board-room
row over the losses at Barclays Capital. His American replacement,
former Bank of America executive Michael O'Neill, resigned because
of a heart problem on the day he was supposed to start work in
London in mid-April. His replacement has not been announced.
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with the bank's emerging-markets losses and rising
costs, O'Neill's withdrawal from the top job contributed to a sense
among some market analysts that the bank was drifting and ripe for
a takeover. Others, however, say that Barclays and its management
remain essentially sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``With or without a CEO, this is still a major bank with a major
market share and it's going to remain a major player,'' said Alan
Reid, a credit-rating analyst with Moody's Investors Service.
``There's more to an organization than a single person, and that's
very much illustrated by what the bank announced today.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Barclays has acknowledged that its costs were
spiraling and promised to contain them.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of costs, this has been a bit of an Achilles' heel
year after year,'' said Nick Collier, an analyst with Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter. ``This announcement provides more tangible
evidence that they are a little bit more determined on costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Trippett, an analyst at Schroders Investment, said the
savings would bring Barclays closer into line with the most
cost-efficient British banks. But, he said, the balance-sheet
benefits would not show until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, Barclays' problems stem from its slow response to a
revolution in British retail banking over a decade that has seen
150,000 jobs disappear as some 4,000 bank and savings and loan
branches closed.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation of traditional mortgage companies into
full-fledged banks, and a rush into the retail financial services
market by supermarkets and other nonbanking concerns, has magnified
the competition.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, technological advances _ first in automated
teller machines, then in telephone, computer and Internet banking _
have forced banks to devise ways to reduce costs without losing
customers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
