</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OVITZ-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVITZ INVESTS IN INTERNET ENTERTAINMENT COMPANY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Michael Ovitz, the talent manager once known as
the most powerful man in Hollywood, is trying to extend his reach
into cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz is an investor in and co-founder of Checkout.com, a
company that will offer information about entertainment and also
sell compact disks, videos and games through a Web site of the same
name.
</P>
<P>
   The other major investor, it was announced Thursday, is Yucaipa
Cos., the group run by Ronald Burkle, the billionaire supermarket
magnate. Last year, Burkle orchestrated the sale of Fred Meyer
Inc., which he controlled, to Kroger Co., thereby becoming the
largest shareholder of the nation's largest supermarket chain.
</P>
<P>
   The Checkout Web site is being developed by Richard Wolpert, the
head of Yucaipa's Internet ventures and also a partner in the new
company. He was formerly the president of Disney Online.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Internet is the greatest thing that ever happened
to the entertainment industry, to the artistic community,'' Ovitz
said, explaining that artists can now present their material
directly to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Checkout's site, which is expected to be in operation this
summer, will not immediately offer consumers the ability to
download music, games or video, though that will come, Ovitz and
Wolpert said.
</P>
<P>
   They described their site as a Web portal for entertainment.
Type in a request, say, for the actor Jim Carrey, and a Web page
about Carrey will be instantly created with information about him,
offers for videos of his movies and links to other sites.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz and Wolpert said they would start many other Internet
ventures. They declined to discuss how much each partner had
invested.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz, the co-founder of the Creative Artists Agency, is trying
to resurrect his career after being ousted from the No. 2 position
at the Walt Disney Co. in 1996, more than $100 million richer from
a severance payment but without a position of power.
</P>
<P>
   Since then he has made an ill-founded investment in Livent Inc.,
the troubled Broadway production company, and has tried to bring a
National Football League team back to Los Angeles. He also started
a new talent management company, Artists Management Group, which
promptly got into a bitter feud with his old agency. Ovitz said the
new Internet company would not discriminate in favor of the
performers he represents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 1854EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
