<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5113 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMBODIA-HATE-ART-NYT     05-20 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-HATE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CAMBODIAN CEREMONY REVIVES PAINFUL MEMORIES OF 1970s  
(ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHOEUNG EK, Cambodia _ With a pyramid of bleached skulls seeming
to stare directly at them Thursday morning, a choir of young women
sang a horrifying dirge.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were hit with spades, they were bound and thrown into
wells, without pity,'' the women sang. ``Small babies were dragged
from their mothers' arms and stabbed, spitted together on sticks,
smashed against trees, without pity. Young women were raped as if
in a game, without pity.
</P>
<P>
   ``O Cambodia, do you remember? Do you remember your bitter
history?''
</P>
<P>
   A thousand mourners listened in grief and silence. ``I think my
head is going to burst,'' a man said.
</P>
<P>
   No one here forgets. This is a country drowning in its bitter
history.
</P>
<P>
   But the manner of remembering has become a subject of dispute
almost as debilitating as the history itself. Punish the Khmer
Rouge leaders _ the authors of Cambodia's tragedy _ or leave them
to age and fade quietly like the bones of their victims? It is not
morality or healing that governs the debate, but political
calculation.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, in the midst of this dispiriting wrangle, Cambodia's
leaders have revived for their own reasons one of their country's
most painful rituals, the Day of Hate.
</P>
<P>
   In the early years after the Khmer Rouge were ousted in 1979 by
a Vietnamese invasion, this was a day for anger and remembrance
when in villages and schoolrooms around the country people told
their stories and wept. Then in 1991, as the nation tried to move
toward a democratic future, the rite was suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's ceremony was held on the grounds of Cambodia's most
famous killing field, where 20,000 people died, a lovely swath of
glowing green rice fields dotted with spiky sugar palms and
bone-thin white cows.
</P>
<P>
   Buddhist monks in their brown and orange robes sat under a
tamarind tree on lavender plastic chairs as hundreds of cicadas
buzzed wildly in the branches above them. Small, dirty children
wandered past, chewing sticks of sugar cane and holding hands.
</P>
<P>
   Coups, killings and do-or-die politics have transformed Cambodia
since 1991, and the convocation Thursday was very much a ceremony
for its time, a convulsion of memory mixed with the pragmatic
agendas of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember forever the criminal acts of the genocidal Pol Pot
regime,'' a black banner said, referring to the late leader of the
Khmer Rouge, the brutal communist movement responsible for more
than a million deaths from 1975 to 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, a pale blue banner proclaimed, ``Long live the Cambodian
People's Party,'' the ruling party of Prime Minister Hun Sen, who
after years of trying has finally bludgeoned his way to absolute
dominance of this exhausted country.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the ceremony from under a large red-and-blue Angkor Beer
umbrella was the deputy governor of Phnom Penh, Chea Sophea. He
brought the day's language firmly down to earth with a few words
addressed directly to the people who were killed here, nine miles
south of the capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am here today,'' he said, ``to inform all of you who died
that owing to the win-win policy of Prime Minister Hun Sen all
Khmer people have reconciled and united. The Khmer people are now
at peace, and the Kingdom of Cambodia has become a full member of
ASEAN,'' the Southeast Asian regional association.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as mourners knelt on the damp grass, the monks clustered
around the pyramid of skulls to chant a Buddhist prayer for the
dead.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement only two days ago that the ceremony was to be
revived took most people by surprise and seemed to run counter to
Hun Sen's apparent policy of ``national reconciliation'' and de
facto amnesties for the Khmer Rouge killers.
</P>
<P>
   Though two top Khmer Rouge officials, Ta Mok and Duch, have been
imprisoned this year and are awaiting trial, several of their
senior comrades have been allowed to ``defect'' and live as free
men.
</P>
<P>
   A Western diplomat suggested that the ceremony might be a
gesture aimed at placating the United Nations and some Western
countries, whose call for the arrest and international trial of
Khmer Rouge leaders Hun Sen has been resisting.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomat said Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in
1977, might be trying to say, ``Look, we really do hate the Khmer
Rouge.'' As if in confirmation, most newspapers Thursday obediently
replaced their usual front-page photographs of gruesome crimes with
photographs of piles of skulls.
</P>
<P>
   But what Hun Sen has actually said is: ``We should dig a hole
and bury the past.''
</P>
<P>
   If that is his real intent, the Choeung Ek killing field offers
its own reply: the past does not always stay buried.
</P>
<P>
   Some 9,000 skulls have been excavated and put on display in a
glass-walled shrine here, but at least as many still lie buried in
shallow graves in the surrounding fields. Bits of bone still poke
up from the earth along with scraps of clothing.
</P>
<P>
   And in the monsoon season, people here say, the flood-soaked
earth sometimes shifts and regurgitates some of the buried bones
and skulls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
