<HEADER>
A5116 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRTRAN-SHAREHOLDERS2     05-20 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRTRAN-SHAREHOLDERS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AirTran announces new route, recovery during shareholders
meeting
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ AirTran plans to start Atlanta-Newark, N.J., flights
July 1, giving the airline service to the two biggest New York City
area airports.
</P>
<P>
   The discount carrier, which already serves La Guardia Airport
from Atlanta, plans an additional five daily roundtrips to Newark
International, Chief Executive Joe Leonard said Thursday after a
quiet annual shareholders meeting here.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran has long sought to fly to Newark but lacked gates at the
congested airport. Leonard said the carrier recently negotiated the
use of gates controlled by Northwest Airlines _ with help from
public officials who want to encourage low-fare competition.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran will join Delta and Continental on the route and
essentially replace Kiwi, which withdrew last winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a discounter in that market to keep fares down,''
business travel expert Chris McGinnis said.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard disclosed the new route after the shareholders meeting,
attended by about 75 people. He spent the meeting touting Orlando,
Fla.-based AirTran's recent signs of financial recovery after two
years of mostly red ink, dating to when it was ValuJet.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard also noted a new ``buy'' recommendation on AirTran stock
by veteran analyst Julius Maldutis of CIBC Oppenheimer. AirTran
shares closed Thursday at $5, up 18 3/4 cents.
</P>
<P>
   During the meeting, one shareholder noted that the carrier has
about $230 million in debt coming due in early 2001 that will have
to be refinanced. He wondered whether the carrier will really have
the cash flow to finance new Boeing 717 jets as it plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes we will,'' Leonard answered, adding the planes' up-front
cost will be offset by lower operating expenses, compared with the
old jets they'll replace. Meanwhile, he said, the company is
already talking with lenders about debt refinancing.
</P>
<P>
   Another shareholder asked whether the company would consider a
stock split while shares are cheap ``as an incentive for those who
have stood by the airline.'' As ValuJet, the airline's shares once
traded above $30 but plummeted after the carrier's 1996 crash in
Florida and safety grounding. Leonard said no split is planned.
</P>
<P>
   He also said an AirTran damages lawsuit against SabreTech, a
contractor whose mistakes led to the ValuJet crash, is scheduled
for trial in St. Louis next week.
</P>
<P>
   ValuJet co-founder Lewis Jordan, who remains an AirTran director
and its biggest stockholder, attended the meeting and said
afterward he believes the company will slowly gain strength under
Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be one step at a time,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
