<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0312 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5117 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-NRA21-COX     05-20 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-NRA21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Officials question whether NRA address appropriate
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Stunned by a school shooting in their own backyards,
some Georgia Republicans were wavering Thursday over whether to
allow a National Rifle Association executive to address their state
convention Saturday in Augusta as planned.
</P>
<P>
   GOP Chairman Rusty Paul, who had refused to revoke the
invitation to NRA Executive Vice President Wayne LaPierre, said
late Thursday that he now wants to consult with party leaders about
the appearance after a student opened fire in a Rockdale County
high school, injuring six.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to make this decision by myself,'' Paul said.
``We don't want the whole convention to be about this issue. We
obviously want to be sensitive to the feelings and emotions of
everybody out there, particularly the feelings of the folks in
Rockdale.''
</P>
<P>
   Although several Republican leaders are urging the cancellation
of LaPierre's five-minute address to about 2,000 party delegates,
an NRA spokesman said LaPierre still planned to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't have anything to do with us,'' NRA spokesman Bill
Powers said of the shooting. Earlier in the week, LaPierre said his
message for Saturday is one that everyone concerned about
minimizing youth violence should listen to. ``Our message is the
one that will make people safe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who call the appearance ill-advised quibble more
with the timing than with the NRA's pro-gun position.
</P>
<P>
   LaPierre's appearance would come about 48 hours after the
Rockdale shooting, a month after a shooting rampage in Littleton,
Colo., left 15 dead, and six months after the NRA irritated many
Georgia Republicans by endorsing Democrats in races for governor
and attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good judgment, at a time like this, and out of respect to
those who've been injured, would be to say this probably wouldn't
be a good thing to do,'' said U.S. Rep. Johnny Isakson (R-Ga).
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Charlie Norwood (R-Ga.), who will chair the convention
in his hometown, is prepared to recommend to Paul that the speech,
one of the first by a lobbyist at the state convention, be
canceled, said spokesman John Stone.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. John Linder (R-Ga.), whose district includes Rockdale
County, also objects to the appearance _ albeit more on principle _
because he doesn't think lobbyists should be given the convention
floor, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the state's most conservative Republicans _
including U.S. Rep. Bob Barr, an NRA board member _ insist that the
speech should go on as planned. To do otherwise, they said, would
lend credence to arguments that guns, not people, cause the
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not concerned about sensitivity issues,'' Barr said
Thursday when asked about the timing of LaPierre's appearance. ``We
need to look for solutions, not at whether something is politically
correct or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, including at least two of the three candidates to
succeed Paul as state chairman, agree with Barr.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has nothing to do with guns,'' said candidate Linda
Herren. ``It's unfortunate timing, but his speech at the convention
has nothing to do with the fact that an angry young man in Conyers
shot some people.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, at least a few Republicans won't be in their chairs
Saturday, mainly because of the anticipated fallout from an NRA
speech that will be heavily covered by the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disastrous timing,'' said Rep. Mark Burkhalter
(R-Alpharetta), who plans to stay away. ``I don't know how, with
this happening today, we can, two days from now, wave the flag and
rah-rah the Second Amendment without ever touching on the
availability of guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
