<P>
   Here are the business news stories the Los Angeles Daily News
plans to move for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs
of Friday, May 21 and thereafter. The stories will carry the ``f''
financial news category code unless otherwise noted. For questions
about stories, contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818)
713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   STARWARS-BOX (Los Angeles) _ The Force turned out be powerful
but hardly overwhelming. Wednesday's opening of ``Star Wars Episode
1: The Phantom Menace'' grossed $28.5 million at 2,970 theaters _ a
single-day record on the one hand but far short of the $40
million-plus some analysts had expected. By Dave McNary. (Will move
in the ``e'' entertainment and ``f'' business news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MCSALAD-TEST (Los Angeles) _ &UR; (ART ADV: Photo showing the McSalad
has been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (212) 556-4204 or 1927.) &LR;  Add
salads-in-a-cup to the list of fads that started in L.A. McDonald's
about a week ago started testing a new menu item _ a salad in a
clear plastic cup that you pour your dressing into and shake to mix
it up _ in Los Angeles and three other markets across the country.
No advertising, no promotions, just test marketing to see if the
McSalad Shakers will sell nationwide. By Enrique Rivero. (Will move
in the ``f'' financial and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   VITAMIN-SETTLEMENT (Los Angeles) _ Vitamin makers cheered a $725
million settlement Thursday in a case of price fixing by two
European chemicals firms. ``I don't see a downside to this,'' said
Paul Bolar, head of regulatory and legal affairs for San
Fernando-based Pharmavite, which markets the NatureMade line of
supplements. ``If it helps lower prices, everybody benefits.'' By
Ben Sullivan. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOLE-EARNINGS (Los Angeles) _ Dole Food Co. announced Thursday
it will report earnings for its next quarter ``materially below
previous estimates.'' The Westlake Village-based fresh fruit and
flower producer said weaker demand in Eastern Europe and Russia is
to blame. By Greg Wilcox. ((Will move in the ``f'' financial news
file.)
</P>
