A5124 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CLEOPATRA-AZR &LR;      05-20 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CLEOPATRA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CLEOPATRA' A ROYAL MESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVE WALKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - ``Cleopatra'' as bad as ``Noah's Ark''?
</P>
<P>
   No. Of course not. But ABC's late entry will finish a close next
to last in the May sweeps miniseries disappointment derby to NBC's
awful ``Ark,'' a laugh-out-loud disaster that opened the current
ratings-intensive onslaught of hype.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Margaret George's hefty novel ``The Memoirs of
Cleopatra,'' this mini dies of a weak heart: ABC has commited
Nile-ism in the extreme by casting Leonor Varela in the title role.
</P>
<P>
   A dynastic dish in any era, the young actress evidently got lost
somewhere between the wardrobe tent and whatever lavish set she was
led to next. According to this script, Cleopatra was a conniving
temptress who influenced the fate of nations. As played by Varela,
it's doubtful she could influence the drive-thru dude to supersize
a No. 3 meal deal.
</P>
<P>
   About that wardrobe tent: The gauzy getups that Varela wears
throughout this four-hour pageant, airing Sunday and Monday, seem
calculated to keep male viewers interested between the big battles.
Her cleavage, in fact, is so accentuated by Cleopatra's toga-based
couture that it should get its own mention in the closing credits.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a complaint or criticism. But it is a warning to any
parents of preteens who've been looking forward to a couple of
evenings of gala tele-history for the whole family.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Cleopatra'' has its share of spectacle _ not to
mention a cast of thousands wearing George Clooney haircuts and USC
marching band costumes _ it is, at base, a soapy romance.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there's enough torch-lit lust here to fill Fox's fall
schedule. The fall of 51 B.C., that is.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to ``The Luuuuuuv Barge.''
</P>
<P>
   The script, as such, does Varela no favors. At one point,
Cleopatra seduces Julius Caesar by saying, ``I am Egypt. Egypt is
yours, for one night only.''
</P>
<P>
   At another (unrelated) juncture, Cleopatra's evil sister,
Arsinoe (played by Kassandra Voyagis), turns to her chariot driver
and says, ``C'mon.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the pretty good actors in the cast get dialog that sounds
like the old Adam West ``Batman'' series.
</P>
<P>
   The two marquee men in Cleopatra's life, Julius Caesar and Marc
Antony, are played by Timothy Dalton (``License to Kill'') and
Billy Zane (``Titanic''), respectively. Both deliver performances
that won't do too much harm to their careers.
</P>
<P>
   A special surprise, Dalton manages to humanize his character
without turning him into a lovesick sap. Dalton has played gods
(James Bond, Rhett Butler) among men before, so this oversize role
is well within his grasp. Handsome devil, too.
</P>
<P>
   Zane tackles an equally challenging acting task, waging manly
war as well as making love to Cleo (while accompanied by frenzied
bongo music). Cool job.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the other male players in this cast get to toss around
quite a bit of clipped Patrick Stewart diction. The most
interesting part of all is Octavian, whom Rupert Graves plays as a
scheming punk.
</P>
<P>
   The picturesque leads and extravagant supporting cast included,
this ``Cleopatra'' has got to be one of the prettiest four hours
ever filmed for TV. From sweeping establishing shots early in
Sunday night's installment to Monday's concluding sea battle, every
pre-Y0K setting appears appropriately costly. Exteriors were done
in Morocco, studio stuff in London.
</P>
<P>
   Through far too many of these sumptuous settings, Varela is
forced to wear royal headgear that resembles an oversize barbecue
tool.
</P>
<P>
   It's as if the network and this miniseries' producer (Robert
Halmi Sr., the same guy who added a pirate attack to the story of
Noah) really believe that we peasants, given glitter and gilt and
some very fancy hats, might not notice a completely hollow
performance occuring beneath those giant head-tongs.
</P>
<P>
   In the words of Cleo's bad sis: C'mon. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dave Walker can be reached at dave.walker(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
