<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0321 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5129 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEBMD21-COX     05-20 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBMD21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WebMD, Healtheon announce merger
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ WebMD and Healtheon announced their much-anticipated
merger Thursday, creating a $19.8 billion company that will lead
the pack of Web sites hoping to be home to health information on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Microsoft said it will buy about a 10 percent stake in the
new company for about $250 million. Microsoft will guarantee
another $250 million in advertising revenue and WebMD subscriptions
for doctors.
</P>
<P>
   The new 1,300-employee company, to be called Healtheon/WebMD,
will base its marketing and sales operations in Atlanta. The
software engineering staff will stay in Santa Clara, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about leadership and winning,'' said Jeff Arnold,
chief executive of WebMD and of the new company. ``With this
merger, health has a home page.''
</P>
<P>
   The new company would be traded under Healtheon's ticker symbol,
HLTH.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon will issue 1.815 of its shares for each of WebMD's 54
million shares. That places WebMD's value at $9.9 billion, based on
Thursday's closing price a $100.62 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon shares closed up $20.37 1/2 Thursday. The stock has
climbed 114 percent the past five days on talk of the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Excite, Intel, Softbank, Covad and Superior
Consultant announced a combined $110 million investment in the new
company.
</P>
<P>
   The merger values the companies equally. The deal will be
accounted for as a purchase. It is expected to close late in the
third quarter or early in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The deal places an enormous value on two companies that have yet
to earn a profit. WebMD lost $7.8 million in the first nine months
of 1998. Healtheon reported a $18.6 million net loss for the first
three months of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But the value of Internet companies are less about short-term
than they are future earnings.
</P>
<P>
   David Restrepo, a research analyst with Jupiter Communications,
attributes the enormous money spent on an emerging market to
potential and track record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a concept investment more than anything. Lots of
companies offer deeper content than what WebMD does. I chalk it up
to two things,'' he said. ``Health care spending is a trillion
dollar industry, 14 percent of the gross domestic product and big
enough to get Bill Gates' attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, the efficiencies of the Internet have been applied
successfully in travel and stocks; now it's health's turn.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're a doctor, WebMD wants to be your home page on the Web,
the place you turn to read news, trade stocks, book hotel and plane
reservations and earn continuing education credits.
</P>
<P>
   If you run a doctor's office, WebMD wants to be the place where
insurance coverage is verified and claims are processed, where lab
orders are placed and received and medical supplies are ordered.
</P>
<P>
   For individuals, WebMD wants to be the place people turn to read
up on new treatments for illnesses or to share information and
experiences via online discussion groups.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold said two-thirds of the combined company's revenue will
come from the physician side. Half of the physician-side revenue
would come from subscriptions, half from advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Restrepo said that while the consumer side of the business is
smaller, it could have an intangible value.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consumer side is smaller overall, but they help create the
brand,'' he said. ``In a way, consumers could be the best
salespeople for WebMD. Increasingly patients are coming to doctor's
offices with printouts from the Web. Doctors are reluctant to pay
attention, but you can't fight the Internet. Its a losing battle.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 64 percent of the searches conducted online are for
health-related information, Restrepo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With more than 49 million people online, anytime you get
two-thirds of people looking for something online, that's a big
deal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The site is free for individuals, but doctors are charged a
monthly fee of $29.95.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the subscriptions are paid by hospital groups. Microsoft
and DuPont have paid for 11 million months of physician
subscriptions.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, Arnold said it isn't important who pays the fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This market is about speed and scale,'' Arnold said. ``It
doesn't matter who pays. It's central to get doctors enrolled and
get to market first. We expect they will pay eventually. But we
also expect to move to a transaction business model.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold said doctors influence 80 percent of the $1 trillion
spent on health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``The value of a physician goes way beyond the $29.95
subscription,'' he said. ``To capture a relationship with that
physician is enormously attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   WebMD has been in business since September. The company grew out
of Endeavor Technologies, which faxed cardiac test results to
physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold said he decided to put the test results on the Web, but
was told by physicians that getting to the Web to find results from
one test took too much time.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of WebMD came when Arnold decided to make physicians'
visits to the Web more worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   The discussions with Healtheon started in early April, when
Arnold was entertaining clients at the Masters golf tournament.
Over dinner at the Ritz-Carlton in Atlanta, Arnold and Michael
Long, Healtheon chief executive officer, decided to pursue the
merger.
</P>
<P>
   WebMD launched in September after raising about $40 million,
including $10 million from HBO &AMP; Co., now McKessonHBOC.
</P>
<P>
   Within months, WebMD announced partnerships with high-profile
companies, including CNN, Lycos and DuPont, which agreed to pay
$220 million over five years to help develop WebMD's physician
network.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
