<SLUG> BC-GTE-BIDDERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GTE BIDDERS SEEK INDIVIDUAL UNITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several bidders for GTE Corp.'s defense-electronics units in
Needham, Mass. are interested in buying fragments of the company
rather than the division as a whole, say people familiar with the
discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Texas-based GTE announced in January it would auction its
Government Systems unit, which has 7,300 employees worldwide
including 1,800 in Massachusetts. Initial bids were due several
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   GTE won't comment on its sale process, but trade press articles
have reported interest in the assets from General Dynamics Corp.,
Boeing Co., and Northrop-Grumman Corp., among others. All three
declined to comment, though people familiar with the thinking of
some potential buyers confirm those companies have expressed
interest.
</P>
<P>
   However, a group of potential bidders hasn't expressed any
interest in buying the assets as a whole, these sources say,
meaning the final total value of Government Systems could be less
than the unit's revenue of $1.4 billion last year. Also,
Lexington-based Raytheon Co. recently declined to submit a bid,
these people say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the auction has gone as well as (GTE) hoped in
terms of the numbers of potential bidders,'' who have made formal
bids, one source said.
</P>
<P>
   A GTE spokesman said the company couldn't comment because of
confidentiality agreements. A Raytheon spokesman declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   GTE plans the sale as it prepares to be purchased by Bell
Atlantic Corp. for about $81 billion in stock. If approved by
various regulatory agencies, the purchase would make Bell Atlantic
the country's largest phone company.
</P>
<P>
   GTE's other major unit in the state, GTE Internetworking, and
its 2,000 employees will become part of Bell Atlantic following the
transaction. The unit, formerly Bolt, Beranek &AMP; Newman Inc., was
purchased by GTE in 1997 for $616 million.
</P>
<P>
   GTE Government Systems focuses on military and public-sector
projects, with many divisions in the Washington, D.C. area. Typical
projects include a $110 million program to install a new high-speed
Internet backbone for the Pentagon and new desktop software at the
Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of another agreement with the Air Force, worth
$115 million, GTE will design a battlefield-imaging system. Other
units focus on imaging and mapping applications, telecommunications
networks, and secure communications-encryption systems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 1917EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0324 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5134 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIDELITY-SMALLER-BOS &LR;      05-20 0378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-SMALLER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY SEES TURN TOWARD SMALLER COMPANIES  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. JAFFE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fidelity Investments, which may be the ultimate
shop for large-company and growth investing, apparently sees the
stock market turning in favor of smaller, less-pricey companies.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking Thursday in formal presentations to the Investment
Company Institute general membership meeting here, Fidelity
Management &AMP; Research Co. president Robert Pozen and vice chairman
Peter Lynch both indicated the stock markets may be ready to turn
in favor of smaller companies and value stocks. ``In April, we had
the sharpest rotations we have seen yet from growth to value,''
said Pozen. ``All of our go-anywhere funds will be moving toward
small-caps and mid-cap stocks, and maybe toward more value.''
</P>
<P>
   The stock market's continued boom _ up 50 percent since last
fall _ has been based on sharp increases in a small number of
stocks. These companies fall under the general heading of ``growth
companies'' because they have been posting consistently rising
sales and/or profits. So-called ``value stocks'' are those of
companies seen as being underpriced, but with the potential to
improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, of the largest 1,000 companies, the top 100 were up
an average of 42 percent,'' said Lynch, best known for having
managed Fidelity's Magellan fund. ``The next 900 were up 4 percent.
There will be some values in those 900 stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   While Fidelity is best known for its investments in large growth
companies, Pozen and Lynch produced a ream of statistics showing
that the firm has been strong in all investment environments.
According to those statistics, Fidelity's equity funds have
outperformed peers 71 percent of the time over the last three
years.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers get even better in bond funds _ Fidelity bested its
peers 76 percent of the time _ and in money market funds, in which
Fidelity outgained more than 80 percent of the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Fidelity executive gave much indication of the company's
future. Pozen said the company has been besieged with requests to
open an Internet fund _ but Fidelity will stick with its broader
sector funds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 1925EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
