A5136 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUNDS-BOGLE-BOS &LR;      05-20 0258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDS-BOGLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOGLE TO OPERATE HIS OWN MANAGEMENT FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. JAFFE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As if his presence at the primary meeting of fund
industry's leaders was not enough of a message, the nametags and
business cards were a dead giveaway. John Bogle Jr. is about to get
back into the fund business.
</P>
<P>
   Bogle, who was instrumental in the growth and development of two
Boston fund firms, plans to open Bogle Investment Management in
Wellesley, Mass. He expects to open two or three mutual funds in
September, raising $200 million to $400 million in assets.
</P>
<P>
   Bogle may be best known as the son of Vanguard Group chairman
Jack Bogle, but he earned his reputation by successfully managing
money first at Quantitative Group and then with n/i Funds. Bogle
abruptly left n/i last winter, essentially because he wanted a more
prominent long-term leadership role in the company.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his departure, Bogle did not say what he planned
to do next. Thursday at the Investment Company Institute general
membership meeting here, he left no doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've looked a lot at what I want to do, and whether I wanted
to be with an established big company or to join a small firm, but
I felt there were too many interpersonal risks getting involved
with existing enterprises,'' Bogle said.
</P>
<P>
   Bogle said he has already made one of the key hires for his new
firm, and was closing in on another top executive, but he declined
to provide names.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 1927EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
