<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5137 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCAIN-0521-cox     05-20 0390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-0521-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MCCAIN LASHES OUT AT CLINTON FOREIGN POLICIES
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) political categories
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican presidential candidate Sen. John McCain
offered his broadest criticism yet Thursday of President Clinton's
conduct of foreign and trade issues, calling the war in Kosovo
``yet another failure in ... the generally inept foreign policy.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, R-Ariz., has been outspoken in the past about Clinton's
declaration that he would not use ground troops in combat in
Yugoslavia. But in a speech at the National Press Club, the former
Vietnam prisoner of war said Clinton's foreign policies have
``badly injured our nation's stature and influence abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who earlier this month unsuccessfully offered a Senate
resolution to authorize whatever force might be necessary to
resolve the Balkan crisis, said he was particularly concerned
Clinton might accept an end to the situation that was less than the
goal he previously set forth. The president has said he wants the
Kosovar refugees to return to their homes in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``These days we are perceived by our enemies as an uncertain
foe, and by our friends as an unreliable ally,'' he said. ``Both
perceptions will be worsened if we should, as I strongly suspect we
will, settle for less in the Balkans than what we went to war to
achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain claimed that Clinton had relinquished American leadership
in world affairs to multinational organizations such as NATO and
pursued ``foreign policies that are little more than international
variants of pork barrel politics, without regard for the long-term
interests of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator was particularly critical of Clinton for failing to
pursue so-called ``fast track'' trade authority in the face of
opposition within the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton went to Africa, preached the blessings of
free markets, but he never lifted a finger to push for trade
agreements when he came home,'' McCain said. ``Of course, it's
easier to challenge Third World reservations about free markets
than it is to challenge the 19th century views that America's labor
bosses hold about trade.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
