<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-ACADEMIA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACADEMIC-INDUSTRIAL PARTNERSHIPS OFTEN THE RULE, NOT THE
EXCEPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Dr. Lawrence Loeb is a nationally recognized molecular
biologist at the University of Washington School of Medicine who
directs the biomedical scientist training program _ the prestigious
M.D.-Ph.D. track.
</P>
<P>
   Loeb and his colleague Dr. James Mullins also are helping launch
a new biotechnology company in Seattle, Koronis Pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   Both scientists and the UW have been given Koronis stock in
return for their expert assistance in developing drugs to combat
viral resistance. It's a private extension of their publicly funded
work at the UW.
</P>
<P>
   But it can be a confusing situation because academic scientists
also have the public responsibility of performing independent
evaluations of new drugs or therapies. Yet here they are launching
a private company whose ultimate goal is to sell these drugs. Isn't
that a potential conflict of interest?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Loeb said, but it's manageable and this is the only way to
advance the research and turn an idea into therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the reality today,'' Loeb said. ``There are potential
conflicts in this arrangement, but it allows me to develop a
high-risk project that I don't have the facilities or time to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Loeb is not unusual. Such academic-industrial partnerships are
rapidly becoming the rule rather than the exception in biomedical
research.
</P>
<P>
   Biotechnology is fueling this transformation like never before.
The strong need for cutting-edge basic science in this industry has
made for intimate partnerships with academia. It's a transformation
that has some people worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an incredibly complicated situation,'' said Dr. Robert
Cook-Deegan, director of the National Academy of Science's National
Cancer Policy Board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Academic research institutions need to be real careful about
conflicts of interest and also about preserving their educational
mission,'' Cook-Deegan said. The economic benefits of these
academic-industrial partnerships cannot be the only yardstick by
which success is measured, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Science depends upon the free and open exchange of
information,'' said Irving Lerch, chairman of the Scientific
Freedom and Responsibility committee for the American Association
for the Advancement of Science.
</P>
<P>
   Lerch said the association launched a study committee in 1997 to
take a hard look at academic-industrial partnerships in
biotechnology because of several incidents raising concerns. Some
of the high-profile examples:
</P>
<P>
   _University of California-San Francisco researcher Dr. Betty
Dong fought for six years before she was able to publish, in 1997,
the results of her study that found a new thyroid drug was no
better than generic version of the drug. Lawsuits by the company
sponsor, Knoll Pharmaceuticals, had claimed publication violated
their proprietary rights on the data.
</P>
<P>
   _Early this year, Dr. Nancy Olivieri of the University of
Toronto was reinstated to her hospital position. Olivieri had been
removed after a drug company, Apotex, sued her for publishing
negative findings about their drug.
</P>
<P>
   _The University of California-San Francisco is suing the biotech
giant Genentech in federal court for $400 million. The university
claims that the firm in 1978 knowingly used a bacterial clone
stolen from a university lab to develop its synthetic human growth
hormone. Genentech claims the researcher legally brought the clone
over from his lab, but that it wasn't used to synthesize their
product anyway and so doesn't violate the UCSF patent.
</P>
<P>
   _Last year, the Swiss drug and agribusiness company Novartis and
the University of California-Berkeley announced they had formed an
unprecedented kind of academic-industrial partnership. Novartis
paid $25 million to the university's department of plant and
microbiology in return for first crack at commercializing any
discoveries over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   But such dramatic controversies are rare. Advocates of
academic-industrial partnerships note that concerns over conflict
of interest and suppression of data are not the only issues that
should be considered.
</P>
<P>
   Public-private benefits
</P>
<P>
   Back when the biotechnology industry was in its infancy,
Congress passed the 1980 Bayh-Dole Act. It not only encouraged
academic-industrial partnerships; it required any institutions
receiving federal money to create ``technology transfer'' offices
to help move discoveries toward commercial products.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the premise that innovations were languishing in labs
because of a lack of financial incentives, the act allowed
scientists and institutions to be rewarded financially for getting
drugs or technologies to market.
</P>
<P>
   Those who know Loeb say he's clearly not entering into
partnership with Koronis for the money (his founder's stock is
worth about $40 right now). He and Mullins are in it because
industry can do something the UW can't do _ scale up production of
the UW team's unique anti-viral approach so it can be tested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our interests are complementary,'' said Dr. Richard Daifuku,
chief executive officer at Koronis and a UW M.D.-Ph.D. graduate.
``We can move their work farther down the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond facilitating larger-scale biomedical research projects,
these academic-industrial partnerships can work to the taxpayer's
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we help the company get off the ground, we'd like to make
sure the public gets some benefit,'' said Dr. Alvin Kwiram, UW's
vice provost for research. The public benefits, Kwiram said,
because the private money that comes back to the UW _ in the form
of licensing agreements or royalties _ helps defray the taxpayer's
burden in supporting academic research.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, scientists say partnerships with industry are their
only access to promising drugs or research materials held by
private companies.
</P>
<P>
   When the biotechnology industry was first launched in Seattle in
the early 1980s _ ``spinning off'' out of labs at the UW and Fred
Hutchinson Cancer Research Center in Seattle _ most academic
scientists were told it was taboo to work with industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was considered an unacceptable conflict,'' said Catherine
Hennings, director of technology transfer at Fred Hutchinson.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the UW and Fred Hutchinson saw some of their best
scientists leave academia for industry, taking with them the fruits
of their labor.
</P>
<P>
   John Des Rosier, director of industrial relations at the UW
Medical School, said partnering with industry allows universities
to retain the best academic scientists. But that doesn't mean the
UW allows academics to do whatever they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``We build firewalls,'' Des Rosier said. Rules minimize
potential conflicts of interest, he said, and protect academic
independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The corporate culture is different than the academic
culture,'' Des Rosier said. ``And they are going to stay
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Problems subtle, invisible
</P>
<P>
   One world-renowned scientist urges caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an academic scientist, I think it's very important to
define at what point it makes sense to have a public-private
partnership,'' said Dr. Mary-Claire King, who researches breast
cancer genetics at the UW. King is also known for her work using
science to identify victims of political killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people think that this is great because it will bring
in a lot of money for them to do their research without strings
attached,'' King said. ``That's naive ... I don't think money ever
comes without strings.''
</P>
<P>
   Loeb's project is an example of the kind of academic-industrial
partnership that can work for both parties, she said, in part
because he's an established scientist who doesn't have to depend on
the partnership for financial support of his research.
</P>
<P>
   For other scientists, especially younger researchers who may be
more dependent on industry support, problems can arise. And there
are warning signs out there.
</P>
<P>
   A study published in 1997 by David Blumenthal of Massachusetts
General Hospital found that 20 percent of some 2,000 biomedical
researchers surveyed had delayed publication of their results for
more than six months, or had not published them at all, because of
concerns from private sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Drummond Rennie, an editor at the Journal of the American
Medical Association, recently noted that the vast majority of drug
studies published today show positive results.
</P>
<P>
   ``This indicates a publication bias,'' Rennie said. It raises
the question of whether negative results are being withheld from
publication, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Hennings at the Fred Hutchinson and Des Rosier at the UW
said their institutions strictly protect the right to publish all
findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not willing to ever agree to keep our researchers'
results confidential,'' Hennings said.
</P>
<P>
   Future is in private hands
</P>
<P>
   Most academic research remains taxpayer-supported through
federal research grants. The UW is one of the top recipients of
federal research dollars, receiving $422 million in 1998, 76
percent of its total research budget. Industry funds accounted for
only about 11 percent percent of the UW Medical School's total
research budget.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Hutchinson received $103 million in federal research
support in 1998, 88 percent of its total research budget. Industry
money accounted for 4 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
   Looked at in this way, private funding of academic research is
still way behind publicly financing of academic science. Even so,
private funding in academia has increased by more than 20 percent
this decade.
</P>
<P>
   And if private dollars spent by drug companies and others in the
biomedical industry for their own corporate research is added to
what industry spends on research in academia, Cook-Deegan said,
private industry surpassed public funding on medical research
sometime in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   This becomes worrisome, he said, if both academia and private
industry start treating scientific information as proprietary
material. The influence of industry on research institutions cannot
only be measured in terms of dollars spent, Cook-Deegan said.
</P>
<P>
   And there are other influences not measured by dollars spent.
</P>
<P>
   Though only a small number of academics actually help start new
companies, an increasing number of faculty at both the UW and Fred
Hutchinson have entered into other types of relationships with
private companies. These include negotiated consulting work,
exchange of information or proprietary materials and how or when to
disclose sponsored research findings.
</P>
<P>
   Of 1,400 faculty at the UW medical school, about half do outside
consulting work for private companies.
</P>
<P>
   At Fred Hutchinson, about half of the 189 faculty do outside
consulting work.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kinds of interactions between academia and industry have
certainly become more prevalent,'' Hennings said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
