<HEADER>
A5151 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      05-20 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS GM SINDEN STANDS BY POST-GAME WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Harry Sinden said he wasn't surprised at the furor his
post-series comments generated among his players and the public
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' president/general manager said he meant it when he
pointedly criticized forwards Jason Allison and Dmitri Khristich
for their ineffective performances against the Sabres that led to
Boston's ouster in the Eastern Conference semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   However, while Sinden didn't back off on his comments on
Khristich, he wanted to elaborate on why he singled out Allison.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only problem with Jason was that after a superb performance
here on Sunday by him, my expectations were the same that Byron
(Dafoe), Raymond (Bourque), and Jason, three players who are
absolutely necessary to us in order to win a game in Buffalo in
which we faced elimination, had to play almost to their utmost
potential,'' said Sinden. ``That's probably what pushed me to vent
myself on Jason more than anything, was his Sunday performance. My
expectations were, `Wow, if we get that again, we'll beat them in
Buffalo.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said it's important for Allison to become more
consistent. After Game 6 Tuesday, he cited Bourque as someone to
emulate. Sinden said by no means did he expect his players to be
Bourque. He was holding up Bourque's attitude, consistency, and
commitment as something to strive for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray Bourque's not the only one,'' said Sinden. ``Don Sweeney
is another one. In all the years they've been here, they don't play
game by game. They play shift by shift. They're not all good ones,
but they're all played with exactly the same attitude. Sometimes
they don't play as well. Sometimes they give the puck away.
Sometimes they fall down, sometimes they do some terrible things,
but their attitude never, ever changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are others, too. I think Rob DiMaio is one. I think Joe
Thornton is starting to learn that. That's what I point to, not to
expect anybody to be as good as Ray but your mental attitude has to
be as developed as well as your skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden acknowledged that Allison was hampered by Khristich as a
linemate and by Sergei Samsonov's struggle because of injury and
youth. However, he said based on Sunday's game, he knows Allison
can do more and therefore he expects more.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't getting any help, that's for sure,'' said Sinden.
``I'm a champion of Jason Allison throughout the league and in the
organization. The guy's got a tremendous talent and he's creative.
But there are nights when it doesn't seem important to Jason. After
Sunday, I was so caught by surprise that we didn't get a similar
performance (Tuesday). I suppose I was out of line in picking on
him for that one particular game but it did eliminate us.''
</P>
<P>
   The way Sinden made it sound Thursday, the situation is very
unresolved with regard to Khristich's future in Boston. When asked
if he wanted Khristich back next season, Sinden paused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I think a lot of things have to be straightened out with
Dmitri and the team and coach (Pat Burns), too. I don't want to
speak for the coach but he wasn't any happier than I was. It's just
that I'm stupid enough to say it.''
</P>
<P>
   Khristich is regarded by management and the coach as an enigma.
Sinden said he hasn't worked at trying to figure Khristich out but
he does pass along his thoughts to the coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just shakes his head, too,'' said Sinden. ``As a coach,
you've got to be careful because he's got to work with these guys
all the time so his feelings and frustrations can't be brought out
perhaps the way mine are. I think Pat would like to solve the
riddle because he can see the skill of the player.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison spends his offseason in Ontario and Sinden said he would
like to talk to him to smooth things over before he leaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do something,'' he said. ``I wouldn't want to leave it
like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so with Khristich.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about him,'' said Sinden. ``I might want to leave
it like this.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised to see defenseman Jonathan Girard make an
appearance in the playoffs in Providence. Sinden said the talented
blue liner, who started the season in Boston before being sent back
to his junior team in Laval of the Quebec League, is about to be
eliminated from the Memorial Cup tournament, which would pave the
way for him to join the Baby B's.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question he's an outstanding talent,'' said Sinden.
``There are things he hasn't perfected yet and he has to get into
the pro game to realize what it's all about here, like Joe Thornton
did. He is an outstanding talent in terms of his creativity, his
skating ability, his shooting, his passing. He's reasonably
good-sized, 6-foot or 6-1 and 195 pounds. He's very sturdy. He has
a good chance to make the team next season. All reports indicate
he's the closest player outside Boston and Providence to making the
team. When he was here before, he wanted to give the puck to Ray
all the time. He didn't want to do anything that might open him up
to error. He was cautious. The way he played in juniors was
anything but that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
