<P>
   The New York Times plans two pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the continuing crisis over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PENTAGON (Washington) _ A lede-all on developments on the
diplomatic front: General Clark makes several appearances around
Washington discussing the possibility of preparing ground troops;
Strobe Talbott is in Russia for talks; further evidence of the
alliance cracking, as Italy's prime minister hardens his stance
against troops. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ The talks in Russia: Viktor
Chernomyrdin and Strobe Talbott, along with President Martii
Ahtisaari of Finland, gather outside Moscow in a follow-up to
Chernomyrdin's talks with Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav
president. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis on all the things
that have gone wrong with the NATO campaign. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ War fatigue is growing in the
Yugoslavian capital as casualties mount, and while stirrings are
faint, a circumspect political debate is developing, and the
splintered opposition is thinking about what Yugoslavia could look
like after the war, and even after President Slobodan Milosevic. By
Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ATTACK (Belgrade) _ A scene/news story on the heaviest
NATO attack on Belgrade since the Chinese Embassy was hit. A
hospital was hit with patients reported killed. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES-U.S. (Fort Dix, N.J.) _ Kosovar refugees at Fort
Dix are to be resettled in communities across the country as soon
as possible. The first families will go to Boise, Idaho; Sarasota,
Fla.; and Seattle. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: A story budgeted earlier, KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels), is now
ELIMINATED. It's spot elements will fold into KOSOVO-PENTAGON.
</P>
