<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5155 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTINGS-NYTS     05-20 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTINGS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 WE DON'T LIVE in PLEASANTVILLE ANYMORE  
 &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.)  By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1999 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Pop quiz:
</P>
<P>
   Think back to your junior high and high school days. What movie,
TV show, song, video game and/or book influenced you the most?
Which pop culture experience affected your thought process, guided
your behavior, and left the most lasting impression on you?
</P>
<P>
   What's that? You can't really think of one?
</P>
<P>
   Congratulations, that's the correct answer. Oh sure, you might
remember imitating James Dean or dancing like John Travolta, or
perhaps you dressed like Cyndi Lauper or you steeped yourself in
the grunge culture _ but those were passing fads indigenous to your
particular teen era. Nothing you read or watched or listened to had
that much of an impact on you.
</P>
<P>
   All right, time for question No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Describe the most humiliating and hurtful experience of your
teen years. The episode, or series of episodes, that wounded you to
the core and made you ache inside so much that you wished you were
dead. The kind of trauma that left permanent psychic scars.
</P>
<P>
   What's that? You'll need extra sheets of paper to accommodate
all you have to say about this matter?
</P>
<P>
   No surprise there either. Unless you were a zitless homecoming
queen or an all-state jock _ and maybe even then _ you no doubt
went through a period when you were ostracized, mocked, embarrassed
or ignored by the coolest, hippest groups in school. You have
painfully vivid memories of the time you didn't get asked to prom
or you were beaten up in the locker room or someone slapped a
``LOSER'' sign on your back and you walked around for an hour
before anyone told you.
</P>
<P>
   Kids can be meaner and tougher than junkyard dogs. They'll tease
and bully and psychologically torture their supposed weaker or
weirder peers, for the sheer rotten fun of it. Nowhere is the class
system more clearly defined than in the hallways of an American
high school.
</P>
<P>
   One month since the shootings at Columbine High, we have yet
another nightmare in the news from Conyers, Ga., and the adult
world continues its effort to find some answers.
</P>
<P>
   Special sessions in Washington have focused on the role of the
entertainment industry in shaping the mindset of today's youth. The
president scolded Hollywood _ then zipped to Beverly Hills for a $2
million fundraiser.
</P>
<P>
   On the cable news networks, the experts blather endlessly about
cultural influences. Nearly all of the Y2K presidential candidates
are offering their own opinions on video games, R-rated movies,
Marilyn Manson, whatever.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, I'm wondering what really has the most negative
impact on the twisted minds of school shooters. In the case of Eric
Harris and Dylan Klebold, was it the Internet and Marilyn Manson
and KMFDM and ``The Matrix'' _ or was it the cumulative effect of
getting slammed against lockers by the baseball players and
wrestlers, of being called ``fags,'' of the daily hallway taunting
at the hands of the privileged jockocracy at Columbine?
</P>
<P>
   What do you think.
</P>
<P>
   We all know this stuff goes on. Every day in high schools across
this country, elite members of the goodlooking, strong, popular
crowd pick on the freaks and the weirdos and the losers _ often
with the encouragement, or at least the tacit approval, of teachers
and administrators. I can remember jocks at my high school
tormenting the kids in gym classes, as coaches looked on and just
laughed. And that ain't unique.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are...Columbine! We are...Columbine!'' Students exhorted
the community to make that group-statement at a number of memorial
services for their slain friends. It was a statement of resilience,
of pride, of family.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a sports cheer. The kind of 1950s, rah-rah,
we've-got-spirit-yes-we-do chant that would have elicited the scorn
of the Trench Coat Mafia.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say excellence in academics, and in sports,
should not be encouraged and rewarded _ but the value systems in
most learning institutions are completely out of whack. We don't
live in Pleasantville any more and it's not always the coolest
thing to be on the cheerleading squad or the football team _ but
don't kid yourself, the star athletes and the attractive kids still
get the best deal in school. Teachers aren't giving special breaks
to Goths.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but who's going to convene a panel on peer pressure, on
decency, on emphasizing tolerance in high schools? It's much easier
to focus on Doom and ``Natural Born Killers'' and teen-Nazi chic.
</P>
<P>
   I still believe nobody other than Harris and Klebold is
responsible for the massacre in Littleton _ but I have a feeling
that in the aftermath of the shootings, more than a few of the
surviving ``cool kids'' at Columbine have had long nights when they
remembered picking on those two and their friends, taunting them
and treating them like dirt because they were different.
</P>
<P>
   I'll bet they wish they had those moments back.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper is a columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times, a
radio host and a commentator for Fox News in Chicago _ and has
appeared on programs such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News
with Dan Rather,'' ``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 1935EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
