<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5160 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOMBING-BO     05-20 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOMBING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERRANT BOMB HITS HOSPITAL IN BELGRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ Radan Dusanka fought back tears Thursday, standing in
the rubble of what used to be her hospital, of what used to be her
ward, the neurological unit at Dragisa Misovic Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have been me,'' she said, looking at the shell of a
building, its three floors collapsed on top of each other.
</P>
<P>
   Dusanka, a nurse, was supposed to work the midnight shift but
changed her schedule at the last moment. It was a decision that
probably saved her life. At least four people died when a missile
that NATO said went astray early Thursday and landed short of a
military barracks here in the Yugoslav capital, crashing into the
hospital's neurological intensive care unit.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the errant NATO bomb kill and injure civilians, it
damaged the nearby homes of several European ambassadors. It was
another embarrassing mistake for NATO, another propaganda coup for
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But for people like Dusanka and Dr. Miodrag Lazic, who work at
the hospital, it was more than another move in the ongoing game of
war between NATO and Milosevic. It was a desecration of a place
that should be a refuge for ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
   Lazic, a urologist and deputy director of the hospital, said he
and other medical staff rushed to the scene around 1 a.m. after
hearing what he called a tremendous explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two nurses were trapped on the third floor, cut off,'' he
said, standing next to a huge crater and the twisted wreckage of
wrought iron bed frames. ``We had to improvise to bring them down.
But the very sight of the killed people, the corpses, was
abhorrent.''
</P>
<P>
   While the neurological ward took a direct hit, several other
hospital buildings were badly damaged by the blast. Among the
injured were two women who were hit by flying glass after giving
birth in the maternity ward.
</P>
<P>
   Lazic said other patients were moved to other hospitals,
including a baby that was born 10 minutes before the bomb struck.
Asked whether the baby was a boy or a girl, an exhausted Lazic,
sweating profusely under a hot midday sun and a leather jacket that
covered his green surgical scrubs, just shrugged and said, ``I
don't know. I'm just a urologist.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporters were given a guided tour of the bomb site by Yugoslav
Army officials, who quickly ended the tour when reporters began
picking up live and spent bullet casings on the access road that
leads to the adjacent military facility. The bullets appeared to be
machine gun ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   Some medical staff at the scene said military vehicles routinely
park on the access road, which is fenced off but right next to the
neurological unit, one of 24 separate buildings on the hospital
grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Leposava Milicevic, the Yugoslav health minister, insisted no
military vehicles or personnel are allowed on hospital grounds. But
NATO officials said their pilots were targeting the military
facility, whose gates are less than 200 yards down the access road
from where the hospital building was destroyed. NATO said the
errant bomb fell about 500 yards short of its target, but said it
could not confirm its bomb hit a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Yugoslav officials, Milicevic said the hospital
bombing was not a mistake, but a deliberate targeting of ``helpless
civilians.'' She also accused NATO of purposely dropping a second
bomb near the hospital 15 minutes after the initial bomb, in an
effort to kill rescuers.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea called allegations that the hospital
was bombed on purpose ``completely false.''
</P>
<P>
   Local residents said they heard up to eight separate explosions
early Thursday, during what was the heaviest bombing in the
Yugoslav capital in about two weeks. One woman resident said she
assumed the bombs were aimed at the nearby home of Zeljko
Raznatovic, the Serb paramilitary leader known as Arkan.
</P>
<P>
   That the bombing began less than a half-hour after the Russian
envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin took off from Belgrade after seven hours
of meetings with Milosevic fed local cynicism.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, NATO officials acknowledged that its pilots had
dropped seven bombs on the military barracks in the Dedinje area,
an exclusive neighborhood that includes ambassador's row. Among the
residences hit was one belonging to the ambassador of Spain, whose
country is the home of NATO secretary general Javier Solana. The
Spanish government was one of several that scolded NATO, asking it
to use more care.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Spanish government considers it to be of the utmost
importance to ensure that military activities are carried out with
the greatest caution in order to avoid victims in the civilian
population and damage to buildings that are not considered
strategic targets,'' the communique from Madrid said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the patients at Dragisa Misovic Medical Center who were
jolted from their beds when the bomb struck was the hospital's
director, Dr. Radisav Scepanovic. Scepanovic had been working
100-hour weeks since the bombing began March 24 and had been
admitted to the hospital's cardiac care unit earlier after
suffering what appeared to be a heart attack, fellow staff members
said.
</P>
<P>
   Milicevic said three patients, two women and a man, and a night
watchman were killed by the bomb. She said the death toll could
rise, because it remains unclear how many people were in the
neurological ward when it got hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hospitals will be targeted again,'' she predicted, saying that
Dragisa Misovic had suffered ``collateral damage'' three times
before, but that this was the first direct hit taken by a hospital
building.
</P>
<P>
   Radan Dusanka, the nurse who worked in the neurological unit,
could only contemplate her good fortune, and the bad luck of those
who were in a hospital ward when the euphemism ``collateral
damage'' became tragically human.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an old woman under all that,'' she said, pointing to
the twisted debris, as water hissed from broken pipes. ``When all
you leave, they will start digging for her again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 1936EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
