<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0338 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5162 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALBANIA-AID-BOS &LR;      05-20 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANIA-AID-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO PLEDGES MILITARY AID TO ALBANIA, MACEDONIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ Over a mid-afternoon beer Thursday, career
soldier and Army 1st Capt. Albert Mullai was making a wish-list of
what NATO could do to repay Albania for its cooperation during the
Yugoslavian crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Even before dusk, the Albanian army's chief spokesman would
learn that more than a few of his wishes had been granted. In
Brussels, NATO announced that it would supply Albania and Macedonia
with long-term aid, and help both Balkan nations meet the
alliance's entry requirements.
</P>
<P>
   That most likely means modernizing their armed forces _ a big
wish of his _ and providing two of Europe's poorest countries with
cash assistance. Representatives of Albania and Macedonia were in
Brussels to discuss those improvements as well as both countries'
current security needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This of course is military assistance which is long term, but
which is also directly linked to their particular needs stemming
from the crisis in the region,'' NATO spokesman Jamie Shea told
reporters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   At almost the same time in downtown Tirana, Mullai was dreaming
aloud of roads without missing manhole covers, camouflage uniforms
that do not need mending, and tanks that do not belch exhaust
fumes. NATO's next potential member has no more than 15,000 regular
Army troops, most of them draftees, few willing to serve beyond the
one-year requirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider ourselves equals with the other armies now here,''
said Mullai, sometimes speaking in adequate English, other times
relying on an interpreter. ``Our help to them is very important. We
give them our airports, our roads, anything they need.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mullai did admit to some pangs of jealousy when he saw
the military equipment brought into Albania by heavy transport
aircraft, another item the country lacks. He conceded much of the
army's own equipment is outdated, some of it more than 50 years
old. But he insisted the Kalashnikovs that soldiers carry _ and
that one soldier was spotted using to play air guitar while in
uniform _ are the finest rifles available.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between my army and their army is that they
have the equipment to fight; we didn't have uniforms, sometimes no
weapons,'' said Kadri Sadik, a World War II veteran who was at the
Defense Ministry to pick up his monthly $18.50 benefits check.
``But Albanian soldiers are like lions when they have to defend the
homeland.''
</P>
<P>
   From all appearances, however, Albanian soldiers appear to lack
the discipline that western armies insist upon in their troops. At
Tuesday's appearance by British Prime Minister Tony Blair, few
soldiers bothered to stand at attention and at Thursday's arrival
of United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan, many of the
soldiers standing in sloppy formation also had empty sidearm
holsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's natural to be jealous of what other people have, but in
terms of knowledge and training, we do not feel inferior...,''
Mullai said. ``It's true that our weapons are previous generation,
but we have enough arms, enough munitions, more than enough....One
good result of communism is that we have a lot of weapons to choose
from, even if they are old.''
</P>
<P>
   Albania, however, has no intention of using those weapons in
close combat against Serbian troops. While Mullai insisted again
and again that the Albanian army has earned worldwide respect as a
fighting force, he also stressed that it was doing everything
possible to avoid provoking Serbian forces who regularly violate
Albania's border. He also denied that Albania was training the
Kosovo Liberation Army to do that job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is the Army is responsible for defending the
integrity and freedom of the country, but normally it's not
responsible for the border line,'' he said. ``In the current
conditions, the army is acting just in the cases where it's needed,
when the border police call for us because what the Serbs are doing
is too much.''
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian army did respond to Serbian incursions with an
unexpected show of force this week. It sent a convoy of nine tanks,
an armored personnel carrier and a truckload of soldiers to the
Albania-Yugoslavia border, where army tanks returned Serbian fire.
</P>
<P>
   On May 11, after the Serbs attacked four border villages,
killing two civilians and wounding numerous others, the Albanian
army also responded with force, Mullai said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four months ago, the provocations started and have continued
nearly every day, but the Army is involved in only two cases,'' he
said. ``We were following this logic: Avoiding provocation is our
goal. That's why the whole time the army was present but did not
get involved with fighting them.''
</P>
<P>
   In at least one respect, Albania has long been ready for an
assault on its sovereignty. The country is dotted with
mushroom-shaped bunkers, more than 600,000 in all, although no one
knows the exact number. The leftover from the communist era also
includes underground shelters which can house thousands of soldiers
at a time. One in the north, in Kukes, descends seven levels and
opens into a cavern that once held everything from weapons to
hospitals to bread-making equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bunker mentality is the previous generation's, not ours,''
said Mullai. ``Bunkers are one form of fortification. They're not
too modern, but they're strong. If used by educated soldiers, they
can be very useful.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the useful old while obtaining the essential new was
another of Mullai's wishes. He spoke of a program to persuade at
least 25 percent of army troops to become career soldiers,
reenlisting for five-year stretches. He boasted of the
multi-lingual capabilities of the army's 2,000 officers, among
which were 1,400 who received part of their military education in
Turkey, England, Germany or the United States. Even now, he said,
his troops train using the same methods as their would-be NATO
partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't help in NATO's attack because our equipment is
different,'' said Mullai, who supports the introduction of NATO or
US ground troops into Serb territory. ``We support them as much as
we can. That is what we can do for the moment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
