<HEADER>
A5168 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIVETTI-TELECOM-NYT &LR;      05-20 0314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIVETTI-TELECOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLIVETTI EDGES CLOSER TO TELECOM TAKEOVER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Olivetti inched closer Thursday to possible victory in a
$65 billion hostile bid for Telecom Italia by amassing nearly 20
percent of the shares in its larger rival, roughly twice the stake
it held 24 hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   With only a day to go before Olivetti's tender offer for Telecom
Italia expires, it was still unclear whether the challenger would
get the minimum 35 percent of the huge utility's shares required to
keep the bid alive. But the surge in the number of shares offered
over 24 hours was interpreted by some market analysts as a sign of
impending success.
</P>
<P>
   If Olivetti amassed at least 35 percent of Telecom Italia, it
would delay, if not wreck, Telecom Italia's friendly merger with
Deutsche Telekom. If Olivetti ultimately acquired Telecom Italia,
it would be one of the largest successful hostile takeovers ever.
</P>
<P>
   Italy's stock market said Thursday night that equity holders in
Telecom Italia had tendered 1.04 billion common shares to Olivetti,
or 19.89 percent of the total, compared with less than 10 percent
as of Wednesday night. But many large investors have said that they
will wait until Friday to decide.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti had indicated earlier Thursday that it had firm
commitments through its banks to get 42 percent to 47 percent of
Telecom Italia shares. Telecom Italia protested that such
disclosures were improper and asked the nation's stock market
regulator to suspend the bid. The regulatory agency denied the
request but cautioned Olivetti about spreading unverifiable
information.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom Italia shares fell 2.4 percent Thursday to 9.69 euros,
or $10.29, after surging Wednesday on expectations of an Olivetti
takeover; Olivetti's share price also dropped, by 1.7 percent, to
3.30 euros.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
