<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5170 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTING21-COX     05-20 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTING21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Breakup precedes shooting of students at Georgia high school
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONYERS, Ga. _ Exactly one month after the fatal shootings in
Littleton, Colo., a suicidal high school student, angry over
breaking up with his girlfriend, turned his anger on the world
Thursday, shooting six of his classmates and emotionally scarring
countless others.
</P>
<P>
   No one was killed at Heritage High School in Rockdale County, a
middle-class community about 20 miles east of Atlanta. Five victims
suffered minor injuries, and a 15-year-old, Stephanie Laster,
underwent surgery after a bullet struck her in the buttocks and
entered her intestines.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-year-old, known to talk big about his guns, started
shooting at about 8 a.m. into a crowd of about 300 students in the
lobby near the cafeteria. Authorities say he was looking to shoot
the boy who had stolen his girl, though that person was not in
sight.
</P>
<P>
   As the rapid-fire shots ruptured the morning calm, panicked
students dropped to the floor, leaped behind tables, or ran out the
doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole school, everybody, was just roaring out of the
school,'' said Amy Ladd, 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pop, pop, pop, pop, pop,'' added Kylie Forrester, a
sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the school, the breathless students hugged one another
for comfort. A half dozen linked hands in a circle and bowed their
heads in prayer. Some said they thought it was a prank, coming on
the last day of senior class. The day before someone released 2,000
crickets in the hallways.
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel Deeter recalled chatting with the teen 10 minutes
before he started shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard you had broken up with your girlfriend,'' Deeter had
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'm real mad about it,'' the student responded.
</P>
<P>
   The teen looked distant and removed as he spoke of the failed
relationship, a romance of two years that ended this week. ``He
looked like he was thinking about something else,'' said Deeter.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the bullets. ``He shot the kid next to me in the
foot,'' Deeter said. ``It was as though he was looking right
through people.''
</P>
<P>
   The shooter, who was wearing jeans and a baggy, blue pullover,
seemed to be firing quickly and at at random. Deeter screamed,
``What are you doing!''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Rosa, a junior, was shot in the right ankle. Jason Cheek
and Brian Barnhardt were shot in the buttocks. Cania Collins was
shot in the knee.
</P>
<P>
   Drake Hoy thought the first shot was a firecracker. The second
sounded real enough, and the third shot sliced into his left foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to run, but it started hurting pretty bad,'' said
Hoy, 18. ``I took off my boot and blood was everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers and parents got him and the other injured students to
the front lawn, from where they were rushed to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   When he finished shooting, the former Boy Scout dropped his
rifle and backed his way outside the building. He pulled out a
handgun and put it in his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   An assistant principal approached him, saying, ``Let me have the
gun,'' said senior Joe Watts, who watched from a window. The teen
handed the revolver to him. If any doubt remains that school
shootings have become a trend, this incident ended the debate. That
the shootings happened in metro Atlanta, in a school known for
parental involvement and good academics, has aroused fear in many
parents, students and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools are no longer immune to guns, drugs and violence,''
said Pam Riley, executive director of the Center for the Prevention
of School Violence in North Carolina. ``But I don't think that all
schools should panic and close. Then the terrorism will win out.
What we need to do is provide ways for kids to do the right
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Heritage High School was named one of the top 10 schools in the
metro area by U.S. News and World Report. About 80 percent of
Heritage graduates go on to college.
</P>
<P>
   After the carnage at Columbine, Heritage was among many metro
Atlanta schools who felt the reverberations. Letters were sent out
to parents assuring them the school was safe. But, like many
schools, Heritage has seen numerous bomb threats in recent weeks.
The school has video surveillance cameras in the hallways and an
armed sheriff's deputy on duty.
</P>
<P>
   With TV crews broadcasting the frightened faces of Heritage
students, a collective angst swept across many schools and
households. Principals scrambled to figure out what to do next and
how to prevent a similar occurrence before the end of the school
year. Some parents, already in a heightened state of concern since
Columbine, have suggested simply canceling the rest of the school
year, bringing down the curtain on a year brimming with fear.
Others called for metal detectors and more police in the schools,
outcries that have been echoed for weeks following Columbine and
the spate of bomb threats.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
