r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LAD     05-20 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENTS, DINGS ARE FEW IN THIS CARR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Oba Carr is the latest in a lengthy line of Oscar De
La Hoya foils, a 9-to-1 underdog considered to be nothing more than
a footnote to De La Hoya's planned September showdown with Felix
Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there are some vital differences between Carr and so many
of those hapless De La Hoya victims in recent years who were
preordained losers before the opening-round bell even rang.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, unlike a Jorge Paez, or a James Leija, or a
Genaro Hernandez, or a Rafael Ruelas, Carr isn't an undersized
target with a brittle jaw. He's 5-9, has a 72-inch reach, and has
campaigned as a welterweight since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   For another, unlike a Hector (Macho) Camacho or a Julio Cesar
Chavez, Carr hasn't celebrated too many birthdays for his violent
sport. He's a mere 27.
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, unlike a Patrick Charpentier, or a David Kamau, or
a Giorgio Campanella, Carr actually can fight. He has a 48-2-1
record with 28 knockouts that includes victories over such noble
men as Frankie Randall, Livingstone Bramble and Derrell Coley.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there are a couple of negatives about Carr, or you can be
sure De La Hoya's promoter, Bob Arum, would never have allowed him
to face his biggest money-maker in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Carr was stopped by Felix Trinidad in eight rounds five years
ago and lost a majority decision to Ike Quartey in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But Carr did dispatch Trinidad to the mat and, anyway, who other
than Pernell Whitaker and Macho Camacho doesn't get knocked out by
Trinidad? Carr also decked Quartey, and their rumble was so close
that one judge called it a draw.
</P>
<P>
   So, while nobody the fight aficionados, the oddsmakers and the
media is giving Carr even a modest chance of upsetting De La Hoya
Saturday night in the first major event ever staged at the new
Mandalay Bay Events Center, Oba Carr himself naturally envisions a
stunning outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people look at me as being a peon,'' says Carr with
emotion. ``They treat me with total disrespect. A lot of people are
talking more about De La Hoya's fight with Trinidad than about his
fight with me. And that's a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt in my mind at all that I'm going to beat
Oscar. I'm definitely in the best shape of my life both spiritually
and physically. I've gone through some trials and tribulations
during my career, but those are over with. My head is clear, and
I've had the best eight weeks of training that I've ever had.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely feel my speed and elusiveness are superior to
Oscar's. I don't think he's ever faced anyone as quick as me, or
even could hit as hard as me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ike Quartey hits you with one punch at a time, but I can hit
you in bunches, three, four at a time. Oscar has never been
attacked the way I will attack him. I have great respect for Oscar
De La Hoya. But I have even greater respect for Oba Carr.''
</P>
<P>
   As do so many fighters, Oba Carr has endured his share of
promotional and managerial miseries, having fought under the banner
of Don King Productions for most of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``For whatever reason, King forced Oba's father, Eddie Carr, out
of the picture as Oba's trainer,'' relates Tom Loeffler, Carr's Los
Angeles-based manager whose Mouthpiece Productions landed Carr a
K-Swiss TV commercial. ``I know most father-son relationships don't
work in boxing, but Oba definitely has been a better fighter during
his career when trained by his father. And his father is training
him once again.''
</P>
<P>
   Carr, a bachelor who still lives in his native Detroit, will
earn a mere $350,000 for endangering his health against De La Hoya,
whose purse is expected to exceed $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big money will come to me after I beat De La Hoya,'' says
Carr, whose fistic inspiration came from having his bike stolen
when he was 6. ``You know, to be honest with you, I find it
insulting the way some people are looking at this fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are some people out there who feel I have what it
takes to win, but there are others who think this fight already has
been settled. No fight is settled until you get in the ring and
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   There are those who believe Oscar De La Hoya's wily promoter,
Bob Arum, would never match De La Hoya against someone capable of
scoring an upset with the multi-million dollar match with Trinidad
looming on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who believe that Carr's fiercest fighting days
were left behind in those punishing brawls he had with Bramble and
Trinidad and Quartey.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who believe that Carr will crumble the first
time De La Hoya catches him with one of his wicked left hooks.
</P>
<P>
   Oba Carr admits such unflattering rhetoric has been grating on
his nerves in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel I have anything to prove as a fighter,'' he says.
``I've fought the best welterweights in the world, and held my own
against them all. I'm a much better fighter now than I was when I
fought Trinidad and Quartey. Much more experienced, much more
dedicated to my craft. Like I said, I have nothing to prove, but I
will prove after I beat Oscar De La Hoya that a lot of people don't
know what they're talking about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
