<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-GENOME-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMAN GENOME PURSUIT IS BIOLOGY'S MANHATTAN PROJECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Behind the hoopla about genes, biotechnology and the
coming revolution in medicine, is a labor-intensive, massive and
contentious scientific effort that is building the foundation for
all the hopes and promises.
</P>
<P>
   It's been called biology's Manhattan Project or the equivalent
of humankind's race to the moon.
</P>
<P>
   It's called the Human Genome Project. And the goal is to
identify the 100,000 or so genes that reside somewhere within the 3
billion ``letters'' of DNA in the human body _ the genome.
</P>
<P>
   Launched nearly a decade ago by the National Institutes of
Health and the U.S. Department of Energy, the goal was to create a
public database of the human genome for all of science _ a
periodical table for biology.
</P>
<P>
   That's still the aim, but times change. Today, the public effort
has competition from the private sector. There's money in them
genes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to create an extremely complicated situation in
which there's a risk the public sector will start to lose control
over this information,'' said Dr. Maynard Olson, a world-renowned
molecular biologist and head of the University of Washington's
genome center.
</P>
<P>
   Olson's team at the UW is one of eight centers designated by the
National Institutes of Health to work on the public effort, which
is also aided by Britain's Sanger Center and the Wellcome Trust of
London.
</P>
<P>
   Competing with the public side is Dr. J. Craig Venter and his
company, Celera Corp., backed by scientific instrument maker Perkin
Elmer. Perkin Elmer makes some of the machines used to perform
rapid, automated DNA ``sequencing'' operations. The Human Genome
Project depends on such machines to identify the linear sequence of
all 3 billion units _ called ``bases'' _ of human DNA.
</P>
<P>
   The machines, in turn, depend upon Dr. Philip Green, a UW expert
in computational biology who collaborates with Olson. Green and his
colleagues wrote the software, called Phred, which is crucial to
distinguishing one base from another.
</P>
<P>
   While the UW's team is among the smaller of the NIH centers
working to decode the human genome, Olson and Green are widely
recognized as leaders in emphasizing sequencing accuracy and data
quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people, especially at some of these bioinformatic
companies, are looking to exploit this stuff based on existing
technologies,'' Green said. ``To me, the most interesting task is
in analyzing the sequence information.''
</P>
<P>
   Venter is a former NIH researcher who moved to the private
sector in 1992 to pursue genome sequencing free of government
restraints he thought were impeding progress.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with hundreds of automated sequencers, Venter and Perkin
Elmer announced a year ago that Celera would complete the genome
privately by the year 2001 _ well before the public project's
expected completion date of 2005. Venter claimed that he was doing
this for the sake of science.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sequence information provides a starting point from which
the real research into thousands of diseases that have a genetic
basis can begin,'' he told Congress last year. ``The sooner we can
get to this starting point, the sooner we can begin to see a payoff
in ultimately improving human health.''
</P>
<P>
   There also is a financial payoff. If Celera and Perkin Elmer are
first to identify a gene sequence with implications for drug
development, they can file a patent.
</P>
<P>
   Venter initially promised to make the private genome data
available immediately but is now saying Celera will release it
quarterly. He also said that the company will charge a fee for
access to the data and market its database commercially.
</P>
<P>
   Olson, who testified at the same hearing in May 1998, has become
Venter's foil, arguing that his frantic private effort to claim
genetic turf is contrary to the purpose of the project and will
result in poor quality data.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we going to spend the next 20 years sorting out problems
in the genome or are we going to do the job right the first time?''
Olson asked.
</P>
<P>
   Venter has certainly spurred the NIH to speed up its efforts, he
said. The question, Olson said, is if speeding things up is in the
public interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk here for the publicly funded program is one of
overreaction,'' Olson told Congress. Infuriating Venter, he
testified that he would stake his reputation on the prediction that
the hasty Celera-Perkin Elmer approach would produce ``low quality
data'' with garbled sequences and more than ``100,000 serious
gaps.''
</P>
<P>
   Venter, asked about Olson's complaint, responded that it was
``irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Some at Celera have recently complained about a delay in getting
an updated version of Phred, Green's program, suggesting the delay
may be aimed at hurting Venter's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Green, however, has said this is because of technical
constraints and noted that the delay will affect the public effort
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Manhattan Project or NASA's moon shot, the Human
Genome Project is often portrayed as a public-private partnership.
Olson said he's concerned it's now become more of a public-private
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more, research in biology is being funded by the
private sector,'' he said. ``I'm not against that. I actually
advocated, early on in the genome project, that the federal
government pay the private sector to do much of this research.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to efficiency and large-scale production, Olson
said, the private sector is better than universities or government.
But when the private sector both pays for and does the research, he
said, they expect to own the product.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a reason why we have publicly supported science,''
Olson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
