<SLUG> BC-NEPAL-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNING PARTY IN NEPAL GAINS MAJORITY IN PARLIAMENTARY ELECTION
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KATMANDU, Nepal _ Political stability may have finally come to
this small Himalayan nation after elections that concluded this
week. The governing Nepali Congress seems on its way to a
parliamentary majority, ending 4 and a half years of fractious
coalitions that brought five governments to one of the world's
youngest democracies.
</P>
<P>
   Nepal is a landlocked kingdom of 23 million people between two
giant neighbors, China and India. In 1990, King Birendra gave up
absolute power in favor of a constitutional monarchy.
</P>
<P>
   But multiparty elections since then have failed to provide a
clear winner that could maintain power. Instead, oddly assembled,
ill-starred alliances became routine.
</P>
<P>
   The latest election, held in two stages on May 3 and May 17, was
needed after the Nepali Congress, made up of social democrats, had
a falling out with the Marxist-Leninists.
</P>
<P>
   The Marxist-Leninists are a splinter group, broken free from the
United Marxist-Leninists, who were deemed to be insufficiently
anti-Indian and anti-American.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, victors were declared for 173 of the Parliament's 205
seats. The Nepali Congress has won 96 and leads in at least six
others, according to the Election Commission. The United
Marxist-Leninists have won 60 seats, the Marxist-Leninists zero and
various other parties 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results show that people are becoming more politically
mature,'' said Bishwa Nath Upadhyay, a retired chief justice of the
Supreme Court and the main framer of the constitution. ``They
realize that a hung Parliament can't be an effective government.''
</P>
<P>
   Months before the vote, Prime Minister Girija Prasad Koirala
said he would step aside and allow his ally Krishna Prasad
Bhattarai to take over. The two men, both in their 70s, have been
rivals and the move was seen as a display of party unity.
</P>
<P>
   Vote tabulations will continue for a few more days. The process
is arduous. Some ballot boxes must be hand-carried across mountain
paths in two-day journeys.
</P>
<P>
   At district counting centers, every paper ballot is unfolded as
officials of each party look on. Only 40 percent of Nepalese adults
are literate. Voters put a stamp of ink next to symbols on the
ballot. Officials commonly quarrel over every smudged mark.
</P>
<P>
   By and large, the election has gone smoothly and honestly,
according to U.N. observers.
</P>
<P>
   Maoist insurgents had demanded a boycott of the vote, but the
turnout exceeded 60 percent, with many people willing to spend
hours in line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
