<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5189 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-HNS &LR;      05-20 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON STRESSES NATO'S DETERMINATION IN OUSTING YUGOSLAV FORCES
FROM KOSOVO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton insisted Thursday that NATO
remained ``united in our determination to persist as long as it
takes,'' to oust Slobodan Milosevic's forces from Kosovo and return
ethnic Albanian refugees to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials projected a portrait of unity, despite
signs of division, as Russian-led diplomatic efforts intensified
along with the air raids over Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who received a briefing from his national security team
at the White House, said the military campaign ``is working'' and
Milosevic has no choice but to accept terms set by the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each day we hear reports of desertion in the Serbian army,
dissension in Belgrade, unrest in Serbian communities. President
Milosevic should know that he cannot change the fundamental terms
that we have outlined because they are simply what is required for
the Kosovars to go home and live in peace,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is not whether `ethnic cleansing' will be
reversed, but how much of the military will be destroyed because of
his intransigence along the way, how much damage will be done to
Serbia because of his delays,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's remarks came as envoys from Russia, Finland and the
United States gathered in Moscow to review reports that Milosevic
was prepared to accept the peace terms but wanted to negotiate with
the United Nations. Also, allied war planes stepped up their
bombing raids despite reports that a stray missile struck a
Belgrade hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke briefly about Kosovo when he announced his
intention to nominate Gen. Hugh Shelton to a second term as
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   However, the president failed to clarify comments made earlier
this week that the use of NATO ground troops remained an option if
the air campaign failed.
</P>
<P>
   The issues of using ground troops or pausing the bombing have
been divisive ones for the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   British Foreign Minister Robin Cook met with Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright in a display of solidarity and said there was no
division.
</P>
<P>
   Britain has pressed the United States to join its call for an
invasion force into Kosovo. Germany and Italy oppose ground troops,
and German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder this week said there would
be no ground invasion. And Italy called for a halt to the bombing
while negotiations are under way.
</P>
<P>
   But Cook told reporters ``there is absolutely no strain between
Washington and London'' on the issue of troops. ``We agree totally
on the objectives. We are totally behind the campaign,'' Cook said,
prior to meeting with Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Cook pressed for preparations to begin for a security
force that would ensure the safety of 1.6 million Kosovar refugees
on their return home. NATO has insisted that Milosevic accept an
international peacekeeping force in Kosovo as one of the peace
terms.
</P>
<P>
   Cook said it was vital to build on the success of the air
campaign. ``We have to prepare so that we are ready to take
advantage of that success and take the refugees home. As the
president (Clinton) said, no option is off the table and that
planning goes ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright appeared earlier in the day on Capitol Hill where she
told members of a Senate appropriation panel, ``We all want this
confrontation to end, but we should have the patience and spine to
ensure that it does so on the right terms.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the NATO position remains that all Serb forces must
withdraw from Kosovo although she added that there has been a
discussion of allowing some Serb forces to remain around the
Orthodox Christian holy sites in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   She said the alliance ``is united in its goals'' against an
isolated and unjust regime. ``We are making progress, and we will
persist and we will prevail,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She appeared before the panel bearing a videotape made by a
Kosovar Albanian who recorded the aftermath of a massacre by Serb
troops. She also said the NATO air campaign has destroyed one-third
of Yugoslavia's military equipment.
</P>
<P>
   She conceded the objectives may be simply stated but ``not
easily achieved.'' She said the removal of Milosevic from power is
not one of the objectives although the United States believes
Yugoslavia would be better off with him gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have to stay very focused on what the objective of
this campaign is, and that is to break the back of his military,
the grip that they have over Kosovo can be ended,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
