<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5190 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-NYT &LR;      05-20 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN ENVOY HINTS AT PROGRESS IN KOSOVO TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Negotiations toward a political settlement over Serbia
seemed to inch forward Thursday when Russian mediator Victor
Chernomyrdin met outside Moscow with U.S. Deputy Secretary of State
Strobe Talbott and Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, Russia registered its unhappiness with
NATO by breaking off its military contacts with the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The parties to the talks here have disclosed nothing about their
details. But when Chernomyrdin, a former prime minister, was asked
earlier Thursday whether there was news, he replied, ``Yes, good
news.''
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin had just returned from Belgrade, where he spent
seven hours in talks with President Slobodan Milosevic of
Yugoslavia. He and Talbott had been in Helsinki before that,
talking for two days with Ahtisaari, the European Union's envoy to
the Kosovo talks.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have also said that the talks are making
progress, but that the sides are at odds over the makeup of an
armed international force that would be sent to Kosovo to enforce
any political agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The Interfax news service Thursday quoted Russian officials as
saying that Milosevic and the envoys also disagree over the scope
of any mandate to be given the international bodies and envoys who
will negotiate the political future of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   (In Belgrade, Yugoslav officials said the talks with
Chernomyrdin had gone well. Goran Matic, an influential minister
without portfolio, said in an interview, ``I think we can expect a
political settlement in the next week.'')
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav troops and paramilitary forces have driven hundreds of
thousands of ethnic Albanians from their homes in Kosovo, and there
are reports of mass killings and rapes. NATO has pledged to
continue bombing Yugoslavia until the troops withdraw and Kosovar
Albanians are allowed to return under protection of foreign forces.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has rejected those conditions, but aside from
insisting that Kosovo remain a part of Yugoslavia, his precise
demands are not publicly known. In recent days, Western officials
have suggested that he is increasingly willing to agree to a
political settlement, as long as it does not brand Yugoslavia the
``loser.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia has called NATO the aggressor and demanded an end to the
bombing as a condition for any agreement. Thursday the Foreign
Ministry accused the Western allies of ``the most blatant violation
of the Geneva Convention on the protection of victims of war'' in
connection with reports of the accidental bombing of a Belgrade
hospital overnight. Serbia says four civilians died in the raid.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's Defense Ministry said Thursday that it had suspended
all military contacts with NATO, recalled all Russian forces from
military training in NATO countries and reduced other exchanges
with the alliance and its members until a settlement is reached.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all that, Moscow seems to have gained a central role in
fashioning an end to the conflict. President Boris Yeltsin talked
by telephone with Ahtisaari on Thursday; a spokesman said Yeltsin
had called for an end to the ``barbarous'' air attacks on
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov also met in Moscow with a
United Nations special envoy on Kosovo, Slovakian Foreign Minister
Eduard Kukan. Ivanov is to meet Friday with another U.N. envoy,
former Swedish Prime Minister Carl Bildt, who had an active role in
ending the fighting in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   And on Friday, Russian officials are to fly to Bonn, where
another session of officials from the seven major industrial powers
and Russia _ the so-called Group of 8 _ will try to narrow
differences over Kosovo. Those talks are to focus on drafting a
proposal for a Kosovo settlement that can be presented to the U.N.
Security Council for approval.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has already drafted its version of a resolution, Ivanov
said Thursday, but he added that it did not cover a number of
differences among the negotiators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
