<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-GOODBOOKS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A time line of the century's most important books
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May23.
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   1900
</P>
<P>
   L. Frank Baum's ``The Wizard of Oz'' and
</P>
<P>
   Sigmund Freud's ``The Interpretation of Dreams'' are published.
</P>
<P>
   1903
</P>
<P>
   Helen Keller writes ``The Story of My Life.''
</P>
<P>
   1904
</P>
<P>
   The first comic books containing colored cartoons are published.
</P>
<P>
   James Joyce and Nora Barnacle have their first date June 16 _
Bloomsday _ the day on which his novel ``Ulysses'' would take
place.
</P>
<P>
   1906
</P>
<P>
   Upton Sinclair writes ``The
</P>
<P>
   Jungle,'' resulting in reforms in the meatpacking industry.
</P>
<P>
   1908
</P>
<P>
   L.M. Montgomery writes ``Anne of Green Gables.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Grahame writes ``The Wind in the Willows.''
</P>
<P>
   1910
</P>
<P>
   E.M. Forster writes ``Howards End.''
</P>
<P>
   1912
</P>
<P>
   Fyodor Dostoyevsky's novel ``The Brothers Karamazov'' is
published in English.
</P>
<P>
   1914
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Rice Burroughs' ``Tarzan of the Apes'' emerges from the
</P>
<P>
   jungle.
</P>
<P>
   1916
</P>
<P>
   Carl Jung's ``Psychology of the Unconscious'' is published.
</P>
<P>
   1917
</P>
<P>
   The newly founded Modern Library publishes D.H. Lawrence's
``Sons and Lovers.''
</P>
<P>
   1919
</P>
<P>
   John Reed writes ``Ten Days That Shook the World,'' about the
Russian Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   1920
</P>
<P>
   Agatha Christie publishes her first book, ``The Mysterious
Affair at Styles,'' and introduces inspector Hercule Poirot.
</P>
<P>
   1922
</P>
<P>
   James Joyce's ``Ulysses'' is
</P>
<P>
   published in Paris in 1922.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Post publishes the first edition of ``Etiquette in
Society, in Business, in Politics and at Home.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendrik Willem van Loon wins the first Newbery Medal for
children's literature with ``The Story of Mankind.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Arlington Robinson wins the first Pulitzer Prize for
poetry with
</P>
<P>
   ``Collected Poems.''
</P>
<P>
   1923
</P>
<P>
   Kahlil Gibran publishes ``The Prophet.''
</P>
<P>
   1925
</P>
<P>
   F. Scott Fitzgerald's ``The Great
</P>
<P>
   Gatsby'' hits the stores.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Woolf writes ``Mrs.
</P>
<P>
   Dalloway.''
</P>
<P>
   1926
</P>
<P>
   A.A. Milne introduces ``Winnie-the-Pooh'' to the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Book-of-the-Month
</P>
<P>
   Club and the Literary Guild are
</P>
<P>
   founded, allowing people to build their libraries by mail order.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Hemingway throws his hat into the bullring with
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sun Also Rises.''
</P>
<P>
   1927
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Mann's ``The Magic Mountain'' is published in English.
</P>
<P>
   1928
</P>
<P>
   The Oxford English Dictionary is published.
</P>
<P>
   1929
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Wolfe's ``Look Homeward, Angel'' is published.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sartoris,'' the first novel in William Faulkner's
Yoknapatawpha County series, is published.
</P>
<P>
   1930
</P>
<P>
   Dashiell Hammett introduces hard-boiled detective Sam Spade.
</P>
<P>
   Sinclair Lewis is the first
</P>
<P>
   American to win the Nobel Prize in literature.
</P>
<P>
   1931
</P>
<P>
   Irma S. Rombauer privately
</P>
<P>
   publishes ``The Joy of Cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   1932
</P>
<P>
   Aldous Huxley writes ``Brave New World.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Ingalls Wilder writes ``Little House in the Big Woods.''
</P>
<P>
   1933
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court allows publication of James Joyce's
``Ulysses'' in the United States after judging it not pornographic.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, the Nazis begin burning books.
</P>
<P>
   1934
</P>
<P>
   Zora Neale Hurston writes ``Jonah's Gourd Vine.''
</P>
<P>
   James M. Cain writes ``The
</P>
<P>
   Postman Always Rings Twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Tory Peterson's ``A Field Guide to the Birds'' flies off
the shelves.
</P>
<P>
   1935
</P>
<P>
   Allen Lane founds Penguin Paperbacks in England, launching a new
era of handy, inexpensive books.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Writers' Project of Roosevelt's Works Progress
Administration is created to give writers jobs during the
</P>
<P>
   Depression.
</P>
<P>
   1936
</P>
<P>
   First nonfiction paperback is
</P>
<P>
   published: ``A Short History of the World'' by H.G. Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Carnegie's ``How to Win Friends and Influence People''
opens the floodgates for self-help books.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Mitchell's ``Gone With the Wind'' is a publishing
</P>
<P>
   phenomenon, eventually becoming the best-selling novel of all
time worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   1937
</P>
<P>
   Franz Kafka's ``The Trial'' is
</P>
<P>
   reissued in English.
</P>
<P>
   1938
</P>
<P>
   ``Animals of the Bible'' by
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy P. Lathrop wins the first Caldecott Medal for best
picture book for children.
</P>
<P>
   1939
</P>
<P>
   The paperback revolution comes to America as Pocket Books begins
selling copies of Shakespeare's tragedies and other books for 25
cents each.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Chandler introduces detective Philip Marlowe in ``The
Big Sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   1940
</P>
<P>
   Richard Wright
</P>
<P>
   publishes ``Native Son.''
</P>
<P>
   1942
</P>
<P>
   Little Golden Books, the first mass-market children's line, is
launched by Albert
</P>
<P>
   Leventhal and sells 1.5 million copies in five months.
</P>
<P>
   1943
</P>
<P>
   Ayn Rand writes ``The
</P>
<P>
   Fountainhead.''
</P>
<P>
   1946
</P>
<P>
   A generation of postwar parents adopts Dr. Benjamin Spock's
``Baby and Child Care.''
</P>
<P>
   1948
</P>
<P>
   Norman Mailer's ``The Naked and the Dead'' is published.
</P>
<P>
   1949
</P>
<P>
   George Orwell's ``1984'' offers a grim view of the future.
</P>
<P>
   William Faulkner wins the Nobel Prize in
</P>
<P>
   literature.
</P>
<P>
   1952
</P>
<P>
   Anne Frank's ``Diary of a Young Girl'' is published.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Vincent Peale's ``The Power of Positive Thinking''
becomes a best seller.
</P>
<P>
   Woody Allen's first writing sees print _ a joke in Earl Wilson's
newspaper column _ under his real name, Allen Konigsberg.
</P>
<P>
   1953
</P>
<P>
   James Baldwin writes ``Go Tell It on the Mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   Ian Fleming's first James Bond novel, ``Casino Royale,'' is
</P>
<P>
   published to little notice.
</P>
<P>
   1954
</P>
<P>
   William Golding's ``Lord of the Flies'' presents a dark side of
boys in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   1955
</P>
<P>
   Flannery O'Connor introduces a bevy of Southern Gothic types in
``A Good Man Is Hard to Find.''
</P>
<P>
   1956
</P>
<P>
   Grace Metalious exposes
</P>
<P>
   the hypocrisy _ and sexual
</P>
<P>
   escapades _ of a New England town in ``Peyton Place.''
</P>
<P>
   1958
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Nabokov's ``Lolita''
</P>
<P>
   creates a stir.
</P>
<P>
   Vineyard Books publishes the first-ever all-color American art
book, ``The American Treasury of Art Masterpieces.''
</P>
<P>
   1960
</P>
<P>
   Allen Drury's ``Advise and Consent'' edges out Saul
</P>
<P>
   Bellow's ``Henderson the Rain King'' for the Pulitzer Prize.
</P>
<P>
   John Updike introduces Harry ``Rabbit'' Angstrom in ``Rabbit,
Run.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper Lee's ``To Kill a Mockingbird'' is published.
</P>
<P>
   1961
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Heller's ``Catch-22'' adds a new phrase to the language.
</P>
<P>
   1962
</P>
<P>
   Publication of Rachel
</P>
<P>
   Carson's ``Silent Spring''
</P>
<P>
   stimulates the environmental protection movement.
</P>
<P>
   1963
</P>
<P>
   Betty Friedan's ``The Feminine Mystique'' inaugurates the modern
women's rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Solzhenitsyn reveals the horrors of Russian
concentration camps in ``One Day in the Life of Ivan Denisovich.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Carol Oates makes her literary debut with the short story
collection ``By the North Gate.''
</P>
<P>
   1964
</P>
<P>
   Bantam Books publishes the first ``instant book,'' the ``Report
of the Warren Commission on the Assassination of President
Kennedy.''
</P>
<P>
   1966
</P>
<P>
   Truman Capote changes the nature of true-crime novels with ``In
Cold Blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacqueline
</P>
<P>
   Susann starts a trashy trend with ``Valley of the Dolls.''
</P>
<P>
   1969
</P>
<P>
   Philip Roth tells all about sex and guilt in ``Portnoy's
Complaint.''
</P>
<P>
   1970
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bouton's ``Ball Four'' inspires a flood of tell-all memoirs.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Blume touches a chord with adolescents in ``Are You There,
God? It's Me, Margaret.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Carol Oates wins the National Book Award for ``them.''
</P>
<P>
   1973
</P>
<P>
   Eudora Welty wins a Pulitzer Prize for ``The Optimist's
</P>
<P>
   Daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   1974
</P>
<P>
   Stephen King breaks into print with his first novel, ``Carrie.''
</P>
<P>
   1975
</P>
<P>
   Books on Tape is launched with George Plimpton's ``Paper Lion.''
</P>
<P>
   1976
</P>
<P>
   Anne Rice starts a bloodsucking trend with ``Interview With the
Vampire.''
</P>
<P>
   1984
</P>
<P>
   Tom Clancy surfaces with his debut techno-thriller, ``The Hunt
for Red October.''
</P>
<P>
   1986
</P>
<P>
   The first four volumes of ``The Baby-Sitters Club'' launch a
publishing
</P>
<P>
   phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   1991
</P>
<P>
   John Grisham becomes king of the legal thrillers with ``The
Firm.''
</P>
<P>
   Nadine Gordimer becomes the first South African to win the Nobel
Prize in literature.
</P>
<P>
   1993
</P>
<P>
   Toni Morrison becomes the first African-American woman to win
the Nobel Prize in literature.
</P>
<P>
   1995
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com launches a huge online bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   1996
</P>
<P>
   Oprah Winfrey launches her television book club with ``The Deep
End of the Ocean'' by
</P>
<P>
   Jacquelyn Mitchard.
</P>
<P>
   1998
</P>
<P>
   Global shifts in publishing continue when German company
Bertelsmann AG acquires
</P>
<P>
   Random House.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Wolfe's ``A Man in Full'' sets off sparks in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   1999
</P>
<P>
   ``Juneteenth,'' Ralph Ellison's follow-up novel to
</P>
<P>
   ``Invisible Man,'' is
</P>
<P>
   published posthumously.
</P>
<P>
   The literary world
</P>
<P>
   celebrates
</P>
<P>
   the 100th
</P>
<P>
   anniversary
</P>
<P>
   of the births
</P>
<P>
   of Ernest
</P>
<P>
   Hemingway and Vladimir Nabokov.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Don O'Briant for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
