<HEADER>
A5193 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYBERAGE-BOOKS23-COX     05-20 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERAGE-BOOKS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bound pages up to challenges of the cyber age?
 &HT;    EDs: Embaroged For Sunday, May 23.
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1900, even the best science-fiction writers couldn't have
envisioned the incredible changes that would transform the book
world in the next 100 years. Surely few would have predicted
mass-produced paperbacks so inexpensive that anyone could afford
them. Or books on tape. Or books that could be read on hand-held
computers. Or instant books or Internet bookstores or mega-best
sellers by authors who are paid millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   After so many changes in the 20th century, what can we expect in
the 21st? Will books as we know them become as obsolete as
Babylonian clay tablets?
</P>
<P>
   Author Tom Wolfe, a keen observer of social trends, doesn't
think so. From his home in New York, Wolfe says he simply cannot
imagine a world in which readers peruse a best-selling novel on a
computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to scroll the pages,'' Wolfe says. ``People got over
scrolls 2,000 years ago. Or you have to download the pages from a
computer. With a book, you don't need to plug it in, and the pages
are already downloaded. The technology of the book is fabulous.
Just because it doesn't have a wire attached to it doesn't affect
its power. The book will continue to be a paramount medium of the
21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Books will always be important, Wolfe says, because they provide
a view that television and films cannot duplicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Films are very clumsy about notation of status,'' he says. ``A
Gucci loafer can look the same as an ordinary loafer. Unless a
character stops and says, `Look at these Gucci loafers,' the
audience is not going to get it. The movies can only show decadence
in broad strokes.''
</P>
<P>
   Books indeed will be around next century, agrees Larry Ashmead,
a senior editor at HarperCollins in New York, but the kind of books
being published is likely to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serious fiction and literary fiction are going to be more
important than what we now call commercial fiction,'' Ashmead says.
``I think literary fiction is going to become commercial fiction.
People are raising their standards and buying good writing. Some of
the old standbys like the Danielle Steels and Tom Clancys are going
to be considered old-fashioned.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be more movie and television tie-ins to books, he
predicts, and more books sold online. Not only are Internet
companies such as Amazon.com helping sell new books _ 2 percent of
total sales last year, according to a recent study _ but they're
also increasing the sales of older books by suggesting other titles
the buyer might like to try.
</P>
<P>
   Other trends Ashmead foresees are an increase in sales of
serious nonfiction books and electronic books and the growth of
regional publishers. Because of mergers, he says, there may be only
five or six major publishers left in New York in the first part of
the next century. The void may well be filled by smaller, regional
publishers.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Perry, president of Marietta's Longstreet Press and of the
Publishers Association of the South, agrees with Ashmead that small
to midsize publishers will continue to see a higher quality of
material than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is cracking the market that is being dominated by
chain bookstores,'' Perry says.
</P>
<P>
   Perry envisions a day when bookstores will follow the example of
furniture retailers and stock only one or two copies of each book
as samples. Next-day delivery will be made from warehouses in the
suburbs where the rent per square foot is cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advantage to small and midsize publishers is not going to
be so much an increased advantage in retail outlets but an
increased advantage in Internet sales. On the Internet, we can't
get cut out of the game because of a shortage of floor space.''
</P>
<P>
   Another change in the next century likely will be more books on
demand, and more books published in smaller numbers for a niche
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we can't print less than 4,000 or 5,000 books and
price them competitively,'' Perry says. ``But with the new
technology, we can publish 500 copies of a book and charge $35 for
the book because the people who want it are not price-sensitive.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing almost everyone in the industry agrees on is the
challenge facing nonchain bookstores. According to Richard Howorth,
owner of Square Books in Oxford, Miss., and president of the
American Booksellers Association, the number of independent
booksellers has declined 45 percent since 1991. What does that mean
to consumers? Despite some publishers' predictions of more interest
in ``serious'' literary books, Howorth worries that less
independent competition will mean even more celebrity-written books
and blockbusters.
</P>
<P>
   ``As more publishing firms merge or purchase each other, and
more bookselling firms integrate with publishers and wholesalers,
and the book business grows more removed from those who care about
books beyond their function as commodity, the more a healthy
reading society, and democracy, are endangered,'' Howorth says.
</P>
<P>
   To help counteract their dwindling numbers, independent
booksellers are launching a national campaign called Book Sense.
The effort will include an Internet site, BookSense.com, that will
enable customers to buy books at competitive prices from
independent bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   Not all independent booksellers foresee a situation where
everyone buys their books on the Internet as salvation in the next
century. Some insist there will always be browsers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The computer-related book business is going to be there, but
there will always be people who want to be out there with other
book lovers,'' says Barbara Babbitt Kaufman, who owns several
Chapter 11 bookstores. ``Some experts predicted the movie business
would suffer with videos and pay-per-view. Instead, the movie
business is better than ever. Why? Because people want to be with
other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Headline goes right here for 30'' story for books page
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology of the book is fabulous. Just because it
doesn't have a wire attached to it doesn't affect its power. The
book will continue to be a paramount medium of the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Tom Wolfe
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology of the book is fabulous. Just because it
doesn't have a wire attached to it doesn't affect its power. The
book will continue
</P>
<P>
   to be a paramount medium of the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   TOM WOLFE
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
