<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMERCIAL-LAUNCH-PAD-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST COMMERCIAL LAUNCH PAD DEBUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By NORA K. WALLACE   
 Santa Barbara (Calif.) News-Press   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANDENBERG AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. _ In one giant leap for
private enterprise, the nation's first commercially owned and
operated space launch pad has opened here.
</P>
<P>
   The first nonmilitary, non-NASA launching operation will allow
small companies, universities and even the Air Force to book
passage for their payloads with a private outfit.
</P>
<P>
   The pad, which is at Vandenberg Air Force Base, was built by
Lompoc-based Spaceport Systems International and ITT Industries. It
has exhaust ducts resembling a skateboard ramp and a surprisingly
low-tech steel ring comprising the nucleus of the facility.
</P>
<P>
   The launch pad stands as one of several emerging public-private
facilities around the nation, all poised to launch the estimated
2,000 new satellites needing rides into space during the next
decade.
</P>
<P>
   The launch site, which was unveiled Tuesday along Vandenberg's
rugged windswept coastline, was heralded as a milestone for the
nation's emerging commercial space industry.
</P>
<P>
   For two men in particular, Earl Severo and Don Smith, the day
was the culmination of more than seven years of dreams, deals and
disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   As an Air Force officer in the 1980s, Severo was in charge of
Vandenberg's doomed West Coast space shuttle project. Its home at
the massive Space Launch Complex-6 stands abandoned as a
multibillion-dollar remnant within sight of the new SSI pad.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who now champions space education, was once in charge of
the Lompoc-based Western Commercial Space Center, the prime
advocate during the days when Santa Barbara County was trying to
build its reputation as a commercial space hub. In 1995, Smith was
a crucial player during the seven-month negotiation of the 25-year
lease for the 100-acre piece of Air Force property containing the
launch pad.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, both men expected their venture would bring up to
24 launches a year by now. But the project was delayed by various
problems _ with personalities, funding and finding customers.
</P>
<P>
   Severo presided over the ceremony Tuesday. ``It's a great day,''
Severo said, speaking of the venture as a milestone.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who was in the audience, said, ``I'm very, very happy
that it is finished to the point it can sustain a launch.''
</P>
<P>
   Although SSI touts itself as the first commercial launch pad, it
was financed by some funding from the state and federal government.
But the bulk of the estimated $20 million needed to build the
facility came from SSI and ITT, which formed a limited partnership
in the project. SSI is responsible for bringing customers and their
projects to the site at Vandenberg and putting the satellites into
orbit.
</P>
<P>
   ``As government budgets decline, commercial launch facilities
can play a crucial role,'' in providing the government with
``reliable, safe and cost-effective'' launch services, said Marv
Sambur, president of ITT Defense.
</P>
<P>
   Sambur estimated that by about 2003 the site could accommodate
two launches a month.
</P>
<P>
   For SSI, the test of its future viability comes in the September
launch of an Air Force Minotaur rocket.
</P>
<P>
   The Minotaur takes its name from the mythological creature that
has the torso of a man and the head of a bull. In the rocket's
case, it is created from the lower stages of a Minuteman 2
intercontinental ballistic missile and the upper half of a Pegasus
rocket. The Minotaur will carry into orbit two satellites, built by
the U.S. Air Force Academy and Weber State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the greatest confidence in this launch site,'' said Jim
Ford, director of Space and Missile Test and Evaluation, who is in
charge of the Minotaur launch. ``I have no doubt it will be
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The Minotaur is one of several rockets under development
designed to lower the cost of putting a satellite into orbit. Such
advances mean the likelihood of more users, especially now that
there's a commercial launch pad.
</P>
<P>
   The Minotaur is expected to be able to put a satellite into
orbit for about $12 million, considerably less than other types of
rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Paul J. Coleman Jr., president of the Universities Space
Research Association, praised the site Tuesday as the potential
home for numerous university-built satellites. He, like other
customers, will be closely watching the September launch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost of the ride is still the all-important thing,'' said
Coleman, who is based at UCLA's Institute of Geophysics and
Planetary Physics.
</P>
<P>
   (The Santa Barbara (Calif.) News Press, is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
