<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-BOXOFFICE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Phantom Menace' breaks one-day record at box office
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's $28.542 million and counting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'' set a one-day box
office record Wednesday, topping the previous single-day high of
$26.1 million set by ``The Lost World: Jurassic Park'' in 1997.
George Lucas' film could be on track to set a new five-day record.
Some say the film could earn $100 million to $140 million by
weekend's end.
</P>
<P>
   Some 5,000 metro Atlantans saw ``Phantom Menace'' on Wednesday
at Regal Cinemas' new Hollywood 24 megaplex, making it the chain's
No. 6 theater in the nation. (Regal is also the largest theater
chain in the world.) In Cobb County (Ga.), General Cinemas' Parkway
Pointe finished in that theater chain's top eight in the nation in
attendance for opening day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars'' fanatics are already deep in new trivia:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In the movie's big Senate scene, for instance, fans have
spotted a group of Spielberg-like E.T.s in the screen's lower left
corner.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In Massachusetts, General Cinemas' Framingham 14 megaplex near
Boston had multiple prints of ``Phantom Menace,'' but one was
different than what the rest of the nation's moviegoers saw.
Instead of one character getting cut in half by a light saber and
falling, this particular print showed the character falling intact.
The print was screened five times Wednesday before 20th Century Fox
replaced it Thursday morning, said Zvi Cole, General Cinemas'
Northeast marketing manager.
</P>
<P>
   Some fans paid to see the film more than once so they could see
that scene both ways, Cole said.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Internet's www.jedinet
</P>
<P>
   .com, run by John Benson, of Dallas, Ga., was likely the first
Web site in the world to post a new clock on its prequel page
counting down in days, hours, minutes and seconds that there are
now 1,093 days to go _ until ``Episode 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
