<HEADER>
A5196 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TREK-DOCUMENTARY21-CO     05-20 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREK-DOCUMENTARY21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Film's mission: To seek out Trekkies
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   They stand in line for hours, dress up as their favorite
characters and spend fortunes on the collectible tie-in products.
</P>
<P>
   No, we're not talking ``Star Wars'' fanatics, but that alter-
</P>
<P>
   nate-universe fan base known as ``Trekkies.'' That's the name of
Roger Nygard's documentary, which looks at the TV franchise's
ardent followers with a tone that fuses affection and deadpan
satire. Most of the time, Nygard and game narrator-interviewer
Denise Crosby (from ``The Next Generation'') let the fans speak for
themselves, often with unintentionally hilarious results.
</P>
<P>
   Such as fussy, 14-year-old Gabriel Koerner, a Trek convention
veteran, who rolls his eyes at the shoddy needlework of the friend
who stitched his uniform. Or the Florida dentist and his wife whose
practice is completely Trek-themed. Or Barbara Adams, the Arkansas
woman who made headlines as a Whitewater juror who wore her Star
Fleet uniform to court.
</P>
<P>
   These are people who dress up their children in Star Fleet
clothes, as well as their pets. For some, ``Star Trek'' is a true
obsession. For others, you get the sense that it's just a
convenient rack to hang their kinks on. Such as the woman whose
devotion to actor Brent Spiner borders on stalking, as she walks
out onto her deck to stare in the direction of his Los Angeles
home. (She calls these timeouts ``Brent-breaks.'')
</P>
<P>
   A little of this goes a long way. If you're not a Trekkie
yourself (or find the species amusing), you might be like the
several viewers who fled the theater early during a preview
screening. But besides nutty character studies, ``Trekkies''
includes some interesting factoids, revealing interviews with cast
members from the various versions of the show, and a perspective on
the series' role as social commentary, not just science fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Long before ``the Force'' entered our vocabulary, this show
popularized the catch phrase ``Live long and prosper.'' Those words
seem to be the lucky mantra of the ``Star Trek'' franchise, which
just keeps on trekkin'.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trekkies''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   A documentary by Roger Nygard, with Denise Crosby, ``Star Trek''
stars, and lots of people in costume. Rated PG for mild sexual and
drug references. At metro theaters. 1 hour, 28 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: ``Star Trek'' groupies get a tribute and a
roasting, all in the same movie.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
