<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5197 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENTURY-BOOKS2NDTAKE2     05-20 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-BOOKS2NDTAKE23-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: read since college.''
</P>
<P>
   FICTION: FORM, FUNCTION
</P>
<P>
   If it is the names that change, it is also the forms. The
naturalistic novel flourished, then waned, then flourished anew.
The psychological novel, introduced almost single-handedly in
English by Henry James, took new forms _ some of which would seem
mutations that might better have been aborted _ and the novel we
always apologized for reading, the detective mystery, achieved
something of an apogee. The works of Raymond Chandler are
memorialized in the Library of America series, and a handful of
other mystery novelists, notably Dashiell Hammett, are recognized
as genuine writers and not slightly disreputable hacks pounding out
pulp fiction in a seedy hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   Partly because of such writers, the paperback came into its own.
What had once been the dime novel, and later the detective novel,
today is the handsomely packaged choice of readers of every stripe.
Indeed, if the century can be called anything, it's the Century of
the Paperback.
</P>
<P>
   But this is largely a commercial index. A more thoroughgoing
study would reveal not only who writes fiction but who reads it. By
the last quarter of the century, women were writing as many novels
as men, and, whatever the cause and effect, they were also reading
more novels than men.
</P>
<P>
   And a generation after Ellison's ``Invisible Man,'' Americans
lengthened their shelves to admit the works of black writers,
beginning with James Baldwin but eventually including Morrison,
James Alan McPherson and others.
</P>
<P>
   What's significant about this is that black writers are read not
solely by blacks. By the 1990s, to paraphrase Henry Louis Gates,
the literature of black Americans had become a coherent body of
work unto itself and, at the same time, part of the larger, white
tradition. It had achieved both racial identity and integration.
</P>
<P>
   The flowering worked in other ways as well. American readers
became acquainted with literature in translation. From South
America came writers such as Gabriel Garcia Marquez, Jorge Borges
and Mario Vargas Llosa, all standbys in every Barnes &AMP; Noble, every
Borders, any independent bookstore. In the years before and after
the fall of the Soviet Union, they found Czech and Russian, Italian
and German writers as well as American, the requisite British and
the occasional French.
</P>
<P>
   Bookselling is commerce, which means it could not be isolated
from the world even if it wanted to. If some did not realize this
before, they came face to face with it _ and with chasms of
cultural difference _ when Salman Rushdie's ``The Satanic Verses''
became more an event in international politics than in literature.
</P>
<P>
   None of this, even so, begins to define the character of
literature in the century that saw the atom split, the bomb
dropped, the moon reached and the globe (despite those seemingly
unbridgeable differences) downsized to a mere village.
</P>
<P>
   If any question could divide writers in our century into one
camp or another, it would be whether they were engaged with the
great issues of their times, like Solzhenitsyn or Nadine Gordimer,
or whether, like Vladimir Nabokov and James Joyce, they believed
the writer's obligation was first to his imagination and not social
realism. On one side might lay moral responsibility, but not
infrequently a preacherly tedium as well; on the other might lay
artistic freedom, but the self-indulgent freedom, sometimes, of the
dilettante.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, a segregation of one from the other is not possible,
as the stories of Eudora Welty, an apolitical writer, subtly show.
In the end, the books that survived in our century have been ones
that somehow reached above their times, sometimes above their
readers' heads, and secured themselves a firm footing on whatever
Olympus stands amid the rubble of a century no writer (unless it
was Orwell) had predicted but many have mined for human meaning.
</P>
<P>
   And even that can take years, maybe a century, to fix in time.
When the New York Public Library, as part of a centennial
celebration in 1995, invited its 175 professional librarians to
nominate books that had had a ``a significant influence,
consequence or resonance'' during its first 100 years, nominations
poured in. W.E.B. Du Bois' ``The Souls of Black Folk,'' published
three years after the century began, anticipated the racial
dilemmas with which it would end. Rachel Carson's ``Silent Spring''
(1962) sounded the concerns that would give rise to the
environmental movement. Albert Einstein's ``The Meaning of
Relativity'' (1923) revolutionized our understanding of space and
time. James D. Watson's ``The Double Helix'' (1968) revealed
something even more individual than genes and chromosomes in the
microbiology of life. In 1922, T.S. Eliot (``a trim anti-Bohemian
with black bowler and umbrella ... ushering us to our seats in
hell,'' V.S. Pritchett wrote) set the century's moral tone of
dislocation and devastation in his poem ``The Waste Land.''
</P>
<P>
   And what need be said about Hitler's ``Mein Kampf,'' except that
it was available in a special bridal edition?
</P>
<P>
   But not even the Fuhrer could compete with Freud. No book
received more nominations than ``The Interpretation of Dreams,''
evidence that, if nothing else, it's meaning we forever seek, when
we're asleep as much as when we're awake.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube's column appears Sundays on the book page.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
