<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0358 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5198 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENTURY-BOOKS1STTAKE2     05-20 1469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-BOOKS1STTAKE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The first in an occasional series on how the arts have reflected
and defined our times _ and what lies ahead
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 23.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In May of 1895, when the New York Public Library was founded,
horse-drawn carriages ferried people up and down Manhattan island,
no one could have told you who Albert Einstein or James Joyce might
be, and the literate class looked across the Atlantic for
enlightenment. In a nation of immigrants, the New York Public
Library would become both schoolhouse and citadel, symbolic of an
unshakable faith in human progress. But at the time there was
nothing much on this side of the ocean to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Twain was an unrefined humorist, too American (and too
popular) to be really respectable. At the most, there was Henry
James, and he had packed his bags and moved to England.
</P>
<P>
   American literature, a century ago, consisted of a handful of
names, some of them already gathering dust _ Washington Irving,
Ralph Waldo Emerson, Nathaniel Hawthorne, Herman Melville, William
Dean Howells. It was a hand-me-down affair, without tradition or
standing in the larger world.
</P>
<P>
   But the 10 years from 1895 to 1905 would be the seedbed for a
new century, one in which American literature variously reflected
the ascension of everything else American. It was during this
fertile period that Ernest Hemingway, William Faulkner and F. Scott
Fitzgerald, today a holy trinity in the American pantheon, were
born. Thomas Wolfe, forgotten today but larger than any of them for
a few brief years, was born in the same span of time, as was Edmund
Wilson, who not only taught Americans what William Butler Yeats,
Joyce and the Symbolists were up to but also gave them an
appreciation for their home-grown literature.
</P>
<P>
   Labels obscure more than they reveal, and yet pundits have no
hesitation in calling it an American century. Trite as it might be,
it is not entirely inaccurate. By any measure, the overriding
characteristic of the hundred years whose hours are ticking away
has been _ for good or ill _ the centrality of American technology,
American power and American art. In 1895, while patents were
pending for such contraptions as automobiles, telephone systems and
moving pictures, no one would have imagined it.
</P>
<P>
   A FATAL SHOT
</P>
<P>
   But when did the century really begin? On the first day of
January 1900? A year to the day later? The calendar would suggest
one or the other and yet all of us know that neither experience nor
memory conforms to the arbitrary demarcation of months, years and
decades.
</P>
<P>
   A customary, if debatable, answer to the question is that it
began in a place far from American shores, although one becoming
darkly familiar. When the shots rang out in Sarajevo in 1914, one
world died and another was born.
</P>
<P>
   The world that died went out, to reverse T.S. Eliot's famous
words, not with a whimper but with a bang. The bullet that entered
Archduke Franz Ferdinand's throat ricocheted on for 37 days, and in
the 51 months that followed, almost 9 million were killed and 21
million injured. Millions more were left homeless. The Great War
was the upheaval that introduced the 20th century, and was the
first of the great dislocations from which literature in this
country and others has arisen.
</P>
<P>
   Every century has seen faiths shaken and secular institutions
left in shambles. But none, surely, has seen what ours has, from
the collapse of imperial empires to the global spread of technology
and terror. None has, in quite so paradoxical a way, seen the
sanctity of the
</P>
<P>
   individual at once affirmed and denied. The richest profusion of
poetry and prose the West has yet produced cannot claim to fully
record or reflect the depth of the experience.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the literature of the 20th century nonetheless captures the
sharper discontinuities, the more grievous horrors and psychic
migrations that have marked our time and that of our parents and
grandparents. No one would call it romantic. Even in a writer like
Fitzgerald, revelry and exuberance foreshadow decadence. And
whatever heroism the 20th century can claim is darkened by the
realization of suffering on vast scales. Witness the angry defiance
of Solzhenitsyn, the lonely tragedy of Pasternak, each in his own
way standing up to brute force. Hear the elegiac lamentation of
Ralph Ellison, writing of his invisibility in white America.
</P>
<P>
   Topology came easier in centuries past. English literature since
Chaucer's time has been marked by the magisterial Ages, often
overlapping: the Age of Shakespeare, the Age of Donne and Dryden,
the Age of Johnson and Swift, the Age of Dickens. No such bookend
categories are at hand as the 20th century closes. Large as they
have loomed in our own time, it would sound ludicrous to speak to
the Age of Faulkner or the Age of Hemingway.
</P>
<P>
   Not even fiction's mass producers have achieved last-name-only
status. People speak of ``John Grisham,'' not just ``Grisham.'' And
notice how they pronounce ``Stephen King'' as if it were one word,
a case of commercial success producing a kind of unitized
construction. Likewise, even a Nobel Prize has not made
``Morrison'' sufficient without the ``Toni.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the century, the times are more fluid, and change,
the only constant, is not observant of reputation. Anne Bernays,
who has spent 30 years in publishing as both a novelist and an
editor, thinks Katherine Anne Porter's ``Pale Horse, Pale Rider''
is ``just about the best short story in American literature.'' But
how many people under the age of 40 have heard of it? How many have
even heard of its author?
</P>
<P>
   Reputations rise and fall, but more often they drift into the
oblivion of indifference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-five years ago,'' Bernays says, ``Kurt Vonnegut was the
most widely read writer on colleges campuses. Now he's a little
irrelevant. I don't know anyone who reads him. I always thought he
took shortcuts. He was very clever but never got beneath the
surface.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said of any number of novelists who caught the
tempo and spirit of their times _ or at least that corner in which
they lived. During the 1940s and '50s, John O'Hara was an
acknowledged master of the American short story, a sharp and acidic
sketcher of middle-class life and a fixture on the pages of The New
Yorker. Today he is unread if not unremembered.
</P>
<P>
   Fiction itself has seen its stock erode. Although opinions
differ, many would tell you that novels became less important to
ordinary readers when they sacrificed narrative for
experimentation. Justin Kaplan, a Pulitzer Prize-winning biographer
of Mark Twain and Walt Whitman, points to the 1930s as one
watershed and to the late 1960s and '70s as another. If the fiction
of the '30s was a golden age of rendering familiar human experience
in story form, by the '70s novelists seemed to have forgotten
common life altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '60s and '70s,'' Kaplan says, ``you had a degradation _
a deliberate degradation _ of the old forms. And that's when
biography began to take the place of fiction _ not entirely, but
seriously _ as a form of vicarious experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The 19th-century novels of Balzac and Dickens were newsreels as
fiction. Social milieu was inseparable from character and plot. In
the postmodern period of the late 20th century, you can read any
number of novels _ not just American but also, and especially,
French _ without a clue to what a character does for a living, how
he grew up, what goes on in the world around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the society we live in, one built on capitalism,''
Kaplan says, ``you wonder that so little (fiction) has been written
on business. It's a model for human competition. Business and
moneymaking are the preoccupations of American life, and yet they
are not a part of our fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   The view that fiction has lost ground is widely accepted, but
far from universal. Reynolds Price, for one, believes American
fiction is ``healthier than it ever has been.'' He is no fan of
experimentalism _ ``I thought if I saw one more story by Donald
Barthelme, I'd scream'' _ but the productivity and intelligence of
American fiction at the end of the century, he believes, are in
full flower.
</P>
<P>
   It is an assertion always accompanied by a balancing disclaimer.
``I don't think Americans ever read very much, except practical
handbooks on how to fix your Model T or how to groom your dog,''
Price says. ``One of the interesting things about (Charles
Frazier's) `Cold Mountain' _ which I liked very much _ is that you
heard so many women who bought it later saying it was the first
novel their husbands had read since college.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
