<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5199 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-TIANANMEN-BOS &LR;      05-20 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TIANANMEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS TIANANMEN ANNIVERSARY NEARS, SOME DISSIDENTS DETAINED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Two weeks before the 10th anniversary of the massacre
of democracy demonstrators near Tiananmen Square, Chinese
authorities have detained several dissidents and heightened
surveillance of many others.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups have documented the detention of at least
seven dissidents since May 13, though some believe the number may
be considerably higher. Three have been released, according to the
Hong Kong-based Information Center of Human Rights and Democratic
Movements in China, but some are not likely to be freed until after
the anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing _ capitalizing on NATO's errant bombing of the Chinese
embassy in Belgrade _ has condemned Western governments for
preaching human rights while bombing innocent civilians. Drawing on
embarrassment over the mistaken bombing, China may feel embolded to
muzzle dissent without fear of global condemnation.
</P>
<P>
   China has allowed broad economic and social liberties in the
decade since the crackdown _ but does not brook any challenge to
the primacy of the Communist Party. China has never tolerated
commemorations of the massacre of hundreds, or perhaps thousands,
of unarmed democracy protesters on June 4, 1989; relatives of
victims are harassed when visiting gravesites, and arresting
dissidents before the anniversary has become an annual event.
</P>
<P>
   But human rights monitors worry repression may be worse this
year, not only because of the 10-year anniversary, but also because
the Communist Party leaders feel pressured both by disgruntled
groups at home and by perceived holier-than-thou Western powers
lobbying for greater freedoms in China.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, several dissidents interviewed say they are
determined to honor the memories of the dead, even if it means
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   One dissident detained this week, Jiang Qisheng, 50, is a former
graduate student leader who served 1 1/2 years in prison without
trial following his involvement in the 1989 movement at People's
University in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Two days before his latest arrest, in an interview with the
Globe during which he was photographed and followed, Jiang said
that ``anybody should be allowed to tell the truth, but it is not
allowed in this society. ... Ten years ago...I had hoped the
government would hear the voice of the people and do political
reform. I didn't want to bring down the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Jiang said he planned to light candles at his home on June 3 and
4, and would try to walk to Tiananmen Square to hold a silent
vigil.
</P>
<P>
   But late Tuesday night, police arrested Jiang, searched his
Beijing home and seized his computer, fax machine, documents and
articles he had written for Beijing Spring, a New York-based
dissident publication. His wife, Zhang Hong, said Thursday night
that police will not tell her where he is being held.
</P>
<P>
   Others arrested include Li Bagen, a member of the outlawed China
Democracy Party in Hangzhou; Yu Zhenbin, a Beijing intellectual,
and Cao Jiahe, a Beijing magazine editor. Caowas blindfolded, tied
and beaten for four days, according to New York-based Human Rights
in China, after circulating a petition to commemorate the dead. He
had apparently collected the signatures of the former chief editor
and deputy chief editor of the People's Daily.
</P>
<P>
   Activists annually plead for a reassessment of the June 4th
movement. But on Tuesday, Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao
said the government had ``made a correct and historical conclusion
on the political turmoil'' and ``it will never be changed...All
Chinese people support this conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday marked the anniversary of the government's declaration
of martial law in Beijing following weeks of student-led protests
for greater political freedoms and an end to corruption. The
protests drew 1 million people to the streets of Beijing, plus
millions more in other cities, before tanks were ordered to clear
the square.
</P>
<P>
   The roundup of dissenters this week came as China's top
prosecutor, in a national conference call Wednesday, urged
vigilance against ``an extremely small number of people with
ulterior motives trying to use sensitive issues to incite
disturbances and sabotage.''
</P>
<P>
   Han Zhubin warned against ``enemy forces at home and abroad,''
and called for a crackdown on ``all criminal activities that
endanger state security,'' according to the Communist Party
newspaper, the People's Daily.
</P>
<P>
   The harsh rhetoric starkly contrasts an earlier statement by
Premier Zhu Rongji, who recently told Communist Party cadres not to
use ``dictatorial means against the people'' when dealing with
social unrest. Zhu is seen as a pro-US reformer, and analysts say
he may have been sidelined by conservative hawks since the embassy
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The crackdown on dissidents comes after vitriolic protests
against Western embassies and consulates here in which Chinese
authorities demonstrated their control _ both in mobilizing crowds
and in dispersing them after four days.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders may have been pleased to have a whipping boy to channel
societal discontent and divert attention from the sensitive 10-year
anniversary. But authorities also likely feared that the
demonstrations could have evolved into protests against an
incompetent government, as have countless anti-foreigner movements
in Chinese history. Police had warned dissidents to stay away from
the anti-NATO protests, and the decision to halt the protests
seemed partly aimed to prevent frustrated masses _ from political
activists to millions made jobless by economic reforms _ from
having a public forum to air grievances.
</P>
<P>
   But Catherine Baber of Amnesty International argued that ``in
the long term, stability is better achieved by allowing people to
express their grievances rather than repressing them.''
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty has documented 241 cases of June 4th protesters still
imprisoned since 1989, but says they are a fraction of the whole.
The Information Center on Human Rights and Democratic Movements
estimates the total at nearly 2,000.
</P>
<P>
   With people still in jail and the government refusing to reverse
its verdict on the event, Lu said dissidents and relatives will
find ways to stage protests. One option, he said, is hunger strikes
in private homes by one or several individuals. Hunger strikes are
a powerful symbol in Chinese culture, and private commemorations
are naturally harder for police to prevent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reassessing the Tiananmen massacre is still viewed as a threat
to stability,'' Lu acknowledged, ``but I think some in the
government realize that they eventually have to do it if they want
the issue to go away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
