<HEADER>
A5200 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-NOTES20-COX     05-20 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Author's a far cry from red ink of school days
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Beginning writers quickly become familiar with
rejections, but few start collecting them as early as Janet Fitch
did. The Los Angeles writer was 8 when she got her first. Actually,
it was for a school paper, but the effect was just as hurtful.
</P>
<P>
   Fitch had written what she considered a beautiful long story,
complete with illustrations, and proudly presented it to her
elementary school teacher. Instead of commenting on the story, the
teacher corrected her grammar and spelling with red ink.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't write again for 10 years,'' Fitch told one
interviewer.
</P>
<P>
   When she did start again, there was no red ink. ``White
Oleander'' (Little Brown, $24), Fitch's debut novel, was accepted
by the first editor to whom she sent it. Before it even hit the
stores, the novel was selected for Oprah Winfrey's book club and
snapped up by Warner Bros. and John Wells Productions for a feature
film. The publisher increased the printing from 20,000 to 700,000.
</P>
<P>
   Now No. 2 on Amazon.com's best-seller list, the novel tells the
story of Astrid, a teenage girl whose beautiful and brilliant
mother is sent to jail for murdering her ex-lover. Astrid is left
to be raised in a series of foster homes until the day she is asked
to give false testimony at a trial that could set her mother free.
</P>
<P>
   Fitch, who was never in foster care herself, drew on the
experiences of childhood friends to write ``White Oleander.'' She
got the idea for the book after reading ``The Pillow Book of Sei
Shonagon,'' a diary by a lady-in-waiting to a Heian empress in
11th-century Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I find remarkable about the Heian court is the noticeable
absence of anything we could call conventional morality or
ethics,'' Fitch said.
</P>
<P>
   Beheadings did not bother Shonagon, for example, but seeing
someone wearing the wrong combination of colored robes would upset
her for days.
</P>
<P>
   Fitch wanted ``to see what would happen if someone with that
extreme aesthetic of the Heian court were forced to live in the
brutal climate of late 20th-century Los Angeles, with a crummy job,
having to do the laundry and whatever,'' Fitch said. ``And so I
wrote the first little short story about this monster, Ingrid
Magnussen, who then got a daughter and became a bigger short story,
which became a novel.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  NEW POET LAUREATE: Andrew Motion, a 47-year-old London
professor of creative writing, was chosen Wednesday to become
Britain's poet laureate, succeeding Ted Hughes. His selection put
to rest rumors that Prime Minister Tony Blair might bypass known
writers in favor of a ``people's poet.'' Sir Paul McCartney was one
name mentioned in that context. Hughes held the post for 14 years
until his death in October.
</P>
<P>
   The job has in the past been a lifetime appointment underwritten
by a case of sherry and 100 pounds ($162) a year, but in a
departure from custom, Wednesday's statement from 10 Downing St.
said that Motion's appointment would be for 10 years and that there
would be an annual payment of 5,000 pounds ($8,100).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  RICHEST PRIZE: British author Andrew Miller is the winner of
the $150,000 International IMPAC Dublin Literary Award for his
novel ``Ingenious Pain.'' The international panel of judges chose
the novel over eight nominees that included Don DeLillo
(``Underworld''), Booker Prize winner Ian McEwan (``Enduring
Love''), Bernhard Schlink(``The Reader'') and Cynthia Ozick (``The
Puttermesser Papers''). Published in the United States in 1997,
``Ingenious Pain'' tells of the rise, fall and redemption of James
Dyer, an extraordinary man who cannot feel pain. Dyer becomes a
brilliant surgeon who travels across Europe to Russia, where he
meets a mysterious woman who becomes his savior. Miller, whose
second novel, ``Casanova in Love,'' was published last year, will
receive the literary award _ the richest in the world _ at a June
12 ceremony in Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  BETWEEN THE PAGES: Authors Kaye Gibbons, Anne Lamott and Bret
Easton Ellis are interviewed in the May/June issue of the fledgling
Book ($4.95) magazine. The six-times-a-year publication also
features reviews and the last short story that Andre Dubus wrote
before he died. In the cover story interview, Gibbons, whose novel
``On the Occasion of My Last Afternoon'' has just been published in
paperback, talks about her next project, a memoir/biography of her
mother, who committed suicide when Gibbons was 10. ``I want to find
out who my mother was as a woman,'' says Gibbons, who lives in
North Carolina. ``I have very few memories of her. I want to find
out how she operated as a woman, find out what she liked, what
jokes she thought were funny.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  WINNERS: British writer P.D. James was given the prestigious
Grand Master award, and Robert Clark's whodunit ``Mr. White's
Confession'' was named the year's best mystery at the annual Edgar
Allan Poe Awards ceremonies recently in New York. Steve Hamilton's
``A Cold Day in Paradise'' won best first mystery novel, and
Alabama writer Tom Franklin's debut collection of stories,
``Poachers,'' won for best short fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Don O''Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
