<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5206 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-INDY-CHEEVER21-CO     05-20 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-CHEEVER21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cheever confident Infiniti engine can bring Indy victory
 &HT;    By Dave Lance
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ All season the skeptics had been asking defending
Indianapolis 500 winner Eddie Cheever Jr. why he changed from an
Oldsmobile Aurora engine to an Infiniti.
</P>
<P>
   The questions were even more legitimate when his new motor blew
Wednesday during practice at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway. But
Cheever isn't overly concerned, though it was with an Olds Aurora
that he beat Buddy Lazier by three seconds at Indy last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this engine, we're way ahead of where we were last
year,'' Cheever said. ``But I'm reluctant to say we're where we
need to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'd say we made a lot of progress. The only problem is we
haven't had enough endurance runs with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheever isn't the first Indy Racing League driver to use
Infiniti, but he is the most renowned. Though no driver had used an
Infiniti engine at Indy before 1997 and no one has won the race
with it, Cheever announced in April that he was switching.
</P>
<P>
   He believes it gives him a ``competitive edge,'' but that's
still to be determined. Cheever's speed with the new engine has
been similar to that with the Olds; during the Indianapolis Motor
Speedway test session April 12, Cheever posted the fifth fastest
lap of 23 participants (223.292 mph).
</P>
<P>
   Though the Aurora is the engine of choice at Indy (75 of the 84
entries use it), Infiniti appears to be closing the gap. Its 720
horsepower is comparable to Aurora's, and engineers have reduced
the Infiniti's weight by 55 pounds to 340 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our chances for victory are vastly superior to what they were
this time last year,'' Cheever said. ``We have a much stronger
relationship with our supporting manufacturers and, in my opinion,
that can make a big difference in performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a much deeper database now and a better relationship
with Goodyear and Infiniti. We didn't have that last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Cheever became the first owner/driver to win Indy
since A.J. Foyt (1977), though it wasn't a smooth ride. Team
Cheever had hired chief mechanic Owen Snyder III just months before
the race and it took time for the two to mesh. Also, Cheever feared
sponsorship might dry up if he didn't have a strong showing,
considering all his tough luck in IRL races.
</P>
<P>
   The low point came when Cheever ran out of engines and had to
borrow one from A.J. Foyt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked if I blew the engine, would I pay for it,'' Cheever
said. ``I said I would.''
</P>
<P>
   He never had to. It was a good race all around for Team Cheever
as teammate Robby Unser finished fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Unser has moved on to Team Pelfrey of Huber Heights and has been
replaced by Belgian Wim Eyckmans, who has spent the past week
conferring with Cheever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running on ovals is very different from what I am used to
driving in Europe,'' Eyckmans said. ``You must be so much smoother
and it is a completely different style of driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am getting the hang of it, and it's a big help having Eddie
there, who understands the European way of doing things.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheever _ born in Phoenix, but raised in Rome _ drove Formula
One from 1978-89 and has driven more Grand Prix races (132) than
any other U.S. driver.
</P>
<P>
   He said winning the Indianapolis 500 gave him a bigger rush than
any of those Grand Prix events. He hopes to recapture that feeling
on May 30.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
