<HEADER>
A5207 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRILL-SAFETY21-COX     05-20 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRILL-SAFETY21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fire up that grill, but don't skip safety
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Last week we talked about getting your grill
ready for cooking. This week we'll talk about using your grill
safely.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the information in today's column comes from the
Barbecue Industry Association, a trade group representing grill
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Check the association's Internet site at bbqind.org for other
safety tips or look in the ``What's Hot'' section for recipes and
cooking suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to safety, some things are basic. You're dealing
with flammable gases, lighter fuels, hot surfaces and toxic fumes,
and you're handling food outdoors, where you're adding potential
contaminants you don't have to deal with in your kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   So read the owner's manual for your grill and use a little
common sense.
</P>
<P>
   General tips
</P>
<P>
   _ Grills produce carbon monoxide that can accumulate and kill
you and your family. Never barbecue in your trailer, tent, house,
garage or any enclosed area.
</P>
<P>
   _ Set up the grill in an open area away from anything flammable,
such as dry leaves or brush. Be aware of the windblown sparks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Place the grill on a level surface. Be sure the legs are all
sound and the feet or wheels are all firmly on the ground. Don't
put the grill in a high-traffic area where it's likely to be
bumped, or where people may brush against the hot grill body.
</P>
<P>
   _ If your grill has electrical accessories such as rotisseries,
be sure they are plugged into properly grounded receptacles. Keep
electrical cords away from walkways.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use long-handled barbecue utensils to avoid burns and
splatters.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wear clothing that does not have hanging shirttails, frills or
apron strings. If you need to adjust hot vents, wear
flame-retardant mitts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use baking soda to control a grease fire and have a fire
extinguisher handy. A bucket of sand or a garden hose should be
near if you don't have a commercial extinguisher.
</P>
<P>
   _ Never leave a grill unattended after it is lit, and never
attempt to move a hot grill.
</P>
<P>
   Gas grills
</P>
<P>
   _ If a burner doesn't ignite, turn off the gas. Keep the grill's
lid open and wait five minutes before trying to light it again. If
the burners go out during operation, turn all gas valves to off.
Open the lid and wait five minutes before attempting to relight,
using the lighting instructions.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you get flare-ups on a gas grill, lower the temperature and
raise the grid holding the food.
</P>
<P>
   _ There are limits on how much propane can be put into a
liquid-propane cylinder. Don't overfill the cylinder or ask a
propane supplier to do so. The air space in the propane cylinder is
needed to allow the liquid propane to enter its gaseous state.
</P>
<P>
   _ When the cylinder is connected, the grill must be kept outside
in a well-ventilated space. When not in use, the cylinder valve
must be turned to the ``off'' position.
</P>
<P>
   _ If storing the gas grill indoors, the propane cylinder must be
disconnected, removed and stored outdoors. Never store a
liquid-propane cylinder indoors.
</P>
<P>
   _ Always store propane cylinders upright and in areas where
temperatures won't exceed 125 degrees Fahrenheit. Never store a
spare cylinder on or near a grill.
</P>
<P>
   Charcoal grills
</P>
<P>
   _ To put out flare-ups, raise the grid the food is on and spread
the coals out. If you must douse the flames with a light spritz of
water, first remove the food from the grill.
</P>
<P>
   _ When using charcoal briquets or wood chunks, form a pyramid
and douse the briquets or chunks with lighter fluid. Wait until the
fluid has soaked in before lighting. Before lighting, cap the
lighter fluid and move it a safe distance from the grill.
</P>
<P>
   _ Never add lighter fluid to existing hot or warm coals. Never
use gasoline, kerosene or any other highly volatile fluid as a
starter. They can explode.
</P>
<P>
   _ As an alternative to lighter fluid, use an electric, solid or
other starter specifically made for lighting charcoal briquets or
wood chunks. After unplugging an electric starter, remove it
cautiously and be careful where you put it. Always cool the starter
completely before storing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Never use an electric starter in the rain or when standing on
wet ground.
</P>
<P>
   _ When using instant-light briquets, do not use lighter fluid or
electric, solid or other starters. Do not add more instant-light
briquets once the fire has been lit; add regular charcoal briquets
if more are needed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Allow coals to burn out completely and let the ashes cool for
48 hours before disposing of them. Dispose of cold ashes by
wrapping them in heavy-duty aluminum foil and putting them in a
noncombustible container.
</P>
<P>
   Food handling
</P>
<P>
   _ When shopping for meat, fish and poultry, put them in your
grocery cart last. Never buy a package that's damaged or torn and
check ``sell-by'' and ``use-by'' dates. Put packaged raw meat in
plastic bags so that leaking juices cannot cross-contaminate other
food.
</P>
<P>
   _ Load grocery bags with meat and other refrigerated foods in
the air-conditioned section of the car, not in the trunk.
Refrigerate meats as soon as possible. Keep them chilled until
you're ready to grill them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Thaw frozen food in the refrigerator or by immersing it in
cold water _ never on the counter. Allow sufficient defrosting
time. If you're in a hurry, thaw meat in the microwave just before
grilling it. Also, marinate meats in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wash your hands in hot, soapy water before preparing food,
after each time you touch raw meat and after any interruptions,
such as using the bathroom or handling pets.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep raw meat, poultry and fish and their juices away from
other food. That means thoroughly washing cutting boards, knives,
platters, etc., before letting them come in contact with other
foods you're preparing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't use the plate or container you use to carry meat to the
grill to carry cooked meat away. Cooking kills bacteria that could
be reintroduced from a plate contaminated by meat juices.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sanitize cutting boards and countertops with chlorine bleach.
Pour on a small amount and let it stand several minutes, then rinse
thoroughly and air-dry or dry with clean paper towels. Soak sponges
and dishcloths in hot, soapy water to which you've added chlorine
bleach.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
