<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETITE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Model offers clothing tips for petites
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ ``The biggest mistake a woman makes is that she
tries to wear the same style that she wore when she felt the
thinnest or youngest,'' says Tori Hartman. ``Often our fashion
sense ends in our late 20s and early 30s.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartman, petite model and author, will share fashion advice at a
series of free petite fashion events for Elder-Beerman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name of the game,'' Hartman says, ``is not to look taller
or thinner, it's about looking terrific no matter what your size.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartman, who began her fashion career as a petite model for Liz
Claiborne, is the author of ``Fabulous You! Unlock Your Perfect
Personal Style.'' She has appeared on ``All My Children,'' written
for ``Another World,'' is editor of Petite Week News and serves as
a TV commentator on fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Hartman says times have changed for petite women. When she was
growing up (she's 5-foot-3) she spent many frustrating and
disappointing hours shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``It meant finding styles in magazines that I loved, only to
discover they didn't make that in my size,'' she recalls. ``I spent
most of my early years as an outsider, hoping there would be
something in the junior department that would work on me.''
</P>
<P>
   That was fine for a teen-ager, but what about an adult?
</P>
<P>
   Hartman is happy to say things are different now. In addition to
petite shops, more vendors are including petite lines and
department stores are boasting bigger and better petite
departments. Manufacturers are finally addressing the mature petite
figure as well.
</P>
<P>
   At Elder-Beerman stores this week, Hartman says she'll cover
trends, teach customers how to update their wardrobes and give tips
on what to pull out of the closet to wear again.
</P>
<P>
   ``A petite can wear capri pants, but it's all about body
proportion,'' she explains. ``The silhouette is really suited for
the more evenly proportioned petite woman or long-waisted or
long-legged women. Shorter-waisted women can try it on but should
make sure they find an overblouse that works with it!''
</P>
<P>
   ``The big news is white, so I'll be showing that, too,'' she
says. ``And after a fashion show, I always work on the floor with
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Her best advice? ``Try it on! Don't rely on your eye to tell you
if it won't fit or work on you.''
</P>
<P>
   Tori Hartman's fashion tips for petites
</P>
<P>
   _ Maintain as much of a solid color line up and down as
possible. If you're wearing a black skirt, for instance, wear black
hose and shoes.
</P>
<P>
   _ A long jacket and long skirt used to be a no-no, but if the
garments are petites they can be worn together. If the look
overpowers you, pair a long skirt with a twin set instead.
</P>
<P>
   _ Floral prints are fine, just try to stay to one color to
accessorize. A good measure of the correct size in a floral print
for a petite is hand size. If it's bigger than your hand, the print
will probably overpower you.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you're mixing two prints, make certain one is smaller than
the other. If you put the larger print on top it will draw the
attention up.
</P>
<P>
   _ The detailing this season is wonderful for petites, and
wearing a pin on your lapel or a scarf around your neck draws
attention to your face.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't beat yourself up for those extra inches on your hips.
Proportion wise, it's perfectly normal for petites to be three to
five inches bigger in the hip than the average missy size. So have
that Twinkie and wear your shoulder pads!
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
