<SLUG> BC-BORDER-PATROL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT SAYS BORDER PATROL DRIVING ALIENS TO REMOTE SPOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ The U.S. Border Patrol has put so much pressure
on the border that illegal immigration has shifted from traditional
hot spots to the more remote areas of the U.S.-Mexico boundary,
where more people are dying, according to a report released
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But it is unclear if billions of dollars and thousands of new
agents have dented the number of people illegally entering the
country, the General Accounting Office said in the report.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO, which is the investigative arm of the Congress, also
found that an unintended result of a new patrol strategy is that
more illegal immigrants are dying in remote areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it does not appear there has been an increase in the
overall number of migrant deaths, some evidence exists that deaths
resulting from attempted crossings in remote areas are
increasing,'' the study's summary says without elaboration.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Stana, associate director of GAO, said, ``There is
evidence the flows are shifting. What we are not seeing is people
being discouraged from even trying.''
</P>
<P>
   The Southwest Border Strategy, which was announced in 1994,
started by using unprecedented numbers of agents, fences and buried
sensors to reduce illegal crossings near El Paso and San Diego,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The aim was to push crossers into more remote areas, and as
officials expected, it led to an increase in the number of people
caught in more open stretches of South Texas and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Chulick, a spokeswoman for the Border Patrol headquarters
in Washington, declined to comment on the GAO's findings until she
could review the report.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, more than 1.5 million illegal immigrants were
apprehended trying to sneak north over the U.S.-Mexico border,
according to the Border Patrol. That compares to 1.4 million in
1997 and 1.5 million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration-rights groups criticized the patrol, saying the
agency has long known pushing people into remote and dangerous
areas would lead to more deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is what we have been maintaining for five years. It is
causing an increase in the number of fatalities,'' said Nathan
Selzer, a spokesman for Proyecto Libertad, a Harlingen, Texas-based
immigration-rights group.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Webb County became the deadliest place on the
border for illegal immigrants. Laredo is the seat of Webb County.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 people died of dehydration while trying to sneak
past agents.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO re-urged a 1997 recommendation that the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, which oversees the Border Patrol, to do a
better job figuring out what works and what does not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just do not know,'' Stana said by phone from Washington.
``You can talk about people you arrest, but you do not know how
many you are not arresting.''
</P>
<P>
   Rey Garza, an assistant chief with the patrol's McAllen Sector,
which includes most of deep South Texas, said it is getting more
difficult to sneak into the country as the agency closes off
additional areas.
</P>
<P>
   Operation Rio Grande, which started near Brownsville, stationed
more agents, boats, and high-powered flood lights along the river
to force would-be immigrants to cross farther up stream, near
Laredo or Del Rio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want them (immigrants) to take the message back: it is
difficult to cross here, and we have the manpower and resources to
do the job,'' Garza said.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO also found that smugglers are charging more money to
sneak people into the United States, and more illegal immigrants
are being caught at the border with fake immigration papers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 2004EDT &QL; 
