A5210 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-20 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: AWAITING EHUD BARAK  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By A.M. ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a day in Israel in June 1992 I talked separately with the
four men I considered most important to their country. I asked them
all the same question, most important to its people and future.
</P>
<P>
   What was their thinking about the statement of President George
Bush that for Israel security was not in land or geography but in
peace with the Palestinians? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They were Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and Defense Minister
Moshe Arens, both of Likud; Yitzhak Rabin of Labor, who soon would
defeat Likud in a national election; and the chief of staff of
Israel's armed forces, respected nationally as a particularly brave
commander. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To my surprise, the men from the acridly contesting parties and
the non-political chief of staff all agreed with each other _ none
with Bush. They said Palestinians would never rest with a slice of
Israel but were targeted at defeating it altogether. They said a
Palestinian state would fight a war of terrorism from their
sanctuary, constantly reinforced by Arab allies.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Ehud Barak, the chief of staff, said day by day the Israeli
military had watched U.S. strategy in the Gulf War. He said smart
weapons were not as important to the victory over Iraq as smart
strategy. He said the United States had taken advantage of great
reaches of space and the wealth of maneuver time to pummel the
Iraqis where and when it would do most military damage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Israel had so little space and time, said Barak,
made what it did have critical to its survival. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next day I talked with Avraham Burg, of Labor's powerful
left wing. I said he sure did sound softer than Rabin about peace
and security. Rabin, said he, would be the ``propellent'' for
Labor's rocket. Then it would be dropped and the rocket would zoom
off on its own way. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, after Israeli withdrawal obligations had been
negotiated at Oslo by the Rabin government, Barak was one of the
Israeli generals furious that the military had not been consulted.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now that he is prime minister-elect, various commentators and
the Clinton administration drip with ecstasy. That's preferable to
the poisoned daggers they kept sending Benjamin Netanyahu. But
these folk are waylaying Barak. The message is ``rush to peace, or
failure will be called your fault.'' The truth is he won't be able
to do anything unless his minority party constructs a coalition
that allows him to rule, and not be Burgered. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu killed himself politically by his talent of turning
members of his Cabinet into devoted enemies. But one day, I think,
Barak will say what so many Israelis, including ex-friends of
Netanyahu, admit privately: By the political guts he showed, the
former prime minister has helped the just-elected one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He infuriated hard-line Likudniks by accepting Oslo's untested
premise of land for peace. He returned Hebron, bitterly contested
by religious Jews and Muslims. He told Yasser Arafat that from then
on Palestinians would have to show progress on dismantling their
terrorist structure, not just putting it in the cooler during
negotiations.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton folk were terribly upset by how stubborn he was about
Israel's security _ terribly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barak was elected not just by Netanyahu's faults, but by his own
reputation for honesty and strength. Now he will face the same
problems as his predecessor _ like Palestinian expectations raised
by Arafat, the nasty Clintonian tilt against Israel, and the
anti-Israeli campaign by the European Union. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How much more mobilization time and space can Israel surrender
without risk to its safety? What concessions to make on Jerusalem?
Answer from both men: Virtually none. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How to keep other Arab states from sending arms, terrorists and
disguised soldiers to swell the illegally large Palestinian
``police'' army? How to limit civilian Arab immigration into
Palestine when Israel's doors are open to any Jew? Concrete answer
to both question: Who knows?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My wife sometimes tells me not to seem so politically gloomy.
All right, get ready for joy: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I am not at all gloomy about Israel. One good man has replaced
another, in a way terrifying to every Arab ruler. It's called
election, and for friends of Israel it is powerful anti-gloom, for
all Israel's years ahead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
