<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5211 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CLEOPATRA-REVIEW-S     05-20 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CLEOPATRA-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FALL OF EGYPT: SCANTILY CLAD CLEOPATRA CAN'T SAVE MINISERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's Egypt, it's hot and clingy, and air conditioning won't be
invented for another 2,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to ``Cleopatra,'' an ABC miniseries that consumed 1,000
Moroccan extras, 600 horses, a ton of copper, 300 wigs and enough
cotton and silk to stretch 1.8 miles.
</P>
<P>
   But it isn't the horses, the copper, the wigs or the Moroccan
extras you'll notice. And certainly not the cotton and silk.
</P>
<P>
   No, it's Cleopatra (Leonor Varela) unplugged and undressed.
</P>
<P>
   The great Julius Caesar (Timothy Dalton) is introduced to her
when she unrolls from a gift rug and gives him that unmistakable
look. It's the look that says: Let us now render unto Caesar what
is his.
</P>
<P>
   One scene later, she's writhing her way up a bed and cooing to
him, ``I am Egypt. Indeed it is yours, for one night only.''
</P>
<P>
   And man, this Caesar is salad.
</P>
<P>
   It seems churlish to point out that Varela, a Chilean import, is
one of television's all-time bad actresses.
</P>
<P>
   She says, ``I am queen of Egypt'' four or five hundred times in
the miniseries, which airs Sunday and Monday, and still she reduces
the Egyptian temptress to absolute ordinariness.
</P>
<P>
   Other than her figure, that is. She's forever getting out of
baths. Or into and out of her see-through, papyrus-thin duds.
</P>
<P>
   As Cleopatra, Varela is moody and vainglorious in a ``Don't Cry
for Me, Alexandria'' sort of way.
</P>
<P>
   She believes that everybody loves her. She flies into irksome
rages. She listens to no one. Worst of all, she squeaks so much
about helping ``my people'' that you'd think Cleopatra was a
liberal Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   It has to say something about Varela's abilities that I
realized, late on, that ``Cleopatra'' was dullest when Cleopatra
was on screen.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton's Caesar puts up with all this in bemused fashion, as if
he's not so secretly finding the whole florid production to be
hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   He takes the sultry queen in his arms, looks toward the camera
and declares, as lovers will, ``I will not leave crumbling stones
behind, but a new world order that will change the present and
shape the lives of history to come.''
</P>
<P>
   The lives of history to come?
</P>
<P>
   Well, anyway, Caesar's enemies slice him up soon enough, leaving
Cleopatra to start all over again with Caesar's good buddy Marc
Antony (Billy Zane).
</P>
<P>
   There's also the matter of Caesarian, Cleopatra's son by Julius
Caesar. Between Julius and Marc, the miniseries pauses briefly for
a Caesarian section.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cleopatra'' is a big-budget Halmi production _ the Robert
Halmis senior and junior _ and shows plenty of flashy spectacle
along with its panoramic views of Varela's bare back.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't add up to excitement. Zane's Marc Antony teams
with Cleopatra to make war against mighty Rome and its new dictator
Octavius (Rupert Graves, in the show's best performance).
</P>
<P>
   He's defeated at sea in about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Marc Antony grovels, gets drunk, decides he still
loves Cleopatra, rallies and marches off to fight Rome anew, on
land.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he's routed in about five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cleopatra does her Xena bit in there somewhere, sword-fighting a
couple of legionnaires, before she finally gets her asp in gear.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
