<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-GUNS (Washington) _ Vice President Al Gore casts the
tie-breaking vote to approve a Democratic-backed gun-control
measure. President Clinton and the Democrats hail the vote that
came just a few hours after a gun-wielding student opened fire at a
high school near Atlanta, wounding six schoolmates. By BENNETT ROTH
and CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-INTERNET-FILTERING (Washington) _ If two senators have
their way, teen-agers will no longer be able to tap easily into Web
sites that feature nudity and graphic sex. Sens. John McCain,
R-Ariz., and Fritz Hollings, D-S.C., are pushing legislation that
would require schools and libraries to place Internet filters on
their computers to block children's access to such sites. By
JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-KOSOVO (Washington) _ With the NATO alliance divided
over the use of ground forces, President Clinton insists that the
air campaign is working and that only Yugoslavia's full compliance
with NATO demands can end the Balkan conflict. By NANCY MATHIS.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NUKES-INDIA-PAKISTAN (Washington) _ One year after the
tit-for-tat atomic weapons testing in south Asia, the ambassadors
to the United States from India and Pakistan say that tension
between the rival countries has diminished along with the threat of
nuclear war. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LITTLETON (Littleton, Colo.) _ As another school
shooting erupts in Georgia, President Clinton heads for a visit to
the Colorado town struck by deadly violence a month ago. By GREG
McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-LEGISLATURE (Austin, Texas) _ With nearly all of Gov.
George W. Bush's agenda pending as the clock winds down on the
Texas legislative session, the governor pays his first visit to the
state Senate in months. He denies that his steps toward a
presidential bid have hurt his leadership in the state. By KATHY
WALT. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-PATROL (Laredo, Texas) _ The U.S. Border Patrol has put
so much pressure on the border that illegal immigration has shifted
from traditional hot spots to the more remote areas of the
U.S.-Mexico boundary, where more people are dying, according to a
government report.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Los Angeles) _ Mike Hampton goes for his sixth
consecutive victory as the Houston Astros wrap up a three-game
series against the Los Angeles Dodgers. By CARLTON THOMPSON. (Game
time is 7:10 p.m. Pacific.)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-OFFENSE (Los Angeles) _ Despite the absence of their regular
left-fielder and shortstop for much of the season, the Houston
Astros' offense continues to rank among the league leaders in
almost every statistical category. Jeff Bagwell's hot start is one
big reason, but it also stems from solid production up and down the
batting order. By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-COLONIAL (Fort Worth, Texas) _ Complete coverage of the
first round of the Colonial Invitational PGA Tournament. By EDDIE
SEFKO.
</P>
