<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5218 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      05-20 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES ALLIES TO STAY THE COURSE ON KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH AND KEVIN CULLEN AND  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Faced with increasing calls for a halt in
NATO's air campaign following the accidental bombing of a Belgrade
hospital, President Clinton appealed to his European counterparts
Thursday to remain tough, vowing to carry on the conflict until
Yugoslavia meets all NATO demands.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments came as Belgrade suffered the heaviest NATO
bombardment in two weeks, on the same day thousands turned out for
the commemoration of Saints' Day to pray for peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue our military campaign until the conditions
are met,'' Clinton said in apparent attempt to stiffen resolve
after the latest mistaken bombing, which killed four people in the
hospital and hit a number of European diplomatic buildings.
``President Milosevic should know that he cannot change the
fundamental terms that we have outlined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to stay focused and patient,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The President's remark follow an announcement by Italian Prime
Minister Massimo D'Alema Thursday that NATO should suspend its air
war once Belgrade agrees to a UN-sponsored peace settlement. And it
comes as Greek Foreign Minister George Papandreou, who favors a
48-hour cease-fire, announced plans to travel to Moscow, Beijing
and Washington to press for a diplomatic end to the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pause in the bombing can occur the moment when we have an
agreement for a draft resolution that can be adopted as a
resolution of the UN Security Council,'' D'Alema said during a
visit to NATO headquarters Thursday. If Belgrade reneges on the
deal, he added, ``military action should then restart.''
</P>
<P>
   The push for a cease fire reflected growing concern among
European leaders that NATO's frequently errant missiles could
weaken public support for the war, which is entering its third
month. In the latest mishap, NATO missiles swerved out of control
in a suburb of Belgrade, striking a hospital, slightly damaging the
Spanish and Swedish ambassadors' residences, and raising calls from
some NATO members to exhibit greater caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be great care to avoid tragic errors that would
increase the sense of uneasiness and incomprehension among the
public,'' D'Alema said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO began bombing Belgrade earlier than usual Thursday night,
just at dusk. At least two bombs struck the New Belgrade section of
the city, where NATO had been targeting fuel tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's Beta news agency said the attack blew out windows
at the nearby residence of the Swiss ambassador, who was hosting a
reception. Guests included the Swedish ambassador, whose own
residence was damaged in the earlier attack. No casualties were
reported at the Swiss residence.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Montenegro's pro-Western president, Milo Djukanovic,
accused Belgrade of plotting a coup following the Yugoslav army's
seizure of the republic's main border crossing into Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The regime in Belgrade wants to install the Yugoslav army as a
dictatorship power in Montenegro,'' Djukanovic told the local
Montena-fax news agency.
</P>
<P>
   In a dacha outside Moscow, representatives from the United
States, Russia and the European Union met to assess the latest
diplomatic developments.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's acting foreign minister, Igor Ivanov, said
representatives from the Group of 8, which includes Russia and the
seven leading industrial countries, have agreed to a basic peace
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged that a draft resolution containing the shape
of a post-war Balkan peace ``contains a number of contentious
points.'' Diplomats from those countries are expected to try to
narrow the gaps in Bonn Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think we have quite some distance to cover in bridging
the gaps in the G8, primarily between NATO and Russia,'' said
former Swedish prime minister Carl Bildt, who is acting as UN
Secretary General Kofi Annan's personal envoy. ``That must be
healed and this is not yet done.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the diplomatic stalemate is a dispute over the
composition of an international force to oversee the return of more
than 800,000 ethnic Albanian refugees driven out of Kosovo by Serb
authorities. Clinton said Thursday that NATO forces must be at the
``core'' of any such force. Russia and Belgrade want the United
Nations to be at the heart of any peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary General Javier Solana said the diplomats are far
from getting a formal peace settlement approved by the UN Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
   Annan pledged Thursday to bring the refugees home during a tour
of Kukes, the largest refugee camp in Albanian.
</P>
<P>
   Martti Athisaari, the Finnish president who is emerging as a key
mediator, expressed frustration at the wave of diplomatic
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we don't need now is more proposals,'' he said
before traveling to Moscow to meet with former Russian Prime
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin and US Deputy Secretary of State
Strobe Talbott. ``What we are doing now is measuring how ready the
Yugoslav leadership is for a peaceful solution.''
</P>
<P>
   US Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright assured Congress
Thursday that Milosevic will have to agree to withdraw ``all'' of
the 40,000 soldiers, police and paramilitary forces from Kosovo
before the NATO air war will end. But she left open the possibility
of a bombing pause if an undertermined ``amount'' of forces leave
the area.
</P>
<P>
   She also warned that Washington is committed to driving
Milosevic from power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal here is to try to get as strong an isolation of the
regime as possible in order to show the people that their future
does not lie with Milosevic,'' Albright said. ``We believe that
Serbia would be better off without him.''
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade Thursday, a senior Yugoslav official dismissed as
propaganda claims by the US State Department on Wednesday that it
had firm evidence of Serb troops summarily executing more than 100
ethnic Albanian men in a Kosovo village.
</P>
<P>
   Goran Matic, a minister without portfolio, said the claims about
massacres by Serb forces were meant to deflect attention from
``NATO's crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Matic also denied reports that there had been between 500 to
2,000 desertions by Yugoslav soldiers who returned to their homes
in southern Serbia, and that there had been antiwar demonstrations
in that region.
</P>
<P>
   Matic said NATO, not the Serb forces, wants to rid Kosovo of all
its people so that it can bomb the province to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO and human rights organizations have said that some
100,000 men are unaccounted for in Kosovo, and refugees report that
men of fighting age were separated from them by Serb troops, Matic
said the ethnic Albanian men are being treated no differently than
other Yugoslav citizens. He said no men under the age of 65 are
being allowed to leave Yugoslavia because they may be needed for
military service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not talking about disappearances,'' Matic said.
</P>
<P>
   To buttress his argument, Matic showed reporters here a
videotape of a farmer in whose potato field an alleged mass grave
was purportedly spotted by US spy planes. The elderly farmer
insisted there were no graves on his land.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian TV reported that the Yugoslav government would establish
a ministry for refugees if NATO ended its bombing campaign. It also
said that Milosevic and the Russia's Chernomyrdin would hold talks
in Belgrade again on Monday or Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Lynch reported from the United Nations; Cullen reported from
Belgrade. Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
