<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOLTA-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: MINOLTA CAMPAIGN FOCUSES ON INSPIRATION INSTEAD OF
HARDWARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JANE L. LEVERE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Minolta Corp., the Japanese maker of copiers and
cameras, is counting on a new ad campaign using photographs by a
number of highly acclaimed artists to buoy its brand in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is the first major work done for Minolta, the U.S.
subsidiary of Minolta Co. Ltd. of Japan, by the New York office of
Hill, Holliday, Connors, Cosmopulos Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The subsidiary, which generates one-third of its parent's global
sales and is based in Ramsey, N.J., hired the agency, a unit of
Interpublic Group of Cos., last summer after a four-year
collaboration with Lois/EJL, a unit of Lois/USA. The work is
budgeted through September 2000 at $10 million to $13 million.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, Holiday's task, said Chuck Kushell, president of the New
York unit, is to reposition the Minolta brand, promoted for years
with the tag line ``Only from the mind of Minolta.'' He said the
agency's strategy was to develop a campaign that would ``celebrate
how important Minolta's cameras and office systems are to specific
groups of people,'' rather than promote the equipment's
technological features, which he called the traditional approach
for such products.
</P>
<P>
   All new advertising, both print and broadcast, contains the tag
line ``Do something important'' and, not surprisingly, striking
photography, in many cases by well-known artists.
</P>
<P>
   One group of ads for Minolta's office products, which generated
approximately three-quarters of the company's $1.2 billion total
U.S. sales in its 1998 fiscal year, verge on the inspirational,
though they avoid being saccharine; they are in publications like
Business 2.0, Fortune and The Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   In one ad, a black-and-white photograph by Elliott Erwitt of the
Magnum photo agency, a woman is striding through Grand Central
Station, surrounded by a crowd of people. The copy asks: ``If not
you, who will write a presentation that grows business, will help
another person succeed, will crack a joke in a meeting that
desperately needs one. Your ideas give you a chance. We'll do
everything humanly possible to help you present those ideas more
powerfully and cost efficiently.''
</P>
<P>
   Other, more humorous ads for office products, running in
technical publications, include a William Wegman color photo of a
dog in a wedding dress, and a 1950s black-and-white photo by Erwitt
of a father carving a Thanksgiving turkey under the watchful eyes
of his family.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the campaign is devoted to ads for Minolta's camera
equipment, which generated the remaining quarter of the company's
total U.S. sales in its last fiscal year. In an ad running in
photography magazines for the Maxxum 9, a 35-mm single-lens reflex
professional camera, a male photographer shown from neck to waist
holds a picture of a young Cambodian girl injured by land mines.
The copy asks: ``Can a photograph stop a war? Can it save a life?
Pray that it can.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the right hands, this camera could change the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Minolta also hired Janusz Kaminski, the cinematographer who won
Oscars for his work on ``Schindler's List'' and ``Saving Private
Ryan,'' to create television advertising for its camera equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, Holiday is testing Kaminski's two 30-second spots in
several markets this summer.
</P>
<P>
   One spot contains the sounds of girls giggling and a hose
running as a woman steps down from a porch and takes a picture. Her
subjects _ whom the viewer never sees directly _ are her two
daughters, slathered in mud; they appear in her photograph, shown
at the end of the commercial, which asks, ``Who will take the
photographs that show us the meaning of family?''
</P>
<P>
   The other spot is somewhat of an in-joke: It re-creates a famous
1957 photograph by Erwitt of a crusty old woman encountering a dog
in the driver's seat of a car parked on a city street. The
commercial shows Erwitt reshooting his original photograph and
asks, ``Who will take the photographs that capture life?'' Both
commercials end by asking, ``Will it be you?''
</P>
<P>
   Although Minolta's new advertising budget significantly exceeds
recent expenditures _ according to Competitive Media Reporting, it
spent $4.6 million on camera and copier advertising in 1997 and
$7.6 million in 1998 _ whether the ads help it increase market
share remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   According to Dataquest, a research company in San Jose, Calif.,
Minolta generated 4.4 percent of all U.S. copier sales in 1998,
tied for fifth with Ricoh Co., behind the giants Canon Inc., Xerox
Corp., Sharp Corp. and Mita Industrial Co.
</P>
<P>
   Intelect ASW, a market research company in Port Washington,
N.Y., said Minolta generated 18 percent of U.S. sales for
single-lens reflex cameras last year, third behind Canon and Nikon
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, Minolta's competitors have spent far more than it
has. For example, Canon's 1998 camera and copier advertising
expenditures were $73.6 million, according to Competitive Media
Reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Kaminski, for one, predicts the emotional appeal of Minolta's
advertising will help it win over buyers. ``The campaign is set in
a very realistic scenario,'' he said. ``It doesn't emphasize the
heroic. These are ordinary people. By deglamorizing the
advertising, Minolta's getting closer to consumers, helping them
think, `This product was created for me.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
