<HEADER>
A5236 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNS21-COX     05-20 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Senate votes to require background checks on gun show sales
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With Vice President Al Gore casting the
tie-breaking vote, the Senate voted Thursday to require background
checks on the sale of all firearms at gun shows, dealing a stinging
defeat to the powerful gun lobby.
</P>
<P>
   The background check provision, part of a $1 billion juvenile
crime bill, would affect some 2.5 million gun sales, roughly half
of all guns sold in the United States every year. The Senate was
moving toward final passage of the entire juvenile justice bill
late Thursday night after more than a week of tumultuous debate
over gun control.
</P>
<P>
   The 51-50 vote requiring background checks at gun shows was a
setback for Senate Republicans, who sought to derail the
Democratic-sponsored initiative with a less restrictive proposal of
their own.
</P>
<P>
   Strategists on both sides of the aisle said Thursday's shooting
in Conyers, Ga., didn't influence votes. But the latest incidence
of school violence, coming on the one-month anniversary of the
deadly school shootings in Littleton, Colo., hung heavy in the
Senate chamber as senators prepared to cast their votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone woke up this morning wavering ... they got a huge
wake up call in Georgia,'' said Sen. Barbara Boxer (D-Calif.).
``This morning's news was yet another reminder of gun violence in
our society.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the wavering senators was Georgia's Max Cleland, who
reversed his opposition to the gun show provision after the
sponsor, Sen. Frank Lautenberg (D-N.J.), made some minor changes
dealing with the definition of gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Cleland said the shooting in Conyers, occurring in the ``back
yard'' of his native Lithonia, reinforced his decision that gun
shows should be more tightly regulated.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the icing on the cake,'' Cleland said.
</P>
<P>
   Ebullient after their victory, Democrats called Thursday's vote
the biggest defeat for the National Rifle Association and other gun
interests since Republicans regained control of the Congress in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you just saw is the NRA loosing its grip on the U.S.
Senate at long last,'' declared Sen. Tom Daschle (D-S.D.), the
minority leader. ``This is a huge victory today.''
</P>
<P>
   NRA Executive Vice President Wayne LaPierre issued a terse
statement following the vote, calling the Senate's action
``made-for-television lawmaking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows this won't stop the crisis in our schools,''
LaPierre said. ``The American people want existing gun laws
enforced and their Second Amendment freedoms protected.''
</P>
<P>
   Gun control advocates, meanwhile, hailed the decision as a
long-overdue change needed to keep guns out of the hands of
children and criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one week, the Senate has closed the gun show loophole,
mandated the sale of trigger locks, prohibited further import of
military-style, large ammunition clips and prohibited violent
juveniles from ever owning a firearm,'' said Sarah Brady,
chairwoman of Handgun Control Inc. ``It has taken five years and
far too many dead children for Congress to break the gun lobby's
stranglehold on common-sense gun regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, who number 45 in the Senate, lost only one of their
members in voting for the gun show provision, Sen. Max Baucus
(D-Mont.). Six Republicans crossed party lines to vote for the
measure, setting up the opportunity for Gore to cast the dramatic,
tie-breaking vote. Gore, who serves as president of the Senate, has
broken only three other ties in his seven years in office.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's tie vote also gave Gore, who is seeking the
Democratic nomination for president, an opportunity to step to the
forefront of an issue that concerns many voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just elated over this victory,'' Gore said after the
vote, making a special mention of the shooting in Georgia. ``Until
we get more control in a sensible way on the easy availability of
guns in our society ... these tragedies will continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than a week ago, Republicans pushed through a measure that
would have made background checks at gun shows voluntary. In an
abrupt turnaround, they offered another proposal that required some
checks, but created some exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   In a final bid to head off the Democratic initiative, Sens. Jim
Jeffords (R-Vt.) and Gordon Smith (R-Ore.) offered a proposal that
would close some of the loopholes for gun show sales and require
anyone purchasing a firearm at a pawn shop to undergo a background
check.
</P>
<P>
   That amendment passed by a wide margin, 79 to 21, but failed to
draw enough Republicans away from also supporting Lautenberg's
stricter provisions. Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.) voted against both
gun control measures.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats were quick to see political fallout
from the votes. Coverdell said Gore's close association with gun
control would not help him win support among independents.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Torricelli (D-N.J.), the Senate Democratic campaign
chair, called the gun votes ``the principal defining issue between
Democrats and Republicans in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very costly week for Republicans in the Senate,''
he said. ``And it will cost them some seats in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell (R-Ky.), the GOP campaign chairman, said
each Republican cast a vote that was right for the member's state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they've all voted in a way that will work for them,''
McConnell said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
