<HEADER>
A5237 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNVOTES-GA21-COX     05-20 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNVOTES-GA21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia senator changes vote to support gun control, fellow
official firmly against measure
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By Wednesday afternoon, Democratic leaders in the
Senate were cautiously optimistic that they had sealed up the votes
to pass a restrictive gun control measure requiring background
checks for all gun sales at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Cleland (D-Ga.) was a key figure in their last-minute
vote tallies. Cleland had voted against the first gun show
amendment, part of the multibillion dollar juvenile justice bill,
the week before.
</P>
<P>
   But Cleland's staff and staff members from the office of Sen.
Frank Lautenberg (D-N.J.), the gun show amendment's sponsor, had
been negotiating for several days to secure Cleland's support.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg agreed to tighten the definition of gun shows to make
clear that sales between neighbors wouldn't be affected, one of
Cleland's demands, and received Cleland's endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   We ``were talking and he said, 'I think we've got a deal,'''
Lautenberg said. ``I think we satisfied him by reducing the edge on
a couple of things we had.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The original concern I had was that if you cracked down on the
gun shows, you are going to force this out into the street, the
black market and onto the Internet, where there is no regulation at
all,'' said Cleland.
</P>
<P>
   With Cleland's vote locked up, Lautenberg and other Democratic
leaders called Vice President Gore to inform him that he should be
on hand for Thursday's vote to break a potential tie. Lautenberg
was counting on at least six Republicans to help push the gun show
measure over the top.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg also took into account the voting of Sen. Paul
Coverdell (R-Ga.). Coverdell, who voted against all of the more
restrictive gun control proposals, views Lautenberg as one of the
Senate's most strident gun control advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell decided early on that he wouldn't be on the same side
of any initiative offered by the New Jersey Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lautenberg is a gun control, anti-Second Amendment
enthusiast,'' Coverdell said after Thursday's votes. ``There is no
chance I would view Lautenberg as creating a balanced, concrete
agenda. He's the guru of the idea that you can manage these events
by controlling guns, skipping over what people do who have either
guns or bombs. He just doesn't have any credibility on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell, who has received $14,635 from gun interests in direct
contributions in the past six years, said no one from the National
Rifle Association lobbied him to vote against any of the gun
control measures adopted as part of the juvenile justice bill.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the restrictions on gun shows, the Senate also
voted over the past week to require child safety locks or lock
boxes to be sold with any hand gun, and to require background
checks for guns bought at pawn shops. Coverdell voted against both
measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I frankly think that most of our schools are quite safe and
that drugs are the major threat, not weapons,'' Coverdell said.
``There were 22 laws broken in Littleton. Does anybody think that
if we had 35 of them ... it would have made a difference? The
answer is obvious, no. But I guess politics being of the sound bite
nature that it is, it just can't restrain itself. Every time
something happens, 50 people stand up and say we're going to solve
it because we write something down on a piece of paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
