<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-CHAT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON MOVES TO END SUIT OVER CHAT-BOARD POSTINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Raytheon Co. ended a controversial lawsuit against 21
people it alleged had disclosed inside company information on an
Internet chat board.
</P>
<P>
   In a court filing Thursday attorneys for Raytheon moved to
dismiss the suit charging a group of computer users had revealed
financial secrets on a World Wide Web chat board operated by Yahoo
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Four employees identified in the suit have since left the
company, and Raytheon said it has now done enough to protect its
private financial information.
</P>
<P>
   The suit by the Lexington, Mass. defense contractor, filed in
February, was one of the widest-ranging to date as companies seek
to clamp down on individuals' chat about them posted on line. It
also drew attention to the ease with which Raytheon was able to
identify Internet denizens despite their use of anonymous screen
names.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon believed at least some of the 21 people it called
``John Does'' were current or former employees, though it knew them
only by their handles, such as ``RaytheonVeteran'' and
``RSCDeepThroat.''
</P>
<P>
   The chat postings caused more than $25,000 in damages and harmed
Raytheon's business reputation, the suit alleged, mentioning
e-mails that proported to describe earnings expectations and stock
forecasts, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   To learn the real identities of the authors, Raytheon obtained
discovery motions against Yahoo and other portals and Internet
service providers. As a result, it was able to learn the identities
of at least some users.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon now says it plans no further disciplinary actions. ``We
think it brings the matter to a close,'' said spokesman David Polk.
``Our internal activities are over.''
</P>
<P>
   But debate about the case is likely to continue, as Internet
free-speech groups have accused Internet service companies of
caving in to Raytheon's demands while giving users the impression
they would do more to protect their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Courts should be wary of such demands for discovery, said David
Sobel, chief counsel for the Electronic Privacy Information Center
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is an example of why courts should be
apprehensive about allowing this kind of discovery,'' Sobel said.
The complaint ``shows the potential for an abuse of the discovery
system in removing the anonymity from speakers on the Interet,''
Sobel said.
</P>
<P>
   One person targeted by the suit also charged that its withdrawal
showed Raytheon wasn't sincere in seeking to recover damages. ``The
whole pretense is false,'' the person said, speaking on condition
of anonymity. ``They were really just after the identities.''
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon's Polk said the case was necessary to protect internal
company affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rationale was, we feel we have to make a commitment to
protecting our proprietary information,'' Polk said. ``We took
steps we felt were appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   In that regard the suit seems to have worked. Lately the Yahoo
message board devoted to Raytheon has contained far less specific
information.
</P>
<P>
   Now the most spirited messages are related to an upcoming union
election at Local 1505 of the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers, which represents thousands of local employees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
