<HEADER>
A5241 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-CLINTON21-COX     05-20 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-CLINTON21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON, IN COLORADO, URGES UNDERSTANDING AND CHANGE
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Hours after the nation's latest school
shootings rocked suburban Atlanta on Thursday, President Clinton
called on the students of Columbine High School to honor the
victims of last month's killings here by working to change the
``culture of violence'' that spawned both tragedies.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also made a plea for understanding as he spoke to about
2,000 Columbine students, faculty and family members.
</P>
<P>
   ``These dark forces that take over people, and make them murder,
are the extreme manifestation of fear and rage with which every
human being has to do combat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The older you get, the more you'll know that a great deal of
life is the struggle against every person's own smallness and fear
and anger, and a continuing effort not to blame other people for
our own shortcomings or our fears.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton journeyed here on a long-planned visit to address the
nation one month to the day after two Columbine students opened
fire on their classmates, killing 12 students and a teacher and
wounding 23 others before taking their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's address took on added poignancy, however, following
the Thursday morning shootings at the Heritage High School outside
Atlanta. That incident left six students wounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thankfully no one was killed,'' first lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton said of Thursday's incident, ``but it should never have
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton was en route to Littleton aboard Air Force One,
Vice President Al Gore cast the tie-breaking vote back in
Washington to pass Senate juvenile justice legislation. The bill,
which now goes to the House, is aimed at making it easier to
prosecute juveniles as young as 14 for violent crimes and to
require background checks before firearms are sold at gun shows and
pawn shops.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, speaking in the White House Rose Garden before leaving
for Colorado, said the Atlanta shooting ``is deeply troubling to
me, as it is to all Americans,'' and pointed to the need for
closing gun control loopholes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This incident, again, should underscore how profoundly
important it is that all Americans come together in the face of
these events to protect our children from violence,'' Clinton said.
``We have got to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Arriving in this Denver suburb on a grey day marked by a brief
hailstorm, the president and first lady visited with families of
the Columbine victims.
</P>
<P>
   Seated around tables set up in the sanctuary of the Light of the
World Catholic Church, the families shared their stories and passed
around homemade scrapbooks memorializing their lost loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   If the mood in that closed-door session was intimate and somber,
there was a strikingly different atmosphere moments later, when
Clinton walked onto the dais at a jammed gymnasium at the Dakota
Ridge High School, just three miles from Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are Columbine,'' the students chanted. Clinton hailed the
boisterous show of spirit as a sign of the powerful renewal
sweeping this wounded community.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton urged the students to harness that spirit to the goal of
helping to build an American society less tolerant of violence and
more forgiving of each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give us a culture of values, instead of a culture of
violence,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow what happened to you has pierced the soul of America
and it gives you a chance to be heard in a way no one else can be
heard,'' said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Help us to build a better future for all our children,'' said
Clinton. ``A future where society guards our children better
against violent influences and weapons that can break the dam of
decency and humanity in the most vulnerable children.''
</P>
<P>
   The president stressed, though, that it won't be easy to cure
the nation's epidemic of school violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot do what we need to do in America unless every person
is committed to doing something better and different in every walk
of life,'' Clinton said, ``beginning with parents and students and
going all the way to the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It really meant a lot to us'' that the president came here,
said Columbine freshman Vickie Abel, 15. ``It's going to make us
stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   In a particularly dramatic moment, cheers rang out when Clinton
introduced two Columbine students _ Sean Graves and Patrick Ireland
_ who emerged from the hospital where they have been recovering
from wounds received in the shootings to attend Thursday's event.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton urged the students to remember during their commencement
ceremonies Saturday that theirs is a special class.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be bittersweet,'' Clinton said. But he urged them to
listen for the support of their nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hear the voice of America,'' Clinton said, ``because America
will be cheering you on.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
