<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5243 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-GUNS-HNS &LR;      05-20 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE BREAKS TIE AS SENATE PASSES GUN MEASURE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
and CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With Vice President Al Gore breaking a tie, the
Senate on Thursday voted to require instant background checks for
purchasers at gun shows and before redemption of a gun at a pawn
shop.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's decisive role in adoption of the Democratic-sponsored
amendment is the latest in a series of developments that point
toward gun control emerging as a pivotal issue early in the 2000
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a turning point for our country,'' Gore said.
``Finally, this majority is turning the corner and helping to
protect the children and families of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   All but six Senate Republicans opposed the measure, and only one
Democrat supported it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Texas Sens. Phil Gramm and Kay Bailey Hutchison, both Republicans,
voted against the proposal. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The amendment became part of a bill, designed to combat
juvenile crime, that was headed for a final vote in the Senate
later Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, playing on their belief that gun control has become a
popular issue, especially in swing suburban constituencies, had
earlier won approval of an amendment that requires handguns to be
sold with safety devices or trigger locks.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., threatened last week
to withdraw the measure from Senate consideration, but by Thursday
he was ready to allow a final vote so the politically troublesome
measure could be shipped to the House.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., has signaled support for
new restrictions on gun sales, but it was uncertain if he can rally
support from enough fellow Republicans, including the leadership
duo from Texas, Majority Leader Dick Armey of Irving and Majority
Whip Tom DeLay of Sugar Land.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic Senate vote came as President Clinton flew to
Littleton, Colo., a month after the deadly gun violence at
Columbine High School, and as another school gun incident unfolded
in an Atlanta suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called Gore to congratulate him for the vote. White
House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Clinton praised the Senate for
taking ``the common-sense approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, in Littleton, Clinton said: ``I applaud the Senate for
today's historic vote to close the gun-show loophole and keep guns
out of the hands of criminals and children.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote was on an amendment by Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J.,
which in a slightly different form was narrowly defeated last week.
The changes attracted the critical vote of Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga.,
creating a 50-50 tie, which Gore broke.
</P>
<P>
   Cleland and other supporters of the measure said he had decided
to switch his vote before the wounding of six students at a
Conyers, Ga., high school.
</P>
<P>
   Cleland said, however, that the shooting in his home state
``really confirmed for me that I was on the right track.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of strict gun control invoked the latest incident to
press for passage of the mandatory checks.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much longer are we going to embrace the gun lobby?'' asked
Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., who while in the House was a major
sponsor of the 1993 law, known as the Brady bill, that first
required a waiting period on gun sales through licensed outlets and
barred gun purchases by felons and the mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   Gun-control advocates said the vote marked a major loss for the
firearms lobby, including the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you just saw is the NRA losing its grip on the United
States Senate, at long last,'' declared Senate Democratic leader
Tom Daschle of South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   NRA leaders vowed to fight additional restrictions on gun sales
and said that ``the Clinton-Gore administration'' was ``pursuing a
charade of lawmaking without law enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows this won't stop the crisis in our schools,''
NRA executive vice president Wayne LaPierre and NRA top lobbyist
James J. Baker said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders buttonholed some of the handful of GOP
senators who supported Lautenberg's amendment last week, but they
were unable to convince any of them to switch. With the roll call
in progress, Lott importuned Sen. John Warner, R-Va., publicly on
the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Republican majority, traditionally opposed to most
gun controls, has seemed uncertain how to react in the wake of the
rash of school shootings and polls showing big majorities in favor
of cracking down on easy access to firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Republicans first voted against mandatory background
checks at gun shows, but reversed themselves two days later.
</P>
<P>
   When Democrats complained that the GOP-backed approach had
loopholes, many Republicans voted earlier Thursday to tighten some
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby steps,'' chided Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt. But in case the
Lautenberg amendment might fail, a number of Democrats voted for
the GOP proposal by Sen. Gordon Smith of Oregon, which passed
79-21.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's amendment was overridden by passage of Lautenberg's
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's proposal would have given state authorities only 24
hours to run a background check on gun buyers, rather than the
three days allowed on purchases at licensed retail outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who had been alerted Wednesday night to the possibility of
a tie, arrived at the Capitol shortly before the vote. It was the
fourth tie-breaking vote of Gore's more than six years as vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Voting in favor of the Lautenberg amendment were 44 Democrats
and six Republicans _ Sens. John Chaffee of Rhode Island, Mike
DeWine of Ohio, Peter Fitzgerald of Illinois, Richard Lugar of
Indiana, George Voinovich of Ohio and Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Voting against were 49 Republicans and Democratic Sen. Max
Baucus of Montana.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
,
</P>
</TEXT>
