<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5244 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-ART-(2T     05-20 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-ART-(2TAKES)-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH GORE BREAKING TIE, SENATE APPROVES GUN SHOW REGULATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(rm) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a charged moment, Vice President Al Gore made a
rare Senate appearance Thursday and cast a tie-breaking vote that
enabled a Democratic gun-control measure to prevail over a less
stringent Republican version.
</P>
<P>
   The 51-50 vote, approving a measure to require background checks
with the sale of firearms at gun shows, reversed the outcome of a
similar vote last week and was easily the most stunning of a string
of Democratic victories on gun control in the Senate over the last
eight days.
</P>
<P>
   It also provided Gore, whose campaign for the Democratic
presidential nomination has yet to catch fire, with a heady
triumph. Democrats believe that American sentiment about firearms
has turned toward their party's advocacy of tighter restrictions,
and Gore got to carry that banner by playing the knight who arrived
in the nick of time to save a teetering cause.
</P>
<P>
   Gore voted on the same day that bullets ripped through yet
another high school, in Conyers, Ga. Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga., said
the shooting was a factor in clinching his decision to switch his
vote in favor of his party's measure.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, for his part, was visiting Littleton, Colo.,
where the shooting deaths of 15 people at a high school last month
altered the political climate enough to make Thursday's events in
the Senate possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a turning point for our country,'' said Gore, a
radiant smile glued to his face, at a news conference after he left
the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   More somberly, Gore added, ``Now I personally would like to
dedicate my tie-breaking vote to all of the families that have
suffered from gun violence.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only the fourth time in Gore's vice presidency that he
broke a tie in the Senate, over which the vce president technically
presides.
</P>
<P>
   Gore took a seat at the head of the chamber as the votes
trickled in, and as the possibility of a tie seemed ever more
likely, Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., giggled and flashed a
thumbs-up sign at the vice president. Other Senate Democrats rushed
over to shake his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Although Republicans have a 55-to-45 advantage in the Senate,
six Republicans who have repeatedly broken party ranks on gun
control sided with Democrats Thursday, while only one Democrat
sided with Republicans. That created the tie.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was attached to a juvenile crime bill, that would
provide $1 billion a year to states for prevention and enforcement.
A similar bill before the House Judiciary Committee does not have
gun-control measures in it, but the committee's chairman, Rep.
Henry Hyde, R-Ill., announced Thursday that such amendments would
be considered when the committee meets to reshape the bill in two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours after the Senate voted on the gun show amendment,
Sen. Trent Lott, the majority leader, called a news conference to
raise a different issue: the leaking of nuclear secrets during the
Clinton administration to the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the success of the Democratic gun-show amendment,
which he opposed, Lott said that the Democrats' campaign for gun
control was largely political preening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guns don't cause people to do these things,'' Lott said.
``Something in their beings is doing it. When do we put the
responsibility on the individuals?''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton, in a statement released in Littleton, said, ``I
applaud the Senate for today's historic vote.''
</P>
<P>
   And a White House official described the Lott news conference as
an attempt to divert attention away from his party's gun-control
``debacle.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic gun-show amendment, which would mandate
background checks on all people buying weapons at these shows,
joined a series of a half dozen gun-control measures that have
passed as amendments to the juvenile crime bill. Many of the
measures garnered broad Republican support, an unmistakable sign of
changed times.
</P>
<P>
   The bill itself, which calls for about $1 billion annually in
grants to local governments to toughen the prosecution of juvenile
crime and enhance efforts to prevent it, had not come to a final
vote by early Thursday night, but seemed likely to pass.
</P>
<P>
   The vote on the Democratic gun-show amendment was the last
strange twist in a bizarre chain of gun-show votes that had
Republicans switching their course or tweaking their position from
one day to the next.
</P>
<P>
   When the Democratic gun-show amendment first came up for a vote
a week ago, Senate Republicans defeated it, 51-47, in a largely
party-line vote. Instead, they approved a rival Republican
amendment that called for voluntary background checks at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Senate Republicans rethought their position and
passed a new gun-show amendment that they said made background
checks mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats noted that the combined Republican amendments
actually relaxed existing gun-control regulations in other areas.
So the Republicans came back with a third amendment, intended to
address concerns about the first two.
</P>
<P>
   That amendment passed Thursday. But only minutes later, the
original Democratic amendment, modified slightly and reintroduced,
supplanted it.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The new outcome was explained in part by the presence of two
Democrats _ Sens. Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York and Daniel
Inouye of Hawaii _ who had been absent last week but voted in favor
of the amendment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Just as critically, Sen. Cleland of Georgia, one of only two
Democrats who had opposed the measure last week, changed his vote
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Cleland said that, because of subtle revisions to the original
Democratic amendment, he had almost firmly decided to switch his
vote on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that awaking Thursday morning to news of the
shooting in his home state erased any tiny, lingering doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``For that to occur in my own state, in my own back yard,
reinforced and steeled my commitment,'' Cleland said. ``It pushed
me over the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   The only Democrat to vote against his party Thursday was Max
Baucus of Montana, whose position suggested the degree to which
geography trumps party affiliation on gun-control issues.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the six Republicans who joined Democrats last week and
again Thursday were from the Midwest, where support for easy access
to firearms is not as fierce as in the South and West.
</P>
<P>
   They were Sens. Mike DeWine of Ohio, Peter Fitzgerald of
Illinois, Richard Lugar of Indiana and George Voinovich of Ohio.
Sens. John Chafee of Rhode Island and Senator John Warner of
Virginia also voted for the Democratic amendment.
</P>
<P>
   These senators said they had problems with several aspects of
the Republican gun-show measures that even a third amendment did
not fix. The measures, for example, would have made it less
cumbersome for licensed gun dealers to sell weapons in other
states.
</P>
<P>
   The measures also would have shortened from three business days
to 24 hours the amount of time given to vendors at gun shows to
conduct background checks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big loophole,'' DeWine said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association had lobbied against the
Democratic gun-show amendment and, after the vote, said that the
Senate had not addressed a larger problem: lax enforcement of
existing gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said that the association's influence was clearly
waning.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have seen today now is, for the first time in a major
kind of gun-control issue, rejection of the National Rifle
Association and a vote for common sense,'' said Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Other gun-control measures in the juvenile crime bill include a
requirement that licensed gun dealers sell child safety devices
with every handgun; a prohibition on gun ownership for anyone who
commits a violent crime as a juvenile, and new restrictions on the
purchase and possession of semi-automatic assault rifles for
children under 18.
</P>
</TEXT>
