<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-SHOOTER21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quiet suspect was more talkative when topic was his guns,
friends say
 &HT;    By Joshua B. Good
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Heritage High School shooting suspect was quiet,
friends said, unless he was talking about guns.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, when he gave his neighbors, Skip and Brad Morgan, a
tour of his house, he didn't say much.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the boys admired the posters of baseball greats Sammy
Sosa and Mark McGuire in the suspect's bedroom, he remained silent.
</P>
<P>
   But when Skip, 17, and Brad, 15, followed the boy into the
basement, the teen started rattling on about his stepfather's
firearms, locked in a cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was full of big, heavy assault rifles,'' Skip remembered.
``He told us the bullets were in the cabinet below the guns and he
knew where the key was.''
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested the Morgan's 15-year-old neighbor Thursday after
he allegedly shot six fellow students at the Conyers' high school.
</P>
<P>
   GBI agents looking for answers searched the 3,000-square-foot,
four-bedroom house in the Hanover Square subdivision the boy shares
with his mother, stepfather and little sister.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's parents were not talking to reporters Thursday. But
the boy's friends and neighbors said they saw changes in the boy,
who was a clean-cut Boy Scout when the family moved to Conyers in
December 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The move came when the stepfather, a trucking company executive,
was transferred from Kernersville, N.C., to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The boy spent his time playing a Mortal Combat video game or
shooting arrows into a target in his back yard, Skip said.
</P>
<P>
   When the Morgan boys went to the suspect's house last summer to
invite him outside to play baseball, he passed on a message through
his little sister that he wasn't coming out. He wouldn't go
swimming in the Morgan's pool, either.
</P>
<P>
   Skip was someone the boy had spent time with five days a week.
They carpooled together going to and from summer school classes
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Skip's dad, Allan Morgan, remembers the boy sitting in the back
of the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't a heck of a lot of conversation,'' Allan Morgan
said. ``If you tried to bring him into the conversation, he'd just
look at you and stare.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the same in those summer classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw him with anyone,'' said Kelsey Garrett, the
school's football team manager who attended a summer school class
with the suspect. He sat behind Kelsey the whole time, and he
virtually never spoke, she said.
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, the boy began hanging out with 16-year-old
Glen Ganyard III and Glen's friends.
</P>
<P>
   Like any high school, Heritage has its cliques. There are the
jocks and the brains. Then there are Glen's friends. Glen says his
buddies are the freaks and the rednecks.
</P>
<P>
   To fit in, Glen and Skip said their friend ditched his preppy
clothes and began wearing baggy pants and scrungy-looking shirts.
He stayed in Boy Scouts, but didn't tell his new friends about it.
He got a girlfriend, but talked bad about her to Glen and she
recently broke up with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last year and a half he's been going down,'' Skip said.
``He'd either put gel in his hair or it would be real greasy.''
</P>
<P>
   Glen said the 15-year-old was boastful and would pick fights but
back down when other boys took his challenge, Glen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was 10-feet tall and bullet-proof,'' Glen said.
</P>
<P>
   Then the suspect got a handgun. He told Glen his parents gave it
to him as a gift. The suspect told Glen his parents took the
handgun away from him recently when they learned the boy carried it
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he knew where it was hid,'' Glen said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning at the boy's bus stop was just like any other
day. He showed up and said nothing as he waited with his sister,
along with Brad and Brad's little sister.
</P>
<P>
   Glen, who recently got his driver's license, drove up.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's up, man?'' Glen asked, as the boy leaned into the
window of Glen's car.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's up?'' the boy responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got any cigarettes?'' Glen asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' the boy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I guess we'll see you in school,'' Glen said and drove
off.
</P>
<P>
   When the boy got on the bus, he went to his usual seat in the
back, Brad said. The boy rode the bus to school, alone in silence.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
