<SLUG> BC-COMPANY-CHARGED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US CHARGES SCAM IN OPERATION OF DATA FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Founded in 1995, Multinational Systems Corp. claimed
to be a national conglomerate with offices across the country and
$100 million in annual sales. But federal prosecutors alleged
Thursday the high-tech data recovery firm was little more than a
racket that scammed $20 million from lenders it duped.
</P>
<P>
   The Cambridge company ``was primarily a sham . . . for the
financial benefit of MSC and its principals,'' according to an
indictment in US District Court in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a group of very smart, very sophisticated, very
creative people who saw an opportunity to take advantage of the
leasing industry,'' said assistant US attorney Allison Burroughs.
``They did very well at it for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   An attorney for Stephen Chan, the company's founder, denied the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve Chan is a young, extremely bright engineer,'' said Atty.
Stephen R. Delinsky. ``He's absolutely incapable of the financial
shenanigans alleged in this indictment. At all times, he acted
under the advice of paid professionals.''
</P>
<P>
   Chan, 27, an MIT graduate, was arrested at his parents' New York
home last August and charged with violating wire-fraud laws shortly
after FBI agents raided MSC's Marlborough, Mass. offices. A federal
magistrate allowed him to remain free following his arraignment.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's indictment alleges 27 counts of money laundering,
mail fraud, and wire fraud. Others named in the indictment include
Michelle Lee, who allegedly oversaw the company's financial
affairs; William Hulse, an MSC employee; and Dennis Burns, a
financial consultant at Merrill Lynch in Williamsville, N.Y., who
allegedly lied to prospective lenders about MSC's financial
standing. If convicted on all counts, Chan faces a maximum penalty
of 30 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   MSC claimed to be a so-called ``disaster recovery'' firm in the
rapidly expanding business of helping companies recover or protect
electronic data in catastrophes such as fire or flood, according to
the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a sprawling compound in Marlborough that Chan
once referred to as ``the ultimate bunker'' in a newspaper profile,
the company rented offices in Los Angeles, Chicago, and New York's
Trump Tower.
</P>
<P>
   The company performed a modest computer tape pick-up service,
according to the indictment. But MSC's daily operations ``consisted
largely of obtaining lease financing from various lenders by means
of false and fraudulent representations,'' the indictment alleges.
</P>
<P>
   The company allegedly used forged opinion letters from a
Japanese accounting firm, fake financial statements, and a
fictitious bank account to convince lenders it was a legitimate
company and obtain huge loans for equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being used to buy equipment, however, the money was
usually dispersed among MSC's principals and various MSC
subsidiaries, the indictment alleges.
</P>
<P>
   In one deal detailed in Thursday's filing, Federated Capital
Services of Farmington Hills, Mich., financed the purchase of
$900,000 worth of vehicles, including two Land Rovers, two Lincoln
limousines and a Mercedes Benz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 2042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
