u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRADE-REPORT-ART-NYT &LR;      05-20 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-REPORT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TRADE GAP A RECORD $19.7 BILLION IN MARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. trade deficit reached another record in
March, the Commerce Department reported Thursday, providing fresh
evidence that the U.S. economy continues to absorb imports at a
prodigious rate.
</P>
<P>
   The deficit for March totaled $19.7 billion, the department
said, up from a revised $19.1 billion in February and well above
the $18.5 billion predicted by economists. It was the third
consecutive month in which the deficit was at a new high.
</P>
<P>
   Exports for the month were $77.5 billion, up $700 million from
February, the first increase in five months and a sign of possible
recovery in key foreign markets for U.S. goods such as Asia. But
imports grew even faster, up $1.3 billion, to $97.2 billion, also a
record.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in import revenue was propelled in part by the
higher cost of crude oil, which has jumped in recent months after
being depressed for the last year.
</P>
<P>
   But imports surged in other categories as well _ notably steel,
autos and auto parts, as foreign producers looked to the United
States as the vibrant market for their products at a time much of
the rest of the world was in the economic doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect the deficit to continue creeping higher in
coming months, although probably at a slower pace than over the
last several months. They said the deficit would not begin
contracting until Western Europe, Japan and the developing nations
of Asia begin enjoying a more marked rebound than they have had so
far.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that until the pace of economic growth in
the U.S. slows and the rest of the world picks up, the deficit will
continue to grow,'' said G. David Orr, chief economist at First
Union Capital Markets.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the trade deficit during a congressional hearing
Thursday, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said it should
not be a problem in the short run because the dollar has been
reasonably stable in value and others have been happy to invest the
dollars they earn through trade back into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no evidence that there is any immediate problem
coming because of the fact that we are, as an economy, growing far
faster than the rest of the world,'' Greenspan told the House
Banking Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the deficit could become disturbing in the long run
if it continued to grow, ``creating a significant rise in debt or
claims against us by foreigners, which could essentially
destabilize our system.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the trade deficit is often as much a political and
diplomatic problem as an economic one. The U.S. deficit with Japan,
long a source of friction between the two countries, surged to $6.5
billion in March from $5.3 billion a month earlier, largely because
of a sharp jump in imports. Washington has been pressing the
Japanese, with mixed success, to do more to stimulate a moribund
economy.
</P>
<P>
   The deficit with China dropped to $4.1 billion from $4.6
billion. China has been the focus of the Clinton administration's
trade policy in recent months, as Washington and Beijing spar over
the terms on which the Chinese should be admitted to the World
Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The best news in Thursday's report was the increase in exports.
For years, the administration was able to point to growing exports
as evidence that its policy of opening markets to U.S. goods was
paying off in the form of domestic jobs and profits. But since the
Asian financial and economic crisis began in mid-1997, the demand
for U.S. products in many foreign markets has been weak, hurting
farmers and manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in exports in March was modest, and it still left
the export level 1.8 percent below where it was a year earlier. But
it reflected improved sales abroad of a variety of products as
diverse as telecommunications equipment, generators, soybeans and
chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the growing deficit, the administration has given no
indication of abandoning its policy of keeping the dollar strong, a
strategy that makes exports from the United States relatively more
expensive but helps hold down domestic inflation by making imports
less expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while the surge in imports could ultimately prove
troublesome, it has benefited consumers by creating competition and
forcing American producers to keep prices down. The announcement by
the Federal Reserve on Tuesday that it would tilt in the future
toward higher interest rates could lead to a further strengthening
of the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   The trade deficit is one of the few tangible ways in which the
American economy has been affected by recent global economic
turmoil. In part because the United States has weathered the
problems well, policy makers here have urged caution in moves to
change the world financial system.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Greenspan and Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin repeated
the message that tough monetary and fiscal policy choices, rather
than a new financial architecture, were the most effective ways to
avert problems in the international economy.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing side by side before the banking committee, they
outlined steps the United States has taken to reduce the likelihood
of another global financial crisis, including encouraging nations
to share more economic data with investors and to keep their
currencies realistically valued.
</P>
<P>
   As a way of insuring that developing nations are able to weather
financial crises, Greenspan suggested that they keep enough
foreign-currency reserves on hand to allow them to pay all their
debts for one year without any additional borrowing. He said that
developing countries should not take on too much short-term debt
and that they keep the average maturity of their foreign debt at no
less than three years so they do not find themselves squeezed by
rapid-repayment demands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
