<HEADLINE>
346-9867.)
</HEADLINE>
  
 McCAIN HARSHLY CRITICIZES CLINTON POLICIES  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)(bl) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a speech outlining his own views on foreign
affairs, Sen. John McCain was harshly critical Thursday of
President Clinton on issues from Kosovo to the Middle East to
international trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president often conducts foreign policies that are little
more than international variants of pork barrel politics without
regard for the long-term interests of the United States,'' said
McCain at a National Press Club lunch. ``The next president,'' he
added, ``has to do a whole lot better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   The lunch gave the Arizona Republican, who is seeking his
party's presidential nomination, a forum in which he could assemble
the range of his foreign policy views in one speech.
</P>
<P>
   On the war in the Balkans, McCain said Clinton had made a
serious mistake at the outset by renouncing the use of ground
troops. And he was contemptuous of the statements of administration
officials that they were not surprised by the aggressiveness of
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic in routing Albanians from
Kosovo after NATO began bombing Serbia. ``Why didn't we warn the
Kosovars,'' he asked, ``if we somehow knew that Milosevic was going
to do this?''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Middle East, McCain said he hoped the election in
Israel this week would result in the resumption of the peace
process. He called the Wye River agreement that Clinton engineered
last year ``a classic Clintonesque exercise.'' He described it this
way: ``Get everybody together, know the outcome, a big photo op,
nice things are said, and then you move on. The Wye River
agreements are in tatters.''
</P>
<P>
   On trade, McCain said, ``Free trade is indispensable to our
prosperity.'' He said if he were president he would negotiate a
free-trade agreement ``with almost any country willing to negotiate
fairly with us.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain criticized Clinton for backing away from support of
admitting China into the World Trade Organization and said the
president had done far too little to promote trade with countries
in Africa and South America.
</P>
<P>
   After the speech, McCain was asked about the statement of former
Sen. Bob Dole that he was considering donating money to the McCain
campaign, a remark that alarmed those running the campaign of
Dole's wife, Elizabeth. ``They haven't installed a phone in his
woodshed yet, so I haven't had a chance to talk to him,'' McCain
replied with a grin.
</P>
</TEXT>
