A5260 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-SECURITY21-C     05-20 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-SECURITY21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scene of Georgia shootings safe, nurturing, faculty and students
say
 &HT;    By Leon Stafford
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONYERS, Ga. _ Even after Thursday's shooting rampage at
Heritage High School, Rockdale County Board of Education member Jim
Borland was uneasy with the idea of installing metal detectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't put a blinder on, but we can't overreact either,''
said Borland, who heads a committee that just last week was
undecided on the idea of creating what would be electronic
checkpoints between students and their campus.
</P>
<P>
   That's because, up to now, Heritage High School has been a place
where guns and violence seem distant concerns. While other schools
throughout metro Atlanta had experienced bomb threats and other
violent gestures in the wake of the recent Littleton, Colo.,
shootings, Heritage reported nothing of the sort.
</P>
<P>
   Parents said students there are nurtured and guided rather than
considered potential security risks.
</P>
<P>
   That's certainly been the experience of Donna Hattaway. When her
parents died within 10 days of each other last fall, she was too
devastated to be of much help to her academically struggling son,
Chris.
</P>
<P>
   So Heritage High School administrators stepped in. They told
Chris that while they understood his sorrow, he had to get back on
his feet and pull up his falling grades. It was what his
grandparents would have wanted, they told him.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, what they said bothered me,'' his mother said.
``But it was just what he needed. He needed someone to put him on
track. And thank God they did because I was in no shape to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Vickie Woods also testified to the school's level of personal
concern. After her son, Michael, 19, was injured in a car accident,
a school administrator came to her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came to see how well he was doing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said that while she is concerned about the shooting, she
still will send her daughter, Lynnsey, 17, to Heritage for her
senior year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My kids have done very well there, and that is why I am just
shocked,'' said Woods. ``My husband and I had talked about moving,
but I didn't want to because I wanted my children to finish here.''
</P>
<P>
   The choice was easy for them, given Heritage's academic track
record. It has been a Georgia Public School of Excellence four
times, most recently this year. It also was a National School of
Excellence in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, U.S. News and World Report named Heritage one of
its outstanding American high schools in January, and the CBS
broadcast news magazine ``48 Hours'' talked with administrators in
April about possibly featuring the school in an upcoming segment.
The premise would be to feature schools nationwide that are
producing academically successful students without radical changes
in teaching styles, class arrangements or program adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   Heritage has 1,303 students and 88 teachers. It is located on
the south side of Rockdale County in a community that is mostly
middle- and upper-middle class. Last year, its students earned an
American College Testing program composite score of 22.7 out of a
possible 36 points. That is 0.7 above the county average and 1.7
above the national average.
</P>
<P>
   The school's average Scholastic Assessment Test score for 1998
was 1014 _ 509 verbal, 505 math _ with 74 percent of students
taking the exam. Though three points below the national average,
the score was 46 points above the state average.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to stressing academics, Heritage offers students
vocational programs such as auto assembly and graphic arts. Next
year, the school will resurrect its horticulture program, which has
been on hold for four years because the school could not find a
teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Heritage, like Rockdale's other two high schools, has a
full-time resource officer from the Rockdale County Sheriff's
Department patrolling the grounds. Alaina Mitchell, 16, a junior at
Heritage, said students felt safe with that and other measures the
school had taken, including locking most doors and insisting that
visitors come to the front office first. She said students had also
taken a zero-tolerance stance against violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one person even said anything, even if they are just joking
around about hurting someone, we would jump all over them,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
