<HEADER>
A5263 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-LASTER21-COX     05-20 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-LASTER21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    First teen-ager's home burns, then bullet strikes
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONYERS, Ga. _ Stephanie Laster couldn't stop thinking about her
impending trip to Florida, where she and members of Haven
Fellowship Church were planning to do missionary work with troubled
teens in crime-ridden neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   But instead, the feisty 15-year-old sophomore from Heritage High
School sat in her bed at Hughes Spalding Childrens' Hospital late
Thursday afternoon, talking to her parents about the shattered day
at Heritage where one of her classmates shot six students.
</P>
<P>
   A year earlier, the family's mettle was tested when fire ravaged
their house in the Honey Creek neighborhood, said neighbor and
friend Steve Merritt. He spent most of Thursday at Hughes Spalding
with Stephanie, her parents Steve and Betty Laster, and her younger
sister, Kelsey, 12.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie was shot once in the buttocks, but the bullet traveled
through her colon and remained lodged in the teen's abdomen
Thursday evening. The injury posed no apparent danger to her
recovery or health, said Dr. Lynn Weaver, interim deputy chief of
staff at Grady Memorial Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The bullet was not removed because attempting to do so would
have caused more damage to the teen's abdominal area, Weaver said.
The teen, in stable condition, will remain at Hughes Spalding over
the next three to five days, Weaver said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie's Sunday school teacher got word of the shooting
minutes before boarding a Delta flight to Atlanta from
Jacksonville. After Wayne Seymour landed at Hartsfield
International Airport and went home to check on his two sons _ both
are students at Heritage _ he went to Grady to see about Stephanie.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart dropped when I heard Stephanie had been shot,'' said
Seymour. ``After I found out my own sons were OK, I wanted to be
here. Stephanie is one of the greatest kids you'll ever want to
meet. She does missionary work with our church, and she was really
looking forward to going down to Florida in a couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing Stephanie, she'll try to go anyway _ she's
strong-willed and determined.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Stephanie who helped keep her family going in the
aftermath of the fire that destroyed their home on March 2, 1998.
The Lasters had just gotten home from church that Sunday when they
noticed smoke seeping from under the garage door, Merritt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they opened the door, the flames were so huge they just
knocked everyone back,'' Merritt said. ``Everyone in the
neighborhood rallied around the family and tried to help them save
as much as they could, but most of their possessions were lost.
Stephanie and her mother just kept the family going with their
spirit and humor and willingness to do anything for the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Merritt, smiling and shaking his head, recounted Stephanie's
words as she awoke from her operation: ``She told me she remembered
falling on her face when she was hit. A few seconds later she said
she stood up, shook her head a bit and calmly said to another kid,
'You know, I think I may have been shot.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
