<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5268 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LOUIMA-COPS-NYT &LR;      05-20 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-COPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYPD'S `WALL OF SILENCE' CRUMBLES IN BRUTALITY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: With NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The wall of silence continues to crash down on Justin
Volpe.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, his fellow police officers have paraded to the
witness stand and offered vivid details in support of an awful
allegation _ that Volpe, in a sadistic rage, rammed a stick into
the rectum of a handcuffed Abner Louima.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring Volpe's angry stares, four officers in the past eight
days have held a jury rapt with chilling accounts of his words and
deeds the night Louima's insides were violated.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just holding it straight out,'' Officer Michael Schoer
said Thursday, describing how Volpe boastfully displayed an
excrement-covered stick.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Sgt. Kenneth Wernick described a similar
encounter, days after Detective Eric Turetzky described Volpe
``swinging the stick around like a sword.'' And Officer Mark
Schofield testified that Volpe borrowed a pair of gloves from him,
then returned them, covered in blood.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, the decision of the officers to testify may
suggest changing attitudes within a Police Department legendary for
its lack of tolerance for ``rats.'' But the testimony also revealed
a general reluctance to come forward immediately, sometimes for
fear of retribution or of being implicated, and sometimes out of a
sense of loyalty to colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Experts in police behavior speculate that the officers may have
eventually spoken up because of revulsion at the charges and
because of fear of being caught in a particularly sweeping
investigation by federal, as well as departmental, officials.
</P>
<P>
   Schoer testified Thursday that when he was first questioned by
investigators from the Police Department's internal affairs bureau,
he lied and withheld his damaging account of Volpe showing him a
two-foot stick.
</P>
<P>
   A month after the assault, when he met with federal
investigators to finally tell about the stick episode, Schoer said
he lied again. Presumably to explain his delay in coming forward,
he told investigators his wife had been threatened _ though this
was false.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared,'' he said. ``I panicked.''
</P>
<P>
   Wernick testified Thursday that he first learned about the
extent of Louima's injuries on Aug. 13, 1997, four days after
Louima was arrested. For days, he said nothing. On Aug. 21, he was
notified that he would have to give a statement to internal affairs
investigators. That night, he said, he finally told a police union
trustee what he knew about Volpe and asked for legal help.
</P>
<P>
   And Turetzky, who was hailed as a hero for being the first
officer to break the code of silence in the Louima case,
acknowledged that he, too, did not come forward until hours before
he was to be questioned by internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Schofield waited eight days to disclose the incident involving
the gloves, saying he was nervous about what would happen to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was concerned,'' he testified.
</P>
<P>
   ``About you, right?'' a defense lawyer asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' the officer answered.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe is one of five officers on trial on charges of violating
Louima's civil rights. He is specifically accused of thrusting a
broom stick or mop handle into Louima's rectum, while a
co-defendant, Officer Charles Schwarz, allegedly held Louima down.
Those two officers and two others, Thomas Wiese and Thomas Bruder,
are all accused of beating Louima in a police car before he was
taken to the station house. And a fifth defendant, Sgt. Michael
Bellomo, is accused of trying to cover up the events.
</P>
<P>
   But the four officers who are cooperating with federal
prosecutors have testified almost exclusively about Volpe, who
could be sentenced to life in prison if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   William Bratton, the New York police commissioner from 1994
until 1996, said the surprising spectacle of so many officers
testifying gives hope that the entrenched culture of secrecy is
weakening.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife Rikki, who's a defense attorney, and I were sitting
there having breakfast this morning and both of us were saying,
`What the hell is this?' '' Bratton said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, his optimism is tempered by the fact that the
officers were slow to come forward, despite the ``egregious''
nature of the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't see the walls of Jericho coming tumbling down
here, but some of the bricks are starting to weaken,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one veteran officer who is a police union delegate said
he was concerned that coercion may be playing a role in the
testimony against Volpe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope the testimony given by the cops is truthful,''
said the officer, who, like others, would talk only if his name was
not divulged. ``I hope people aren't being forced to give false
testimony because their jobs were threatened or because they worked
out some kind of deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Said another officer: ``These guys are willing to testify
because of the nature of the crime and because of pressure by the
department to talk. But you bet they aren't going to say they saw
Volpe do the deed in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been questioned before about this incident and they
are giving answers that don't go to the allegations per se, but to
the facts and circumstances surrounding them. And everyone is still
going to see them as rats.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Lynch, president of the John Jay College of Criminal
Justice, said studies have shown that the old culture of silence in
many police departments is giving way to a new ethos of openness
among a generation of better-educated, better-trained officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police officers with college degrees have fewer civilian
complaints, faster promotions and higher self-esteem,'' he said.
They also are more dissatisfied with their departments, he said,
and therefore more willing to challenge traditions that place
loyalty above accountability.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is that the wall of silence is being broken,''
Lynch said.
</P>
<P>
   He cited as one example Turetzky, who is currently taking
classes at John Jay College.
</P>
<P>
   Turetzky testified that he decided to cooperate with
investigators out of a sense of duty. He denied suggestions by
defense lawyers that he was motivated by any animosity toward
Volpe, who claimed credit for posting a disparaging caricature of
Turetzky in the 70th Precinct station house.
</P>
<P>
   Little is known about the motives of the other officers. Defense
lawyers declined the opportunity Thursday to cross-examine either
Wernick or Schoer. Marvyn Kornberg, a lawyer for Volpe, said
Thursday, ``I think before the case is over you'll understand why I
didn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it clear whether those who have broken the wall of
silence will be supported by their colleagues. On Thursday morning,
minutes before testimony was to resume, Wernick stood near the door
of the courtroom chatting with a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Just then, Volpe walked up and stopped but a few feet from
Wernick. For several seconds, he glared at the beefy sergeant, and
then he started to move closer still. One of his lawyers grabbed
him by the arm and pulled him into the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Wernick, occupied by his friend, didn't notice a thing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
