<HEADER>
A5269 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-SENIORS21-CO     05-20 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-SENIORS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Class `robbed' of rite of passage
 &HT;    By Jennifer Brett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONYERS, Ga. _ Ryan Freeman had three special pens ready to sign
yearbooks Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking forward to seeing everybody one last time,'' he
said. ``I was trying to dress nice and everything.''
</P>
<P>
   But not long after he put on his crisp Tommy Hilfiger polo
shirt, Freeman was watching his school on television as helicopters
circled overhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe it, we see our school, all these people
talking about Conyers, Georgia,'' he said. ``I saw Janet Reno say
`Heritage High School.'''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was the seniors' last day at Heritage High, and it was
supposed to be a day for penning farewell messages, sharing
memories and saying goodbye. Instead, the class of 1999 spent the
day coping with a shooting they say will stain their memories of
high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll remember it forever,'' Freeman said. ``Instead of
signing yearbooks, we're watching our school from helicopters.''
</P>
<P>
   Two hours after police had secured the school and blocked the
road leading to it, Freeman was getting gas at a station down the
road from Heritage. His hands shook as he demonstrated the stylish
signature he'd been practicing for his friends' yearbooks.
</P>
<P>
   Junior Kevi Hall, 16, wheeled into the parking lot and ran over
to Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard you got shot!'' she said, hugging him tightly.
</P>
<P>
   Hall and Krystle Graham, also a 16-year-old junior, said they
now want to finish high school as home schoolers rather than return
to Heritage this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might miss out on walking with my class or senior prom, but
at least you don't have to worry about getting shot,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   By a number of standards, Heritage High is the kind of school
parents want for their kids. Its average SAT score for 1998 was
1014 _ 46 points higher than the state average. Its graduation rate
was nearly 80 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   But the 250 students graduating May 28 said the shooting took
away a cherished rite of passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was going to be a special day, our last day as a high
school student,'' said Patrick Edwards, 18. ``I was looking forward
to signing yearbooks and saying goodbye to people.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he grieves for the shooting victims, and feels violated
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like they took my last day at Heritage,'' Edwards said.
``I feel like more than just my last day at Heritage has been
robbed. I feel like my safety's been robbed.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards was a place-kicker for the Heritage Patriots and is
angry that when he thinks back to his days on the field, the
shooting will inevitably creep into his memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely is an unfair way of having to leave,'' he said.
``It's not supposed to end this way.''
</P>
<P>
   Daven Cox, 18, had begun the day full of senior pride. He
eagerly displayed his class ring, engraved with his name, year and
an armed patriot, the school's mascot. Another patriot stands guard
in the center of the blue stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were just going to have fun today,'' Cox said. He
didn't even make it to school. By the time he neared the parking
lot, authorities were turning cars away, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy,'' he said. ``I didn't think it could happen at our
school.''
</P>
<P>
   Several seniors said that although more than 1,300 students
attend Heritage, the school manages to retain a community feeling.
They said the shooting was unbelievably out of sync with the school
they knew for four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always felt like it was a safe school,'' said Amy Arnold,
18. ``I've always felt safe going there.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, she's glad to be leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured there would be senior pranks, but nothing like
this,'' Arnold said. ``I have a little sister who goes to Sims
(Elementary School). It gives me a different outlook on her going
to middle school and high school. You turn on the TV and you see
stuff. You don't expect to see your own school.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
