<SLUG> BC-KOREA-SANCTIONS-930(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. OFFERING A DEAL TO END ECONOMIC BOYCOTT AGAINST NORTH KOREA 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton is sending an envoy to North
Korea next week with a proposal to gradually lift the 50-year-old
economic embargo against the country in exchange for several major
concessions, including an agreement that the North will end its
long-range missile program, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Several current and former administration officials expressed
doubts that North Korea would accept the limits on military
programs in the proposal, though an end to the sanctions would
allow the famine-scarred nation to trade with the West.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea's sales of missiles in the Middle East and to
Pakistan have constituted its only lucrative export in recent
years. And any agreement to lift some of the sanctions would be
subject to congressional approval, which would be an uphill battle.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the diplomatic overture represents the biggest change in
Washington's approach to North Korea since the Korean War ended in
1953. Since that conflict ended in stalemate _ no formal peace
treaty has ever been signed _ the United States has prohibited
virtually all trade, investment and travel and most communication
with the Communist nation.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time that the United States has made a
comprehensive proposal to lift those sanctions or offer the
prospect of full diplomatic recognition, a matter of prestige for
the isolated country that officials say the envoy, former Defense
Secretary William Perry, will raise during his visit.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials have declined to detail the contents of
the proposed deal that Perry is hoping to present in person to
North Korea's reclusive leader, Kim Jong-il.
</P>
<P>
   Perry's trip is the first time a presidential envoy has been
dispatched to the North, although former President Jimmy Carter
traveled there on his own to defuse a nuclear crisis in 1994. That
trip ultimately led to an agreement by the North to freeze its
nuclear weapons program, though American intelligence agencies
believe the North may already hold enough fissionable material to
produce one or two crude nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright announced Perry's visit on
Thursday in congressional testimony, confirming reports that had
circulated in Washington for several days. But she said nothing
about the offer to lift sanctions in return for concessions by Kim,
who has ruled North Korea since the death of his father, Kim
Il-sung, weeks after Carter's visit in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomatic visit culminates a six-month review of North
Korea policy that Perry began, at Clinton's request, after several
years of what even some administration insiders volunteer was a
dangerous neglect of the country. The timing of Perry's trip was
also closely linked to the start on Wednesday of the first American
inspection of a huge, mysterious construction project under a North
Korean mountain that American intelligence agencies feared was
originally intended to house a secret nuclear processing plant.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether Perry, who is carrying a letter from
Clinton, will ?? meet with Kim Jong-il, which he had suggested
earlier would be a precondition for a visit. ``We certainly hope to
meet with Kim Jong-il,'' a senior administration official said on
Thursday, suggesting that the North Koreans had provided winks and
nods that such a meeting is being arranged.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Perry persuades Kim that it is in North Korea's
interest to give up the weapons program and curb its behavior, it
is unclear that he can persuade Congress that a lifting of
sanctions is in America's interest.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives on Capital Hill have already charged that the
administration is pursuing a policy of appeasement. On Tuesday,
Rep. Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y., who leads the House Committee on
International Relations, introduced a bill he called the North
Korea Threat Reduction Act that would prohibit Clinton from lifting
the sanctions _ some of which are imposed at the discretion of the
president, others by congressional mandate _ and will make it
difficult to provide food aid to North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Perry has met with members of Congress, and on Thursday gave a
classified briefing to members of the Senate. He has also traveled
repeatedly in recent months to Japan, South Korea and China,
seeking their support for a new American approach.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction has been mixed: South Korea's president, Kim
Dae-jung, has pursued what he has called a ``Sunshine Policy'' of
fuller engagement with the North and urged the United States to do
the same. Japan has been far more cautious, especially after the
North shot a three-stage missile over Japan on Aug. 31, a test that
appeared intended to demonstrate that North Korea could hit any
Japanese city and the tens of thousands of American troops based in
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   What administration officials have declined to discuss is what
advisers around Perry call Plan B: How to respond if North Korea
decides not to trade its missile program for a gradual relaxation
of the American economic embargo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been the hardest part, and I think it is the issue
that has delayed the Perry report for so long,'' said Donald Gregg,
a former American ambassador to South Korea, and a CIA operative in
the region during the Cold War. ``To be credible, this plan has to
have a plan about how to deal with the North if they turn this
down. For a while it looked like the recommendation would be benign
neglect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it is clear,'' said Gregg, who now heads the Korea Society
in New York, ``that if we leave them alone, they go back to
building nuclear weapons and missiles.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In his few public comments while he has been putting together
recommendations for a new policy, Perry has said that he thought it
was important to ``test the proposition that North Korea wants a
more positive relationship'' with the United States, but to be
prepared to respond if it continues on its current path.
</P>
<P>
   That path has been erratic. In 1993 and 1994 the United States
and North Korea appeared veering toward a dangerous confrontation
that Perry, the defense secretary in those years, has since said
could have led to war. North Korea had taken steps that led
American officials to believe it was about to harvest a load of
plutonium at its nuclear facility at Yongbyon, north of Pyongyang,
the capital. Washington was prepared to seek sanctions at the
United Nations, a move North Korea had hinted could lead to
military reprisals.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was within hours of ordering additional troops to South
Korea when Carter visited Kim Il-sung, the country's founder and
its leader during the Korean War. He made the breakthrough that
ultimately led to a freeze of construction of North Korea's
Yongbyon nuclear reprocessing facility. Kim died the next month,
but the accord went ahead.
</P>
<P>
   In return for the freeze, Japan and South Korea agreed to build
two light-water reactors in North Korea for electricity production,
and Washington agreed to provide fuel oil to help the country
through its long winters. But Congress slowed those fuel shipments,
and the construction of the plants has moved very slowly; financing
is just now coming together.
</P>
<P>
   So last year North Korea resumed some classic provocations.
First there was the huge underground construction site. The
administration said little about it to Congress, and the
revelations about its existence in mid-August led to a storm of
congressional protests against Albright, who some members charged
had misled them. That was followed by the missile test over Japan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
