<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNSELING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Corporate Career Counseling
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Ilana DeBare &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Laura Orozco had been the No. 1 telephone salesperson in her
division of Sun Microsystems for almost two years, but she was
getting bored. She thought of leaving the company. She thought of
signing up for some career counseling sessions at a local
nonprofit.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Orozco took advantage of an unusual employee benefit
offered by Sun _ free on-site career counseling sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Orozco ended up staying with Sun and becoming a software project
coordinator. Two years later, she again used Sun's counseling
program to help navigate a move into project management.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without career counseling, I would have left the company for
sure,'' said Orozco, 32. ``But career services introduced me to
other people and other departments in Sun that I never would have
known about. They did everything from giving me a Meyers Briggs
skill test, to looking over my resume.''
</P>
<P>
   Sun, based in Palo Alto, is one of a handful of companies that
offer career counseling as a standard benefit for all their
employees.
</P>
<P>
   It's a gutsy move. Many firms shy away from it, worried that
freely available career counseling would simply help their best
employees jump ship for new and better jobs elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But Sun officials say the program _ which provides individual
counseling to about 250 people each month _ actually helps them
hold on to workers in today's tight labor market.
</P>
<P>
   Sun has found that attrition among employees who use career
counseling is about three percentage points lower than among those
who don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We in Silicon Valley are all competing for the same dwindling
talent pool, so you need to have programs to keep employees in the
organization.'' said Carol Guterman, career services program
manager for Sun. ``If our career program can stop one employee a
month from leaving the company, we're saving the company money.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, there was little need for the kind of
sophisticated career-development programs now offered by Sun and
firms like Pacific Bell, Hewlett-Packard and IBM.
</P>
<P>
   Companies sometimes offered counseling to small groups of
laid-off employees as part of an outplacement program. But most
firms simply assumed that workers could figure out their own path
through the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``There used to be very clear-cut career ladders, where you
could look on a chart and see where you were supposed to go _ from
Analyst 1, to Analyst 2, to Analyst 3,'' said John Parkington, an
organizational effectiveness consultant with Watson Wyatt in San
Francisco. ``That's pretty much vanished. I don't know any
companies in North America that are building career ladders these
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, with companies constantly merging and changing, many
employees realize they have to draw their own personalized career
map.
</P>
<P>
   And a growing number of employers provide some limited kinds of
career help _ software programs to assess people's skills, for
instance, or occasional workshops on career issues.
</P>
<P>
   But sustained and individualized programs like the one at Sun
remain very uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Human resource folks are ambivalent about whether they can
sell these programs to senior management because the payoff isn't
easy to demonstrate,'' said Parkington. ``And some people say,
`Jeez, if we give counseling to people to enhance their careers,
they'll just bug out.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sun's program grew out of a temporary counseling center put in
place during a period of layoffs in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 18 months, there was no need for outplacement, but
someone had the foresight to change it into an `inplacement'
center,'' Guterman said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Sun offers four free career counseling sessions a year to
all of its 27,000 workers, as well as other services like brown-bag
workshops on career issues.
</P>
<P>
   About 8 percent of Sun's employees use the career services in
any given year.
</P>
<P>
   Counseling sessions are confidential and employees don't need to
inform their managers that they've signed up.
</P>
<P>
   The counselors are outside experts from the nonprofit Career
Action Center who work at Sun on a long-term contract basis _ an
arrangement that allows them to remain independent of the company
while developing an insider's knowledge of Sun's structure and
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked them to go into a site, set up their office as if it
were their own private practice, and get to know that division and
the way the organization works,'' Guterman said.
</P>
<P>
   Other Bay Area companies offering significant career-development
benefits include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Pacific Bell, which has five full-time career specialists who
last year provided 1,224 counseling sessions as well as various
workshops. Pacific Bell launched its program in 1989 in response to
a request by the Communications Workers of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The union wanted us to help employees deal with the reality of
change in the telecommunication industry, assessing and developing
people's skills so they could find the right career path,'' said
Joan Massola, state manager of the company's career development
centers.
</P>
<P>
   _ IBM, which has offered individual career counseling at in &LR; its
various locations since the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hewlett-Packard, which doesn't have a large individual
counseling program but has made ``career self-reliance'' a major
corporate goal since 1994. HP's program relies mainly on periodic
workshops and on a career-assessment software program called
CareerSteps, which has been used by 6,000 of the firm's 126,000
employees since it was installed in February.
</P>
<P>
   The software is ``an inexpensive way for an employee to do a lot
of assessment,'' said Lauren Martin Brown, who oversees HP's career
education efforts. ``It doesn't have the experience or wisdom that
a career counselor does. But this is the closest most of our people
will ever get to having a career counselor, and the closest we want
to come as a company to having counselors.''
</P>
<P>
   At Sun, counselors help employees grapple with a wide range of
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Recent college grads want to know how to plan their careers.
Other new hires want help figuring out the structure of Sun.
</P>
<P>
   Mid-career employees want to get out of a career rut, or switch
from engineering into marketing. Employees of all kinds come in for
help in improving their interview skills or retooling their
resumes.
</P>
<P>
   The counselors occasionally find themselves in the touchy
situation of talking with an employee who wants to leave Sun. If
the worker's career goals really require him or her to leave, the
counselors will support that decision.
</P>
<P>
   But those cases are surprisingly rare.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Sun is a large enough organization that many
employees manage to change careers while remaining with the
company.
</P>
<P>
   For another thing, employees who are determined to leave often
don't stop to talk to the counselors.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the people who are going to leave are head-hunted and
don't need us,'' said counselor Linda Artel. ``The people who come
to see us tend to like the company and want to stay. One reason
they come to us is to find a way to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Braham, 39, is a Sun manager who not only uses the
counseling program himself but enrolled his entire team in a career
workshop. Two-thirds of his 28 employees have gotten individual
career counseling.
</P>
<P>
   On a personal level, Braham says that counseling taught him to
network more effectively _ a skill useful to his work at Sun as
well as his own career.
</P>
<P>
   As a manager, Braham says the career program has created more
motivated and loyal employees. His employees know what their goals
are and understand how their work fits in with those goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only one of my people has left Sun in 2-1/2 years,'' he said.
``One reason is that they feel they can achieve their personal
ambitions working here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
