<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: 3 OPTIONS FOR WASHINGTON, ALL WITH MAJOR RISKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Encumbered by some testy NATO partners and by a
desire to wrap up the war over Serbia, the Clinton administration
faces several unpleasant options under the pressure of a looming
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the White House on Thursday, President Clinton insisted
again that the NATO air campaign was working and asked the nation
and Congress to be patient. His message was repeated in Washington
by British Foreign Minister Robin Cook.
</P>
<P>
   But hours later, the supreme NATO commander, Gen. Wesley Clark,
warned military chiefs in a briefing complete with color slides
that he could not guarantee that air power alone would force
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia to capitulate.
</P>
<P>
   With no breakthrough in sight in the diffuse diplomatic efforts
and no discernible triumph on the horizon, administration officials
said they had three choices, to press forward on the current
course, to increase significantly the air assaults or to persuade
the alliance that preparations should begin for ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Any decision to prepare ground troops, most likely to oversee
the repatriation of refugees, has to be taken in a few weeks if the
force is to be ready by winter, NATO officials said. An initial
deployment of troops would also send a useful message to Milosevic,
the NATO officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all options are mutually exclusive. But all include
considerable political hazards, including further fracturing of the
alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel something has to give,'' an administration
official said of the atmosphere at NATO. ``They feel they have to
have a military breakthrough or a diplomatic breakthrough. Everyone
is tired of this. Maybe we're getting to the first stage in
changing the strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   An important point in the diplomacy was supposed to have
occurred Thursday in Moscow, when Russian envoy Victor Chernomyrdin
reported to Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott on his meeting
Wednesday in Belgrade with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin's session with Milosevic was the first in several
weeks, and it was conducted after Milosevic had been assumed to
have ``stewed a bit,'' as one diplomat described it, about the NATO
air strikes. Talbott had spent hours with Chernomyrdin in Helsinki
to prepare him to present the allies' point of view to Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Although Chernomyrdin suggested in Moscow that there had been
some forward motion, a senior administration official here said it
was ``totally unclear'' whether Milosevic was prepared to move
toward accepting the NATO demands.
</P>
<P>
   A European diplomat who has dealt frequently with Milosevic said
Thursday that the diplomatic track with Russians as mediators with
the Yugoslav leader was akin to ``crawling,'' and would take
``many, many weeks to get anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who wanted an exit through diplomacy, the exit is
quite a way off, the diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   The air campaign, set back by the mistaken bombing of the
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade nearly two weeks ago, picked up steam
again this week with heavy strikes against the capital.
</P>
<P>
   But a bomb went astray early Thursday and hit a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, a senior administration official said again Thursday
that the assaults were beginning to hurt the Yugoslav army.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping up the air campaign could lead to several results that
the White House has been at pains to avoid. The first is increased
risk to U.S. pilots, who are flying most of the sorties. No U.S.
pilots have been killed.
</P>
<P>
   The second problem is the greater risk of killing additional
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. public opinion has become more sensitive to the killing of
civilians by NATO bombers, and support for the air war has dropped,
although several polls indicate that most Americans continue to
support the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, some senators said this week that the
increasing civilian deaths had prompted them to support a bombing
pause.
</P>
<P>
   That suggestion was also vigorously put forward Thursday by
Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema of Italy, the second-largest
supplier of NATO air power.
</P>
<P>
   The option that the administration appears most reluctant to
choose is persuading the alliance to hasten preparations for ground
troops as an international security force in postwar Kosovo.
Britain has strongly argue for preparations. Germany, most of all,
opposes using any ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has ruled out an invasion force, but has agreed
that U.S. soldiers should be part of any security force that would
help repatriate the hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanian
refugees after the bombing has stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Such a force would need to be 48,000 troops, the Pentagon said
this week, much more than the 28,000 estimated before the war
started. Given that the administration had agreed that 4,700
Americans would participate in a force of 28,000, 6,500 Americans
would be deployed for the larger force, officials estimated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our inclination would be we need to move forward with it, so
we are in a maximum position to be ready,'' a senior administration
official said of the security force.
</P>
<P>
   But he declined to estimate a timeline for such a buildup. The
official stressed that NATO had not yet asked member countries how
many troops or what categories they would be prepared to
contribute.
</P>
<P>
   But that cautious approach _ deploying ground troops as
peacekeepers, and not as a threat to Milosevic _ is causing ever
more frustration at NATO headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look what the Americans are doing,'' said an American NATO
planner. ``Trudging down the same difficult track, which is getting
stonier and stonier. The administration keeps hoping Milosevic will
break before they do.''
</P>
<P>
   There was still a belief at NATO headquarters that jibed with
the White House view, that if the air campaign continued long
enough, the allies would prevail.
</P>
<P>
   But what then, asked the American NATO planner, adding, ``You've
ended up with a desert in Kosovo _ a totally collapsed structure _
and you still have Milosevic in power.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
