<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5281 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON &LR;      05-20 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Moving Temp Firms May Not Pay
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Ilana DeBare &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I have been working as a temp for a small business on
one or two afternoons a week. After two months, I asked my
employment agency for a raise but they declined. I work through
several agencies and know that they all have different pay scales.
If I can get another agency to pay me $2 or $3 more than my current
agency, can I ask the employer to switch to the agency of my
choice?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  Switching agencies could end up boosting your pay, but
it may be more complicated than you think.
</P>
<P>
   Most temp agencies want to hold on to the workers they've
recruited. They cast a cold eye on ``temp-napping'' by rival
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   So some agencies require their client companies to sign
contracts limiting the kind of interagency switch you're
considering. Or they require client firms to pay hefty fees in
order to hire a temp permanently _ fees that might apply in your
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Your boss should read through his or her contract with the temp
agency to see if there are any limits on hiring you through another
agency.
</P>
<P>
   If the contract doesn't present any legal problems, go ahead and
make the move. More temp workers should follow your lead and look
at whether the wages they're getting paid are competitive.
</P>
<P>
   But keep a couple of things in mind: You probably won't be
welcomed back with open arms in the future by the agency you're
leaving.
</P>
<P>
   And the income you gain may be less than you imagine. Several
temp industry managers told me it's unusual to see a wage spread of
$2 or $3 for the same clerical job with the same employer. (On the
other hand, it's not uncommon to see a significant wage gap when
doing similar work for different employers because the employers
are billed at different rates.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be very surprised if it's a $2 or $3 difference,''
said Jill Gruber, vice president of branch operations at Westaff, a
temporary staffing firm in Walnut Creek. ``The market tends to keep
wages competitive. Typically, the difference between agencies is
less than $1.''
</P>
<P>
   Switching Visas
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am a native of India who arrived in the United States this
spring on an H-4 visa. I'm living with my husband, who is a
computer programmer with an H-1B visa. I have a three-year
bachelor's degree in business from India, along with one year of
computer training, and I now am studying to get an MBA. I'd like to
work while I finish my studies so that my husband doesn't have to
bear all the financial burden. But the H-4 visa doesn't allow me to
hold a job. What can I do?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Your husband has an H-1B visa, which is a temporary work
visa for skilled professionals. You have an H-4 visa, which allows
spouses and children of H-1B visa holders to live here but not work
here.
</P>
<P>
   There are two different ways you could seek a legal OK to work,
according to Los Angeles immigration attorney Carl Shusterman.
</P>
<P>
   One way would be to switch to an F-1 student visa because you're
apparently enrolled in business school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students have permission to work at some on-campus jobs right
away and to work at some other kinds of off-campus jobs after nine
months,'' Shusterman said.
</P>
<P>
   The other option is to apply for an H-1B visa yourself.
Typically, the government limits H-1B visas to people with
bachelor's degrees. So you'd have to demonstrate that your
three-year degree combined with other training or work experience
amounts to the equivalent of a bachelor's degree in this country.
</P>
<P>
   There are some hurdles with this approach. Because H-1B
applicants must be sponsored by an employer, you'd need to line up
a job before you actually could apply for a visa. And the annual
quota of H-1B visas has been handed out already for this year so
you'd have to wait until the start of the new fiscal year, in
October 1999, to have your application processed.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to pursue an H-1B visa, you should talk to an
experienced immigration attorney. To find out if you're eligible
for a student visa, talk to the foreign student adviser at your
school.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, you can find a detailed description of the
different kinds of visas on Shusterman's Web site at
 &LR; www.shusterman.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Overtime Conundrum
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am a buyer in a manufacturing concern who is paid on a
salary rather than hourly basis. For the third time in recent
months, I've been asked to come in for mandatory weekend work. Can
I demand overtime pay for this? They're treating me as an exempt
employee, but I think they may be wrong because I don't supervise
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: You may be legally exempt from overtime even if you don't
supervise anyone, under what is called the ``administrative''
exemption from overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The California Employer Advisor newsletter in Tiburon publishes
a good guidebook summing up the rules for overtime exemption. To
qualify for an administrative exemption in California, it says,
workers must:
</P>
<P>
   _ Spend 50 percent or more of their work time on tasks involving
the exercise of ``discretion and independent judgment in the
performance of intellectual work.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Have decision-making power over ``matters of consequence'' to
the company.
</P>
<P>
   _ Assist an owner, manager or other exempt administrator.
</P>
<P>
   _ Work under general rather than close supervision.
</P>
<P>
   _ Earn at least $1,150 per month.
</P>
<P>
   As a buyer, you may meet these criteria if you have the
authority to make significant decisions about purchasing _ even if
you don't supervise a single soul. The answer really lies in the
details of your particular job and how much responsibility you're
given.
</P>
<P>
   Want more information on the rules for exemption? Check with the
California Labor Commissioner's office at (415) 557-7878, or call
the Employment Law Center, which offers free legal advice to
low-income workers, at (415) 864-8208.
</P>
<P>
   Employers also may find it worthwhile to order the CEA exemption
guidebook for $34 from (800) 695-7178 or  &LR; www.employeradvice.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways, San
Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco 94103. Or send
e-mail to workways(at sign)sfgate.com. &LR;   &LR; Or call (415) 764-2815. We
can't respond to each query, but we will answer as many in print as
we can. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
