<HEADLINE>
FOX WILL HAVE MORE CONVENTIONAL FARE NEXT SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reality bites the dust.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not exactly. But Fox next fall will be cutting back on
``reality-based'' series in favor of more conventional fare. The
network on Thursday unveiled eight new series _ five dramas and
three comedies _ along with plans to shuffle five other shows to
new time slots.
</P>
<P>
   One of the newcomers, ``Time of Your Life,'' has Jennifer Love
Hewitt in a spinoff of ``Party of Five.'' One of the comedies,
currently titled ``Ally,'' is a blenderization by David E. Kelley
of previously filmed scenes from ``Ally McBeal.''
</P>
<P>
   The shows getting new slots are ``King of the Hill'' and
``Futurama,'' both moving to Sunday; ``That '70s Show'' and ``Party
of Five,'' both switching to Tuesday; and ``Family Guy,'' to
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A summary of Fox's new fall series:
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm in the Middle. A comedy about a 9-year-old kid from a
dysfunctional family who turns out to be a genius.
</P>
<P>
   Time of Your Life. Jennifer Love Hewitt's Sarah Reeves leaves
San Francisco, searching for answers to her mysterious past. She
winds up in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Ally. If an hour's worth of ``Ally McBeal'' is too much (or if
you just can't get enough), this half-hour compilation of unused
and previously seen footage from ``Ally McBeal'' is the answer to
your prayers.
</P>
<P>
   Get Real. Hourlong drama about a family of six trying to keep it
together under one roof. Debrah Farentino (the mom), Jon Tenney
(the dad) and Christina Pickles (the grandma) are the adults trying
to stay a step ahead of Meghan, Cameron and Kenny.
</P>
<P>
   Manchester Prep. Think ``Dynasty, the Teen Years.'' It's all
about ``sex, scandal and betrayal'' among the teenage elite of New
York's Upper East Side, centered on a love-hate relationship
between a boy and his new stepsister.
</P>
<P>
   Action. A half-hour satire of the movie business, starring Jay
Mohr and Illeana Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Caulfield. One-hour drama about a 19-year-old Philadelphian
who turns down a college scholarship to join the police force. Sean
Maher stars as Ryan Caulfield, who still lives at home with his
mom. Mary McDonnell co-stars as Ryan's mom, Rachel.
</P>
<P>
   Harsh Realm. Chris Carter, creator of ``The X-Files,'' combines
action-adventure with sci-fi in this drama based on a series of
comic books. Seattle resident Scott Bairstow stars as a soldier
fighting for his life in a world where reality and virtual reality
are indistinguishable. D.B. Sweeney plays a ``virtual'' guy named
Mike Pinnochio.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Murphy's animated sitcom ``The PJs'' isn't on the fall
schedule, but Fox has placed a full order of 22 episodes and plans
to return it to the schedule in midseason. The network also has the
newsmagazine ``Fox Files'' on the bench, along with two new dramas,
``Dark Angel,'' a sci-fi drama from James ``Titanic'' Cameron, and
``The Opposite Sex,'' about an all-girls prep school gone co-ed,
plus a new comedy, ``Titus,'' starring comedian Chris Titus.
</P>
<P>
   Here is Fox's prime-time lineup for next fall, with new series
in bold type (times listed are Seattle time):
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   7-7:30 p.m.: ``Malcolm in the Middle''
</P>
<P>
   7:30-8 p.m.: ``King of the Hill''
</P>
<P>
   8-8:30 p.m.: ``The Simpsons''
</P>
<P>
   8:30-9 p.m.: ``Futurama''
</P>
<P>
   9-10 p.m.: ``The X-Files''
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY
</P>
<P>
   8-9 p.m.: ``Time of Your Life''
</P>
<P>
   9-10 p.m.: ``Ally McBeal''
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY
</P>
<P>
   8-8:30 p.m.: ``Ally''
</P>
<P>
   8:30-9 p.m.: ``That '70s Show''
</P>
<P>
   9-10 p.m.: ``Party of Five''
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY
</P>
<P>
   8-9 p.m.: ``Beverly Hills, 90210''
</P>
<P>
   9-10 p.m.: ``Get Real''
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY
</P>
<P>
   8-9 p.m.: ``Manchester Prep''
</P>
<P>
   9-9:30 p.m.: ``Family Guy''
</P>
<P>
   9:30-10 p.m. ``Action''
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   8-9 p.m.: ``Ryan Caulfield''
</P>
<P>
   9-10 p.m.: ``Harsh Realm''
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   8-8:30 p.m.: ``Cops''
</P>
<P>
   8:30-9 p.m.: ``Cops''
</P>
<P>
   9-10 p.m.: ``America's Most Wanted: America Fights Back''
</P>
<P>
   Series from Fox's 1998-99 schedule that won't be back next fall:
</P>
<P>
   Brimstone
</P>
<P>
   Costello
</P>
<P>
   Getting Personal
</P>
<P>
   Guinness World Records:
</P>
<P>
   Primetime
</P>
<P>
   Fox Files (will return in midseason)
</P>
<P>
   Holding the Baby
</P>
<P>
   Living in Captivity
</P>
<P>
   Melrose Place
</P>
<P>
   Millennium
</P>
<P>
   The PJs (will return in midseason)
</P>
<P>
   The World's Funniest
</P>
<P>
   World's Wildest Police Videos
</P>
