<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5286 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-FEARYEAR21-C     05-20 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-FEARYEAR21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Students have endured a year of fear
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick, Bo Emerson and Jeffry Scott
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Graduation can't come soon enough for Stephen
Hendriks, a Chamblee High senior who's ``unbelievably sad'' that
the fun of high school has been gunned down by shootings, threats
of other violence and a fearful, suspicious atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're glad to escape from high school and run away from all
these problems,'' the 18-year-old said Thursday after news spread
of the latest school shooting, in Rockdale County. ``Most kids just
want to get out and start out next year with a clean slate, and
maybe this stuff won't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Frazzled principals, teachers and parents, too, say they need a
summer break badly to reduce anxiety levels that have built since
the shootings a month ago at Columbine High in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all ready for a vacation,'' said Charlie Henderson,
principal at Clarkston High. ``We haven't had any problems here,
not any, but still we're more aware that these kinds of things can
happen, and you have to be worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just say that everybody will be relieved to see this year
end.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not just the news of shootings that has people on edge.
Since the Columbine shootings, many schools have had to endure
their own bomb threats and emergency drills. Students have been
suspended for statements that might have been seen as jokes before.
</P>
<P>
   Chamblee High has installed surveillance cameras. Walton High in
east Cobb has rigged 72 doors to open only from the inside. Decatur
High requires students to take bathroom breaks in a group.
</P>
<P>
   Recent tornado alerts in many metro school districts added
another layer of tension. So this may be the tensest end of the
school year since the height of the Cold War, when air raid sirens
often blared, preparing students for handling a nuclear attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were slow to accept that school may not be the safest place
for our children,'' said Chamblee Principal Dianne Clark. ``I never
dreamed this kind of thing would dominate. Never in my wildest
dreams did I think we would ever be concerned about such things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been on heightened alert for the last month,'' said
Walton Principal John Flatt. ``We are constantly updating our
security plans. We're urging students and parents and teachers to
constantly keep their eyes and ears open.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is looking, sensitive to any change in personality,
change in dress, that kind of thing,'' said Dr. Barbara Wideman, a
psychologist who works for the Cobb County school system. ``All
over Cobb, the administrators and teachers are in the halls,
looking and listening.''
</P>
<P>
   Which means students must cope with extra supervision _ and
suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   Decatur High received three bomb threats last week, prompting
evacuations. ``They've got the school on lockdown,'' said Travis
Adle, a senior at Decatur.
</P>
<P>
   But Travis and his friends approve of the restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are extreme measures,'' says junior Ron Crane. ``But
(bomb threats) are messing with our education.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all looking around a little bit more,'' said Jennifer
Turner, a 16-year-old junior at Wheeler High School in Cobb. ``All
this trouble has added stress to the end of the year, which is
stressful anyway. Definitely, we don't want to be here anymore, and
not just because summer is coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor do the jitters always end when the school day does.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other day, I was in Captain D's. I sat down with my
husband, and I was looking around to see where the exits are,''
said Laura McGraw, whose son Devin attends Walton. ``Everybody
seems sensitive to what is being said now.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody feels the same fear. Some seem to have become numb
to the threats.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we heard about the (Rockdale) shooting, we thought it was
no big deal because nobody got killed,'' said Brandi Burton,15, a
freshman at Jonesboro High School.
</P>
<P>
   And, though Thursday's shooting touched metro Atlanta, others
still see the shootings as distant events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work at a Catholic school and my children both go to a
Catholic school,'' said Eileen Maron of Decatur. ``Maybe I'm naive,
and I don't feel like this could happen to my children. There's
something special about Catholic school that I feel like protects
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Still others avoid worry by adopting a fatalistic attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to school every day,'' said Jonathan Rohan, a junior at
East Coweta High School. ``If I get shot, that's just what happens.
I'm probably in more risk driving from home to school than I am of
being blown up anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   More commonly, though, students, parents and teachers deeply
feel the recent events.
</P>
<P>
   Katie Garrett said the events of the last month ``took some of
the excitement out of finally being king of the hill'' for her son
Matt, a senior at Newnan High.
</P>
<P>
   Now she is counting the days until her children are out of
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be glad when it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hendriks, the Chamblee senior: ``A lot of students are
saying, 'Maybe this summer this will blow a lot of frustrations
over, and people will come back rejuvenated, not hurting. I come to
school to learn.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's frustration, sadness and despair, all due to all
the stuff that's happened. No one can say it hasn't influenced them
in some way.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
