<HEADLINE>
LATE SELL-OFF IN COMPUTER ISSUES PULL DOW DOWN 20.65
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A late sell-off in Internet and other computer-related stocks
helped drag down major stock-market averages Thursday, erasing
modest gains that had prevailed for most of the session.
</P>
<P>
   Yet analysts were generally upbeat, pointing out that advances
outnumbered declines by nearly a 3-2 margin on the New York Stock
Exchange and to some normal jitters over the expiration Friday of
stock and index options.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is that the bulk of it was unwinding'' before the
expirations, said Alfred E. Goldman, chief market strategist at AG
Edwards, referring to a final-hour swoon that left the Nasdaq
composite index with a loss of 35.17 points, or 1.36 percent,
closing at 2,542.23.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts noted another solid advance by smaller stocks,
with the Standard &AMP; Poor's small-cap index climbing 1.06 percent
into positive territory for the year and to the highest level since
Jan. 11. The Russell 2000, a similar gauge, climbed just over
four-tenths of 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a healthier market for having broadened out'' beyond
big-cap growth stocks in the past several weeks, said Larry
Wachtel, market analyst at Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   And investor appetite remained ravenous for the latest Internet
company to go public. The shares of EToys Inc., priced late
Wednesday at 20, soared as high as 85 before ending the day at 76
9/16.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, up nearly 59 points in
midmorning, traded narrowly before a late slump left it with a loss
of 20.65 points, or nearly two-tenths of 1 percent, to close at
10,866.74.
</P>
<P>
   IBM was the biggest casualty, falling three, to 232 7/8,
followed by Alcoa and United Technologies, down 2 11/16, to 58 5/16
and 2 9/16 to 63 1/16, respectively. Pacing the gainers were
Procter &AMP; Gamble, ahead by 1 11/16 to 96 11/16, followed by Merck,
up 1}, to 72\, and Johnson &AMP; Johnson, up 1 5/8 to 95. Two other
drug stocks, Warner Lambert and Schering Plough, also gained after
word they were discussing a merger.
</P>
<P>
   High-technology stocks were broadly lower, with Amazon.com down
8}, to 130 13/16, Ebay 10 3/16 to 186 5/8, Dell 1 9/16 to 38\,
Intel 2, to 57 11/16, Texas Instruments three, to 114 3/8 and
Microsoft 7/8, to 78 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange volume eased to a moderate 752.3
million shares from 767.7 million on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
