<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPPER-SCHEME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERRILL CHARGED WITH 2ND FIRM IN COPPER CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal regulators filed a lawsuit Thursday against Global
Minerals and Metals Corp., a Manhattan commodities merchant, and
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., the investment firm, contending that the two
companies took part in an illegal scheme to manipulate world copper
prices in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, lawyers at the Commodity Futures Trading
Commission said executives at Global Minerals had conspired with a
rogue copper trader at Sumitomo Corp., the large Japanese trading
company, to illegally corner the copper market in a scheme that
fell apart in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The commission charged Merrill Lynch with knowingly aiding and
abetting Global Minerals and Sumitomo in the conspiracy. Merrill
Lynch provided the two companies with a trading account and more
than $500 million of financing and lines of credit, the regulators
said in their court complaint. Merrill Lynch executives knew that
the two companies were using the trading account to buy up much of
the world's copper supply, the regulators said, and withhold it
from the market to artificially inflate its price.
</P>
<P>
   The regulators said that Merrill Lynch had profited from aiding
the two companies in the scheme by making its own trades on the
copper market as the price rose. The investment firm's profits on
those trades were ``in the millions of dollars,'' said a lawyer who
has been briefed on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill denied the commission's charges Thursday, saying the
allegations had no merit. The firm said in a written statement that
its business transactions with Sumitomo ``were conducted in a
commercially reasonable fashion and were fully visible to the
regulators at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Merrill Lynch had no knowledge that the conduct of Sumitomo,
one of the world's largest companies, was unlawful,'' the statement
said, ``and Merrill Lynch had no intention to render assistance to
any conduct that was improper.''
</P>
<P>
   And, H. Peter Haveles Jr., a lawyer for Global Minerals, said
the regulators' complaint was ``based on an `Alice in Wonderland'
view of the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Haveles said regulators in London, where most of the copper
trades took place, had been fully informed of the company's
activities at the time. The company is confident, he said, that the
administrative law judge that hears the case will conclude that
Global Minerals and its executives did nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   If the judge decides that the regulators' charges are true, the
companies could be fined as much as triple the amount they gained
from any illegal transactions and could be ordered to pay
restitution for any damages that occurred.
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, Sumitomo settled charges that U.S. commodities
regulators brought against it by agreeing to pay $150 million in
fines and restitution. Sumitomo settled without acknowledging or
denying the regulators' charges.
</P>
<P>
   Sumitomo's copper trader, Yasuo Hamanaka, pleaded guilty to
criminal charges in Japan in 1997 and is serving an eight-year
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Hamanaka, who became known in the commodities world as
``Copper,'' bought huge positions in both physical copper and
contracts for its future delivery. Capitalizing on weak disclosure
rules, he was able to buy and sell and confuse other traders about
the true size of his copper holdings and thus about the real global
demand. Most of the trading occurred on the London Metal Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the trades ran up the price of copper. But when the
scheme collapsed in the spring of 1996, Sumitomo still had large
positions in the copper market and lost $2.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In their lawsuit Thursday, regulators provided more details on
how Hamanaka worked to corner the world's copper market. They said
that the trader and R. David Campbell, a New York resident, had
talked between 1989 and 1992 about how they could manipulate the
price of copper to their mutual advantage.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the regulators said, in the spring of 1993,
Campbell helped create a new copper trading company, Global
Minerals and Metals. Campbell and Hamanaka then agreed to a series
of copper supply contracts, the regulators said, in which Global
would sell and Sumitomo would buy physical copper in large
quantities.
</P>
<P>
   Because Global was a ``start-up copper merchant,'' it was unable
to get credit lines large enough for the huge copper trades that
were needed to corner the market, the regulators said. But in April
1994, a managing director at Merrill Lynch solved this problem, the
regulators said, by devising a plan where Sumitomo and Global
opened an account in the name of Sumitomo. Global was given the
authority to trade on that account, which was backed by Sumitomo's
credit, the regulators said.
</P>
<P>
   The regulators said that Merrill Lynch employees knew what the
two companies were trying to do. The regulators said that Global's
chief copper trader, Carl Alm, had discussed strategies with a
Merrill Lynch employee, Martyn Phillips. ``Alm and Phillips
frequently executed trading strategies designed to tighten supply
and increase price,'' court papers said.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators charged both Campbell and Alm with helping Global
carry out the illegal trades.
</P>
<P>
   An executive at Merrill Lynch who agreed to talk on the
condition of anonymity said there was nothing unusual in giving
$500 million of financing to a company of Sumitomo's size, or in
allowing Global, its business partner, to execute trades on the
account.
</P>
<P>
   In its statement, Merrill Lynch said that it had fully
cooperated with the regulators' three-year investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merrill Lynch is extremely disappointed that despite the
substantial factual record developed, the commission has decided to
institute this proceeding,'' the statement said.
</P>
</TEXT>
