<HEADLINE>
HARD TO UNDERSTAND SOME OF UPN'S MOVES FOR FALL SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hard to figure where UPN is going these days. But it sure makes
for interesting copy.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the viewer-starved network announced a fall
prime-time schedule that includes five new series, but it also
canceled the animated series ``Home Movies,'' its most interesting
new comedy in years.
</P>
<P>
   Among the newcomers are three comedies, a drama and a weekly,
two-hour helping of fake wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   A rundown on UPN's new series:
</P>
<P>
   Mo'Nique. Half-hour comedy spinoff of ``Moesha,'' featuring
Countess Vaughn in the role of Moesha's friend, Kim Parker.
Mo'nique, played by stand-up comic Mo'Nique, is Kim's mom, who
decides it's time to go back to school, much to Kim's dismay. Best
character name: Probably Mo'Nique, no?
</P>
<P>
   The Grown Ups. Jaleel White (Urkel of ``Family Matters'') plays
Calvin Frazier, regional vice president of a corrugated-box
company. While hoping his new title serves as a babe magnet, he
lives with a woman who thinks he's gay. Best character name:
Marcus, Calvin's arch rival.
</P>
<P>
   Shasta McNasty. The title alone is worth at least one visit.
``Shasta McNasty'' is a sitcom, and it's the name of a fictional
hip-hop group made up of three guys _ Ran, Dennis and Scott (Dale
Goldboldo, Jake Busey and Carmine Giovinazzo) _ who live together
in Venice Beach. Despite their success, they continue to act in the
manner of typical slacker bachelors. Best character name: Can't
beat Shasta McNasty.
</P>
<P>
   Secret Agent Man. A throwback to ``Man from U.N.C.L.E.'' days
from the makers of ``Men in Black,'' featuring a trio of agents
working for a government agency that monitors high-stakes global
espionage. Costas Mandylor, Dondre Whitfield and Dina Meyer star.
Best character name: Monk, played by Mandylor.
</P>
<P>
   WWF Smackdown! The World Wrestling Federation comes to network
TV. Best character name: With the likes of Stone Cold Steve Austin,
The Undertaker and The Rock, the WWF is nothing but weird names.
</P>
<P>
   Here is UPN's prime-time lineup for next fall, with new shows in
bold (times listed are Seattle time):
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY
</P>
<P>
   8-8:30 p.m.: ``Moesha''
</P>
<P>
   8:30-9 p.m.: ``Mo'Nique''
</P>
<P>
   9-9:30 p.m.: ``The Grown Ups''
</P>
<P>
   9:30-10 p.m.: ``Malcolm &AMP; Eddie''
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY
</P>
<P>
   8-8:30 p.m.: ``Dilbert''
</P>
<P>
   8:30-9 p.m.: ``Shasta McNasty''
</P>
<P>
   9-10 p.m.: ``Secret Agent Man''
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY
</P>
<P>
   8-9 p.m.: ``7 Days''
</P>
<P>
   9-10 p.m.: ``Star Trek: Voyager''
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY
</P>
<P>
   8-10 p.m.: ``WWF Smackdown!''
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   8-10 p.m.: ``Blockbuster Video's Shockwave Cinema''
</P>
<P>
   Series from UPN's 1998-99 schedule that won't be back next fall:
</P>
<P>
   America's Greatest Pets
</P>
<P>
   Between Brothers
</P>
<P>
   Clueless
</P>
<P>
   DiResta
</P>
<P>
   Family Rules
</P>
<P>
   Guys Like Us
</P>
<P>
   Home Movies
</P>
<P>
   Legacy
</P>
<P>
   Love Boat: The Next Wave
</P>
<P>
   Mercy Point
</P>
<P>
   Reunited
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Diary of Desmond Pfeiffer
</P>
<P>
   The Sentinel
</P>
</TEXT>
