<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST THREE KOSOVAR FAMILIES LEAVE FORT DIX TO START NEW LIVES IN
U.S.
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Idaho, Wash.)   (rk) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT DIX, N.J. _ With little more than hope, anxiety and a few
pieces of carry-on luggage between them, the first three families
of Kosovar Albanians left the haven of this Army base, where they
were embraced just two weeks ago, and fanned out across the
American landscape to begin their new lives in this country.
</P>
<P>
   The three families, 18 people in all, had learned only on
Wednesday that they would be moving from Fort Dix to apartments in
Sarasota, Fla., Seattle and Boise, Idaho. Under a glorious morning
sun, friends they had made in these last tumultuous weeks stood by,
tearful at their imminent departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anything about Boise,'' said Arlinda Gashi, 19,
as she waited to see her friend Mirsade Bejiqi, who was leaving for
Idaho. ``But now I know that it's potato city.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Bejiqi, 20, came out, she collapsed in tears as she
hugged her friends. ``How many times do I have to say goodbye to my
friends?'' the young woman said. ``That's the real question.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for her family in English, Ms. Bejiqi said she had
never heard of Boise, and wanted most of all to go home to Kosovo.
``Whenever it's better in Kosovo, I will go back,'' she vowed.
</P>
<P>
   Sevdie Pllana, 39, said she had never heard of Sarasota, where
she was headed with her husband, Mehmed, 69, and their three
daughters. She said one daughter had learned about the United
States and reassured her when they were told they would be moving
south.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told us Florida was a good place to live,'' Ms. Pllana
said. ``We hope it will be better.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's departures begin the resettlement of the Kosovar
refugees, who now number more than 3,000 here. On Friday six more
families, totaling 25 people, will leave for destinations still
unannounced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Resettlement organizations are making an effort not to
concentrate the refugees in any specific region of the United
States, but to resettle them in clusters in communities throughout
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Muhamet Hakiqi, 28, stood outside drawing a map of the United
States on a slip of paper. He asked how Seattle, Wash., where one
of the families was flying to today, could be on the West Coast,
confusing it with Washington, D.C., where President Clinton lives.
Hakiqi said he was feeling ``a little bit upset _ I don't know
where these people are going.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last weeks, the Kosovars have been checked by doctors and
immigration and law-enforcement officials. Once approved, the
newcomers are eligible to apply for permanent residency in a year,
and for U.S. citizenship in five years.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, representatives from nonprofit refugee relief
agencies have been collecting data on the families and parceling
out the newcomers for resettlement by one of nine resettlement
agencies, which have found communities throughout the country that
are eager to welcome the Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   The resettlement agencies receive an initial grant of $740 for
each refugee they resettle, some of which may be passed along to
the refugees. The agencies are reimbursed for any additional
services they may provide, including English lessons or help in
finding jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their confinement, the refugees have had their every
need attended to at Fort Dix, where soldiers have child-proofed the
barracks and officials have provided English lessons and cultural
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday the newcomers ended a chapter of uncertain waiting that
began with their forced expulsion from their battle-torn homeland
in Yugoslavia. They traded the security and comforts of Fort Dix
base for freedom in this vast country, which they know mostly
through television and books.
</P>
<P>
   Lavinia Limon, the head of the refugee resettlement program for
the Department of Health and Human Services, said Thursday that she
sent the Kosovar Albanians out with good wishes but had not been
prepared for the emotional response.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you walk out this door and onto that bus, you're free to
enjoy all the rights of citizens except voting,'' she told them.
One man smiled broadly. Others broke down in tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some confusion,'' Ms. Limon said, adding: ``As
Americans, we don't know what it's like not to be free, and they
don't know what it's like to be free. They will learn this, over
the course of time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
