<HEADLINE>
THE PLAY'S THE REAL-LIFE THING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember  &UR; Ronald Reagan &LR; 's ``real-life'' anecdotes that turned
out to be plucked from the movies? A pair of British psychologists
claim in a new book that actors really believe that they become the
roles they play. In ``Fame: The Psychology of Stardom,''  &UR; Glenn
Wilson &LR;  and  &UR; Andy Evans &LR;  write that confused actors ``lose track of
who they really are.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Daniel Day-Lewis &LR; , who played Hamlet in 1989, confused the
ghost of Hamlet's father with the ghost of his own father, they
said. ``His personal life intruded. He could not carry on in the
part.''
</P>
<P>
   The authors also cited  &UR; Charlton Heston &LR;  for his performance as
Captain Queeg in a British production of ``The Caine Mutiny'' (but
ignored Heston's portrayal of Moses, a role that left him with a
permanent case of outstretched arms and jutting jaw).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE KID HAS PLANS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Peter &LR;  and  &UR; Mary Jo Collier &LR; , who live in Nevada City and are
the authors of ``The King's Giraffe'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster; $16), the
book that 11-year-old  &UR; John O'Connor &LR;  volunteered to read at the
Presidio branch of the public library, say that sales definitely
got a boost when the story broke last week. ``We're about 250,000th
on the Amazon list,'' said Peter Collier, ``up from about
400,000th.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he and his wife chatted with O'Connor a few days ago;
when they asked him what he wanted to be when he grew up, they
assumed that he'd say teacher or professor. ``Entertainment
lawyer,'' O'Connor told them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Yes, it DOES seem as though the first lady is running. The
Washington Post reports that after five years of summer vacations
on Martha's Vineyard, the Clintons are looking into the Adirondacks
(upstate New York) or Shelter Island (near the Hamptons).
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Tracey Ullman &LR;  gave Bazaar magazine a travel tip: ``Don't buy
the terrible black dress advertised in the back of the New Yorker.
I saw  &UR; Madeleine Albright &LR;  get off a plane recently, and I could
see that she had on the travel dress.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Bob Saget &LR;  and  &UR; Dana Delany &LR;  were at UCSF on Monday for an
all-day symposium on scleroderma, a degenerative disorder that was
fatal to Saget's sister and is suffered by half a million
Americans. The National Institutes of Health spends $4 million on
the disease; research is done solely at laboratories at UCSF and
Johns Hopkins.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAR AND WIDE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ In a report on upscale summer camps for children, the Wall
Street Journal describes Hummer Camp, at which teen- &LR; agers are
taught to drive the $90,000 vehicles over rough terrain in Utah. A
pair of night-vision goggles is issued as standard equipment to
each camper.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reading about herbal malaprops this week spurred a Pacific
Bell directory assistance operator to reveal that a caller asked
the other day for a number of a person who resided at the
``Riverview Condoms around Stockton.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MENU SELECTIONS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Jack in the Box has announced that it is adding ketchup to its
Jumbo Jack, a move the company calls ``the first significant change
to the product's formulation in two decades.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Ice cream flavors, salad dressing, coffee grounds ... and now,
candy.  &UR; Susan Yip &LR;  forwards an analysis chart making the Internet
rounds, in which personalities can be judged based upon the
person's candy preference. A sample: Almond Joy-lovers are ``sexy,
always ready to give and receive, very energetic and really like to
get into life. Horny people are always attracted to you.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Procter &AMP; Gamble's Jif line is going to test-market flavored
peanut butter, in apple-cinnamon, berry blend and chocolate silk.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a born-again Christian, but I prefer to be called a Jesus
freak. Born-again sounds too much like twice baked potatoes.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Anne Lamott, author of ``Traveling Mercies,'' in a Book
magazine interview.
</P>
</TEXT>
