<HEADER>
A5303 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-VANILLA-ICE-SPI     05-20 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-VANILLA-ICE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VANILLA ICE CLAWING HIS WAY BACK WITH NEW ALBUM, TOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GENE STOUT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In 1994, Vanilla Ice nearly killed himself with a
potentially lethal mix of heroin, marijuana, booze and other drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to escape permanently,'' the former rap star
said by phone this week from Miami. ``My friends were dumping
buckets of cold water on me. It was an ugly scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla Ice had reached the peak of his career in the early '90s
with the hit album ``To the Extreme'' and its chart-topping rap
single, ``Ice Ice Baby.'' Fueled by the popularity of his MTV
videos, the album sold more than 15 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   But the unmerciful backlash that followed turned Vanilla Ice _ a
white rapper with platinum-blond hair and a cocky image _ into a
national joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very cocky, very stupid. Just young and dumb,'' he said.
``But I know the impact I had was phenomenal, whether positive or
negative.''
</P>
<P>
   After his overdose, Vanilla Ice realized he had to pull himself
together. He had a leaf tattooed on his abdomen to signify he was
turning over a new leaf.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Vanilla Ice _ born Rob Van Winkle _ is clawing his way
back with an album, ``Hard to Swallow,'' that is radically
different from his rap of the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla Ice described its hardcore sound as ``skate rock'' or
``Adidas rock.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Vanilla Ice and his seven-piece band created the sound on
their own, the former rapper credits producer Ross Robinson _ who
has worked with Korn, Sepultura, Limp Bizkit and other hard-edged
bands _ with giving it the right spin.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me what the music is and it's hard to explain,'' he
said. ``Ross Robinson pretty much invented the sound. It's a
mixture of punk, metal and hip-hop.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the songs are cathartic. ``Zig Zag Stories'' focuses on
his drug experiences, while ``Scars'' stirs up tales of abuse from
his childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The music is like therapy,'' he said. ``I was all alone on
this planet when I overdosed. And I felt like I had no friends to
talk to about this stuff. It was trapped inside me. So I've used
the music to talk about it and let it out. I feel much better
now.''
</P>
<P>
   One song, ``Too Cold,'' features a line from ``Ice Ice Baby.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to say, `Look, guys, this is me. I'm not running or
hiding from anything. This is how I sound now. You either like it
or you don't.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I accept my past, but I've moved along. And I've cut the
string, so to speak. I'm not a puppet or record company whore
anymore. I'm trying to keep it real.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla Ice's band includes two guitarists, two bassists, a
drummer, a deejay and background singer. Most of the shows on the
tour have been at clubs and small theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love playing clubs,'' he said. ``It's so in-your-face, so
personal. It's not about trying to milk a stadium full of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla Ice described the shows as ``dark, energetic and
spontaneous,'' with lots of Gallagher-esque antics. ``One night we
brought a bag of flour out and got it all over us, the crowd,
everything,'' he said. ``It was a mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the tour began in October, Vanilla Ice and crew have
performed more than 100 shows to crowds that included goths, punks
and mainstream rockers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may have listened to Vanilla Ice when they were in high
school because everybody across the country did,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they weren't really into rap or hip-hop. They were more
into Pearl Jam and Smashing Pumpkins and bands like that. So they
can appreciate the rock side of what I'm doing now.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla Ice looks back on his days of rap stardom with a mix of
pride and regret. He began his career as a raunchy rapper
performing for predominantly black audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually he had to choose between two record deals. The first,
for about $30,000, would have placed him in a recording studio with
rap group Public Enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working with them would have given me tremendous credibility
as a rapper,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The second deal, which he accepted, was a recording contract
worth $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anybody in my shoes would have done what I did,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was three car payments behind and I was living with three
other guys in an apartment and couldn't pay the rent. It was like
winning the lottery and I took it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize the consequences of being turned into a
novelty act literally overnight. I was playing to 12-year-olds in
braces at huge arenas. And I was asking myself, `Where did my real
crowd go? They were gone.'''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Vanilla Ice played it smart with his finances.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I went on a huge spending spree, I put on the brakes.
And then I started studying about all these entertainers who made
millions and just lost it. I tried to learn from that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like most celebrities who have been over the waterfall in a
barrel, Vanilla Ice values the kinds of things he once took for
granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at my 19-month-old daughter and realize that she would
not be here if I succeeded in killing myself,'' he said. ``Now I
see what life's about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
