<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5304 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-COLA-ART-875(2     05-20 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-COLA-ART-875(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READING, WRITING AND MARKETING PRODUCTS IN PUBLIC SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., N.C., N.J., Calif., Wyo.)  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Dan DeRose, marketing consultant, was busy doing
the math for his new client, the Newark Public Schools.
</P>
<P>
   The question on everyone's mind: How much money could the
district make if it signed an exclusive contract with a soft-drink
company? The answer, DeRose said: a lot more than it gets right
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say everyone drinks one product a day, and let's
just count the students,'' he said. ``At 45,000 times 180 days of
school, that's 8.1 million cans. At 75 cents apiece, that's $6
million walking out the front door of your school every year in
quarters and dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's get a lot of it,'' he told his audience of principals,
athletic directors, PTA officials and one student. ``Let's get some
of it back to the schools.'' Even $5 million would make a
difference in the district's $550 million budget.
</P>
<P>
   With his square shoulders, steady smile and conscientious use of
the first-person plural, DeRose and his company, DD Marketing, are
storming a once-quiet backwater in the soft-drink business. Schools
regard him as a font of information. Soft-drink companies, which
used to make low-key deals on their terms with local school
districts, hate him with a passion.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best-known consultants in a rapidly growing
specialty, DeRose, who is based in Pueblo, Colo., says he has
obtained exclusive contracts, or is negotiating them, for 63 school
systems nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The exclusive contract, a winner-take-all creation of the
soft-drink companies themselves, eliminates rivals' products from a
school, a hotel, an airline. Thanks to Coca-Cola and Pepsico's
desire to market to children, and the eagerness of schools for the
income, DeRose has found a niche.
</P>
<P>
   Almost evangelical in his zeal, he primes school officials to
take on the soft-drink companies, raising the stakes for all
concerned and profiting handsomely from the deals that go through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan DeRose is probably the person most responsible for this
current feeding frenzy,'' said Alex Molnar, a professor of
education at the University of Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Others say there is a need for his services. ``Most educators
don't have a background in food management,'' said Barry Gaskins, a
spokesman for the Pitt County schools in Greenville, N.C., which
hired DeRose last year. ``They're trained in the three R's, and the
R's don't include retail.''
</P>
<P>
   While demand for exclusive contracts has never been greater,
there is a distinct downside. Some lawmakers want to ban the sale
or giveaway of soft drinks on school grounds during the school day,
citing nutritional concerns and the ubiquity of ads and vending
machines. Advocates for education say students are captive
audiences who should not be sold to the highest bidder.
</P>
<P>
   DeRose is working with Valerie Wilson, the food-services manager
for Newark schools, who wants to consolidate the system's patchwork
arrangement _ some Coke here, some Pepsi there, plus other brands.
Whoever wins the contract would supply sodas for vending machines
and juices in 82 school cafeterias and water and other drinks for
athletic events.
</P>
<P>
   After some discussion about the merits of the idea, officials
solicited bids from three marketing consultants, settling on
DeRose, Ms. Wilson said. Earlier this month, nattily dressed in a
gray suit, blue silk tie and black alligator loafers, he met with
the committee Ms. Wilson assembled to discuss the fine points.
</P>
<P>
   He warmed up by discussing deals he has orchestrated for school
systems in Colorado and Kansas _ one for $11.1 million, the other
for roughly $5.3 million. ``In Kansas City,'' he noted, ``they were
getting 67 cents a kid before, and now they're getting $27.'' Then
he went to the heart of the issue: how much Newark's kids could be
worth.
</P>
<P>
   As in hundreds of school systems around the country, Newark
officials are unable to pay for every program on their agendas. The
system was so badly mismanaged that in 1995, the state took
control.
</P>
<P>
   To make the most of its assets, DeRose said, Newark should make
a deal with just one soft-drink giant. ``We're going to get what we
call a rights fee,'' he said, adding that companies like Coke and
Pepsi love exclusive contracts because they imprint brand loyalty
on young minds.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, DeRose cited his own first-grader, Anna, whose
school in Pueblo has an exclusive contract with Coca-Cola, the work
of DD Marketing. ``From now until she's graduated, all she'll drink
is Coke,'' he said. ``She goes out for pizza and we ask, What do
you want to drink, honey? Coke. She doesn't even know how to spell
Pepsi.''
</P>
<P>
   Several critics compare DeRose to the title character in ``The
Music Man,'' the musical about a small town falling for a
charlatan's pitch. ``He really illustrates the worst aspects of
commercialism in schools,'' said Andrew Hagelshaw, senior program
director for the Center for Commercial Free Public Education in
Oakland, Calif. ``He is making millions of dollars off
commercializing public schools, and he is not taking into account
any of the negatives.''
</P>
<P>
   How many millions? DeRose would say only that ``We're doing
really good.'' He charges a percentage of the final contract _ 25
to 35 percent, according to school systems that have hired him.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Recently he modified his commission for a $4.6 million contract
between Coca-Cola and the Manteca, Calif., schools. DeRose offered
to accept $160,000, far less than 25 percent, after Coke first
refused to bid on the contract, said Jerry Ogden, an assistant
superintendent there.
</P>
<P>
   Such fees, soft-drink companies say, are outlandish. ``These
consultants who charge commissions based on the fees in the
contracts generally bring little or no value to the school
system,'' said Bob Lanz, a spokesman for Coca-Cola Enterprises, the
Coke bottler for Newark.
</P>
<P>
   Statements like these elicit smirks from DeRose, who likes to
read from Coca-Cola's 1997 annual report _ lines like ``Sales of
Coca-Cola and other company products exceed one billion servings
per day'' _ as part of his sales pitch. The names and logos of Coke
or Pepsi do appear frequently on exclusive contracts he arranges.
``They'll want ads in athletic programs, something on tickets, and
the scoreboard,'' he told the Newark group. But when Ms. Wilson
asked whether there would be ``Coke and Pepsi plastered all over
the building,'' DeRose replied: ``We'll do whatever you want.''
</P>
<P>
   DeRose insisted he was helping make schools more realistic for
children. ``If you have no advertising in schools at all, it
doesn't give our young people an accurate picture of our society,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he added, children should not be ``bombarded with it.''
His partner in DD Marketing came up with the idea of putting ads on
school buses, and the company also markets Zap Me, a
computers-in-schools program that includes ads in one corner of the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say soft-drink contracts distort a school's role. They
differ from contracts for textbooks or pencils, which are
educational essentials, Molnar said.
</P>
<P>
   Others worry about the nutritional impact. ``Twenty years ago,
teen-agers drank twice as much milk as soda pop, and now they drink
twice as much soda as milk,'' said Michael Jacobson, executive
director of the Center for Science in the Public Interest.
</P>
<P>
   The Newark group seemed impressed by DeRose's presentation,
which included frequent pauses to answer questions. ``It's a first
time for us,'' said Roger Jones, a spokesman for the Newark Public
Schools, when asked why the system needed a consultant. ``It's an
opportunity to bring together all the people involved in vending so
we have one voice speaking for everyone,'' and help generate a
windfall ``that ultimately goes back into our system so students
benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of DeRose's projects work out. The Pitt County school
board paid him nothing after opting not to pursue a contract. Both
Coke and Pepsi refused to bid, though a vending company made an
offer.
</P>
<P>
   But the board learned a lot. ``Just by the fact that Dan DeRose
walks in and says this is the kind of money you could get, you know
it's there,'' said Gaskins, the Pitt County spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, ``some of our board members felt this was too
good to be true, and another rubbing point was the commission that
would be paid to DD Marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the thought of generating that kind of revenue stream,
where you didn't have to raise property taxes, you didn't have to
increase the sales tax and you didn't have to do battle with the
county commissioners, was very attractive,'' Gaskins conceded.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it's always easy money. School officials in Colorado
Springs learned last year that only beverages purchased from
vending machines count toward the system's 70,000-case annual
quota, said John Bushey, an administrator, which has forced the
system to pay closer attention to purchases to make the most from
its $11.1 million contract with Coca-Cola. ``Quite honestly, they
were smarter than us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With their costs rising, Coke and Pepsi say they want to avoid
deals that involve marketers like DeRose. ``I'm surprised that
during his presentation, the high school band didn't break into a
spontaneous version of `Seventy-Six Trombones,''' said Lauren C.
Steele, a spokesman for Coca-Cola Consolidated, a bottler in
Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi also views consultants with distaste. ``We tend not to
love working with these guys,'' said a spokesman, David DeCecco.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, soft-drink companies would make low offers and
schools would usually accept them, lacking the time and inclination
to pursue alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the word is out. ``Coke came to the table with an offer
last week, and I said, `based on what you did in Manteca and what
you did in Wyoming, this isn't good enough,''' said Bill Erlendson,
an official with the San Jose, Calif., school district, who used
information DeRose provided. He was expecting a revised bid from
Coke this week.
</P>
<P>
   The plan for Newark calls for installing eight vending machines
at each of the city's 13 high schools; two to four at each of the
69 lower schools. ``Typically, we like to add a machine in a hall,
to give the company a presence,'' he said. Committee members were
asked to sign confidentiality agreements, to keep the offers secret
from competing bidders, DeRose said.
</P>
<P>
   The Newark group next meets June 1 to discuss the proposal
DeRose assembles, before soliciting bids from the beverage
companies. If all goes according to plan, Newark will sign an
exclusive contract by the time school opens in September.
</P>
<P>
   At its last meeting, the committee did express several
reservations, including whether one old high school would be able
to support eight vending machines on its existing electrical work,
and whether the girls' basketball team would still be able to sell
drinks at football games.
</P>
<P>
   DeRose smiled, fixed his gaze on the group and said: ``All of
your concerns, I've heard them 500 times before. All of your peers
across the country have the same concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``To give you a little comfort: when this process is over, we're
all going to have more money than we have now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 2125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0429 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5309 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-SHAS-ART-2TAKE     05-20 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SHAS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SECOND ISRAEL' CELEBRATES FIRST BIG ELECTION WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Natan Yehuda is still elated, three days after a
long, joyous night of beef and wine celebrating the staggering
electoral triumph of his political party and spiritual home, Shas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more they push us down, the more we will rise up,''
Yehuda, 40, said in an open-air market Thursday, with a hearty
handshake and wide smile. ``Before they know it, we will be prime
minister.''
</P>
<P>
   Shas, an ultra-Orthodox party representing working-class
Sephardic Jews, has been the political phenomenon of the last
decade, a social and religious movement with a strong message of
ethnic pride. The party's followers are descendants of Jews who
immigrated from North Africa and the Middle East after 1948. Shas
has risen from scratch to secure a place as the third largest party
in the multi-partied Israeli Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Until Monday's elections, Shas was dwarfed by the two major
parties, Likud and Labor. On Monday, however, as Likud and Labor
shrunk, Shas mushroomed. It captured 17 out of 120 seats, up from
10 and only 2 less than Likud.
</P>
<P>
   That stunned many Israelis, who struggled to reconcile what
seemed to be contradictory results: the landslide victory of Ehud
Barak, a secularist kibbutznik, as prime minister, and the
unexpected rise of a political movement led by three rabbis _ one
scholarly, one mystical and one, Aryeh Deri, a convicted criminal.
</P>
<P>
   The seeming contradiction underscores that the fiercest battle
lines in Israeli society are between secular and religious. If
Barak's victory was part of a backlash against the power held by
religious parties under the departing prime minister, Benjamin
Netanyahu, Shas' gain was a stab in the other direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God, for He is good!'' proclaimed the banner headline in
the special election edition of the Shas Party newspaper, Day by
Day.
</P>
<P>
   But in another, more basic way, the two wins _ by Barak and Shas
_ are two sides of the same coin. They both reflect the failure of
Netanyahu and of his demoralized Likud Party. Just as Barak
siphoned voters from Netanyahu, Shas stole them from Likud, a
traditional home for the Sephardic working class, the so-called
Second Israel. Sephardic Jews in Israel often complain of feeling
like outsiders, belittled and discriminated against by the
Ashkenazic elite.
</P>
<P>
   The sub-headline in the Shas paper tells that story: ``The dream
has come true! The Second Israel is not second anymore! Sephardim
have captured the state of Israel!''
</P>
<P>
   A political party built on a fundamentalist religious movement,
Shas has used its access to government funds to develop a national
social service infrastructure. Offering hot meals, pre-school,
government jobs and Torah studies, it has built a loyal following
among poor Israelis of North African and Middle Eastern descent. It
has developed into a kind of Sephardic power movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the closest thing we have to the Islamic movement,'' said
Shahar Ilan, a religion expert for the Haaretz newspaper. ``It's
not violent. But Shas is a party that builds on its institutions of
welfare and education. It is the real proletarian party of
Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Likud earned the most votes in Jerusalem and Shas came
in fifth. This year, Shas captured more votes there than any other
party.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Shas' new adherents are not strictly religious, but were
drawn in partly by what they perceived to be the persecution of
Deri.
</P>
<P>
   Deri's conviction on corruption charges this spring galvanized
many Sephardim. Many accepted Deri's view _ expressed in a
videocassette and CD-rom called ``J'accuse'' _ that he had been
singled out and persecuted by the judicial system because he was
Moroccan-born and successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joseph went to jail in Egypt, and eight years later he was
king,'' Yehuda said. ``The same will happen to Aryeh Deri. If he
goes to jail, he will come out prime minister.''
</P>
<P>
   Sentenced in April to four years in jail, Deri, who was a close
ally of Netanyahu, is free pending an anticipated appeal of his
conviction on bribery and fraud charges. On Tuesday, feeling
exonerated by his supporters, Deri announced he would step down as
Shas' political leader and resign from Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   In Rabin Square in Tel Aviv, on the night of elections, hundreds
of young Israelis pleaded with Barak to turn his back on the
ultra-Orthodox Sephardic party when he forms a coalition
government. ``Just not Shas!'' they chanted.
</P>
<P>
   But a party that earned nearly 430,000 out of 3.7 million votes
is difficult to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can scorn these numbers, and no one can scorn these
people,'' Yossi Beilin, a top-ranking Labor official, told Israel
television.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, who aims to build a broad government, says that he will
not include Shas if Deri remains the leader behind the scenes. The
leftist Meretz Party, a key member of Barak's future coalition,
said it would not sit beside Shas in a coalition with or without
Deri, protesting what it calls the religious party's defiance of
the ``rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barak has called the party ``a genuine political and social
movement,'' and some of his colleagues in Labor have been
rehabilitating the image of Shas as a viable partner now that Deri
has stepped down.
</P>
<P>
   The rehabilitation effort stems largely from the Barak
government's sense of the future. Since the Shas leadership, as
opposed to that of Likud, is emphatically and unconditionally
pro-peace, the presence of Shas in a coalition could add crucial
support for concessions in any peace negotiations with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his book-lined study, Rabbi Reuven Elbaz, one of the
movement's leading rabbis, explained Shas' position on peace and
some of his own views.
</P>
<P>
   With piercing eye contact, Rabbi Elbaz spoke in the soothing but
animated tones of a charismatic leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Sephardim are Middle Eastern people,'' he said. ``We lived
with Arabs in the past with no problems. We respected them. They
respected us. In fact, they give more respect to the Jews who are
believers, like us. In the end, the Arab people too believe in the
Lord.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should let the rabbis negotiate on this issue,'' he
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   An aide, Binyamin Edry, 28, later offered his view: ``If one
sheep is surrounded by 70 wolves, he cannot do battle. So as the
saying goes, if you can't beat them, join them. We're all sons of
the same maker.''
</P>
<P>
   Edry pointed to the work that Shas has done developing social
service systems in some Israeli Arab villages. This earned Shas, as
he noted, many votes in many Arab towns, like Kafr Manda and Yirka.
</P>
<P>
   As yeshiva students studied beneath him in a high-ceilinged
hall, Elbaz traced his own involvement in the back-to-religion
movement that Shas has spawned among the Sephardim. He spoke of
touring coffee shops and billiard halls.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you walk into the stronghold of those so far from the
Torah? I was asked,'' he said ``Slowly we did. From one small
yeshiva of born-agains, we developed over the years into 230
branches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the same way with Shas,'' he said. ``We started with 4
seats, then 10, now, thank the Lord, 17. Next time, it will be 25,
26.''
</P>
<P>
   Elbaz said it was partly ``natural growth,'' given the large
families in the religious Sephardic population, partly the
recruiting success of Shas' schools and jobs programs, partly
ethnic pride and partly ``a feeling of oppression.''
</P>
<P>
   Pulling on his beard, he said he was puzzled by what seemed to
be fear of the ultra-Orthodox by secular Israelis. ``They think
we'll force them into it, don't they?'' he said. ``But the Torah is
not imposed.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying he had a ``deep friendship'' with Barak _ and photographs
to prove it _ he described him as ``very, very gentle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are no devils around him, he will lead very, very
well,'' the rabbi said. ``He does not have hate for religion. I
believe we could work very well with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Ovadia Yosef, the spiritual leader of Shas, has said that
he believes Deri's resignation opens a door into Barak's
government, and that he would welcome an alliance, Haaretz reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Shas officials have supposedly already accepted that they are
bound to lose the powerful Interior Ministry, which oversees
immigration policy and much municipal-level social spending.
Yisrael Baaliyah, the Russian immigrant party of Natan Sharansky,
campaigned to wrest its control from Shas, and will likely get it.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians' campaign increased Moroccans' jealousy of Russian
immigrants _ for receiving benefits denied them decades ago _
indirectly fueling their resentment and probably driving more to
Shas.
</P>
<P>
   The peace issue aside, Shas ministers in Barak's government
could well constrain on his efforts to promote harmony between
secular and religious Jews. And it would alienate many who voted
for him partly out of anger at the special powers and privileges of
the religious parties under Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   But Elbaz, his palms laid flat on an oversized Hebrew text
before him, said he did not feel that Barak had much choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no need for groveling,'' he said. ``But he can't lead
the country without us. The social sector, the poor people, would
rise up if their interests were not represented.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
