<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIA COMES THROUGH AGAIN WITH A QUIRKY COMEDY, `THE CASTLE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever since the days of ``Crocodile Dundee,'' Australia has been
good for at least one delightfully quirky, jump-out comedy hit
every year _ a ``Priscilla, Queen of the Desert,'' ``Muriel's
Wedding'' or ``Strictly Ballroom.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's example could be ``The Castle,'' an Aussie comedy
that's been the biggest domestic hit of recent years Down Under. It
debuted last weekend at the 25th Seattle International Film
Festival and begins a regular theatrical run on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It's the story of the Kerrigans, a lower-middle-class family
that lives happily in an eyesore of a home on the edge of
Melbourne's international airport. As the film opens, they discover
that the airport is expanding and their home is to be torn down.
</P>
<P>
   The senior Kerrigan _ an extremely good-natured tow-truck driver
_ simply refuses to believe the Australian Constitution will allow
such a soaring injustice to occur, and the movie chronicles his
battle to save the Kerrigan ``castle.''
</P>
<P>
   The running joke _ which is accented by voice-over narration by
the youngest Kerrigan son _ is that the family doesn't have a clue
as to how hopeless their plight is, or how absurdly naive their
worldview is. They're gullible, trusting and boundlessly
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   The trick first-time director-writer Rob Sitch pulls off is
that, while the movie is set up to ridicule the Kerrigans and their
values, it doesn't. Gradually and subtly, it celebrates them and
vindicates the power of their childlike faith.
</P>
<P>
   Another film from the Seattle International Film Festvial's
opening weekend that's leaping into a regular theatrical engagement
on Friday today is ``Lovers of the Arctic Circle,'' a breathless
romance directed by the popular Basque filmmaker Julio Medem
(``Vacas,'' ``The Red Squirrel'').
</P>
<P>
   It's the story of the epic, star-crossed love affair between
Otto and Ana (each played by three different actors during the
course of the film), who fall instantly in love as children, seem
destined for one another in every way, but have a heck of a time
getting together.
</P>
<P>
   It is non-linear (jumping back and forth in time), structured in
a series of titled chapters (alternating the points of view of the
lovers), sumptuously photographed, voluptuously surreal and
fatalistic and, overall, so silly it's only an inch away from
self-parody.
</P>
<P>
   The Castle. Directed by Rob Sitch. Written by Sitch, Tom
Gleisner, Jane Kennedy and Santo Cilauro. Cast: Michael Caton, Anne
Tenney, Stephen Curry, Charles Tingwell. Miramax. 82 minutes. Rated
R for no obvious reason.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Lovers of the Arctic Circle. Directed and written by Julio
Medem. Cast: Fele Martinez, Najwa Nimri, Nancho Novo, Maru
Valdivielso. First Line Features. 112 minutes. In Spanish with
English subtitles. Rated R for nudity and sex scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
