<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SERBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIVES, MOTHERS PROTEST, AND GENERAL SENDS TROOPS BACK HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Five days of demonstrations by women in
southern Serbia who were angry because their men had been drafted
for military service in Kosovo ended Thursday when many of the men
returned home.
</P>
<P>
   The army commander in Kosovo, Col. Gen. Nebojsa Pavkovic,
intervened to defuse the anger of the women, reservists' wives and
mothers who were demanding news of the men. Pavkovic also commands
the Third Army, based in Nis.
</P>
<P>
   He met with hundreds of women on Wednesday in two separate and
stormy sessions in the Krusevac Town Hall, listening to their
complaints and calling the men heroes.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, soldiers began arriving home in army trucks
and cars, apparently given permission to return from Kosovo in
large numbers, and residents reported that Krusevac was quiet
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The women's main demands had been for new information. Their
anxiety turned to terror when the bodies of seven soldiers were
brought home for burial last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The women were expecting the men to return after the official
announcement on May 9 that troops were being withdrawn from Kosovo.
But rumors flew that there had been many casualties, residents
said.
</P>
<P>
   One woman who attended a meeting with Pavkovic said the women
had asked him to understand that they were not unpatriotic and did
not want the army to abandon Kosovo, just that they wanted news.
</P>
<P>
   Some were angry and complained that while the men were in
Kosovo, rich young men went around town talking on their cellular
telephones. Many complaints were based on economic hardship. With
the main breadwinners absent, some for 40 days, many women are
struggling.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings were sometimes heated, but ended with the women
applauding the general. One gave him a gift, a sweater. He listened
to their complaints, one woman said, and promised that reservists
would serve shorter terms and that the men would be relieved.
</P>
<P>
   Pavkovic described the March 1998 class of draftees as ``real
heroes.'' Those troops should have ended their one year of service
two months ago, but have had their period extended. Some
demonstrators in Krusevac were mothers who were protesting the
extension.
</P>
<P>
   The timely return of some reservists was also probably an army
move to defuse the tension. NATO had reported that 500 to 1,000 men
had demanded to return home after hearing of the demonstrations.
When they were denied permission, NATO officials said, the troops
deserted.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the governing Socialist Party, Ivica Dacic,
dismissed any suggestion that the men were deserters. ``Such a
thing exists only at NATO briefings, and they are aimed at
undermining national unity and the defense of the country,'' Dacic
said.
</P>
<P>
   An army official in Belgrade said, however, that the men had
been given permission to go home. Those soldiers who returned
clearly did so with permission and little tension, residents said.
They stood in groups on village street corners, hugging friends and
relatives, said a resident who had traveled by bus through the
region. Gunfire sounded through the night and much of the morning,
apparently from soldiers who were celebrating the return by firing
in the air.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations have clearly embarrassed local authorities,
as has recent violence in Belgrade aimed at the opposition
Democratic Party headquarters. Foreign journalists have been denied
permission to travel to Krusevac and Aleksandrovac, near the Kosovo
border.
</P>
<P>
   Several foreign television crews including CBS News and CTV of
Canada had film of the damage to the Democratic Party offices
confiscated or heavily censored.
</P>
<P>
   That Pavkovic went to talk to the women was a signal of how
serious the protests had become. It may also be a sign of his
natural charisma. He is the country's most visible general, has
frequently appeared on television and has been promoted three times
since the beginning of the yearlong Kosovo war.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with a weekly newspaper, Svedok, he warned NATO
not to try a ground offensive, because ``hell awaits them.'' It was
a fierce message to the allies, but it was also a rallying cry to
his troops and the people of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our people and our army are determined to defend Kosovo at any
cost,'' Pavkovic said. NATO ``cannot advance overland without many
casualties. Of course, we can count on taking losses, too. But if
they come here, they must know that they will not be able to stay
and survive. They are going to die day by day, month by month, and
die horrible deaths.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
