<SLUG> BC-FILM-LOVE-LETTER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE LOVE LETTER' IS BEST RETURNED TO SENDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hong Kong romance, ``Comrades: Almost a Love Story,'' was
not even an art-house hit in this country but it was probably the
best-reviewed foreign film of 1997 and won the best picture award
at that year's Seattle International Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, it is not too surprising that its director, Peter Ho-sun
Chan, would be one of the Hong Kong directors invited to make a
big-budget Hollywood film after the near-collapse of the former
colony's film industry during the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike John Woo and the others who have successfully made
the transition to these shores, Chan's particular gift seems to
have been stunted by the Hollywood machine. His first U.S. film,
``The Love Letter,'' is a fairly charmless dud.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a novel by Cathleen Schine, it's about the effect of a
gushy and anonymous love letter on a number of characters in a
small, idyllic, seaside Massachusetts town _ most prominently Helen
(Kate Capshaw), a single, 40ish bookstore owner who first finds it.
</P>
<P>
   She assumes it was written by Johnny, the hunky 20-year-old (Tom
Everett Scott) who works part time in her store. When he stumbles
upon it, he assumes Helen wrote it to him. Then Helen's business
partner, Janet (Ellen De Generes), finds it, and assumes it was
written to her. And so on.
</P>
<P>
   The mix also includes George (Tom Selleck), the town fireman
who's always loved Helen; Jennifer (Julianne Nicholson), a
tomboyish young woman who also works in the bookstore and has a
crush on Johnny; and Helen's mother (Blythe Danner), who has a
secret romantic agenda of her own.
</P>
<P>
   As this mass of romantic confusion plays out, the best thing
about the movie is Capshaw, who proves herself to be more than just
the boss' wife (the film was produced by DreamWorks, and she is
Mrs. Steven Spielberg). Without trying, she's quite appealing, and
she holds the screen well.
</P>
<P>
   But she has little chemistry with the annoyingly boyish Scott,
and she can't do anything with a premise that never once seems as
light and magical as the producers obviously hoped it would be, and
a script that is labored and grindingly unfunny.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, the movie lacks the kind of light, deft directorial
touch that a Lubitsch or a Renoir might have used to make the
souffle rise. Chan clearly has no feel for eccentric Northeastern
characters or small-town American life, and everything about ``The
Love Letter'' rings false.
</P>
<P>
   The Love Letter. Directed by Peter Ho-sun Chan. Screenplay by
Maria Maggenti. Cast: Kate Capshaw, Blythe Danner, Ellen DeGeneres,
Tom Selleck, Tom Everett Scott, Gloria Stuart. DreamWorks. 89
minutes. Rated PG-13 for sex scenes and brief nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 2135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
