<HEADLINE>
NO REAL TENSION, TOO MANY DETAILS IN `ENDURANCE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In movie decades past, it was often the custom to surround a
popular athlete with professional actors and cast him as himself in
a movie version of his own life _ ``The Jackie Robinson Story,''
``The Bob Mathias Story,'' ``The Greatest'' (Muhammad Ali), etc.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's ``Endurance'' renews this custom in a somewhat artier
style with its biography of Haile Gebrselassie, the long-distance
runner who grew up in soul-devouring poverty in rural Ethopia to
became one of the stars of the 1996 Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The first, and most interesting, part of the film traces the
early years of the determined runner on a drought-ravaged farm,
where his stern father is less than supportive of his athletic
interests, and his kindlier mother dies young.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to years later and Haile has moved to the capital city of
Addis Ababa, where he lives with his older brother and has joined a
track club. Only a few scenes later, we're at the Olympics, where
he establishes himself as what one commentator calls ``perhaps the
greatest runner ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Leslie Woodhead, a documentary filmmaker, says
his intention was to make less a competition movie and more a kind
of Robert Flaherty-like entho-documentary in the vein of ``Nanook
of the North.'' And the first half of his film does a fair job of
this.
</P>
<P>
   But even these scenes soon get bogged down in numbing
ethnological details, and the rest of film fails to build any real
tension. The Olympics sequences are almost completely devoid of
drama, and the script never quite makes it clear exactly why he's
regarded as being such a special athlete.
</P>
<P>
   And while Gebrselassie exudes a quiet determination and
likability, he's simply no actor. His face and eyes are opaque, his
manner is self-contained, and he communicates little of the fierce
inner drive that propelled him to these Olympian heights.
</P>
<P>
   Endurance. Directed and written by Leslie Woodhead. Cast: Haile
Gebrselassie, Gebrselassie Bekele, Assefa Gebrselassie. In English
and Ethiopian with English subtitles. 124 minutes. Rated G,
suitable for all audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
