<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5324 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-HOWFAR21-COX     05-20 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-HOWFAR21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Educators struggle with school safety options
 &HT;    By Joanne Huist Smith, Mark Fisher, Mara Lee and Margo Rutledge
Kissell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Some Beavercreek parents want National Guardsmen
stationed in Ankeney Junior High, where a homemade bottle bomb blew
up in a cafeteria trash can Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Other parents criticize any effort to bring in police or
security. They feel it stifles students' opportunity to express
themselves and act like kids, school officials said.
</P>
<P>
   With yet another school shooting Thursday _ this time in a
suburban Atlanta high school _ principals around the Miami Valley
dealt with an onslaught of parent calls and student fears. As the
clock ticks down to summer break, educators say they wrestle with
choices that limits student freedom to ensure safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``The job comes with a tremendous responsibility to protect
children,'' Jack Poore, principal of Springboro High School, said.
``Everybody wants tough discipline for everyone except their own
child.''
</P>
<P>
   In the month since two disgruntled Columbine, Colo., students
massacred 12 classmates and a teacher, then killed themselves,
Miami Valley schools have been plagued by bomb threats, rumors of
violence and threats against students. Rumors of pending violence
led officials in the Trotwood-Madison school district to call a
town meeting. In Xenia, four high school students were arrested
April 29 in connection with threats made to others. In Dayton, bomb
threats were made at Patterson Career Center and Colonel White High
School for the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   David Elliott, principal at Ankeney Junior High, said school
administrators in the area are ``stuck in between that proverbial
rock and a hard place'' on how far to go to take precautions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terribly difficult to try to strike the balance between
students' rights and doing everything in your power to ensure their
safety,'' Elliott said Thursday. ``At this point, we are trying to
err on the side of caution and safety.''
</P>
<P>
   The Beavercreek City School District recently put security
guards at Ankeney and Ferguson junior high schools and Beavercreek
High School.
</P>
<P>
   June Arnett, assistant director of the National School Safety
Center in Westlake Village, Calif., said when the school climate is
hot, freedom should take a backseat to safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the kind of climate we have in schools right now,
whatever freedoms we have to remove from our children are
justified,'' Arnett said.
</P>
<P>
   With the end of the school year near, Arnett hopes local school
boards will spend the summer re-evaluating school safety policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``School violence isn't a national issue; it's a local issue,''
Arnett said. ``School boards and the communities they serve have to
decide how much they want to spend to prevent violence and what
freedoms they want to take away from kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning our schools into armed camps with security guards and
metal detectors won't solve the problem, said Raymond Vasvari,
legal director of the American Civil Liberties Union of Ohio. In
the month since the Columbine shootings, students and their
families have filed 40 complaints with the ACLU, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are being singled out because they look different or
because they wear black or because they like funky music,'' Vasvari
said. ``I worry that our schools are sowing seeds of suspicion,
intolerance and mistrust. That's a misguided reaction and may be
laying the seeds for the next disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Schools would be better served, Vasvari said, by learning to
identify children with potential problems _ kids who've talked
about suicide or whose grades have plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can provide these children with intervention,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   John Ochsenbein, educational consultant for Huber Heights-based
Risk Management Professionals, gives seminars on preventing school
and workplace violence.
</P>
<P>
   He said schools can go too far by reacting too much _ for
example, by closing school based on unsubstantiated rumors.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can go so far as to create your own sense of paranoia,''
said Ochsenbein, a former school counselor in the Mad River School
District.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton City Schools are not planning restrictions or security
measures beyond those that have been in place all year, but they
are seeking to head off any budding confrontations among students,
school officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton schools have several initiatives, including peer
mediation and conflict resolution programs, designed to prevent
escalation of school violence.
</P>
<P>
   Jolene Wallace, the Dayton school district's assistant
superintendent for secondary schools, said she has asked Dayton's
secondary school principals to identify students who are constantly
picked on and talk to them, as well as to those students who might
be participating in the verbal abuse, to try to head off potential
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're instructing our staff to be vigilant and to make
themselves aware of and follow the procedures we have in place,''
Wallace said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank DePalma, superintendent at Centerville schools, also
emphasized cutting down on taunts at school.
</P>
<P>
   ``This offers our best chance at preventing violence,'' he said.
``Teasing, whether `I'm gonna kill you' type stuff to calling
people `fat' or `fags' _ It's all serious in this day and age.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the shootings last year, if an elementary school student
shoved another student, they would get a lecture.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, we're sending them home'' DePalma said. ``Most
cases, it's just for the rest of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Northmont schools already a rule that says students can't
intimidate, verbally abuse, sexually harass or make obscene
gestures to anyone else in the school. Next year, the school will
create a `menacing' category, which will have a more severe
punishment, Gale Mabry, superintendent of Northmont schools said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
