<HEADER>
A5325 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-OFFICIALREAX     05-20 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-OFFICIALREAX21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia leaders still stumped for solutions to violence
 &HT;    By Doug Cumming and Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia leaders were already groping for answers. The
shooting Thursday at Heritage High School brought a new urgency,
but still no easy answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really shows how much work it's going to take when one of
the best high schools we have in Georgia is unable to use
preventive measures to stop something like this from happening,''
said Brian Kintisch, director of the Macon-based Center for
Children and Education, which unsuccessfully fought parts of the
state's new school discipline law that his group considered too
punitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing can be taken for granted any longer,'' said Essie
Stewart Johnson, president of the Georgia Association of Educators,
the state's strongest teachers union. Johnson said everybody, but
especially the citizens of Rockdale County, realizes that security
guards, metal detectors and surveillance cameras can never stop
violence.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, politicians jumped on the suburban Atlanta
shooting in the debate over a gun control amendment that passed in
the Senate on Thursday. Rep. Johnny Isakson (R-Ga.) said he plans
to introduce House legislation within the next couple of weeks for
a staff position in schools that would handle discipline cases and
work with authorities. Each of the nation's 87,000 public schools
could apply for the federal funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the one thing every school doesn't have, and one thing
that will help address a major problem in the country,'' said
Isakson, former chairman of the Georgia state school board. ``The
tragedies are becoming far too frequent.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Barnes declined comment but cleared his appointments
for the day and visited the most seriously wounded girl, who was in
the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   State school Superintendent Linda Schrenko, who also declined
comment, did not change her appointments, speaking in schools in
Union County all day. But she had spelled out proposals on the
Department of Education Web site, http: //www.doe.k12.ga.us. Among
them: metal detectors in every school and safety funding through a
tax on violent electronic entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Others called for more attention to students' needs. ``I hate to
say this, but I think for the most part schools are safe, and
there's nothing that we can do that would absolutely prevent what
happened,'' said Cathy Henson, retiring president of the Georgia
PTA and soon-to-be member of the state school board. ``It's really
hard to say what the problem is, other than angry and frustrated
kids with problems, and access to guns.''
</P>
<P>
   D. Smith Pass, who co-chaired a safety and violence task force
that Schrenko initiated in 1997, said balance is needed between
reactive measures, such as more security, and pro-active measures,
such as teaching conflict resolution. ``Hopefully, we will work
ourselves out of the metal detector business,'' she said. ``The
Legislature, the governor, the superintendent of education, and
more importantly, every citizen in the state has to get together
and decide how we get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
