A5327 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-RESIDENTREAX     05-20 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-RESIDENTREAX21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Conyers residents only hope for answer
 &HT;    By Duane D. Stanford
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONYERS, Ga. _ Not since a tornado spun through Conyers in 1973,
killing two and injuring 300, have Rockdale County residents been
forced to recover together from a crisis like Thursday's Heritage
High School shooting. Just hours after the shooting, they came to
the frightening conclusion that, like the twister, this, too, was
unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens in suburbs, not the big city,'' Louise Colquitt,
70, said as she ate fried chicken and okra at the VFW.
</P>
<P>
   Her identical twin, Cille Roberts, quickly added, ``I think it
could happen anywhere with the mentality today.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, the twins and other Rockdale residents jaded by two
years of reports from suburban schools in places like Littleton,
Colo., and Pearl, Miss., still struggled to process the day's news.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just never think it's going to happen where you live,''
said Susan McIntosh, who manages the VFW restaurant, where the
all-you-can-eat country buffet is a favorite.
</P>
<P>
   A small, rural bedroom community in the shadows of Atlanta, 25
miles away, Rockdale is nonetheless used to the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Conyers' Georgia International Horse Park hosted equestrian and
mountain biking during the 1996 Olympics. Nancy Fowler has drawn as
many as 100,000 from Mexico, Argentina and beyond to her White Road
farm north of Interstate 20 when she relays visions she says are
from the Virgin Mary. And the Monastery of the Holy Ghost, about
five miles by car from Heritage High School, sells its fresh-baked
bread to tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday brought a new fame. County and city workers answered
calls from news agencies all over the country and from as far away
as Tokyo. The Heritage shooting stung the community's pride and joy
_ its school system, which is considered among the best in metro
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at all the variables here, you ask that
question, `How could this happen?''', said Conyers Mayor Randy
Mills, placing his blame on loosening societal values. ``This is
bigger than what you see here. How can you get your arms around
this?''
</P>
<P>
   Rockdale Commission Chairman Norman Wheeler expressed similar
feelings: ``When you realize it did happen, it puts you to the
point of almost feeling helpless.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most suburban counties, Rockdale has growing pains.
Developers are building houses faster than commissioners can talk
the federal government into letting them build roads. Longtime
residents think about moving away, frustrated by traffic, dense new
subdivisions and tacky commercial corridors. The dream of bringing
upscale office developments to the county has been stalled by two
years of controversy over its troubled water and sewer system.
</P>
<P>
   But Rockdale is also the kind of place where the South Rockdale
Civic Association eats a potluck supper before its monthly
meetings. It's the kind of place that values parkland and green
spaces. In many parts of Rockdale, neighbors are barely within
shouting distance.
</P>
<P>
   In Rockdale, ideas of God and country are still sacred, and a
.22-caliber rifle is a rite of passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all had them when we were younger,'' Colquitt said at
the VFW. At a nearby table, 68-year-old Jean Clay echoed a
sentiment heard often in Rockdale: ``Put the name of the Lord back
in the school, put discipline back and give the teachers the
control of the classrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   For twins Cille Roberts and Louise Colquitt, the answer isn't so
easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Colquitt said as she stared at a wall and
chewed fried okra. ``Is there a solution?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
