<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAD-BROKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
6 STOCK BROKERS PLEAD GUILTY TO ILLEGAL TRADING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Six stock traders, including four who worked on the
floor of the New York Stock Exchange, pleaded guilty Thursday to
felony charges of illegal stock trading in a case that has raised
questions about the integrity of trading on the nation's biggest
stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Securities regulators and federal prosecutors are continuing to
investigate the extent of illegal trading by brokers who work on
the floor of the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   But the ability of the authorities to bring more charges, either
for criminal wrongdoing or for civil violations of securities laws
or stock exchange rules, appears to have been weakened by the
government's inability in the current case to sort out the specific
illegal acts and the amount of ill-gotten gains.
</P>
<P>
   William Killeen and Thomas Bock, the co-owners of Oakford Corp.,
a trading firm, now defunct, each pleaded guilty to one count of
conspiracy to engage in unauthorized trading. In U.S. District
Court in Manhattan, Killeen and Bock acknowledged that they set up
accounts for use by the four New York Stock Exchange floor traders,
allowed the traders to enter orders at their discretion and then
split with the traders the profits from the activity. Oakford also
pleaded guilty to the same charge.
</P>
<P>
   That type of trading violates federal law and New York Stock
Exchange rules, which generally prohibit brokers on the floor of
the exchange, who are in a position to see large, potentially
market-moving orders being placed, from trading for their own
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Killeen and Bock also pleaded guilty to one count each of tax
evasion, based on separate charges that they used corporate money
to pay personal expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The four exchange traders _ Thomas Cavallino, Edward Mueger and
two brothers, John Savarese and Mark Savarese _ also pleaded guilty
to one count each of conspiracy to engage in illegal trading.
</P>
<P>
   The agreements by the defendants to plead guilty substantially
reduced the charges originally brought in February 1998 by the U.S.
attorney in Manhattan. Prosecutors had also charged each trader
with illegally profiting from their activity.
</P>
<P>
   That charge was dropped from the plea bargain, however, and
prosecutors surprised even the judge overseeing the case when they
said that they could not determine the amount of profits generated
by the trading _ or even which particular trades were illegal.
</P>
<P>
   When they announced the case, prosecutors said the ring of rogue
brokers made more than $11 million in illegal trading profits.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors and securities regulators have since contended that
as many as 64 brokers working on the exchange floor have engaged in
similar trading activities. But the ability of the authorities to
bring criminal charges against other defendants might be hampered
by the government's inability to say which specific trades violated
the rules against discretionary transactions and how much in
illegal profits those trades produced.
</P>
<P>
   Federal sentencing guidelines for the charges to which the two
Oakford officials pleaded guilty put their potential sentences at
15 to 20 months in prison plus probation and a fine. The four floor
brokers face zero to six months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Jed Rakoff, responding with surprise to the prosecutors'
contention that they could not quantify the illegal gains from the
trading scheme, said again Thursday that he might conduct his own
hearing to determine the profits. The results of that hearing might
give the judge cause to set stiffer sentences. A sentencing hearing
is scheduled for Sept. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Five other floor brokers and one clerk previously pleaded guilty
to similar charges, and one has already been sentenced to 15 months
in prison. On Wednesday, prosecutors agreed to drop charges against
another broker, John D'Alessio, who was also a floor official at
the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Stock Exchange spokesman said Thursday that the
exchange's suspension of D'Alessio, which went into effect when the
indictment was announced, was not affected by the pending
withdrawal of the charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
