u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEB-DEATH-PENALTY-NYT     05-20 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEB-DEATH-PENALTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEBRASKA IMPOSES 2-YEAR MORATORIUM ON EXECUTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (mk) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Responding to concerns that the death penalty was
being applied unfairly, the Nebraska Legislature voted Thursday to
impose a two-year moratorium on executions.
</P>
<P>
   Although other states have considered such suspensions,
Nebraska's is the first legislature to approve one. The purpose of
the moratorium would be to allow time for a study on whether the
race or economic status of the defendant, or any other issue
unrelated to the crime, plays a role in death sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   But the legislation faces the likelihood of a veto by Gov. Mike
Johanns, a first-term Republican who supports capital punishment
and has expressed opposition to the moratorium. Still, the governor
said Thursday that he would take a serious look at the measure,
which he has five days to sign or veto. After that, it becomes law
without his approval.
</P>
<P>
   The vote in the one-house Legislature was 27-21, two more votes
in favor than were needed for passage but three fewer than would be
required to override Johanns' veto. And while the governor could
allow the bill to become law without his signature, he suggested
Thursday that he would not choose that path. ``I think I'm here to
make difficult decisions,'' The Associated Press quoted him as
saying.
</P>
<P>
   A co-author of the legislation, state Sen. Kermit Brashear, a
R-Omaha, said he did not oppose the death penalty but was
unconvinced that it was being applied fairly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you love the law and you love justice, you must be
committed to fairness,'' Brashear said. ``And when I see 165
murderers in Nebraska prisons and only 10 are on death row, I want
to know: Why are some of these people treated differently?''
</P>
<P>
   Brashear said that while he did not believe that Nebraska itself
practiced racism in its use of capital punishment, ``there is
clearly a racial component and a socioeconomic component
nationwide'' in death sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   Although they account for only 13 percent of the country's
population, blacks make up 42 percent of the 3,600 or so prisoners
on death rows. In Nebraska, three of the 10 death-row prisoners are
black or American Indian.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the fate of the bill, opponents of the death penalty
said, the vote Thursday sends a heartening message.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Hawkins, executive director of the National Coalition to
Abolish the Death Penalty, based in Washington, said Nebraska, a
mostly conservative state, was not a place where such deep-seated
reservations about executions might have been expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a change in the public attitude on the death
penalty,'' Hawkins said. ``We're very encouraged by what we're
hearing in the heartland. It says something about where Middle
America stands.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins and other foes of capital punishment attributed that
change to a variety of factors. One was Pope John Paul II's
strenuous opposition to executions. Another was the concern over
mistaken convictions that has been stoked by a series of cases in
Illinois. In the last 12 years, a dozen men on death row there have
been exonerated, one of whom, Anthony Porter, came within two days
of being put to death last fall.
</P>
<P>
   A bill has been introduced in the Pennsylvania Legislature that
calls for a moratorium on executions. A bill passed recently in
Montana bans the execution of anyone who is a juvenile when
arrested for the capital offense. Texas, the leader in executions,
is considering a measure that would outlaw putting to death anyone
who is mentally retarded.
</P>
<P>
   The action in state legislatures represents the reversal of a
trend seen three years ago, Hawkins said, when politicians were
looking for ways to give the death penalty broader reach.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the states assess the use of the death penalty, the
number of executions nationwide are soaring.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-four inmates have been executed so far this year, Hawkins
said, predicting that perhaps 100 people will be put to death by
the end of 1999. That would be a record number of executions since
the Supreme Court reinstated capital punishment in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Nebraska has carried out three executions since
1976, the latest in December of 1997. One inmate on death row,
Randolph Reeves, was spared in January when the state Supreme Court
granted a stay of execution based on the promise of equal
protection under the law. A lawyer for Reeves, an Omaha Indian, had
argued that the death penalty discriminated against minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty eight states have the death penalty, although some, like
New York, have not put any inmate to death in more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   States without a death penalty are Alaska, Hawaii, Iowa, Maine,
Massachusetts, Michigan, Minnesota, North Dakota, Rhode Island,
Vermont, West Virginia and Wisconsin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
