and wounded six fellow students at the school on Thursday in yet
another school attack in a comfortable suburban community. After
the shooting the student fell to his knees, stuck a gun in his
mouth and surrendered in tears to Brinkley, according to witnesses.
(Alan S. Weiner for The New York Times)
(NYT22) CONYERS, Ga. -- May 20, 1999 -- GA-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-6, 5-20
-- T. J. Soloman, 15, the alleged gunman in the shootings at
Heritage High School on Thursday, in a photo from the school's 1998
yearbook. Six students were injured in the attack which came
exactly one month after the massacre at Columbine High School in a
Denver suburb. (Alan S. Weiner/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WASHINGTON -- May 20, 1999 -- CONGRESS-GUNS-3, 5-20 --
Vice President Al Gore, center, who cast the tie-breaking vote in
the Senate for approval of new gun control legislation, addresses
reporters while flanked by Democratic Senators on Capitol Hill
following the vote on Thursday. Senators from left are: Diane
Feinstein, Edward Kennedy, Harry Reid, Charles Schumer, Patrick
Leahy, Tom Daschle, Frank Lautenberg, Richard Durbin, Barbara
Boxer, and Barbara Milkulski. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- May 20, 1999 -- CONGRESS-ECON, 5-20 --
Outgoing Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, left, Alan Greenspan,
chairman of the Federal Reserve, prior to their testimony before
the House Finance Committee on Thursday. Greenspan told Congress
that Fed policy-makers support efforts by the Clinton
administration to make the global financial system less susceptible
to future Asian-style currency crises. (Shana Raab/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- May 20, 1999 -- CONGRESS-GUNS-2, 5-20 --
Vice President Gore, second from left, who cast the tie-breaking
vote in the Senate for passage of new gun control legislation,
joins jubilant Democratic Senators at a news conference on Thursday
after the vote. Senators from left are, Charles Schumer, Gore,
Patrick Leahy, Tom Daschle and Frank Lautenberg. The vote came a
few hours after the outbreak of gunfire at an Atlanta-area high
school in which six students were injured. (Justin Lane/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- May 20, 1999 -- CONGRESS-GUNS-1, 5-20 --
Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga., in his office on Thursday after voting to
support the Democratic proposal on new restrictions on gun
transactions at gun shows and pawn shops. The vote came a few hours
after the outbreak of gunfire at an Atlanta-area high school in
which six students were injured. Cleland, in an earlier vote, cast
his ballot against the measure before it was revised. (Justin
Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
