woman. (White House Photo/Cox Newspapers) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BELMONT, Mass. -- May 20, 1999 -- TOYS-MUSCLES, 5-20 --
Dr. Harrison Pope and Jay Borowiecki with their action figures.
Pope, a researcher at McLean Hospital, has studied how the plastic
body shapes of Star Wars and GI Joe toy figures have bulked up
since they were introduced in the 1960s and 70s. He believes the
action figures promote an unrealistic body image for young men,
encouraging them to use steroids and work out with weights
compulsively. (Bill Green/Boston Globe Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) ROSLINDALE, Mass. -- May 20, 1999 -- HOLOCAUST-STLOUIS-2,
5-20 --Bella Loeb, 95, left, with her daughter Ruth Loeb Forrest at
the Hebrew Rehabilitation Center for the Aged earlier this week.
Ruth Loeb Forrest was among the 900 Jews who sailed on the St.
Louis in 1939 across the Atlantic to Cuba where they thought they
had the paperwork necessary to await immigration to the United
States. Instead, they were rebuffed by Cuban officials, denied
entry into the United States and eventually forced back to Europe.
More than 220 subsequently died in the Holocaust. (Suzanne
Kreiter/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) LEXINGTON, Mass. -- May 20, 1999 -- HOLOCAUST-STLOUIS-1,
5-20 -- Liane Reif-Lehrer during a walk in the woods in the Boston
suburb. Reif-Lehrer was 4 years old in 1939 when, along with family
members, sailed aboard the St. Louis from Europe to Cuba where they
thought they had the paperwork necessary to await immigration to
the United States. Instead, the 900 Jews aboard the ship were
rebuffed by Cuban officials, denied entry into the United States
and eventually forced back to Europe. More than 220 subsequently
died in the Holocaust. (Suzanne Kreiter/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) KOSARE, Kosovo -- May 20, 1999 -- KOSOVO-KLA, 5-20 --
Kosovo Liberation Army fighters approach a load of ammunition
transported to their base on a tractor. A loose collection of
clan-led militias before the NATO air war began, the KLA lacks
sufficient training, heavy armament and vehicles hearty enough to
handle the rugged mountain tracks and be a stronger challenge to
Yugoslav forces. (Charles W. Holmes/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) CONYERS, Ga. -- May 20, 1999 -- GA-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-3,
05-20 -- Freshmen Christine Tate, 14, center, and Joanna Stuckey
comfort each other as by Joanna's mother, Sue Stuckey offers her
support. Six students were shot with minor injuries Thursday at
Heritage High School when a student, identified as a Heritage
sophomore, opened fire about 15 minutes before classes were to
begin. (John Spink/Atlanta Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) CONYERS, Ga. -- May 20, 1999 -- GA-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-2,
05-20 -- Vice Principal of Heritage High School in Conyers, Andy
Symons, directs confused students on the school's athletic field.
Students were released onto the athletic field where they were
reunited with their parents after a sophomore, who was apprehended,
opened fire at the school. Six students were suffered minor
injuries on the final day of classes for seniors at Heritage. (John
Spink/Atlanta Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) CONYERS, Ga. -- May 20, 1999 -- GA-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-1,
05-20 -- Rebecca Harris embraces daughter, Bonnie, a 17-year old
junior. Six students were shot with minor injuries Thursday at
Heritage High School when a student, identified as a Heritage
sophomore, opened fire about 15 minutes before classes were to
begin. Students were in lock down until the suspect was apprehended
and then released to the athletic field where parents reunited with
their children. (John Spink/Atlanta Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
