<HEADER>
A5338 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAYTONA-BLACKS-NYT &LR;      05-20 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAYTONA-BLACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACKS SUE HOTEL, CHARGING BIAS AT COLLEGE REUNION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Black plaintiffs filed a federal lawsuit
Thursday charging that the Adam's Mark Daytona Beach Resort, one of
the more luxurious hotels here, discriminated against
African-Americans who had gathered in April for the Black College
Reunion, an annual event that draws young black men and women from
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court in Orlando, asserts,
among other things, that the hotel overcharged the event's
participants for rooms, required full payment in advance by check
or money order, as well as demanding a $100 refundable damage
deposit, a $25 deposit to have room telephones turned on and a
deposit of $300 for access to minibars. None of these policies, the
lawyers contend, applied to whites who were staying at the hotel at
the same time.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also asserts that Adam's Mark Daytona required blacks
who stayed at the hotel during the reunion to wear bright orange
wristbands to indicate that they were guests and to buy an
additional wristband, for $50, for anyone who wanted to visit them.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, Fred Kummer, chief executive officer of
HBE Corp., owner of the Adam's Mark, said Thursday that it was
standard policy for hotel to require guests to wear wristbands
during special events ``to ensure that guests do not exceed the
maximum room occupancy at such events, thus violating fire codes
and impacting the quality of the stay for other hotel guests.''
Kummer said the hotel also asked guests for a $100 damage deposit
during other large Daytona Beach gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The refundable deposit required at BCR was no different than
that which is usually requested for any hotel guests who do not
offer credit cards at registration for the coverage of incidental
expenses,'' Kummer said in his statement.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the plaintiffs said, however, that they were required
to pay deposits even though they paid for their rooms with credit
cards.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit asserts that uniformed officers from the Daytona
Beach Police Department and the Volusia County Sheriff's Office
were out in force at the hotel to make sure blacks were wearing
their wristbands. Sherri Davis, a spokesman for the Daytona Beach
Police Department, said Thursday that she did not have records
immediately available on whether officers were on or off duty while
working at the hotel. The sheriff's office could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was in county jail the whole weekend,'' said
Napoleon Berrian, 28, who drove from Atlanta with his brother and
two friends to stay at the Adam's Mark during the reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Latoya Straughn, 25, of Ocala, Fla., said she had attended the
reunion with three female friends and that they opted to wear the
``cheap, plastic'' orange bands on their ankles, rather than on
their wrists, where they would clash with their clothes. As a
result, Ms. Straughn said, ``every five feet, and/or every 10
minutes,'' an officer would ask her for proof that she was
registered at the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the plaintiffs said that during the weekend they
repeatedly noticed white guests not wearing wristbands and not
being challenged.
</P>
<P>
   The Black College Reunion has provoked increasing debate in
Daytona Beach, a city of 62,000 residents that consists of an
overwhelmingly white beach community on a barrier island and a more
heavily black section on the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Begun in 1984 as a relatively small social weekend involving
students from two black schools, Florida A&AMP;M University in
Tallahassee and Bethune-Cookman College in Daytona Beach, the event
now attracts more than 100,000 people. Its size now puts it on par
with other social events in Daytona like Race Week, when stock car
fans gather for the Daytona 500, Bike Week, when thousands of
motorcycle enthusiasts flock here, and Spring Break, the
traditional six-week-long party that attracts hordes of exuberant
college students.
</P>
<P>
   While the crowds at Race Week, Bike Week and Spring Break are
overwhelmingly white, Black College Reunion is the only major
annual event in Daytona whose participants are almost all black.
</P>
<P>
   Business executives, city officials and some residents complain
of noise by participants and assert that the primary activity of
the weekend, cruising and socializing on Route A1A, the main road,
creates horrendous traffic jams.
</P>
<P>
   Since the late 1980s, local officials have felt that Spring
Break also was getting out of hand, said Larry Fornari, president
of the Hotel/Motel Association of Volusia County. Daytona Beach has
tried to discourage visits by rowdy college students by emphasizing
that laws will be strictly enforced, he said, and the city has
sponsored concerts and beach sports to relieve congestion on the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   Fornari said Daytona Beach had tried a similar approach with the
Black College Reunion, and failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a cruise and see-and-be-seen event,'' he said. ``That's
what they want to do while they're here. I don't think they want to
be involved in other events, or history has shown that they don't
want to be in other events. And that poses a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The trouble escalated last year when a male participant from
Orlando engaged in a gun battle with police, wounding four officers
before he was killed. Some city leaders, including Mayor Bud Asher,
said later that they wanted to get rid of the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black College Reunion as presently constituted is neither a
desirable or an acceptable event for Daytona Beach,'' Asher said at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the City Council passed a plan that would allow
police officers to halt all traffic heading over the six bridges
leading onto the commercial beach strip. Officers would allow only
residents, employees of city businesses and hotel guests to drive
across the bridges.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
sued the city, contending that the traffic plan violated the rights
of assembly of the black participants in the reunion weekend. In
April, Judge Patricia Fawsett of the U.S. District Court in Orlando
agreed and issued an injunction banning the city from instituting
its traffic plan.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the plaintiffs contend that executives of the Adam's
Mark were among the most vociferous in demanding that the city halt
the Black College Reunion. After the judge threw out Daytona
Beach's traffic plan, the lawyers assert that hotel executives
decided to make the event so unpleasant to the participants that
they would not come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Adams Mark incident, the mistreatment of the BCR students
did not occur in a vacuum,'' said Bruce Gear, a lawyer with the
NAACP.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
