r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTHEON-SFCHRON &LR;      05-20 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTHEON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Healtheon Confirms Deal _ Stock Jumps
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Dan Fost  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Healtheon Corp. shares soared another 25 percent yesterday after
the company confirmed it is merging with WebMD to create what could
become the Internet's leading provider of health care information
and services.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara's Healtheon will exchange 1.815 of its shares for
each of privately held WebMD's 54 million shares outstanding. That
would value WebMD at $9.9 billion, based on Healtheon's closing
price.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon's stock soared $20.38 to $100.63 yesterday, giving it
a market value of $7.1 billion. The company's stock has surged 114
percent since rumors of the merger first surfaced a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   The new entity will have its corporate headquarters in Atlanta
and a ``technology headquarters'' in Santa Clara. It will be named
Healtheon/WebMD, but all its products will be called WebMD.
</P>
<P>
   The deal attracted big investments from other industry players.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is paying $250 million for an 11 percent stake in the
new company. Additionally, Microsoft has committed $150 million to
help cover the $29.95 monthly fee for 11,000 physicians, allowing
them to subscribe free to the service, and another $100 million for
advertising and sponsorships.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont Co., a large drugmaker, has committed $180 million to
underwrite physician subscription fees and $40 million in
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Others, including Intel Corp., Excite Inc. and the Japanese
media company Softbank Corp., will invest an additional $110
million in the venture.
</P>
<P>
   The merged company will be run by WebMD's 29-year-old chief
executive, Jeff Arnold. Healtheon CEO Mike Long, 46, becomes
chairman and chief operating officer. Healtheon co-founder and
Chairman Jim Clark, 53, will be a board member.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are betting that the new firm, by using the Internet,
will help streamline the inefficient but lucrative health care
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Health care information management is in the dark ages, so
it's ripe for the sort of automation the Internet can bring to
it,'' said David Simons, managing director of Digital Video
Investments, a New York research firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real stumbling block is you have this myriad, incredibly
disparate, endless array of legacy systems, none of which were ever
designed to talk to each other,'' Simons said. ``Getting that to
work together is the real challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet won't necessarily fix the problem, he said. Taming
health care ``has been one of the Holy Grails of the Information
Age,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal draws much of its cachet from the involvement of Clark,
who has struck it rich for the third time. Clark also helped found
Silicon Graphics and Netscape Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's 11.7 million Healtheon shares were worth $1.17 billion
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The merger brings the business-to-business goals of Healtheon
together with WebMD's consumer-oriented services, said David
Restrepo, the health analyst at Jupiter Communications in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon has used the Internet to connect physicians,
hospitals, insurance companies and pharmaceutical firms.
</P>
<P>
   WebMD _ which was founded in 1996 as a cardiac monitoring
company, but sold that business last year to reinvent itself as an
Internet firm _ initially provided online information to doctors
but more recently acquired two companies that serve health care
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon/WebMD is likely to acquire more companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect them to get an online vitamin vendor or drugstore or
develop it themselves,'' Restrepo said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether these two money-losing companies can merge themselves
into profitability is by no means certain.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``It remains to be seen whether they can pull off this very
ambitious project,'' Restrepo said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
