<HEADER>
A5340 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-CLINTON-N     05-20 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TELLS LITTLETON SHOOTINGS `PIERCED THE SOUL' OF THE
NATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also GA-SCHOOL-SHOOTING and GA-SCHOOL-SHOOTER) (DW) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Against the grim backdrop of yet another
school shooting, this one in Georgia, President Clinton told this
grief-racked but determined Rocky Mountain town Thursday that the
massacre here had ``pierced the soul of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that was partly because of the number of dead, 15,
and partly because suburban Littleton is like so many other places
in America.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Littleton shootings had caught the attention of the
whole world, the president said, the community now had a chance to
teach everyone about overcoming hatreds, distrust and the urge for
vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your tragedy, though it is unique in its magnitude, is, as you
so well know, not an isolated event,'' Clinton told an audience of
nearly 2,000 people, mostly students, packed into a high school
gymnasium about a 15-minute drive from Columbine High School, where
the shootings took place a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know somehow that what happened to you has pierced the soul
of America,'' he said, ``and it gives you a chance to be heard in a
way no one else can be heard, by the president and by ordinary
people in every community in this country. You can help us to build
a better future for all our children.''
</P>
<P>
   The president also made a pointed reference to the arsenal
amassed by the two killers, saying that access to such weapons
``can break the dam of decency and humanity in the most vulnerable
children.''
</P>
<P>
   At several points in the program, at which Hillary Rodham
Clinton, the first lady, also spoke, the audience responded with
cheers and foot-stomping, giving the event the incongruous feel of
a pep rally. The Clintons seemed surprised by the reaction, but
they quickly interpreted the cheers as a determination of spirit,
which they both lauded.
</P>
<P>
   The president and first lady spoke after meeting privately for
90 minutes with the families of all but one of the 13 victims in
the April 20 rampage. The parents of John Tomlin did not attend.
Not included were the families of Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold,
the two boys who killed their classmates and a teacher, and then
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Shoels, whose son Isaiah, 18, was one of those killed,
said afterward that he had given the president a two-page letter
that Clinton promised he would read. Shoels said: ``Such a tragedy
as this, we should use it as a tool to make change. I cry before I
go to sleep, and in the morning I still feel the tears. But I have
to stay strong as a human being.''
</P>
<P>
   In the role of national healer, which Clinton said he had
assumed all too often in his six years as president, he also
extended some compassion to the killers, saying that their struggle
with demons is a universal one.
</P>
<P>
   ``These dark forces that take over people and make them murder
are the extreme manifestation of fear and rage with which every
human has to do combat,'' he said. ``The older you get, the more
you'll know that a great deal of life is the struggle against every
person's own smallness and fear and anger and a continuing effort
not to blame other people for our own shortcomings or our fears.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, Clinton placed phone calls to five of the
students who are still hospitalized with injuries from the
shootings. In a surprise for the audience here, two of those
students _ Sean Graves and Patrick Ireland _ attended the
president's speech, whisked to the school by ambulance. Their
introduction from the stage brought a thunderous and emotional show
of support. Patrick was the student who had been captured on film
crashing through a window in the school to escape the siege.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging the periodic cheers, Mrs. Clinton, who spoke
before her husband, told the audience, ``We have suffered and wept
and prayed and hoped and, yes, cheered, as lives have been mourned,
as those who are injured have healed.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the Columbine seniors would be graduating on
Saturday, Clinton said he knew the commencement would be
bittersweet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even your archrivals at Chatfield will be cheering you on,''
he told them. ``When you hear those people cheer for you, I want
you to hear the voice of America, because America will be cheering
you on. And remember that a commencement is not an end, it is a
beginning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
