<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5343 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GENENTECH-SFCHRON &LR;      05-20 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENENTECH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Jury Gets Purloined DNA Case   By Tom Abate 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Which scientist lied?
</P>
<P>
   That's what a federal jury in San Francisco must decide after
hearing closing arguments yesterday in an extraordinary patent
infringement case that pits the University of California against
Genentech Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The case has rocked the biotech world because the two scientists
who led Genentech's human growth hormone project in 1979 _ Peter
Seeburg and David Goeddel _ took opposite sides in the case and
essentially called each other liars on the stand.
</P>
<P>
   Summing up the six-week trial, UC attorney Gerald Dodson tried
to persuade jurors that, 20 years ago, Seeburg and Goeddel made a
secret pact to use a patented DNA sample _ which Seeburg filched
from a UC lab _ to create Genentech's lucrative growth hormone
drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``Genentech has never paid UC a dime for the commercial use of
this invention,'' Dodson said.
</P>
<P>
   UC hasn't filed a damage claim yet, but Dodson has said his
client could seek royalties and punitive damages up to $1.2
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides predicted victory. Genentech has said it would
exercise its right to appeal any negative verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech attorney John Kidd told jurors his client doesn't owe
the university any money because it hadn't used UC's DNA or
infringed on UC's patent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pioneered the work, we created the industry, we made a
medicine for people, not the university,'' Kidd said.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides devoted much of yesterday's closing arguments to
painting different pictures of Seeburg, who took the stand for UC,
and Goeddel, who testified for Genentech.
</P>
<P>
   Goeddel maintained that his former colleague Seeburg invented
the story that they had conspired to fake their experiments at
Genentech.
</P>
<P>
   Seeburg emerged as the most complicated character in this
courtroom drama.
</P>
<P>
   The German-born scientist, now 53, came to the United States in
the late 1970s to do research at the University of California at
San Francisco. In spring 1978, Seeburg was one of three UC
scientists who identified the DNA for human growth hormone. Dodson
called it a breakthrough invention for which UC immediately filed a
patent, naming Seeburg and several colleagues as co-inventors.
</P>
<P>
   But in November 1978, after a falling out with his UCSF boss,
Seeburg quit the university to join Genentech's crash program to
create a growth hormone drug. Seeburg testified that just before
midnight on Dec. 31, 1978, he snuck back into his old UCSF lab,
took a sample of the DNA that UC was trying to patent, and stashed
it in a refrigerator at Genentech.
</P>
<P>
   Despite UC demands that the DNA be returned, Seeburg testified
it remained in refrigeration until early May 1979. During that
spring, Goeddel had joined Genentech's project to help cultivate
its own batch of growth hormone DNA that owed nothing to the UC
sample.
</P>
<P>
   But Seeburg testified that in early May, he and Goeddel
concluded the Genentech effort had failed. He testified that he and
Goeddel decided to use the UC sample in their experiment and to
keep this a secret _ faking the data they reported in a 1979
scientific paper which they published in the journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
   Although Seeburg was admitting his part in scientific fraud,
Dodson painted the German scientist's confession in the best light.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man has a scientific reputation,'' Dodson said of
Seeburg, whose work until now has made him highly regarded. ``He
has put that on the line to come here and tell the truth ... about
the agreement with Dr. Goeddel that he can no longer keep.''
</P>
<P>
   Genentech's lawyers attacked Seeburg's credibility, using his
own testimony about marital and drug problems during this period in
1979 and noting that by his own admission he worked only an hour or
two a day some days. Kidd said Goeddel joined the project after
Seeburg ``failed to perform'' and suggested that Seeburg grew
resentful when Goeddel, five years Seeburg's junior, was glorified
as principal inventor of Genentech's growth hormone drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he (Seeburg) is finally getting even with the person who
stole his dream and got the credit he wanted,'' Kidd said.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech lawyers also reminded the jury that Seeburg, one of
the named inventors on the UC patent, stands to win perhaps 10
percent of any money that the jury might award UC. That would work
out to $120 million if UC got all the punitive damages it has
requested.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to tearing down Seeburg's testimony, Genentech
sought to build up Goeddel, who founded his own biotech firm,
Tularik Inc., after leaving Genentech.
</P>
<P>
   Much of yesterday's arguments revolved around the contents of a
black lab notebook in which Goeddel kept track of the
Genentech-sponsored growth hormone experiment. That notebook is
essential for Genentech to prove that its growth hormone differs in
important ways from UC's variety.
</P>
<P>
   UC's outside experts testified that in the May period _ when
Seeburg says he and Goeddel secretly used UC's DNA _ the two
Genentech scientists didn't have enough time to perform the
experiment Goeddel described.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech attorneys countered with testimony from Goeddel's
former lab assistant, Elizabeth McLeod Yelverton, now a genetics
professor at the University of Southern Alabama, corroborating
Goeddel's version of events.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Judge Charles Legge gave the nine jurors the weekend off
before ordering them to reconvene Monday morning to begin
deliberations. A verdict is expected next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
