<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0458 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5349 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-ABORTION-LAW-ART-9     05-20 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-ABORTION-LAW-ART-930&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITMAN BACKS BILL THAT RESTRICTS ABORTION RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JERRY GRAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ For the first time in her political career, Gov.
Christie Whitman said Thursday that she would support legislation
restricting some abortion rights, endorsing an Assembly bill that
would require parental notification before a teen-age girl can get
an abortion in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, which was approved Thursday afternoon by the
Assembly Judiciary Committee in a 5-2 vote, still faces a vote in
the full Assembly _ where the speaker, Jack Collins, said there was
broad support _ and in the Senate, which could make changes to it.
But with the backing of Whitman, the legislation is expected to
become law soon.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman, a moderate Republican who has been one of the most
outspoken supporters of abortion rights in her party, had
previously opposed parental notification. But, facing a race next
year for the U.S. Senate and not wishing to alienate conservatives,
she yielded on the issue after persuading the sponsors of the bill
to soften some of the language in their proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bill released from the Assembly Judiciary Committee today
appears to strike an appropriate balance between the legitimate
needs of a young woman and the rightful interests of her parents,''
Whitman said in a statement that her office issued within an hour
of the committee's vote. ``It is a vastly improved measure.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the changes she made was a broadening of the circumstances
under which a judge could grant a waiver of the rule; for instance,
allowing a teen-ager to get an abortion if she seemed mature enough
to make that decision herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``In its current form, it appears to provide a common-sense
solution to the problem of respecting parental rights and
preserving personal choices,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Even as opponents of abortion cheered Whitman's position on the
issue, a group of moderate Republicans who support abortion rights
praised the governor and tried to make sure that she was protected
from criticism from the left.
</P>
<P>
   ``This does not represent a change in Whitman's strong support
of abortion rights,'' Lynn Grefe, national director of the
Republican Pro-Choice Coalition, said in a statement that Whitman's
office circulated to reporters along with the governor's statement.
``This bill would pass with or without her signature, and therefore
she used her considerable knowledge and understanding to insure
that no teen will be harmed. Once again, the pro-choice community
applauds her political acumen and work on behalf of women.''
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey has long been considered a bulwark when it comes to
abortion rights, and any movement in that position, no matter how
slight, is sure to attract national attention in the abortion
debate. Supporters of measure said that they had already been
contacted by abortion opponents in other states, including New
York, to share information on the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The major roadblock to parental notification may be the New
Jersey courts, which have traditionally been unwavering in support
of abortion rights and have struck down previous efforts that they
found infringed on minors' rights to have access to abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the legislation, which included representatives of
the New Jersey Bar Association and the American Civil Liberties
Union, testified Thursday that they considered the measure
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, they said, it would violate the equal protection
guarantees of the federal and state constitutions since the state
does not require parental notification for a pregnant minor to
receive medical treatment and care when she carries a baby for a
full term.
</P>
<P>
   The notification bill, which was sponsored by Assemblyman John
Rooney and Assemblywoman Marion Crecco, both Republicans, would
require doctors to notify a parent or guardian before performing or
inducing an abortion on an unmarried girl under 18. Doctors would
be required to notify the parent either personally or by certified
mail, and an abortion could not be performed until at least 48
hours after the parent was notified.
</P>
<P>
   But in an effort to meet constitutional concerns and to make the
legislation politically palatable to the governor, the sponsors
amended their bill before the Judiciary Committee Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Language in the original proposal had mentioned only biological
or adoptive parents, but Whitman insisted that it be expanded to
include any adult who assumed the parental role, like an aunt or
uncle, a grandparent or an older sibling.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was also amended to broaden the exceptions to parental
notification. In its original form, a girl could petition a
Superior Court judge for a waiver if she could demonstrate that she
was a victim of abuse, cruelty or neglect.
</P>
<P>
   It was changed, again at the Whitman administration's
insistence, to read that a waiver could be granted if the judge
found convincing evidence that the girl was ``sufficiently mature''
to decide whether to have an abortion; that there was a pattern of
physical, sexual or emotional abuse of the girl by the parent or
guardian; and if for any other reason the notification of the
parent was ``not in the best interests of the minor.''
</P>
<P>
   To try to avoid a constitutional challenge, sponsors at the last
minute added a clause that would allow doctors to perform an
abortion on a minor without parental notification if the doctor
could certify that the abortion was necessary because of a medical
emergency.
</P>
<P>
   A medical emergency is defined as a condition in which an
immediate abortion is required because of risk of death or risk of
substantial and irreversible impairment of a major bodily function.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even though Thursday's vote did not go to the heart of the
abortion debate _ whether a minor can or cannot have an abortion in
New Jersey _ it was a significant gain for anti-abortion forces,
who have tried unsuccessfully since 1989 to get a parental
notification bill through the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Polls have consistently shown that most New Jersey residents
back the right of a woman to have a legal abortion. But a
Quinnipiac College poll taken in March 1998 showed that residents
also favored some limits. By a 71 percent to 24 percent margin, the
poll showed that New Jersey residents supported a requirement that
parental consent be given before a girl under 18 years of age could
have an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   In lobbying legislators and in their testimony before the
Judiciary Committee Thursday, proponents of the notification bill
cited those poll results and a recent study by the Alan Guttmacher
Institute that showed New Jersey had the highest rate of teen-age
pregnancies in the nation and the highest rate of abortion among
teen-agers _ 58 percent of all adolescent pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly could vote on the legislation as early as Monday,
and supporters said their goal was to get the bill through the
Senate and on to the governor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 2153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
