<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5352 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTHEON-WEBMD-ART-N     05-20 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTHEON-WEBMD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 HEALTH-RELATED INTERNET FIRMS TO COMBINE IN $7.85 BILLION DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ga.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Healtheon Corp., a rapidly growing Silicon Valley start-up with
big ideas for changing the health care system, said Thursday that
it would buy WebMD Inc., a seven-month-old Internet company, in a
stock deal valued at $7.85 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon is also allying itself with some of technology's
best-known names, selling $250 million of its high-flying stock to
Microsoft Corp. and $110 million to other backers, including Intel
Corp. and Excite Inc., the Internet portal company.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, which will have a stake of more than 10 percent in
the combined company, Healtheon/WebMD, also pledged $100 million in
advertising, which would be added to $40 million already committed
for advertising by DuPont Co. It is Microsoft's first big foray
into Internet health care.
</P>
<P>
   The new company said it would also have promotional and other
tie-ins with an array of media companies including CNN, MSNBC and
the Westwood One radio chain and Internet companies like MSN and
Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon, which went public at $8 a share in February, reached
a high of $114 Thursday before closing at $100.625, up $20.375.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to buying other companies, ``their stock is free
money,'' said Linda Killian, a portfolio manager with the
Renaissance IPO Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Although they have relatively few customers, and no profits, a
common Internet predicament, Healtheon and WebMD have sweeping
aspirations. Healtheon, which has been growing through
acquisitions, offers electronic processing of health care claims
and online registration for health plans, It also links doctors
over the Internet with hospitals, pharmacies, laboratories and
insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   WebMD, a privately held company based in Atlanta, specializes in
Internet support groups in which consumers can learn about
health-care subjects like nutrition and cancer, as well as
physicians' services.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the companies hope to sell electronic products to
hundreds of thousands of doctors whom they covet as gatekeepers to
$800 million in annual health care spending. The doctors could also
become a lucrative audience for drug company advertising and other
medical marketers.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate goal would be to link all types of customers and
providers of health care, using the Internet as an end run around
the many obstacles to communication between thousands of computer
systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to bring the advantages of the Internet to health
care, an industry that has been slow to adopt new technology,''
said James Clark, the co-founder of Netscape who also co-founded
Healtheon in 1996 in Santa Clara, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   But for just that reason, some analysts questioned whether
Healtheon and WebMD could ever herd thousands of notoriously
independent-minded doctors into its system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Health care is such a cottage industry and it is so hard to
link all the doctors,'' said James Hudak, a managing partner of
Andersen Consulting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Health is fundamentally different than securities trading or
auctioning on the Internet, like Ebay,'' he added. ``Health is not
a commodity.'' As for quality and accuracy, he said, ``you have to
know, Is the information you are getting correct or is it coming
from some cyberquack?''
</P>
<P>
   Privacy of medical records of patients is another sensitive
issue. WebMD chief executive Jeffrey Arnold said that personal
information about consumers would not be sold without their
consent. The WebMD Web site says that data about consumers will be
sold only in broad aggregate form, for example as percentages.
Healtheon chief executive W. Michael Long said the company ruled
out selling personal data to pharmaceutical companies or anybody
else.
</P>
<P>
   As for protecting the data, from unauthorized intruders, Long
said that ``security of the data has been a prime focus of our
engineering over the last three years,'' from encryption into
secure codes to storage on data bases. ``We have been a market
leader in demonstrating that the Internet can be as secure an
environment as any,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold of WebMD declined to disclose his company's finances. He
changed the subject to $500 million in commitments, including an
additional $150 million from Microsoft, which he said had been
promised by companies that would subsidize doctors who would be
recruited to use the company's Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   That $150 million would provide free introductory access to
180,000 doctors for five years. There are 5,000 doctors now using
the system and 49,000 more whose fees have already been paid by
sponsoring organizations like health systems.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon/WebMD hopes to have positive cash flow by the end of
next year. But before it can make a profit, it faces several years
of charging off good will that it acquired in its chain of mergers
and acquisitions. Healtheon and Mede America, another merger in
process, have combined annual cash flow of about $130 million.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon processes electronic claims for United Healthcare
Corp., which has an 11 percent ownership stake in Healtheon through
a business developed by United and later acquired by Healtheon.
Cigna Corp. also buys claims processing services.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon also provides online enrollment services for a few
thousand members of health plans served by Blue Shield of
California. And Healtheon processes lab test orders for SmithKline
Beecham Clinical laboratories, which is being purchased by Quest
Diagnostics Inc.
</P>
<P>
   In the merger, 1.815 Healtheon shares will be exchanged for each
WebMD share, so that existing shareholders of each company will
have about 50 percent of the new company.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
