<HEADLINE>
FROGS! WE GOT FROGS! ON WITH THE SHOW! 
(ATTN: N.Y.)
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By ELIZABETH CAMPBELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HURST, Texas _ Michelle Werthen knows the fate of the 16th
Annual Lake Worth (Texas) Bullfrog Festival is on her shoulders _
or at least her patio.
</P>
<P>
   Seven sage green bullfrogs arrived at her apartment on Thursday
from New York, and they are the stars of the festival in the Fort
Worth suburb, which began Wednesday and runs through Sunday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just can't escape,'' Werthen said as the $125 bullfrogs
lounged lazily in a net-covered fish pond on her apartment patio in
Hurst, just outside Fort Worth. ``When they came out of their box,
they stretched and yawned.''
</P>
<P>
   The frog-finding frenzy reached fever pitch after a newspaper
article described the local chamber of commerce's desperate search
for bullfrogs. Executive Director Judy Haas was led to Ward's
Natural Science Establishment in Rochester, N.Y., which shipped the
frogs by Federal Express.
</P>
<P>
   Werthen's guests, renowned for their jumping prowess, arrived
about noon in a wax-covered box cushioned in moss. Werthen said
that when the delivery driver saw the ``live frogs'' label, he
figured she had ordered a meal for a pet boa constrictor.
</P>
<P>
   The seven frogs appeared fine in a prefabricated fish pond with
heavy netting securely clamped on it to keep the frogs from leaping
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they were happy to get out of their cramped
quarters,'' Werthen said.
</P>
<P>
   She has plenty of crickets to feed them before their race at 2
p.m. Saturday. FrifArM
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
