<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSMETICS-MARKETPLACE-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COTY IS IN TALKS TO ACQUIRE DEBT-RIDDEN REVLON
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DANA CANEDY and LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coty Inc., a leading seller of fragrances and cosmetics, is in
talks to acquire part or all of Revlon Inc., the debt-ridden
cosmetics company controlled by billionaire Ronald Perelman,
executives close to the negotiations said.
</P>
<P>
   The talks are preliminary and could fall apart over price or
other terms. Another suitor might also step forward with an
attractive offer.
</P>
<P>
   A combination with Coty would enable Perelman to rid himself of
an investment that has proved disappointing and give Coty a
dominant position in the United States and a stronger brand to
market worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   If a deal is completed, Revlon would become part of Benckiser
NV, the Dutch consumer products company, which has been on an
acquisition binge and picked up Coty in 1992. Revlon's sales last
year were $2.2 billion. Coty had sales of $1.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies declined to confirm they were in negotiations,
and a spokesman for Perelman's holding company, MacAndrews &AMP;
Forbes, said he had no comment. But Revlon's stock has risen more
than 22 percent this week on speculation that a deal was imminent.
Shares of Revlon gained 75 cents Thursday, to $29.25.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was so heavy on Tuesday, in fact, that the New York
Stock Exchange requested the company issue a statement explaining
the ``unusual market activity.'' The volume was twice the daily
average for the last three months. Revlon stated then that it was
not its policy to comment on rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Still analysts and industry experts said that the two companies
would be a good fit. Revlon products, including the Revlon, Almay
and Ultima II makeup brands, are sold in the same aisles as Coty's
Jovan Musk, Lady Stetson and Sand and Sable fragrances.
</P>
<P>
   Coty has long sought this kind of stellar cosmetics brand to
complement its fragrance business in the United States. Revlon, for
its part, has been struggling to increase its international
presence, just as Estee Lauder has succeeded in doing.
</P>
<P>
   A deal could not come soon enough for Revlon. In addition to
declining orders from retailers here, the company has suffered from
weakened consumer purchasing power abroad. At the same time, it
faces stiffer competition from Procter &AMP; Gamble Co., which is
taking on the Almay line with the U.S. introduction this year of
Oil of Olay cosmetics. Johnson &AMP; Johnson, too, recently added
makeup to its Neutrogena skin-care line.
</P>
<P>
   The inventory crunch at Revlon and problems abroad have led to a
string of disappointing financial results and a sagging stock
price, which sank to $12 last fall.
</P>
<P>
   The stock's dismal performance prompted Perelman to announce in
April that he would consider selling what has been the jewel of his
portfolio. At the time, Revlon said it had retained Goldman, Sachs
&AMP; Co. and Lazard Freres &AMP; Co. to review the company's options.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Coty, other names that have been circulating as
potential bidders are Unilever NV, the Dutch consumer goods company
that makes Elizabeth Arden cosmetics; the Shiseido Co., a Japanese
cosmetics company, and Procter &AMP; Gamble, which makes Cover Girl
cosmetics. Procter &AMP; Gamble is the most unlikely buyer for the
entire company, however, because it would almost certainly face
antitrust problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me one of the last great, well-known brand names
to be up for sale,'' William Steele, managing director of Banc of
America Securities, said. ``There is a scarcity value involved
there, so I would expect a number of companies to look at this.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Analysts estimate that Revlon could fetch between $35 and $50 a
share. That amount would be in the range of prices for other
consumer companies, which tend to sell for 1 1/2 to two times
revenue. And while the Revlon name is certainly worth a premium,
they say, the company has lost some of its negotiating power
because of its recent poor performance, heavy debt level of $1.7
billion and Perelman's apparent eagerness to sell.
</P>
<P>
   If the price does not become a sticking point, purchasing Revlon
would certainly fit into Coty's growth strategy. The company
acquired 14 businesses between 1990 and 1996 and says it wants to
become the premier global fragrance and cosmetics business. In a
business outline, Coty said it wanted to ``gain a seat at the table
with L'Oreal, Avon and Estee Lauder.''
</P>
<P>
   Coty has a strong perfume and makeup business worldwide. It
recently expanded into Brazil, Hungary, Colombia, Ukraine and
Turkey. And it plans to push into developing countries in regions
including Latin America, Eastern Europe and Asia. In the United
States the company is strong in mass retail perfumes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big hole is in the U.S. mass makeup business,'' Allan G.
Mottus, publisher of the Informationist, a trade publication, said.
``They have nothing. That would give them a marriage of two
distinct groups, being fragrance and makeup, one that I think could
be a very powerful entity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
