<SLUG> BC-BBO-BURKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS' BURKS POSITIONED FOR SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Ellis Burks was a free agent with two bad
knees. That can be a deadly blow to a baseball player's bank
account.
</P>
<P>
   Free agents with physical problems usually have a hard time
getting a job in the off-season. Most of the time they end up
facing two dreary options: a one-year contract laden with
incentives but with a low salary, or a minor-league contract with
an invitation to spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Burks was spared such fates this past off-season. The San
Francisco Giants wanted him back, bad knees and all. Just a few
days after declaring for free agency, Burks reached an agreement
with the Giants on a two-year, $10 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the guys we wanted to keep,'' Giants manager
Dusty Baker said. ``We didn't want him to get out there and be
entertained by other clubs or be flirting with anybody. He's not
only a big part of the spirit of the team, but he's also one of our
big-ability guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Burks, ``They offered me a two-year deal even though they
knew I was going to have knee surgery. They had a lot of faith in
me and showed a lot of confidence in my ability. So I said, I'm
staying, no questions asked.'',There was one stipulation: a
position change. Burks once refused to move from center to right
field while with the Boston Red Sox, believing it was a demotion.
Now he was insisting upon it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps the body,'' said Burks, who won a Gold Glove as a
center fielder in 1990. ``You don't have to run as much. You don't
have to back up everywhere like you do in center. Right field is
less stress and strain on the body.''
</P>
<P>
   Burks is 34, and the position change is his one concession to
age, the knee operations and six trips to the disabled list. He
admits his legs feel as if they have a million miles on them. He
has had more than 500 at-bats in a season just twice in the past
eight years.
</P>
<P>
   But the Everman High School graduate, a two-time all-star and
one of the best baseball players to come out of Tarrant County, is
nowhere near ready for a career change. This might be a critical
year, coming off double knee surgery, but the Giants' eagerness to
get him signed quickly after last season is a strong indication he
still commands respect as a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. 1, he's a quality guy,'' Baker said. ``He's liked and
respected by all of his teammates. He comes to the park ready to
play and plays hard every day. He doesn't complain, and he doesn't
make any alibis or excuses. He loves to play and he loves to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't even mention his playing ability. He can still
hit, hit with power, field, throw, run, there's nothing he can't
do. And he's not even at full speed yet. He's still not too far
removed from knee surgery. He's only going to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants acquired Burks from the Colorado Rockies on July 31
for center fielder Darryl Hamilton and two minor-league pitchers.
The Giants were looking for more power in the lineup to support
Barry Bonds and Jeff Kent.
</P>
<P>
   Burks, whose parents, James and Nettie Terry, still live in Fort
Worth, had built a house in a Denver suburb for his wife, Dori, and
his three children, Carissa, 10; Elisha, 7; and Christopher, 4, and
was happy in Colorado. But he says the trade to the Giants tur.em
out to be a good move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little skeptical at first,'' Burks said. ``I had never
been traded before, and I didn't know how it would go. I had to
find a new place to live, get acclimated to a new city. But the
guys made me feel welcome and so did the organization. So
everything has worked out well.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Burks has been thrust into a more prominent role with Bonds
sidelined until July because of elbow surgery. The Giants pointed
to Burks as the player who could keep them from floundering until
then, and he has moved into Bonds' No. 3 spot in the order. The
Giants remain in contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just another opportunity and another challenge,'' Burks
said. ``That's all this game is about, opportunity and challenges.
I know I can play this game; everybody around the game knows I can
still play.''
</P>
<P>
   He's just three years removed from his best season. Burks hit
.344 for the Rockies in 1996 with 40 homers, 142 runs scored and
128 runs batted in. He is one of three players, along with Hank
Aaron (1963) and Alex Rodriguez (last year), to get at least 40
homers, 200 hits and 30 stolen bases in a single season.
</P>
<P>
   He still believes he's as good a player as he has ever been,
although his numbers won't be as impressive away from Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   This year he's hitting .267 with five home runs and 22 RBI.
Baker points out Burks still is not 100 percent after the knee
operations, and Burks points out he usually gets better as the
season goes along.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers back that up. They also show the move to right field
should help.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past three years, Burks has hit .292 before the
All-Star break and .338 afterward. He also has hit .331 playing one
of the corner outfield positions and .302 in center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm not injured, my numbers are as good as anybody's,''
Burks said. ``I've had some bad luck, but I know how to deal with
it. I still love the game. It's always been a passion for me ever
since I started playing. That drives me. When you're still having
fun and still having success, you're still motivated to keep
playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel I can play three or four more years. Once I get
through that, I can retire on my own terms. You don't want to get
pushed out of the game, but I still believe I can play three or
four more years.'' \Ntagtop:T.R. Sullivan, (817) 390-7760
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 2157EDT &QL; 
