<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS MIGHT FEEL FORCED TO GO AFTER SCHILLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The Philadelphia Phillies are winning, but
Curt Schilling is not convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are competing, but I don't think our owners are
committed to winning,'' Schilling said. ``I haven't seen any signs
the last two years that ownership is willing to spend money to help
us win games. For us to be successful, to contend and to win,
they've got to get a big-name pitcher in here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've shown we can play good baseball. We're hitting pretty
good. But we've got to go out and get a starting pitcher. You bring
in a Randy Johnson or Kenny Rogers or Brad Radke, then we're
legitimate contenders. But they haven't shown the commitment to do
that, physically or financially.''
</P>
<P>
   The subject is a difficult one for Schilling, who is off to a
7-1 start with a 2.58 earned-run average. He remains the subject of
extensive trade rumors, most notably to the Cleveland Indians and
the St. Louis Cardinals, although the Phillies right now don't want
to trade him.
</P>
<P>
   There are those around this area who would love for the Rangers
to get him, although the cost would be steep if he is traded, and
giving Ruben Mateo for him would be a bad move.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling, who is in the second season of a three-year, $15.9
million contract, would like to stay in Philadelphia. But he said
again Wednesday he would welcome a trade if the Phillies aren't
serious about competing. To him, that remains the case, even though
they were 21-18 after Wednesday's loss to Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would certainly not block a deal if the Phillies weren't in
contention in July and our owners weren't willing to do what it
takes to win,'' Schilling said. ``But I have a total no-trade
clause in the contract, and we want to go to a team where we are
comfortable and we have a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are a team with whom he would be comfortable. Dick
Bosman was his pitching coach when Schilling was in the Orioles'
farm system, and he became good friends with Rick Helling when they
were both part of the all-star team that toured Japan at the end of
last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' first choice _ the smart choice _ is to try to win
this season without being forced to make another trade that
disrupts their farm system. The Rangers are about a year away from
having their system fully rebuilt, and unloading three or four
prospects for Schilling would only delay the process.
</P>
<P>
   But the temptation will be hard to resist this summer,
especially given the current state of their rotation. There is no
doubt Schilling is the No. 1 starter the Rangers need badly. Just
start with that he has four complete games this season, and the
Rangers have none.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one guy is going to be the savior; it takes all 25 guys,''
Schilling said. ``But I would bring something to the table, a
chance to win every fifth day ... a better-than-average chance of
winning. The ability to pitch in big games is something I crave.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Phillies keep winning, Schilling won't be traded. If they
falter, he becomes the big prize in the midsummer trade market. The
Indians will go hard after him, and so too would the Yankees, just
to keep him out of Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Once that gets going, the Rangers will feel the pressure to join
in, just as they did with Roger Clemens. The Yankees' recent slump
will only make it more enticing.
</P>
<P>
   Then it will come down to how much they're willing to give up
for that ``final piece of the puzzle,'' the one that has proved so
elusive in the past.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
