<HEADLINE>
BECAUSE OF NEED, RANGERS ALTERING PROMOTION PLAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Rangers' rotation struggled through late
April, yet general manager Doug Melvin dismissed a major-league
promotion for right-hander Ryan Glynn as an option.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn, the organization's most successful minor-league pitcher
at Triple-A Oklahoma, inspired a promotion conversation after his
one-hitter on April 28 against the New Orleans Zephyrs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm encouraged by the way he's throwing,'' Melvin said then,
``but he's still better off doing that consistently and getting in
a good groove down there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who remain leery of rushing prospects through their
minor-league system, prefer for their players to experience a
successful full season at a particular level before moving on to
the next.
</P>
<P>
   The events of this season have altered that plan.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn, whom the Rangers recalled Sunday, became the fourth
player promoted from Oklahoma in only the first seven weeks of the
season. Glynn joined right-hander Jeff Zimmerman, left-hander Mike
Venafro and shortstop Kelly Dransfeldt on the Rangers' 25-man
roster.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers did not envision those four contributing at the
major-league level before this season began.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not by choice,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said.
``It's been because of need. Zimmerman and Venafro are here because
of need. Glynn is here because of need. Dransfeldt is here because
of need. That's what your Triple-A club is for.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers purchased Zimmerman's contract April 13 to reinforce
an exhausted bullpen created by the rotation's early-season
failures. Venafro was recalled April 22 after John Burkett went on
the disabled list and remained with the Rangers when left-hander
Eric Gunderson went on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Dransfeldt made his 16th start Wednesday since his May 1 recall
for the injured Royce Clayton, who could be reinstated from the
15-day disabled list before tonight's game in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers recalled Glynn on Sunday after right-hander Esteban
Loaiza (fracture, right hand) went on the disabled list, and Oates
announced two days later that the 24-year-old rookie would replace
the struggling Burkett in the rotation and start Tuesday at Tampa
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``If other people were doing their jobs,Pe!z wo]6dn't
</P>
