<HEADLINE>
STARS FEELING DECREASE IN PRESSURE AT ADVANCED HEIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The pressure certainly isn't off the Stars, but
it has changed, Stars center Guy Carbonneau and coach Ken Hitchcock
said.
</P>
<P>
   By advancing past the second round of the playoffs, the Stars
have at least met their accomplishments of last season. And while
Hitchcock and Carbonneau said that in no way makes the Stars any
less hungry to win, it does reduce the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying this is going to be easy,'' Carbonneau said.
``But when you have a team that has a lot of success during the
regular season, you can't afford to lose in the first two rounds.
There's a lot of pressure that if you do, your season is a
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that we think we can lose now, or we don't put
pressure on ourselves, but the monkey is off our backs a little
bit,'' he said. ``Now, we don't sit there and say, `We can't make a
mistake, we can't lose.' Now we can look at it and say `Let's do
this positive, let's do this to win.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said the pressure on the Stars was tremendous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think now that we're past it, you can say we felt it,''
Hitchcock said. ``This is definitely a different kind of pressure
now.'' YOUNG LEGS While most fans will be focused on the Avalanche
scoring trio of Joe Sakic, Theo Fleury and Peter Forsberg, the
Stars can't afford to overlook the Avalanche's less glamorous
players, center Joe Nieuwendyk said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fleury is obviously another threat for them, but I think a
bigger factor for them has been the play of their two young
rookies, \RMilan\S Hejduk and \RChris\S Drury,'' Nieuwendyk said.
``A lot of people talk about Detroit's depth in the past few years,
but Colorado had more depth than Detroit because of the play of
that third line.''
</P>
<P>
   Drury and Hejduk each are among the three finalists for NHL
rookie of the year (Ottawa's Marian Hossa is the third) and the two
Avalanche forwards have combined for 10 playoff goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they had that last year,'' Nieuwendyk said.
``That third line did a lot of damage. And while they might not be
getting a lot of attention, certainly we're looking at them.''
INJURY UPDATE The Stars were up to practicing almost a full lineup
yesterday and could have at least one more component on the
practice ice today. Pat Verbeek missed workouts yesterday as he
rested from flu symptoms. He is expected to practice today.
Defenseman Shawn Chambers is still rehabilitating an injured right
knee and is not expected to play in Game 1 of the Western
Conference finals tomorrow, Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said he is leaning toward using rookie defenseman Brad
Lukowich over veteran Doug Lidster in place of Chambers in Game 1,
and that he'll also be working to get Lukowich more ice time than
the six minutes Lukowich has averaged in his past two outings.
MENTAL BATTLE Ken Hitchcock said the Stars have advanced to the
point where they are prepared to keep an opposing goaltender from
getting into their heads the way Edmonton Oilers goalie Curtis
Joseph did two seasons ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've learned that lesson,'' Hitchcock said. ``If you're going
to allow a goaltender to frustrate you and outwork you, you're
going to be in trouble. We know the only way to beat a hot goalie
is to outwork him.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
