<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-AVALANCHE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGES, ROY TRIGGER AVALANCHE'S WINNING TURNAROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Colorado Avalanche tough guy Claude Lemieux stood at
his locker in the basement of Joe Louis Arena early last week and
tried to explain what happened in the humiliating back-to-back
losses at home to the Detroit Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't so much what the Red Wings were doing, Lemieux said
scornfully after the Avalanche trailed 2-0 in the Western
Conference semifinal series, ``It's more what we didn't do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they didn't have to work too hard to beat us,''
Lemieux said.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in winning four consecutive games to eject the
defending Stanley Cup champion Red Wings from the playoffs came
down to changes Colorado made after the second game. Those upgrades
seem to have put the Avalanche in the role reserved for Detroit as
the favorite in the Western Conference finals against the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're facing a much better team \Rthan Detroit\S in my mind,''
Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk said. ``They proved that in the last
series, and now we have to go out and beat this team. After what
they did to Detroit, I don't think anybody's worried about Detroit
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of what the Avalanche did to Detroit had to do with
``getting back,'' and not just to basics, including:
</P>
<P>
   Getting back a healthy Valeri Kamensky, an addition that not
only bolstered one of the club's top two lines but also
strengthened the third line by allowing the talented Adam Deadmarsh
to move down alongside Chris Drury and Shjon Podein.
</P>
<P>
   Getting back to smart play. The Avalanche's obsession with
physical play in the first two games led to a string of untimely
penalties. When the series moved to Detroit, the Avalanche players
kept their collective temperament in check for the rest of the
games.
</P>
<P>
   Getting back to the net. The Avalanche vowed to clog the area in
front of Detroit goalie Bill Ranford starting in Game 3, and it
did. Throughout the series, Colorado continued to drive hard to the
goal against Ranford and his replacement, Chris Osgood, increasing
their number of quality scoring chances. Eventually, those chances
became goals.
</P>
<P>
   Getting back the ``real'' Patrick Roy. Widely regarded as
perhaps the best big-game goalie in hockey, Roy played like it the
last three games. Roy frustrated Red Wings scorers time and again,
causing them to miss open shots and fire others weakly.
</P>
<P>
   The return of Kamensky ``brought a lot of enthusiasm and
excitement to the dressing room,'' Colorado center Joe Sakic said.
``We've got a lot more depth when we've got Val back. He's such a
great player, he opens up the ice.''
</P>
<P>
   Avalanche coach Bob Hartley said: ``He's got lots of speed and
lots of skills. He generates great chances.''
</P>
<P>
   With the pressure on the top two lines removed upon Kamensky's
return, all the Avalanche lines appeared to play better _ even the
fourth line, where strongman Dale Hunter properly returned. This
nullified the Red Wings' previous edge in depth.
</P>
<P>
   Equally important to the Avalanche was a reinstalling of on-ice
discipline, particularly when it came to unnecessary rough stuff.
Stupid penalties left Colorado repeatedly shorthanded in the first
two games.
</P>
<P>
   For example, trailing 2-0 in Game 2, the Avalanche took several
penalties, killing hopes for a comeback. Such penalties, caused by
frustration with Detroit's tight neutral ice defense in Games 1 and
2, were minimized in the final four games.
</P>
<P>
   One Avalanche player who pointed out the folly of excessive
physical play was defenseman Miller, who scored a key goal in the
crucial 5-3 victory in Game 3 and finished at plus-5 for the series
with a goal and three assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just playing stupid,'' a suddenly vocal Miller said
after the frustrating first two games. ``It was disheartening and
an absolute lack of effort. We have to change the way we're
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche did change the way it was playing, to a smart,
controlled style, taking advantage of opportunities and not forcing
situations.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Forsberg, whose world-class game picked up as the series
wore on, put it this way: ``We sat back a little more and didn't
run around as much.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of that smarter game, the Avalanche drove harder to the
net.
</P>
<P>
   Said Hartley after Game 3: ``We managed to get closer to the
net. We had good jump to the net and we beat them to the puck.''
</P>
<P>
   But the unlikely comeback would not have been possible without
Roy, the three-time Stanley Cup champion and two-time Conn Smythe
award winner as the most valuable player of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrick is unique in his ability to raise his expectations,''
Hartley said. ``I've never seen an athlete put so much pressure on
himself and then live up to it.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
