<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: IMPORTED NOISE IN ATLANTA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You could hear they were New Yorkers even before
spotting the orange and blue colors supporting the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Patrick, I'm from Manhattan,'' one fan yelled at
courtside, although Patrick Ewing did not acknowledge him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Jeff, I got bad legs, but I can play,'' another one
shouted during warm-ups, drawing just the slightest sideways smile
from the coach, Jeff Van Gundy.
</P>
<P>
   Loud and familiar and pointed, these fans made up fully one
quarter of the crowd that huddled in one dreary little corner of
the looming Georgia Dome. They were giving the Knicks a verbal
touch of Noo Yawk Thursday night as the Knicks tried to make it two
straight over the Hawks in their second-round playoff.
</P>
<P>
   Who were these people? Some of them were transplanted New
Yorkers, brought here by the vicissitudes of transient corporate
life. Others were current New Yorkers who realized they had a
better shot at buying tickets here than at the fat-cat emporium on
Seventh Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Even factoring in a Delta Airlines fare, some of them were
probably saving money over what they would have to pay the friendly
gents who ply the scalper trade in the shadows around the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' players appreciate it when New Yorkers, either real
or wannabe, express themselves so blatantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to go into a gym and have some fans,'' Chris Dudley
said. ``It was the same in Miami for the first game. There were
guys with KNICKS painted on their chests, just like Yankee fans. I
think it helps us.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Childs said: ``A lot of these people have lived in New
York, and they support us. It's kind of funny.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks were not amused that 25 percent of Knicks fans could
drown out the other 75 percent of the crowd of 18,513 during
Tuesday's 100-92 victory by the Knicks. The total itself was fine,
considering that Madison Square Garden, always sold out, holds
19,763 fans, but the nature of the Dome crowd was most emphatically
Noo Yawkish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate,'' Tyrone Corbin said. ``It's in our home
building, and they're cheering for the other team. But it happens.
We can't get wrapped up in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Corbin acknowledged that the local fans never got into the game
after the Hawks fell behind early. In New York, however, a
depressing start to a playoff game would prompt a massive volley of
boos _ just to show that New Yorkers care, in our own surly way.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem may be that the Georgia Dome is not actually
the Hawks' home. They are just using it while their new arena is
being constructed just up the hill. The dome is configured for
21,000 seats, which even with curtains and movable stands, are
swallowed up in the dome, which has 71,200 seats.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks also play some games at Georgia Tech, which produces
an identity crisis among fans, who never know where they are
parking or sitting. The man from Congo, Dikembe Mutombo, is of the
opinion that Atlanta fans ``do not care for games,'' but he is only
judging from the tepid reception to his sport. For example, Ted
Turner did not come to the first four playoff games here _ and he
owns the team.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that there is only one sport down here. Turner
discovered how it worked here a couple of decades ago when his
Braves actually had a pretty decent run in the first two-thirds of
the season, but the ball park was practically deserted on the first
Friday night of a homestand.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody broke the news to Ted. It was late August, and the high
schools were playing ``foo'ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Dome actually rocks for the Falcons, although
they've been having trouble filling it, on occasion. Now the
National Hockey League is returning to Atlanta, where the sport
failed once before. The Braves, one of the great baseball teams of
the decade, do not always sell out their playoff games, either.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is the diffused nature of Atlanta, with its
_ shall we say? _ modest downtown, and suburbs that sprawl out to
Gingrich Country and beyond, dependent on interstates clogged
during rush hour. Turner adamantly insisted on placing the new
arena next to the CNN building, rather than in the 'burbs, but
Hawks games currently lack the urban buzz that accompanies any
event in the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Smith of the Hawks has said he is looking forward to
playing in the Garden Sunday afternoon and Monday night because of
the intensity. Smith understands. There was some intensity in the
Dome _ but most of it was produced by people wearing orange and
blue. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
