<SLUG> BC-FLORIDA-SENATE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Logan in U.S. Senate race _maybe as independent
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Servic--
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Like a thunderstorm over a picnic,
Willie Logan snatched a rare ray of sun away from the Democrats on
Thursday with his decision to run for the U.S. Senate _ possibly as
an independent.
</P>
<P>
   While many top Democrats dismiss Logan's candidacy as nothing
more than a distraction, others worry that Logan could siphon votes
away from the party's likely nominee, insurance Commissioner Bill
Nelson, and give the election to the Republicans next year.
</P>
<P>
   Logan remained mostly mum about his plans, saying only that he
will meet with voters during the next few weeks to explore his
potential for victory. ``Then,'' he said, ``I will decide how I
want to access the ballot.''
</P>
<P>
   The 17-year state representative from Opa-locka said even if he
runs as an independent he will remain a registered Democrat. ``My
candidacy will not be based on any particular politics or political
party,'' he said during a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   With only five open Senate seats in the nation and control of
the chamber at stake, both national parties are targeting Florida,
where two-term Republican U.S. Sen. Connie Mack is retiring. ``This
race is going to get a lot of attention,'' said Republican
strategist Mike Murphy. ``You'll see both parties spend a lot of
money to win Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   Logan's unceremonious removal last year from his post as House
Democratic leader caused a deep rift within the party.
</P>
<P>
   During the governor's race, Logan endorsed Republican Jeb Bush.
Declaring his own independence, Logan worked closely with GOP
leaders during the legislative session that ended this month. At
the same time, however, Logan attended a Democratic caucus and
spoke on behalf of Rep. Lois Frankel of West Palm Beach who was
chosen to lead House Democrats next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been sending a lot of mixed signals,'' said one
Democratic leader, who asked not to be named. ``I think Willie is
just looking out for what is best for Willie and right now the best
thing for Willie is to work both parties to his advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have certainly responded. Former state party
Chairman Tom Slade said he would love it if Logan would run as an
independent. Slade said he'd help raise money for Logan, who would
be unlikely to take away many GOP voters.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have been giddy over the prospect of having Nelson
unchallenged. When Mack announced earlier this year that he would
not seek a third term, candidates quickly lined up in both parties.
Weeks later, after more thought, Democrats such as U.S. Reps. Peter
Deutsch of Fort Lauderdale and Robert Wexler of Boca Raton, quickly
dropped out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   In a race that is expected to cost an estimated $10 million to
$15 million, Nelson could be in the position of sitting back,
having a quiet primary season while the Republicans chew each other
up and spend valuable cash trying to win the nomination. That's
exactly what happened to the Democrats in 1988. There were six
candidates in the primary and the eventual winner, Buddy MacKay,
staggered into the general election, losing in one of the state's
closest races to Mack, who had only a token challenger in the GOP
primary.
</P>
<P>
   So far Republicans have two serious candidates: Education
Commissioner Tom Gallagher and U.S. Rep. Bill McCollum of Altamonte
Springs, who may be best known for his role as one of the
prosecutors during President Clinton's impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans could have a third candidate if state Senate
President Toni Jennings of Orlando decides to get into the race.
She spent several days in Washington last week talking to
pollsters, media consultants and others in an effort to measure her
chance of winning. Republicans supporting her candidacy believe she
could take some women's votes away from the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   If she gets into the race, Republicans would be certain to have
not only a primary vote, but a runoff election as well, giving the
winner, who could be nearly broke, just four weeks to take on a
cash rich Democratic nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks so good for us it frightens me,'' said Charlie
Whitehead, a retired Panama City car dealer who took over the helm
of the Democratic Party at the urging of Nelson and other party
leaders who said they needed help strengthening the party.
Whitehead, who had been party chairman during most of the '80s,
said, ``I've been around long enough to know it can't stay this
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
