<HEADLINE>
NOT SORRY TO BOTHER YOU AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Minn., Ill.)   (For release Sunday, May 23)  
(Eds.: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been
used in the end note instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(af) 
 By MICHELLE COTTLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I'm a manager at a large corporation. I work long hours and
regard my time away from the office as an invaluable chance to
recharge and to relax with my family. But supervisors and
colleagues call me constantly me at home (or page me or call my
cell phone), often asking that I rush back to the office. I can't
just turn off my pager and cell phone, because I'm expected to be
on call for emergencies. Increasingly, however, I am called about
not-so-important matters. How do I cut down on these annoyances
without having my dedication questioned?
</P>
<P>
   A. Welcome to the dark side of the workplace without boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Pagers and cell phones can lead people to think you're available
24 hours a day, said Barbara Miller, a consultant in Mill Valley,
Calif., who specializes in work- and life-style issues. ``But the
reality is that nobody can function as a working person 24 hours a
day,'' she added. ``We all need downtime.''
</P>
<P>
   A first step is to talk with your co-workers about the problem,
to see if they have similar frustrations. ``It's almost guaranteed
that you are not the only one in your work group with this
problem,'' said Susan Seitel, president of Work and Family
Connection, a publishing and consulting firm in Minnetonka, Minn.
So you can do everyone a favor by getting the issue out in the
open.
</P>
<P>
   Define your terms and set limits. ``Have informal conversations
with individual culprits,'' advised Bonnie Michaels, president of
Managing Work and Family, a consulting firm in Evanston, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Ask why they feel a need to consult you on everyday matters, for
example, and explore alternative paths to answers. If the problem
is technical, remember that the same high-tech world that produced
the pager has also given us data bases and Web sites with quick
access to all kinds of information.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, decide what constitutes an emergency and what
merits what response. A message on your answering machine might be
OK for important, but not vital, matters, while a cell-phone call
could be reserved for code-blue crises.
</P>
<P>
   Talking to your boss, however, will require diplomacy. ``Rather
than saying, `I'm upset because you've been calling me at home for
the last three weeks at 7 o'clock at night,' go in and say, `I
really need you to help me problem-solve on this one,''' Ms. Miller
advised.
</P>
<P>
   Try to depersonalize the situation. ``Encourage your boss to
look at this as a systemic issue rather than just your issue,'' she
said. That can show that you're a team player, not a whiner.
</P>
<P>
   Once the limits have been set, find ways to enforce them. After
a certain hour, consider using your answering machine to screen
calls, returning only those about true emergencies. But don't take
such steps to avoid confronting the boundary issue head-on at the
office, Ms. Michaels said. Otherwise, she added, ``the calls are
just going to continue, and somebody's going to get mad because you
don't call them back.''
</P>
<P>
   (Michelle Cottle is a Washington writer. Each week, she responds
to readers' questions about career and workplace issues. Send them
by e-mail to working(AT)nytimes.com or by mail to Working, Money &AMP;
Business, The New York Times, 229 W. 43rd St., New York, N.Y.
10036.)
</P>
</TEXT>
