<HEADER>
A5370 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-TAX21-COX     05-20 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-TAX21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tax breaks on domestic goods unlikely, but other cuts may follow
in Texas
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ State lawmakers have all but buried proposed tax
breaks on such things as clothing, school supplies and diapers, but
a lead House Democrat on Thursday said tax cuts still likely to be
approved this session are balanced between businesses and
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Two House committees on Thursday approved three Senate bills
that include about $1.4 billion in tax cuts and tax prevention
measures. Tax prevention measures slow down future tax increases,
but do not lower current taxes.
</P>
<P>
   About $220 million of the $1.4 billion would go to businesses;
$20 million would go to consumers who use the Internet. The rest,
about $1.2 billion, would be divided between businesses and
consumers who own property, with business property owners expected
to take the largest portion of the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have chosen the wrong taxes to cut,'' said Dick Lavine, a
senior analyst for the Center for Public Policy Priorities, which
advocates on behalf of low-income Texans. ``The average Texan will
not be seeing the benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   The center says taxes shouldn't be cut, but if lawmakers cut
taxes, they should target them to low- and middle-income families.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rene Oliveira, (D-Brownsville), is chairman of the House
Ways and Means committee, which approved two of the bills. He said
he's disappointed that tax cuts on diapers and school supplies are
unlikely to pass. But he said a still-viable proposal to cut sales
taxes on over-the-counter medicines is good for all consumers and
helps balance the proposed cuts between consumers and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trade-off for me is that over-the-counter tax cuts help
everybody,'' Oliveira said. ``The school clothes and school
supplies and diapers are things that help people at some point in
their lives. To help the most people during all of their lives, the
over-the-counter is the best vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   The House Public Education Committee approved the third bill,
which contains about $1.2 billion in measures meant to hold down
and cut local school property taxes. The bill, Senate Bill 4, also
contains $1.7 billion for $3,000, across-the-board teacher pay
raises and about $900 million in new school spending. It also
contains measures to end social promotion in schools. The practice
is meant to keep students on grade-level with their peers even
though they haven't mastered the material at their current levels.
</P>
<P>
   By House rules, all three bills must clear the full House by
Wednesday. The Senate then is expected to reject House proposals,
setting up conference committees that would have to produce
compromise bills. Those bills then would have to be approved by the
House and Senate by May 30.
</P>
<P>
   The session ends May 31, but that day is reserved for
corrections to passed legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The Ways and Means Committee had about $500 million to divide
between business and consumer sales tax cuts. But the House already
has approved about $450 million in such cuts for small Texas
corporations and on over-the-counter medicines. That means changes
to already approved business and sales tax cuts will have to be
made to accommodate those approved by the committee Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts approved Thursday include several that are key to Gov.
George W. Bush, including $20 million in Internet access sales tax
cuts and business tax cuts for research and development and
investment tax credits. They also contain key Democratic cuts,
including job creation tax credits and additional investment tax
credits for business investments in 90 poor counties, largely along
the Texas-Mexico and Texas-Louisiana borders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a commitment to work on a balanced proposal,'' said
Oliveira, chairman of the tax-writing Ways and Means Committee.
``It' going to take a lot of cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Troy Fraser (R-Horseshoe Bay) said a large portion of the
business tax cuts being discussed are targeted to small businesses.
That, he said, makes them closer to consumer tax cuts than business
tax cuts. Fraser, who's pushed the tax cut for small businesses,
also said all tax cuts will be good for consumers in the end
business tax cuts allow for better prices or more jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tax cuts are tax cuts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
