<HEADLINE>
CSUN, UCLA WIN PLAYOFF GAMES IN SOFTBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Although unspoken, the ghosts of past postseason
failures hung over the Cal State Northridge softball team.
</P>
<P>
   Until Thursday. The fifth-seeded Matadors knocked around No. 2
Missouri 7-3 in an NCAA region opener at UCLA to record their first
win in the postseason after six consecutive losses over three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Northridge (30-22) scored a season-high six runs in the second
inning and got home runs from infrequent power sources.
</P>
<P>
   Seniors Katrina Nolletti and Ashlie Hayes each hit their second
home runs of the season in the second inning, making it easy for
pitcher Tara Glaister (21-13). Northridge reached today's 3 p.m.
game against Minnesota. Missouri (38-20) plays Alabama today at 10
a.m. in an elimination game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just feels good,'' Northridge coach Janet Sherman said.
``We felt good, we felt confident. We're enjoying the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Northridge trailed 1-0 after one inning, which must have had
Sherman wondering about the team's fate in this year's tournament.
But then came the second inning and she was able to breathe easier.
</P>
<P>
   Nolletti's three-run shot _ only her second of the year _ off
Stephanie Falk (24-12) barely cleared the left-field fence and gave
CSUN a 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I popped it up to left field,'' Nolletti said. ``I
didn't think I got it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayes followed two batters later with a mammoth 250-foot shot to
left-center that finished the inning's scoring and chased Falk. It
was the fourth time this season Northridge had scored six times in
an inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hit two out in the second inning, and that's the
ballgame,'' Missouri coach Jay Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   After the second, Northridge collected just one hit, but by then
the runs had the desired calming effect on Glaister (one earned
run, eight strikeouts, three walks). Not needing to fret about the
location of every pitch, Glaister got the first five outs by
strikeout and scattered seven hits.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Missouri scored two unearned runs in the fifth inning
to halve Northridge's lead to 6-3, Glaister wasn't concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't so touchy about spots,'' she said. ``I had some space
if something were to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Little else did, except for Jessica Creith's sacrifice fly in
the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   __ UCLA 7, Alabama 0: Courtney Dale pitched a one-hitter with 10
strikeouts and Julie Adams hit two two-run home runs and drove in
five. Top-seeded UCLA (56-6) advanced to today's 12:30 p.m. game
against Creighton. Alabama dropped to 39-25.
</P>
<P>
   Dale (29-1) pitched five perfect innings, then lost her bid for
her first perfect game with an errant throw to first. She lost the
no-hitter in the sixth when Kelley Askew dumped a leadoff single to
left field.
</P>
<P>
   Dale said she was unaware she had a perfect game or a no-hitter.
Coach Sue Enquist wasn't surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``She plays the game one pitch at a time,'' Enquist said. ``She
can dominate. She has great composure. She had control, she had one
slip, she regrouped and she closed the door.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA pounded Alabama pitcher Penny Cope with four runs in 21/3
innings. Cope two-hit UCLA the last time the teams played March 12
in a tournament in Chattanooga, Tenn. UCLA won that game 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   Adams' five RBI matched a season high, last accomplished March 6
against Creighton. It also was her second multihomer game this
season.
</P>
</TEXT>
