<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: DEMOCRATS GAIN GROUND, AN INCH, ON GUN CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the past two extraordinary weeks in the Senate,
Democrats and gun control advocates accomplished far more than any
of them had ever thought possible.
</P>
<P>
   But for all of the celebration, the package they assembled was
still a modest one, falling short of President Clinton's proposals
after the Colorado shootings and much less attempting anything as
far-reaching as a handgun ban.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats did not dream of bringing up, for example, the
president's proposal to limit individuals to buying one handgun a
month. They lost an effort to limit gun sales on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   And fearful that they could endanger final passage of the
juvenile-justice bill if they overplayed their hand, gun control
proponents stopped short of trying to restore a waiting period for
handgun purchases, a part of the 1993 Brady law that has since
expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has ever said this is the last thing on guns,'' said
Sen. Tom Daschle, the minority leader from South Dakota. ``This was
the most realistic approach we could use, given the circumstances
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, if the measures were limited, the package _ including a
requirement of background checks at gun shows _ was the first major
congressional victory for gun control advocates in five years. And
there was evidence that a new political center was developing in
the nation on guns and violence, as Americans recoil from school
shooting after school shooting.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two weeks, Republicans lurched from position to
position, as their first efforts to stop the Democratic measure to
require background checks at gun shows proved politically
untenable. Now two Republican presidential candidates, Elizabeth
Dole and Sen. John McCain, have come out in favor of some measures
for gun control. So, too, have the two Republican congressional
leaders, Sen. Trent Lott, the majority leader from Mississippi, and
Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Lott, to the dismay of many conservatives, did not
yank the bill from the floor when momentum started shifting the
Democrats' way. This Republican repositioning is important because
gun control is an emotional social issue where change comes hard
and any movement is significant.
</P>
<P>
   It took the proponents of the Brady bill seven arduous years to
put in place its regulation of handgun purchases. And since 1994,
when Republicans took control of Congress with significant support
from the National Rifle Association, the gun lobby has been
considered invincible.
</P>
<P>
   That supremacy was shattered Thursday when Vice President Al
Gore cast the dramatic tie-breaking vote that passed the measure to
require background checks at gun shows. So Democrats were able to
say Thursday, as a triumphant Gore did, that ``this is a turning
point for our country'' and that change often begins ``with the
narrowest of margins.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats acknowledged that to achieve their victories they had
carefully scaled back their ambitions, framed gun control as a
child-safety issue and selected such politically popular measures
as safety devices for guns.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer of New York said the measures that the
Democrats selected to fight for had to pass two tests: that they
had a realistic chance of becoming law and that they could be seen
as bearing some relationship to what had happened in Littleton,
Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This debate has really been about common sense, moderate
efforts to limit the accessibility and availability of weapons to
children,'' said Sen. Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts, who has
been battling for gun control since his two brothers were
assassinated in the 1960s. He said that while the political climate
was changing, it had not changed enough that he could pass the
measure that eluded him three decades ago: a ban on cheap handguns
known as Saturday night specials.
</P>
<P>
   What the Senate votes mean for further gun control is uncertain.
These proposals still have to get through the House, where pro-gun
sentiments run stronger and conservatives have greater sway.
</P>
<P>
   And while Democrats vowed to continue with a new gun control
offensive on another day, Sen. John Chafee of Rhode Island, long
one of the few Republicans in favor of gun control, predicted there
would be a hiatus before Congress considers any more stringent
measures.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear, however, that gun control will be an issue in the
2000 campaigns. Gore obviously relished the opportunity to use his
incumbency to cast the tie-breaking vote. Democrats have also vowed
to use the GOP lurches on gun control against the Republicans from
swing states who are up for re-election in 2000, like Spencer
Abraham of Michigan, Rod Grams of Minnesota and Slade Gorton of
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans were furious that they had been caught so
flat-footed. ``We're losing,'' complained Sen. Bob Smith R-N.H., a
presidential candidate, who is an avid opponent of gun control.
``The other side skillfully used terrible tragedies to change
peoples' votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives groused that Lott had allowed the gun-control
debate at all, and Republican moderates complained that their party
leaders had been so tone deaf that they allowed Sen. Larry Craig of
Idaho, a board member of the National Rifle Association, to be
their point man on the debate.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., who heads the Senate Republican
re-election effort, argued optimistically that the confusing
multitude of votes over the past days had allowed Republicans to
stake out positions that would be acceptable whether they came from
western, more pro-gun states, or the more moderate northeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our candidates largely voted the way they should have
given their particular states,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
