<HEADLINE>
SORTING OUT FALLOUT FROM A LAWSUIT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For many long and unprofitable years, air-pollution control
companies waited for the Environmental Protection Agency to enforce
provisions of the Clean Air Act of 1990 that made each state
responsible for keeping its air breathable.
</P>
<P>
   The companies figured that if the agency cracked down on the
states, the states would crack down on polluters. And they, in
turn, would buy precipitators, scrubbers, and other machines that
remove pollutants.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1997, the agency started spewing forth those rules, and
the $3 billion industry thought its future was secure.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, though, a federal appeals court appeared to snatch
that security away. In a lawsuit brought by three states and
several industry groups the court ruled that the EPA had been too
arbitrary in setting a new low standard for fine particulates _ in
other words, soot _ and had exceeded its constitutional powers in
tightening standards for ozone, a main ingredient in smog.
</P>
<P>
   Are the air-cleaning companies back to square one? Jeffrey
Smith, executive director of the Institute of Clean Air Companies,
a trade association, thinks not. But he is worried.
</P>
<P>
   Q. With the smog-and-soot rules in limbo, are orders going to
dry up?
</P>
<P>
   A. Not for now. The EPA gave the states as long as 10 years to
comply with some of the new rules, so some orders wouldn't have
come in for several more years. The compliance deadlines for
reducing toxic substances and NOx _ the nitrogen oxides that are
the precursors to ozone _ fall much sooner, and those rules are the
main sources of our orders now.
</P>
<P>
   Last quarter, our members booked more orders than in any quarter
of the last eight years, and it was mainly because of NOx. The NOx
rules are based on the old ozone standards, so last week's court
decision shouldn't have an impact.
</P>
<P>
   But anything the EPA does of any consequence winds up being
litigated, and the NOx standards are in litigation, too. Opponents
of ambient air standards have had a great week _ they're in a
celebratory mood, giddy with success. This decision is energizing
them to build legal war chests to oppose other rules, including the
NOx rules.
</P>
<P>
   Q. If those NOx rules are overturned, how severe a blow would
that be to air-cleaning companies?
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't think they will be overturned. And, there is a
backstop rule in place anyway. Under the Clean Air Act, states that
have heavy concentrations of NOx in their air because of emissions
blowing down from other states can petition the EPA to take
remedial action. About a dozen states have already done that, and
if existing rules are overturned, they will probably press their
case. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. So last week's court action is not having a dampening effect
on your industry?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Of course it is.
</P>
<P>
   When the EPA came out with its new rules in 1997, it energized
us. For the first time in a long time, we had a sense of a firm,
certain, inevitable future market. That made it easy to attract
investors and to recruit and keep talented people. We began
spending again on research and development, looking for more
efficient and less costly technologies, and we started finding
them.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision may dissipate a lot of that energy. We got
burned earlier this decade when we expected an immediate surge of
orders from the Clean Air Act that never came. That left us
respectful and wary of the deleterious effect that any sense of
delay or uncertainty can have on orders.
</P>
<P>
   The nature of the air pollution control market is that customers
buy just enough, and just on time. They may rethink or postpone
purchases of air pollution control technology based on their
perception that Congress or the EPA will rethink the entire Clean
Air Act. That may not be factually correct, but business acts on
perception, not reality.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Your association was influential in getting the tighter
smog-and-soot rules passed. How do you plan to keep them alive now?
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It is not our policy to participate directly in any
litigation. But we're spending a lot of time on the phone with
federal and state officials, making sure they understand that if
you interpret the court's decision rationally, it should not ripple
into other areas like NOx controls.
</P>
<P>
   And we're spending a lot of time with our members, too, trying
to reassure them that the sky is not falling. After all, the court
didn't disagree with the proposed standards, just with the way the
EPA articulated its criteria for setting them. There's no reason to
believe that the EPA can't put together a justification of the
standards that would pass muster with this panel. And, I expect the
EPA to vigorously pursue its options on appeal, even if it means
going to the Supreme Court.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. If it does, will it win?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think so. But remember, I expected them to win this time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
