<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ONLY A START ON GUN CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, May 21:
</P>
<P>
   The debate over gun control took a dramatic turn Thursday. Hours
after another frightening school shooting episode _ this time at a
high school outside Atlanta _ Vice President Gore cast a
tie-breaking vote in the Senate to tighten existing gun control
laws, dealing an important defeat to the National Rifle
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's vote broke a 50-50 tie on a proposal by Sen. Frank
Lautenberg, D-N.J., to close a major loophole in the Brady law that
makes it easy for youths and criminals to buy firearms at gun shows
without any background checks. The proposal, a retooled version of
a measure Senate Republicans had narrowly killed nine days before,
also closed a dangerous new loophole buried in the phony gun-show
bill Republicans approved last week. The loophole would have
allowed convicted felons to reclaim their guns from pawnshops.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, led by Lautenberg and Sens. Charles Schumer of New
York and Richard Durbin of Illinois, showed admirable persistence
in pressing the gun-show issue. They also benefited from the votes
of two Democratic senators, Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York and
Daniel Inouye of Hawaii, who had been absent for the original vote,
and a switch by another, Max Cleland of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Equally important were the votes of six lonely Republicans who
rose above intense partisan pressures to defy the gun lobby on the
gun-show issue _ John Chafee of Rhode Island, John Warner of
Virginia, Peter Fitzgerald of Illinois, Richard Lugar of Indiana
and George Voinovich and Mike DeWine, both of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless the majority leader, Trent Lott, and most of his
Republican colleagues have yet to be persuaded of the urgency of
broader reform. Despite the passage of the gun-show measure, the
amendments _ attached to a juvenile justice bill _ are
disappointingly meager.
</P>
<P>
   One provision, for example, would require that trigger locks be
provided separately with gun purchases. But it sets no deadline for
requiring that locks be incorporated as part of the design. The
Senate did agree to bar further imports of large military-style
ammunition clips, as well as sales of assault rifles and shotguns
to juveniles under 18 and their possession by juveniles under 18.
But it stopped short of raising the age for sales and possession of
these weapons from 18 to 21.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Senate defeated Schumer's proposal to subject
Internet gun sales to background checks, and completely ignored at
least three other important proposals. One would have reinstated
the Brady waiting period for purchasing guns. The second would
limit gun sales to individuals to one per month to deter
large-scale gun trafficking. The third would allow criminal
prosecution of parents whose failure to securely lock away their
guns results in violence by a juvenile.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation will shortly move to the House, where gun
control forces in and outside of Congress will need to step up the
pressure for a much stronger package. That includes President
Clinton and Gore. The vice president's rescue mission Thursday
should help improve not only his political fortunes but those of
his party, which in contrast to the Republicans has shown real
independence from the gun lobby.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Senate's weak performance demonstrates, there is a
lot more that can be done to keep guns out of the hands of troubled
schoolchildren. And as the school shooting in Georgia reminds us,
there is a lot more that must be done.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 2212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
