<SLUG> BC-BIZ-MIDSTREAM-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RITES OF SURVIVORSHIP  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been
used in the end note instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
 (af)  
 By JAMES SCHEMBARI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was fitting that this financial revelation came in church.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent service, our minister honored the people who
have been members of the congregation for at least 50 years. As he
called their names, they stood at their pews, some with the aid of
canes. Almost all of them were women.
</P>
<P>
   I looked at my wife, Christine, sitting next to me, and I
suddenly realized that she could be among the honorees someday and
that I would not likely be standing next to her. The odds are that
Christine, a television reporter, will outlive me by a good
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   I leaned over and whispered my thoughts to her, and we spent the
rest of the service holding hands. I was sitting in that church
trying to figure out how I was going to save for my children's
college education as well as our retirement _ and still have enough
for Christine when she's going to church solo.
</P>
<P>
   Not a very romantic notion, but a prospect that financial
experts say baby boomers must consider. After all, the Census
Bureau says that in 1997, some 46 percent of all women 65 and older
were widows, while only 16 percent of men that age were widowers.
And if wives indeed outlive their husbands, the family's assets
must outlive the husbands, too.
</P>
<P>
   Having a sound financial strategy is an obvious first step
toward that goal. Like many other certified financial planners,
Elaine Bedel of Indianapolis recommends conventional investments
first, with life insurance as a possible supplement.
</P>
<P>
   If couples think that their assets will not last long enough to
provide for a surviving wife, they can buy insurance to cover the
shortfall. She favors level term policies that can offer hundreds
of thousands of dollars in coverage at the same, or level, premium,
for as long as 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance agents often recommend whole life insurance and
variable annuities, which offer both investment returns and death
benefits. But financial planners, citing the fees and tax
complications, say many people would be better off buying term life
insurance while using their other funds for conventional
investments.
</P>
<P>
   Even a solid strategy, however, can weaken if one partner is not
a participant. In many families, one spouse often takes financial
charge, and even in the 1990s, it's usually the husband.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Phelps, 53, a vice president of employee benefit sales at
Conseco Risk Management in Carmel, Ind., had always managed his
family's assets. He had the expertise and his wife lacked interest.
His father had died young, so he knew the importance of
preparation. Recently, Phelps asked his wife, Kay, to accompany him
to visit Ms. Bedel.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I still had time to do something about it, I wanted to
make sure we had our finances on track,'' he said. ``I wanted my
wife to be more involved and aware of what was happening. I was
concerned that if something happened to me she wouldn't know where
to start financially.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Phelps, 53, an administrator of a scholarship program for
the Independent Colleges of Indiana in Indianapolis, found the
meeting useful, but still counts on her husband. ``He's so
conscientious, and such a good husband and parent,'' she said. ``I
guess I have always had so much confidence in his love and caring
for me that I knew everything would be taken care of.''
</P>
<P>
   Phelps now carries about $1.25 million of life insurance, mostly
term insurance. He plans to cut back, sharply though not entirely,
as he nears a retirement he intends to finance with his
investments. ``I've been in the insurance industry for 30 years and
have a loyalty to the product, so I am reluctant to give it up,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But how much money will a widow need? The more men think about
it, the thriftier they might become today to provide their wives
with more security tomorrow. Assuming continued low inflation, Ms.
Bedel said that if a man who is 45 today lives to 65, and his wife
outlives him by 10 years, she will need $750,000, assuming living
expenses of $50,000 a year. If she outlives him by 20 years, the
total rises to $1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   To reach those totals, a Mr. Wonderful must immediately start
saving $1,250 or $2,000, respectively, a month or invest $150,000
or $250,000 now and get an 8 percent return until he dies.
</P>
<P>
   So get busy, guys. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (James Schembari is an editor at The Times. His column on the
prime earning, spending and striving years will appear the fourth
Sunday of each month. E-mail: jimschem(AT)nytimes.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
