<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ASKING STUDENTS TO DO MORE WITH LESS
</HEADLINE>
 (af) 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, May 21: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki sounded tough last week about making high
school graduation requirements stricter, telling reporters that
``we should not back down one iota from our efforts to raise
students' performance standards.'' But his utterly inadequate
education budget would make it difficult for most New York state
school districts to meet those standards, and practically
impossible for districts serving the poorest students.
</P>
<P>
   State lawmakers of both parties have good reason to be nervous,
because beginning next year all students will have to pass the
rigorous Regents English exam to graduate. Assemblyman Richard
Brodsky has proposed legislation to allow school districts to use
alternative assessments in place of the Regents tests. But in
theory, students would still have to show higher achievement to
graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, students could choose to take basic competency tests
to graduate rather than the harder Regents exam that leads to a
Regents diploma. In New York City, fewer than 25 percent of
students get the Regents diplomas. A recent report showed that 27
percent of high school seniors statewide and 37 percent of seniors
in New York City would not have graduated last year if the new test
requirement had been in place. The standards will become more
demanding in subsequent years when students will have to pass
Regents exams in other areas besides English. Some community
leaders worry that 20 percent or more of seniors will not graduate
under the new regime.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Regents wanted to improve student performance. That
goal still makes sense. For too long New York state has awarded
second-class diplomas to barely literate students. But standards
cannot be raised in a vacuum. The state cannot expect students in
schools without decent libraries, laboratories or trained teachers
to pass tests that have no connection to what is happening in the
classroom. The solution is not to dumb down the standards but to
provide enough resources so that even students from impoverished
areas have a chance to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   The Regents have recommended increasing the state education
budget by $885 million for the coming year, especially targeting
the neediest districts. The money would pay for after-school
instruction, more summer school, more teacher training and repairs
to facilities like science labs. But Pataki slashed the amount to
$270 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, he is reneging on a 1997 budget deal that
provided property tax cuts favored by suburban areas in return for
more spending to cut class sizes and finance preschool programs.
New York City schools will be among those hit hardest. The city
will get only 28 percent of his meager budget increase, even though
it educates 38 percent of the students in the state and serves 62
percent of students living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   The fight now has to be about resources, not achievement
standards. Without financial commitments from the governor and the
legislature, New York state will soon be engaged in the pointless,
destructive exercise of flunking tens of thousands of students who
never had much of a chance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
