<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chen gets chance to display progress
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bruce Chen is getting a second chance tonight, about
seven weeks later than he expected. The rookie is slated to start
in place of John Smoltz while he's on the disabled list with an
inflamed elbow
</P>
<P>
   For Chen, who lost the fifth starter's job during spring
training, it's a chance to impress the Braves' front office and
perhaps win back a spot in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to go out and win the game,'' Chen said. ``As much
as I'd like to show everyone I'm ready, I don't want to try too
hard.... It's definitely an opportunity. But I can't say this will
determine the outcome of my future. It's not the most important
start of my life. I'll go out and try to continue what I did in
Richmond.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen was 3-2 with a 2.30 earned run average at Richmond, and was
dominating there except for one start when he gave up seven runs.
Otherwise, his ERA was 1.10. He said he discovered a flaw in his
delivery that he has corrected.
</P>
<P>
   Chen was among the last to get the word that he was being
recalled, and his Richmond coaches and teammates used that to get a
good laugh at his expense Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves had sent word that Chen was to throw only 30 pitches
in his start Monday night so he'd be well rested for tonight's
start.
</P>
<P>
   Chen threw a 1-2-3 first inning with one strikeout and saw
teammate Ismael Villegas warming up in the bullpen. He pitched
another 1-2-3 inning, this time with two strikeouts, and then saw
Richmond pitching coach Bill Fischer signal for Villegas to come in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like `Hey's what's up? My arm is fine,''' Chen said.
``After that Fish started laughing and said `You're going up.'''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Cox said Thursday the Braves hadn't decided who
would be sent down when Chen is activated today. Both John Hudek
and Russ Springer are out of minor-league options. A likely choice
would be Justin Speier.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez not happy with his hitting
</P>
<P>
   Javy Lopez entered Thursday night's game with a .303 batting
average, highest among the regulars, but he wasn't happy with the
way he's been hitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not concentrating the way I want to,'' Lopez said. ``Even
before my mom died I wasn't feeling good at the plate. I wasn't
feeling good when I came back (after a week off). My mom was part
of the reason, but not the reason. I don't want people to think the
reason I'm doing bad is because I'm thinking of her, because I'm
always thinking of her.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has sore hamstring
</P>
<P>
   While chasing a foul ball Wednesday, Brian Jordan aggravated the
hamstring that hampered him the last week of spring training. He
played Thursday night, but wasn't at full speed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
