NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE ADVISORY
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material is for use only by
arrangement with New York Times Syndicate/Special features. For
purchase information see end of text. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The following is a menu for this week's New America News
Service:
</P>
<P>
   IN ISRAEL, JOURNALISTS OUT FOR BLOOD. If you think the American
press is tough on politicians, think again, suggests columnist Bill
Maxwell, on assignment in the Middle East. The hard-hitting,
focused commentary in Israel's leading media outlets, conservative
and liberal alike, he reports, makes that of most of their American
counterparts read like sophomoric peregrinations. ``Israeli opinion
writers do not need a cause celebre, either an issue or an event or
a person, to go for the jugular,'' he writes. ``Serving a
news-addicted, navel-gazing readership, they employ, among other
journalistic devices, the scalpel, the rapier and the blunt
instrument.''
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN SPRING: A TIME FOR NEW BEGINNINGS. When the first buds
appear on the trees, there is a stirring in Indian hearts, muses
columnist Tim Giago. ``Our Lakota ancestors used to hold religious
ceremonies to welcome the spring, and in the Lakota camps warriors
and women prepared their weapons and cooking utensils for the
buffalo hunts about to begin,'' he writes. This is a ritual that
took place for thousands of years, he says, ``and I believe today
it is still a part of the subconscious mind of every Lakota child,
as it has been through the generations.''
</P>
<P>
   IMMIGRATION INITIATIVE 2000. The same mentality that brought
California the controversial and divisive Proposition 187 in 1994
is preparing a new initiative for the state-wide ballot next March
(2000) that would convert local cops into immigration officers,
reports columnist Raoul Lowery Contreras. ``That will unleash
traffic cops, park rangers, meter maids, State Treasury messengers,
and part-time constables into every nook and cranny of California
to search for people illegally in the country,'' he writes. And you
can bet they won't be looking for blue-eyed blonde types, either,
he adds.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER SKILLS FOR LOW INCOME WORKERS. Visitors to the Web site
for Computers in Our Future (CIOF) in Santa Barbara, California,
are greeted with this stark factoid: 60 percent of new jobs next
year will require computer skills that only 22 percent of workers
now have. But an ambitious program at CIOF is helping low-income
workers gain valuable job skills that could turn this situation
around. Created to foster computer literacy among the poor, this
modest classroom-size education center has already helped more than
2,000 people in its first year of operation, writes Tim Dougherty
in Hispanic Business.
</P>
<P>
   WEST `DISCOVERS' EASTERN MEDICINE. Traditional Asian medicine
appears to be undergoing a popular rebirth in the United States.
Vinita Srivastava, in A. Magazine, examines the West's
``discovery'' of age-old Eastern healing traditions. ``Migration
and shifting public perception may be chipping away at the pariah
status of traditional Asian medicine,'' she writes, ``but
disagreements over the validity of Asian therapies continue to
ensnare governments, major corporations, environmental activists _
and desperate patients looking for cures.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
