<HEADER>
A5399 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIAN-SPRING:GIAGO-N     05-20 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-SPRING:GIAGO-NU-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIAN SPRING: A TIME FOR NEW BEGINNINGS
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material is for use only by
arrangement with New York Times Syndicate/Special features. For
purchase information see end of text. 
 By TIM GIAGO (Nanwica Kciji) 
 &HT;    (Tim Giago, Lakota Indian, is CEO of book publishers Lakota
Times Publishing, Inc., located in Sioux Falls, S.D. His Indian
name is Nanwica Kciji.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    When the first buds on the trees opened into the green leaves of
spring, there was an air of excitement among the boys and girls at
the Holy Rosary Mission boarding school on the Pine Ridge Indian
Reservation in South Dakota.
 &HT;    Perhaps the stirring in our hearts was inherited from our Lakota
ancestors who would hold religious ceremonies to welcome the
spring. There would be joy and anticipation in the Lakota camps as
the warriors and women prepared their weapons and cooking utensils
for the buffalo hunts about to begin.
 &HT;    The cold and oftentimes bitter winter was behind them and the
Lakota prepared to move from their winter camps to their favorite
hunting grounds. This is a ritual that took place for thousands of
years and I believe it was a part of the subconscious mind of every
Lakota child through the generations.
 &HT;    At the mission school it also meant that school was about to let
out.
 &HT;    For nine months we had been virtual captives at the mission. We
attended classes, went to church services seven-days-a-week, and
ate the nearly inedible meals in the school dining halls. We ate so
much yellow, cornmeal mush that our opponents at sporting events
posted banners that read, ``Crush the Mush.''
 &HT;    During the year some of us worked in the farm and dairy units
for Brother Bauer. Some worked in the cobbler and carpentry shops
for Brother Gross. Others worked with the blacksmith, Brother Eban.
And the lucky ones worked with the school baker, Brother Sier.
 &HT;    I worked with the coach; a Lakota man named Bob Clifford was the
school barber. On Sunday nights when the movies were shown in the
school gym, Chuck ``Wobbie'' Trimble and I made the popcorn, bagged
it, and then sold it at the movie concession stand. Of course, we
tried to sneak as many mouthfuls as possible without being caught
by the Jesuit prefect, Mr. Bryde.
 &HT;    So for nine months we went to school, went to church, went to
our jobs and watched for the first signs of spring. When it finally
arrived it was like a miracle.
 &HT;    Early in the morning of the day school let out, we gathered with
our meager belongings and waited in front of Red Cloud Hall for our
parents in the caravans of cars and wagons that would soon be
arriving to take us far away from Holy Rosary Mission.
 &HT;    My cousins Frosty, Pat and Heavy Garnette lived at Potato Creek
(we called it Spud Creek) just a short distance from my home at
Kyle in the center of the reservation. My friends Bill and Johnny
Bear and Dutchie Apple also lived in Kyle and we would talk
excitedly about spending those long, hot summer days fishing and
swimming in Kyle Dam as we waited impatiently for our mothers and
fathers to arrive.
 &HT;    We watched with happiness _ and fear _ as each car made the turn
onto the school grounds from Mission Flats. We were happy because
we knew we were going home but a little frightened that perhaps our
parents had forgotten us. As we spotted our family cars we heaved a
great sigh of relief.
 &HT;    To this day I feel a flutter in my heart and there is a gleam in
my eye when the first leaves of summer appear on the trees. It is a
time for new beginnings.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Tim Giago 
<TEXT>
