</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRATION-INITIATIVE:CONTRERAS-NU-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMMIGRATION INITIATIVE 2000
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material is for use only by
arrangement with New York Times Syndicate/Special features. For
purchase information see end of text. 
 By RAOUL LOWERY CONTRERAS 
 &HT;    (Raoul Lowery Contreras, Mexican American, is a columnist and
editorial board member of La Prensa San Diego. He hosts his own
radio talk show on KOGO-AM.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    As the black-and-white patrol cars of Anycity, California, leave
their stations, observers can note that the town will be well
patrolled by the men and women of the police force.
 &HT;    That may change if a bunch of radicals in Los Angeles get their
way on the state-wide ballot next March (2000). They would convert
local cops into immigration officers.
 &HT;    A crime wave of tsunami proportions could hit the state when
local police officers pretend to be immigration cops. As they waste
their time hassling people who look ``Mexican,'' actual criminals
will run amok on copless streets.
 &HT;    The same mentality that brought us the controversial and
divisive Proposition 187 in 1994 is preparing this new initiative
that will unleash traffic cops, park rangers, meter maids, State
Treasury messengers, and part-time constables into every nook and
cranny of California to search for people illegally in the country.
 &HT;    The proposed title of the initiative: The Local Immigration
Officer Training Act. It would mandate that local/state laws and
policies prohibiting ``cooperation'' between local and state law
enforcement agencies will be by-passed by this Act and such
agencies ``shall provide full cooperation to peace officers in the
performance of immigration law enforcement functions pursuant to an
agreement under'' the U.S. Code.
 &HT;    Under this Act, for example, will a Hispanic legally in the
country report a crime if the victim may be in the country
illegally? Will predator criminals intentionally target illegal
aliens as victims knowing they will not report the crime for fear
that the beat cop will be more concerned about legal residency than
the robbery, burglary, assault, or rape?
 &HT;    Supporting the proposed act is a cabal of anti-immigrant,
anti-Mexican activists. They are the usual suspects. Among the
usual suspects, Los Angeles conservative blacks. This is done to
convince the media and the general public that the sponsors of the
proposed Act are not radical White Supremacists, but rather
inter-racial community minded people who have positive goals. They
fall short, however, when one reads the ``Findings and
Declarations'' of the proposed Act.
 &HT;    Remember, these sponsors are not sociologists, law-enforcement
professionals, elected officials, community organizers. In many
cases they aren't even educated people. They cite no studies, nor
community experience, only their own views _ and gigantic
gratuitous assertions. The following is a sample:
 &HT;    ``Section 1. Findings and Declaration. The People of California
find and declare: That the federal government's enforcement of the
United States immigration laws has failed to prevent millions of
aliens from unlawfully entering California and taking up residence
within the State; That the unlawful presence of millions of aliens
imposes intolerable burdens on California public schools, public
health resources, and other state and local government services and
facilities and fosters a climate of lawlessness that threatens
social peace and stability.''
 &HT;    There is no ``climate of lawlessness'' in California. Are there
``millions of aliens'' in California who have ``unlawfully''
entered the state and taken up ``residence?'' No! No one knows how
many illegals there are, though the Census and Immigration
officials estimate somewhat over 5 million illegal aliens of all
nationalities in the entire country.
 &HT;    The assertions that ``millions'' of illegals are creatinga
``climate of lawlessness'' do not compute with plunging crime rates
all over the state including the inner-cities.
 &HT;    And who will the cops stop?
 &HT;    Don't be fooled by the local pro-immigration-cop proposal. The
proponents will insist the proposal is aimed at all illegal aliens,
not just Mexicans. But everyone knows that is not so.
 &HT;    Will cops stop blonde, blue-eyed people to check if they are
illegal Canadians among us? There are hundreds of thousands of such
illegals living and working in California. Will cops bother them?
No.
 &HT;    Cops will stop everyone who looks Mexican. Every such person
will have to carry proof of citizenship and legal residency.
Imagine, we _ and I _ will have to satisfy cops as to whether we
are living here legally. I won't have to do that in New York, or
Texas, or New Hampshire, just in California.
 &HT;    So, here come police checkpoints, warrantless searches and
midnight raids. People who don't look Mexican won't be
inconvenienced, this time.
 &HT;    But, what about next time?
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Raoul Lowery Contreras 
