<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-LITERACY-NU-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER SKILLS FOR LOW INCOME WORKERS
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material is for use only by
arrangement with New York Times Syndicate/Special features. For
purchase information see end of text. 
 By TIM DOUGHERTY 
 c. 1999 Hispanic Business 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Visitors to the Web site for Computers in Our Future (CIOF) in
Santa Barbara, California, are greeted with this stark factoid: 60
percent of new jobs next year will require computer skills that
only 22 percent of workers now have.
 &HT;    The bad news doesn't end there. The page goes on to tell of an
inequity that lies at the heart of CIOF's raison d'etre: Just 4
percent of U.S. families earning $20,000 or less own a computer
compared to 66 percent of those earning more than $50,000.
 &HT;    Fortunately, developments at the Santa Barbara CIOF facility
itself have been more encouraging. Created to foster computer
literacy among low-income individuals, this modest classroom-size
education center has already helped more than 2,000 people in its
first year of operation.
 &HT;    ``The numbers are better than we ever thought possible. We're
already talking about expanding,'' exclaims John Romo,
vice-president of continuing education for Santa Barbara City
College (SBCC), a partner in the program.
 &HT;    One of 11 such sites across the state funded in part with grants
from the California Wellness Foundation, Santa Barbara's CIOF is
unique in terms of its size and, some organizers would say,
success. Housed at an area community center, it is outfitted with
20 computer terminals where neighborhood residents can learn basic
office applications and Internet navigation, both in a formal
classroom setting and during open access hours.
 &HT;    According to Romo, the center came by its comparatively large
compliment of computers (it's the state's largest CIOF site)
through corporate sponsorship and partnerships with local education
agencies such as SBCC and the area high school district.
 &HT;    If they differ in terms of size and resources, though, all CIOF
sites work from the same premise: computer know-how is the key to
professional advancement.
 &HT;    Data to support the assertion are not hard to find. The top
three job categories in the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics'
Occupational Outlook Handbook, for instance, are all
computer-related: database administrator, computer engineer, and
systems analyst in descending order. Perhaps in recognition of the
trend, 30 percent of Hispanic households now own a computer, up
from 13 percent in 1994, a recent report by the Tomas Rivera Policy
Institute found.
 &HT;    ``We see it as a public health issue, the thinking being that
people who are computer literate will likely be able to better
provide for themselves and their families,'' says Gary L. Yates,
president and CEO of the California Wellness Foundation.
 &HT;    Established in 1992, the private foundation provides grants for
health promotion, wellness education, and disease prevention.
 &HT;    Because the CIOF program targets low-income individuals,
cultural sensitivity is an important concern. In Santa Barbara
classes are taught in English and Spanish. Care is also taken so
participants are not overwhelmed by the subject matter.
 &HT;    ``We're talking about people who have never had access to
computers, at home or through work,'' says Jose Martinez, director
of the Santa Barbara CIOF.
 &HT;    Though the program is aimed primarily at youth and young adults
age 14-23, in the case of Santa Barbara's site at least, a
concerted effort is made to involve parents and other community
members as well. This has made for more than a few instances of
children teaching adults, according to Martinez.
 &HT;    Of course, success tends to beget expansion pressures, and such
has been the case in Santa Barbara. Waiting lists for the center's
computers are becoming increasingly common, and newly added classes
fill quickly. Romo says he's begun exploring partnerships with
other community groups to open other CIOF sites in the community.
 &HT;    In the short term, however, the Santa Barbara CIOF site will
likely have to content itself with its original constituency, which
suits administrators fine. They've just begun tracking the progress
of people who have passed through the program, and initial
indications have been very positive.
 &HT;    In a program to be continued this summer, for example, Santa
Barbara's CIOF recently hosted 43 at-risk students for six weeks of
instruction in Web page development and computer maintenance.
Participants were required to sell Web site concepts to local
businesses before designing and posting them on the Internet. At
the end of the program, many students received job offers and
others are eligible to become certified technicians.
 &HT;    ``Fifteen of them already have jobs in technology-related
fields. It's incredible!'' says Martinez.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Hispanic Business 
<TEXT>
