<HEADER>
A5402 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASIAN-MEDICINE-NU-NYT     05-20 2451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIAN-MEDICINE-NU-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST `DISCOVERS' EASTERN MEDICINE
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material is for use only by
arrangement with New York Times Syndicate/Special features. For
purchase information see end of text. 
 By VINITA SRIVASTAVA 
 c. 1999 A. Magazine 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    In 1983, my grandmother was suffering from heart disease in an
overcrowded hospital in Mumbai (then Bombay). She was flown to New
York City, where my aunt, an M.D., made sure she had the best
treatment options of Western medicine.
 &HT;    While Bibiji, as my grandmother is called, placed her faith in
the Western medicine that saved her life, she also continued to
rely on the spices and healing cures that came from her world,
using huldi (turmeric) for cuts, and chyawanprash, an herbal
supplement for strength used in the Aryuvedic healing system of
South Asia.
 &HT;    My doctor aunt wanted my grandmother off those old traditional
remedies that she believed interfered with the Monday through
Sunday pill regimen. But Bibiji defied my aunt and relied on her
years of experience, opening plastic bags of mixed powders and jars
of black jam and taking spoonfuls anyway. Very good, she said, this
is very good.
 &HT;    In the private arena of my grandmother's sickness, two vastly
different systems of healing collided. The holistic approach toward
health _ a balance of exercise, herbal supplements and spiritual
well-being _ is the cornerstone of traditional Asian medicine. And
``alternative'' methods such as acupuncture and Aryuvedic sound
therapy (chanting) have withstood the test of centuries.
 &HT;    But while some Western doctors have begun to research and
integrate Asian techniques in their own practices, the attitude of
the U.S. medical establishment toward these healing models has
until recently been one of stubborn resistance _ rooted in a
complicated matrix of colonialism, ignorance and the efficacy of
scientific discoveries like the MRI and penicillin.
 &HT;    Migration and shifting public perception may be chipping away at
the pariah status of traditional Asian medicine, but disagreements
over the validity of Asian therapies continue to ensnare
governments, major corporations, environmental activists and
desperate patients looking for cures. Traditional Asian medicine
can split families, produce miracles or cause tragedy, depending on
your perspective.
 &HT;    Karna Singh first learned of alternatives to Western medicine
when his brother Gora, a dancer, was diagnosed with AIDS in 1993.
Karna watched the toxic side effects of prescription drugs weaken
Gora's already frail condition and decided to research other
options. Gora gave up on the drugs and went the herbal way, and
Karna saw him dance again. But the doctor, who did not know about
the dancer's herbal turn, encouraged him to try the new
pharmaceutical cocktails. When Gora went back on the drugs, his
condition deteriorated. He died in 1997, leaving Karna to campaign
for HMO coverage of alternative healing.
 &HT;    Some insurance companies and HMOs, including Oxford, Blue
Cross/Blue Shield, Aetna Health Management and Travelers, are
starting to cover alternative therapies, but policies still depend
to a large extent on state laws. Washington state passed a law in
1996 requiring insurers to pay for visits to any certified,
licensed health care provider within the state. And alternative
health plans are available in Arizona, California, Colorado,
Florida, Massachusetts, New Mexico, North Carolina and Wisconsin.
 &HT;    Moreover, there are active lobbies all over the country pressing
for a fundamental change in the predominant health care paradigm.
``The question of health goes way beyond a tablet or an
injection,'' says Singh. ``We have to get into the whole way of
life. It's about how we do things.''
 &HT;    It seems public opinion is behind him. In a special issue
dedicated to alternative medicine, the Journal of the American
Medical Association (JAMA) reported in November that approximately
83 million (one-third of all Americans) have used some form of
herbal medication and that visits to ``alternative practitioners''
increased by 50 percent between 1990 to 1997.
 &HT;    A stream of recent news reports has interpreted the trend as
part of the ``green'' movement, a backlash against the
chemical-industrial-technological character of life in the United
States. At the heart of it all is the realization that there are
aspects to illness, both emotional and spiritual, that have not
been adequately addressed by Western medicine.
 &HT;    Despite the growing interest in ``alternative medicine,'' many
traditional Asian healing methods still carry a certain stigma that
confines them to a perennial gray area. Less than 40 percent of
those who use alternative therapies inform their medical doctors,
according to JAMA. And payment for alternative treatment most often
comes out of pocket.
 &HT;    In contrast to the ``quack'' stereotype, however, acupuncturists
and herbologists must undergo a lengthy training period in order to
practice legally. In the United States, hopeful practitioners study
for three to four years before taking the certification exam of the
National Commission for the Certification of Acupuncture and
Oriental Medicine (given in English, Chinese or Korean). In
addition, most states have their own licensing requirements.
Training in Asian countries is even more rigorous _in China, for
example, it includes five years of study plus a minimum of three
years as an apprentice.
 &HT;    Traditional Asian techniques have an impressive track record
with chronic conditions, often prevailing where Western medicine
has failed. Rui Lian He, an acupuncturist and herbologist
specializing in infertility problems, has some patients who travel
to her Brooklyn, New York office from as far away as Connecticut
and Tennessee because of the success of her treatments.
 &HT;    One of her patients, a 27-year-old New York City schoolteacher
named Vaughn Maloney, said he suffered from debilitating back pain
three years ago. Sitting, getting up and climbing stairs caused
searing pain, but Maloney's doctor told him there was nothing
wrong. A friend referred him to He, who prescribed a combination of
herbs to clear up a ``blockage of energy,'' and he has felt no back
pain since. ``She uses preventative measures,'' says Maloney. ``I
have a regular doctor, but I don't go to him anymore.''
 &HT;    Anecdotal evidence abounds attesting to the capacity of
traditional Asian therapies to heal chronic conditions such as
asthma, allergies and back pain. And the JAMA report includes
studies demonstrating the efficacy of various traditional Asian
therapies in correcting breech position in late pregnancy,
relieving irritable bowel symptoms and healing some symptoms of
carpal tunnel syndrome.
 &HT;    Regulatory bureaucracies, however, have been slow to respond to
the trend. Popular remedies like ginseng and goldenseal cannot be
sold as medicine but as ``dietary supplements,'' because they
cannot make medical claims without the approval of the Food and
Drug Administration. If someone wants to sell a product for
medicinal purposes, they must first apply for a new drug
application _ a process that requires regulation testing and costs
millions of dollars. And that does not include the money needed for
clinical trials.
 &HT;    In fact, 25 percent of all pharmaceuticals on the market are
derived from natural remedies. Aspirin, the birth control pill,
certain heart medications and some cancer drugs all come from
herbal derivatives. Many in the medical establishment believe the
expensive research behind these pharmaceuticals is absolutely
necessary. ``Those remedies have all been rigorously tested,'' says
Dr. Anita Srivastava, a family and community physician at Women's
College Hospital in Toronto (and sister of the author).
 &HT;    ``I don't have anything against natural remedies, but I resent
people who assume pharmaceutical companies are evil, doing harm.
Just because something is natural does not mean it is not harmful.
People who make herbal products are out to make a buck. Just like
the pharmaceuticals,'' says Srivastava, coming off her emergency
room shift. ``I had to use forceps tonight to pull a clove of
garlic from a woman's ear. She said it cured congestion, which is
maybe true, but she has to do it safely. With a pharmaceutical you
get the same thing every time.''
 &HT;    Much of the recent media hype surrounding herbal medicine has
fixated on this ``Wild West'' atmosphere in which American
consumers are trying out herbs without being informed about the
proper dosage and potentialy negative side effects. This goes very
much against the traditional Asian approach, in which herbology is
considered an exact science.
 &HT;    ``Every herb can be dangerous if you take too much,'' warns He.
She says it is important for those taking herbs to do so under the
supervision of an herbologist who knows how to combine herbs to
counterbalance negative effects.
 &HT;    These days, popular interest in traditional Asian therapies is
bringing medical philosophy full-circle. ``Germany and the United
States are recapturing folk medicine _ whether it's African,
aboriginal, Aruyvedic or Chinese,'' says Singh. ``e trailing behind
the Western realization that these (old techniques) have answers.''
 &HT;    Asian and Western medical theories have traversed the globe so
much that while some research firms predict the U.S. herbal
medicine market could reach $12.3 billion by 2001, Chinese exports
now account for o world's $15 billion market in herbal products.
Even within China, traditional medicine sales are sagging due to
the increased reliance on Western pharmaceuticals.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, major U.S. pharmaceutical corporations, with brand
names like Bayer, Centrum and Benadryl, have begun to market their
own herbal supplements. The presence of these corporate giants in
the herbal world (praised by some as a development that will rid
the market of snake-oil-peddling charlatans) is likely to crush
mom-and-pop herb companies. For American consumers unfamiliar with
Chinese or Hindi labels, buying herbs with a popular brand name
bolstered by millions of marketing dollars, seems a safer bet. Even
Wal-mart is introducing its own line of herbal supplements.
 &HT;    Dr. Deepak Chopra, who went to medical school in India and once
worked a $101-per-week job in Plainfield, New Jersey, is one of the
few successfully making a fortune in the West off of things Indian.
Sales of Chopra's books, in which he simplifies ancient Hindu texts
and philosphies for the American masses, have soard past the 10
million mark.
 &HT;    Despite his stunning popularity and colossal book sales,
however, this Buddha of Surburbia has been mocked by mainstream
medicine as an Indian guru and a throwback to the Beatles' yoga
days. The National Council Against Health Fraud has accused him of
substituting superstition for medicine. And in 1991, JAMA printed
an article that so offended Chopra that he took them to court for
mocking his beliefs (the suit was settled out of court for an
undisclosed amount).
 &HT;    The spiritual emphasis of the holistic approach in Asian
medicine is one reason for its growing popularity. Unlike the
Western approach of isolating the problem in order to cure it,
Asian therapies are based on a `full body' approach that places
some of the power and responsibility in the hands of the sick
themselves.
 &HT;    The key component of Asian healing systems is not cellular
biology but the human energy field, called qi in China, kuna in
Hawaii and prana in India. East Asian healing practices, typfied by
the Chinese system, seek to regulate qi with herbs and treatments
such as acupunture. And Aryuveda balances prana through the
relationship between food (seen as medicine), body, mind and
spirit. Both these systems say good health is all-encompassing, and
they require a full relationship with the body, mind, and spirit
 &HT;    Dr. R. Zhu, a traditional Chinese doctor trained in herbology
and acupuncture with a practice in Manhattan's Chinatown, says he
chose Chinese medicine over Western because he believes they are
less toxic. Zhu comes from generations of herbologists and still
uses family secrets to treat patients. His rates are cheaper than a
visit to an M.D., with a sliding scale ranging from $20 for a minor
prescription to $40 for more involved treatments. Although Zhu
admits that when he is unable to treat a sick person, he sends them
to the hospital, his medicine is the preferred route to health in
Chinatown.
 &HT;    While practitioners of Asian medicine have readily acknowledged
the strength of Western medical science in treating acute,
life-threatening conditions, the U.S. medical establishment has f
acupuncture's capacity to heal over 43 disorders, including
sinusitis and addictions.
 &HT;    There are other signs that Asian and Western medical
philosophies may be coming together. In China, doctors trained in
Western medicine work alongside acupunturists and herbologists, and
acupunture is often used as a natural (and cost-effective)
substitute for anaesthesia in minor surgeries.
 &HT;    In the United States, practicing M.D.s are taking abbreviated
training courses in traditional Asian therapies, according to the
American Association of Oriental Medicine. And the FDA passed the
Dietary Supplement Health and Education Act in 1994, allowing
companies to make some health claims on their products.
 &HT;    The change has its limits, however, according to Elizabeth
Carstens, the marketing manager of Nature Care (the company is the
U.S. distributor for Dabur India, the oldest and largest
manufacturer of Aryuvedic products). Although Dabur India has been
researching Aryuvedic products for 116 years, holding clinical
trials at their Research Foundation in New Delhi, India, ``We
(still) cannot make disease claims,'' says Carstens. ``For example,
you can say something supports the joints but not that it is used
to treat arthritis. And we can't have `medicine' anywhere on our
product, and others pass on Asian healing methods, disparate
approaches to health are slowly beginning to move together. Western
society wants easy and fast answers, Dr. Zhu says. But healing
oneself takes time, and one must swallow the bitter herbs day after
day.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 A. Magazine 
