<HEADER>
A5412 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-STAMPS-$ADV23-NY     05-20 0360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-STAMPS-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU CAN'T KICK THE TIRES, BUT YOU CAN LICK THE STAMPS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BARTH HEALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PSSST! Wanna buy a nice old car _ cheap? The Post Office has
some Model T Fords, half a Gatsby-era limo and some well-finned
1950s models including a turquoise '57 Chevrolet Bel Air cream
puff, all going for 32 or 33 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe you would settle for a stylized hood ornament _ pretend
it's from a Rolls-Royce _ for just 10 cents. The ultimate tailfin
of the '50s, from the classic '59 Cadillac, is just 15 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Postal Service is issuing sheets of ``Celebrate the
Century'' stamps, 15 for each decade, with each stamp highlighting
a different bit of history. Stamps for the next decade to be
celebrated, the 1950s, come out on Wednesday with three automotive
motifs: the aforementioned Bel Air as a paean to ``Tail Fins and
Chrome,'' plus drive-in movies and stock-car racing. The stock-car
stamp features another '57 Chevy, along with a '59.
</P>
<P>
   An automotive theme has been threaded throughout the series.
There was a Model T Ford for the 1900s and a Gatsby limo, sort of a
composite Duesenberg, for the 20s. The Ford Mustang is next to
arrive, in August, on the 1960s sheet.
</P>
<P>
   The topics have been chosen by popular vote, with mail-in
ballots at every post office and an electronic ballot at the Postal
Service's Web site (http://www.usps.gov).
</P>
<P>
   Alas, there were no automotive topics chosen for the 1970s _ the
decade of fuel crises was not a stellar period for car design. For
the 1980s, minivans ran 21st in a field of 25 possibilities,
defeated by Cabbage Patch dolls and four electronic-oriented
categories. (Video games got the most votes.)
</P>
<P>
   There is a chance that an automotive stamp will make the 1990s
series, however; sport utility vehicles are on the current ballot.
</P>
<P>
   If they fail to make the cut, hobbyists can just settle for
those 10-cent hood ornaments and 15-cent Cadillac fins. But they
appear on coil stamps used for advertising mail, so a special
permit is needed to use them on your subscription renewal for Car
and Driver.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
