<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5418 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-NUKE-1STLD-WRIT     05-20 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-NUKE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE COMMITTEE CONCLUDES CHINA STOLE NUCLEAR SECRETS, OFFICIALS
SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Subs 5th and 6th graphs to note activities may have taken
place in previous administrations; 10th and 12th graph to clarify;
14th graph to correct day of briefing; 20th graph to add first
reference to Federico Pena)  
(rm) 
 By JEFF GERTH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A House committee has unanimously concluded that
China systematically stole significant U.S. nuclear design secrets,
enabling Beijing to accelerate its weapons program so that it now
possesses thermonuclear weapons design information on a par with
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's report will be released next week, but this
summary came Thursday from officials who have read the committee's
final report or heard its findings in a closed Senate briefing on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The stolen technology has allowed Beijing in a few years to leap
from a 1950s-era nuclear capability to possessing the most modern
technical information, the officials said. China vehemently denies
the accusations of espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Senators who attended the closed briefing, which was conducted
by Reps. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., and Norman Dicks, D-Wash., said
the findings were deeply disquieting.
</P>
<P>
   According to officials who have been briefed about its contents,
the report concludes that Beijing's acquisition of secret U.S.
weapons designs was part of an intelligence collection effort that
spanned 20 years, including both Republican and Democratic
administrations.
</P>
<P>
   The report also enumerates an array of thefts from the
government's weapons labs, including classified information about
seven advanced nuclear warheads, among them the W-88, the most
sophisticated nuclear weapon in the U.S. arsenal; that theft is
believed to have occurred during the Reagan or Bush administration.
The report also says that China stole design information about the
neutron bomb.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said that after
listening to the briefing Wednesday about Chinese espionage, ``the
hair on the back of my neck stood up because it's scary.'' The
Mississippi Republican added, ``I haven't seen anything like it
before in my 26 years in Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Building and deploying a nuclear weapons system requires more
than the design information, but such data is among the most
closely of American military secrets. Lott questioned why President
Clinton and his administration didn't act sooner to prevent
security breaches and he criticized the White House for delaying
the release of the Cox committee report.
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokesman, Jim Kennedy, said, ``Senator Lott's
comments are mystifying given the fact that Chairman Cox has said
we've been working cooperatively with the committee.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 the Energy Department and the Central Intelligence
Agency began to learn the record of China's alleged espionage. But
President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore were not personally
told of the findings until much later, officials said. On Thursday,
at a Senate hearing, Energy Department documents were released
showing that Gore's office was told by Energy Department officials
early on, at least in 1996 and possibly in 1995, about the first
indications of Chinese espionage at U.S. weapons laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's national security adviser, Leon S. Fuerth, was briefed in
April 1996, according to testimony before the Senate Energy and
Natural Resources Committee by Notra Trulock, an Energy Department
intelligence official. This came about the same time the
president's deputy national security adviser, Sandy Berger, was
first told about China's spying.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Rosshirt, a foreign affairs spokesman for Gore, said
Thursday that Fuerth has no recollection or record of a 1995
briefing. He confirmed the 1996 briefing but said that Fuerth
waited until last March to tell the vice president about China's
alleged espionage, shortly after news accounts of the spying
appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Berger did not speak with the president about Chinese spying for
at least a year, telling the Cox committee that it was in early
1998. Berger's aides now say he remembers informing Clinton in July
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's briefing by both Cox and Dicks was an unusual
display of bipartisanship at a time when Congress has been riven
over issues ranging from gun control to Social Security reform.
</P>
<P>
   The findings in the Cox report reflect the unanimous conclusions
of both Republicans and Democrats on the House committee, which has
spent months investigating allegations of Chinese espionage. Some
of the committee's findings remain classified and will not be
included in the report.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright or Secretary of Commerce
William Daley were not briefed by the Energy Department on the
allegations until the end of last year, when the Cox committee
finished its report, officials said. Since the first of the year,
the committee and officials in the administration have been
laboring intensively to figure out which portions of the report
could be declassified, but according to Cox the effort did not
quicken until March.
</P>
<P>
   Cox has said that about 30 percent of the committee's findings
will remain secret due to concerns by intelligence and law
enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has said he acted quickly upon learning of the
espionage threat at the government's weapons labs, ordering a
series of tightened security measures in February 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But Trulock, a top intelligence official at the Energy
Department, told the Senate committee Thursday that some White
House officials and senior Energy Department officials did not act
expeditiously on the information that he and his aides brought to
them in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Richardson, who took over the leadership of the Energy
Department from Federico Pena in the fall of 1998, has enacted a
far-reaching reorganization, especially in recent months since the
completion of the Cox committee report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since my appointment as secretary of energy, no mission has
been more important to me than improved counterintelligence and
security at the Department's national laboratories,'' he told the
House Committee on Science Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The questions about the Clinton administration's response to
information about Chinese espionage go beyond security procedures
at the labs. The Cox Committee, officials said, also found fault
with the administration's loosening of controls over the export of
sensitive commercial technologies which have applications to
nuclear weapons systems.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, President Clinton relaxed controls on sales of advanced
computers to countries like China. The next year, his
administration resisted Congressional efforts to retighten those
controls. The Cox committee concluded that some of the American
computers sold to China went to organizations involved in military
activities and that ineffective verification requirements raise the
possibility that American computers have been used for such
military purposes as upgrading nuclear weapons or developing more
accurate missiles, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, China pledged to stop physically testing nuclear
weapons, increasing its reliance on advanced computers for
simulations.
</P>
<P>
   Also in 1996, the U.S. intelligence community reported that
China had successfully stolen secret American design information
about the neutron bomb.
</P>
<P>
   That same year President Clinton shifted the licensing
responsibility for some commercial satellite sales from the more
security-oriented State Department to the business-friendly
Commerce Department. The Cox Committee, officials said, concluded
that the shift was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   The technology used to launch a satellite into space is similar
to the technology used to deliver a missile armed with nuclear
warheads.
</P>
<P>
   The Cox committee hired an outside expert to evaluate help that
was given Chinese scientists in the mid 1990s by two U.S. aerospace
companies, Hughes Electronics and Loral Space and Communications.
The companies are under criminal investigation and have denied any
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The committee concluded that the companies illegally transferred
information that benefited China's civilian and military rockets
and is helpful in the design of future Chinese ballistic missiles,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the panel's most severe criticism was aimed at Hughes,
which the committee found had intentionally side-stepped State
Department licensing requirements in 1995, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The issue involves a 1995 decision by the Commerce Department
that said it permitted Hughes to help the Chinese solve a rocket
failure _ even though State Department approval was required.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the chairman of Hughes also headed President
Clinton's export advisory council.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
