<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-LIBERMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERALD J. LIBERMAN, EXPERT ON STATISTICS, DIES AT 73  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y.)   By NICK RAVO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gerald J. Lieberman, a former Stanford University provost and an
expert in statistics and operations research, died on Tuesday at
his home on the Stanford campus in Palo Alto, Calif. He was 73.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, commonly known as
Lou Gehrig's disease, according to a statement from the university.
</P>
<P>
   In his later years, as his condition worsened, Lieberman was a
research subject at Stanford's Center for the Study of Language and
Information, working with engineers who were designing
communications devices for the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   He tested a variety of equipment, including a voice synthesizer
that researchers outfitted with special word-prediction software.
His synthesizer was programmed so that he could rattle off his
favorite catch phrase _ ``Take the rest of the day off!'' _ with a
single stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman was provost or acting provost during the presidencies
of three Stanford leaders and held several other administrative
positions, including vice provost and dean of graduate studies and
research and associate dean of humanities and sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman was born on Dec. 31, 1925, in Brooklyn. He graduated
from Cooper Union in 1948 and received a master's degree from
Columbia University in 1949. He received his doctorate from
Stanford in 1952. The next year, he joined the Stanford faculty in
statistics and industrial engineering.
</P>
<P>
   He retired in 1995. At the time of his death, he was professor
emeritus of operations research and statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is survived by his wife, Helen; three daughters, Janet
Lieberman Argyres of Castro Valley, Calif., Joanne Lieberman of
Palo Alto and Diana Lieberman of Palo Alto; a son, Michael
Lieberman of Palo Alto; a sister, Shirley Ross of Great Neck, N.Y.,
and two grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
