<HEADER>
A5422 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-CARS-MAXIMA-ART     05-20 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-MAXIMA-ART-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2000 NISSAN MAXIMA: MAXIMUM BANG FOR MINIMUM BUCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23)  
 (af)  
 By PETER PASSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the modern pantheon of hot cars, the Nissan Maxima ranks as a
minor deity _ not up there with, say, the BMW 3-Series, yet forever
to be honored as the first midsize sport sedan for about the same
price as a drab family hauler.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced in 1981, the Maxima had crisp handling and a peppy
engine, and it quickly won converts among Americans accustomed to
Detroit bargemobiles and dorky Japanese compacts. A new, sleeker
design in 1985 _ with front-wheel drive and a standard V6 engine _
brought annual sales into six-figure range.
</P>
<P>
   Another major makeover in 1995, which delivered more interior
room and better performance for less money, cemented customer
loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   But in today's global market, all automakers must run simply to
stay in place. And a series of snazzy, competitively priced midsize
sedans led by the Audi A4 cruelly dated the old Maxima. Yes, it
still had an enviable record for reliability as well as the
smoothest V6 around.
</P>
<P>
   But now that the competition was so refined, including somewhat
less expensive family sedans like the Honda Accord and Toyota
Camry, the rack-and-pinion steering seemed too light, the driver's
seating position seemed a bit awkward and the styling looked dowdy.
Sales have remained above the 100,000 mark, in large part because
Nissan offered sweet lease deals and generous rebates on the
already modest sticker price.
</P>
<P>
   Could the Maxima make a comeback? The auguries were not
promising: Nissan was strapped for cash and, in any case, top
executives feared that any radical change in the familiar shape
would alienate tradition-minded customers in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   But with a lot of help from the design studio in California and
the engineering nerds in Japan, Nissan has pulled off the
improbable. After a mechanical revamping and substantial face lift,
the Japanese-built 2000 Maxima is again a world-class,
no-compromise sport sedan and a marvelous bargain to boot. Even the
styling, though no match for the cool postmodern designs coming
from Europe, will turn a few heads.
</P>
<P>
   Some specifics: The standard 24-valve, 3-liter V6 has been
goosed to 222 horsepower, a gain of 32, and the torque curve has
been flattened to provide raging acceleration in the 20 to 60 mph
range at which most drivers merge into freeway traffic. The
four-wheel independent suspension has merely been tinkered with.
</P>
<P>
   But somehow, small mechanical changes have led to large gains in
surefootedness. The light feel of the wheel has been fixed with
more sophisticated speed-sensitive power steering.
</P>
<P>
   With stop-and-go traffic and cell phones to contend with, most
Maxima buyers will doubtless choose the electronically controlled
four-speed automatic. But purists can still opt for the
glassy-slick five-speed manual that I drove.
</P>
<P>
   The Maxima does not stint on safety. Front air bags are
standard, of course, and side air bags can be had for extra money.
The Maxima's excellent anti-skid disk brakes are still excellent.
</P>
<P>
   An electronic traction control is available as an option on cars
with the automatic transmission. All models get terrific halogen
headlights. And the sporty SE version will be available with
17-inch wheels and grippy low-profile tires.
</P>
<P>
   Evolutionary changes in the Maxima's suspension and drivetrain
are complemented by revolutionary changes in comfort and
convenience. The wheelbase is just 2 inches longer, the body is
stretched by only 1.5 inches and the curb weight is up just 50
pounds, but the cabin is far more airy.
</P>
<P>
   The previous Maxima's front seats seemed too narrow and the
footwells too small for long American legs. Now the seating is
reminiscent of the Lexus ES300 or the new Acura 3.2TL, with
eight-way adjustment, more padding and room to sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   The back seat, miracle of miracles, can now manage a fifth
passenger in relative comfort. And the suppression of road noise is
up to the standards of the near-luxury class.
</P>
<P>
   The Maxima's controls have been improved, too, with handsome,
readable gauges and bigger buttons. The audio system comes in three
grades ranging from a 60-watt, four-speaker version to a 200-watt,
seven-speaker behemoth by Bose, with integrated cassette and CD
players.
</P>
<P>
   Cup holders and a second 12-volt outlet have been added in the
rear. And the 60-40 split back seats fold forward, allowing
oversize objects to pass through from the trunk.
</P>
<P>
   So what about the Maxima's looks? Both the front and rear have
been reworked to pass for contemporary without sacrificing what
Nissan's chief designer, Gerald Hirshberg, calls it's
``Maxima-ness.'' It's still no beauty, but the over-the-hill
generic Japanese aspect is gone.
</P>
<P>
   I've saved the best for last. Better handling, more power and a
much stiffer chassis have transformed the Maxima into a driving
machine that transcends the class. Equipped with the five-speed
manual, it has become the poor man's BMW _ and I mean the 5-series
BMW with a real back seat, not the 3-series that barely
accommodates four.
</P>
<P>
   My guess is that dealers who can coax showroom browsers into
test drives will make a lot of easy sales.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not the very best: the by-no-means-stripped Maxima
GXE lists for just $21,569, while the gussied-up GLE can be had for
$26,769. Adding leather and a sunroof can run up the bill a bit
more. But feature-by-feature, the Maxima is a solid $3,000 to
$5,000 less than comparable sedans from Acura, Audi and others. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 2231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
