<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY MOVES TOWARD REQUIRING `SMART GUN' TECHNOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ A state Senate committee Thursday unanimously
approved a requirement that all handguns sold in the state five
years from now be equipped with so-called smart-gun technology,
computer chips or other features that make the guns inoperable by
anyone other than their owners.
</P>
<P>
   The vote marked the first time that a smart-gun requirement had
advanced this far in any state legislature and was cheered by gun
control advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Jersey is on track to become the first state in the nation
to require that only firearms that have been personalized for an
authorized user can be sold in the state,'' said Sarah Brady,
chairwoman of Handgun Control, the nation's largest gun control
lobbying organization.
</P>
<P>
   The vote came on the wave of widespread national concern about
school shootings, like the one in April in Littleton, Colo., and on
the day that yet another school shooting drama was unfolding in
Conyers, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate committee, as expected, also approved a bill Thursday
requiring trigger locks on handguns; it would take effect
immediately upon becoming law.
</P>
<P>
   With regard to the smart-gun measure, both Democratic and
Republican supporters said that the requirement would pave the way
for the next generation of laws intended to reduce gun violence and
make guns truly childproof.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Richard Codey, D-Essex County, a co-sponsor of the
measure with state Sen. Joseph Palaia, R-Monmouth County, said: ``I
endorse trigger locks, but that wouldn't have prevented the
Littleton massacre, and maybe nothing would have. But childproof
handguns can.''
</P>
<P>
   Although likely to pass in the Senate, the measure still faces
an uphill battle in the Assembly, which is controlled by
Republicans, like the Senate, and has traditionally been more
receptive to the gun lobby. But this is an election year for
Assembly members, a factor that could persuade legislators to vote
for the smart-gun legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Should the measure pass both houses it will still have to be
signed by Gov. Christie Whitman. Although Whitman favored trigger
locks long before many political figures in the state, she has
expressed doubts about whether the technology to produce smart guns
has advanced enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to look at that again if and when this measure
passes,'' said Pete McDonough, a spokesman for the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Under the measure, which is slated for a vote in the full Senate
next month, trigger locks would immediately be required on all
handguns sold in the state. Three years from now, the state
attorney general, if convinced that there is a proven smart-gun
technology available, could order that the technology be included
on all handguns sold in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The requirement could be delayed for two more years if the gun
industry is unable to develop smart guns by then. But in any event,
the smart-gun requirement would go into effect no later than 2004,
Codey said.
</P>
<P>
   The measure that was passed Thursday had dropped requirements
that many supporters felt could have indefinitely delayed the
effective date or mired it in subjective considerations about the
``commercial viability'' of the technology.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Morton, president and chief executive officer of Oxford
Micro Devices, a company in Monroe, Conn., that manufactures
smart-gun devices, said that smart guns could on the market within
18 months of the passage of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying before the committee, Morton said there were about 30
patents related to smart-gun technology. They ranged, he said, from
devices like the one his company produces, which reads fingerprints
and compares them with those of authorized users stored in a
computer chip, to radio-controlled or magnetic systems that match a
mechanism in the gun with a mechanism carried by authorized users.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the trigger-lock and smart-gun measures, the
committee also passed bills Thursday that would grant sales tax
exemptions and rebates up to $5 on the purchase of trigger locks
and firearm vaults.
</P>
<P>
   The intense political interest in gun issues could be seen
throughout Thursday's packed hearing. Early in the session,
proponents and opponents of the smart-gun measure recessed and were
closeted in the offices of Senate President Donald DiFrancesco, who
reportedly helped hammer out a compromise that allowed the
trigger-lock bill and the smart-gun measure to move forward
together. Committee members returned but immediately ran into
confusion about the exact form of the compromise and had to recess
briefly again to clarify the terms.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Miller, executive director of the Coalition of New
Jersey Sportsmen, which is made up of gun owners who support
trigger locks but oppose the smart-gun requirement, said the
smart-gun measure was ``nothing more than a gun ban.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller blamed Senate Republicans for allowing the measure to
advance, predicting that it would hurt the political chances of
DiFrancesco, who is expected to run for governor if Whitman wins
the U.S. Senate seat of the retiring Sen. Frank Lautenberg.
Similarly, he said, Whitman would be hurt politically should she
ultimately embrace the smart-gun measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whitman and DiFrancesco are going to lose us as a base, all in
order to pick up no one among the Democrats,'' Miller said. ``This
is all foolish.''
</P>
</TEXT>
