<HEADLINE>
NBA'S BIG FUTURE: DUNCAN VS. O'NEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Tim Duncan and Shaquille O'Neal are the preeminent
centers in the NBA today, and they seem to have inherited the
burden of carrying the league into the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   However, NBA observers say it's too early to start comparing
what they do on the basketball court to any of those clashes of old
between Bill Russell and Wilt Chamberlain. And that's in spite of
what has transpired in the West Conference semifinals between
Duncan's San Antonio Spurs and O'Neal's Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't guard each other that much, so I don't know if I
can compare them to Russell and Chamberlain,'' Spurs forward Sean
Elliott said. ``But they'll have to guard each other a lot in the
future, because there's going to be a day when \RSpurs center\S
David \RRobinson\S isn't here any more, and Tim is going to be the
center. So I'm sure they will have some battles.''
</P>
<P>
   Both O'Neal and Duncan will have their talents on display when
the Lakers and Spurs play at the Great Western Forum in Inglewood,
Calif., tomorrow at 4:30 p.m. in Game 3 of this best-of-seven
series. San Antonio won two games at home this week and leads the
series, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan dominated Game 1 with 25 points and six blocks, then made
the game-winning shot in Game 2. But Duncan, contrary to popular
belief, claims he is not the straw that stirs the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of players on this team who have helped us get
to where we are today,'' he said. ``I'm just trying to do my part
to help us win some games.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan has the skills of a forward, but is trapped in a center's
body. The 7-foot, 255-pounder starts at power forward for the
Spurs, but slides over and plays center when Robinson needs a break
or gets in foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   However, Duncan knows that when Robinson _ who turns 34 in
August _ retires, he'll see much more of O'Neal in head-to-head
combat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq is such a big body that we have to get him out of the
post and not give him high percentage opportunities,'' Duncan said.
``But there's no one person that can go out there and stop him
one-on-one. It's a team effort, and we're going to need that.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal said the matchup _ whatever it is _ will be in his favor
going into the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim Duncan is cool, but no one man can guard me,'' O'Neal
said. ``The only way to guard Shaq is to break the rules that the
NBA is supposed to enforce, but they never enforce them, which is
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Marty Blake, the NBA director of scouting, said he doesn't
particularly favor O'Neal over Duncan, or vice versa. He simply
gives the advantage to the player who is surrounded by the best
collection of talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're totally different kind of players,'' Blake said.
``Duncan can do more things that Shaq, but Shaq is overpowering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq is a dominating force in the middle. He'll get better.
He'll play a long time, and they've got to find a way to get him
the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Both O'Neal and Duncan are candidates to win this year's NBA
most valuable player award. That comes after O'Neal led the Lakers
in scoring (26.3) and rebounding (10.7), and led the NBA in
field-goal shooting (.576 percent), while Duncan led the Spurs in
scoring (21.7) and rebounding (11.4).
</P>
<P>
   Duncan's rise is phenomenal, because the swimming fanatic didn't
pick up a basketball until he was 14 years old. That was nine years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now in only his second NBA season, Duncan is playing like a wily
veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim has done just a terrific job in figuring out what the NBA
is all about,'' Robinson said. ``He amazes me with his maturity
level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told someone, when I first saw Tim play, I said I believe
I'm going to be playing more at the center position, because he can
pass and handle the ball better than I can.''
</P>
<P>
   While no one expects Duncan and O'Neal to match the championship
exploits of Russell and Chamberlain _ they collectively won every
NBA title from 1959-69, plus two others _ NBA fans can anticipate
some fierce matchups in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Tim's contract is up, I told him, `I'm going with you,
brother,' '' Spurs guard Mario Elie said. ``That guy is special.
He's a talented young player. And so is Shaq.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
