<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER COLLEAGUE TESTIFIES AGAINST SUSPECT IN POLICE TORTURE
CASE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A second police officer testified Thursday that the
officer accused of torturing Abner Louima made statements linking
himself to the attack in the restroom of a Brooklyn police station.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Michael Schoer told a jury in U.S. District Court in
Brooklyn that Officer Justin A. Volpe showed him a stick and said
that a brownish stain on it was human feces, several hours after
prosecutors say Officer Volpe rammed a stick into Louima's rectum.
</P>
<P>
   Schoer testified on a day when Volpe's lawyer, in a sharp
reversal of his stated plans, chose not to cross-examine the first
officer who testified Volpe made statements regarding the torture
of Louima. After the testimony on Wednesday of the first officer,
Kenneth Wernick, had ended for the day, the lawyer, Marvyn M.
Kornberg, had told reporters to ``wait for the cross'' before
forming any judgments on the reliability of the witness. But in a
surprising move Thursday, Kornberg told the judge that he had no
questions for Wernick, a sergeant who held the rank of officer at
time of the alleged beating. Kornberg later told reporters: ``We've
changed our position, it's that simple. We've changed the trial
tactic in the case. You'll see why when we finish the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoer testified Thursday that Volpe showed him a stick in the
70th Precinct station house in Flatbush on the morning of Aug. 9,
1997. ``He was holding a stick or an object that appeared to me to
be a stick,'' Schoer said. ``Off the cuff, I asked him what was
that,'' he said, referring to a stain ``two or three inches long''
on a stick that he said was about two to two and a half feet long.
</P>
<P>
   Schoer's testimony corroborated part of Wernick's. The sergeant
testified that Volpe boasted to him on the same morning of having
shoved a stick ``five or six inches'' into Louima's rectum.
</P>
<P>
   Wernick's testimony was the first to support Louima's account
early in the trial that Volpe had jammed a stick into his rectum
after Louima, 32, a Haitian immigrant, had been arrested in a melee
outside a Flatbush nighclub.Prosecutors say that the attack with
the stick caused major injuries to Louima's rectum and bladder.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Volpe, three other officers are on trial on
federal charges of violating Louima's civil rights. Louima
testified that a second officer _ identified by prosecutors as
Charles Schwarz _ had held him down while Volpe brutalized him.
Louima said Volpe, Schwarz and two others _ identified as Thomas
Wiese and Thomas Bruder _ beat him in a police car before he was
taken to the station house. Louima is black and all the officers
are white. A fifth defendant, Sgt. Michael Bellomo, is charged with
trying to cover up the alleged beating in the police car.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Schoer, who is still with the 70th Precinct,
acknowledged under questioning by a prosecutor, Alan Vinegrad, an
assistant U.S. Attorney in Brooklyn, that when he was first
interviewed in August 1997 by Police Department investigators about
Louima's account of torture, he did not tell them that Volpe had
shown him a stick or that he said it had human feces on it.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that he did tell investigators from the FBI about
the stick in September 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
