<HEADLINE>
FLESCH HOPES FIRST WIN FALLS ON BIRTHDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J. DOUGLAS FOSTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Steve Flesch already has earned the respect
of his peers on the PGA Tour. He did that last year by placing 35th
on the money list with $777,186, which earned him the Tour's Rookie
of the Year award.
</P>
<P>
   Flesch wants more _ specifically, he wants his first Tour title.
And he took a big step toward getting that in yesterday's opening
round of the MasterCard Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   Flesch, a left-hander who will turn 32 on Sunday, overcame Texas
winds and the difficulty of playing in the next-to-last pairing of
the day to take the first-round lead with a 4-under-par 66. He
birdied the last two holes to establish a one-stroke cushion ahead
of Jeff Sluman and Vijay Singh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like I need to win,'' Flesch said. ``But surely I
would love to do that. I was playing well a couple of weeks ago so
I had a little bit of confidence coming in. Yeah I'm still waiting
on my first win but I'm not pressing to get it. I just want to go
out and put myself in the position to win and one of those Sundays
I'm going to play well.''
</P>
<P>
   He's hoping the first winning Sunday happens on his birthday. If
so, he'll be able to look back at yesterday's round as one of the
keys. On a day when only 15 players shot below par, Flesch made
just two bogeys _ one at the par-4 No. 9 and another at the par-3
No. 13 after waiting through a backup of two groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a little bit of a distraction,'' Flesch said. ``When
you sit around for 15 minutes you lose a little bit of the
rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   He recovered quickly, making par on the next three holes before
birdies on Nos. 17 and 18 gave him the lead. At 17, he hit a
pitching wedge within 12 feet and made the putt, then hit a 9-iron
within 15 feet on 18.
</P>
<P>
   Flesch was playing with a brace on his right elbow, there to
absorb shock on the ulnar bone he fractured on March 5.
</P>
<P>
   And just two months after slipping off the stairs at his home in
Kentucky, he's holding the first-round lead at a PGA event for just
the second time this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at it, the chance to be leading overnight is
more of a confidence thing,'' Flesch said. ``We've got three more
long days on a good golf course where the greens are firming up. If
the wind continues to blow it's not going to be way under par
winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a patience game, but I'm very happy about leading
overnight. It makes you sleep a little bit better.''  &LR; tagtop:J.
Douglas Foster, (817) 685-3868  &LR; tagbottom:dfoster &LR; star-telegram.com
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
