<HEADLINE>
BY STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
 
SILVER MEDALLIONS GIVEN TO GOLFERS (For use by NYTimes News Service
clients) c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ MasterCard Colonial participants discovered
a surprise in their lockers yesterday: sterling silver medallions,
presented by tournament officials to commemorate their
participation in the 1999 event.
</P>
<P>
   The medallions awarded to past champions were inscribed with
their names and the year or years of their triumphs. It marked the
first time in tournament history that medallions were presented to
every player in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to give them something to remember Colonial by,''
said Phil Thomas, tournament chairman. \Nname:_ Jimmy Burch
DOUBLE-DUTY CARRIER Fred Funk's caddie is carrying more than his
golf bag this week. She's also carrying his unborn child.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Funk learned two weeks ago that she is pregnant with the
couple's third child that's due in January. But that did not stop
her from filling in this week after Funk fired his former caddie,
Paul Jungman, after a disagreement at the Houston Open.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Funk said, he plays his best golf with his wife on
his bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``She keeps me straight. She's not afraid to get in my face if
she thinks I'm doing something wrong on the course. If I have a
real boo-boo, she gets mad,'' said Funk, who carved out a
bogey-free 68 in yesterday's opening round.
</P>
<P>
   As for prospective names, Funk said: ``I think we'll call it,
`Y2K Funk.' '' \Nname:_ Jimmy Burch CREATIVE SHOTMAKING It took a
little creative shotmaking for 1974 Colonial champion Rod Curl to
salvage a bogey at the par-4, 404-yard No. 10. Curl sailed his
third shot over the green, where it landed about 10 inches from a
large tree trunk.
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding the inevitable problem it would have caused on the back
swing, Curl instead hit straight at the tree, banking the ball off
the trunk and landing about 10 feet from the pin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like banking my shot,'' Curl said, who finished with a
77. \Nname:_ Kathy Kudravi BEEN THERE, DONE THAT The last time
Franklin Langham played at Colonial, in 1996, he scored an eagle on
the par-4 18th hole, using a sand wedge from the fairway to hole
his shot from 98 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Langham might have been absent from Fort Worth for two years,
but he proved yesterday that he has not lost his magic on the 18th
hole. With his ball in the fairway about 116 yards from the hole,
he used a pitching wedge and watched as the ball took three hops on
the green and bounced off the pin. He sank his putt for a birdie
and a first-round score of 2-under-par 68.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a guarantee that you will do well in the tournament,
but it always helps when you have nice feelings about 18,'' Langham
said. \Nname:_ Kevin Lyons SOME KIND OF 5 Scott McCarron had one of
the most interesting plays of the day when his tee shot on the
par-4 17th rolled into the concrete drain that goes down the right
rough. The ball, moving in the water, was stopped and marked by a
marshal.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving a ruling, McCarron learned he could drop the
ball and play it where the marshal marked it _ even though the ball
began rolling in nearly two inches of water in the concrete drain,
which is a hazard.
</P>
<P>
   McCarron dropped the ball, took a few steps and hit the moving
ball. Not exactly a common shot in golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I practice that shot all the time,'' McCarron said jokingly.
``I'm going to practice it right now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe he went after it with spikes on,'' playing
partner Billy Mayfair said. ``He could have slipped and killed
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   The shot out of the hazard hit a tree and left McCarron behind
another tree. He had to hit a left-handed shot into the rough, then
hit the ball on the green and one-putted for a bogey five.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hit a moving ball, hit a left handed shot and make five,''
McCarron said. ``That's a great five.'' \Nname:_ J. Douglas Foster
HELPING HAND Phil Mickelson, hitting out of the rough, did not want
to take any chances with a stake for the gallery rope near the 10th
green.
</P>
<P>
   The potentially offending metal object was between Mickelson's
ball and the flagstick.
</P>
<P>
   As a course marshal prepared to cut the rope off the stake,
63-year-old Stan Underwood came to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   ``No need to cut it,'' Underwood said, ``I was in the Navy, so I
can untie any kind of knot. It was sort of a half hitch. You could
tell Phil was getting a little nervous, so I wanted to help.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Mickelson's shot wasn't even near the stake
and he wound up bogeying the 10th. \Nname:_ Eric Zarate WAS
PREPARED Tommy Armour must have been a Boy Scout. He knows how to
``be prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Armour noticed his feet sliding around in his shoes during the
first six holes yesterday before making a mid-round switch.
</P>
<P>
   On the No. 7 tee, Armour changed shoes, almost as if he expected
he'd need a second pair.
</P>
<P>
   The footwear Armour discarded won't be seeing the light of day _
at least on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave 'em to someone in the crowd,'' Armour said. ``They got
a brand new pair of Florsheims.'' \Nname:_ Troy Phillips AND THEN
THERE WERE 110 The MasterCard Colonial field shrunk by two players
yesterday as John Daly withdrew and Dudley Hart was disqualified.
</P>
<P>
   Daly, who has missed the cut in each of his three previous
Colonial appearances, withdrew after an opening-round 10-over-par
80. Hart was disqualified for signing an incorrect scorecard. He
signed for a four at the par-4 No. 15 when he had actually made a
five. \Nname:_ J. Douglas Foster RUNAWAY HEADGEAR A not-so-ordinary
distraction had Scott Verplank backing off his approach at No. 9
for a second time.
</P>
<P>
   With Verplank ready to fire, a straw hat rolled into his line of
sight from the left side of the fairway. A wind had caught the back
brim of spectator Robert Taylor's hat before he could grab hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping it would just go all the way to the other side,''
Taylor said. ``I figured they'd step on it or something. I'm just
glad no one went into the water.''
</P>
<P>
   A marshal retrieved Taylor's hat for him after Verplank, Loren
Roberts and Bill Glasson made their approaches. \Nname:_ Troy
Phillips
