<HEADER>
A5433 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VITAMIN-PRICE-FIXING-     05-20 0409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VITAMIN-PRICE-FIXING-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: the company.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The long investigation got its big break three months ago, when
Rhone-Polenc of France, one of the members of the cartel, came
forward with crucial evidence in order to avoid prosecution.
Lawyers said that Rhone-Polenc had decided to cooperate in large
part because of a pending $22 billion merger with Hoechst AG, which
cannot be completed without the approval of antitrust officials in
the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Spratling, head of the antitrust division's criminal
section, said that top executives had treated the industry as one
huge company that they called ``Vitamin Inc.'' Spratling said the
executives ``took great pains to conceal the activity,'' issuing
instructions to destroy all records and notes of their meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply put, the vitamin cartel was as bad as they get,'' said
Spratling, an official in the antitrust division for 28 years.
``Nothing was left to chance _ or, more accurately, to
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Spratling said that federal sentencing guidelines allowed the
government to seek fines as large as $1.3 billion against Roche and
$300 million against BASF. But prosecutors decided on the lower
figures as part of the deal reached with the companies.
</P>
<P>
   The fine imposed Thursday on Roche dwarfed the previous record
cases. The largest total fine collected by the Justice Department
before now had been $340 million paid by Daiwa Bank in 1996 for
fraud and coverup in a large securities fraud case. And the largest
previous fines imposed by the antitrust division occurred earlier
this year, when SGL Carbon agreed to pay $135 million and UCAR
International $110 million for their role in a cartel that had
controlled the market for graphite electrodes.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, with more than four months remaining in its fiscal
year, the Justice Department's antitrust division has already
collected $913 million, substantially more money than the total
amount collected in its entire history.
</P>
<P>
   The vitamins cartel case grew out of a smaller investigation
into price-fixing in the additives market that involved some of the
same companies at the heart of the price-fixing inquiry. That
investigation ultimately led to a $100 million fine imposed upon
Archer Daniels Midland in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Klein said that the vitamins case is one of more than 30
investigations now under way of international cartels in a variety
of industries.
</P>
</TEXT>
