<HEADLINE>
ELKINGTON INTENDS TO PLAY THROUGH SICKNESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ When last we checked on him, Steve Elkington
was withdrawing from the Shell Houston Open last month after
becoming ill with viral meningitis, his third bout with the disease
since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Elkington emerged from six weeks of inactivity to
card a two-under-par 68, good enough for a six-way tie for fourth
place during the first round of the MasterCard Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to \Rlet it\S stand in my way,'' said the
Australian-born Elkington, who lives in Houston. ``This last bout
was not as serious as the other two _ the recurrences get less and
less severe. I didn't lose any weight or my strength. I don't feel
sick. I don't feel weak. I don't see any reason why I can't play
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Elkington, 36, was first found to have viral meningitis_ a
swelling of the spinal cord near the base of the brain _ while he
was in Australia in 1986. Doctors diagnosed it again a day before
the 1998 GTE Byron Nelson Classic. Over a 10-month period before
the second diagnosis of meningitis, Elkington had suffered a
strained rotator cuff, a strained hip, a strained foot, and had
seven sinus infections.
</P>
<P>
   Elkington, who has won nine PGA Tour events including the PGA
Championship in 1995, had shot a 65 on the Saturday of the Houston
tournament to get on the leader board. Then he began experiencing
severe headaches and neck soreness _ a few of the symptoms most
commonly associated with the disease _ and checked into a hospital,
where he stayed for four days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the measles _ you are only supposed to get it
once,'' Elkington said. ``But I've got a recurring form of the
virus, and the funny thing is, I keep giving it to myself. It's not
going to kill me. It's not career-threatening. I talked to all of
the specialists, and they don't know if it has to do with anything
_ allergies, stress, my immune system. They just don't know. I
guess if I would not have been in the good shape that I was in, it
would have been worse.''
</P>
<P>
   It has also been a rough month for Elkington's caddie, Joe
``Gypsy'' Grillo. Grillo had a benign tumor on his finger removed
recently and won't be back until early June. Yet despite the recent
run of health problems, Elkington refuses to get down on himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm lucky because I've played on the tour for 13 years _ I've
got a great family, great kids,'' Elkington said. ``I've done
everything I've wanted to do this decade. Is it a little
frustrating? Yes, I have some sicknesses. But it hasn't hurt my
ability to play. In 10 years, I've only missed about six months.
That is not too bad in an athlete's life, if you compare golf to
some other sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not life-threatening,'' he said, ``it's just a
nuisance.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
