<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RATES ARE RISING. ARE THE BEARS NEAR?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)   (af)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is Goldilocks dead, choking on her porridge, or merely suffering
indigestion?
</P>
<P>
   People have long wondered just how long the ``not too hot, not
too cold'' environment that has amazed economists and nourished
financial markets for years could last. Recent events suggest we
may be in the introductory phase of a very different story.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer price report for April, which showed an increase of
0.7 percent, hit on May 14. Then, last week, the Federal Reserve
Board, for the first time in more than two years, said it was more
inclined to raise rates than to lower them.
</P>
<P>
   One could argue that inflation is entitled to one bad month
every now and then. And since 1996, the Fed has adopted a bias
toward tighter monetary policy 14 times, but has actually raised
interest rates only once.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with stocks at high levels, there is little margin for
error. Kevin Parke, chief equity officer at MFS Investment
Management in Boston, talked last week about the possibility of a
post-Goldilocks economy. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Bond traders have been pushing up interest rates for some
time now. Is this just a blip, or are we in an upward trend? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The fact is that bond traders overreacted to last fall's
global financial crisis by pushing bond yields down too far. Now
you are getting a bounce back up, but I think it is best measured
from a floor of 5.25 percent, not the 4.75 percent level they
reached during the crisis. We think the correct range for bond
yields is between 5.25 percent and 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that bond yields went through 5.90 percent is
fantastic, because it means that the market is not complacent. Bond
traders are a policing mechanism, keeping a lid on inflation and
economic growth. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. So do you still believe in Goldilocks? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The rise in bond yields and the Fed's announcement last week
insures a continuation of the Goldilocks scenario. It will help
keep us in the middle ground we have occupied for some time. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The Fed didn't actually say it was going to raise rates, and
many analysts say it is unlikely to do so this year. Do you agree? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I would be surprised if the Fed didn't eventually raise
interest rates this year. As international economies recover, that
puts more pressure on rates. And one of the main reasons the Fed
cut rates three times last year was to help the world financial
system. If they truly believe the patient is now healthy, they can
turn off the I.V. machine.
</P>
<P>
   We are not worried about consumer inflation, because there is no
indication you can pass on price increases at all. In fact,
companies are still cutting prices. Just look at what Amazon.com
did with best sellers last week. And the competition followed. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Does a change in rates warrant a change in how investors pick
stocks? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You want to find companies that can thrive in a relatively
slow-growth, low-inflation environment and companies with
managements that can take advantage of opportunities. This will be
more of a stock-picking market, not one you just throw money at. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can the hot growth stocks that have led the market thrive in
this environment? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You have to be very careful what you pay for high-quality
growth stocks.
</P>
<P>
   This market has been helped by earnings, but it has also been
helped by higher valuations for growth stocks. If interest rates
are rising, I don't think these sorts of price-to-earnings
multiples can be justified.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks are the longest-duration financial instrument we have.
They are like zero-coupon bonds. When rates are stable,
price-to-earnings multiples will be stable. When rates are falling,
which they have been for some time, the ratio will rise. The last
thing you want to pay is 40 times earnings for a company whose
growth rate is slowing. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Name a few companies that fit your criteria for purchase at
this point. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. In the pharmaceutical area, a sector where most will
experience a slowdown in growth, we see some companies whose growth
rates are accelerating, like American Home Products and Pharmacia
Upjohn.
</P>
<P>
   In industrials, United Technologies will continue to be a very
strong performer. About 25 percent of their business is in Asia,
which will show an improvement. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. A number of companies saw the crisis in Asia as a chance to
buy local businesses at bargain prices. Do you like any of them? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. One industry that will benefit from those who bought on the
cheap in Asia is investment banking. Merrill Lynch, Goldman, Sachs,
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and Citigroup all gained market share in
these parts of the world. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Some market forecasters say that with rates rising, a
correction of 5 to 10 percent is quite possible in the next month
to six weeks. Do you share that concern? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't know about the near term, but I do think the market
is vulnerable, because there is an excess of speculation in the
market. Things have been too easy for too long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
