A5440 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      05-20 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Ireland: Nato Partnership Eyed
</P>
<P>
   Ireland formally announced that it intends to join the
Partnership for Peace, an American-sponsored organization of
non-NATO countries that coordinates security policies with NATO.
Prime Minister Bertie Ahern denied assertions that this would
violate Ireland's tradition of military neutrality, which kept the
country neutral in World War II, and virtually silent on NATO's air
campaign in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Russia: Jostling for Power
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin's first day on the job was
marked by early signs of intense Kremlin politicking, after
Aleksandr Zhukov, chairman of the parliament's budget committee,
said he would not join the Cabinet unless given a free hand to
draft an economic program. Stepashin has 10 days to name a
government, whose members must all be cleared by President Boris
Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   Israel: A First For Arab Woman
</P>
<P>
   The first Arab woman was elected to the Israeli parliament,
Husniya Jabara, from the Israeli Arab town of Taibe, will be seated
as a member of the leftist Meretz Party, which gained a 10th seat
in the final vote count.
</P>
<P>
   Israel: Two Jobs for Barak
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak, a highly decorated former
general, told the newspaper Haaretz that he intends to serve as his
own defense minister for the first two years of his term in order
to coordinate ``the security-diplomatic momentum in the peace
process.'' This would follow the model of his mentor, the late
Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Argentina: Impeachment Rejected
</P>
<P>
   Congressmen aligned with the government party have blocked a
request by a federal judge to impeach Foreign Minister Guido Di
Tella on charges he concealed evidence of illegal arms sales to
Ecuador in 1995. A congressional committee said there was ``no
evidence to prove the minister was responsible.'' Di Tella had
argued in his defense that his ministry passed on information to
the Defense Ministry once it discovered that arms had been diverted
illegally to Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Primary Organizer Tapped
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Gutierrez Barrios, a legendary former head of Mexico's
intelligence apparatus for much of three decades, has returned from
semiretirement to head the committee within the governing
Institutional Revolutionary Party that is to organize the party's
Nov. 7 national primary election. Gutierrez's last post was as
interior minister under former President Carlos Salinas de Gortari.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Opposition Seeks Allies
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's main leftist party, the Party of the Democratic
Revolution, has invited other opposition parties to participate in
a joint national primary election to elect a presidential candidate
to represent an opposition alliance in July 2000 elections. It
suggested a date, Oct. 31, one week before the presidential primary
scheduled by the governing party.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam: Press Controls Tightened
</P>
<P>
   The National Assembly approved a hotly debated revised press law
that will require newspapers to pay compensation to the subjects of
critical stories and publish corrections even if the information
they printed is correct. Critics said the law will hobble a
long-running press campaign against official corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia: Mending Fences with Indonesia
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of Malaysia and Indonesia met on the Indonesian
island of Batam in an attempt to ease relations that have been
strained by issues that range from territorial disputes to logging
rights to illegal immigration as well as an appearance of
Indonesian support for the Malaysian political opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia: Ministers Named
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad reshuffled his Cabinet,
appointing three new ministers, apparently to strengthen his ruling
party in advance of a general election that must be held some time
in the coming year.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 2250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0515 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5442 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NEWS-CHIEF-PROFILE     05-20 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NEWS-CHIEF-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO TURN THAT DRIVE AND ANGER INTO AN HONORED CAREER IN TV
NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Texas, Okla.)   (bl)  
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The essential story about Paula Walker Madison, the
news director of WNBC-TV's Channel 4 and one of the few black
female news directors in the country, took place at Cardinal
Spellman High School, circa 1969, when she was growing up in Harlem
on welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Madison's current-events class was discussing Mayor John V.
Lindsay's budget cuts, and soon enough one of the many white
students said something like why didn't the mayor get all those
people off the dole. Ms. Madison sat mute, then raised her hand at
the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked how many of them have had a social worker come to
their house and look in their closets to see if your mother had a
man in there?'' Ms. Madison recalled. Also, ``How many of them had
to make a Monopoly game because they didn't have the money to buy
one?'' And how many had eaten salty ``welfare cheese'' and Spam?
</P>
<P>
   The story doesn't end there. Afterward, the nun told Ms. Madison
that what she had said was important and would she please come back
and repeat it for the afternoon class?
</P>
<P>
   ``And I said, `Who's going to take  &UR; my &LR;  afternoon class for
me?''' Ms. Madison said. ```I did not come to this school to share
my experiences with a comfortable middle class group so that they
could learn what it was like to be poor and black.' I was there to
get an education.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Ms. Madison, 46, one of the more conspicuously successful
black women in the city, has taken that anger and drive to become
the pulse of a top-rated news program in the nation's No. 1 market.
(In recent years Channel 4 has more often than not edged out its
main competitor, WABC-TV's Channel 7, as the No. 1 news broadcast
at 11 p.m.) This is in part because of spillover from NBC's popular
entertainment programming, like ``ER,'' but fans of Ms. Madison,
and there are many, say it is also because she puts on less blood
and more substance _ like the graphic eight and a half minutes of
an instructional video on breast self-examination that she
broadcast in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the best teaching tool that I had seen,'' said Ms.
Madison, who had discovered a lump in her own breast and had it
removed _ it was a benign cyst _ a few months before the video was
shown. ``But I wasn't even doing it correctly.'' Ms. Madison said
the response from viewers was overwhelmingly positive; Memorial
Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center, which made the video, said it
received more than 3,000 requests for it. Ms. Madison dismissed a
few critics who said she should have made her own video, and not
used the hospital's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not experts,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In her office last week, Ms. Madison had a certain blunt,
commanding style. ``If you're stupid and you're incompetent, you
don't want to be near Paula,'' said Ti-Hua Chang, an 11 p.m.
reporter, who is not, and likes her. ``I think people in the
newsroom are afraid of her.'' Andrew Lack, the president of NBC
News, who is not Ms. Madison's boss but runs the news division of
her network, assessed her this way: ``Capable. Tough cookie.'' And
also: ``No nonsense. Shoot from the hip. Get it done. Don't mess
with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Madison's style was evident in her description of her
parents, who immigrated separately to New York from Jamaica,
married, then spent decades in a messy marriage. ``My father was an
educated man,'' she said. ``My mother was not an educated woman.
Part of what defined my mother's status was color. My father is a
very dark-skinned man. My mother is fair-skinned. She had Chinese
features, long hair.'' (Her father was Chinese.) In short, ``a
physical appearance that was `appreciated' _ I'll say it that way.
They didn't have a lot in common.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Madison was a toddler, her father, who had entered
America using the false name Moncrief Powell, was deported. Ms.
Madison's mother became a citizen while he was gone, enabling her
father to come back after a year as the real Elrick Williams Sr.,
which changed Ms. Madison's name from Paula Powell to Paula
Williams _ for years a source of confusion to the record keepers at
her school.
</P>
<P>
   By the time she was 7, her father, a tool and die maker, finally
moved out to Queens, got into custody battles with her mother and
frequently didn't pay his support. Ms. Madison's mother took in
sewing, but the city sent welfare checks until Ms. Madison's older
brother, who went to Williams College and then Harvard Business
School, stepped in. ``He was the first millionaire I knew,'' Ms.
Madison said. (Her other brother, a former drug addict, is a
trucker.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Madison went to Vassar, married, had a daughter, was a
reporter at The Syracuse Herald-Journal, The Fort Worth
Star-Telegram and The Dallas Times-Herald, divorced, then worked
her way up as a news director at television stations in Texas and
Oklahoma, where her mother moved in and helped raise her daughter.
In 1989 she came back home and went to work at WNBC; she has been
news director since 1996. She lives in Westchester County and is
married to Roosevelt Madison, Tom Brokaw's make-up artist.
</P>
<P>
   One of her goals is to diversify the broadcast, realistically.
``If we're going to cover street crime, violent crimes, we're going
to have some representation among black people,'' she said,
referring to ``the proverbial perp walk.'' But: ``All investment
bankers are not white men. Nor are all nurses white women. Nor are
all subway conductors African-American.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
