<HEADER>
A5443 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIMES-SQUARE-SIGN-NYT     05-20 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMES-SQUARE-SIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE OF THE BILLBOARD THAT HASN'T BEEN BUILT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK_ With visions of world domination dancing in his head,
Frank G. Zarb, chief executive of Nasdaq's parent, decided that his
electronic stock market had to erect the biggest, most dazzling
billboard in Times Square for all the world to see.
</P>
<P>
   So he decided to put it on 4 Times Square, the skyscraper known
as the Conde Nast Building. About the size of three basketball
courts, it would wrap around a 10-story cylindrical structure that
forms the building's northwest corner.
</P>
<P>
   Enter S.I. Newhouse, the chairman of Conde Nast, which publishes
such glossy magazines as The New Yorker, Vanity Fair and Details.
Newhouse, with visions of airy and chic offices, brought in a
renowned architect and designers to make the company's new
headquarters _ much of it in the middle of the cylinder _ an
esthetic haven.
</P>
<P>
   Newhouse does not want Nasdaq's huge $20 million electronic sign
to darken his windowsill.
</P>
<P>
   So, the financial titan, the magazine mogul and their common
landlord at 4 Times Square, Douglas Durst, are locked in a dispute
over the giant video display, which Newhouse contends will block
natural light from his windows. Citing his lease, he is claiming
the right to bar the sign from the side of the tower, at Broadway
and 43d Street.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute, which under the terms of their lease has been sent
to an arbitrator, has left many Times Square denizens chuckling.
Just a few years ago, many companies refused to advertise in what
was then a shabby Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   Landlords bitterly opposed zoning regulations that required
large, bright signs on buildings in the district. Today, Budweiser,
Cadillac, Calvin Klein and Suntory are vying with Nasdaq to pay
millions of dollars a year to advertise their wares at what is
called the crossroads of the world. The number of billboards in
Times Square has tripled, to 150, in the last two years alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all part of the wonderful explosion of light and action
in Times Square,'' Tama Starr, president of the Artkraft Strauss
Sign Corp., said of the battle. ``It's fitting that Times Square is
the home of the biggest and the brightest sign, until the next one
comes along.''
</P>
<P>
   The sign war at 4 Times Square is only the latest of the
troubles at the soon-to-be completed tower. The construction has
been marred by small fires, a scaffolding collapse that left one
person dead, and an elevator accident in which a worker died.
</P>
<P>
   None of the participants are eager to talk about the sign
dispute. Maurie Perl, a spokeswoman for Newhouse and Conde Nast
Publications, declined to comment, and Michael Jones, senior vice
president at Nasdaq, referred all questions to Durst.
</P>
<P>
   The developer tried to take a middle road between his squabbling
tenants. ``Conde Nast is proud and protective of its sensational
new headquarters,'' Durst said. ``Nasdaq wishes to build a
spectacular sign for its new marketing center. Our leases provide
for a speedy alternative dispute resolution process. We're
confident this issue will be behind us by the time Conde Nast takes
occupancy, in the near future.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq sign would be the biggest single sign in Times
Square, where there are scores of pulsating neon, electronic and
vinyl billboards. It would also be the largest LED _ light-emitting
diode _ display in the world, according to sign makers. Diodes
would enable a single image to move across the sign's 14,000 square
foot surface, or divide the sign into a multitude of images.
</P>
<P>
   Zarb, the chairman of Nasdaq's parent, the National Association
of Securities Dealers, signed a deal last summer to move his
marketing center from an obscure location in the financial district
to 4 Times Square, where it could better be seen by millions of
tourists and television viewers. In an attempt to create a virtual
trading floor that would rival the often televised opening bell of
the New York Stock Exchange, Nasdaq is building a round,
glass-walled television studio on the first two floors of the 4
Times Square cylinder.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq video sign would stretch from the 3d floor to the
10th. The problem is that the top half of the cylinder is peppered
with five rows of five-foot-by-eight-foot windows that look onto
the art departments of Newhouse's magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Conde Nast, which was the first tenant to sign on for Durst's
project, has leased floors 4 through 22 in the 48-story tower,
where it is to have a titanium and blown-glass lunchroom _ Titanium
Cafe _ designed by the architect Frank Gehry and personal bathrooms
for the publishers, top editors and vice presidents in the Conde
Nast publications.
</P>
<P>
   The sign has cutouts for the 30 windows. But the drawings showed
the face of the sign extending five feet from the building,
creating what Newhouse bemoaned was a tunnel-like effect around his
windows. The sign itself is only about 18 inches thick, but there
is room for ventilation and a three-foot-wide catwalk behind the
sign for maintenance workers.
</P>
<P>
   Newhouse and his lawyers seized on clauses in their lease that
they said gave them the right to block substantial design changes
and prohibited any sign from extending more than 20 inches from the
building facade, according to people on both sides of the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq contends that the sign complies with its lease, a
different document. Besides, it says, the graphic artists at Conde
Nast do not rely on natural light anyway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
