<SLUG> BC-SENATE-GUNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUN-SHOW CURB PASSES AS GORE BREAKS TIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democrats, with the help of a rare vote from Vice
President Al Gore, won a dramatic victory on a gun-control measure
Thursday that would put tough limits on gun-show sales. The measure
is part of a sweeping bill, which the Senate later passed, that
would pour $5 billion into juvenile justice programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a turning point for our country,'' Gore said after
breaking the tie in his role as president of the Senate. ``Finally,
this majority is turning the corner and helping to protect the
children and families of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote was cast as President Clinton visited Littleton, Colo.,
one month after two students killed 13 people and themselves.
Moreover, hours before the vote, six students were wounded in a
school shooting in Georgia, an event that immediately became a
focal point of the floor debate.
</P>
<P>
   The overriding juvenile crime bill, which had languished for
months until the Littleton shooting, passed 73-25. The legislation
now goes to the House.
</P>
<P>
   Gore cast his vote on one of the most contentious measures, that
would require background checks on all purchases of weapons at gun
shows. It also would require someone who redeems a weapon at a pawn
shop to undergo a background check.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters and opponents of the measure said the recent spate of
school shootings turned the political tide in favor of gun control.
</P>
<P>
   ``The series of tragedies in the schools sharpened the public's
focus on the issue. It showed the unreasonableness of the National
Rifle Association,'' Senator Edward M. Kennedy said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA remained unbowed, accusing the White House of backing
``a charade of lawmaking without law enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``NRA will continue to hold a mirror up to this dishonest
process until the American people demand more meaningful and
substantive action from government,'' the organization said in a
statement. ``Everyone knows this won't stop the crisis in our
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Gore's tie-breaker, a crucial vote came from Senator
Max Cleland, a Georgia Democrat. Cleland had been leaning against
the measure, but changed his mind Wednesday night after being
assured the amendment would not drive unlicensed dealers into the
black market. If any doubt remained in Cleland's mind, the
shootings in Georgia ended it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't just an issue in Littleton, Colo., anymore,''
Cleland said. ``It was hometown people, in my backyard, and I said
anything I can do I want to do to work on this problem.'' Thursday
was the second time in eight days that Republicans have been
embarrassed over the gun-show sale issue. On May 12, the
Republican-led Senate rejected a Democratic proposal requiring
background checks for gun-show sales, only to wake up to widespread
criticism the following day. Republicans then reversed themselves,
approving a modified restriction on gun-show sales.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats, apparently sensing that the mood had shifted
after the shootings in Littleton, said the Republican measure was
filled with loopholes, such as allowing high-volume dealers known
as ``special licensees'' to sell firearms without making background
checks on buyers.
</P>
<P>
   That led to Thursday's political maneuvering in the Senate. It
began when Republicans tried to kill a growing momentum for tougher
background checks at gun-show sales proposed by Senator Frank
Lautenberg, Democrat of New Jersey. Republicans offered a
compromise measure that included some restrictions on gun sales at
pawn shops and gun shows, but did not go as far as the Lautenberg
amendment. The Republican measure passed 79-29.
</P>
<P>
   But Lautenberg said the Republican proposal still had too many
loopholes, most notably a 24-hour time limit for background checks.
Lautenberg said most gun sales should go through immediately if
there are no questions about a buyer's background, but authorities
need three days if trouble signs arise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to imagine we can't even take enough time to
investigate the prospective buyer to make sure we are protecting
people,'' Lautenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Orrin G. Hatch, the Utah Republican, led the opposition,
saying Lautenberg's measure would backfire. ``I think it will push
people to sell guns in the black market, which I think would
undermine everything he is trying to do,'' Hatch said of
Lautenberg.
</P>
<P>
   As the Senate prepared to vote on the Lautenberg amendment, Gore
took his seat on the dais as president of the Senate. A clerk
handed Gore the roll-call results.
</P>
<P>
   ``On this vote, the yeas are 50 and the nays are 50,'' Gore
said, employing the language required by parliamentary rules. ``The
Senate being equally divided, the vice president votes in the
affirmative. The amendment is agreed to.'' It was the fourth time
Gore has broken a Senate tie since he was elected vice president.
</P>
<P>
   One of the 45 Democrats voted against the Lautenberg amendment:
Senator Max Baucus of Montana. Six Republicans supported it:
Senators John Chafee of Rhode Island, Michael DeWine of Ohio, Peter
Fitzgerald of Illinois, Richard Lugar of Indiana, George Voinovich
of Ohio, and John Warner of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The $5 billion juvenile justice bill includes $450 million a
year for drug testing and detention centers, $435 million annually
for juvenile crime prevention, $75 million in state grants, and $40
million for research of juvenile crime programs.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would make it easier for prosecutors to charge
juveniles 14 and older with violent crime, study the way children
are affected by gun-marketing, music, television, and the Internet;
and revoke the right of gun ownership for people convicted of a
gun-related crime as a juvenile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
