<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-CUBS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cubs' win prolongs Maddux's miseries
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The May madness continues for Greg Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   After supplying their struggling ace with only two runs in his
three previous starts this month, the Braves scored three times in
the sixth inning off Steve Trachsel.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jordan, whose grand slam was the key to their win
Wednesday, ripped a two-run double past third base to cut the Cubs'
lead to 5-3. Ryan Klesko followed with a run-scoring double, but
spoiled the rally by getting doubled off second base on Williams'
liner to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux had another head-scratcher going through the first five
innings, allowing the Cubs, whom he'd beaten seven of eight times
before this week, to take a 5-1 lead. In his last 24 1/3 innings,
he has given up 22 runs, and his earned run average has risen to
5.02. Maddux provided few answers Thursday night, only raising more
questions.
</P>
<P>
   After he retired the first two hitters, Sammy Sosa and Mark
Grace reached Maddux for back-to-back home runs in the first
inning.
</P>
<P>
   The second scoring outburst started more subtly with a one-out
Lance Johnson infield hit and a Mickey Morandini grounder through
the middle that barely eluded Walt Weiss and a potential double
play. Maddux retired Sosa on a fly ball, but left a 3-2 pitch over
the plate for Grace who drove in his second run with a shot to the
right field corner.
</P>
<P>
   With Maddux down 3-0 at that point, Henry Rodriguez dropped a
bloop single softly into center field to score Morandini and Grace.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux was spiraling toward his fourth loss in a row and second
to the Cubs in a week when the Braves offense woke up.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
