<SLUG> BC-BKN-IVERSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS A SHOOTING GUARD ALLEN IVERSON MAKES A BIG DIFFERENCE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRIS BROUSSARD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Allen Iverson is free. No longer hindered by the constraints of
playmaking, he is finally able to be himself on the basketball
court. He does not have to set up shots for his teammates or force
himself to think pass rather than shoot. Oddly enough, as a
shooting guard, he is now doing what he seldom did as a point
guard. He is making his Philadelphia 76ers teammates better.
</P>
<P>
   Since Iverson entered the National Basketball Association three
years ago, the knock on him has been that he does not improve the
players around him. His ``no one can stop me'' mentality was
unbecoming of a point guard, and the proof was in the 76ers' woeful
records in his first two seasons. But things changed when Coach
Larry Brown moved Iverson off the ball this year.
</P>
<P>
   The 76ers became one of the surprises of the league, qualifying
for the playoffs for the first time in eight years, ousting the
favored Orlando Magic in the first round, and spawning a new
appreciation for the Iverson in team.
</P>
<P>
   When Philadelphia plays host to the Indiana Pacers in Game 3 of
their Eastern Conference semifinal Friday night at the First Union
Center, Iverson will not be viewed as a point guard with his
priorities out of whack. He will be the wild card who, if able to
get into his rhythm, can lift his 76ers to improbable heights and
make the Pacers' comfortable 2-0 lead in the series disappear as
quickly as one of his stunning crossover dribbles.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Daly, Orlando's respected coach, who implemented a
scaled-down version of his famed Jordan Rules in an effort to
defend Iverson, witnessed as much when the 76er star scored 30 or
more points three times as the 76ers eliminated the Magic, three
games to one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you guys have any concept of the impact this kid
has on a game,'' Daly said after Iverson had 37 points and 9
assists in the series finale. ``This was the Allen Iverson show.
He's a tremendous competitor. What he does for the Sixers, I don't
think even they realize.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not long ago that critics were saying Iverson did little
for the 76ers. An unconventional point guard, he produced All-Star
statistics while alienating his teammates. Even his assists _ he
averaged a solid 6.8 a game his first two seasons _ came as an
afterthought, often when he found himself in the air with no
alternative but to pass.
</P>
<P>
   But now Iverson is seen as one of the league's leading most
valuable player candidates. After leading the league in scoring
with 26.8 points a game, he will most likely be named first-team
all-NBA, and even Brown, his hard-to-please coach, throws accolades
his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good players make other players better,'' said Brown, who is
in his second season in Philadelphia. ``I didn't know when I first
got here if that was the case with Allen. And early on in my first
season, I didn't see any chemistry out there and I didn't see that
as part of what he was about. But from the second half of last
season and this year, he's doing what great players do: making
other players better.''
</P>
<P>
   The newfound appreciation for Iverson's ability to improve the
play of his teammates is a direct result of the 76ers' success. But
the fact is, little has changed besides his position. His game is
as undisciplined as ever, but because he is no longer responsible
for running the offense, it works.
</P>
<P>
   His shooting percentage dropped significantly, from .461 last
season to .412 this year, his assists average fell to 4.6 and his
turnovers remained high (3.5 a game). But because opponents are
forced to double-team Iverson, the 76ers have one more man than the
opposition crashing the boards. That is one reason Philadelphia
finished tied for second in the league in rebounding and forwards
Theo Ratliff and George Lynch averaged career highs in rebounds.
Center Matt Geiger averaged a career-high 13.5 points. With the
defense preoccupied with Iverson, Eric Snow, a career backup,
averaged 8.6 points and 6.3 assists as a starter. Iverson, in turn,
credits his teammates for his success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys are the ones that set the screens for me and get me
the ball in the spots that I need the ball in,'' Iverson said.
``They bring me a lot of energy and they always believe in me, and
for a basketball player, it's important to know that your teammates
are behind you,'' Iverson said.
</P>
<P>
   Not every one, however, is convinced that Iverson has arrived.
Julius Erving, the most spectacular player in 76er history, was
critical of Iverson after he averaged 28.3 points in the four
playoff games against the Magic. Erving, Orlando's executive vice
president, said he would take Portland's Damon Stoudamire and
Seattle's Gary Payton over Iverson.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I see him play and I see the way they use him, it's
really a throwback to the pro summer leagues, where you've got a
guy who's going to dribble around until he finds an opening and
then put it up,'' Erving said. ``Philly had the most simplified
offense you can have _ give the ball to Allen and get out of the
way. And if he throws it to you, shoot it. With that offense, it's
going to be a roller coaster ride because some nights he's going to
go 3 for 21 and people will say, `Why are you letting the guy do
all of this?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Iverson had one of those nights on Tuesday in Indiana, when he
made 7 of 28 shots in scoring 23 points in Game 2. But when he
scored 13 in the fourth quarter as Philadelphia cut a 17-point
deficit to 2 before losing by 85-82, everyone was praising Iverson
for giving his team a chance to win. That is what he will be
expected to do again in Game 3. The 76ers' fortunes depend on it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
