<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-WITNESS-KILLED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT IN SLAYING OF 8-YEAR-OLD WAS TIPPED OFF BY A NEIGHBOR,
POLICE SAY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. _ A man charged with fatally shooting an
8-year-old boy who was a witness in a murder case was tipped off to
his whereabouts by a neighbor who paged the gunman when the boy and
his mother returned from grocery shopping, according to a police
account released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The lookout's pay, collected in advance, was a handful of crack
cocaine, according to the police. The bargain was struck after the
neighbor had refused to kill the boy, Leroy Brown Jr., and his
mother, Karen Clarke, for ``a couple of hundred dollars,''
according to documents filed in state Superior Court here.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors previously identified the neighbor as Josephine Lee,
32, who pleaded guilty to serving as a lookout for Adrian Peeler,
23. Leroy was to have testified against Peeler's brother, Russell
Peeler, 27, at his trial in the May 1998 slaying of Ms. Clarke's
fiance, Rudolph Snead Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The Peeler brothers, both of Bridgeport, were charged last month
with the Jan. 7 murder of the boy and his mother. Both men pleaded
not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   The documents say that after summoning the gunman by pager, the
neighbor accompanied him to the door of Ms. Clarke's duplex on a
dead-end street here.
</P>
<P>
   The gunman rang the bell and when Ms. Clarke asked, ``Who is
it?'' the neighbor gave a friendly greeting, and Ms. Clarke opened
the door a little bit, according to the account.
</P>
<P>
   The neighbor said that the gunman ``flew over me and pushed the
door open,'' according to the account. Groceries that the boy and
his mother had dropped in the front hall flew everywhere, and there
was a struggle and a gunshot, the account said. Ms. Clarke's blood
was later found on one of the grocery bags, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The neighbor said Leroy and his mother fled upstairs, with the
boy yelling as they went, the documents say. The gunman badgered
Ms. Clarke about her son's impending testimony and then shot her,
the neighbor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard the shot and the little boy was reaching out for his
mother,'' said the neighbor, who had followed the gunman upstairs,
according to the account. ``He was yelling, `Mommy, mommy, mommy,
mommy.'''
</P>
<P>
   Leroy was still yelling for his mother when he was shot in the
head, the neighbor is said to have told the police. His body was
found face down at the top of the stairs, shot behind his left ear,
in both arms and in his upper back, the authorities said. A stray
bullet was found in the wall near his body.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Clarke was shot in the right forearm and twice in the upper
abdomen, the authorities said. Her body was found lying on the
floor of a back bedroom, next to a phone. The receiver was off the
hook.
</P>
<P>
   Before the killings, a judge had ordered prosecutors to provide
Leroy's name and address to Russell Peeler's lawyer so a defense
could be prepared, and the police had stopped protecting the boy at
his mother's request.
</P>
<P>
   Outrage about the deaths has spurred an overhaul of
Connecticut's witness-protection laws, and Gov. John G. Rowland has
said he will sign the plan that emerges from the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The neighbor, according to the police account, told
investigators that the offer of a few hundred dollars to kill Leroy
and his mother had come as the Peeler brothers cooked crack cocaine
in her kitchen. According to the account, after the neighbor
refused, Russell Peeler turned to his brother and Adrian Peeler
said, ``I'll take care of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan C. Benedict, the state's attorney in Fairfield County,
said the Peelers would not be tried for at least several months
because of the preparation required in a capital case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
