<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARISMATIC HAD STUMPED THE EXPERTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The horsemen who competed against
Charismatic in a $62,500 claiming race at Santa Anita on Feb. 11
would like to say they saw Triple Crown potential in the runner-up
that cool Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   They can't.
</P>
<P>
   ``My crystal ball was broken that day,'' joked Mike Harrington,
trainer of Valley Don, who came in third, a neck behind
Charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could you ever see this coming?'' said Danny Sorenson,
jockey for Valley Don.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised, like everybody,'' said Juan Garcia, trainer of
What Say You, who finished first by a neck in the 6{-furlong
sprint, only to be disqualified for interference, making
Charismatic and jockey Chris McCarron the winners.
</P>
<P>
   If Charismatic wins the June 5 Belmont Stakes to complete
America's first Triple Crown sweep in 21 years, it won't be the
Kentucky Derby, the Preakness or the Belmont that defines his
rags-to-riches story.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the race _ five starts before the Derby _ in which
trainer D. Wayne Lukas and owners Bob and Beverly Lewis risked him
for a claiming price, the equine equivalent of baseball's waiver
wire.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody bought Charismatic, probably because they agreed with
Lukas' dim appraisal of the one-time $200,000 yearling. To be sure,
nobody imagined finding a Derby winner in a lineup of nine $62,500
claimers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't pay much attention to him,'' said trainer Nick
Canani, who did claim eighth-place Devil's Judge out of the same
race.
</P>
<P>
   To understand how far Charismatic has come, consider that the
other eight horses in that race have combined for 22 starts since
then and recorded just two victories. Seventh-place Lee's Jewel
went on to win a $25,000 claimer at Hollywood Park, and ninth-place
Buddynamedme went on to win an allowance-level race at Churchill
Downs.
</P>
<P>
   What Say You, the disqualified winner, is 0 for 5 since then.
Devil's Judge hasn't raced while recovering from an attack of
colic. Valley Don has been claimed for $40,000 _ also by Nick
Canani _ fourth-place Orca Bay for $32,000, and Lee's Jewel for
$32,000 and $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   It was Buddynamedme, a close-up fourth turning into the stretch,
who got the worst of the interference attributed to What Say You,
dropping back to last place at the wire. The three Santa Anita
stewards placed What Say You ninth behind Buddynamedme in the
official order.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a difficult decision,'' steward Tom Ward said Thursday
after reviewing minutes of the deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was a bad decision, said Garcia, the trainer, and
Randy Valdez, the jockey for What Say You. They conceded What Say
You veered toward the grandstand in the stretch, bothering
Charismatic, sixth-place Purdue Castle, Devil's Judge and
Buddynamedme. But they maintained that What Say You had to veer to
avoid Valley Don, who was lugging out from the rail.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenson, Valley Don's jockey, said What Say You and Valdez
shifted out because they overreacted. Sorenson said Charismatic
deserved to collect the $47,000 winner's purse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charismatic was going to win the race (if he hadn't been
impeded),'' Sorenson said in the Hollywood Park barn area Thursday
morning. ``I don't think he was going to win by much, but he was
going to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia agreed that Charismatic, who took the turn wide as he and
McCarron rallied from eighth, ``was the best horse in the race.''
</P>
<P>
   He went into it with a 1-for-9 record after finishing last
behind winner General Challenge in the 1 1/16-mile Santa Catalina
Stakes. Trainer Mike Mitchell liked the looks of Charismatic in the
paddock before the Santa Catalina and considered taking the colt
when he was entered in the claiming race.
</P>
<P>
   But Mitchell said he decided not to put in a claim slip because
of his affection for the Lewises, who give him tickets to the
February drag races in Pomona each year. Mitchell said he doesn't
regret the decision. He admits that although he liked Charismatic,
he didn't see a Kentucky Derby in the 3-year-old's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``My pitch (to a prospective owner) wouldn't have been, `He can
win the Derby!' '' Mitchell said. ``It would have been, `He can win
for 80 (thousand dollars).' ''
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic went off as the bettors' 5-2 third choice in the
Feb. 11 race. He was an insulting 17-1 when he ran second to the
promising Apremont in an allowance sprint eight days later.
</P>
<P>
   His dramatic improvement since then _ apparently the result of a
harder training regimen _ has warmed the hearts of the men who fill
their barns with claiming horses and can only dream of Triple Crown
glory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for the industry,'' Harrington said. ``This sport
thrives on hope. And this is a horse who at one time was considered
a disappointment who went on to do something great.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm rooting for him,'' Garcia said, looking ahead to the
Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   If they can't make history themselves, those Feb. 11 losers can
enjoy their roles as footnotes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was joking around with Juan (Garcia),'' said Valdez, who
rode What Say You to the neck victory that was taken away, ``you
better put him in the Belmont, so we can beat Charismatic again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
