<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LITTLETON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON REMINDS LITTLETON RESIDENTS NOT TO LOSE FAITH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ A month to the day after the tragic Columbine
High School shootings occurred, President Clinton brought his
condolences and message of hope to this community where 15 people
died and hundreds have suffered trying to carry on with their lives
in the aftermath of the worst school violence in the nation's
history.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to several thousand people, including hundreds of
Columbine students, Clinton told the community it had suffered not
only ``terrible losses ... and heartbreak'' caused by the violence
but also the loss of ``a certain kind of innocence'' young people
should not have to part with ``so soon or so suddenly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All of you are left with searing scars and unanswered
questions that must be healed, answered or dealt with as best you
can,'' Clinton said, adding that for many there may never be any
satisfactory answers to shootings and bombings that ripped apart
this quiet Denver suburb a month before students were scheduled to
graduate.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you cannot lose your faith,'' Clinton counseled.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's address was at Dakota Ridge High School because
Columbine is still being treated as a murder scene. Columbine
students have been attending classes at another school in
preparation for graduation ceremonies that will take place
Saturday, despite the shooting and bombing rampage that was carried
out on April 20 by Columbine students Eric Harris and Dylan
Klebold.
</P>
<P>
   The two teen-agers killed 12 of their classmates and one
teacher, and wounded 21 other people before taking their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   Talking about the commencement ceremony, Clinton noted it would
be ``bittersweet'' for most in the community. He said it would not
be everything Columbine seniors had ``hoped it would be when you
were freshmen.'' But he encouraged them to ``remember that a
commencement is not an end. It is a beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not mention Harris and Klebold, but he spoke of the
``dark forces'' that can ``take over people and make them murder,''
and which, he said, every human being ``must do mortal combat
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Those forces, Clinton said, can tear away at the mind and heart
of anyone who loses faith in themselves and what the future can
hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see here today that you have decided not to give your mind
and heart away,'' the president continued. ``I ask you to share it
with all Americans who love you and need you.''
</P>
<P>
   The gymnasium where Clinton spoke was packed with Columbine
students, who wore white T-shirts bearing a slogan that has become
a symbol of pride for this community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are Columbine,'' the slogan goes, and the students shouted
it repeatedly as Clinton, accompanied by first lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton, entered the school.
</P>
<P>
   Before his speech at Dakota Ridge, Clinton and the first lady
met privately at a nearby Catholic church with some 75 relatives of
the victims of the Columbine violence.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said the president also spoke by telephone
with five of the wounded students who were still hospitalized
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons moved quietly among the relatives, offering
comforting words and hugs to some and listening as several
recounted stories about a slain child.
</P>
<P>
   The White House had been waiting for an appropriate time for the
Clintons to visit Littleton. The violence erupted as Clinton was
preparing to host the North Atlantic Treaty Organization summit in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was later invited to speak here by district school
officials who, White House aides said, asked that he visit one
month to the day after the incident occurred. School officials said
they did not want it to be a memorial service but something that
would help bring ``closure'' for the community.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks before Clinton's speech, the first lady also spoke of
closure and healing, not just for Littleton, but the country as a
whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened at Columbine has had an impact unlike any I have
ever seen or felt: It has pierced the heart of America,'' she said,
adding that the strength and commitment ``to rebuild'' shown by the
community here has inspired the nation.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Clinton also referred to the school shooting in
Conyers, Ga., Thursday morning in which six students were injured
when one of their classmates suddenly opened fire with a gun.
Thankfully, Clinton said, the students who were wounded are
expected to make a full recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that if this can happen here, it can happen
anywhere,'' Clinton said. ``Your tragedy, though it is unique in
its magnitude, is not an isolated incident.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said there would be ``no more fitting monument or
tribute to those who died than to promise ourselves that we will do
everything we can to prevent it from happening anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called on all Americans to ``take what happened in
Columbine, and not only never forget it, but use it to make more
opportunities for others to live the kind of lives we would have
wished for those who were lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's speech moved some in the crowd to tears. But the
gathering here seemed more like a pep rally with the students
shouting ``We are Columbine'' and cheering enthusiastically for the
president and first lady.
</P>
<P>
   The visit by the Clintons, said Columbine freshman Vickie Abel,
15, ``really meant a lot to us. It's going to make us stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
