<HEADLINE>
IMMUNEX GETS A $450 MILLION INFUSION FROM AMERICAN HOME PRODUCTS
INC. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Immunex Corp. on Thursday issued a $450 million note
to American Home Products Corp., giving the Seattle biotech company
the largest infusion of cash in its history.
</P>
<P>
   The convertible subordinated note with an interest rate of 3
percent was bought by American Home Products, which owns a majority
stake in the company, in a private placement. Immunex plans to use
the money to accelerate clinical development of new drugs, to begin
planning for its new research headquarters in Seattle and to expand
its commercial manufacturing capacities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will help the company unlock the value of its scientific
discoveries by accelerating development of products,'' said Andrew
Heyward, analyst with Ragen MacKenzie in Seattle. ``In Immunex's
case, they are discovery rich and cash- and infrastructure-poor
(with respect to) getting drugs into the clinic.''
</P>
<P>
   The company, which has the capacity to take one new drug into
clinical trials a year, wants to increase that capacity to four new
drugs a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the company can't develop (the new drugs) themselves,
they'd have to license them out,'' said Heyward. ``So from a common
shareholder's perspective, this is a good deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The company also plans to use the money to look for strategic
acquisitions of products, technologies or other businesses, and to
increase the sales of Enbrel, its recently approved drug for
rheumatoid arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   ``These new financial resources fuel our strategic plan and help
Immunex capitalize on global opportunities for continued growth,''
said Ed Fritzky, chairman and chief executive officer of Immunex.
</P>
<P>
   The note is convertible to common stock at a price of $173.68
per share, a 30 percent premium over the average price over the
past eight trading days.
</P>
<P>
   American Home Products may convert the note into common stock of
Immunex at any time, including in response to a notice of
redemption by Immunex.
</P>
<P>
   Immunex can redeem the note in three years, provided that its
closing stock price for 20 consecutive trading days is at least
$208.42 a share. After four years, Immunex can call the note at any
time as long as its closing stock price for 20 consecutive trading
days exceeds or equals the conversion price.
</P>
<P>
   If American Home Products were to convert the note, it would
increase its ownership in the company from 54.11 percent to 55.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   With the close of the AHP financing, Immunex has about $640
million in cash and current assets.
</P>
</TEXT>
