<SLUG> BC-HKN-RIVALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEHTINEN, FORSBERG HAVE COMPETITION DEEPER THAN NHL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Jere Lehtinen remembers playing against Peter
Forsberg way back when, back before Forsberg became a $38 million,
NHL poster boy in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty long ago, eh?'' said Lehtinen, a
less-than-$2-million-a-season winger in Dallas. ``I don't know how
many years, 10 maybe. I was like 16, 17. I think we play every year
after that, and of course, I keep track of him because he's such a
good player ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen let his thought trail into silence, a hint of animosity
tinged his words. His familiarity with Forsberg began in games
between Sweden and Finland.
</P>
<P>
   Forsberg's a Swede. Lehtinen's a Finn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they like each other very much,'' Stars winger
Jamie Langenbrunner said. ``It's an extra little thing and you can
notice it. It's definitely a Finn-Swede thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So no,'' Lehtinen said, the two players are ``not like
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Finns and Swedes have issues, kind of like Baby Boomers and
Gen-Xers do. So a sort of national-trash talk begins, on topics
from politics to weather to hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than if you play against some other country,''
Lehtinen admits, ``because we are neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   Seems neighborly familiarity also breeds rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen and Forsberg once again renew the Finn-Swede thing when
the Avalanche meet the Stars in Game 1 of the Western Conference
finals scheduled for 6:30 p.m. tomorrow at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Forsberg has his rival beat in marketability, becoming
an NHL superstar while media guys struggle to pronounce Lehtinen
(leh-TIH-nehn) even though Lehtinen won the Selke Trophy last
season as the game's best defensive forward.
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen has had his rival's number in face-to-face matchups, as
Forsberg has struggled against Dallas. The Swede has zero goals and
four assists in the past two seasons playing against Lehtinen and
his Stars teammates.
</P>
<P>
   His usual defender?
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I see with Lehtinen is there's a rivalry that goes
deeper than just the NHL,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``It's
like: `Not on my shift.' When you give Lehtinen a challenge, he
really embraces that challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   And Forsberg presents a Jaromir Jagr-like challenge.
</P>
<P>
   He had eight points in Colorado's last four games of the Western
Conference semifinal series against Detroit, including game-opening
and game-clinching goals in a series-clinching 5-2 victory in Game
6.
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen, and his linemates Mike Modano and Brett Hull, likely
will be asked to slow Forsberg and his linemates Valeri Kamensky
and Claude Lemieux in this series, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a real big key,'' Modano said of Forsberg. ``He controls
the tempo of the game when he's on the ice with his patience, with
his strength on the puck, with his ability to make passes and make
moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's able to hold onto it as long as he wants to. When he's
doing that, it allows time for Lemieux andKamensky and those guys
to get open and find ice. Those two guys feed a lot off Peter.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen does, too.
</P>
<P>
   He likes to play Forsberg. It is a chance to prove he's just as
good and another chance for him to prove that Finland's better than
Sweden. Lehtinen takes this chance very seriously. Just ask his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time we played, Forsberg gave him a pretty good
shot,'' Langenbrunner said. ``Jere usually just shrugs those off,
but he turned around and whacked him pretty good. It's fun to
watch. It's good to see Jere play that way, with a little
attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Not like friends.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
