<HEADLINE>
PUTTER SAVES SINGH'S OPENING R0UND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Early this month, Vijay Singh finished in a
tie for fifth at the Shell Houston Open, his second consecutive
top-10 finish and fourth of the year. So, what did he do to
celebrate?
</P>
<P>
   He took two weeks off to practice his putting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leaving Houston, where I putted really badly, I told myself,
`If I want to win tournaments, I can't do it by putting the way I
did in Houston, or the way I did two weeks before that \Rat
Greensboro, N.C\.S,'' Singh said. ``I had two weeks off and ... all
I did was putt for a long time. I think I should do more of that
rather than just going out and hit balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, in the first round of the MasterCard Colonial at
Colonial Country Club, Singh's dedication to his short game paid
off. He holed putts of 20, 25 and 10 feet for birdies on the back
nine after dropping a 30-footer for eagle at No. 1 en route to an
opening round 3-under-par 67 and a tie for second place, one shot
behind first-day leader Steve Flesch.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't only Singh's putting that worked. He employed a deft
short game overall, getting up and down from precarious positions
at the 12th, 15th and 16th holes to save his round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I putted really good today,'' Singh said. ``Today was probably
the best short-game round I've had for a long time. I did miss a
lot of greens, but I got up and down a lot. Considering all that,
I'm pleased to finish 3 under.''
</P>
<P>
   A good short game was the requirement of the day as the gusty
winds made club selection difficult and landing anything close to
the pin a near impossibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a difficult day,'' said Singh, the defending PGA
champion who won earlier this year at the Honda Classic in Florida.
``The winds were all over the place. I think it's the hardest round
of golf I've played, considering the wind. It wasn't consistent. It
was gusty.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh said judging distances presented pros with a quandary all
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't pick a right club even from 110 yards away,'' he
said. ``It's more or less gusting and you're hoping the wind will
stay the same way you think it will.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Singh mastered Colonial's greens, he said they were
difficult to navigate, too, because they are firm and getting
firmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Picking a right club and trying to stop it on the green is
another thing,'' he said. ``I think it's going to be a very
high-scoring tournament.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
