A5584 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-LEBRETON-COLONIAL     05-20 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LEBRETON-COLONIAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OTHERS GONE WITH THE WIND, BUT NOT COURSE-WISE SLUMAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ It was a swirling wind, a mocking wind. It
was the kind of day where the golfers at Colonial didn't know
whether they needed a 3-wood or a windsock.
</P>
<P>
   If cussing were allowed on the PGA Tour, we would have a page
full of it today.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we bring you the continuing exploits of golfer Jeff
Sluman, the human windsock.
</P>
<P>
   At 5-foot-7 and an unimposing 140 pounds, Sluman strikes you as
the kind of guy who should have been tethered to the No. 9
flagstick yesterday, rather than ensconced near the top of the
MasterCard Colonial leader board.
</P>
<P>
   But, indeed, there he sits _ yet again.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when the fickle gusts made par a precious novelty,
Sluman shot a 3-under 67, slipping in under the Doppler radar.
</P>
<P>
   ``On days like today,'' Sluman explained, ``if you understand
the trajectory of the shots you hit, that's the key to playing
Colonial well all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, in other words, was not the day to tee it high and
let it fly. Those mighty thrusts were last seen headed toward the
Fort Worth Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   John Daly and Paul Stankowski each shot 80. There are
trajectories ... and then there are trajectories.
</P>
<P>
   But though he has never won here, Sluman continues to be a
veritable Colonial Merlin. In 12 tries, he has six finishes in the
top 14, including a second place in 1996 and a third to Tom Watson
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been fortunate here,'' Sluman said. ``I think I've played
well just about every time I've been here. I think generally I have
a pretty good feel of how to play the golf course well.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer, my friend, is blowing in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't speak for any of the other players,'' Sluman said,
issuing his disclaimer. ``But it's my opinion that any time you're
in Texas and the wind starts blowing like this, if the golf course
will let you and you can hit it close to the ground, you need to.''
</P>
<P>
   Sluman was making his seemingly annual visit to the media
interview room, as the leaders are urged to do. In last year's
Colonial, Sluman lashed down rounds of 67-67-66-69 for his
third-place check. In 1997, he put together scores of 66-69-68-70.
In 1996, he shot 69-67-70-68, missing the stylish plaid jacket by
two strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Sluman, in a nutshell, hasn't been over par at Colonial in four
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I love it here,'' he said yesterday. ``I love par 70s.
That's my type of game.''
</P>
<P>
   Colonial's reputation as a course where the driver might not be
the savviest choice in the golf bag doesn't faze the 41-year-old
Sluman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys actually might \Rthink it is\S,'' said the
Rochester, N.Y., native. `` But those will probably be the guys
who'll be packing up tomorrow at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   To record his 67, Sluman had to chip in _ twice _ from 15 feet.
He birdied the 420-yard seventh hole, reaching with a 3-wood and
sand wedge. A driver and 3-wood left him with a 12-foot putt for an
eagle on the par-5 11th, but he had to settle for a birdie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not as short as some people believe,'' Sluman offered.
</P>
<P>
   He meant ``short'' off the tee. But let's be blunt here: Sluman
looks like he could fit in Daly's golf bag. He has freckles and
could pass for the club pro at Mayberry Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   If we want to interview someone truly meaningful, he said, talk
to his wife Linda. She is Dr. Sluman, a medical oncologist,
treating cancer patients in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``She does the important things,'' Jeff said. ``She saves lives.
I just play.''
</P>
<P>
   Sluman, however, has belted out a modestly successful 19-year
career on the golf tour. His career earnings total more than $7
million and his victory at the Sony Open in Hawaii last January was
his fourth.
</P>
<P>
   In 14 events this year, the consistent Sluman has missed a cut
only once.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, his name remains curiously missing from the Colonial Wall
of Champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would nag me if, maybe, I had lost by a shot after I had
missed a back-handed putt in the first round, or something like
that,'' he said. ``But if I shot 12 or 13 under and a guy shot
better than me, then I would just shake your hand and say
congratulations.''
</P>
<P>
   He has done it here before. But Jeff Sluman has conquered the
gusts at Colonial so often over the past four years, his time seems
due. \Ntagtop:Gil LeBreton, (817) 390-7760
\Ntagbottom:lebreton\Nstar-telegram.com
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
