<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLONIAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLESCH FIRES 66 DESPITE UNPREDICTABLE GUSTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ One by one, they scaled the MasterCard
Colonial leader board, only to be blown back to the pack by
swirling, 25 mph wind gusts.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Hoch briefly separated himself from the field, but
surrendered five strokes to par over his final seven holes. Several
other golfers exchanged the lead like unwanted Christmas presents
on Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, second-year pro Steve Flesch seized control of the
tournament with back-to-back birdies while playing in the
next-to-last group of yesterday's opening round.
</P>
<P>
   Flesch's 66 marked the best effort by any golfer during the
highest-scoring opening round at Colonial in 10 years. Of 112
starters, only 15 broke even-par 70 on a day when Colonial played
to a scoring average of 72.38. It marked the fewest sub-par rounds
to open a Colonial since 1989, a fact that provided a pleasant
surprise for Flesch as he prepared for a 2 p.m. tee time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with the wind, you always think someone is going to get
really low out here every day,'' said Flesch, who offset two bogeys
with six birdies to finish at 4-under par. ``I figured someone
would have gotten to 5 or 6 under by the time I started. But I
looked up on the board and the best I saw was 2 under. I was
shocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you start late, that gives you a whole different mindset
than seeing a 9 under up there, like we did last week \Rat the GTE
Byron Nelson Classic\S. You see something like that and think, `If
I don't shoot 4 or 5 under, I'm going to get lapped out there.'''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was Flesch who did the lapping with some crisp
short-iron play. Of his six birdie putts, none traveled longer than
15 feet and four were from four feet or less.
</P>
<P>
   His birdie-birdie finish allowed Flesch, the 1998 PGA Tour
rookie of the year, to carve out a one stroke lead over PGA champ
Vijay Singh (3 under) and Jeff Sluman (3 under). He stands two
strokes ahead of a six-player group at 2 under, highlighted by
Steve Elkington and John Cook.
</P>
<P>
   Among first-round leaders at PGA Tour events this season, only
frontrunners at the Masters (3 under) found themselves closer to
even par than Flesch after 18 holes. Singh said he was not
surprised by the fact that bogeys (422) outnumbered birdies (238)
by almost a 2-1 margin in yesterday's opening round.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the hardest round of golf I've played this year,''
said Singh, who drained birdie putts of 20 and 25 feet, as well as
an eagle putt from 30 feet at No. 1. ``You couldn't really pick the
right club, even when you were 100 yards away. The wind changed
direction, it seemed like, nearly every other shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Sluman, who chipped in twice for birdies during his opening
round, said he frequently found himself between clubs because of
gusts that shifted from Southeast to Southwest at a moment's
notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trajectory of your shot is the key on a day like this. You
can't let the ball get hung up in the wind,'' said Sluman, who
predicted the winning total for 72 holes could be no more than
8-under if similar conditions prevail through Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   If so, Flesch finds himself halfway home. He began his day with
a 10-foot par save at No. 1, then peppered approach shots within
four feet of the cup at Nos. 2, 7 and 8, setting up
momentum-turning birdies. But the biggest birdies proved to be from
12 and 15 feet, respectively, on the two closing holes.
</P>
<P>
   Flesch's secret?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fortunate not to hit a lot of half-shots out there,''
Flesch said. ``On most of my birdies, I could take full swings with
the approach. When you have the wind blowing like that, you don't
want to have to finagle an 8-iron, 9-iron or pitching wedge because
you might not make a very good swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor should a player rest too comfortably with the lead when 61
pursuers are within six strokes after 18 holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have the chance to be leading overnight, it builds more
confidence,'' Flesch said. ``But the way these scores are bunched,
this tournament is wide open. We have three more long days here at
Colonial.''
</P>
<P>
   They'll seem even longer, rest assured, if they continue to
include swirling, 25 mph wind gusts.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
