<HEADLINE>
AT LAST, CHARISMATIC LOOKS TO BE FAVORITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charismatic, the onetime claimer who won the Kentucky Derby at
odds of 31-1 and two weeks later won the Preakness at 8-1, was back
in his barn at Churchill Downs in Louisville, Ky., on Thursday
preparing for the Belmont Stakes two weeks from Saturday.
Charismatic will probably face a full field of 15 rivals, but will
no longer be a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have to do a lot,'' said his trainer, D. Wayne Lukas,
who has swept the Triple Crown with two horses in the same year but
never with one. ``The big story line is going to be, can he come
back from two weeks, two weeks, two weeks, three weeks? We'll let
him dictate his own schedule leading to the Belmont. We're probably
looking at a light work Monday or Tuesday, then another light work
Monday or Tuesday the following week.''
</P>
<P>
   When Charismatic tries the mile-and-a-half Belmont, he will not
be running at long odds. He will be the favorite at maybe 2-1 as he
tries to sweep the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   Only 11 horses have done it, and none since Affirmed in 1978.
Fourteen horses failed to do it when they lost the Belmont,
including two in the final strides in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the unusual feats of durability in recent years,
Charismatic has handled this series of races: fourth in the Santa
Anita Derby on April 3, first in the Lexington Stakes on April 18,
first in the Kentucky Derby on May 1 and first in the Preakness on
May 15. Then it's the Belmont on June 5.
</P>
<P>
   Belmont a Possibility for Silverbulletday
</P>
<P>
   Only 20 fillies have run in the Belmont Stakes in 130 years,
only two have won it, and none has won it since Tanya, 94 years
ago. So it is not considered very likely that Silverbulletday will
buck those odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we would want to do that to her,'' her
trainer, Bob Baffert, said from Churchill Downs. ``We'd have to
figure out if she'd like to go a mile and a half and see how she's
training.''
</P>
<P>
   He said after the Preakness that he would not try
Silverbulletday against colts until later this summer, maybe in
Monmouth Park's Haskell Invitational in August, when she would be
older and the money greener: $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   But he got caught in a war of words this week about running in
the Belmont. The prize might be the Horse of the Year title. The
rub might be Bob Lewis, who owns Charismatic but is also a major
client of Baffert's. Lewis has said, in effect, that the more the
merrier. But it is not clear if Baffert would want to ruin Lewis'
shot at the Triple Crown or wants to tempt fate by breaking the
pattern of success for his prize filly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
