<DOCNO> NYT19990520.0535 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5609 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN     05-20 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S DO THE HUMANE THING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Part of the mindless fun of playing along with ESPN's
SportsCentury Top 50 Greatest Athletes of the 20th Century, aside
from trying to belch it fast three times after downing a Big Gulp,
is trying to guess who'll come next.
</P>
<P>
   After Oscar Robertson was announced as No. 36, I made up a rough
list to see how many true athletes were left that could fill the
other 35. I came up with about 40 names.
</P>
<P>
   Stupidly, I didn't bet on a horse.
</P>
<P>
   At No. 35, the '73 Triple Crown winner Secretariat will be
featured on today's regular weekly segment at 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Did I mention Secretariat is A HORSE?
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. Mickey Mantle came in at No. 37. Sandy Koufax
was No. 42. Sorry, guys. You were great. But a horse _ he was
better than you.
</P>
<P>
   Will John Elway make the list? If not, you're gonna have to be
the one to tell him he's been bumped for that logo on the side of
his helmet. Too bad for him; he has the teeth but was born with two
fewer legs.
</P>
<P>
   No question, Secretariat isn't just any horse. But he was, by
all accounts, still a horse, genetically created in this case to do
one task. Two other equines _ Man O'War at No. 84 and Citation at
No. 97 _ also made ESPN's list of the top 100. But that's when the
horsing around should have been stopped.
</P>
<P>
   You let one animal in, you've opened the barn door _ donkeys,
dogs, chickens and pigs. All of which are some things these
athletes have been CALLED at one point, but, in reality, THEY
weren't the actual beast. And that was an important distinction.
Aside from what former boxer John ``The Beast'' Mugabi or ex-relief
pitcher Brad ``The Animal'' Lasky might say.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, Secretariat, but there's got to be some strict rules here
if this ESPN end-of-the-century gimmick is going to fly. We
suggest:
</P>
<P>
   1) Anything with a tail _ out.
</P>
<P>
   2) Something that can be turned into another form of athletic
equipment doesn't qualify. Think horsehide, pigskin and baseball
gloves. And who-knows-what's been used to string tennis rackets.
</P>
<P>
   3) If it can't be interviewed, it can't be on the list. So,
again, Steve Carlton has no shot.
</P>
<P>
   4) Something that gives rides to undersized men and women can't
be on the list. Same for anything that grew up in a petting zoo.
</P>
<P>
   5) You can't include something that can only count on two things
in life _ death and a taxidermist.
</P>
<P>
   Or why not just go with Webster's definition: An athlete is ``a
person who is trained or skilled in exercises, sports, or games
requiring physical strength, agility or stamina.'' A horse is a
horse, a horse of course.
</P>
<P>
   We watch Kentucky's Demolition Derby each year and get chills
when that pack of 238 round the final turn and begin jousting for
position. But there's no mistake _ these are horses, with humans on
top of them. Or, in the case of that pre-Preakness race, with
humans in front of them.
</P>
<P>
   Horses can spur emotions. We don't discount that, either. In the
ESPN special tonight, TV journalist Jack Whitaker says it about
Secretariat's 31-length win at Belmont that clinched the Triple
Crown: ``Everybody was speechless. Then, when it all set in, people
were crying. I actually saw people crying at this event. It was
such an overwhelming thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Jack, you know this was taking place AT A RACE TRACK. How
many of those were people who were also tearing up betting slips,
distraught because their horses didn't come in?
</P>
<P>
   Two other things to consider, then we'll let it slide. One is,
you can't be an athlete if you're injected with drugs. And on the
flip side, athletes aren't put down. After a hoof disease,
Secretariat was given a lethal injection in 1989. That makes him
the only Top 50 athlete ever to experience such a thing. O.J.
Simpson, at No. 49 on the list, could have been the second.
</P>
<P>
   Those forward-thinking humans who determined this list _ ESPN
recruited what it calls ``a distinguished panel'' of 48
journalists, historians, observers and administrators _ were
obviously pulling a prank when they wrote in Secretariat. Who'd
have thought not only Price and Waterhouse would take them
seriously but so would the ESPN researchers who had to find tape
for the shows.
</P>
<P>
   Take off the blinkers.
</P>
<P>
   The only guidelines these experts were given was to vote on
athletic ability alone. For that reason, there's a chance neither
Jackie Robinson nor Arthur Ashe will make the list, insiders have
informed us. That alone would be the real shame. Almost as pitiful
as when Jesse Owens actually raced against horses to make some
extra cash.
</P>
<P>
   With all the lists of the greatest this-and-that we've had to
endure just because we're unfortunate enough to be alive at the
century's end, this list is fast moving up to the top my new list:
worst ideas for lists to mark the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
   There's time to fix it, if ESPN gets off its high horse.
Reconvene the elders and have them vote just on ATHLETES this time.
Go ahead and keep Willie Shoemaker and Eddie Arcaro up there. The
beastmasters deserve their due.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, Lou Gehrig will be No. 34 on ESPN's list. Shouldn't
he have been closer to, say, the top 20? That's what the debate
should be. We shouldn't have to worry about whether the Iron Horse
has lost out to the actual thing. &QL; 
WHAT SMOKES
</P>
<P>
   __ There's a certain rustic charm about Speedvision's half-hour
``Speed Shop'' (weekdays, 3 p.m.). Think QVC meets Fred Sanford.
Want a blown oil pan from Al Hofmann's actual Funny Car? Funny, but
the other day, they were selling 'em, item AHU-005, for $400 (plus
shipping and handling). And it's autographed. Less pricey but just
as race-worn-beat-up-chic are blown main caps, pistons and
connecting rods right off Hofmann's engine block ($59.95 each).
Sound hokey? Check out the conversation pieces on the Web site
(http://www.speed-shop.com) &QL; 
__ Bud Furillo started this week as sports director and will
provide two daily commentaries on KXPS-AM 1270, the all-sports
station in Palm Springs. His plans, for now, are to work there
until the first of the year and see what happens. &QL; 
__ Extended, albeit irregular, weeknight sports segments on
UPN-Channel 13 for Newy Scruggs. With luck, viewers will be seeing
more versions of his ``Talk About Sports'' Sunday call-in shows
during the week. &QL; 
WHAT CHOKES
</P>
<P>
   __ ``Are you beyond criticism? . . . How much does it hurt when
people write things that aren't flattering?'' probed Gary Miller,
the host of ESPN's ``Up Close,'' to his guest Monday. ``Umm. . . it
used to bother me, but I think I know, I understand who's watching
and the general appeal that I have and you're not going to please
everyone all the time. I only get upset when people get their facts
wrong when they come after me and then I go after them and they
backpedal pretty quick. But that's fine. I think the viewers enjoy
what I do. . . .'' In essence, it was the perfect wrap-up question
from the inquisitive Miller, after career clips were shown, after
he talked about how loyal his company has been to him, all ``the
greats'' he's met in his very lucky career and a graphic of the six
movies he's appeared in. Oh, the guest? Chris Berman. Which made
this show possibly _ no, definitely _ the lowest point in ESPN's
near 20 years of broadcasting. The next will be when Miller is
forced to book and then pretend to interview another member of
ESPN's Insane Clown Posse. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
