<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-BUYER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDMAN SACHS LIKELY TO SEEK BUYER FOR N.Y. JETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Leon Hess' death two weeks ago stirred speculation
about who would be the New York Jets' next owner. Although Hess'
will has not been filed, the family's anticipated hiring of the
investment firm Goldman Sachs to identify a buyer clarifies a
belief that Hess did not want to pass the team to his family as a
legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs handled the sale of the Cleveland Browns for the
National Football League last year. The process took several months
and starred six candidates, including Alfred Lerner, who paid $530
million.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets should attract at least as many suitors because of the
allure of owning an NFL team in the country's biggest market. One
of those bidders could be Cablevision chairman Charles Dolan, who
bid on the Browns with his brother, Larry. Both men declined
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Former Miami Dolphins coach Don Shula was part of the Dolans'
bid in Cleveland, and would have run the expansion team's
operations. If Shula were part of a successful Dolan acquisition of
the Jets, he would undoubtedly conflict with Bill Parcells, the
team's football czar.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets have said nothing about the timing of the expected
sale, or about the intentions of the Hess estate. A lawyer who
represents the family declined to comment on when the will would be
filed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you're dealing with a degree of secrecy but a
sequence of events that will have to occur,'' said Jets president
Steve Gutman Thursday during a screening of the team's 1998
highlight video.
</P>
<P>
   An announcement from the Jets about the logistics of the
expected sale could come as early as Friday.
</P>
<P>
   One person who is unlikely to have an interest in buying the
team is John Hess, 44, who succeeded his father as the chairman and
chief executive of Amerada Hess, an independent oil and gas
company.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Hess is described as similar to his father in his
encyclopedic knowledge of the oil business, attention to detail,
sense of humor and devotion to his family.
</P>
<P>
   They also share an aversion to the news media. Leon Hess rarely
spoke to reporters beyond a friendly greeting; John's spokesman at
Amerada Hess did not respond to a request for an interview. The
company's Web site contains no personal information about John
Hess, but financial records show he was paid $1.3 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   John Hess is Harvard-educated and speaks several Arabic
dialects. Leon Hess took over his father's bankrupt fuel-delivery
business in 1933 and never attended college.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like his father, John is tireless,'' said Nicholas Brady, a
board member of Amerada Hess, and a former Treasury Secretary.
``They're the same in their preoccupation with business. It's a way
of life for John.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon Hess stepped down as the company chairman in 1995 but came
to work every day as chairman of the executive committee. Father
and son worked closely, the elder Hess acting as chief adviser and
remaining a formidable presence at the offices on Sixth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Leon ran the company it was totally his, but when he
passed it to John, he really did it,'' said former New Jersey Gov.
Thomas Kean, who serves on the board of Amerada Hess. ``I wondered
if Leon would really let go. But he did.''
</P>
<P>
   William Johnson, a board member who is the chairman of H.J.
Heinz, said, ``Leon was very deferential to John and John consulted
him on every decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has been roiled by low oil prices, which have forced
John Hess to restructure the company and make cutbacks. Last year,
the company lost $458.9 million on revenues of $6.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   One difference between the Hesses involved the Jets. Although
Leon Hess was deeply passionate about the team, John Hess is not,
or at least not enough to want to take over the team. Father and
son watched every home game together in the owner's box at Giants
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leon hurt when the team lost,'' said Kean, the president of
Drew University and an executor of the Hess estate. ``He'd turn to
me and say, `Here we are, suffering again.' John rooted for the
Jets, his kids are rooters, but it wasn't the same for John as it
was for Leon.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady added: ``I'd guess John wasn't as interested in the Jets
as his father. Leon was clear that he didn't want his family
involved in football.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon Hess was an occasional visitor to the Jets' training
complex at Hofstra University and after each home game he joined
players in the locker room. John Hess has rarely, if ever, been
seen at Hofstra or in the Jets' locker room, and is not remembered
for having attended NFL owners' meetings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
