<SLUG> BC-GOLF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL JUDGE DENIES DISABLED GOLFER'S REQUEST TO USE A CART IN
QUALIFIER FOR U.S. OPEN   
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., N.C.)   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge Thursday denied a disabled professional golfer's
request to use a cart in a local qualifier for the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Robert Miller ruled in South Bend, Ind.,
that Ford Olinger of Warsaw, Ind., would not be allowed to use a
cart under the Americans With Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he did not consider the Casey Martin case in making
his decision. Miller said the two cases were different because
Martin's suit sought to use a cart on the PGA Tour, not just for a
single event.
</P>
<P>
   In denying Olinger's request Miller wrote in his ruling that
athletic competition presented a different concern for the ADA than
the workplace. Olinger argued that a degenerative hip disorder made
walking 18 holes nearly impossible for him, but Miller agreed with
the U.S. Golf Association's contention that walking was a
fundamental aspect to competitive golf and that allowing Olinger to
ride a cart would provide him an unfair advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point of an athletic competition,'' Miller wrote, ``is to
decide who, under conditions that are about the same for everyone,
can perform an assigned set of tasks better than any other
competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   Olinger had successfully sued the USGA last year to use a cart
in a local qualifier for the U.S. Open, but he did not qualify for
the section, shooting a 12-over 83.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who has a circulatory disorder in his right leg that
makes it painful for him to walk long distances, won a suit last
year to ride a cart on the PGA Tour under the disabilities act. The
PGA Tour has appealed that ruling and oral arguments were heard
earlier this month before the Ninth U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals,
but a decision is not expected for months.
</P>
<P>
   The USGA will honor its agreement with Martin to allow him to
ride in this year's U.S. Open at Pinehurst, N.C., while his suit is
under appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's case with the USGA appears to be on solid ground even
though an outside counsel for the USGA suggested otherwise earlier
this week. Lee Abrams, a lawyer, said that if he won the case
against Olinger, Martin may have to walk. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
