<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-PATAKI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAITING FOR PATAKI: CITY HALL HOLDS BREATH, FEARS WORST 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Traditional salutations are no longer offered around
Rudolph Giuliani's City Hall these days. Instead of ``Good morning,
that's a nifty tie,'' one is more likely to hear variations of the
following:
</P>
<P>
   Hear anything? Whaddaya hear? Anything?
</P>
<P>
   The context is understood. The questions center on trying to
divine what Gov. George Pataki is up to with the political speech
he plans to make on Monday, the details of which are being guarded
as though a leak might compromise national security. The governor's
aides will only issue assurances that what he has to say is Very
Important.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it is the governor's intention or not, the extraordinary
secrecy has spurred fevered speculation within the Giuliani
administration, ranging from convoluted analysis to panicked
suspicion. But the curiosity is understandable. If just one of the
several rumors about the nature of the speech is true, it will have
a direct impact on the political future of Giuliani, who is
considering a run for the U.S. Senate seat being vacated by Daniel
Patrick Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday alone, the following rumors were uttered on the steps
and in the corridors of City Hall: The governor is endorsing Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas for president; he plans to run for
president himself; he is running for the Senate, believing that he
alone can beat Hillary Rodham Clinton, a possible Democratic
candidate, and that the state Senate majority leader, Joseph Bruno,
will succeed him; he is endorsing Rep. Rick Lazio of Long Island
for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Wait, there's more. That former Sen. Alfonse D'Amato is running
again. That Pataki is endorsing Elizabeth Dole for president. And
this: that the governor's wife, Libby Pataki, will be running for
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   An elementary understanding of politics, or just common sense,
would lead most people to eliminate several of these options.
</P>
<P>
   For example, an endorsement of Bush is considerably more likely
than a run for the Senate by Mrs. Pataki, and D'Amato is said to be
content with his lucrative post-Senate career as a rainmaker.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever the announcement turns out to be, several in City
Hall expect that the governor's speech will be designed in some way
to undermine the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   First, the governor's camp and the mayor's camp do not like each
other for reasons that range from distrust to competition; about
all they share is political paranoia. Second, impishness is not a
characteristic often attributed to the governor. But when he
announced his coming announcement earlier this week, he refused to
say outright that he had no plans to challenge Giuliani for the
Republican nomination for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Third, dozens of the state's Republican leaders and elected
officials have been invited to attend Monday's speech. Everyone, it
seems, except Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Some in Giuliani's camp even detect a sinister message in both
the timing and the location of the governor's announcement. It is
to be held in the very same ballroom at the Sheraton New York Hotel
and Towers that Giuliani is scheduled to use for his annual
birthday fund-raising event the very next night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing of the announcement and the place of the
announcement are clearly designed to steal some of the thunder from
the mayor's big fund-raiser the next day,'' said a Giuliani aide.
``I don't believe in coincidence. And it's hard to believe that the
governor decided to do this at the same hotel the day before,
unless there was some ulterior motive behind the decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Several state Republican leaders said that aides to the mayor
had sought them out, asking for intelligence. But they said they
knew as much as the aides did, which is to say nothing. Brendan
Quinn, the executive director of the Republican State Committee,
spoke for many when he said, ``I don't know anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Kieran Mahoney, a political consultant close to the Pataki
administration, brought a John le Carre-like level of secrecy to
his ``no comment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even off the record tell you whether I know or don't
know,'' the adviser said. ``I am totally noncommunicative on this
one subject. If I make any informational statements, they provide
clues. And I'm not in the clue business today.''
</P>
<P>
   The secrecy and the urgency have annoyed some Republicans.
County leaders from around the state find themselves putting up
their own money for transportation and hotel accommodations to
attend a meeting whose purpose is unknown to them. Several leaders
expressed concern that the Pataki camp might have outsmarted itself
by overselling what could turn out to be an anticlimactic
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some dissatisfaction about the way this is being
done,'' said one official from upstate. ``The timing, the
secrecy.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the announcement, absent any leaks, the rumors are sure to
continue. The Pataki camp supposedly has ordered balloons for
Monday's event at the Sheraton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Balloons?'' one person asked. ``Why balloons?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
