<SLUG> BC-AMAZON-SHAREHOLDERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPECT MORE ACQUISITIONS AND DEALS, AMAZON SHAREHOLDERS TOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN COOK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ What do Beanie Babies, a 5-pound porcelain bust of
Star Wars character Boba Fett and an autographed Albert Einstein
photograph have in common?
</P>
<P>
   They're some of the trinkets that Amazon.com chief executive
Jeff Bezos has bought in the past couple of months on his company's
new online auction site.
</P>
<P>
   About 350 Amazon.com investors got a rare glimpse into Bezos'
personal collection of pop-culture detritus on Thursday at the
company's second annual shareholder's meeting, held at the Sea4tee
Art Museum.
</P>
<P>
   But shareholders _ some who came from as far away as New York
City and Allentown, Pa., _ had a lot more than Boba Fett and Beanie
Baby dolls on their minds.
</P>
<P>
   Comparison shopping sites, discounted books, credit card fraud,
employee morale, stock market volatility, competition, and of
course, profitability, were all major topics addressed.
</P>
<P>
   One issue, which re-surfaced several times at the 90-minute
meeting, was Amazon.com's switch from being the world's biggest
bookseller to what is essentially a giant online retailer with
interests in music, videos, groceries, drugs and pet supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com, which recorded a $61.7 million loss in the first
quarter, has been on a buying spree of late, taking minority stakes
in online retailers HomeGrocer.com, drugstore.com and Pets.com.
Bezos said Amazon will continue to expand its product offerings
through investments and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are doing is focusing on all of the insurmountable
opportunity that we see,'' said Bezos. ``There is so much Internet
opportunity that now is the time to invest.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Amazon.com's expansion efforts will bring continued
losses, many shareholders said they believe it is the right
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazon.com is essentially the new Kmart model, they can sell
everything,`` said Carole Kitchell of Seattle. ``If that means
losing money in the short-term, I am OK with that.``
</P>
<P>
   Scott Moyer, a stockholder from Allentown, Pa., who was
attending the meeting with his 9-year-old son, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are always worried when a company is losing money,'' Moyer
said. ``But you have to look to the long term.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what Bezos is doing. Amazon.com, which has
acquired 6.1 million customers in the past 12 months, will continue
to ally with thousands of partners in an attempt to build out
product categories.
</P>
<P>
   The company's $1.4 billion cash reserve could be a huge
advantage in its expansion efforts if the Internet bubble were to
burst, Bezos said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the bottom drops out of the Internet market then there may
be companies, that could be purchased with cash,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bezos did not shed any light on possible acquisitions or product
categories, saying only that Amazon is interested in partners who
are fanatical about customer service.
</P>
<P>
   Other topics Bezos addressed at the meeting:
</P>
<P>
   _The decision to offer a 50 percent discount on all books on the
New York Times best-sellers lists: ``The reason we are making the
shift in pricing is because we believe a rapid shift from off-line
to online (shopping) benefits us at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   _Comparison shopping sites which allow users to cruise the
Internet for discounted prices. ``It is a concern for us. But it is
a concern the way gravity is for Boeing.''
</P>
<P>
   _Retaining employees who are worth millions of dollars. ``You do
end up in a situation where you have a large number of volunteers
and that is a little scary. What you have to do is try to build a
company where the right people want to stay for the right reasons
... and the wrong kind of people are rejected out like a virus in a
healthy immune system.
</P>
<P>
   _Competitive threats from traditional retailers and online
upstarts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are surrounded by ever-growing competition and we sort of
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   _On Barnes &AMP; Noble last November purchasing Ingram Book Group,
Amazon.com's main book distributor. ``No one is comfortable having
one of their major competitors as their supplier.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-20-99 2343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
