<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-20 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5626 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-ANIMATION-FILMS-A     05-20 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-ANIMATION-FILMS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORMA DESMOND HAD IT WRONG: THE PICTURE MAKERS GOT SMALL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 23)  
 (af)  
 By JOEL KOTKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STUDIO CITY, Calif. _ With his easy manner and casual dress, Dan
Chuba looks more like a Silicon Valley nerd than a Hollywood mogul.
But Chuba, at 38 already a veteran of special-effects wizardry, and
his partners at Hammerhead Productions are counting on their
mastery of digital technology to help them build the new model of
the 21st-century Hollywood studio.
</P>
<P>
   Operating out of a white stucco mansion on four acres
overlooking the San Fernando Valley, the four-year-old company has
already produced one low-budget film, ``Shadowbuilder,'' and has 10
projects in development and one, a more elaborate feature called
``Supernova,'' in production.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, Hammerhead is doing special-effects work on
other people's movies, has a deal to make music videos and is
building a Web site to sell its special-effects software and tapes
and disks of its films.
</P>
<P>
   Chuba contrasted all his activity with the sadder realities at
the major studios, most of which are sharply cutting production
budgets. ``The studios are leveraged out,'' he said. ``They don't
have control of the pipeline. They are reducing their quantities of
movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``But people still need the product,'' he continued. ``Someone
has to do it, and it's creating all sorts of opportunities for
independent players like us.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the entertainment industry, and even in its Los
Angeles heartland, independents, particularly those with strong
technical or artistic assets, share a sense that the major studios
are slowly losing their grip on the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Many are encouraged by the recent successes of such outsiders as
the New York-based Miramax, owned by Walt Disney but kept on a very
loose leash, which dominated this year's Academy Awards. And they
point to the hits churned out by the computer animation leader,
Pixar, and most of all, to the growing dominion of George Lucas'
Industrial Light and Magic over a wide swath of moviedom.
</P>
<P>
   In the Los Angeles of not so long ago, when giants like Walt
Disney, Louis B. Mayer and Jack Warner bestrode the industry, such
thoughts would have been treated as all but treasonous. The big
studios in those days controlled the most advanced facilities and
the skilled labor necessary to make high-quality feature films.
</P>
<P>
   But today, some entrepreneurs at independent firms regard
mainline studios as technologically backward, artistically
tone-deaf and poorly managed. Worst of all, said Carl Rosendahl,
president of Pacific Data Images, the effects house where Chuba got
his start, the studios have allowed their historic brands and
images to wither.
</P>
<P>
   ``The identity of the studios used to be strong in the '30s and
'40s,'' Rosendahl said in his airy offices in Palo Alto, 400 miles
north of Hollywood. ``MGM did musicals, another did monster movies,
Disney did Walt's movies. But now they don't have it. Disney isn't
even doing its own best work.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosendahl, whose company produced the hit animated film ``Antz''
last year and is working on ``Shrek,'' for release at the end of
2000, conceded that even the best-financed independents still need
the major studios to help distribute and market completed films.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Data Images' films are distributed by Dreamworks SKG,
which also owns part of Pacific. Pixar, whose ``Toy Story'' and ``A
Bug's Life'' have been big animated success stories, relies on
Disney.
</P>
<P>
   But over time, even this dependence could be reduced. The
emergence of digital distribution of films over satellite links,
Rosendahl suggests, could reduce the cost of distributing films by
tens of millions of dollars. And videos increasingly offer a direct
distribution pipeline to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, only a handful of non-majors, like Troma of New
York, are truly independent of studio power.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the major studios _ including Dreamworks, the
youngest and widely considered the most creative of the majors _
still dominate film production, especially big-budget blockbusters,
which are made mainly through co-production deals. Independent
studios are a force principally in the lower-budget niches for
B-movies and ``art house'' films and in animation.
</P>
<P>
   One way the independents are weaning themselves from the
traditional studio system is by diversifying their work beyond
simply producing filmed entertainment. Companies like Pacific Data
Images and Hammerhead operate broadly as creators of creative
content for what might be called the cultural-industrial complex.
They delve into everything from commercials and theme park rides to
Internet entertainment, computer games and music videos.
</P>
<P>
   This versatility helps smooth out the feast-or-famine nature of
film work, supplies a useful flow of cash and helps companies build
technical expertise and flexibility, according to Scott Ross,
president of Digital Domain, a large effects house in Venice,
Calif. With 350 employees, Digital Domain produces CD-ROMs, makes
commercials and works on theme entertainment attractions in
addition to its film work.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood's increasing reliance on technology also plays into
the independents' hands, because they generally have cost
advantages over the studios. Hammerhead's Chuba estimates that his
company can produce effects for roughly half of what it would cost
a major studio to do the work in-house.
</P>
<P>
   But the driving force behind what Ross calls ministudios _
specialist companies like his that are moving into mainstream
feature production _ goes beyond cost. It arises from a realization
that, while it can be dazzling fun to make effects, producing
feature films remains one of the most potentially lucrative and
prestigious parts of the entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people here want to work on feature films,'' said
John Hughes, president of Rhythm and Hues, the Los Angeles-based
special effects shop that earned an Academy Award for its work on
the hit comedy ``Babe.'' ``That's what they came here for in the
first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet if making films has not lost its allure for new
entertainment entrepreneurs, doing so at the traditional studios
certainly has. Legendary for bickering, bureaucracy and management
by financiers rather than auteurs, the studios can be much less
appealing to hot young talent than the less structured, more
entrepreneurial firms like Hammerhead or Santa Monica Studios,
another effects house-turned-ministudio.
</P>
<P>
   Chuba said talented animators also prefer basic working
conditions at Hammerhead's Studio City headquarters, with its pool
and sweeping views, to life on the crowded, sprawling lots at
Universal, Disney or Warner Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like this kind of space, and working with interesting
people, and that draws them to operations like ours,'' he said.
``It's collaborative, it's technologically cutting-edge and its
fun. We still have the feel of the Rebel Alliance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
