<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HAWKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS DEFEAT HAWKS, 77-70 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Latrell Sprewell and Marcus Camby, the hip-hop
additions to the New York Knicks, combined to make the Atlanta
Hawks look a little too old, a little too outdated to keep up with
their youth on Thursday night _ and for that matter, maybe in this
series.
</P>
<P>
   The two gave the Knicks, a team that could have become
complacent after their Game 1 victory on Tuesday, a confident strut
as they left the Georgia Dome on Thursday night with a 77-70
victory and a commanding 2-0 lead in their four-of-seven-game
second-round series.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have a chance to sweep the Hawks in Madison Square
Garden with Game 3 on Sunday and Game 4 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter that a mentally drained Allan Houston, who
scored just 2 points, missed his first five shots, was careless
with the ball and was benched for most of the game. Coming off the
bench, Sprewell scored 31 points _ matching his Game 1 total _ and
Camby had 11 points and 13 rebounds. Patrick Ewing, meanwhile,
scored 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was ugly, no doubt about it,'' Sprewell said of the game.
``But we did something we hadn't done in the regular season, and
that's finish in the fourth quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the series, Sprewell said, ``It's intense, and it's
everything I expected it to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks nudged ahead in this defensive, ugly struggle when
the Hawks' Steve Smith, who had another miserable night and scored
only 9 points, turned the ball over late in the third quarter. An
aware Chris Childs picked it up and delivered a pass to a sprinting
Sprewell, who put down a two-handed dunk at the end of the third
quarter to give the Knicks a 54-52 lead.
</P>
<P>
   That lead swelled to 64-58 when Camby put down a hard dribble
and flew through the air like a condor, floating over the
long-limbed Dikembe Mutombo and put down a one-handed dunk with 7
minutes 30 seconds left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Unrelenting, Sprewell then scored 5 straight points to give the
Knicks a 69-58 lead with five minutes remaining. There was nothing
the Hawks could do as a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do feel a little faster,'' Sprewell said, ``but they have
the guy Mutombo waiting there in the center, so it's not so easy
once you get by the initial defender.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks shot just 30 percent. Smith was 2 for 16, Mutombo was
3 for 9 and Mookie Blaylock scored 17 points but was 7 for 20.
Mutombo had 17 rebounds but only 8 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks wanted to approach this game as a chance to push the
Hawks to the edge of the cliff. But early on, the shine was off and
the energy pumping through the Knicks was as flat as Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   It was like the aftermath of the Knicks' Game 1 victory over the
Miami Heat.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't as if the Knicks weren't trying, but they didn't seem
as desperate as the Hawks after taking Game 1 of this series.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to come up with the touch and focus he had during his
34-point performance in Game 1 in Atlanta, Houston missed his
opening four shots and turned the ball over three times in the face
of Hawks' double teams in just 13 first-half minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But there was Houston's sidekick, Sprewell, itching to make an
impact off the bench. The Knicks had missed all but 1 of their
first 15 shots and had watched the Hawks build a 13-2 lead before
Sprewell stepped in to stop the madness.
</P>
<P>
   In his first minute on the floor, he started an 11-1 run with a
steal and ended the first half with 17 points. With Camby running
by his side and coming up with 10 rebounds and two blocked shots,
Sprewell and his young buddy delivered their team a 38-36 lead at
the half.
</P>
<P>
   That low score was reflective of defense, the Hawks' strategy to
slow down the game and sloppiness, a trend that continued in the
third quarter. With Sprewell on the bench to start the period, the
Knicks fumbled the ball away and lost their lead as the Hawks
scraped up a 42-42 tie.
</P>
<P>
   It was Sprewell and Camby who formed a bench combination that
overwhelmed the Hawks in the first half. Although they were getting
back better in transition than they had in Game 1 _ and disrupted a
number of fast-break opportunities _ the Hawks had no counter for
Sprewell and Camby.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks' Smith was smothered at every opportunity and finished
the first half 1 for 9. Mutombo was trying to keep up with the
active Camby, who competed with him blocked shot for blocked shot.
With a live Camby, Ewing was able to float away from Mutombo and
knock down a couple of jumpers to provide a backdrop to Sprewell's
show.
</P>
<P>
   Without concern for life or limb, Sprewell routinely drove into
the elbows of Mutombo, changed his shot and drew a foul in the
process. He went to the free-throw line 10 times in the first half,
hitting 7 foul shots. The Hawks, as a whole, went to the line just
11 times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
